<HEADLINE>
THE WESTERN FIRES 
 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, Aug. 9:
</P>
<P>
   The American West is a checkerboard of fires this summer, with
some 66 large wildland fires currently burning in 11 Western
states, many of them out of control. Every so often a year comes
along when conditions favor combustion. The forests and rangeland
become as dry as mouse nests, and when thunderstorms pass by,
bringing lightning without rain, ignition is inevitable. It
happened in 1988, when more than 1.5 million acres of Yellowstone
National Park went up in flames. And it is happening again now,
thanks to unusually dry vegetation, hot temperatures, low humidity
and rainfall, and winds that can fan a small blaze into a
conflagration. So far, some 4 million acres are burning or have
already burned, nearly twice the average annual acreage burned in
the last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   One fire in Washington state was started by an electric fence.
Some have been started by human carelessness. Those kinds of causes
it is possible to militate against. But in an arid year in a
combustible region, after decades of unremitting fire suppression
and fuel buildup, every low-pressure system worries firefighters
because the lightning it carries is capable of touching off an
enormous number of widely separated fires. On one particularly bad
day last week, dry thunderstorms generated 75,000 lightning strikes
that sparked more than 400 new forest fires across the West.
</P>
<P>
   The fires have stretched resources to the breaking point as some
20,000 civilian firefighters have struggled for months to control
the flames and have been assisted by military battalions and crews
from Canada and Mexico. President Clinton toured the fire scene in
the Payette National Forest in Idaho on Tuesday and said he would
release $150 million in emergency funds to fight the fires. It is
badly needed. There will be time later to assess whether more
should be done in future years to reduce the volume of combustible
vegetation in the forests before they can be ignited. For now, the
critical need is to bolster the containment efforts. Rain would be
a blessing, but even a few days of high humidity and low wind would
make a difference. Some of the fires may burn until the snows
come. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
