<HEADLINE>
TIMING'S EVERYTHING FOR U.S. SWIMMERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Notorious for their quirks and fickle
equilibriums, swimmers rarely tinker with something so sacrosanct
as the calendar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a mistake,'' U.S. swimmer Tom Dolan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see where it's going to make a difference,''
backstroker Lenny Krayzelburg countered.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is the toughest swim meet of their lives, the U.S.
Olympic Swimming Trials, which begin today at the IU Natatorium. So
deep is the U.S. pool of talent, the expected 1,300 Olympic
hopefuls over the next eight days will have to be at their peak
just to make the U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
   And surviving that, the top two finishers will have to gear up
and do it all again in Sydney in less than six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Too soon? Given the temperamental nature of swimmers, with their
shaving schedules, tapering schedules and
no-longer-talking-to-the-media schedules, it can't help.
</P>
<P>
   To a consensus gold-medal favorite such as Krayzelburg, holding
the trials in the middle of August might not matter. The native of
Ukraine is not expected to be pressed to make the team in either of
his two events, the 100- and 200-meter backstrokes.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, youngster Ed Moses set short-course world records in
his two events, and he figures to have places locked up in the 100-
and 200-meter breaststrokes.
</P>
<P>
   But in most other events, this is no time to be gazing ahead to
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   As Krayzelburg himself said on the eve of the trials, ``There's
a lot of pressure here.''
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the U.S. trials have been held in March _ four
months or more before the start of the Olympics. But both the 1992
Barcelona Olympics and the Atlanta Games in 1996 began in the heat
of July.
</P>
<P>
   The '88 Olympics, held in Seoul, South Korea, began in September
of that year. Those trials were held in Austin, some five weeks
before the Games.
</P>
<P>
   The medal tally in Seoul _ 18, with only eight golds _ remains
the Americans' lowest of the past 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six weeks is not enough time to refocus and build your body
back up,'' Dolan said.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian trials, by comparison, were held in May, as were
the Chinese team trials.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches have argued that the timing should not hurt. By holding
the trials so close to the Games, they say, the Olympic swimmers
will not be treading water on their own for the better part of four
months. With 52 Olympians making up the team, the coaches' fear is
that the athletes would have been following 52 different programs.
</P>
<P>
   That won't happen this time, they say. From here, the winners
will soon reconvene in a pre-Olympic training camp.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone is to blame, the hidebound veteran swimmers are
pointing the finger at college coaches, who complained that the
traditional timing of the U.S. trials in mid-March clashed with the
collegiate schedule. Four years ago, the NCAA championships came
two weeks after the Olympic Trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what people are saying is true _ it'll be tough,''
Olympic gold medalist Amy Van Dyken said. ``But from my standpoint,
I'm coming back from shoulder surgery. I'm glad the trials came as
late as they did.''
</P>
<P>
   Though only 27, Van Dyken represents the old guard that will
have its hands full making this U.S. team. The Colorado resident
won four gold medals in Atlanta. Fellow sprinter Dara Torres has
two gold medals and will be swimming to make her fourth Olympic
team.
</P>
<P>
   But somebody is going to be left home. The women's freestyle
sprints are loaded with pedigreed performers like Ashley Tappin and
Jenny Thompson, as well as new names like Courtney Shealey and
Liesl Kolbisen.
</P>
<P>
   The world will be watching. The swim world always seems to watch
the Americans, who have won an even-400 medals since the first
Olympic swimming races were held in 1896. No nation has won more,
nor has any nation matched the 177 gold medals that U.S. swimmers
have won.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, the past two times that a U.S. team competed and
didn't lead the overall swim medal count were 1956 and 1988. In
1956, the Olympics were held in Melbourne, Australia, and a rabid
crowd cheered the home team Aussies to eight golds.
</P>
<P>
   An omen?
</P>
<P>
   In Sydney, the Americans again will face an enthusiastic,
partisan Australia crowd. More than 100,000 paid their way to see
the Australian trials, held in Homebush Bay in the same pool as the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Swim watchers are saying that this will be Australia's strongest
Olympic team ever. They will be shaved, tapered, rested and ready.
</P>
<P>
   Expect to hear a lot of old-fashioned American complaining this
week.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
