<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ASTROS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL METS DON'T STAND UP, SO THEY FALL APART IN HOUSTON 
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The New York Mets who have surged through the last two
weeks did not show up at Enron Field on Tuesday night. Mike Piazza
and Edgardo Alfonzo sat out with minor injuries. A misfiring Al
Leiter replaced the dominant one that the Mets have known. Even
Mike Bordick, the sure-handed shortstop, made an error.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a 9-3 loss to the Houston Astros, who got seven
strong innings from their starter, Brian Powell. Pitching just his
second major league game in two years, Powell gave up one run, five
hits and a walk.
</P>
<P>
   Powell not only outpitched Leiter (12-5), but he also popped up
a double against him off the nearby left-field scoreboard. Leiter
lasted only five innings, his shortest start this year, allowing
five runs (three earned), six hits and two walks. The Mets lost for
only the third time in 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter struggled in his first two starts after pitching in the
All-Star Game, but he was masterly in his last two, allowing one
run in seven innings both times. Only 10 batters reached base via
hit or walk in those games, and Leiter won both.
</P>
<P>
   He got into trouble immediately Tuesday night. Julio Lugo hit a
routine grounder to short leading off the bottom of the first, but
Bordick's high throw pulled Todd Zeile off first base. Zeile caught
the ball and tried to swipe a tag, but Lugo was safe and Bordick
was charged with his first error as a Met, in his 10th game with
the team.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter then walked Lance Berkman, and Jeff Bagwell grounded a
single to left, scoring Lugo. Richard Hidalgo doubled to left for
another run, and a third scored when Chris Truby grounded out to
first.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter ended the first by getting three outs in a row, but more
trouble was ahead. With one out in the second, Powell hit a ball
that would have probably been an easy flyout in any other park.
Enron Field has a 19-foot-high wall that does not angle back
measurably, and Powell's 350-foot pop grazed the facing.
</P>
<P>
   Powell pulled into second with a double, his second career hit,
and two batters later, Berkman tripled to deep center field, giving
the Astros a 4-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Eusebio walked to lead off the fourth, but third baseman
Robin Ventura stopped Tim Bogar's ground ball with a belly-flop
dive. He fired a perfect throw to second from his knees for one
out, and Kurt Abbott completed the double play with a fine throw to
Zeile.
</P>
<P>
   Again, Leiter seemed to be in control. He got out of the fourth
and had not allowed a hit in 10 batters until Bagwell singled with
two outs in the fifth. But Bagwell stole second, and Hidalgo got
jammed but looped a run-scoring double to left. Leiter stood still
in front of the mound for about 10 seconds, his left hand on his
hip, staring at the corner where the double had knocked around.
</P>
<P>
   He would face only one more batter, Moises Alou, who lined a
ball toward Leiter's contorted face. Leiter threw his glove up just
in time to catch it, and he smiled in relief as he walked off,
shaking his glove to diminish the pain.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter had thrown 91 pitches by then, and he was removed for Pat
Mahomes in the sixth. Benny Agbayani had homered in the top of the
inning to cut the Astros' lead to 5-1, but a ghastly inning by
Mahomes put the game out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   It took Mahomes 39 pitches to get through the sixth. He gave up
two singles, three walks, a stolen base and a wild pitch, yielding
three runs. One of the walks came with the pitcher at bat, and
another was with the bases loaded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
