<HEADER>
A6419 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-MARINERS-BB     08-09 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-MARINERS-BBA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS DROP THE CIVILITIES AND HAMMER YANKS 8-5 
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Seattle Manager Lou Piniella stepped from the
visitors' dugout before the national anthem on Tuesday, made eye
contact with his counterpart across the field and dramatically
doffed his cap and bent a knee in respectful tribute. Yankee
Manager Joe Torre and his staff responded in kind.
</P>
<P>
   Those might be the last acts of civility between teams possibly
heading for a playoff showdown. The Mariners whipped the Yankees,
8-5, in spite of four home runs by the Yankees on a hot and steamy
afternoon, and exchanged knockdown pitches before departing Yankee
Stadium with three straight victories in the four-game series.
</P>
<P>
   It was a cranky day for the Yankees. After reliever Jeff Nelson
was ejected for offering an opinion on the work of the home plate
umpire, Mark Carlson, Chuck Knoblauch, the Yankees' leadoff hitter,
was placed on the 15-day disabled list with an elbow injury that
may or may not improve this season.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch, on the disabled list for the first time in his
10-year career, initially hurt his right elbow making an awkward
throw against Baltimore on July 24. Knoblauch's condition has not
improved, and he was given a dye test on Tuesday, which club
officials said confirmed an earlier diagnosis of inflammation.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch can still hit, in spite of his elbow trouble, and if
he cannot play second base, then Torre may consider using him as
the designated hitter. Derek Jeter led off in his place.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees took a 1-0 lead in the second inning when David
Justice hit his 28th homer; he added another two innings later. But
in the top of the sixth inning, with Seattle leading, 3-2, the
Mariners rallied against Denny Neagle.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs and runners at first and second, Neagle got ahead
of Rickey Henderson, no balls and two strikes. But Neagle
eventually walked Henderson _ his critical mistake, Neagle would
say later. The bases were loaded, the count went to three balls and
two strikes on Carlos Guillen, and Neagle tried zipping a fastball
over the outside corner.
</P>
<P>
   The right-handed-hitting Guillen poked the ball toward right
field that rode a swirling wind and just cleared the 314-foot sign
in the right-field corner for a Grand slam. Yankee Stadium will
usually be a friend to Neagle, a fly ball pitcher, but this time it
hurt him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time anybody wraps something around the pole, there's
really not a whole lot you can do about it,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Grimsley relieved Neagle and nailed Edgar Martinez with a
fastball, and Piniella patrolled the Seattle dugout, talking aloud.
When Justice came to bat in the bottom of the sixth inning,
Mariners pitcher John Halama threw a fastball behind Justice, clear
retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pitch got away from him,'' Piniella said later. ``Although
Edgar did get hit the previous inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Halama said, ``Whatever Lou said stands for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice said later that he understood what Halama was trying to
do, and that he had no problem with it. But Justice did turn and
ask the umpire, Carlson, if he was going to give a warning to
Halama, and became somewhat animated when Carlson said no. Before
the next pitch, Justice stepped far back in the box, in
anticipation of another brushback that never came.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Justice was called out on strikes twice on pitches
that appeared to be out of the strike zone. Justice never said
Carlson retaliated for Justice's arguments, but it was apparent he
felt that way. ``Y'all got TV,'' Justice said. ``Y'all saw it.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenallen Hill and Jorge Posada also hit home runs _ too little,
on a frustrating afternoon for the Yanks. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
