s e BC-STANLEY-TONG-FILM-$AD     08-09 1307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STANLEY-TONG-FILM-$ADV13-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK TO HONG KONG, WHERE THE ACTION IS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, August 13) 
By MARK LANDLER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ When Stanley Tong left his hometown for Hollywood in
1996, Hong Kong's film industry was headed for a crack-up as
spectacular as anything in a Jackie Chan movie.
</P>
<P>
   Box office revenue was plummeting, scripts were threadbare and
rampant piracy was driving a whole generation of movie-watchers
away from theaters. Demoralized by the grinding pace and
stultifying atmosphere of Hong Kong, local filmmakers fled this
former British colony faster than the British themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Tong, a 40-year-old former stuntman who directed Chan in
hyper-kinetic Hong Kong action films like ``Rumble in the Bronx''
(1996) and ``Police Story III: Supercop'' (1992), did not easily
find success in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   His first American film, `` Magoo,' (1997) a $30 million Disney
remake of the 1960s cartoon about a crotchety, near-sighted old
goof, left audiences as befuddled as its hapless hero.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Tong has returned to Hong Kong and is back on familiar
ground _ shooting an action film about the Chinese police busting a
smuggling ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to America because I wanted to learn how to make
Hollywood movies,'' Tong said. ``But I always wanted to come back
to where I grew up. I want to make Chinese films for an
international audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Tong is one of several Hong Kong filmmakers who have come home
this year. Some were disillusioned with the vagaries of Hollywood.
Others have been lured by the new money that is sloshing around
since the end of the Asian economic crisis. Still others missed the
frenetic energy and anything-goes culture of making movies here.
Whatever their reasons, these prodigal sons of Hong Kong cinema _
most are men _ hope to revive an industry that had been left for
dead two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an optimism here which hasn't existed for a long
time,'' said Wouter Barendricht, a sales agent for Asian movies who
runs the Hong Kong-Asia Film Financing Forum. ``People were in such
shock about the state of the industry that nothing happened for
several years.''
</P>
<P>
   After tumbling to $100 million last year from $167 million in
1993, Hong Kong's box office receipts are likely to bounce back to
$130 million this year, according to the Hong Kong Motion Picture
Industry Association. The industry will release 130 films in 2000,
one-third more than last year. At its peak, in the early 1990s,
this movie-mad city cranked out 230 films a year.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's resurgence has been driven by several factors. After
two years of recession, money is pouring back into film production.
Some comes from old-line Hong Kong production companies, which are
restyling themselves as Internet companies and desperately need
``content.'' Some comes from Hollywood studios, like Columbia
Pictures, which have set up local operations to finance Asian
films.
</P>
<P>
   The industry has also been helped by Hong Kong's belated
crackdown on piracy. Under heavy pressure from the United States
and the local film industry, the new Chinese government has raided
the producers of illegally copied video compact discs. Movie
executives say the campaign has worked: with bootleg VCD's drying
up, people are paying to see popular films at the multiplex.
</P>
<P>
   Harder to quantify, but also important, was Hong Kong's
relatively smooth transition from British to Chinese rule. Local
studios that had cut back their spending in 1997 out of fear that
China might curtail freedoms relaxed after it became clear that
Beijing did not plan to meddle in the territory.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most basic reason is better movies. After a long
stretch of derivative action movies, Hong Kong is starting to turn
out memorable, original films. It started with ``Stormriders,'' a
special-effects-laden fantasy directed by Andrew Lau that was a
rare hit in the doldrums of 1998. It has extended through ``In the
Mood for Love,'' a finely wrought domestic drama by Wong Kar-wai.
The film won a best actor award at this year's Cannes Film Festival
for Tony Leung Chiu-wai, the first for a Hong Kong actor.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is ``Crouching Tiger, Hidden Dragon,'' the highly
acclaimed martial-arts epic directed by Ang Lee (``The Ice Storm,''
``Sense and Sensibility''), which just has been named the closing
night film for the New York Film Festival on Oct. 8 and will open
in New York in December. Although strictly speaking not a Hong Kong
film _ it was co-financed by Columbia and Lee is from Taiwan _
``Crouching Tiger'' used a Hong Kong production crew and features
two of its hottest stars, Chow Yun Fat and Michelle Yeoh.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Crouching Tiger' is a milestone for the local film
industry,'' Barendricht said. ``It's an Asian film with a strong
Hong Kong base. That's what this industry is increasingly going to
look like.''
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong films used to be filmed only within the territory and
only in Cantonese, which made them difficult to market overseas.
Tong recalled how difficult it was to sell early Jackie Chan movies
to American studios. Not until ``Rumble in the Bronx,'' which had
dialogue in Chinese and English _ and was putatively set in New
York _ did Chan break through.
</P>
<P>
   The returning filmmakers are determined not to be parochial.
Tong is shooting his new film, ``China Strike Force,'' in Chinese
and English (less challenging than it sounds, given its lengthy
action sequences). He also chose Shanghai as the location, partly
because it is cheaper than Hong Kong, but also because he wanted to
get to know mainland China better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of the world's major film industries, Hong Kong has the
smallest home market,'' Tong said. ``If you have a movie that only
works in Hong Kong, you are dead before you start. If we can get
good distribution in China, it will be our biggest market in 20
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Tong knows the theme of his movie will play well with the
Chinese authorities. The fight against smuggling and other forms of
corruption is a hot button with the Communist leaders, including
President Jiang Zemin and Prime Minister Zhu Rongji, both of whom
are former mayors of Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Chan is another local director who came back to Hong Kong
with a view to expanding the industry's horizons. Chan, 37, spent
three years in Hollywood, where he directed Kate Capshaw in ``The
Love Letter'' (1999). He recently started a Hong Kong-based
company, Applause Pictures, that will develop pan-Asian pictures.
Among his first projects are films by mainland Chinese and Thai
directors.
</P>
<P>
   Chan said the best Asian films increasingly travel across
borders. A recent, if somewhat mournful, example was a low-rent
Japanese horror film, ``The Ring,'' which managed to clobber its
local competition to become one of Hong Kong's highest-grossing
films in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Applause Pictures is backed by Star East, a Hong Kong company
that is transforming itself into a one-stop shop for Asian
entertainment on the Internet. It plans to produce movies and
television shows, sell merchandise and create Web sites for
performers throughout the region. What Star East needs _ and what
Chan will happily supply _ are movies to fill all these
distribution channels.
</P>
<P>
   I could have come back, hired the 10 best directors in Hong Kong
and set about rebuilding the golden age of the Hong Kong cinema,''
Chan said over a cup of coffee in the gilded lobby of the Peninsula
Hotel here. ``But I don't believe there can be another golden
age.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Tong, Chan said Hong Kong _ with a population of 6.8
million _ was simply too small to recapture its once dominant role
in the Asian film industry. On the other hand, its marquee
directors, crackerjack production crews and deep pools of capital
make it a natural hub for a regional industry.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Not all Hong Kong filmmakers have given up on the idea of a new
golden age. Another of the returnees, Tsui Hark, the acclaimed
director of ``Once Upon a Time in China'' (1991), recently finished
shooting a fantasy film (as yet untitled) that is a sequel to his
1983 classic, ``Zu, Warriors From the Magic Mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   Using the latest in computer-generated special effects but
drawing on a 500-year-old Chinese legend, Tsui hopes to bring a
world of mythical warriors soaring above mist-shrouded mountains to
a new generation of moviegoers.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was filmed in Beijing, ``Zu'' is a typical Hong Kong
production. It was shot on a tight budget and an even tighter
45-day schedule that required the cast and crew to work round the
clock. On one particularly grueling day, Tsui slept fitfully in a
chair next to the set, while an exhausted crew set up a shot
involving the film's hero and heroine soaring through the heavens.
</P>
<P>
   Such brutal schedules used to be common here because of the
large volume of productions and the relatively small number of
actors and directors. This contributed to the poor quality of Hong
Kong films, because directors often began shooting with only the
semblance of a script. Scenes were often added or cut willy-nilly
to suit the schedules of double-booked stars.
</P>
<P>
   Here again, Hollywood's influence is making itself felt. Tsui,
who spent two years in the United States making Jean-Claude Van
Damme films (``Double Team,'' 1997, and ``Knock Off,'' 1998), said
he now worked with finished screenplays. Tsui also immersed himself
in American production techniques and brought some back to Asia.
The special effects designers on ``Zu'' are from the United States.
Despite the film's frantic schedule, Tsui said, he has throttled
back his pace to one or two movies a year, instead of several.
</P>
<P>
   Tsui's other new project, ``Time and Tide,'' exemplifies the new
discipline in Hong Kong movie-making. The $3.8 million action film
is backed by Columbia Pictures, which monitored every aspect of its
budget and production schedule. Although the film is a shoot-'em-up
about Chinese gangsters, Tsui agreed to cut some of the violence
from the script to satisfy the studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Hong Kong, producers hire directors and leave them alone,''
said Tsui, a 50-year-old whose wild hair and unlit cigar make him
look like an enfant terrible. ``But in Hollywood, they want to know
what the story is about. They're very focused on details.''
</P>
<P>
   If Lee's ``Crouching Tiger'' is an indication, the discipline of
Hollywood may result in better films. But Barbara Robinson, the
managing director of Columbia Pictures Film Production Asia, notes
that old habits are hard to break.
</P>
<P>
   ``While these directors know what it takes to make a Hollywood
movie, it doesn't follow that they will stick to those principles
back here, if they can get away with it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tsui, for one, seems like a grudging convert. Although he
concedes that Hong Kong's film industry was almost killed by bad
movies, he still sees merit in its frenetic, on-the-fly culture.
While he welcomes Hollywood's money, he does not want to create a
Hollywood of the East.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the studio ideas come from video stores,'' he said. ``I
think it's very silly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
