<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 00:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6425 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-AMERICAN-ROUTES-MUSIC     08-09 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-ROUTES-MUSIC-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRISSCROSSING THE WIDE MAP OF AMERICAN MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, August 13) 
 By SAMUEL G. FREEDMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few nights after Nick Spitzer was ousted from his job as a
disc jockey, his friends on the Philadelphia rock station WMMR-FM
gave a farewell party. They had listened over the previous two
years as Spitzer had spun Bessie Smith and Merle Haggard during
afternoon drive-time, and they knew that the program director had
been ridiculing the choices as ``nostalgia music.'' Now, in
December 1973, Spitzer had resigned rather than be consigned to the
2 a.m. shift, when his taste could do little damage to ratings.
</P>
<P>
   So Spitzer's girlfriend at the station presented him with a copy
of the book ``Country Music, U.S.A.,'' even though she herself
preferred British Invasion bands. Another colleague handed him a
Sony cassette recorder bought with donations from staff members.
For his own part, Spitzer vowed to his friends, ``I'm going where
music is made, not where records are made.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a quarter-century later, that party looks more like a
beginning than an end. Spitzer's uncompromising passion for
American music in all its vast variety has found expression in the
nationally syndicated public radio program ``American Routes.''
Part travelogue, part oral history, part musical survey, the show
is 100 percent Nick Spitzer, which is to say that in a given two
hours each week it might range from Thelonious Monk to Doc Watson
to Lauryn Hill, stopping along the way to interview a New York
cabbie or a Delta barber, deliberately heedless of categories.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to enlarge someone's ear,'' Spitzer said during a
recent telephone interview from the ``American Routes'' studio on
Royal Street in the French Quarter of New Orleans. ``You want them
to listen to the radio and say, `What's that?' The secret is to be
sui generis.'' More deeply, he explains: ``I'm not a
multiculturalist. I'm a creolist. I'm drawn to the boundaries where
cultures meet and overlap and simmer together. I gravitate to mixed
realities.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than three years after its debut, ``American Routes'' has
been picked up by more than 175 stations nationally, including such
powerful National Public Radio affiliates as WAMU in Washington,
KOPB in Portland, Ore., and KUOW in Seattle. (In New York, WFUV-FM,
90.7, carries the show at 5 p.m. on Sundays.) The music critic Nat
Hentoff, writing in The Wall Street Journal, likened ``American
Routes'' to an evening spent with the legendary folklorist Alan
Lomax.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer has achieved such success against significant odds.
Commercial rock radio, eclectic if sometimes amateurish in its
early days, has been divided into rigid niches for more than a
generation. Many of the college stations that kept alive the
free-form style during the 1980s have more recently tied themselves
to the Adult Acoustic Alternative format, known in the field as
Triple-A, which aims at baby-boomers with folk-rock artists like
Shawn Colvin and John Prine. And NPR affiliates have tended to
limit themselves to a single style of programming, whether jazz or
classical or information. Even syndicated music shows, like
``Afropop'' or the Celtic ``Thistle and Shamrock,'' generally hew
to a single identifiable genre.
</P>
<P>
   ``The orthodoxy of ratings thinking,'' said Steve Behrens,
editor of Currents, a trade newspaper covering public broadcasting,
``is that you want a constant format so people can know what
they'll hear whenever they tune in. If you're not playing what they
want, they may not come back. And if they don't come back, they
won't become members and financial supporters. So public-radio
people are reluctant to split their format. It takes convincing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``American Routes'' has surmounted such wariness partly by dint
of Spitzer's own reputation, built up during a 25-year career as an
author, anthropologist, record producer, radio host and
music-festival impresario. From its outset, ``American Routes'' has
been identified with him in the way that ``This American Life'' is
indelibly tied to its creator and host Ira Glass or ``Fresh Air''
is to Terry Gross. And the roots of Spitzer's sensibility go back
well before his professional radio career.
</P>
<P>
   Now 49, Nick Spitzer grew up in Manhattan and Long Island as the
son of a refugee and a rebel _ a German Jewish father fortunate to
have come to America for college before the Nazis barred the door,
and a blueblood mother whose forebears left their native Virginia
as abolitionists. From his father, a trained cellist who worked as
a chemist in the United States, Spitzer received an immersion in
Beethoven and Wagner. From his mother, behind the wheel of a '51
Plymouth, he got the scent of adventure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost every night, she'd put my brother and me in the car for
our `sleepy-bye ride,''' he recalled. ``She'd play the radio and
we'd see the city. We'd hear the ocean liners tooting on the river.
We'd go to Harlem. We'd go down to Greenwich Village and see the
Beat crowd. My mother believed all of America is part of what our
lives should be.''
</P>
<P>
   On the radio, meanwhile, Spitzer heard Mel Allen and Red Barber
jawing their way through Yankees games, Cousin Brucie and Murray
the K working through the pop charts. ``What I took away was two
things,'' he said. ``The visual imagination of radio _ that you
could be listening to a game from out west and visualize that
ground ball hitting a rock and bounding into left field. And that
rock and roll was cracking into the Top 40 and changing my idea of
music. In school, you're singing `15 miles on the Erie Canal,' and
here's `I found my thrill on Blueberry Hill.'''
</P>
<P>
   During college at the University of Pennsylvania, Spitzer put
his welter of musical interests to use both at the campus radio
station, WXPN, and in the folklore department, where he took a
course in cowboy songs and did research among the Italian-Americans
in South Philadelphia. Even before Spitzer found and lost the job
at WMMR, one of his professors was steering him to the graduate
program in folklore at the University of Texas in Austin. There, he
steeped himself in the mongrel cultures that to this day fascinate
him _ the Mexican, Czech and German mixture in South Texas; the
French, African and Caribbean melange of New Orleans and Cajun
Louisiana. And he came to realize that he was as estranged from the
academy as he was from commercial radio.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``In the world of folk music, there are hard-core academics who
don't want anything contaminating the purity of the songs,''
Spitzer said. ``They're not open to the idea of cultural mixture
and synthesis. They have the idea that everything radiates out from
the pure center and the bounds are questionable. But the bounds are
where I went.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the late 1970s he produced a couple of zydeco records,
boarded for a while with the fiddler Dewey Balfa and began
compiling, on his Sony cassette recorder, what is now a 1,000-hour
collection of oral histories. He raised grant money for Louisiana
to create a position of state folklorist, to which he was promptly
appointed. And when he developed cancer in the mid-1980s, he took
Cajun and Afro-Caribbean folk remedies in addition to chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Spitzer began working with the producer Mary Beth
Kirchner on a series of folklore documentaries for Radio
Smithsonian. ``From the moment I met him,'' she said, ``I knew
there were few people in the country who could assemble music and
voices the way he could.'' Spitzer reported several folklore
segments for NPR's ``All Things Considered'' in the early 1990s,
and he and Kirchner developed radio broadcasts from a series of
folklore concerts he arranged for Carnegie Hall and Wolf Trap.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it seemed to Kirchner that none of those forums had fully
captured the Nick Spitzer who had burst into her office back in
1977 rhapsodizing about zydeco music, the Nick Spitzer who could
wax for an hour about any record he owned. In early 1997, when his
resume was nearly 20 pages long and she had won an Alfred I.
duPont-Columbia University Award for producing the radio
documentarian Norman Corwin, Kirchner called him with a dare:
``You've wanted to do a show for 25 years. Maybe now's the time to
do it. Otherwise, you'll spend the rest of your life wondering,
`What if?'''
</P>
<P>
   The pair applied to the Corporation for Public Broadcasting for
a $90,000 grant, enough to prepare three months' worth of weekly
shows. The corporation, duly wowed, unilaterally tripled the
amount. In November 1997, Spitzer launched ``American Routes'' on
the community station WWOZ in New Orleans with Clarence Bonton
Garlow's rendition of that Cajun incitement to revelry, ``Bon Tons
Roulet.''
</P>
<P>
   By early 1998, American Public Radio (since renamed Public Radio
International) was syndicating ``American Routes'' to 39 stations.
While Kirchner, as executive producer, wrote the grant applications
and pitched the show at public-radio conventions, Spitzer infused
it with his aesthetic. From the beginning, each ``American Routes''
broadcast adopted a particular theme _ daily life in the Delta, for
instance, or the legendary highway Route 66 _ and explored it
through both music and taped interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Famously loquacious off the air, Spitzer speaks on ``American
Routes'' mostly through the recordings themselves and his crafty
way of structuring a show. Sometimes, as in a segue from Howlin'
Wolf to Tom Waits, Spitzer suggested lines of influence across
genres; sometimes he emphasized the disparity in interpretations,
playing the original cast recording of ``Old Man River'' from
``Showboat'' right after a version by the jazz saxophonist Gene
Ammons. Without being pedantic about it, Spitzer also enhanced the
show with his scholar's knowledge, for instance explaining after
Dr. John's cover of ``Junco Partner'' how its syncopation grew out
of inmates' work songs at the Angola state prison in Louisiana and
was called the ``jailbird beat.'' Several stations that carry
``American Routes'' have been pressing for Spitzer to spend more
time on-mike himself.
</P>
<P>
   By now, nearing the third anniversary of ``American Routes,''
Spitzer commands a budget of $500,000 and a full-time staff of
five. Though he consults ``Country Music, U.S.A.'' from time to
time, he has retired his Sony cassette recorder to an exhibit in
the Louisiana capitol building. But he still ventures out to record
interviews, recently speaking with a New Orleans plasterer named
Allison (Totie) Montana, who doubles as the Big Chief of a tribe of
Mardi Gras Indians. The result, in typically catholic Spitzer
fashion, will air on a Labor Day weekend show that also explores
the legacy of Woody Guthrie.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the show I wanted to do when I left Philadelphia,''
Spitzer said. ``There was no outlet for it then. Finally, I had to
build my own.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
