<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6427 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-LA-FACTORIES-LADN     08-09 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-FACTORIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. TOPS CHICAGO, N.Y. IN MANUFACTURING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Despite job erosion and few smokestacks on the
horizon, Los Angeles County remained the nation's top manufacturing
center last year with the San Fernando Valley playing a key role, a
study to be released Wednesday concludes.
</P>
<P>
   The county averaged 643,400 manufacturing jobs during 1999 and
the third-largest concentration of them was in the San Fernando
Valley, according to the study by the nonprofit Los Angeles
Economic Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago ranked a close second and Detroit was third. New York,
which often draws comparisons with L.A., ranked fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Being No. 1 is a familiar spot for the county. It's been the
nation's biggest manufacturing center, jobwise, every year in the
1990s but three; Chicago held the title from 1994 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   And manufacturing will continue to thrive in the region, the
report predicts.
</P>
<P>
   There is a skilled work force that can make satellites, digital
optics equipment and fabricated metal to exacting tolerances. And a
number of sectors, including high technology, are supported by
clusters in various areas such as Pasadena, the western San
Fernando Valley and the neighboring Conejo Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Being No. 1 is more than symbolic, notes Jack Kyser, the
nonprofit group's chief economist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a status thing but if you're an area that has a lot of
immigrants, manufacturing can help these people get good jobs and
get assimilated,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The county's concentration of manufacturing jobs reflects this,
with South Los Angeles and the San Gabriel Valley ranking one and
two, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Include all five Southern California counties and the region had
more than 1 million manufacturing jobs last year. Add in San Diego
and factory jobs along the Mexican boarder makes this one of the
largest manufacturing centers in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at it over the long haul the big surprise is that
the Los Angeles region lost so much aerospace and despite that,
it's still the nation's leading manufacturing center,'' said Ted
Gibson, chief economist for the California Department of Finance.
</P>
<P>
   While the raw numbers are impressive, the number of jobs has
been slipping, especially in the aerospace and apparel sector,
Kyser said.
</P>
<P>
   And Los Angeles is by no means the manufacturing powerhouse it
once was. Manufacturing employment, for example, peaked in 1987 at
887,200 jobs, 243,800 more than last year.
</P>
<P>
   So there is cause for some concern.
</P>
<P>
   The study said attention should be focused on:
</P>
<P>
   _ Providing quality industrial sites, which can be accomplished
by recycling older land with environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
   _ Paying more attention to training workers at the high school
and junior college level.
</P>
<P>
   _ Informing the business community about incentive programs that
can increase the number of manufacturing jobs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Meeting infrastructure needs like increasing airport and
freeway capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Kyser said job erosion began in the first quarter of 1998 and
should continue through at least this year. Most of the losses have
been classic aerospace positions.
</P>
<P>
   And the sector is also hindered by a shortage of industrial
space.
</P>
<P>
   The report said Ventura County has been in a manufacturing
growth mode since 1996 and should reach a new high this year with
about 40,400 jobs. Aerospace and high technology is a major driver,
accounting for 26.5 percent of these jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing has been growing in the Riverside/San Bernardino
area since 1994 and will also reach a new high this year with an
estimated 123,800 jobs. The Inland Empire is one of the few areas
where land is available for new facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manufacturing still plays a key role in the economy of
Southern California despite stories to the contrary,'' Kyser said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 0026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000809.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 00:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6428 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MARLBORO-MUSIC-$ADV13     08-09 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARLBORO-MUSIC-$ADV13-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VAUNTED MUSICAL TRADITION SEEN THROUGH FRESH EYES 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, August 13) 
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARLBORO, Vt. _ We've been trying to figure out what to call
this thing for 50 years,'' Frank Salomon said of the venerable
Marlboro Music School and Festival, which ends its 50th season here
today with a public concert. ``It is not what people customarily
think of either as a school or as a festival.''
</P>
<P>
   True, it is an odd school that has no teachers or students; only
participants, as they are called, some with much experience, some
with little, purposefully mixed and working together in rehearsals
and performances of chamber music. The learning is in the doing.
And it is an odd festival that determines its concert programs only
a week or so in advance, trusting listeners to travel from far and
wide all unknowing, and welcome whatever pieces and performers are
put before them.
</P>
<P>
   Not that anything is left to chance; far from it. The event is
closely administered, as it has been for some 40 years, by Salomon,
a concert manager and artists' representative from New York, and
Anthony Checchia, a concert manager from Philadelphia. And there
are artistic directors: New ones this season, in fact, the pianists
Richard Goode and Mitsuko Uchida. But apart from special areas of
concentration _ music this year (and this afternoon) by Thomas
Ades, the composer in residence; discussions of Bach performance
next year by the cellist and Baroque specialist Anner Bylsma _ they
have little say in the repertory, which is determined on the basis
of request lists from the participants.
</P>
<P>
   Goode and Uchida are the only directors since the distinguished
pianist Rudolf Serkin, who died in 1991, having run the festival
for most of its first four decades. Goode was present for the first
three weeks of the seven-week season, and Uchida for the last six.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no platforms, no slogans,'' Uchida said. ``At
Marlboro, we simply look deeply into the music and have time to do
so, and we share it with everybody and in some cases with the
public.''
</P>
<P>
   That looking deeply happens in rehearsals, which are the
lifeblood of the festival. The daily round of activity is
simplicity itself. Like-minded performers are put together in rooms
on the tiny campus of Marlboro College to rehearse specific works
drawn from those request lists. Distractions are few, for the
college, housed in a converted dairy farm, is some two miles from
the center of this southern Vermont town, also tiny. If and when
the rehearsals come to fruition, the piece may be put on a concert
program either in the dining hall for an invited audience or in
Henry Z. Persons Auditorium for the general public.
</P>
<P>
   But managing the system, with 75 performers distributed among
various groups, ranging from a few to a dozen or more, with at
least one experienced participant in each, is, to say the least,
complex. Performers rehearse from three to five pieces in different
groups for as much as 28 hours a week.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony McGill, a superbly talented young clarinetist recently
hired by the Cincinnati Symphony Orchestra, was heard repeatedly in
a day with eight solid hours of rehearsal. ``Is it harder on the
brain or on the lips?'' Uchida asked during one rehearsal, of
Schoenberg's ``Pierrot Lu-naire.'' The lips, McGill reported.)
</P>
<P>
   Alisa Belzer, the scheduling director, tracks it all with
color-coded cards on a big grid of a board. Why not a computer?
``Scheduling software is either too big or too small,'' Belzer
said, making clear that she had answered that question far too
often. ``There are so many idiosyncrasies that it would need to be
a powerful program, like something used at an airport. It would be
really expensive, and I'm not sure it's worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the board is part of the quaint, treasured Marlboro
tradition. So is the road sign ``Caution: Musicians at Play,''
which is supposed to stand near the entrance to the campus but was
stolen again this year. And so arethe wadded napkin balls that have
filled the air during meals ever since a young Judith Serkin, now a
senior cellist at the festival, and her father, Rudolf Serkin,
pelted each other decades ago. ( Uchida congratulated herself at
one meal on being unaccountably but blessedly exempt from attack.
She was beaned moments later.)
</P>
<P>
   Marlboro wears its history heavily. The festival was founded in
1951 by an illustrious group of musicians, all immigrants from a
war-torn Europe: Adolf and Herman Busch, Serkin and Marcel and
Blanche Moyse. Adolf Busch directed it for one season before his
death in 1952, when Serkin took over. Of the group, only Blanche
Moyse is alive, still conducting Bach at 90. Famous participants
over the years have included Pablo Casals, Alexander and Mischa
Schneider, and Felix Galimir as mature artists, and Yo-Yo Ma,
Emanuel Ax, Van Cliburn, James Levine and any number of others in
their youth. Many a musical partnership was forged here, and some
45 marriages had their start. (Not all lasted.)
</P>
<P>
   The histories of the festival read disconcertingly like ``The
Lives of the Saints'' and seem at times to suggest that nowhere
else is musical performance approached with anything like the same
probity and seriousness of purpose. An oppressive air of reverence
can stir resistance in a first-time visitor. But it doesn't last
long. For Marlboro does in fact seem to be a haven for idealism
unusual if not unique in the music world. Here, after all, are
musicians at the top of their field, freely passing on the lessons
of experience for no pay, expecting in return only the joys of
collaboration and some renewal in their own psyches.
</P>
<P>
   Orchestral players have perhaps the most to gain from so radical
a change of scene. ``In my world you hit a certain point where you
stop learning,'' said Richard Hawley, the principal clarinetist of
the Cincinnati Symphony though still young himself. ``You don't
stop improving, but thought and concentration are difficult when
you're part of an orchestral jukebox. This is a place to grow and
develop.'' At the same time, orchestral players have much to lose
financially. By taking leave from most of their summer employment,
they may give up as much as $10,000 of their annual salaries while
receiving pittances for expenses along with transportation costs
and housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody coming here is not coming to make money,'' Uchida said
with righteous pride. It is especially hard to attract top-level
soloists, who stand to make a great deal on the summer-festival
circuit. ( Uchida and Goode are, of course, such soloists, and they
are not paid even for their additional duties as directors.) Uchida
grudgingly envisions a day when it may be necessary to pay to get
the right people. Nor would such practice be without precedent;
Casals was paid, paid a lot, Uchida said, and that in a day with
fewer competing opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The resistance to payment is evidently philosophical rather than
financial. With an endowment of more than $25 million, Marlboro
seems to be well heeled. Much of its annual budget of $1.5 million
goes for fellowship aid to help cover the costs of room and board
for the younger participants on the basis of individual need. The
participants are expected to pay a nominal amount toward these
costs as well as provide their own transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't talk about it, but maybe you feel it,'' Uchida said
approvingly of the lack of payment to the senior participants.
``That may make the crucial difference in the spirit of the
place.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other factors in that spirit as well, including a
deep-seated sense of community, which centers on the dining room, a
former barn. Participants mingle freely at meals. At dinner, all
the participants, even the most senior, take turns waiting on the
others. Between meals, the dining room (along with virtually every
other room on the campus) is used for rehearsals, and on Wednesday
evenings, it is used for concerts, as it was regularly in the years
before the auditorium was built on the campus, in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reasons, to judge from a recent array of rehearsals
and concerts, Marlboro is a model of musical democracy in action.
Not only does the repertory reflect the desires of individual
performers, necessarily in varying degrees, but the rehearsals also
encourage a free and open interchange. Older players tend to couch
suggestions in deferential terms (``if everyone agrees''), and
younger ones seem unafraid to pipe up. (It may not always have been
thus; stories of outbursts by the excitable Galimir, who died last
fall, are legion.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet however much Marlboro's programming may depend on the
personal preferences of participants, the basic repertory has
always leaned heavily on the Germanic classics favored by the
European founders, particularly Serkin. That emphasis seems
unlikely to change. ``We're both Germanophiles,'' Uchida said,
speaking as well for Goode in his absence ``We overlap so much. We
both have a huge love of Debussy and Chopin, and we'd both be
perfectly happy without a note of Tchaikovsky.'' But Uchida also
stressed the new directors' commitment to contemporary music,
especially in the form of the composer-in-residence program, which
had been dropped for a time.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for the stability, not to say predictability, of
Marlboro's basic repertory over the years is that new performers
are always eager to trot out some of the standards on their own.
Given the theoretically unlimited rehearsal time and the
availability of so many fine and varied collaborators, participants
like to venture into music they don't often perform with their own
groups or can't master with a few of their friends.
</P>
<P>
   There is thus a premium on the big pieces of the chamber
repertory like, this season, the octets by Schubert and
Mendelssohn, and Dvorak's Opus 44 Serenade. Works that mix strings
with winds, like the Schubert and the Dvorak, or add singers are
also choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Brahms songs with viola are performed at least every
year,'' Stephanie Houtzeel, a mezzo-soprano who has performed them
here, said with some exaggeration. But sure enough, here they were
again, being performed by another young mezzo-soprano, Carola
Guenther, with Ryo Sasaki, a young violist, and Luis Batlle, a
pianist and longtime Marlborough participant. And for one listener,
Guenther's smooth, warm interpretation of the two songs, though
heard only in rehearsal, was a highlight of these visits.
</P>
<P>
   The other was a luminously transparent performance of
Schoenberg's ``Verklaerte Nacht,'' brilliantly led by Hilary Hahn,
the young violinist, and anchored by Siegfried Palm, a veteran
cellist. Palm, in another Marlboro tradition, often honored in the
breach this summer, played second cellist to a young first, Sumire
Kudo.
</P>
<P>
   Houtzeel, meanwhile, gave a fine, strong account of Ravel's
``Sheherazade,'' and Guenther began grappling less securely with
the Sprechgesang of ``Pierrot Lunaire'' for a performance this
weekend. For that is another kind of work that makes particular
sense at Marlboro: One that requires endless rehearsal. Uchida
scheduled 17 rehearsals, 1 fewer than when she performed the work
here a few years back with Galimir as the guiding force from the
violin. At the 13th rehearsal, fairly basic issues were still being
discussed, like how to differentiate the sound and mood of one song
from the next. What was most fascinating was the extent to which
all the instrumentalists took an interest in the meanings of the
German text and the ways they should be expressed in every part.
</P>
<P>
   Another rehearsal showed how quickly such lavish rehearsal time
can be taken for granted and how difficult it must be to readjust
to the real world after the season. In the third movement of
Prokofiev's First String Quartet, Samuel Rhodes, the longtime
violist of the Juilliard String Quartet, asked for a restart at
rehearsal No. 29 in the players' parts. At a later stopping point,
Emi Ohi Reznick, the second violinist, wanted to go back to No. 33.
Colin Jacobsen, the first violinist, commented on ``something four
bars before 31.'' But then Rhodes recalled something else, even
farther back. ``In that case, let's do three before 30,'' Jacobsen
said, putting things almost back where they had started the time
before.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such intensive labors, some works never find their way
to the concert stage. Nor, in some years, do all the participants,
although each performed at least one work this year. The official
emphasis, therefore, is on the value of the learning process in
rehearsal rather than on performance. But as Checchia, the
administrator, pointed out, ``The performance is also part of the
learning process.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the weight of its traditions and all of its proven
success in training performers, Marlboro has undergone change
throughout its history. During the Casals era, the 1960s and '70s,
orchestral music was performed in quantity; it is rare today. Even
opera has occasionally been represented. But undoubtedly the
biggest shock was the death of Serkin, whom the board found
literally irreplaceable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything here has sort of evolved,'' said Salomon, the
administrator. In this case, the board formed a senior artistic
committee of three performers, Uchida, Goode and Andras Schiff,
another pianist. But Schiff eventually yielded to other demands,
including his own summer festival in Hohenems, Austria. Uchida and
Goode were appointed directors last November.
</P>
<P>
   The future looks bright indeed. New participants are selected on
the basis of auditions, first on tape, then live, and the caliber
of the players applying and being accepted has perhaps never been
higher, said Carol Faris, the admissions director. In view of the
remarkable track record of Marlboro alumni, that is a claim to be
taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   But the future can wait. First come a few more glances back. The
festival's touring arm, Musicians From Marlboro, will present three
anniversary programs in November, all passing through New York. In
the first, at Carnegie Hall, Goode and Uchida are to perform Bach's
Concerto in C for Two Keyboards (BWV 1061).
</P>
<P>
   Bridge Records plans to release an anniversary set next year,
and Sony Classical has already released another on two CD's. It is
especially notable for the inclusion of a Serkin favorite,
Beethoven's Choral Fantasy. Tradition again: Serkin used to perform
this work to end the season, with the whole community joining in
the chorus. In this performance, from 1981, his son the pianist
Peter Serkin conducts, and the choral singing is lusty and
committed, giving a sense of the force this festival tends to exert
on those in contact with it.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every performer encountered this summer recounted that
his or her first experience at the festival had been a
life-altering experience. One who did not, oddly, was Uchida. ``I
didn't really understand what it was about,'' she said of an
isolated visit in 1974. She returned in 1992 as part of that
post-Serkin stopgap committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I take away a lot,'' she said. ``Selfishly, that's what I
come for. I always go away enriched.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
