<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS GETS BAD BREAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ The third time proved anything but the charm
for USC defensive tackle Jamaal Williams, when X-rays revealed he
broke his leg on the first day of training camp, the third fracture
in less than 12 months for the true freshman.
</P>
<P>
   Williams suffered a hairline fracture in his right leg and will
redshirt this season. He is expected to be out four to six weeks.
His injury came just one day after USC coach Paul Hackett
identified him as the surprise of last week's freshmen-only
practices.
</P>
<P>
   But then came Monday's accident, which is becoming a trend for
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-4, 260-pound lineman broke his leg last September in
the season opener for St. Augustine High outside San Diego. He
missed the rest of the year. The second break occurred last March
in a basketball pickup game. Then came Monday's mishap, when his
leg was hit during a drill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the first one, I've lost a lot of calcium,'' Williams
said. ``I think that's what happened. I'm going to have to start
taking a lot of calcium pills. This one is less severe though. It's
more like a hairline fracture.''
</P>
<P>
   All three fractures have occurred in bones located directly
above Williams' foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to play this year, but I guess this is a redshirt
year, which is fine,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Paul Hackett said the Trojans might move a player over
to the defensive line to compensate for any potential depth
problems.
</P>
<P>
   __ Different time, same result: USC's kicking woes of spring
continued in training camp, as none of the kickers distinguished
themselves in Tuesday's practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're off to a bit of a shaky start with the kicking, which I
anticipated,'' Hackett said. ``The holding and snapping are still
getting settled.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior David Bell, junior David Newbury and freshman John Wall
of Birmingham High are fighting for the kicking job, but at least
one decision has been made: Free safety Ife Ohalete will be the
holder. Defensive tackle Bernard Riley is the early leader to be
the snapper.
</P>
<P>
   __ Nonqualifier: Defensive tackle Sagan Atuatasi did not fulfill
the necessary academic requirements and will not be admitted into
the university. He had been attending junior college the past year,
after playing football at Los Alamitos High.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett might give Atuatasi's scholarship to a walk-on, with
senior wide receiver Matt Nickels and senior linebacker Ryan
Shapiro the top candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Nickels has a slight advantage over freshman Keary Colbert to be
the No. 3 receiver, as Hackett remains disappointed in sophomore
Steve Stevenson, who is out with a hamstring injury.
</P>
<P>
   __ O-line update: The depth chart remains unsettled, but right
now the starters along the offensive line are Brent McCaffrey (left
tackle), Trevor Roberts (left guard), Eric Denmon (center), Zach
Wilson (right guard) and Jacob Rogers (right tackle). This is not a
set lineup, however, and junior Faasea Mailo is being considered
for a starting position at either tackle spot.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential starter at right tackle is true freshman Joe
McGuire. He has been beaten a few times early by veteran defensive
linemen, but offensive line coach Steve Morton said those
occurrences are quickly diminishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm seeing improvement,'' Morton said. ``Physically, he has
the tools, it's just a matter of picking things up.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson returned from summer school and practiced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   __ A legacy: Safety Kyle Matthews of Westlake High is walking on
to the team. He is the son of former USC linebacker Clay Matthews.
</P>
<P>
   Another ex-player, 1979 Lombardi Award winner Brad Budde,
attended Tuesday's practice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
