<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 00:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6431 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NY-ARCHITECTURE-$ADV1     08-09 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ARCHITECTURE-$ADV13-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVING UP TO THE MEMORIES OF A POETIC OLD SKYLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, August 13) 
 By HERBERT MUSCHAMP    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This is a plea on behalf of ethos, the set of
cultural values that underlies the forms of artistic expression _
or eidos, if you'll excuse the Sunday morning anthropology lesson
I'm about to foist on you. The ethos of ancient Egypt, for example,
was theocratic hierarchy. Its eidos was the pyramid. Nice forms,
pyramids. Not so nice, the beliefs that gave rise to them. But it's
enlightening to know about the beliefs nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Decisions are now being made about a cluster of major civic
projects that, between them, will exercise an unprecedented impact
on the immediate and long-range future of New York. All the
projects have an important role to play in meeting the fundamental
challenge faced by New York and other aging urban centers: The
transition from the industrial city of the 19th century to the
cultural matrix of the 21st. The projects are on different scales,
and each calls for a different eidos _ a distinctive formal
response. But the ethos that should shape these responses is the
same: Sense of place; historical awareness; an educated view of
where history is going; and a receptive state of mind.
</P>
<P>
   As of this writing, decisions are imminent on two contested
Manhattan sites. They are 2 Columbus Circle, the midtown site now
occupied by Edward Durell Stone's Venetian-style campanile,
originally designed for Huntington Hartford's Gallery of Modern
Art, and the East River waterfront property, just below South
Street Seaport, on which the Solomon R. Guggenheim Foundation
proposes to build a museum designed by Frank Gehry. Also in the
works are a waterfront park for Brooklyn and a citywide plan
designed to attract the 2012 Olympic Games to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Just last spring, it was possible to predict with some
confidence that cultural values, in particular architectural
values, would play little part in the outcome of these and other
civic projects. Rather, the choices would be driven by a
combination of economic and political considerations. There was
cynical speculation that before heading off to Washington, Rudolph
Giuliani (as is often the norm in politics) would directly or
indirectly reward his supporters with real estate development
plums.
</P>
<P>
   What has changed, of course, is that the mayor will not be
heading to Washington. He will presumably not be leaving City Hall
before his term runs out. And, because of the mayor's brush with
mortality, he is said to be better disposed than formerly to do the
right thing. New Rudy or not, this is as good a time as any to talk
about good things, and about some of the bad things that prevent
good things from happening in architecture _ that prevent the ethos
from taking architectural form.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone can make a list of bad things. Mine would include the
cultural illiteracy of key decision makers, both in city government
and in private civic groups; the notion that the new buildings for
cultural institutions can be mere boxes for housing cultural
functions; the failure to grasp, therefore, that the cultural
responsibility of the container is at least as great as the
contained. Not least, one must factor in the interlocking wheels of
public relations and private dealmaking that join to bestow vaunted
cultural status on utterly worthless buildings.
</P>
<P>
   I want to focus on the Guggenheim project because, of all the
plans now pending, it is the eidos that draws most deeply from the
New York ethos: The city's open-endedness, its receptivity to
change. As such, the project could help shape the standards by
which designs for other civic projects should be judged.
</P>
<P>
   Set aside for the moment the particulars of Gehry's design and
the global ambitions of Thomas Krens, the Guggenheim Museum's
Napoleonic director. Look instead at the landmark that has
commanded the East River waterfront, on the Brooklyn as well as the
Manhattan sides, for more than a century. Consider the mental as
well as the physical landscapes dominated by the Brooklyn Bridge,
the bridge's impact on the imagination of citizens, painters and
writers, its metaphoric as well as its functional value.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Think about Hart Crane, the great lyric poet of 20th-century New
York. Crane's opus, ``The Bridge,'' the democratic ideals
symbolized by the bridge and the cultural milieu that supported the
expression of those ideals _ these are as finely woven into the
Guggenheim's site as the cables that support the bridge's roadbed.
Come now, do you really want to see this site submerged beneath the
platforms of some river-themed upscale floating hotel? (That is the
other plan the city is considering.)
</P>
<P>
   If you live in Brooklyn, you can see the Brooklyn Bridge as Hart
Crane thought it should be seen: As a portal from the old world to
the new. At once a departure and an approach, the bridge summons up
images of things left behind and things as yet untried. It
stretches between an ending and a beginning, the familiar and the
unknown, hierarchy and equality, ancient customs and freedom from
them.
</P>
<P>
   The skyline of lower Manhattan, which Crane photographed from
his window at 110 Columbus Heights, was a vision of possibility.
Or, as Whitman phrased it more simply two generations before, ``The
shapes arise!'' Together, bridge and skyline were the eidos, the
formal expression of ideas the poets put into words.
</P>
<P>
   This is the background against which the Guggenheim project
should be seen. While not conventionally contextual, Gehry's design
is acutely responsive in formal terms to the lower Manhattan
skyline and the riverfront location. It is a tripartite
composition, divided horizontally. The public spaces at the base,
including an immense skating rink, extend the river surface inland.
The steel cloud above is fashioned from titanium ribbons; within
are galleries and a central atrium. The cloud appears to be
composed of long strips of reflective river surface that have been
loosely wrapped, an unstable mass of creative energy. Above that, a
450-foot tower appears to lean slightly to the north, as if
awestruck by the skyline's panache.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody can claim that this is a background building. To blend in
would be alien to its nature. This is due not only to the formal
originality of Gehry's design, but also to the idea animating it.
That idea, simply put, is that subjective expression has a critical
role to play in architecture at this moment of the city's
transition from an industrial to a cultural space.
</P>
<P>
   We are accustomed to subjective treatments of the city in
poetry, painting, film, photography, music, fiction and dance. And
we bring our own subjectivity to bear when we gaze at the skyline.
But we still expect the architects of individual buildings to
conform to some imagined objective ideal. Buildings should not be
artistic performances. They are not sculpture. They should not be
individualistic or, to cite a term that has been misapplied to
Gehry, egocentric.
</P>
<P>
   So-called contextualism is the latest version of this prejudice.
It restricts architects to the dictates of external authority _ in
this case, the forms and scale of neighboring buildings. It denies
them the freedom to reckon creatively with the city as it evolves.
As a consequence, it prohibits the city itself from becoming the
architect's muse.
</P>
<P>
   There is a picture of the man who served as Crane's muse during
the time he was writing ``The Bridge.'' His name is Emil Opffer. He
is shown standing on the roof of 110 Livingston Street, with the
bridge in the background. Opffer himself was a bridge. He enabled
this deeply introverted, alcoholic poet to engage with the world in
a far more direct, physical way than was possible with his writings
alone. Opffer was a bridge toward love and the inspiration that
comes from it.
</P>
<P>
   Crane's muse was a merchant seaman, frequently absent, which
probably satisfied the poet's need for romantic yearning. And
Opffer's roving, maritime life drew the sea into the compass of
Crane's mental landscape. It is the sea, not just the East River,
that Crane's bridge is always crossing. In 1932, at age 32, Crane
drowned himself in its depths.
</P>
<P>
   This is the real context from which Gehry's design springs. The
design denies any inherent distinction between architecture and
other forms of cultural expression. That denial is based on a sharp
historical awareness of the city at this moment. It is not an
expression of ego. It reflects a solid grasp of the role
architecture ought to play in the cultural city. It, too, is a
bridge, a span between past and future. More than a mere monument
to itself, the design recaptures the unfamiliarity that the skyline
represented for Crane.
</P>
<P>
   Cities are productive places. If they can no longer support
industrial production, they must throw their weight behind cultural
production. They must look beyond the model of cultural consumption
toward a more productive set of conditions. If they remain content
to package culture as an inventory of select consumer products,
their future will be indistinguishable from that of a suburban
mall. Gehry's design points the way out of this fate. The fluid
line between our inner and outer worlds _ between the objective and
the subjective _ is one of the critical cultural issues of our
time. The Guggenheim plan frames this issue more concretely than
any New York has seen.
</P>
<P>
   Under Krens' direction, the Guggenheim has carved out a singular
place for itself in the cultural system. The museum's exhibitions
are occasions for consumption, but they are also creative
productions in their own right. So is the Guggenheim's global
network of branches. These are at once centers for culture
consumers and components of a larger, creative vision of art as a
form of international exchange.
</P>
<P>
   As I think back on the exhibitions mounted during Krens' tenure,
I am struck by how many of them have taken urbanization as their
subtext. For example, the present show, ``1900,'' documents the
relationship between industrial and cultural production in the era
of the great world's fairs. As such, it offers a prehistory of the
present moment. ``The Great Utopia'' and ``The Italian
Metamorphosis'' have also provided historical slices that
illuminate the contemporary urban condition.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani is said to be a traditionalist. So am I. But New York's
most vital tradition is its ethos of change. To represent that
enduring ethos, the eidos must change. This is the city's great
paradox.
</P>
<P>
   People should not be asking whether Gehry's design fits into the
context of lower Manhattan. They should be asking whether New
York's new buildings fit into the urban context that Krens, among
others, has been putting together. That context is now global, but
in origin it is local. It is New York's gift to modern times.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
