<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TROCKS-DANCE-ART-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STARRY TROUPE THAT PAYS ITS WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, August 13) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JOSEPH CARMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   What renowned American classical ballet company garnered enough
engagements in 1999 to employ its dancers for an impressive 41
weeks? The Joffrey Ballet, maybe? American Ballet Theater? No, it
was Les Ballets Trockadero de Monte Carlo, fondly known as the
Trocks, home of bulldozing stars like Olga Supphozova and Ida
Nevasay-neva. The company, opening at the Joyce Theater on August
15, will present two repertory programs consisting primarily of
Slavic chestnuts, including the New York premiere of an impeccably
affected ``Raymonda's Wedding,'' coached by Elena Kunikova. Because
of an advance sell-out of their last Joyce engagement, the Trocks
are extending this year's New York summer season to a full two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping ballerinas who are veritable ships of state in working
form requires running a tight ship. Although heavy on levity, the
all-male comedy ballet troupe, now in its 26th year, is run by a
troika of no-nonsense leaders: Eugene McDougle, the general
director; Tory Dobrin, the artistic director; and Pamela Pribisco,
the ballet mistress. Their ingredients for financial as well as
artistic success consist of low-cost, high-quality productions,
impressive technical standards, audience accessibility and an
undeniable talent for slapstick.
</P>
<P>
   Not a drop of grant money has ever been received by the Trocks.
During the dance boom of the 1970s, the Trocks qualified for the
National Endowment for the Arts' Dance Touring Program and became
one of its biggest moneymakers. According to the program's
guidelines, however, it was the sponsors who received the money,
not the Trocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always felt that one of the reasons that the company has
been financially successful was that we didn't get any funding in
the beginning and did not, therefore, build up a superstructure
that required a lot of money just to maintain a large staff and
office space,'' says McDougle. He and Dobrin still run the company
out of their apartments, renting rehearsal space at City Center
when not on tour.
</P>
<P>
   After a slump in the 1980s, when the quality of the productions
suffered, the Trocks pulled themselves up by their point shoe
ribbons and developed a more professional look. Nancy Gabriel, vice
president of IMG Artists, which now handles bookings for the Trocks
and other high-profile companies like the Parsons Dance Company and
Pilobolus, identifies the Trocks' critically acclaimed 1997 London
season at the Peacock Theater as a turning point. ``Their level of
artistry, technique and comedic genius have never been at a higher
level in their 26 years of existence,'' Gabriel says. ``They are
attracting the best dancers who are getting rave reviews.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while the Trocks of yesteryear felt quite at home
falling off point, it is not unusual to see their current crop of
16 ballerinas churning out batches of triple fouettes or propelling
themselves well into the stratosphere. When Madame Supphozova (aka
Robert Carter) launches into a diagonal of chaine turns in
``Paquita,'' her tutu takes on the ferocity of a buzz saw.
</P>
<P>
   The newly acquired technical superiority can be attributed to a
generally higher level of male dancing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The better trained they are when they come in,'' Pribisco
says, ``the easier it is for them to learn to do point work,
because it's not a different technique. It's an additional
knowledge that they haven't experienced yet, because men don't do
that vocabulary.''
</P>
<P>
   Les Ballets Grandiva, a successful male troupe founded by a
former Trocks dancer, Victor Trevino, has also benefited from
better male dancers. Paul Boos, a New York City Ballet alumnus who
coaches Grandiva's dancers, stresses that, although the ballerinas
may be portraying wilting sylphs or spry soubrettes, the physical
demands of their performances are high.
</P>
<P>
   The wild popularity of Grandiva and the Trocks in Japan has
provided a substantial part of their meal tickets. While the Trocks
toured 37 cities in the United States and 6 European countries in
1999, the company recently completed its 16th Japanese tour with
fees that actually produced a surplus. Its high jinks may be a
perfect outlet in a nation that appreciates the broad sense of
humor displayed in Tokyo's television game shows.
</P>
<P>
   But it is a similarity to the Kabuki Theater tradition, and not
just in the form of heavily crayoned eyebrows and brazenly slashed
eyeliner, that begs comparison. ``We fit into their cultural
norms,'' McDougle says. ``Traditional Japanese theater has been
totally male dominated. They have no problem accepting us as men
doing women's roles.'' The adulation has even taken the form of an
organized fan club of giggling teen-age Japanese girls who hurl
bouquets at their favorite divas.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of overall marketability, Gabriel praises the
flexibility of the troupe. ``Sometimes they are presented on a
straight dance program, other times on a variety or special
attraction series, on a comedy series, or even on a family series.
In short, there is almost always a place for them.'' Exquisitely
made costumes, accompanied by simple sets, keep the freight costs
of touring down.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be ignored is the audience appeal of old-style, Ballets
Russes-inspired divas vamping in the spotlight and flaunting their
indispensable mannerisms. ``Everyone in the Trocks is encouraged to
really go to the max with their personalities,'' says Dobrin.
``And, you know, it's much easier when you have a wig, makeup and
eyelashes on. You tap into those areas of your character that are a
little wacky anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
