<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 00:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6434 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-AFRICAN-INSTRUMENTS-$     08-09 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICAN-INSTRUMENTS-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAUTIFUL TO HEAR, AND TO SEE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, August 13) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Perhaps more than for any other people, music has
been an integral part of the lives of Africans. Whether it has been
the chants of boatmen on the Niger, or the sound of the kora (a
kind of lute) played by a griot as he recites the history and
genealogy of a people, or the brassy horns and vibrant rhythm
sections of a contemporary band in a Lagos nightspot, Africans _
and their descendants in the diaspora _ always seem surrounded by
music. So it hardly comes as a surprise for a museum curator to
decide that traditional African instruments should not only be
listened to but looked at.
</P>
<P>
   That is the point of ``Audible Artwork: Selected African Musical
Instruments,'' a pleasant though rather modest exhibit showing here
at the National Museum of African Art through April 8. Mounted,
encased in glass and subtly lighted, the wooden rasps, gongs,
rattles, drums, thumb piano and whistles that make up the exhibit
shed their utilitarian mien, presenting themselves as objects of
art.
</P>
<P>
   Music seems to be a prevalent theme for the Smithsonian
Institution this summer. Across the garden from the Museum of
African Art, the Arthur M. Sackler Gallery is presenting ancient
Chinese instruments in an exhibit called ``Music in the Time of
Confucius.'' Not far away, the National Museum of American History
is sponsoring ``300 Years of the Piano.'' It seems as though the
museums are striving to make up for this city's discordant
political rhetoric with a reminder that life is often harmonious.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to these other exhibits of musical instruments, the
small scale _ 11 pieces _ of ``Audible Artwork'' gives the Museum
of African Art's effort a kind of ``me too'' quality. Still, it is
worth the time minutes it takes to enjoy, not only for the beauty
of the instruments but also as a primer on the breadth of African
art.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most people tend to think of African art only in terms
of masks, figures and drums,'' said Bryna Freyer, the exhibit's
curator. ``I think it's getting better in that regard because of
our museum and other museums like us. The fact that we put on shows
of pottery, and small personal objects and musical instruments,
tends to say to people out there: `Hello! This is art work! This is
important!'''
</P>
<P>
   There is an opportunity to listen to the instruments, of course.
The exhibit provides a station with headphones that allows a
visitor to hear traditional drumming by the Ga peoples of Ghana, a
song accompanied by a five-string harp fashioned by the Zande
people of the northeast Congo and a harvest celebration in Burkina
Faso featuring xylophones, gourd drums and whistles.
</P>
<P>
   But the exhibit's point is visual, not auditory, and each of the
pieces is presented in elegant simplicity. As visitors enter the
exhibit room at the bottom of a staircase on the second level of
the underground museum, they immediately see two sistrums, a kind
of rattle. The first, fashioned by the Bamana people of Mali, is
made of wood and gourds. With the pie-shaped gourds hanging on the
end of a polished stick that itself resembles a wishbone, the
Bamana sistrum looks like a mushroom doubled over from a punch to
the gut. It is unadorned, like those that accompany the chants of
young Bamana boys as they march to be initiated into the n'tomo
youth association. Once they have gone through this rite of passage
on the way to manhood, their sistrums would be decorated with grass
fibers.
</P>
<P>
   On a slightly more grand scale is the sistrum used to mark time
in an Ethiopian Orthodox Church service. Grasped with a handle made
of horn, the sistrum has two ornate copper alloy pillars, each
topped with an onion-shaped dome. The intricate working of the
brass is a testament to the craftsmanship of the late 19th and
early 20th century artisans.
</P>
<P>
   Dominating the exhibit is a large drum made around 1935 by the
Ghanaian artist Oseil Bonsu, perhaps the most important Asante
sculptor of the 20th century, who is well known for the drums he
created for the Ntan society _ a kind of civic association that
also performs at weddings, funerals and festivals. Bonsu's drum is
a brightly painted hodgepodge of symbols and tales in red, green,
brown and beige. It contains breasts, probably representing
fertility, as well as pictures of puff adders capturing frogs,
birds, elephants and palm fronds. It sits atop a figure of a lion.
One could spend hours transfixed by this alluring drum, trying to
figure out all its maker is trying to say.
</P>
<P>
   While there are more formidable pieces in the exhibit, none can
match the stark beauty of the wooden three-note whistles of the
Nuna people of Burkina Faso. In their most basic function, they
serve as a signal for hunting dogs. They are also played in
ensembles at funerals and celebrations of the hunt. Propped in a
display case, they seem like stylized stick figures of an eerily
human form, standing arms akimbo.
</P>
<P>
   Next to them is a tiny whistle carved from ivory in the late
19th or early 20th century by a craftsman from either the Mbun or
the Pende tribe (the curators are not sure which) of the Congo. The
rounded figure with the quizzical face seems a perfect symbol for
the show. Its sound commands hunting dogs to pay attention. Its
elegance _ like that of the show as a whole _ implores visitors to
do the same.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
