<HEADER>
A6437 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w BC-SILICON-DEMOCRATS-SFC     08-09 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SILICON-DEMOCRATS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PELOSI LEADS LAWMAKERS ON TOUR OF SILICON VALLEY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Introducing Old Democrats to the New Economy, Rep.
Nancy Pelosi will lead 38 House colleagues Wednesday on a detour
through Silicon Valley and San Francisco's Multimedia Gulch on
their way to the Democratic convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The group will breakfast with venture capitalists, mingle with
industry chieftans, &LR;  like Jerry Yang of Yahoo and John Warnock of
Adobe Systems, and dine with Gordon and Ann Getty. They will visit
Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. to discuss online stock investing, get a
biotech briefing at Alza Corp. in Mountain View, and finish up with
lunch at George Lucas' Skywalker Ranch in Marin County.
</P>
<P>
   The group will have members of the Bay Area's delegation,
including several who oppose the high-tech industry on its top
issues: freer trade with China, more H1B visas for skilled
immigrants and tort reform.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi helped lead the unsuccessful effort in the House to block
permanent normal trade relations with China. Others, including
Oakland's Barbara Lee and the East Bay's Pete Stark, have voting
records that put them solidly at the bottom of the scorecard issued
by the Information Technology Industry Association, a Washington
lobby that tracks such issues.
</P>
<P>
   The tech lobbies are thrilled nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's terrific they're coming out,'' said Lezlee
Westine, acting co-chief executive of TechNet. ``I think what
they'll realize is that Silicon Valley is very policy driven, and
the recent vote on permanent normal trade relations with China,
which had 75 percent of Republicans voting yes, really bought a lot
of goodwill for Republicans in Silicon Valley. ... The more
dialogue they can have with nonpartisan Silicon Valley executives
the better it will be.''
</P>
<P>
   With the world now marveling at the unprecedented tech-driven
economic expansion, Democrats and Republicans have been making
regular pilgrimages to Silicon Valley, promising aid on policy and
pleading for campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Democratic trip will coincide with a visit by
several Republicans led by House Speaker Dennis Hastert, &LR;  and
including Tom Campbell, a Silicon Valley representative now running
for the Senate against incumbent Democrat Dianne Feinstein.
</P>
<P>
   The aim of the Democratic trip, Pelosi said, is to allow members
``to breathe the air and drink the water of entrepreneurship that
is palpable and tangible in our area.''
</P>
<P>
   That way, Pelosi said, they can return to Washington ``better
equipped to shape solutions that are in our public interest but
sensitive to the concerns of individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   The trip will showcase Pelosi's efforts to fashion what she
calls a ``New, New Democrat,'' a political hybrid who is neither an
old-fashioned tax-and-spend liberal hostile to business, nor a
member of the ``New Democrats,'' the moderate wing that has spent a
decade trying to shift the party to the center.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, New Democrats are not so sure about this New
New hybrid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rhetoric has changed, but it's not necessarily backed up
by votes,'' said one New Democrat House member, adding that
Pelosi's own voting record ``suggests she doesn't even know where
Silicon Valley is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you have a zero voting record (on tech issues), you
can raise money in Silicon Valley,'' this member added. ``All roads
now lead to Silicon Valley and Northern California. It's a
beautiful place and everyone wants to go.''
</P>
<P>
   But the tech-driven economic expansion has proven so spectacular
that it has dramatically shifted the political terrain in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Atkinson, technology policy director for the Progressive
Policy Institute, the New Democrat think tank, said the new economy
is forcing old Democrats to reposition themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the course of the past decade, it has become more and
more obvious that old economic rules don't apply and that the old
liberal formulas don't apply either,'' Atkinson said, citing large
government social programs, command-and-control regulation and
policies focused principally on income redistribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality of the world and the changes in the economy make
those old approaches invalid,'' Atkinson said. ``I think liberal
Democrats understand there's this new challenge out there for them,
and that holding on to old ways isn't going to get them anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, House liberals complained that the nation's chief New
Democrat, President Clinton, was abandoning core liberal values --
on trade, on welfare, on spending -- in his efforts to lay claim to
the political center.
</P>
<P>
   But now, the promised payoff has arrived. The economy is
generating huge budget surpluses, freeing liberals from the
constraints of deficits that for years hindered the creation of big
new programs.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Democrats can advance a new prescription drug benefit for
Medicare and still claim fiscal prudence, while Republicans find
themselves on the defensive, saying they want a prescription drug
benefit too.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi believes that Old Democrat ideals can be joined to the
New Economy. ``The progressive philosophy...serves us well in this
new era,'' she said in a conversation earlier this year. `'I am a
committed liberal, but that doesn't mean I'm wedded to the old way
of doing things.''
</P>
<P>
   House Democratic leader Dick Gephardt _ who will join the trip
with a press conference near San Francisco's Fairmont Hotel on
Thursday _ signalled the party's change of stance in a major speech
to Northern Virginia tech leaders last March, where he lauded the
wonders of the new economy and promised that ``high tech issues
will flourish'' in a Democratic-led House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our role can be a constructive one if we adhere to an approach
that allows the private sector the breathing room to solve some of
these problems itself,'' Gephardt said. ``I look forward to leading
a Democratic House that does everything possible to ensure that we
can continue this longest peacetime expansion, with technology
leading the way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 0037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000809.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 00:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6438 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-REFORM-PARTY-SFCHRON &LR;      08-09 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-PARTY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BUCHANAN WINS REFORM FIGHT  &HT;     By JOHN WILDERMUTH 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan's ``peasants with pitchforks'' grabbed control of
the Reform Party Tuesday as former backers of party founder Ross
Perot walked out of a rancorous party meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The crucial session of the party's 168-member national committee
meeting in Long Beach took place just before the opening of
tomorrow's four-day party convention. It was designed to let the
warring factions resolve questions about the legality of the
party's mail-in primary and an attempt to bar the conservative
Buchanan from the Reform Party ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the closed meeting ended with about 60 anti-Buchanan
delegates stalking out as uniformed police officers tried to break
up the various pushing and shouting matches taking place outside
the meeting room.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's over now,'' said Bay Buchanan, the candidate's sister and
chief political adviser. ``It is Pat Buchanan's nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   But the dissenters went to a hotel a block away and held their
own national committee meeting, which they said represented the
real Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see some semblance of order before the convention
opens, but I don't see it happening,'' said Donna Donovan, a
dissident who was fired as the Reform Party spokesman by Buchanan
backers earlier this week. ``You can't negotiate with outlaws.''
</P>
<P>
   The chaos surrounding Tuesday's meeting has been more the rule
than the exception for the Reform Party in the past few weeks. The
party, which united behind Perot four years ago, has broken into
squabbling sects as Buchanan has moved closer to the party's
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Late last month, the party's executive committee announced that
they had tossed Buchanan off the ballot for vote fraud, charging
that he had illegally signed up hundreds of thousands of his
backers as Reform Party members.
</P>
<P>
   But the next day, party chairman Gerald Moan, a Buchanan backer,
said the action was illegitimate because two of the committee
members had been recalled a month earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Buchanan said the Reform Party was doomed if they
blocked his nomination and blasted the efforts of former party
Chairman Russell Varney to keep him off the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I offer the Reform Party a fighting battle, and what Mr.
Varney and the rest of them are offering is a great mix of
Kool-Aid,'' he said, referring to the Rev. James Jones suicide
potion in Jonestown.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, a conservative commentator, bolted the Republican
Party last October after two unsuccessful runs for the GOP
presidential nomination. He said at the time that his populist
message was now a better fit for the Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   The prize for the Reform Party nomination is $12.6 million in
federal campaign funds, based on Perot's performance in 1996. While
the country is unlikely to elect a third-party candidate, the
millions in public funding could make the Reform Party candidate a
very visible player on the national scene.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Buchanan's success stems from the ``Buchanan Brigades,''
supporters he has pulled together in his other runs for the
presidency. Many of them, Republicans and independents, have
followed him in the third-party bid.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of REFORM08 (76690 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``Pat Buchanan went into 30 states and won the vast majority of
the (Reform Party) delegates,'' said K.B. Forbes, a spokesman for
Buchanan. ``On the other side are people who have lost continually,
but who won't accept it.''
</P>
<P>
   With the party ripped in half, the future of the convention also
is in doubt. Anti-Buchanan forces have suggested that they could
flood the convention with their own backers or even hold a separate
convention of their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unclear to me what's going to happen, but I imagine that
if Gerry Moan has to open the convention and turn it into a
Buchanan pep rally, it will open,'' said Donovan, a spokeswoman for
the dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 3 of REFORM08 (76690 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
