<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 00:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6439 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-FILM-PACKARD-$ADV13-2     08-09 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PACKARD-$ADV13-2TAKES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 A RICH HISTORY WORTH SAVING: Philanthropist David Packard is on
a  crusade to restore film classics  
 (For release Sunday, August 13)  
 By MICK LaSALLE  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ On a balmy Saturday night in July, shortly
before a screening of ``Roman Holiday,'' David Packard unlocks a
glass case and puts up photos of the film's star, Audrey Hepburn.
Dressed in a white short-sleeved shirt, he rearranges the photos
until he comes up with an aesthetically satisfactory arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   In another movie house, such a task might have been left to an
employee making scarcely more than minimum wage. At the Stanford,
it's done by Packard himself, the self-described ``partially
benevolent dictator'' and heir to the Hewlett-Packard billions.
</P>
<P>
   That Packard discovered and came to love classic American cinema
is one of the luckiest things that ever could have happened to
classic cinema. In the past 20 years, Packard, 59, has done more
for film preservation than any private citizen in history,
funneling millions upon millions of dollars into archives such as
the Library of Congress, the University of California at Los
Angeles and the George Eastman House.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if the Stanford is just the tip of the iceberg with regard
to Packard's efforts, it is also, to mix metaphors, the jewel in
his crown. Packard has restored the 1925 theater to lustrous glory
and devoted much of his energy to showing vintage films there. The
Stanford specializes in films from the 1910s to the early 1960s,
everything from ``Intolerance'' to ``Breakfast at Tiffany's.''
</P>
<P>
   On this night Packard takes the stage and, as is his
prerogative, introduces the film. He tells the packed audience that
Audrey Hepburn is his favorite actress. He also allows that he
wouldn't mind showing only her films, all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a great speaker,'' Packard explains a couple of days
later. ``I don't say very much. But people just like that somebody
is running the theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet all is not well in Packard's world. The week before, the
film critic for the Palo Alto Weekly, Jeanne Aufmuth, was quoted in
that newspaper as criticizing Packard's programming. She said he
showed the same films over and over, and that his movie choices
were turning the theater into a ``blue hair'' place.
</P>
<P>
   Packard is angry, and ready with statistics showing that seniors
make up only 10 percent of the audience for films such as ``Roman
Holiday'' and that 8 percent of the audience consists of people
younger than 18.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's morning, two days later. Packard is at his foundation's
office. He's still outraged. He painstakingly goes through the
schedule to show that most of the new schedule is made up of
Stanford Theatre firsts, including a series of obscure silent films
Packard recently had restored at the Stanford Theatre Foundation
Film Preservation Laboratory, his facility at UCLA. But what most
rankles him is the accusation that the Stanford is a ``blue hair''
place. ``That's the most outrageous lie.''
</P>
<P>
   He has the weekend box-office figures to prove it: 928 regular
tickets sold, 140 seniors. ``It's not that I, becoming a senior
myself, don't like seniors. It would be kind of discouraging to run
a nostalgia show with tottering old people trying to remember their
youth. That's not what's going on at the Stanford Theatre.''
</P>
<P>
   For a man who broods over comments made in a suburban weekly, he
is singularly unworried about making himself ingratiating to the
press. ``This is a reporter,'' he says to one of his employees.
``You can touch him if you like.''
</P>
<P>
   Packard is not the easiest person to talk to. At times he seems
to be applying his considerable intellect to trying to figure out
what diabolical snare awaits him behind questions such as why
Audrey Hepburn is his favorite actress. ``I hope I don't have to
explain to you why people love Audrey Hepburn,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about a comment he made about feeling ``discouraged''
with age, Packard bristles. ``You're trying to do a personal story
about me. This is not about me. This is about the theater. I told
you the rules, and I'm talking about film preservation, and the
Stanford Theatre and everything we do. I'll tell (set ital)you(end
ital) what we can talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody is put off by Packard's idiosyncratic charm. Paolo
Cherchi-Usai runs the Eastman House archive in Rochester, N.Y., and
deals with Packard regularly. ``I kind of understand why he talks
to me that way. If I were him, I'd probably do the same. It's a way
of breaking the old rules. Beneath the way he addresses you, the
tone he uses, the way he leaves you off guard, is a whole set of
challenges _ ways he wants to check your reaction. Even if I had
nothing to do with film preservation, I'd still like the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Packard did not spend his life watching movies. Until he was 35,
he had little interest in film. He was a professor of ancient Greek
at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill when a friend
invited him to a screening of ``The Wizard of Oz.'' If he had a
Damascus-like conversion, it came the second night, when he saw the
Judy Garland film ``Meet Me in St. Louis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I was, supposedly an intellectual. Why would I love `Meet
Me in St. Louis' so much? I don't know, but I loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   From then on, he ``quietly started getting interested in
movies.'' He moved to Los Angeles to teach at UCLA and gradually
got to the point where he was going to repertory houses all the
time. It was also at this point, as a board member of the David and
Lucile Packard Foundation (his parents' organization), that he
started giving grants to the UCLA Film and Television Archive.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (MORE) &LR;
</P>
