<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A MATCH MADE IN HEAVEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for changes throughout)   By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As though this presidential campaign did not
already have enough father-son drama, now comes the mother of all
contests between Father and Son.
</P>
<P>
   The main battleground state is the state of grace. Democrats and
Republicans are seeking a geographical advantage, but it is
celestial. Both sides seem weirdly obsessed with snagging a divine
endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   W. brazenly tried to lay claim to the Son, accepting Christ as
his personal savior and favorite political philosopher, and
proclaiming June 10 Jesus Day in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president chose to contest this holy ground by
revealing that he was a born-again Christian who often asked
himself ``W.W.J.D. _ What Would Jesus Do?''
</P>
<P>
   But with the two sons fighting over the Son, Gore decided to
find a running mate with direct access to the Father. The usually
cautious Gore made an inspiring and brave choice of a senator named
Lieberman, the first Jew on a major party's national ticket and a
believing and practicing Jew who regularly invokes God.
</P>
<P>
   In his Nashville debut on Tuesday, Lieberman mentioned God 13
times in 90 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The last pol to break a religious barrier, Jack Kennedy, always
played it coolly secular. He would never have prayed in a campaign
speech, or conceded he might be tied up with religious rites on
weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years ago, JFK promised to keep religion out of politics.
Now candidates promise to drench politics with religion.
</P>
<P>
   Trumpeting values and godliness is the way these boys of summer
promise to exorcise the frisky ghosts of Bill and Monica from the
sacred Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton dominates the race he is not in. In '92 he chose
Gore as his running mate because he needed the Tennessee senator's
Dudley Do-Right image. Having a Vietnam vet and a family man beside
him allowed Clinton to seem less slippery.
</P>
<P>
   Only eight years later, Mr. Clean found himself in need of a Mr.
Clean.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has come away from the White House sex and money
scandals with a patina of grime. The vice president who was chosen
for rectitude, not geography or charisma, felt he needed to choose
a running mate for rectitude, not geography or charisma.
</P>
<P>
   After defending the beleaguered Clinton as ``one of our greatest
presidents,'' Gore had to make up for that ill-considered moment by
choosing a new partner whose piety offset his old partner's
hedonism.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, the first Democratic senator to denounce Clinton as
``immoral'' during the Monica megilla, saw the offer from Gore as
comparable to being ``called to the ministry.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president is in a bitter competition with the first
lady for campaign money and attention, and yet he has ended up
picking someone who might help her in New York. (Hillary wasted no
time in trying to co-opt Lieberman to campaign with her, noting
demurely, ``but I can't be greedy.'')
</P>
<P>
   The new Democratic ticket must take care not to overdo the
sanctimony as they run away from the lame-duck rogue. Al must sweep
into Hollywood with a guy Hollywood can't stand. Lieberman has
teamed up with the conservative Bill Bennett to castigate Hollywood
for its moral ``toxicity,'' saying the town ``doesn't understand
piety.''
</P>
<P>
   He has excoriated the NBC megahit ``Friends'' as too sexy for
prime time and suggested that the FCC review the content of
programs when renewing licenses.
</P>
<P>
   In Nashville, the senator hailed Tipper for the puritanical
crusade that the Gores have spent years begging Hollywood to
forget.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Bush team praised the selection, we must keep an
eye on that nasty Republican fringe. When the going gets tough, the
hardball henchmen around the Bushes have a way of exploiting
differences and craftily implying that anyone who is not like us is
not ``on the American side,'' as Bush Pere put it at the flag
factory during the Willie Horton campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The McCains are still seething about Bush supporters in South
Carolina spreading word of their dark-skinned adopted daughter from
Bangladesh. And in '88 Michael Dukakis, with his Greek roots, was
treated as an exotic. On the Bush bus, Loretta Lynn complained of
Dukakis: ``Why, I can't even pronounce his name!''
</P>
<P>
   We can only dread what will happen when this crowd wraps its
tongue around Hadassah.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 0043EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000809.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 00:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6441 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-FILM-PACKARD-$ADV13-2     08-09 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PACKARD-$ADV13-2NDTAKE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PALO ALTO, Calif.: Television Archive.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, if Packard's manner is less than sparkling, his good
deeds are manifold. At Eastman House, for example, he has built
nitrate vaults to store archival film material. ``Most donors are
eager to spend money on a film and have their name on it,''
Cherchi-Usai says. ``Building a structure that's essentially a
large refrigerator, that's not appealing to many donors. David is
one of the few who understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Packard donated money to the American Film Institute's
three-volume catalog of ``Feature Films, 1931-40.'' His foundation
_ the Packard Humanities Institute _ is putting up $20 million
toward restoring and restructuring San Jose's Fox so it can house
Opera San Jose for part of the year. The theater will also show
movies.
</P>
<P>
   Packard's most astounding philanthropic feat was on behalf of
the Library of Congress' film archive. The archive needed a
facility to do its storing, cataloging and film restoring.
Packard's foundation spent ``6 or 7 million'' to buy a never-used
structure built by the Federal Reserve to house currency in the
event of a nuclear war.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the past two years, we've been working on a plan for
redoing it for (the Library of Congress') needs,'' Packard says.
``It will cost $100 million to complete this enormous facility.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are the kinds of numbers Packard deals in. The Packard
Humanities Institute has assets of $2 billion. ``By law, a
foundation has to spend 5 percent. We have to spend $100 million a
year, so we have a duty to concentrate on big things.'' Besides
film preservation, the institute funds projects in archaeology,
music and history. The complete papers of Thomas Jefferson,
Benjamin Franklin and George Washington are in the process of being
put online for everyone to use.
</P>
<P>
   The Stanford Theatre story began in 1987. Packard rented the
theater for two weeks to hold a Fred Astaire festival. ``I remember
pacing up and down on the Friday the festival opened, thinking to
myself, `If 50 people come, it'll be worth it.' Well, I think we
had just about a sold-out theater on Friday, and on the first
Tuesday night we sold 1,250 tickets, and it was the night of the
All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took my father there that Tuesday, and he couldn't believe
how many people were coming and what a good time they were having.
He had a very good instinct about human nature,'' Packard recalls.
``He said, `David, I never would've believed this, but you've
proved your point. If you want to do this, the foundation will pay
for it.' So we bought the theater.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stanford Theatre was closed for two years to bring it back
to its 1925 splendor and to make seismic renovations. It reopened
in December 1989 with ``The Wizard of Oz.'' Since then Packard has
balanced his appreciation for mainstream fare from Hollywood's
golden age with a willingness to show newly restored obscurities
that no commercial theater would dare put onscreen for fear of
going broke. Films restored at the preservation laboratory he set
up on the grounds of UCLA regularly turn up on the Stanford
Theatre's calendar.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really does care about movies,'' says David Francis,
curator of the Library of Congress collection. ``He is absolutely
committed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Stanford Theatre is my cultural crusade,'' Packard says.
``I want people to grow up loving Cary Grant and Audrey Hepburn and
Jimmy Stewart. I don't understand why there's one theater that
shows `Roman Holiday,' `Top Hat' and `Meet Me in St. Louis,' and
there are hundreds and hundreds showing all kinds of stuff. The
balance is way off. I'm sure some of the people seeing the
second-rate things that are out now would be happier seeing the
first-rate things made in the last 100 years.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
