r e BC-FILM-PACKARD-RESTORE-     08-09 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PACKARD-RESTORE-$ADV13-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE FILM RESTORATION WORLD, DAVID IS GOLIATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: For use with FILM-PACKARD-SFCHRON)  
 (For release Sunday, August 13)  
 By MICK LaSALLE  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ ``I've been interested in film preservation
since 1980 _ much longer and on more of a scale than anybody,''
says David Packard, owner and programmer of the Stanford Theatre in
Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Packard's work has been at the University of California
at Los Angeles, where he is regarded not just as a donor but as a
colleague as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a very advantageous relationship, very amiable and
pleasant,'' says Eddie Richmond, who runs the UCLA Film and
Television Archive. ``He shares our passion, involvement and
interest in film. For David, film preservation is a necessary step
on the way toward making films available to people. He believes
that movies are meant to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Films restored with Packard's funding include ``Morocco''
(1930), ``The Man I Killed'' (1932), ``The Smiling Lieutenant''
(1931) and ``The Plastic Age'' (1926), and there are many more. A
quick look at the calendar of UCLA's current ``Festival of
Preservation'' shows the Packard name on more than a dozen entries.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, Packard bought the film collection of the Silent Movie
Theatre on Fairfax Avenue in Los Angeles, most of it in 16mm, which
included prints of dozens of films that existed nowhere else.
Because paying labs is so expensive, and their schedules are so
tight, Packard decided to create his own preservation facility on
the grounds of UCLA. The facility is administered by UCLA
employees, who are paid indirectly by Packard's foundation through
the university.
</P>
<P>
   Packard's facility is a long, pristine room with a rather
beautiful black cast-iron machine in it. It looks as primitive as a
locomotive, but then the technology of motion pictures is
primitive. On the shelves are film cans with titles of obscure
silent films that are waiting to be seen again _ some for the first
time in more than 70 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a classical scholar by trade,'' Packard says. ``We can
read Homer and Plato because they were preserved by monks and
monasteries. Then in the Renaissance people discovered all this
stuff, and it was there. And it might not have been there. We can
read `The Iliad' and `The Odyssey,' but there were other Homeric
poems. We are at this period when a lot of the negatives aren't
going to survive forever. But at the right temperature and humidity
they'll last a lot longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent UCLA-Packard restorations include ``The Sensation
Seekers'' (1926) by director Lois Weber and ``Soul Fire'' (1925)
starring Richard Barthelmess.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the Stanford Theatre's 75th anniversary was celebrated
with a screening of ``I'll Show You the Town,'' a Reginald Denny
comedy that played on the theater's opening night in 1925.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turned out that the only material for that title was in an
archive in Europe, with Dutch and French intertitles,'' says
Richmond. ``We paid them to bring the print over to UCLA for
preservation work. We got Universal to give us the continuity so we
could reproduce the English intertitles. I came up for the
screening. It was a nice evening, and there was a large, large
crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
