<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6443 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     08-09 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CALL FOR WINGS IN THE CITY OF ANGELS  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I return from Los Angeles with good news!
</P>
<P>
   People up here who say that traffic in the Bay Area is as bad as
traffic in L.A. are rum-soaked alarmists. Either that or they
haven't been to L.A. since '49.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with Los Angeles, our traffic jams are pathetic and
scraggly. Our jams are cute, like a little kid dressing up in a
baseball uniform so he can look like a real big-leaguer.
</P>
<P>
   Rush hour in L.A. is 22 hours long. And sometimes it starts
early.
</P>
<P>
   The speediest driver in Los Angeles is Al Cowlings.
</P>
<P>
   And smog? One of these days the air in Los Angeles is going to
catch fire, and there's going to be trouble. You could make a
fortune in L.A. selling two-mile-high snorkels.
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES is, however, a good place to drive your Ford
Explorer with the self-shredding Firestone tires.
</P>
<P>
   Just kidding! After some research, I have determined that those
Firestone SUV tires that have reportedly caused dozens of deaths
are perfectly safe.
</P>
<P>
   If there really were a safety problem, the Firestone people
would establish a hotline that would be available to concerned
customers.
</P>
<P>
   There is a hotline, but it is always busy. And if you call the
Bridgestone-Firestone Technical Service Center, you are put on
permanent hold.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously the danger is just not there, otherwise a responsible
and caring company like Firestone would spend enough money to
install enough lines and operators to talk to all concerned
customers.
</P>
<P>
   I BATTED .500 on my round trip to L.A., experiencing only one
flight cancellation on United Roulette.
</P>
<P>
   The cancellations are frustrating, but here's a travel tip: Do
 &UR; not  &LR; stow away in the wheel well of a jet.
</P>
<P>
   If you think conditions are cramped and service is lousy in
coach, you should sit in wheel well. The in-flight movie is your
life flashing before your eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ONE MORE L.A. note:
</P>
<P>
   In Alhambra, a suburb about six miles east of downtown L.A.,
they've come up with a brilliant concept: traffic calming.
</P>
<P>
   It does not involve crop-dusters spritzing traffic jams with
Prozac mist, though that's an interesting concept.
</P>
<P>
   Due to an incomplete freeway nearby, a lot of commuters were
taking a daily shortcut through Alhambra, clogging that city's
traffic flow. Along the city's main roads, ``Traffic calming''
street signs are posted, as noted by reader Myles Lampenfeld.
</P>
<P>
   And to discourage this unwanted traffic, the City Council voted
to mess around with the timing of the traffic signals during rush
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Signals are set to give much less (not more) green-light time to
the short-cutters, making their jaunt through Alhambra, as one city
official told me, ``less of an enjoyable ride.''
</P>
<P>
   By the way, the ``Traffic calming'' is carried out by the city's
Dept. of Public Works, the director of which is Jim Funk.
</P>
<P>
   AND SPEAKING OF fine names, the Claremont Hotel is under fire
(so to speak) for its heavy-handed brush clearance.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors call the project ``clear-cutting.''
</P>
<P>
   The Claremont's defense is presented by hotel manager Ted Axe.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE tabbed Joe Lieberman as his running mate. Cynics say
this is a cheap attempt to disarm critics of the present
administration's ethics.
</P>
<P>
   To which loyal Dems scoff, ``What ethics?''
</P>
<P>
   As an optimistic Democrat, I prefer to look at it this way: Now
the ticket's integrity tank is half-full.
</P>
<P>
   But sadly, Gore overlooked the lesson the American public made
clear in the last three presidential elections: A clown as VP
really sells the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   --The agricultural region in Russia bordering Kazakhstan has
been hit with a 14-mile-long locust swarm. Would it be worth
diverting that swarm to the Napa Valley, to see if the locusts will
eat the glassy-winged sharpshooters?
</P>
<P>
   --Dick Armey told an off-color gay joke about Barney Frank, and
Armey's spokesperson Michelle Davis explained, ``It's a bad joke,
and he was just trying to get it over with.'' So shouldn't we send
all the bad, offensive and off-color jokes we can think of to Dick
Armey, so he can tell them at parties and get them all over with?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 0046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
