<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6445 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-UNITED-DNC-LADN     08-09 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNITED-DNC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITED'S SCHEDULING PROBLEMS COULD HAMPER DNC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOMINIC BERBEO and JASON KANDEL 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; United Airlines, the official airline of the
Democratic National Convention, canceled 14 flights at LAX and 226
worldwide on Tuesday amid pilot contract talks _ representing a
possible snag for the upcoming high-profile political event.
</P>
<P>
   Between Saturday and Tuesday, the airline reported at least
1,080 of its 2,400 daily flights worldwide had been canceled,
mostly due to bad weather and an increase in sick calls by pilots
who have vowed not to work overtime until a new contract is
reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw a sharp increase in the number of sick calls by pilots
over the weekend,'' said United spokesman Matthew Triaca, who said
the sick calls contributed to the cancellation of at least 14 of
210 scheduled flights at LAX.
</P>
<P>
   Triaca said the airline would take every precaution to ensure
negotiations don't upset next week's Democratic convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be fully staffed, and make every provision to
accommodate our customers,'' he said. ``We don't expect any
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Ragone, a DNC spokesman, predicted the cancellations would
not affect the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, there has been no indication that the negotiations at
United are affecting the flight plans of those coming to town for
the convention,'' he said. ``We're hoping it stays that way.''
</P>
<P>
   United says its pilots have refused to work overtime since their
five-year contract expired April 12 and have increasingly called in
sick. But the pilots say there is no organized work slowdown and
problems are more the result of United's failure to hire enough
pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Union spokesman Herb Hunter said there is no planned action to
disrupt the Democratic convention but couldn't promise hassle-free
flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would think United would want to have enough pilots and
flights available for the DNC, but that's up to them,'' Hunter
said. ``We don't know what will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   In May, United began canceling flights worldwide, eliminating
some 4,800 of its 70,000 monthly flights between May and August, a
trend connected to the negotiations, Triaca said.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, United President Rono Dutta apologized
to passengers for the inconvenience of the delayed and canceled
flights, which he said were exacerbated this past weekend by
disgruntled pilots and bad weather conditions nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   United is offering for passengers who experienced flight
cancellations vouchers redeemable on competing airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Issues related to contract negotiations with our pilots were
compounded by severe thunderstorm activity in the Midwest and along
the East Coast,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Burbank Airport on Tuesday, three scheduled United arrivals
were canceled, airport spokesman Victor Gill said. United makes up
about 15 percent of all flights in and out of Burbank.
</P>
<P>
   As the number of canceled flights accumulated, passengers at
Burbank Airport anxiously awaited news of rescheduled flights,
while others took the delays in stride.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Murdock, 50, of Silverlake was a little nervous as he
counted the minutes until his scheduled departure for San Francisco
for a speaking engagement at a computer symposium of 100 people.
Because his 2:28 p.m. flight had been canceled, the airline gave
him the option of catching the next flight at 4:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I have to figure out, OK, 15 minutes to get to the hotel,
15 minutes to change and freshen up, and then I have to get there,
and I'm the first speaker,'' Murdock said. ``I'm cutting it a
little close.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Rogers, 54, got his flight bumped two hours earlier. He
didn't mind. He was headed home to San Francisco from a student
loan conference in Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm used to delays with United,'' he said while sitting in the
terminal, taking a break from reading the newspaper. ``But this
time, I got a flight two hours earlier _ if it leaves on time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
