A6446 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-GORE-VEEP-SFCHRON &LR;      08-09 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-VEEP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 LIEBERMAN LAUDS GORE FOR `ACT OF CHUTZPAH'  &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Evoking the memory of John Kennedy, the nation's
first Roman Catholic president, Vice President Al Gore said Tuesday
that Democrats are prepared to ``tear down an old wall of division
once again'' by nominating Connecticut Sen. Joe Lieberman as his
running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe and I come from different regions and different religious
faiths, but we believe in a common set of ideals,'' Gore said at a
rally in Nashville, Tenn., where he formally introduced Lieberman
as his choice for vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, an Orthodox Jew and the first non-Christian ever to
appear on either major party's presidential ticket, began his
remarks with a personal invocation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Lord, maker of all miracles, I thank you for bringing me
to this extraordinary moment in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   He then praised Gore for ``breaking this barrier for the rest of
America forever.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, there are some people who might actually call Al's
selection of me an act of chutzpah,'' a smiling Lieberman said to
cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Lieberman stood beside their wives in the broiling
Tennessee sunshine, taking off their jackets to reveal matching
white shirts dripping with sweat.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic ticket was buoyed by news that the United Auto
Workers had decided to endorse their candidacy after months of
openly flirting with third-party candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Union President Stephen P. Yokich said in a statement, ``It's no
secret that we disagree _ and disagree sharply. ... Yet even on
trade, where we don't see eye-to-eye, Al Gore is better, much
better, than George W. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   An overnight CNN/Gallup poll, which had Bush ahead of Gore by a
double-digit margin earlier this week, suddenly showed the race had
tightened to a statistical dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's reputation for moral rectitude and nonpartisan
behavior is making him a difficult target for Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush praised Lieberman for his ``convictions, his strong faith''
and his positions on Social Security, missile defenses and school
vouchers. Like the Texas governor, Lieberman has expressed support
for private investment of Social Security funds, investment in a
missile defense system and school vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This selection now presents the vice president with an
interesting test of whether he will continue attacking positions
his running mate shares or whether he will lift up our nation by
elevating the tone of his presidential campaign,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Standing beside Gore Tuesday, Lieberman ridiculed the notion
that he could be mistaken for a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all due respect,'' Lieberman said to laughs, ``I think
that's like saying that the veterinarian and the taxidermist are in
the same business because either way, you get your dog back.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman borrowed a line that then Vice President George Bush,
father of the GOP nominee, used during his 1988 campaign against
Michael Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have to change horses in midstream, doesn't it make
sense to get the one that's going in the right direction?''
Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Gore nor Lieberman ever mentioned President Clinton
during the 45-minute-long rally.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman wasted no time trying to leverage his reputation for
integrity to bolster Gore's standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leadership is not just another word, it means something. It
requires courage. It requires character,'' Lieberman said. ``And I
stand here today and say to you from personal experience that Al
Gore has both.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman called Gore ``a man of family and a man of faith.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has never wavered in his responsibilities as a father, as a
husband and, yes, as a servant of God Almighty,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   It is his ability to deliver such an endorsement that made
Lieberman an attractive candidate to Gore, who is under attack from
Republicans for being too closely associated with Clinton and eight
years of White House scandals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican convention really focused attention on the need
for something other than a third term for Clinton-Gore,'' said
Democrat Geraldine Ferraro, whose selection as Walter Mondale's
running mate in 1984 also made history.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman was preceded to the podium by his wife, Hadassah, who
was born to Holocaust survivors in Czechoslovakia and emigrated to
the United States when she was 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether you and your family immigrated from Europe, Africa,
Mexico, Latin America or Asia, I am standing here for you,'' she
said. ``This country is our country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
