<SLUG> BC-GAS-PRICES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RISING NATURAL GAS PRICES BAFFLE INDUSTRY ANALYSTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A budding debate within the natural gas
industry is raising questions about why prices have more than
doubled since last November.
</P>
<P>
   One of the latest groups to weigh in, the American Gas
Association, had expected some price increases as an incentive to
boost gas production. But it didn't expect _ nor did many others _
the steep run-up of recent months.
</P>
<P>
   The gas association also is skeptical about some of the reasons
cited to explain the boost, especially the explanation that
electric utilities are increasing their use of gas to produce
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is out of balance,'' said Paul Wilkinson, the gas
association's vice president of policy.
</P>
<P>
   This week wholesale gas prices have been about $4.50 per
thousand cubic feet, compared with $2 last November. Wholesale
prices are passed on directly to consumers, and if current prices
hold up, they would cost an average household an additional $200 to
$300 this winter. Nationwide, the additional cost to residential
customers could top $6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Even if gas prices fall, consumers will still be hit with higher
bills because utilities have been buying and storing some of the
gas that will be used in the winter. And it's not just households
who can expect higher bills. Commercial customers are preparing,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Budgets are going up to meet the extra cost,'' said Jim
Zakoura, an attorney for Kansas Industrial Consumers, an
association of large commercial users of energy.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about why prices are up have mainly been raised within
the natural gas industry. But that's likely to change as winter
approaches and higher heating bills start hitting mailboxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are valid questions,'' said David Sommerer, head of the
Missouri Public Service Commission's gas procurement division.
</P>
<P>
   The doubts have zeroed in on several areas. Traders have been
using the American Gas Association's weekly storage numbers as
evidence that utilities will have trouble meeting demand this
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Though stockpiles are running slightly behind, there will be
sufficient gas in storage by winter, says the gas association.
Nevertheless, the storage numbers have caused gas prices to swing
as much as 20 percent in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like it, and nobody (who's in the market buying gas)
likes it,'' said Michael Eichenberg, president of Mountain Energy,
a Kansas City marketer of natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   But among the reasons given in recent months for the price
increases, perhaps none has baffled observers as much as the one
involving electric utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Natural gas prices began to increase in earnest in May on the
New York Mercantile Exchange, where contracts for future delivery
of natural gas are bought and sold. The futures market is widely
followed by the natural gas industry and is influential in setting
wholesale prices.
</P>
<P>
   Traders were keeping an eye on temperatures across the country.
Bloomberg Business News asked a trader why prices were up that day.
The answer: It was going to get hot.
</P>
<P>
   Electric utilities were adding more generation to handle peak
days of demand, and most of it was going to be powered by natural
gas.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Van Cleve, a trader with TW Energy Consultants in the
Kansas City area, recalls seeing accounts about the gas-fired
generation coming into operations and how that would increase
demand for natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen plenty of stories,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even the federal Energy Information Administration was taking
seriously the effect of electric utilities on gas use and price. In
its energy outlook for July, it singled out electric utilities as
the reason behind the higher gas prices.
</P>
<P>
   But others were puzzled by the assertion. The energy
administration's own estimates showed electric utility consumption
of gas would be flat this year.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, any numbers on electric utility consumption of natural
gas are difficult to find, said Wilkinson of the gas association.
Nevertheless, the natural gas markets responded to fears that the
demand from electric utilities would stretch supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's helped create a crisis mentality,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That traders were overplaying the electric utility angle was
also the point of a study by Energy Security Analysis, an
independent energy research group in Wakefield, Mass. It looked at
how much gas-fired generation was coming on line and, taking into
account the weather, how much natural gas would be used.
</P>
<P>
   Its conclusion: a modest increase in overall demand. It
estimated that there was a 1 percent increase in the draw on
natural gas supplies by the electric utilities that was more than
balanced by weakness in other areas of demand for natural gas. The
research group questioned whether there was support for today's
high prices.
</P>
<P>
   If the assessment is true, can consumers expect prices to
eventually get back down to $2 or below? Not necessarily.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Eliason, vice president of gas strategy for Kansas Gas
Service, said there were sound reasons for prices not to return to
those levels. When prices sank below $2, producers scaled back
production of extra gas _ and supplies tightened up.
</P>
<P>
   His estimate is that wholesale prices between $2.50 and $3 per
thousand cubic feet will be sufficient incentive for producers to
meet future demand. Although that doesn't mean that the markets
won't deliver some price shocks along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's emotion in today's (gas markets),'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 0102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
