<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CURBSIDE-RECYCLING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY RESIDENTS TURN DOWN CURBSIDE RECYCLING PROPOSAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MANSUR  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ For a third time since 1990, Kansas City
voters on Tuesday rejected a citywide curbside recycling program,
this time by a ratio of 54 percent to 46 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Although winning in precincts along the state line from downtown
to the Waldo neighborhood, the measure failed everywhere else.
Still, proponents pledged Tuesday to keep pushing for a different
way to pay for the service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to give up on curbside recycling,'' said Bob
Mann, leader of Citizens for Recycling. ``We're going to look for
other options.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote with more than 97% of precincts reporting: Yes 22,410,
No 26,250
</P>
<P>
   City leaders should be persuaded to find a way to start curbside
recycling because the election results show a large percentage of
Kansas City residents are willing to pay for it, Mann said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly believe we'll have curbside recycling in the next
three years,'' he said. ``I really believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the precincts supporting the measure Tuesday already pay
for curbside recycling through homes associations.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the program's opponents have made clear they are not
against recycling, but they object to forcing everyone, including
senior citizens on fixed incomes, to pay the $1.95 monthly fee for
the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Kansas Citians favor recycling overwhelmingly,'' said
Mark Bryant, president of Freedom Inc., a political club
influential in the black community. ``But they disagreed with the
finance plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also think it's time for the proponents to get the message
on the financing plan and find alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City proposal would have included single-family and
duplex households _ about 133,000. They would have paid the monthly
fee with their water bills. Apartment buildings of up to six units
could have subscribed voluntarily. Trash service would not have
been affected.
</P>
<P>
   The materials proposed for collection: all paper other than
tissue and wax-coated, including cardboard, magazines, catalogs,
junk mail and newspaper; No. 1 and No. 2 plastic items; steel cans;
and aluminum.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, Proposition 2 on the ballot, each household
would have received a bin for paper and a second for the other
materials. Each bin would have been collected at the curb on
alternating weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The program and the $1.95 monthly charge were to start in late
winter or early spring. The proposal would have required the city
to seek voter approval if it ever wanted to charge more than $2.50
per month.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign on behalf of the proposal was low-key, relying on a
network of avid recyclers built over the last decade by Bridging
the Gap. The group was formed after the 1992 defeat of curbside
recycling.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, voters also rejected curbside recycling, but this year
Mann hoped that a large network of volunteers who regularly showed
up at community drop-off centers would go to the polls Tuesday to
carry the recycling proposal to victory.
</P>
<P>
   Mann's group also has begun a statewide Environmental Excellence
Campaign, to which 25,000 individuals have subscribed. He hoped
those supporters also would push the proposal beyond its past
problems at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat Tuesday left Kansas City among just a few major U.S.
cities without curbside recycling, but Mann said the city's
environmental ethic has improved greatly since voters rejected the
program in the early 1990s. What's more, Kansas City doesn't
deserve the anti-recycling image created by the voter rejections of
recycling, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't deserve that reputation,'' Mann said. ``Overland Park
never had to vote on it. Would (nearby) Overland Park (Kan.) have
passed it eight years ago? I don't know. But certainly other cities
would have voted it down.''
</P>
<P>
   Mann added that recycling proponents had much to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the only city in America that has to deal with the
earnings tax, the Hancock Amendment and free trash service,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, city leaders promised to use the earnings tax to pay
for trash services. Missouri's Hancock Amendment requires voter
approval of fees and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   In light of the defeat, city officials will examine how to
adjust the city's existing recycling service _ a system of drop-off
centers, most of them open only on weekends, said John Stufflebean,
who directs the city's environmental management office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to do a comprehensive look at where we'll go with
recycling over the next five years,'' Stufflebean said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 0111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000809.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6450 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-STUDENT-HARASSMENT-KA     08-09 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDENT-HARASSMENT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL DISTRICT TO PAY $72,500 TO FORMER STUDENT IN HARASSMENT
CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Pleasant Hill Public School District has
agreed to pay $72,500 to a former student who alleged he was
sexually harassed by other students who thought he was gay.
</P>
<P>
   The district also has agreed with the U.S. Justice Department to
establish a two-year program to ``prevent, identify and remediate
harassment and discrimination'' on the basis of sex or sexual
orientation.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials and others said the program
required by the settlement appeared to be the first in the nation
authorized to protect students based on their sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the first intervention that we're aware of and it's very
important,'' said Patricia Logue, supervising attorney for the
Lambda Legal Defense and Education Fund's Midwest office in
Chicago. ``It really makes clear how much abuse is targeted at gay
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lambda fund works for the rights of homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Patterson, the attorney representing the former student,
said his client was happy with the settlement of the year-old civil
rights lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pleased the school district will make a commitment in
the future to prevent any sort of harassment and ensure this sort
of thing doesn't happen again,'' Patterson said.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer representing the school district noted that, in
agreeing to the settlement, school officials acknowledged no
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this transpired before we had a new school board,
superintendent and administration,'' said Thomas Mickes of St.
Louis. ``They looked at this and said we've got some good legal
arguments. But whether or not it technically violates the law,
everybody deserves to go to school in an environment free of
teasing or harassment.''
</P>
<P>
   In his lawsuit, the student contended that he was sexually
harassed by his classmates, who incorrectly thought he was gay.
Furthermore, the student alleged that Pleasant Hill administrators
knew of the harassment, but did nothing to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   The student said the harassment stretched over four years,
beginning in 1994 when he was 14. The lawsuit alleged the boy was
called names in the school cafeteria and corridors, beaten and
nearly run over by a car driven by two classmates.
</P>
<P>
   Before the settlement, district officials argued they had taken
reasonable steps to stop the harassment when they learned of it.
</P>
<P>
   The order, signed July 31 by U.S. District Judge Fernando Gaitan
Jr., followed an earlier decision by the Justice Department last
month to join the case on the student's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   In the settlement, the district agreed to hire consultants to
prepare a plan to identify and eliminate discrimination and
harassment based on sex or sexual orientation within the district.
</P>
<P>
   That plan will include regular reports to the Justice
Department, written procedures and standards, training for school
staff members and development of a student curriculum on
harassment.
</P>
<P>
   According to the order, the district will remain under federal
scrutiny until September 2002, assuming the Justice Department does
not file for an extension of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was among the first filed in Kansas City last year
after a U.S. Supreme Court ruling opened the door to actions based
on student-on-student sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   A similar lawsuit filed on behalf of a girl in the Richmond
(Mo.) School District settled recently for $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers filed with the settlement, the district also
denied any liability or wrongdoing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
