<HEADLINE>
MEDIA ATTENTION SUBSIDES AT KANSAS BOARD OF EDUCATION MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE BEEM  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPEKA, Kan. _ What a difference a year makes.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, 60 persons addressed the Kansas Board of Education,
and journalists and cameras packed the board room for two days as
the board discussed and voted on science standards that would
downplay evolution.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday the cameras were gone. Three speakers came forward.
One addressed the science standards, which appear to be on the way
out.
</P>
<P>
   But the debate continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue is not going to die or become extinct,'' Judy
Smith, state director of Concerned Women for America, a
conservative group, told the board. ``Because of the attention
those promoting evolution have given it, this issue now has a life
of its own.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith criticized recent promises made by moderate Republicans
and Democrats running for the state board to rewrite the science
standards, which do not include references to the age of the earth,
the big-bang theory of the universe's origin and some aspects of
evolutionary theory.
</P>
<P>
   The standards are guidelines for what Kansas students should
learn and are tested on. The state board, which oversees the
state's 304 school districts, voted 6-4 a year ago to approve them.
Five conservatives and a moderate backed the standards; four
moderates voted against them.
</P>
<P>
   The vote on evolution _ the theory that living things share
common ancestors but have changed over time _ reinvigorated the
longstanding debate over science and religion. The six board
members who voted to downplay evolution cited, in part, their
hesitation to include information that would go against some
students' religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives Linda Holloway of Shawnee and Mary Douglass Brown
of Wichita _ two of the six members who supported the standards _
lost re-election bids in the Republican primary a week ago. A third
conservative, Abilene farmer Scott Hill, resigned his seat in July.
</P>
<P>
   Hill's successor, Salina lawyer Bruce Wyatt, was appointed by
Gov. Bill Graves on Monday and sworn in. Wyatt began his tenure at
Tuesday's meeting. He said on a break that if he won his Nov. 7
race against Democrat Eloise Lynch of Salina, he would make a
motion in January to reopen debate over the science standards.
</P>
<P>
   Wyatt and other candidates want to bring back a set of
standards, written by a 27-member committee of science teachers and
professors, that lists evolution as a concept unifying all
scientific disciplines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe evolution should be included in the science
standards, because it is the consensus of the worldwide scientific
community,'' Wyatt said.
</P>
<P>
   That is what Loren Lutes and John Staver have been saying all
along. On Tuesday the co-chairmen of the 27-member committee sat
silently in the back of the board room. They said later that they
had begun working on a sixth draft of their committee's standards.
</P>
<P>
   Lutes, superintendent of the Oskaloosa School District, and
Staver, a science education professor at Kansas State University,
say they had learned much in the last year that would make their
next set of standards better.
</P>
<P>
   ``As science educators, we were not as careful to make sure that
people learned the difference between science and beliefs,'' Lutes
said. ``And we're dedicated to doing a better job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
