<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S VETO LOGIC A BIT FLAWED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: President Clinton's explanation for his opposition to
tax relief for married couples seems to contradict conventional
politicoeconomic wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   When he vetoed legislation designed to give married couples an
election-year income tax break, he said giving the tax break would
undermine the fiscal discipline responsible for sustaining what has
been a record economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
   This reasoning, however, runs counter to long-held Keynesian
orthodoxy among Democrats that governments can best stimulate
economic growth by getting money into the hands of the public to
spur consumption. It's called pump-priming and even the Republicans
embraced their version of the concept by turning to supply-side
economics. Supply-siders believe lower taxes encourage productive
behavior, but ultimately the same goal is served by encouraging
consumer activity.
</P>
<P>
   What is even more curious about the president's position is that
he has indicated a willingness to go along with the GOP bid to end
the marriage penalty in return for support of his proposal to
implement a Medicare prescription drug benefit. The Republicans
aren't buying the proffered quid pro quo, though, because they have
their own drug benefit plan, which is less expansive.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what anyone thinks of the idea of government
helping seniors with prescription costs, adding this entitlement to
Medicare will certainly cost as much over time as the revenue hit
Uncle Sam would take if the marriage penalty is ended. This reality
implies the president is being less than forthright when explaining
his motives for opposing the GOP on the marriage penalty issue.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the matter of President Clinton's characterization
of marriage penalty relief as a ``tax giveaway.'' This, of course,
hews to the mindset that Washington should have first claim to the
fruits of the citizenry's labor even if it doesn't need all the
resources it's claiming.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government is reaping record amounts of revenue,
thanks to a booming economy and two substantial tax increases
during the past decade. The surpluses it boasts aren't budget
surpluses, as claimed, but tax surpluses that rightfully belong to
the taxpayers who made them possible.
</P>
<P>
   Although these surpluses are supposed to be sacrosanct in the
name of financing great future initiatives, they really don't
exist. If you believe they do, ask somebody in the federal
government to show you the account designated ``surplus revenue to
be used later to pay for great stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   They can't because in the scheme of federal finance money comes
in and money goes out. Since it can't be saved, it gets spent.
</P>
<P>
   Even if there were a mechanism by which extra revenue could be
saved, it wouldn't be saved in the sense we understand the concept
because politicians will spend every cent available to them. Most
politicians are hard-wired to tax away all the revenue they can
squeeze from taxpayers. The most talented are masters at plucking
the goose without causing a lot of undue hissing on the part of the
victim.
</P>
<P>
   So what if the GOP is indeed playing an election-year game with
its tax-cut campaign? If this is what it takes for taxpayers to get
a fair shake from Washington, it's worth it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
