<HEADLINE>
MENDED MERCKER MAKES WAY BACK INTO ROTATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ When pitcher Kent Mercker learned that he had
suffered a cerebral hemorrhage on the Edison Field mound May 11, he
didn't know if he'd live long enough to see his children graduate
from high school, let alone if he'd ever pitch again.
</P>
<P>
   But Mercker is back _ he will start Saturday's game for the
Anaheim Angels against the New York Yankees at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's going to be an emotional day for me,'' he
said. ``I got pumped up pitching in my rehab assignment, but that's
not the same as taking the mound in a major-league game.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercker underwent days of tests immediately following the
hemorrhage, and doctors concluded it was caused by a blood vessel
that burst and disintegrated. There was no malformation of blood
vessels, no aneurysm and therefore virtually no chance of another
hemorrhage.
</P>
<P>
   But until that determination was made, Mercker had to live with
the thought that his life was in immediate danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, you definitely think that,'' he said. ``They tell you
your brain's bleeding and they don't know why. If they do the tests
oblem that it could happen again. But they came back and told me
no.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercker will take the mound three months and one day after the
incident, but it is sooner than the Angels had planned. Mercker was
supposed to make a second rehab start tonight, but because Angels
pitchers are dropping faster than even they are used to, there was
a need for the quick return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's ready to take on the challenge of competing at
the major-league level,'' manager Mike Scioscia said. ``We'd like
to get upwards of 80 pitches from him, and that should be enough to
get him deep enough into the game.''
</P>
<P>
   !tvspt2!Moving day: Monday was a day of many changes for the
pitching staff. Ken Hill was released and Brian Cooper was sent to
Triple-A Edmonton. Ramon Ortiz was called up. Jarrod Washburn was
activated from the disabled list before the game, then placed back
on the disabled list after the game.
</P>
<P>
   That left the Angels short a pitcher Tuesday. But instead of
calling up another pitcher, they called up outfielder/first baseman
Chris Hatcher. Hatcher, who was acquired by the Angels from the
Cubs in a trade July 28, has a combined 26 home runs and 77 RBI
this season with Triple-A Iowa and Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels currently have a three-man starting rotation of
Ortiz, Matt Wise and Scott Schoeneweis. Mercker will be the fourth
starter when he is activated Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
