<HEADLINE>
SERENA WILLIAMS NEEDS ONLY 38 MINUTES IN FIRST ROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN BEACH, Calif. _ Any doubts about Serena Williams'
condition following a five-week layoff were officially vanquished
early in her first-round match against Ruxandra Dragomir at the
estyle.com Classic on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, the tournament's defending champion who had not played
since Wimbledon, dominated all facets of the match and needed just
38 minutes to earn a 6-0, 6-1 victory at Manhattan Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really ready to play,'' Williams said. ``I was
practicing (Monday) and telling my dad how ready and eager I was to
get back out there.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, Dragomir, a 27-year-old Romanian, was a good
sport. The crowd cheered her on, presumably because they wanted
more than a half-hour of tennis for their admission fee, and
Dragomir obliged them by raising her left fist in the air after
winning her only game.
</P>
<P>
   It was the only moment of levity for Dragomir, who could never
quite get the correct timing on Williams' powerful baseline strokes
and sent ball after ball sailing out of play.
</P>
<P>
   Typical of Williams, however, she found something she could
improve on, which must be a terrifying thought to Dragomir and
Tamarine Tanasugarn, the qualifier who Williams will face this
afternoon in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I thought I could have played a lot better,''
Williams said. ``I could have served a lot better. My highest serve
was 110, and it's usually 118 or 119. I actually tried to hit it
hard, and I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who turns 19 next month, is using Manhattan Beach as a
tuneup for the U.S. Open, where she will attempt to defend her only
Grand Slam title. Other players might be concerned about building
some confidence and momentum after a long break, but not Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``My confidence is pretty much at the same level all the time,''
Williams said. ``I'm feeling pretty good about my game right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to get back to playing like I did at
Wimbledon. Play quick and get off the court fast so I can focus on
my mental game.''
</P>
<P>
   Another youngster made a big impact Tuesday and pulled the first
upset of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Daja Bedanova, a 17-year-old from the Czech Republic in her
first year as a professional, recorded her first win over a top-10
player when she earned a 6-3, 6-4 victory over France's Nathalie
Tauziat, seeded sixth and ranked eighth in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Bedanova's only previous experience against a top-10 player was
last year, when she lost to Venus Williams in Philadelphia. She
stayed in control of Tauziat for much of the match and had her
serve broken just once.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end it was much better, but in the beginning I was very
nervous,'' said Bedanova, the youngest player at Manhattan Beach
this week.``I think I played some good games.''
</P>
<P>
   Amy Frazier, who won the Manhattan Beach tournament in 1994,
started slowly but rallied to easily defeat qualifier Marlene
Weingartner of Germany, 7-6 (8-6), 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier pulled off a stunning upset of top-seeded Martina Hingis
in last week's Acura Classic in Carlsbad but doesn't display much
of the confidence of a player on a hot streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I've been playing well, but I'm not sure that last
week or the past couple weeks have anything to do with this week,''
said Frazier, who will face Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario in the second
round. ``This tournament is so tough, it just feels good to get out
of the first round.''
</P>
<P>
   In other first-round matches, Sanchez-Vicario, the seventh seed,
defeated Barbara Schett of Austria 6-4, 6-1; eighth-seeded Sandrine
Testudof France beat Russia's Elena Likhovtseva, 6-2, 6-4;
qualifier Tamarine Tanasugarn of Thailand beat Spain's Magui Serna
6-7 (6-8), 6-3, 7-5; and Belgium's Dominique Van Roost beat Russian
qualifier Tatiana Panova 6-1, 6-2. American Lisa Raymond beat
Mirjana Lucic of Croatia 6-3, 6-3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 0135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
