<DOCNO> NYT20000809.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6455 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-REPLACEMENTS-HNS &LR;      08-09 1645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REPLACEMENTS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Casserly likes how The Replacements captures '87 strike
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN McCLAIN
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The Replacements, the Keanu Reeves/Gene Hackman film
based on the 1987 NFL players strike, is bringing back a flood of
fond memories for Charley Casserly, general manager of Houston's
expansion team.
</P>
<P>
   The Replacements, which opens nationwide Friday, is based on the
Washington strike team that went 3-0 and helped pave the way for
the Joe Gibbs-coached Redskins to win Super Bowl XXII.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt, it's the best football movie ever,'' Casserly
said after watching a special screening. ``In a four-star system,
I'd give it five stars _ four for the movie and one for Washington
beating Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   As Bobby Beathard's assistant general manager with the Redskins
in 1987, Casserly was largely responsible for finding and signing
the replacement players who defeated the Rams, Giants and Cowboys
before the strike ended.
</P>
<P>
   As the general manager for owner Bob McNair's team, Casserly
will make the first pick in the 2002 draft. He is hoping a
franchise quarterback will be available, but he won't reach for
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Keanu Reeves will be a free agent,'' Casserly said. ``I
like his mechanics, arm strength and leadership ability, but I
don't know if we could fit him in our salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see. He got $11 million for the movie and had to play
only four games. That's $44 million for a regular season. I don't
know if even Bob McNair can afford that, but he'd be a great draw,
wouldn't he?''
</P>
<P>
   In the film, Reeves replaces Houston native Brett Cullen, the $8
million-a-year superstar quarterback who leads his striking
teammates off the field and into the picket line.
</P>
<P>
   Hackman is a George Allen-type coach who had been fired by Jack
Warden, a Jack Kent Cooke-type owner. Warden convinces Hackman to
coach the replacement team.
</P>
<P>
   The producers had to follow strict guidelines. For legal
reasons, nowhere in advertisements, promotional material or the
film itself is there any mention of anything or anyone related to
the NFL. The team is called the Washington Sentinels. No color
schemes that had been used in the NFL within the last 10 years
could be used for players or cheerleaders in the film.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran screenwriter Vince McKewin disclosed when filming began
a year ago at the Baltimore Ravens' PSINet Stadium that he was a
devoted Redskins fan who based much of his script on Washington's
team of replacement players. The brainchild behind the film was
producer Dylan Sellers, who came up with the idea when he was
bedridden with the flu and watching a television show about the
1987 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an unprecedented time in the NFL,'' Casserly said.
``Gibbs and his staff should get all the credit for doing a
marvelous coaching job. Joe and Bobby constantly preached to our
regular players to stay together _ to go out together or to come in
together. Gibbs stayed loyal to the regular players and did a
masterful job of walking down the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went into the movie with some reservations, but I have to
admit that I thought it was great. A lot of what we went through
during that period is on the screen.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, after the players went on strike, they picketed on
the street outside the facility and threw eggs and rocks at buses
bringing replacement players to their first practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one scene, a player cracks a window in a bus,'' Casserly
said. ``When that happened at our facility, one of our defensive
linemen, Darryl Grant (who played at Rice), actually stood in front
of a bus and forced it to stop. Then he smashed the window and
broke it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost a couple of (replacement) players because of that.
They were afraid of more retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knew that a strike was possible. We tried to prepare
by keeping close tabs on players we cut during camp and preseason
that season and the season before. We didn't go after big-name
players. We were careful to try to sign players familiar with
Gibbs' offensive system and (Richie) Petitbon's defensive system.''
</P>
<P>
   Casserly, whose 23-year career with the Redskins ended last year
when he was fired by owner Daniel Snyder, made two trips to the
film's location and was impressed with the football scenes and the
accuracy of the script.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of those scenes brought back some great memories,''
Casserly said. ``In the movie, there's an offensive lineman who's
incredibly fat. I remember we signed one lineman who was so fat
I'll never forget what (offensive line coach) Joe Bugel told Gibbs.
He said, `Damn, Joe, when I reached out to show him how to use his
hands to block, my hand disappeared into his stomach.'
</P>
<P>
   ``In another scene, they sign a player out of prison. We
actually signed four from a halfway house. We had this safety from
Texas Tech (Charles Jackson). After our first night together, I
remember him saying, `I'm proud to represent the state of
Washington.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Linemen were the hardest players to find, especially on
offense. We were desperate. I called a coach at Cal
State-Northridge and asked him about one of his former players. The
coach said he was big and tough but didn't know what kind of shape
he was in.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a time like that, big and tough was good enough for me. The
guy was student-teaching when we signed him. We didn't have time
for physicals. I remember he came to my second-floor office right
after he got there. He was huffing and puffing. I asked him if
they'd already had him on the treadmill or he'd been lifting
weights. When he was finally able to catch his breath, he said,
`Stairs,' and I thought, `Oh, my God.' But we signed him.''
</P>
<P>
   The cast of Hollywood characters compares with those in real
life. In The Replacements, there are offensive linemen so fat they
look as if they're going to explode; a super-fast wide receiver
with pitchfork hands; a maniacal middle linebacker; a European
kicker with a serious cigarette addiction; a born-again Christian;
and a deaf receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to constantly recruit players because so many left or
got hurt,'' Casserly said. ``Everyone was desperate for players.
Our drug test consisted of just asking them if they used any drugs.
It's just amazing what teams were going through.''
</P>
<P>
   In the film, the team recruits replacement cheerleaders. Because
of a shortage, they're forced to hire a few strippers. There were
no replacement cheerleaders, but McKewin had to produce a love
interest for Reeves. Brooke Langton, who was on Melrose Place for
two years, co-stars as the head cheerleader who falls in love with
Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the cheerleaders have one of the film's best scenes.
When the Sentinels are behind in one game, the cheerleaders do a
wicked routine to Donna Summer's Bad Girls, distracting the
opposing offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that impressed me the most when I visited
the set was how interested they were in what actually happened
during the strike,'' Casserly said. ``Hackman was such a class act,
a true professional. In the movie, he's got total control, just
like George Allen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's one scene where he's making a speech to motivate his
players. I remember Gibbs telling them the same thing. It was
before our last strike game at Dallas. Everyone knew the strike was
ending after that game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe told them something like, `Men, it's a cliche to say
there's no tomorrow, but for you guys, there really is no tomorrow.
All of you wanted a second chance. Well, what more could you ask
for in a second chance? The Dallas Cowboys on Monday Night Football
in Texas Stadium.' And you know what? They went out and beat the
Cowboys.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys had many of their regular players, including Tony
Dorsett, Randy White, Danny White and Ed ``Too Tall'' Jones, cross
the picket line before the Redskins game. The Redskins were
lopsided underdogs but pulled out a 13-7 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truthfully, the Cowboys' minds weren't on that game,''
Casserly said. ``With all the attention given to players crossing
the picket line, I think they were pretty distracted. We got a
couple of big hits early on `Too Tall' and Randy White, and they
were never the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back, it's kind of funny because (former Cowboys
general manager) Tex Schramm is the one who came up with the idea
for replacement players before the season. Our replacement players
beat his regulars.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, though, our guys were going to come in, too, before
that game. The league rule said players had to come in no later
than Wednesday to be eligible to play that Sunday. Because the game
was on Monday, our guys thought they could wait until Thursday, and
the league said no, so they had to stay out.''
</P>
<P>
   Casserly, his wife, Bev, and daughter, Shannon, were in the
dressing room when one bonding scene was shot with the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone treated us great,'' Casserly said. ``Reeves was a
super guy. He had (former NFL quarterback) T.J. Rubley helping him,
and he looked the part. Hey, the football scenes were outstanding.
They had a guy (Allan Graf) who's handled the football action
scenes in a lot of movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I hope the movie does well, because they put a lot
of time, money and effort into making it as realistic as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   If not for their replacement team, the Redskins might not have
reached the Super Bowl. They won the NFC East with an 11-4 record.
They played at Chicago in the second round of the playoffs and
upset the Bears. The Redskins hosted the NFC Championship Game and
beat Minnesota, a wild-card team that had upset New Orleans and San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins then defeated Denver 42-10 in Super Bowl XXII. The
replacement players each received a half share of $32,000 for their
contributions to the Super Bowl-winning season.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
