<HEADLINE>
DREIFORT HITS TWO HOMES IN DODGERS WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Since the All-Star break, Darren Dreifort's done
it with his right arm, winning his first four starts and
re-establishing himself as a force in the Los Angeles Dodgers'
starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   He did pretty well in his fifth start, too, but no one really is
going to remember his 6 effective innings Tuesday against the
Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the ever-lasting memory will be the pair of homers
Dreifort hit _ measuring a combined 903 feet _ as the Dodgers hit a
season high five home runs and led the Cubs 7-5 entering the bottom
of the eighth inning at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield broke his tie with the Cubs' Sammy Sosa for the
major league-lead in homers, hitting his 36th of the season in the
fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort became the first pitcher to hit two homers in a game
since Atlanta's Derek Lilliquist did it May 1, 1990, against the
Mets. Dreifort also became the first Dodgers pitcher to hit two
homers in a game since Don Drysdale did it Aug. 23, 1958, against
the Milwaukee Braves at the Los Angeles Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   His first shot was a 441-foot blast near the edge of the
right-field bleachers in the fourth inning. Dreifort's other homer
was a 462-foot blast into the left-center field bleachers in the
fifth inning. His chance for a third homer went by the boards when
he struck out i inning.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort's three homers this season are the most by a pitcher
since Fernando Valenzuela hit three in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Dreifort's never been a slouch with the bat. During
his All-American career at Wichita State, he batted .318 with 25
homers and 89 RBI in 314 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and Dreifort also pitched a doozy of a game to improve to
9-7, including 5-0 since the All-Star break. In allowing two earned
runs on six hits, he kept his post-All-Star break ERA at 2.67.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort allowed three runs (one earned) in the third inning,
but it shouldn't have been the case.
</P>
<P>
   With runners on first and second and one out, Sosa grounded to
shortstop Kevin Elster for what should have been a perfect double
play. But Elster's flip to Mark Grudzielanek was wide of second and
rolled to the wall adjacent the Cubs' dugout, allowing pitcher Phil
Norton and Ricky Gutierrez to score. Mark Grace added an RBI single
to put 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   Elster, starting because the lefty Norton (0-1) was pitching,
got one of the runs back with a solo homer in the fourth inning. It
turned out to be the first of four the Dodgers hit in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Two pitches later Dreifort followed with his first of the night
to tie it 3-3. Devon White grounded out and Grudzielanek flied out,
but Sheffield retook the major league lead and gave the Dodgers a
4-3 lead with his solo homer. Eric Karros singled to left and Shawn
Green hit Norton's 1-0 pitch over the right field fence for a 6-3
Dodgers lead.
</P>
<P>
   The four homers in the inning allowed by Norton, making his
second major league start, tied a major league record. It was the
18th time the dubious feat was accomplished, the last being St.
Louis' Andy Benes last month against Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' five homers were also the most they've hit in a
game since belting six at Colorado on Sept. 26, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, even with the homers and the offense and the fun the fans
had watching Dreifort make like Sheffield or Sosa, a hair-raising
moment came inthe top of the seventh. Cubs center fielder Gary
Matthews Jr. lined a ball off the heal of Dreifort's glove,
apparently glancing off his left wrist. It sent shivers through the
Dodgers, but Dreifort remained in the game.
</P>
<P>
   However, he wasn't out of trouble. Eric Young grounded out to
third, Gutierrez walked and Sosa struck out. But Mark Grace singled
to score Matthews Jr. and pull the Cubs to within 7-4. Mike Fetters
relieved and got Rondell White to end the inning, but allowed a
two-out solo homer to Jeff Reed in the eighth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
