<HEADLINE>
MARINERS SLAM, SWEEP WHITE SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ There was a time that a performance like the one
turned in by Joel Pineiro would be worthy of immediate
canonization, keys to the city of Seattle and a lifetime pass to
EMP.
</P>
<P>
   All Pineiro did yesterday was take the biggest step in baseball,
from the minor leagues to the majors. He did it with style. And he
did it against the team with the best record in the American
League.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my, this is the best feeling in the world,'' Pineiro said
after his contribution to a doubleheader sweep of the White Sox,
the team with the best record in the American League. ``I'm still
in la-la-land.''
</P>
<P>
   And what will be Pineiro's reward for having pitched six innings
to beat the White Sox in the first game of a doubleheader Tuesday
night in Comiskey Park? He got the word after the game that he's
leaving la-la-land and heading back to Class AAA Tacoma.
</P>
<P>
   He'll leave with the memory of his first major league victory.
And he'll leave with an image of one of the best defensive plays of
the year, the capper to the Mariners' 7-5 win in Game 2 after
Pineiro had pitched the Mariners to a 12-4 victory in the opener.
</P>
<P>
   Kazuhiro Sasaki walked a batter and hit a batter to open the
ninth with the Mariners holding a two-run lead. Center fielder Mike
Cameron saved him a run with a terrific shoetop-level catch, but
the Mariners defense was just getting warmed up.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Baines, as a good a ninth-inning hitter as there is,
simply crushed a Sasaki pitch. He hit the ball as hard as a ball
can be hit and not have the seams unravel. First baseman John
Olerud reacted with stunning quickness, diving to his left to spear
the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the ball was by Ole,'' second baseman Mark McLemore
said. ``Baines has been around for 700 years because he always hits
like that in that situation. But when I looked into the corner, I
didn't see the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did Sasaki.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just praying he caught the ball,'' Sasaki said. ``What
he did was awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Mariners have been doing is awesome. By sweeping,
Seattle moved to 21 games over .500 (67-46) for the first time in
franchise history. Of a more immediate concern, the Mariners moved
five games in front of Oakland in the American League West race.
Seattle has won five games in succession in New York (three) and
Chicago (two), the homes of the current AL East and AL Central
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   And they have their top two starters, Jamie Moyer and Aaron
Sele, going in the final two games in Chicago today and tomorrow.
The best the Mariners would hope for in talking about this
eight-game trip through hostile territory was winning five times.
Now they have a chance for more. They want more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be greedy,'' shortstop Alex Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle won the opener behind Pineiro and a couple of grand
slams, one each by Jay Buhner, who opened the Mariners' scoring in
the first inning, and by Edgar Martinez, who brought the last four
runs home in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez hit a solo homer in the opener, and he hit another
rocket, this one leaving an impact crater when it landed 458 feet
from home plate in the fourth inning. Because it came with the
White Sox holding a 4-0 lead in the fourth, it didn't seem like a
big deal. And after Chicago scored to go up 5-1 in the bottom of
the inning, it seemed less big still.
</P>
<P>
   But in the fifth, the Mariners massed three consecutive hits by
Dan Wilson, McLemore and Rickey Henderson after an inning-opening
walk to Carlos Guillen. That produced one run, and Cameron came off
the bench with a pinch-hit double against his old team, getting the
M's to within 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   The inning should have ended there, but Sox shortstop Jose
Valentin, after getting the first out on a potential inning-ending
double play grounder, threw the ball away at first base. Two runs
scored on the play, giving the Mariners the lead and setting up
starter Freddy Garcia, who hadn't pitched well, for the win.
</P>
<P>
   The error was Valentin's 29th of the year, a staggering total
for the shortstop on a team in first place. The entire Mariners
starting infield in Game 2, for example, has committed 20 errors.
Total. The Chicago defense, the worst in the majors, cost the White
Sox a chance to salvage a split.
</P>
<P>
   And the Mariners' defense, as personified by Cameron and Olerud,
preserved the sweep.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's more proof that we're one of the best defensive teams
in the league,'' Cameron said. ``Olerud's play was bigger than
mine. He saved two runs, for sure. But we've gotten here by making
those kinds of plays.''
</P>
<P>
   They've also gotten here by pitching. Garcia was wild, but hung
around long enough to get the win in the nightcap. Pineiro was
simply better than the White Sox, at least for this night.
</P>
<P>
   What Pineiro asserted by beating the White Sox was that the
Mariners have quality arms at Tacoma, ready for promotion to the
big leagues. And what the Mariners will assert by sending Pineiro
back down is that there's no room at the inn.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle. Too much pitching. Imagine that.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old Pineiro had a relatively easy time of it. He
didn't even have a bad case of nerves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had butterflies more when I was stretching and warming up,''
the slightly built (6 feet 1, 180 pounds) right-hander said. ``In
the game, everything was fine. I think pitching for a first-place
team relaxes you.''
</P>
<P>
   Pineiro relaxed the White Sox's bats to the point of putting
them to sleep, hitting the corners and keeping his breaking ball
down. He didn't give up a run until the fifth, when Charles Johnson
homered.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, the Mariners were holding a 6-0 lead, and the
White Sox, owners of the most productive offense in the AL _ they
lead in average at .290 and in runs scored _ weren't able to solve
the Pineiro puzzle. He threw all four of his pitches, mostly for
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I expected he'd do,'' Buhner said of Pineiro.
``He was excellent. I've seen the way he carried himself in spring
training. He was ready.''
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there were those four runs that Buhner provided
with his 10th career grand slam. It was Buhner's only hit of the
game, but it was the game's defining moment. Chicago starter Jon
Garland opened the game giving up a single, but then got a double
play. After that, though, his pitches were up and he walked the
next three men he faced, bringing up Buhner.
</P>
<P>
   The count went full, mostly because Garland was having trouble
keeping the ball down in the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that situation, I'm sitting on a fastball,'' Buhner said.
``I'm looking for one thing and one thing only.''
</P>
<P>
   He got it. Then he got all of hit, launching a 420-foot drive
into the left-field bleachers that triggered a Seattle offensive
spree that would see the M's pound out 17 hits, including three
homers, in the opener. Game 2 saw nine more hits and two more
homers.
</P>
<P>
   And another win. With a chance for more today and tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get greedy,'' Rodriguez said, stressing the point.
</P>
<P>
   Greed is good.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
