<HEADLINE>
&HT;    ... WRITETHRU 
DREIFORT HITS TWO HOMERS IN DODGERS WIN
</HEADLINE>
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Since the All-Star break Darren Dreifort's done it
with his right arm, winning his first four starts and
re-establishing himself as a force in the Los Angeles Dodgers'
starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   He did pretty well in his fifth start, too, but no one really is
going to remember his 6 effective innings Tuesday against the
Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the lasting memory will be the pair of homers Dreifort
hit, measuring a combined 903 feet, as the Dodgers hit a
season-high five home runs and beat the Cubs 7-5 at Dodger Stadium
to end a losing streak at three games.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield broke his tie with the Cubs' Sammy Sosa for the
major-league lead in homers with his 36th of the season in the
fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love hitting, but that's not my job,'' said Dreifort, who
took a curtain call after the second home run. ``We would have won
without it. I take a lot of pride in my batting, but my job is what
I did on the mound.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort became the first pitcher to hit two homers in a game
since Atlanta's Derek Lilliquist did it May 1, 1990, against the
Mets. Dreifort also became the first Dodgers pitcher to hit two
homers in a game since Don Drysdale did it Aug. 23, 1958, against
the Milwaukee Braves at the Los Angeles Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   His first was a 441-foot shot into the edge of the right-field
bleachers in center field in the fourth inning. Dreifort's other
homer went 462 feet into the left-center-field bleachers in the
fifth inning. Dreifort struck out in the sixth inning in his quest
for his third homer of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty impressive,'' Cubs first baseman Mark Grace said. ``He
hit 900-feet worth of homers. Heck, he could hit fourth in our
lineup. It's better than me.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort's three homers this season are the most by a pitcher
since Fernando Valenzuela hit three in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Dreifort has never been a slouch with the bat. During
his All-American career at Wichita State, he batted .318 with 25
homers and 89 RBI in 314 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort also pitched a doozy of a game for his fifth straight
win since the All-Star break. He is 9-7 overall. In allowing two
earned runs on six hits, Dreifort kept his post-All-Star break ERA
at 2.67.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Dreifort) can do that kind of stuff,'' Dodgers second baseman
Mark Grudzielanek said. ``I don't know why we don't use him in
pinch-hitting situations. He is a valuable asset. You can't ignore
his bat. Get him ready, let him take some BP, and I say we go for
it. If you get him some more at-bats, get him ready, look out,
Sheff.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort allowed three runs (one earned) in the third inning,
but it shouldn't have been any.
</P>
<P>
   With runners on first and second and one out, Sammy Sosa
grounded to shortstop Kevin Elster for what should have been a
perfect double play. But Elster's flip to Mark Grudzielanek was
wide of second and rolled to the wall adjacent the Cubs' dugout,
allowing pitcher Phil Norton and Ricky Gutierrez to score. Mark
Grace added an RBI single to put the Cubs ahead 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   Elster, starting because the lefty Norton (0-1) was pitching,
got one of the runs back with a solo homer in the fourth inning. It
turned out to be the first of four the Dodgers hit in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Two pitches later Dreifort followed with his first of the night
to tie it 3-3. Devon White grounded out and Grudzielanek flied out,
but Sheffield retook the major-league lead and gave the Dodgers a
4-3 lead with his solo homer. Eric Karros singled to left and Shawn
Green hit Norton's 1-0 pitch over the right-field fence for a 6-3
Dodgers lead.
</P>
<P>
   The four homers in the inning allowed by Norton, making his
second major-league start, tied a major-league record. It was the
18th time the dubious feat was accomplished, the last being St.
Louis' Andy Benes last month against Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' five homers were also the most they've hit in a
game since belting six at Colorado on Sept. 26, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hit five, that's outstanding,'' Dreifort said. ``We didn't
need to hit that many to win the ballgame, but we did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
