<SLUG> BC-BBA-NEWANGLS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    ... WRITETHRU 
ORTIZ EDGES IDOL MARTINEZ
</HEADLINE>
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Anaheim Angels manager Mike Scioscia and
pitching coach Bud Black couldn't emphasize it enough during spring
training _ please, please don't compare 24-year-old Ramon Ortiz to
Boston Red Sox ace Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia and Black might find that a little more difficult to
do, now that the Angels pitcher has beaten his mentor, throwing a
complete-game two-hitter to defeat the Red Sox 2-1 Tuesday night
before 27,293 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz had thrown 100 pitches entering the ninth and had to face
the Red Sox's Nos. 2, 3 and 4 hitters. He got Jason Varitek on a
popup to the catcher, Nomar Garciaparra grounded out to first and
Carl Everett popped to third.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, my God, I don't believe it,'' Ortiz said after the game.
``He's my idol. Today was the greatest day of my life. I still
can't believe I won the game. . . . I just felt very proud to be
facing him. I was pitching against the best pitcher in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that prevented Ortiz (4-2) from throwing a
shutout was a bad call from second-base umpire Mike Fichter. Troy
O'Leary led off the fifth inning with a liner off the wall in right
field. But right fielder Orlando Palmeiro played the carom off the
wall perfectly and fired to shortstop Benji Gil.
</P>
<P>
   The throw was a few feet up the line, but it seemed to catch
O'Leary off guard. He went in standing up but not before Gil tagged
him on the rear as he went by. Fichter, however, called O'Leary
safe.
</P>
<P>
   A groundout to second by Brian Daubach got O'Leary to third, and
Ed Sprague's grounder to second scored O'Leary.
</P>
<P>
   But even after the Red Sox scored their run, Ortiz maintained
the composure the Angels have been looking for. He needed that
composure again in the seventh when center fielder Garret Anderson
dropped a routine fly ball from O'Leary with one out, allowing
O'Leary to take second. After a visit from catcher Bengie Molina,
Ortiz retired the next two hitters to escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told him, 'He made an error, try to pick him up,' ''
Molina said. ``Don't let the run score. Not only for the team, but
for Garret. He feels bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz has spent most of this season in the minors because he has
lacked that composure, particularly during tough situations. And
there could not have been a more-difficult task than pitching
against Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Molina has taken on the chore of trying to keep Ortiz's emotions
under control, but he said Tuesday he didn't have to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have to do anything tonight,'' Molina said. ``He did
it on his own. He was very calm. When he struck out Sprague (in the
sixth) was the only time he got excited, the only time in the game
I told him to calm down. . . . I was very surprised because I know
the kind of game it was for him. I think he was trying to copy
Pedro, the way Pedro works.''
</P>
<P>
   The strategy worked, even if it disappointed a season-high
walk-up crowd of 6,798 that came to see Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``They might have come to see Pedro tonight,'' Scioscia said.
``But they're coming back to see Ramon.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez (13-4) pitched a typical game. He allowed only three
baserunners _ a solo homer by Tim Salmon in the second and singles
by Palmeiro and Anderson in the fourth. Anderson's two-out single
on a 1-2 pitch drove in Palmeiro from second with the decisive run.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez struck out nine and walked none; Ortiz struck out six
and walked two. The two pitchers have been compared because they
are both from the Dominican Republic and have similar throwing
styles.
</P>
<P>
   As Ortiz took the mound to start the ninth, he said a prayer,
then looked into the Angels bullpen and saw nobody warming up.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went out for the ninth inning, I said, 'Help me God,
help me really bear down and pitch,' '' Ortiz said. ``I was very
emotional when Troy Glaus caught the ball for the last out of the
game. I went crazy. I started to jump like a little kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz said he shared a hug with Martinez before the game, then
watched him pitch from the dugout during the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole game, I watched him the whole game,'' Ortiz said.
``Ever game he pitches, on TV too.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Martinez: ``I'm glad I was here for his day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
