r a BC-ROBB-COL-AZR &LR;      08-09 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBB-COL-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-ROBB-COL-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    DEFINING YEAR AS BUSH AND BOOMERS GROW UP(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By ROBERT ROBB(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - There was an interesting subtext in George W. Bush's
acceptance speech, a quest to define the baby-boomer generation and
the lessons it should have learned from the cultural war of the
1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Bush didn't claim that the cultural war continues, as Pat
Buchanan mistakenly did at the 1992 convention. After all, there
aren't many baby-boomer adults going around proclaiming that the
country is rotten to the core, and that drugs and licentious sex
are good.
</P>
<P>
   There remain important cultural battlefields today. But the
cultural war of the 1960s, in which many boomers comprehensively
rejected the values of their parents, is over.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, there are '60s cultural warriors who still regard
their experiences as noble and inspiriting. Not that they are
anxious for their sons or daughters to replicate them, mind you.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons appear to fall in this category. When Bill was
caught dissembling about his draft circumstances during the 1992
campaign, Hillary vehemently objected to a proposed statement
because she felt it equivocated about the moral high ground of
those who objected to the war.
</P>
<P>
   Bush framed his acceptance speech in terms of a generational
handoff. He began with a tribute to the World War II generation,
and then said, ``The question comes to the sons and daughters of
(their) achievement. {hellip} What is asked of us?''
</P>
<P>
   He cited Bill Clinton as emblematic of the boomer generation, as
indeed he is. Smart without being wise. Professing virtues he does
not practice. Engaging in destructive personal behavior while
holding himself out as morally superior to those who don't.
</P>
<P>
   In a phrase full of self-revelation, Bush said the boomer
generation needs to ``show we have grown up before we grow old.''
</P>
<P>
   He gave boomers credit for ``test(ing) limit'' that led to
improved conditions for women and minorities. However, he said,
``At times, we lost our way. But we're coming home.''
</P>
<P>
   He described reforming Social Security and Medicare as a
generational responsibility ``before the challenges of our time
become crises for our children.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's generational pitch isn't programmatic; it's moral,
and ethical, and religious. As he put it, ``We know we must renew
our values to restore our country.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, Bush is appealing to boomers to redefine who they are
by replacing Bill Clinton, the first boomer president, with
himself, the son of the last president of the World War II
generation, and a boomer who has learned the right lesson of the
cultural war: that for much of what is truly important in life, our
parents were right and we were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Whether boomers feel they need to redeem themselves from the
example of Bill Clinton as the first boomer president is uncertain
political territory. And it is uncertain how this appeal applies to
Al Gore, as opposed to Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Bush apparently was a fringe observer during the cultural war.
He wasn't a protester, and he didn't dissemble to avoid serving.
But he did act to make the likelihood of facing combat fairly
remote. He was admittedly undirected for much of his adult life,
ultimately given focus by faith and fatherhood.
</P>
<P>
   Gore volunteered for military service, although reportedly more
out of a sense of duty to his father than to his country. He
reports returning from the Vietnam War, and his father's electoral
defeat, disillusioned. But he recovered quickly enough to run for
Congress as soon as the Constitution's age requirement permitted
it. And he's been a politician ever since.
</P>
<P>
   The boomers are unquestionably the most self-indulgent
generation in American history. Paradoxically, Bush is catering to
this self-indulgence by casting the election, in part, as an
opportunity for boomers to redefine themselves as having finally
grown up.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Robb at bob.robb(a)arizonarepublic.com or (602) 444-8472.
His column appears Sundays, Wednesdays and Fridays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
