r a BC-WITCH-AZR &LR;      08-09 0400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WITCH-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-WITCH-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    SELF-DESCRIBED WITCH ACCUSED OF PERFORMING SEX RITUALS WITH
GIRLS(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By CHRISTINA LEONARD(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - Police say a self-described witch lured young girls
into his home to practice witchcraft but ended up playing
inappropriate games of ``Truth or Dare'' with them.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Vernon Benton now sits behind bars, accused of 17 felony
sex-related offenses.
</P>
<P>
   On occasional Sunday afternoons since January, police say, the
25-year-old Phoenix resident gathered nearly a dozen girls at a
west Phoenix park to hold rituals. Wearing a puffy white shirt,
pants and boots, Benton led the girls in praying, chanting and
humming, Detective Bob Ragsdale said.
</P>
<P>
   After the rituals were over, Benton brought some of the girls
back to his apartment near 43rd Avenue and Thomas Road, where they
played ``Truth or Dare'' that involved sexual contact, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Benton's wife, Spring Benton, vehemently denied the accusations
today, saying that the arrests stem from false accusations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all a lie. It's retaliation,'' she said. ``My husband
is innocent. He did not deserve this. I am behind my husband 100
percent, and I have a lot of proof that he did not do this because
I was always there.''
</P>
<P>
   Spring Benton, who has two children and is pregnant with a
third, said she and her husband practice Wicca, a nature-based
religion. Among other things, those who follow Wicca practice god
and goddess worship and the use of magic defined by the belief,
``An ye harm none, do what ye will,'' according to the
(beginitalic)Dictionary of Religion(enditalic).
</P>
<P>
   She said they occasionally have held gatherings, but those
included only adults.
</P>
<P>
   Benton, a security guard, originally was arrested July 19.
However, police submitted additional allegations to the Maricopa
County Attorney's Office on Friday. He was being held on $106,200
bond on suspicion of multiple counts of sexual conduct with a
minor, child molestation, sexual abuse, indecent exposure and
public sexual indecency.
</P>
<P>
   So far, police have identified four victims - ages 10 to 15 -
but said there may be more victims. Anybody with information is
urged to call Child Help at (602) 534-3200. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at christina.leonard
</P>
<P>
   (a)arizonarepublic.com or (602) 444-8543.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 0803EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000809.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 08:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6522 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MEISSNER-AZR &LR;      08-09 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEISSNER-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-MEISSNER-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    INS TARGETS SMUGGLERS(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By TESSIE BORDEN(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - U.S. Immigration Commissioner Doris Meissner this
morning will announce a new enforcement push to destroy the
networks immigrant smugglers use to move human cargo {ndash}
airports and safehouses.
</P>
<P>
   The effort, dubbed Operation Denial, will pull U.S. Immigration
and Naturalization Service agents from other duties in Phoenix and
other offices in Tucson, Las Vegas and Reno, Nev. It will assign
them around the clock at Sky Harbor International Airport, Las
Vegas' McCarran Airport, and the main land routes in between.
</P>
<P>
   They hope to choke a distribution system in which smugglers use
Phoenix addresses as safehouses and commercial flights as
large-scale ``mules'' to move illegal immigrants from city to city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phoenix has emerged as a real focus point of the violence and
victimization associated with smuggling,'' Meissner said in an
interview with The Arizona Republic Tuesday. ``We have become more
and more aware of the depth and sophistication of smuggling in
Phoenix.''
</P>
<P>
   Meissner will detail the operation at a press conference
scheduled for this morning in Phoenix. More than 100 agents will be
assigned first to the airports and then to help local police, who
normally get tips on suspected safehouses. On Tuesday afternoon,
INS officials briefed Phoenix Police Chief Harold Hurtt on the
effort.
</P>
<P>
   The extra officers will first work three shifts at Sky Harbor,
targeting smugglers who buy rows of one-way tickets to cities like
Chicago, Los Angeles and Dallas for illegal immigrants, then herd
them onto flights just before takeoff. Agents hope to shut down
such smuggling in months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going after the organized smuggling enterprises, the
money, the document fraud, the network,'' Meissner said. ``We want
to do a major disruption of these enterprises. We're prepared to be
at this for several months.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, when local safehouses start filling up with immigrants
waiting to leave town, the agents will target them in force.
</P>
<P>
   Ahr said about 10 INS agents will be in Flagstaff to guard the
main road smugglers use to get to McCarran when Sky Harbor gets too
``hot.'' They will try to catch the smugglers before they leave the
state.
</P>
<P>
   The operation is unique for the extent to which the INS informed
organizations that work with immigrants, meeting with them during
planning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like in the last year, the INS has really tried to
become more forthright and more anxious to involve organizations
such as ours,'' said Kathleen Judd, director of the for-profit
Immigration Outreach Center, which deals with citizenship problems.
``(They) let us know what's happening within their offices and what
they are trying to do to better their services.''
</P>
<P>
   The airport assignment won't be anything new for some agents.
Five Phoenix-based anti-smuggling agents have been working Sky
Harbor since January. To date, they have made more than 1,500
arrests and confiscated more than 19 vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Woodrum, chief of investigations at the Phoenix office,
recently called the airport ``a Grand Central Station for immigrant
smuggling.'' Investigators even keep a catalogue, complete with
pictures, of suspected smugglers they arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Few are freelancers, said Jack Weaver, in charge of the Phoenix
anti-smuggling unit. Instead, they are small cogs in large
operations that reach into Mexico to ``brincadores,'' or jumpers,
who sneak immigrants through the U.S.-Mexico border fence.
</P>
<P>
   Once across, Weaver said, the immigrants get turned over to a
driver that takes them to Phoenix. There, yet another custodian
keeps them at a safehouse. After a few days, that person hires
somebody else to drive the people to the airport, get the tickets,
and put them aboard the planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is organized traffic,'' Meissner said. ``People do not
cross these areas by themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   At any point, each smuggler may demand more money or abandon his
cargo, as has happened in recent months in remote desert areas
where immigrants have died of heat exposure.
</P>
<P>
   And problems multiply when rival smugglers try to steal each
other's loads, Weaver said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're called rip-off crews,'' Weaver said. ``They go to
someone's drop-house and steal their aliens ... It creates a lot of
potential for violence.''
</P>
<P>
   The money paid has risen with the level of organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1985, the average cost of a drive from the border to
Phoenix was $200 to $400,'' said James Jankowski, who supervises
the airport detail. ``Now, it can be as much as $1,200, and as much
as $5,000 if it involves an OTM (Other than Mexican).''
</P>
<P>
   Ahr said agents will closely monitor Operation Denial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, once this thing is over, can we expect any
difference?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ahr's answer is yes, in part because agents will gain much more
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have more documentation, more photos, more people
identified,'' he said. ``That will serve as a deterrent effect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
