<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Time's Austin cartoon isn't familiar
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Let me blow on my knuckles in excitement,
because Austin has made the big time again.
</P>
<P>
   Time magazine's Aug. 7 Republican Convention issue contains a
full-page cartoon map on Page 100 called ``A Map of the Governor's
Austin,'' done by artist Eric Chase Anderson, a Houston native who
attended the University of Texas and is living in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the governor's jurisdiction doesn't extend into
South Austin, because the map begins at the Capitol and ends at
Town Lake.
</P>
<P>
   The map shows some of the governor's alleged haunts, among them
the Cigar Palace at Eighth and Colorado streets, where, according
to the map, ``the governor buys his cigars.''
</P>
<P>
   I realize the Republicans are trying to act like the Democrats
in an effort to be inclusive. But in light of the cigar goings-on
at the White House, I would think the governor would distance
himself from the stogie thing.
</P>
<P>
   The map also features Las Manitas, the artsy Mexican food place
at 211 Congress Ave. I have a hard time imaging George W. hanging
out at Las Manitas, since it's the kind of place where the fire
sprinklers are rigged to detect and spray Republicans when they
walk through the door. However, Cynthia Perez, one of the owners,
says Bush has been in a couple of times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the first time he came in. We didn't know who was
more scared _ him or us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It's a cute map, what with an illustration of the governor
dressed in a suit, cowboy hat and running shoes, but it ignores
many hectic details of life in our fair city. The map has the
``jogging governor'' running peacefully along the Town
Lakehike-and-bike trail, but Anderson left out the large truck that
nearly ran over him. There isn't a single traffic cone on the map.
And where are the building cranes, and the techies wandering
aimlessly into the intersection with cell phones jammed in their
ears?
</P>
<P>
   Miraculously, the artist misplaced the Four Seasons Hotel. How
do you lose a 291-room hotel? The Four Seasons is at the end of San
Jacinto Boulevard, on Town Lake. The artist puts the Four Seasons
inland on a corner of Second and Trinity streets.
</P>
<P>
   You'd think the artist could have found the Four Seasons. At
$250 to $375 a night, just follow the smell of money and hang a
right.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a big whoops. The map calls Cesar Chavez Street by its
former name of First Street. It also has a drawing of the Iron
Works Barbecue, at Red River and Cesar Chavez, and says it is ``the
governor's favorite BBQ.''
</P>
<P>
   Does the governor come in a lot? ``Uhhhhh, no,'' said Charlotte
Finch, the Iron Works' owner. Maybe he has his food picked up.
</P>
<P>
   The map mentions Hut's, the hamburger joint on West Sixth
Street, and says the governor says he swings by when he wants ``a
quick bite.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen the governor in a long time,'' said Michael
Hutchinson, the owner.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does the map show a Jeep Cherokee circling a downtown block
for 20 minutes, looking for a place to park. So though it may be
``A Map of the Governor's Austin,'' it's not the same Austin I live
in.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso can be reached at 512-445-3606 or at
jkelso(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
