<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Women ministers undaunted
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   They call themselves ``sisters in the Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   Pastors Dorothy E. Johnson, Ramona Hunter and Emma Curtis-White
lead congregations within blocks of each other in Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   When they get together, they chat and laugh like girlfriends.
But the subtext is spiritual, not personal.
</P>
<P>
   They don't compete for members _ ``There's enough sheep out
there to bring in,'' Hunter notes _ but turn to each other for
support in a world that often spurns women in the pulpit.
</P>
<P>
   Only Johnson was ordained in the Southern Baptist Church, but
all three are troubled by the Southern Baptist Convention's
declaration this summer that women should no longer serve as
pastors. They all know what it's like to be told, ``I can't come to
your church because you are a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Are they discouraged? Demoralized?
</P>
<P>
   Not a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't oust me; I'm standing on Jesus and his word,'' said
Johnson, senior pastor and co-founder of New Philadelphia Community
Baptist Church. ``It's better to obey God than man.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter's own congregation, Progressive Missionary Baptist
Church, supported her when she took over for her husband, longtime
pastor Sherman Hunter. Yet Hunter resisted the call to the
ministry: ``For a year I didn't tell anybody that I felt a
calling.''
</P>
<P>
   When she finally decided to heed the call, ``It was like someone
lifted a building off my back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That calling of mine was SOMETHING,'' echoed Curtis-White.
</P>
<P>
   It was strong enough to compel her to leave her home church, a
Baptist congregation, in Cincinnati. When she sang gospel in the
church choir, the pastor greeted her with a warm smile whenever she
entered the church. After she announced her intention to enter the
ministry, he would avert his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   That hurt _ but it didn't stop her. A year ago, Curtis-White
founded the Church on the Rock Ministries, a ``street ministry''
that feeds the needy every Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   These pastors worry less about their own future as ministers
than about the spiritual well-being of men like those who voted to
oust women from the Southern Baptist Convention.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was non-binding, a sort of spiritual don't-ask, don't-
tell policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What bothers me is that they're not seeing in the spirit,''
Curtis-White said. ``We're supposed to see in the spirit and not
gender.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Hunter, ``When Jesus Christ commissioned his church, he
said, 'Go ye, and bring his word.' He did not say, 'Go men.'''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis-White chuckled at the memory of a man who argued that the
text was 'go he.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Girl, he's got a problem!'' Hunter roared.
</P>
<P>
   The women also meet in the more formal setting of the Women
International Interracial Interdenominational Christian Ministers
Alliance. Founded by Johnson, it brings ministers and laywomen
together to volunteer in the community. The group's second annual
conference begins Aug. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Many men have been supportive of these pastors' calling.
</P>
<P>
   And the others? Johnson has a message for men who don't mind
putting women in charge of fundraising and Sunday school, but
somehow deem them unfit for the pulpit:
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you fight me, the more I'm determined.''
</P>
<P>
   Contact Mary McCarty at marymccarty(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
