A6578 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN10-COX     08-09 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Al buys a conscience, and a conservative, too
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Following the Republican convention in Philadelphia, Texas Gov.
George W. Bush led Vice President Al Gore by 17 percentage points
in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   That's a bunch. Trying to put the best face on these dismal poll
results, Democrats responded that Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis led Vice President George Bush by a similar amount at one
point only to eventually lose the election.
</P>
<P>
   A more dramatic turnaround occurred nearly four years later when
President Bush enjoyed an astonishing 92 percent popularity
preference only to later lose to Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Democrats argued, all candidates get a poll bounce
coming out of their conventions. Gore also will rebound coming out
of the Democratic convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   They're probably right. But a Monday night USA Today/CNN/Gallup
poll after Gore announced his selection of Connecticut Sen. Joseph
Lieberman as his running mate showed Bush's lead had been cut to
only 2 points.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the usual plus and minus error points, the results
clearly show that Bush and his running mate Dick Cheney dropped
dramatically after Gore selected Lieberman _ a man best known for
taking the microphone on the Senate floor and condemning Clinton
for immoral, harmful and deceitful behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The big bump in Gore's poll numbers appears to be based on his
selection of a man who said Clinton had ``compromised his moral
authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely, that's why Gore selected Lieberman. Gore wanted to
separate himself from a man he has praised with puppy-like devotion
for the past eight years, especially at a bizarre hug fest on the
White House lawn after Clinton had been impeached. That's when Gore
predicted that Clinton would ``go down in history as one of our
greatest presidents.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, on the other hand, said Clinton had ``lowered himself
and his office'' by engaging in behavior that sends a harmful
message to American families, ``particularly to our children.''
</P>
<P>
   Known as the moral conscience in the Senate, Lieberman has
teamed up with Bill Bennett, a Republican moralist, to condemn the
coarsening of American values by Hollywood, in music and on
television.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush picked Dick Cheney to buy some foreign policy experience
and gravitas, Gore apparently picked Lieberman to buy some morality
and integrity. The poll numbers show that it has worked.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's selection of Lieberman, roundly hailed by most Americans,
did not go over with liberal Democrats who felt betrayed.
</P>
<P>
   In response to Gore's selection of Lieberman, Robert Scheer, a
contributing editor the Los Angeles Times, wrote, ``What a gutless
wonder Al Gore is turning out to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Scheer condemned Gore for picking a running mate ``whose
anti-Clinton sound bites, including attacks on the Clinton health
plan, not to mention condemning Clinton before the impeachment
proceedings in the Senate, could make up the entire ad campaign for
George W. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Bush campaig Lieberman supports a strong military, free
trade, school vouchers, a moment of silence in public schools,
cleaning up trash in television programming and some privatization
of Social Security. He also has questioned affirmative action and,
according to Scheer, voted for a 1994 Jesse Helms bill that barred
federal funds to schools that used materials ``supportive of
homosexuality.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore knows that you can't please everyone. His selection of
Lieberman, however, shows that Gore intends to please as many
people as he can.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is the Senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
