<DOCNO> NYT20000809.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6580 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS10-FILE     08-09 1609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS10-FILE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: THIS IS FILE 1 OF 2
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com. Please include your name and hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've read that people who are in their homes during storms
when lightning occurs should stay away from windows, because
lightning can strike through the glass. If that's the case, why are
we considered safe in cars when lightning strikes?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's not the glass that protects you in a car, it's the car's
metal frame, said Greg Forbes of The Weather Channel. Metal is an
excellent conductor, and the lightning current normally will flow
through the car frame to the axles, then to the wheel rims, then
arc to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   People are relatively safe from lightning inside their homes as
long as they aren't in contact with some of the most likely routes
that lightning might take through the house, such as pipes and
wires, Forbes added.
</P>
<P>
   While lightning can go through window glass, it's more likely to
find some other path, because glass isn't a good conductor. It's
more likely to hit the roof, than go horizontally through the
window. Being away from the exterior walls _ windows included _
isn't a bad idea, though, because it puts you farther from the
lightning strike outside.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes added these additional safety tips: Don't talk on the
telephone (an electrical current from the lightning may travel down
the wire); don't take a bath or shower (because an electrical
current may travel along the pipes); and don't touch appliances (a
current may go through your home's electrical wiring into them).
</P>
<P>
   Q: With the hurricane season just starting, is there an online
site where one can obtain a hurricane tracking map on which to
follow them?
</P>
<P>
   A: Several sites offer good hurricane tracking information,
including these:
http://lumahai.soest.hawaii.edu/TropicalWeather/atlantictrack.gif;
http://hurricane.terrapin.com/;
www.nwrc.nbs.gov/special/track2.html; www.nws.noaa.gov/.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I saw where Melissa Manchester's father was a bassoonist with
the Metropolitan Opera orchestra. Is that where she got her
interest in music?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. According to biographical information on the
singer-songwriter's official Web site _ www.melissa-manchester.com/
_ her father introduced her to all the classics, and by the age of
15 she already was a published poet.
</P>
<P>
   Born on Feb. 15, 1951, in New York, she graduated from the High
School of the Performing Arts, where she studied acting. After
that, she entered New York University School of the Arts and
enrolled in a songwriting class taught by Paul Simon. She landed a
staff writing job at Chappel Music and performed as a solo
singer-pianist in clubs in Greenwich Village and on Manhattan's
Upper West Side, where she met Bette Midler _ soon becoming
Midler's backup singer. Within six months Manchester had a
recording contract, was a headliner at Carnegie Hall, and was on
her way.
</P>
<P>
   Her Web site, by the way, doesn't mention her mother or other
family members. ``The Encyclopedia of Pop, Rock &AMP; Soul'' also
mentions only her father.
</P>
<P>
   Q: To what political party does Alan Greenspan belong? What
president appointed him to his current position?
</P>
<P>
   A: According to Current Biography Yearbook, the chairman of the
Federal Reserve System is a moderate Republican. He was nominated
by President Reagan on June 2, 1987, and was renominated in 1991 by
President Bush and again in 1996 by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you settle a friendly discussion? How many continents are
there, what are they, and what is the authoritative source for this
information?
</P>
<P>
   A: World Book Encyclopedia, The New Encyclopedia Britannica, the
Houghton Mifflin Dictionary of Geography and Random House
Unabridged Dictionary all say there are seven: Asia, Africa, North
America, South America, Antarctica, Europe and Australia (listed in
order of size). Technically Europe isn't a continent, but a
peninsula of Asia, in which case the combined continent is called
Eurasia _ and there would be six.
</P>
<P>
   The islands of the Pacific, or Oceania, aren't part of any
continent. Australia is sometimes considered part of Oceania, but
Oceania isn't a continent on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you do if the Census Bureau hasn't sent anything in
the mail or come to your residence to count you?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Census Bureau says people who didn't receive a
questionnaire and weren't contacted by an enumerator should contact
their local census office and ask for field operations. The
regional census center for your state should be found in the
government section (blue pages) of the phone book.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Several years ago, Q&AMP;A answered a question about some
relatives of Queen Mother Elizabeth having been put in a mental
hospital in England in the 1940s, with their existence never
acknowledged. Can you refresh my memory about that? Have there been
any new developments?
</P>
<P>
   A: The London Observer revived the subject in an article in late
July, but it added little to the reports that came to light in
1987. At that time, the news leaked out that Katherine and Nerissa
Bowes-Lyon, nieces of the Queen Mother, had been confined in the
Royal Earlswood Mental Hospital in Surrey for 46 years.
</P>
<P>
   Burke's Peerage, the guidebook to aristocratic lineage, had
recorded the sisters as having died in 1940 and 1961, which turned
out to be false. Nerissa Bowes-Lyon died in 1986. There has been no
mention of the fate of her sister, Katherine, so it's assumed that
she is still living.
</P>
<P>
   The sisters, daughters of John Herbert Bowes-Lyon, the Queen
Mother's late brother, and Fenella Trefusis, a daughter of the 21st
Baron Clinton, were committed secretly to the hospital in 1941 by
their mother. Three other women, cousins of the Bowes-Lyons sisters
and daughters of Harriet Fane, sister-in-law of the Queen Mother,
also were placed in the hospital in 1941. Two were still living in
1987, but nothing about them has been reported since.
</P>
<P>
   Genealogists said all five may have shared a genetic flaw passed
by the 21st Baron Clinton, and not the royal family.
</P>
<P>
   The recent London Observer report added one bit of information:
that the 99-year-old Princess Alice, duchess of Gloucester, who is
Queen Elizabeth's aunt and sister-in-law of the Queen Mother,
remains ``hidden'' in Kensington Palace in west London. A
Buckingham Palace official said she was ``with us some of the time,
but not at others.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: How is the number of delegates to the Republican and
Democratic national political conventions determined? Is it based
on population, number of voters, or what?
</P>
<P>
   A: Each party has its own formula, resulting in ever-changing
numbers of delegates.
</P>
<P>
   For the Republicans, each state receives a base of six
delegates-at-large. American Samoa, Guam and the Virgin Islands
each receive a base of four, while the District of Columbia and
Puerto Rico are allotted 14. Each state also receives three
congressional district delegates for each representative it has in
the U.S. House, regardless of political affiliation (not applicable
to American Samoa and the others). Then there are ``bonus
delegates'' awarded based on various factors, such as to those
states whose electoral votes were cast for Bob Dole in 1996, or to
those states electing a Republican senator or governor during
specific years.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party introduced a formula in the 1960s that
still calculates the base delegate allocation per state. The
formula involves the total number of Democratic votes in the last
three presidential elections of each state, added to the state's
total electoral vote. On top of that is the ``superdelegate''
number _ now known as the PLEO, or Party Leader and/or Elected
Official _ which was added beginning with the 1984 Democratic
National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I haven't seen any mention of Nancy Coverdell in the media
since her husband, Sen. Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.), died suddenly.
Where is she? Any news to report?
</P>
<P>
   A: She's living in the couple's home in Washington, helping to
close out her late husband's Senate office. Georgia Republican
leaders have been very protective of Nancy Coverdell and her
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where did the name of Philadelphia's Hahnemann University
Hospital, where former President Gerald Ford was treated after a
stroke, come from?
</P>
<P>
   A: Samuel Hahnemann was a German physician and medical reformer
who died in 1843 _ five years before a college in Philadelphia
bearing his name was born.
</P>
<P>
   He was considered the ``father of homeopathy,'' a system of
medical treatment relying on the body's basic power to heal itself,
as opposed to ``heroic'' medical practices of the time such as
bleeding, purging and leeching.
</P>
<P>
   The present institution began as Homeopathic Medical College of
Pennsylvania, founded in 1848 by three young doctors, Jacob Jeanes,
Walter Williamson and Constantine Hering. The new enterprise for
healing arts prospered and grew. In 1884, the college joined forces
with the Homeopathic Hospital of Pennsylvania under the name of The
Hahnemann Medical College &AMP; Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   In 1948, the college's centennial year, Hahnemann's Dr. Charles
P. Bailey performed the world's first successful valvular surgery
within the human heart, the repair of a mitral valve. Bailey's
research was the subject of a Time cover story in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
