</P>
<P>
   DRLAURA-DUEL _ Conservative family-advice givers Dr. Laura and
John Rosemond are locking horns over daycare. Laura says it's
always bad; Rosemond isn't so sure. This points up a difference
that divides even conserative soul-mates: Laura puts the child at
the center of the universe and Rosemond puts the parents there. We
also inquire of parents: What does this dispute say about the value
of parenting experts, whose advice floods the media? (Harris,
Atlanta JOurnal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   LAURABUSH-SUITS _ People expect a first lady, whether of Texas
or of the United States, to have a certain look _ feminine,
professional and conservative, regardless of her political
leanings. Should she monkey with that formula even a tad, they'll
let her know. Dallas designer Michael Faircloth creates the outfits
that Laura Bush wears for public appearances, including the
half-dozen suits she packed for last week's Republican National
Convention. (Sturrock, Palm Beach Post). 19. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   BAT-PROJECT _ SAN LUIS VALLEY, Colo. _ When San Luis Valley
residents wake up each morning, there are 2 tons fewer bugs outside
than there were the night before. Tons of bugs disappear each
night, especially in summer, not that the farmers mind. They're
glad, and so is everyone else. And the fact that they have bats to
thank for the insect eradication doesn't seem to bother anyone.
Bats, it turns out, aren't the bloodthirsty villains often
portrayed in books and movies. They're vital to many Colorado
ecosystems and, in the case of the San Luis Valley, vital to the
economy because of crops saved from insects. And bats are being
unintentionally exterminated. Throughout the United States,
destruction of bat habitat is driving them into abandoned mines. In
the last 20 years, mines have been closed to ensure public safety,
but with little thought to the bats possibly living inside. (Grand
Junction Daily Sentinel). 30.
</P>
