<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: When Tiger Woods first came to prominence and was asked about
his race, he said that he was a mix _ and, for fun, had made up a
word to describe his racial heritage. I believe the word was
``Cablanasian.'' Can you break down the term Woods uses, and
explain its components?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's spelled Cablinasian, which the golfer cobbled together
from these words: Caucasian, black, Indian, Asian.
</P>
<P>
   According to Current Biography Yearbook's entry on Woods, his
father, Earl Woods, is one-quarter Chinese, one-quarter American
Indian, and half black. His mother, Kultilda Punsawad Woods, is
half Thai, a quarter Chinese and a quarter white.
</P>
<P>
   As golf's most prominent athlete of multiracial heritage, Tiger
Woods has been criticized on occasion for not identifying himself
as black. But he usually refuses to weigh any aspect of his lineage
more heavily than any other, and maintains that he considers the
focus on his race insulting. ``I don't want to be the best black
golfer ever,'' he often says. ``I want to be the best golfer
ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where did the phrase ``life of Riley,'' as in the expression
``living the life of Riley,'' originate?
</P>
<P>
   A: As with many expressions, there are several theories about
the origin. Perhaps the most prevalent is that it comes from a
comic song written by Pat Rooney of the ``Dancing Rooneys'' in the
1880s and performed by him on the vaudeville circuit. The song's
hero, Riley, tells of what he would do if he struck it rich: He
promises that New York ``will swim in wine when the White House and
Capitol are mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is that it traces to poet James Whitcomb
Riley (1849-1916), whose simple, sentimental poems depicting the
lives of barefoot boys loafing and living a life of ease in the
summer were immensely popular at the time the phrase came into use.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another possibility is the turn-of-the-century tune ``The
Best in the House Is None Too Good for Reilly,'' although the
change of spelling is a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   The books ``Facts on File Encyclopedia of Word and Phrase
Origins'' and ``Morris Dictionary of Word and Phrase Origins,''
readily available at libraries, explain such things as this.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I remember that about 25 years ago, during a drought, the
government sent some supersonic airplanes overhead to stir up the
atmosphere with a sonic boom and create rain. It worked, as I
recall, because rain began to fall soon afterward. Am I right?
</P>
<P>
   A: A sonic boom would have had no impact on the changing weather
pattern, according to Colin Marquis, senior meteorologist at The
Weather Channel.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have any information about Chandi Heffner, the adopted
daughter of Doris Duke? As I recall, they didn't split amicably.
</P>
<P>
   A: Charlene Gail ``Chandi'' Heffner, a former belly dancer and
Hare Krishna devotee, stays out of the public eye. But some things
about her relationship with the tobacco heiress are documented.
</P>
<P>
   Heffner was 35 when she was adopted by Duke in 1988. By February
1991, Heffner was persona non grata on the Duke property and Duke
was quoted as saying the adoption was ``the greatest mistake I ever
made in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke died Oct. 28, 1993, having disinherited Heffner and leaving
the bulk of her fortune to various charities and educational
foundations. Heffner sued, seeking to become the beneficiary of the
estate.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, it was reported that Heffner had settled her claims
for $65 million, and she hasn't been in the news since.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If the Confederate submarine Hunley, which sank in the harbor
at Charleston, S.C., in 1864, was built in Mobile, Ala., how was it
transported to Charleston, where it sank?
</P>
<P>
   A: By train. Records show that it was secured on two railroad
flatcars for the trip, said Faith Colaluca of Friends of the
Hunley, a nonprofit organization created by the state of South
Carolina to raise public and private funds for the recovery of the
submarine.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm a new first-time homeowner and am having a lot of
difficulty removing tree stumps. My father claims to have seen a
newspaper article with a recipe for dissolving them. What can you
tell me?
</P>
<P>
   A: Walter Reeves, a University of Georgia horticulture educator,
says commercial products promise to decompose roots rapidly by
chemical action. As an alternative, he suggests letting insects and
fungi consume the tissue of the stump naturally, converting it to
soil humus.
</P>
<P>
   To accelerate the natural process of decomposition, use a drill
to bore holes as deeply as possible into the stump. A circular saw
or even a hatchet can be used to cut and rough up the exterior.
Next, sprinkle a layer of ``woods dirt'' _ the top layer of soil on
the ground beneath your trees _ over the stump, packing it into any
holes in the wood. Then sprinkle a cup of 10-10-10 fertilizer over
the stump and lightly mist everything with water.
</P>
<P>
   To keep the stump warm, cover it with clear polyethylene
plastic, anchored with rocks and limbs. The plastic will trap solar
heat underneath and make the stump a cozy home for the organisms
that will feed on it. If you wish, plant morning glory, purple
hyacinth of English ivy to hide the stump and plastic.
</P>
<P>
   Within a year, the stump will be well on its way from your
property.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was the upshot of the arrest in Miami of Andy Pargh, the
``Gadget Guru'' on NBC's ``Today'' show? The story was in the news
in early December, but I never saw a followup.
</P>
<P>
   A: The case doesn't appear to have been resolved, according to
the Miami-Dade Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   Pargh was arrested Dec. 4 in Sunny Isles, Fla., just north of
Miami Beach, and charged with one count of cocaine trafficking. He
was released on $50,000 bond four hours later.
</P>
<P>
   Recorded information at the Dade County clerk's office reported
Tuesday that the case was adjudicated guilty, and a report hearing
will be held on Aug. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Pargh, meanwhile, no longer appears on NBC's morning show. His
Web site _ www.gadgetguru.com/ _ says this: ``We appreciate the
support you have given the Gadget Guru over the last 15 years. The
Gadget Guru is taking some time off . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported that Billy Graham paid $80,000 to rent the
Georgia Dome five years ago, the Southern Baptist Convention paid
``nearly twice that'' for the facility last year, and Bishop T.D.
Jakes paid $75,000 for his recent ``Woman, Thou Art Loosed!''
conference. How much did the National Football League pay to use
the Dome for Super Bowl XXXIV?
</P>
<P>
   A: The tab was $253,500, said Dome spokesman Matt Garvey. But he
wanted to clarify one point: It was the Metro Atlanta Super Bowl
Host Committee, and not the NFL, that paid the rental fee.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Dick Cheney may be the next vice president. How did he avoid
military service during the Vietnam War?
</P>
<P>
   A: This subject came under close scrutiny when Cheney was
nominated to be secretary of defense in 1989. According to draft
records, he received deferments first as a student, then as a
father.
</P>
<P>
   As reported by the Associated Press, a longtime friend, Joe
Meyer, dismissed any notion that Cheney pulled strings to avoid the
service. Meyer, who roomed with Cheney in college in Wyoming and
now is Wyoming's secretary of state, said Cheney wasn't very well
known at that time, and his father, local administrator for the
U.S. Soil Conservation Service, hardly had major political
influence.
</P>
<P>
   According to draft records, Cheney was deemed available for
military service in February 1962 after he dropped out of Yale
University. In March 1963, while enrolled at Casper College in
Wyoming, he was granted his first student deferment. It was renewed
while he was at the University of Wyoming in Laramie. Upon
graduation in May 1965, he again was declared available for
military service, but received another student deferment when he
became a graduate student in political science that fall.
</P>
<P>
   Lew Brodsky, director of public and congressional affairs for
the Selective Service, told the AP that student draft deferments
were common. ``Most men who were in school automatically qualified
for the 2-S deferment, which was the classic student deferment at
the time,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   When Lynne Cheney became pregnant with their first daughter,
Cheney received his final draft deferment in January 1966.
Elizabeth Cheney was born on July 26, 1966.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called hardship deferment enacted in 1963 included
fathers living with their children. The provision was terminated in
1970.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We travel the East Coast a lot. Where can we get a listing of
all the participating stations that broadcast Atlanta Braves games?
</P>
<P>
   A: You can find a Braves network list online at this site:
www.atlantabraves.com/bravespbtvradio/0,1800,49,00.html. On the
map, click on any state and you'll see the city, radio station call
letters and location on the dial.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
