NYT-08-09-00 1143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000809.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 11:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6609 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-PYRAMID-$ADV13     08-09 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PYRAMID-$ADV13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIAN PYRAMID NEW MECCA OF PARANORMAL
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Aug. 13 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Unlike Fox Mulder of The X-Files, Russian mathematician
Alexander Golod doesn't believe the truth is out there _ he says
it's in there.
</P>
<P>
   In a four-story gray pyramid, to be precise, that rises
majestically _ and unexpectedly _ from a forest-lined potato field
alongside the main highway leading north from Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Golod, an academic turned businessman, built the structure
because he believes in what he calls ``Pyramid Power,'' a force
that mankind can harness to cure AIDS and eliminate crime, civil
war, bad harvests, cancer and earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a faith healer, I am a scientist,'' said Golod, a
scruffy, pale man whose long face exudes contentment. ``As a result
of this pyramid being built, I predict that AIDS and hepatitis will
disappear (in the Moscow region) in a few years.''
</P>
<P>
   His predictions are based, he says, not on the supernatural but
on scientific truths and mathematical theorems that humans do not
yet understand. All you have to do, he says, is believe.
</P>
<P>
   And thousands of Russians, bored or disenchanted with
traditional religions, do, making Golod's pyramids _ he's already
built eight _ Meccas of the paranormal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drank the water, and I lost my headaches. I bought the
stones, and my garden bloomed,'' said a 44-year-old woman named
Lena, referring to the amulets she bought after they had been
``charged'' inside Golod's pyramid.
</P>
<P>
   As she stood in line on a recent rainy afternoon to visit the
hollow, fiberglass structure, Lena was happy to talk about her
belief in the pyramid's healing powers but refused to give her last
name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't go so far as to say it's a holy place, but there is a
current of energy that is unmistakable,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Golod, who owns a used tire business and is a military defense
contractor, says the cosmos suffers disease and war because space
is distorted by negative human actions. He claims the pyramid's
measurements, based on ancient mathematical equations used by the
Egyptians, re-balance cosmic forces within the pyramid itself.
According to this logic, the bigger the pyramid, the bigger is its
influence on the natural world.
</P>
<P>
   The Moscow pyramid _ completed last December _ is Golod's
largest and most expensive project. Built without nails, the
structure took almost two years and $800,000 to complete, he says.
Costs for the others averaged about $125,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   Golod's most famous pyramid is on Lake Seliger in northern
Russia, a site he chose because it was located under a hole in the
ozone layer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several months after we built this in 1997, the hole was back
to normal,'' he says excitedly, displaying what he says are before
and after pictures taken by Russian weather satellites. ``Just
think of what would happen if we built a bigger (pyramid) in the
Southern Hemisphere.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You Americans, you could rid yourself of tornadoes with a few
of these,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Golod's ideas have been embraced by Russian cosmonauts, medical
doctors and politicians.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of amethysts charged at the Moscow pyramid were taken
aboard the space station Mir to promote world peace. And Russia's
Olympic rowers and wrestlers are taking Golod's rocks to the Sydney
Games this summer, hoping the stones will aid their performances.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some visitors to the pyramid are skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   Igor Sechin, a 31-year-old father of one, was one of hundreds of
people who came on a recent weekend to visit the pyramid out of
curiosity. He said the trip didn't make him a believer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kind of people who believe that pyramid will cure them are
the kind of people that will believe anything. Only those kind of
people would buy this junk,'' Sechin said, pointing to the $10
model pyramids and $1 bottles of pyramid water sold outside.
</P>
<P>
   Golod rejects charges of hucksterism. He produces reams of paper
with test results from Moscow research institutes to support his
claims that pyramids affect the natural world. A study last year by
the Moscow Institute for Experimental and Theoretical Biophysics
found that water exposed to the pyramids has ``a stimulating effect
on the ability of human cells to survive and proliferate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It would take me 30 years (of selling souvenirs) to recoup my
costs,'' he said, sitting in his rundown Moscow office decorated
with a five-foot-tall plastic globe. ``I'm doing what I can to
improve the planet. There is no escaping that we are all connected
to its future. I want to make the Earth a better place for my
grandchildren to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Coker's E-mail address is: megc(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 1143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000809.0066 </DOCNO>
