   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'')
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-TRADE (San Antonio) _ Vincente Fox, Mexico's new
president whose election was aided by reforms generated by the
North American Free Trade Agreement, will be promoting his idea of
expanded trade and a common market throughout the hemisphere when
he travels to Ottawa and Washington later this month. By BILL DAY.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-PREVENTION (San Francisco) _ Faced with firm evidence that
the rate of new HIV infections among gay men is rising sharply, San
Francisco's health director wants to revamp prevention efforts,
including a retreat from the use-a-condom-every-time mantra that
has been the heart of most AIDS prevention campaigns. By ULYSSES
TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   HOTELS-POOR (San Francisco) _ A state appeals court has revived
a challenge to San Francisco's hotel conversion ordinance, saying
hotel owners shouldn't have to pay society's costs of housing the
poor. By BOB EGELKO.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL-BUSINESS NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FORD-MODEL-E (San Francisco) _Its case thrown out by a Detroit
judge for lack of jurisdiction, Ford Motor Co. has refiled a
lawsuit against a Fremont, Calif.-based Internet startup called
Model E in U.S. District Court in Oakland. The giant auto maker
claims the name Model E would create consumer confusion about
whether Model E's business was associated with Ford's antique
vehicles, most notably the Model T. By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-DSL (San Francisco) _ NorthPoint Communications Inc. and
Verizon Communications here plan to merge their digital subscriber
line businesses and create a new DSL company. NorthPoint will
become the primary provider of high-speed Internet access for
Verizon, the company formed when Bell Atlantic Corp. bought GTE
Corp. By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES/LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LAP-ROBES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Lap robes were once a requisite of
the carriage trade for keeping clean, snug and warm. Today, they
remain popular for warmth during a football game or polo match, to
picnic on, snuggle up with when reading a favorite book or use when
the power goes out. By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT(``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-STEREOTYPES (Undated) _ Minority actors on television are
getting it from both sides. Because (mostly white) authors often
write only what they know about, juicy parts for blacks and
Hispanics are often lacking, a paucity highlighted last year by the
NAACP and others. TV has worked hard over the past year to play
catch-up, but it can do better (especially with Hispanics). By MARK
McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SHARK-SUITS _ (Indianapolis) _ The dress code came. The dress
code went in the U.S. Olympic Swimming Trials. U.S. Swimming
initially banned from the trials a full-body suit that takes a long
time to wiggle into. It's known as the ``shark suit'' because the
fabric allegedly mimics the sleek skin of a shark. The suit would
be permitted in the Olympics, but the governing body feared that
some competitors wouldn't be able to get one in time for the trials
meet. A little saber-ratting from the lawyers for a manufacturer
changed that policy. By GWEN KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-POPE (Napa,Calif.) _ Defensive back Marquez Pope aspires to
more than just being a member of the 2000 Oakland Raiders. He wants
to be one of their leaders and says he can help them win a title.
By FRANK BLACKMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ You have to wonder if a drug
called Empathy could be the toast of young people, a Raver Madness
segment on ``60 Minutes'' and a scourge to be fought by politicians
and law enforcement. A capsule of Empathy sounds like something
Bill Clinton would take to feel others' pain, but that's the name
almost given to Ecstasy. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LEARNING (San Francisco) _ Sometimes the best road to career
success is a blind alley. Workers get so used to learning a few
particular skills for one particular career that they deprive
themselves of the joy of learning. It becomes a chore, not an
adventure. By DAVE MURPHY.
