<HEADER>
A6645 &Cx1f; tab-z
u d BC-20MINUTE-MENUS-ADV30-     08-09 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-20MINUTE-MENUS-ADV30-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV30  
 HEALTHY 20-MINUTE MENUS: OLD-FASHIONED MEATBALLS; BROCCOLI-POTATO
SALAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDITORS: For use Wednesday, Aug. 30, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's 20MINUTE-MENUS. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of 20MINUTE-MENUS _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By MARIAN BURROS    
 c.2000 Foxcraft Ltd.    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not easy to make good meatballs if the amount of fat in the
ground beef is small. If you take fat away you have to add
something to take its place. So perhaps the name I have given this
recipe for meatballs is not fair. The additions, fresh tomatoes,
parsley and basil, are not exactly the ingredients found in
old-fashioned meatballs.
</P>
<P>
   But they serve a double purpose: they add moisture and keep the
meatballs light, and they add a great deal of flavor. It's like
having meatballs with the tomato sauce inside.
</P>
<P>
   Potato salad swathed in a mayonnaise dressing is usually the
summer salad of choice, but the old-fashioned version would not
exactly fit into the healthy menu category. If you use oil and
vinegar you can definitely cut down on the calories. Putting
broccoli in a potato salad is the easiest way I know to make
broccoli palatable to almost anyone. To me its gives an interesting
texture to the salad and wonderful color. The acidity of the
vinegar, the sharpness of the mustard and the touch of sweetness
and complexity of the Worcestershire sauce counteract the cabbagey
taste of broccoli that some people don't like.
</P>
<P>
   Let's call this meal a new age version of old-fashioned food.
</P>
<P>
   OLD-FASHIONED MEATBALLS
</P>
<P>
   16 ounces 10 percent fat ground beef
</P>
<P>
   1 cup seasoned dry bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   Enough parsley to yield 1/3 cup chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces ripe tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Bunch basil to yield 6 large leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 large sprig oregano
</P>
<P>
   1 large garlic clove
</P>
<P>
   1. Wash, dry and chop parsley; wash, trim and finely chop the
tomatoes; wash, dry and slice the basil leaves; wash dry and chop
the oregano; mince the garlic.
</P>
<P>
   2. Mix the ground beef with the bread crumbs and all the other
ingredients and shape into 1.5-inch balls.
</P>
<P>
   3. Heat a nonstick pan large enough to hold the meatballs in a
single layer. Reduce heat to medium high; add oil and saute the
meatballs on all sides until they are brown.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 3 servings
</P>
<P>
   BROCCOLI AND POTATO SALAD
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces small new potatoes
</P>
<P>
   16 ounces whole broccoli or 8 ounces broccoli florettes
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1. Wash the potatoes; do not peel. If the potatoes are larger
than an inch in size, cut in half or quarters. Boil the potatoes
until they are cooked, 10 to 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Cut off tough stems from whole broccoli. Cut the florettes
into bite-size pieces and steam about 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Meanwhile whisk together the olive oil, vinegar,
Worcestershire and mustard in a serving bowl.
</P>
<P>
   4. When potatoes are cooked, drain and cut into bite-size
pieces. Stir into dressing.
</P>
<P>
   5. When broccoli is cooked, drain and stir into potato salad.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 3 servings
</P>
<P>
   GAME PLAN
</P>
<P>
   Prepare salad through step 2.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare meatballs through step 3.
</P>
<P>
   Finish salad.
</P>
<P>
   YOUR PANTRY
</P>
<P>
   Garlic
</P>
<P>
   Extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   White wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING LIST
</P>
<P>
   16 ounces 10 percent fat ground beef
</P>
<P>
   Package seasoned dry bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   Bunch parsley to yield 1/3 cup chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces ripe tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Bunch basil (6 large leaves)
</P>
<P>
   Bunch oregano (1 large sprig oregano)
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces small new potatoes
</P>
<P>
   16 ounces whole broccoli or 8 ounces broccoli florettes
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION INFORMATION PER SERVING: 615 calories, 18 grams total
fat, 7 grams saturated fat, 95 milligrams cholesterol, 1,215
millligrams sodium, 75 grams carbohydrate, 3 grams fiber, 40 grams
protein.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on
20-MINUTE-MENUS articles and other features.
</P>
