<SLUG> BC-LAP-ROBES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LAB ROBES OFFER WARMTH, STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Lap robes were once a requisite of the carriage
trade for keeping clean, snug and warm.
</P>
<P>
   Riding in a horse-drawn carriage or an early automobile was apt
to be a wet, muddy or dusty experience.
</P>
<P>
   Lap robes kept passengers warm and saved their clothing from
dirt and wear. They were stored with the outside folded out, to
keep the inside clean.
</P>
<P>
   Carriage blankets, another name for lap robes, were also
considered part of the chic apparel of the day, often complementing
the owner's wardrobe, or the lining of the carriage, sleigh or
auto.
</P>
<P>
   Lap robes came in a variety of materials. Some were faced with
leather, generally pigskin, and lined with plaid worsted material
or fur such as bear, buffalo or fox.
</P>
<P>
   Today, they remain popular for warmth during a football game or
polo match, to picnic on, snuggle up with a favorite book or for
use when the power goes out.
</P>
<P>
   Pendleton lap robes (at retail stores or http://nwpendleton.com)
have made the transition from drafty automobiles to a casual drape
over the back of a sofa or folded at the foot of the bed for an
afternoon nap.
</P>
<P>
   Some styles, such as the wide variety of woven cotton Irish
throws and crocheted afghans, are even considered works of art.
</P>
<P>
   For a luxurious lap robe, consider one made of cashmere.
Cashmereclub.com (http://cashmereclub.com) carries at least 16
colors (each costs approximately $798). Or consider a Polar Fleece
lap blanket in a solid or plaid ($20 to $33 at retail stores). Some
even feature a pocket for tucking your feet in to keep your toes
warm. When not in use, this pocket throw can be folded up to use as
a pillow.
</P>
<P>
   If you have allergies, look for a 100 percent non-allergenic
polyester Kanata fleece lap robe (at stores or
http://kanatablanket.com). It is brushed and sheared on both sides
for softness and pill resistance, and edged with whipstitching.
</P>
<P>
   Collectors might even wish to own a classic lap blanket and
carrying case in reversible plaid. That style was the regulation
Second Class Ticket Holder issue on the Titanic. To find it, go to
http://steamertrunkmerchants.com or call 212-585-4208.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 1256EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000809.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6657 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-STEREOTYPES-HNS &LR;      08-09 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-STEREOTYPES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TV STEREOTYPES ARE A TWO-WAY STREET 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The madness on television has to stop. Did you know that on a
given day you can see:
</P>
<P>
   _ An Italian playing a mobster?
</P>
<P>
   _ An African-American or Hispanic playing a hoodlum?
</P>
<P>
   _ An Irishman in a bar, or one wearing a priest's collar?
</P>
<P>
   _ A blonde who's dumb?
</P>
<P>
   That's right, stereotypes all.
</P>
<P>
   People, or at least special-interest groups, are screaming. But
what they fail or refuse to recognize is that stereotypes are
sometimes _ but only sometimes, in individual cases _ true.
</P>
<P>
   When used to define an entire race, ethnicity or class, they are
obviously and categorically bankrupt. But does that mean television
and movies should never offer a portrayal that could be construed
as being stereotypical?
</P>
<P>
   The safe route many white television producers take is ``no,''
especially after they received a well-deserved hammering last year
on the lack of diversity in casting. Steven Bochco is a notable
exception. His diverse casts on ``Hill Street Blues,'' ``L.A.
Law,'' ``NYPD Blue'' and ``City of Angels'' (the latter featuring a
predominantly black cast and crew) gives him a justifiable free
pass.
</P>
<P>
   No, this is a rant on political correctness of Hollywood and the
ironic result: Minority actors are often excluded from some ``bad
guy'' roles by the push for inclusiveness that's supposed to help
them.
</P>
<P>
   Minority actors are getting it from both sides. Because (mostly
white) writers often ``write what they know,'' juicy parts for
blacks and Hispanics are often lacking, a paucity highlighted last
year by the NAACP and others. TV has worked hard over the past year
to play catch-up, at least numerically. It can do better
(especially with Hispanics).
</P>
<P>
   But the diversity question results in another byproduct that
actually hurts minorities. Because there have been so few roles for
blacks and Hispanics, advocacy groups often demand that people of
color be put into parts that are more role models than just good
roles. If there's an opening on a television drama for a precinct
captain or judge, any African-American of the right age who ever
did a school play should apply.
</P>
<P>
   What about HBO's great miniseries ``The Corner,'' which depicted
the seedy, drug-ridden side of Baltimore with a cast that was
almost entirely African-American? It took a black director, Charles
Dutton, to make that fascinating, grim project _ and don't think he
didn't get flak for it. Needless to say, it would never would have
aired on a broadcast network.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is double-barreled. First, ``hero'' roles are often
one-dimensional, lacking the depth, complexity and edge that call
for a good actor to display their chops: The talented James
McDaniel, for example, could do so much more on ``NYPD Blue.''
Secondly, this means meaty or even pedestrian ``bad guy'' roles
often don't go to minorities.
</P>
<P>
   (This applies to commercials, as well. Ask yourself this
question: When was the last time you saw a minority cast as the
thief, burglar or other bad guy in a commercial? Think of the
recent beer ad in which a purse snatcher is knocked cold by a
flicked beer cap: Could you even imagine the perp being black? Not
in this environment.)
</P>
<P>
   Role-model roles? No. But they put food on the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot ask every black actor or every writer to write
icons _ to write only (positive) representations of the black
community,'' said Lynne Thigpen, the Tony Award-winning
African-American actress who stars in the new CBS drama ``The
District.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time that we get to play people, and sometimes those
people are flawed. That doesn't mean you can never have a Hispanic
who murders someone, that everybody has to be white who murders
someone.''
</P>
<P>
   Thigpen's comments have an interesting context. Despite its
diverse cast, ``The District'' is getting hammered for its premise:
A white police commissioner (Craig T. Nelson) comes to Washington
to clean up a failing _ and predominantly African-American _ police
force. Yes, the ``white knight'' aspect of the show makes me queasy
as well, although the producer said parts are being reworked before
airing.
</P>
<P>
   Thigpen nails it: If television had a steady diet of nothing but
minorities-as-thugs, the outcry would be not only deafening but
unquestionably valid. To bend the other way _ to ignore reality, or
cower in the face of political forces, and deny minority actors
chances at jobs _ might not be as bad, but it's certainly
troubling.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, producers can blunt the ``no bad role models''
argument by creating more roles (especially leading parts) for
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Furious advocacy groups are gaining momentum, and no one wants
to be left out. Italian-American organizations are going full-bore
against ``The Sopranos'' (ignoring the fact that the federal agents
who are the ``good guys'' of the series are Italians, as well).
</P>
<P>
   Things have gotten so surreal that the makers of ``Madigan
Men,'' a new ABC sitcom about an Irish father and son and
American-born grandson in New York City, had to fend off questions
from reporters about a scene in a bar (you know, the drinking
thing). And _ do you believe it? _ grandpa from off the boat wears
... a wool sweater. Shameless!
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's a bit of a jump to go from bar to stereotype,''
said Gabriel Byrne, the show's Dublin-born star. ``There are
stereotypical characters that are dealt with in a stereotypical way
by inferior writers, and I don't think we're going to have that
problem here.''
</P>
<P>
   The moral goal of all script writers should be to create a
fictional reality that at least resembles real life. But the truth
is that bad guys (and women) come in all colors; at times, the
stereotype overlaps with the specific and individual.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Italian mafia tend to be, well, Italian. Some
Irish men have been known to go to bars. And, yes, some blondes _
as well as brunettes, redheads, guys and television critics _ are
dumb.
</P>
<P>
   These ``stereotypes'' are indeed exceptions to the rule. But
there should be no rule against these exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
