<HEADER>
A6678 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-MEXICO-TRADE-HNS &LR;      08-09 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-TRADE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MEXICAN PRESIDENT-ELECT SEEKS A NORTH AMERICAN COMMON MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Filed in the ``a'' and ``f'' categories; note optional
trim)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BILL DAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The North American Free Trade Agreement, enacted
in 1994, is widely credited with encouraging the reforms that led
to Vicente Fox's election last month as Mexico's next president.
</P>
<P>
   Now Fox wants to expand the trade relationship between his
country, Canada and the United States, and possibly extend free
trade throughout South America. Fox is traveling in Argentina,
Brazil, Chile and Uruguay this week and will be in Ottawa and
Washington later this month discussing trade issues.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has proposed forming a common market similar to the European
Union, comprising the United States, Mexico and Canada, and
eventually linking such an organization with the budding South
American common market known as Mercosur.
</P>
<P>
   A common market would go much further than NAFTA's abolition of
tariffs between its signatory parties. A North American common
market would more closely link Mexican, Canadian and American
economic and social policy, and would present a united front when
establishing trade pacts with other nations and organizations.
</P>
<P>
   As with the European Union, which is a 15-nation pact covering
much of Western Europe, a North American common market could also
lead to a common currency _ mostly likely the U.S. dollar _ and the
ability of workers in each country to freely move between the
others.
</P>
<P>
   It is these two points that will likely be Fox's main obstacles
both at home and in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a perception that it'll hurt the U.S. economy, which
is largely wrong in my opinion,'' said Steve Golub, an economics
professor at Swarthmore College in Pennsylvania. ``But another idea
is true: In industries where companies compete directly with
companies in those countries, it will hurt them, and they'll lobby
against it tooth and nail.''
</P>
<P>
   Canada may or may not be a willing partner. The original free
trade agreement was negotiated in the late 1980s, when Conservative
Brian Mulroney was prime minister. After the agreement was enacted,
Mulroney was replaced by Liberal Jean Chretien. Chretien's minister
of foreign affairs, Lloyd Axworthy, was an ardent free trade
critic, though the new government has warmed to NAFTA.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Trites, a spokesman for the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and
International Trade, points out that as president-elect, Fox has no
official standing to discuss policy with the Canadian government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should these views become Mexican government policy, then
Canada will be pleased to examine any proposal put forward,''
Trites said. ``Until then, it would be premature to speculate on
such matters.''
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, the Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), the
party Fox beat for the presidency, is likely to use its power in
the National Assembly to oppose replacing the peso with the U.S.
dollar.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tradeoff there,'' Golub said. ``The benefit is you
get stable money and avoid crashes, and that can encourage
investment. The cost is a political cost. It's a huge chunk of
sovereignty you're giving up to the gringo dollar.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox may be aided in his quest for a common market by the recent
``dollarization'' of Ecuador, and a proposal in Argentina to tie
that country's economy to the U.S. currency. But in those cases,
supporters opted for dollars because their own currencies were
weak.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's peso is relatively strong and weathered Fox's election
without the devaluation that often accompanies a presidential
transition.
</P>
<P>
   It is significant, observers say, that Fox chose to undertake
this foreign trade initiative a little more than a month after his
election victory and four months before Dec. 1, when he officially
assumes office.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fox's candidacy was linked early on with NAFTA. Not only is he a
former Coca-Cola executive with strong support for international
trade, but he was also a beneficiary of the government reforms
President Ernesto Zedillo instituted to encourage foreign
investment.
</P>
<P>
   This year saw Mexico's first-ever primary elections.
Traditionally, the president _ always a member of the PRI until Fox
ended the party's lock on power _ simply picked his successor.
Meanwhile, NAFTA has helped expand Mexico's middle class, which
boosted Fox's National Action Party.
</P>
<P>
   Now Fox wants to do more. He argues a North American or
hemispheric common market would increase Mexico's standard of
living. Fox maintains that narrowing the gap in wages between
American and Mexican workers will slow illegal immigration.
</P>
<P>
   He will press that point in meetings with President Clinton and
Vice President Al Gore in Washington on Aug. 24, and the next day
when he meets with GOP presidential candidate George W. Bush in
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   While both Gore and Bush favor NAFTA and free trade in general,
creating a common market would be a tough sell in Congress. Shoyer
said such an idea would ``raise a litany of controversies,''
including labor, environmental and social issues.
</P>
<P>
   Golub agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it will happen anytime soon,'' he said. ``Chile
wanted to get in on NAFTA a few years ago, and they deserved to,
but the U.S. didn't want it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe in a few years, if prosperity continues and it doesn't
look like the (trade) deal with China or NAFTA are hurting
industries, it might have a chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 1334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000809.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6679 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d BC-FOOD-CHEFS-ART-BOS &LR;      08-09 1286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHEFS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 HARRIED BIG-CITY CHEFS FIND REFUGE IN DOWN EAST FLAVOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKLAND, Maine _ Marsha Demarest drove some 400 miles from
Hillsdale, N.J., to Maine, a state for which she has no particular
affection.
</P>
<P>
   She came for dinner. And she left more than satiated.
</P>
<P>
   Demarest was such a devotee of award-winning chef Melissa Kelly
when Kelly cooked at the Old Chatham Sheepherding Company Inn in
upstate New York that she didn't think twice about following her
palate to the chef's new restaurant, Primo, on the Maine coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget that dinner. It'll be one of my greatest
warm, fuzzy memories when I'm an old lady,'' said Demarest, who
enjoyed a feast that Kelly cooked just for her because she had
driven all that way unaware that the restaurant's opening had been
delayed.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival this season of Kelly _ named best chef in the
Northeast by the prestigious James Beard Foundation two years ago _
highlights how Maine is becoming a refuge for some of the nation's
rising-star chefs.
</P>
<P>
   Many are fleeing high-stress, manic New York kitchens, figuring
that if they are going to have to work punishing hours, they might
as well do it for themselves, and do it where they love to live. In
Maine they can be at once connected to the ocean that provides
their seafood and the small farms that produce their vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   The chefs are not the only ones benefitting. Their presence is
beginning to transform an area known primarily for its steamed
lobster and clamrolls, into a destination for ``foodies'' from near
and far.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with several fine restaurants lining the coast, the
culinary adventurer can feast on Primo's seared local halibut with
a sweet corn and lobster risotto. Or the apple wood grilled hanger
steak at Fore Street in Portland. Or the warm oil poached salmon in
a hot-and-sour broth at the Castine Inn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were intrigued by the idea of doing something you rarely
find in America, a great restaurant in the countryside,'' said
Clark Frasier, who is owner/chef of Arrows in Ogunquit along with
partner Mark Gaier. ``Ten years ago, it was a really odd concept in
this country, but it's getting more common.''
</P>
<P>
   And more choices are on the way. Matthew Kenney of Matthew's on
Manhattan's Upper East Side plans to open a restaurant in Portland
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   These are the days when the Food Network and food magazines have
mass audiences, when raddichio is a household word. People like
Demarest will travel for a great meal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're getting all kinds of serious foods in places where you
didn't see it 20 years ago,'' said Peter Wells, a senior editor at
Food &AMP; Wine magazine. ``A great restaurant outside of a city can
flourish more easily. It used to be that it had to be noticed by
The New York Times to succeed. Now it doesn't have to languish
until someone comes along and makes it famous.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of Maine's chefs said they were inspired by traditions
in France, where the vast majority of the highest-rated restaurants
_ those who have earned Michelin's three stars _ are outside of
Paris. Tow Gutow of the Castine Inn, for one, decided to
appropriate that model after cooking in some of those French
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Still, working in a small town poses obstacles not found in the
big city. Castine is five or six hours from Boston, a half-hour
from Route 1, and has no traffic light, fast food or movie theater.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gutow had worked with David Bouley, David Burke and
Diane Forley in New York, he was not a name like Kelly. So the
Castine Inn's reputation has evolved slowly since he and his wife,
Amy, bought it in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   A Michigan native, the 30-year-old Gutow still relies more on
vacationers who happen to be in the area than on people who make
the trip just for his food. To a chef brimming with ambition, the
low profile sometimes hurts _ and it makes it a lot harder to
attract high-quality chefs to work under him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating to see the people I've worked with on the
cover of Food &AMP; Wine and Gourmet and The New York Times Magazine,
while I'm still every year struggling for staff,'' Gutow said. ``I
do wonder, if I stayed in New York, what would I be doing and who
would I be? But I'm still happy to be here, and I wouldn't go
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Gutow said he would rather raise his 19-month-old daughter in a
gorgeous small town than in New York City. He'd prefer to work
almost every hour of the day for himself than slave away in a
militaristic Manhattan kitchen, where the head chef is expected to
scream at everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   His life, indeed, is very different in rural Maine. He is active
in a local organization promoting organic foods. In the off-season,
he has slaughtered chickens _ to get as close as possible to the
food he cooks _ and taught English at a nearby high school. He
serves as a volunteer firefighter.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, 35, has had it somewhat easier, although she is just
getting started in Maine. Three of the cooks who worked under her
at her last job in upstate New York, moved to Maine with her. With
her prestigious award, and her work alongside big-name chefs like
Larry Forgione of An American Place and Alice Waters at Chez
Panisse in San Fransisco, Primo's debut has not been a quiet one in
Rockland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The area is abuzz about Primo, there's no question about
that,'' said Greg Dugal of the Camden-Rockport-Lincolnville Chamber
of Commerce. ``I want to try it really badly, but I hear it takes
weeks to get a reservation.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, who grew up on Long Island, said that while she's happy
Primo has taken off quickly, she doesn't have ambition beyond the
60-seat restaurant. She and her fiance, baker and pastry chef Price
Kushner, might open a little bakery in addition to the restaurant.
That's about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our hopes and dreams. Not in another city; not in
another town,'' said Kelly, just before she began scouring for
sugar snap peas and carrots at the Camden Farmers' Market early on
a Saturday morning. ``I don't need to be a big-time chef, I really
don't. All I need is to have a little restaurant that makes people
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The reasons these chefs chose their adopted home all revolve
around ocean and countryside and peace and quiet, but also food:
local hake and lobster and monkfish, local Swiss chard and green
beans and blueberries. The cold Maine environment actually yields
stronger, tastier produce, said Sam Hayward of Fore Street in
Portland, who was something of a pioneer chef when he came to Maine
22 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   All the chefs develop close relationships with their purveyors,
requesting certain crop varieties a season ahead of time, trading
the latest family news with their scallop divers, traveling to pick
up produce they can't get delivered.
</P>
<P>
   One after another, they say that their job is not to work magic
with obscure ingredients, but just to bring out the flavor of
simple foods. ``I want people to say, `This is what chicken tastes
like! This is the best chicken I've ever had,' '' Gutow said.
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted, though, that they do not find Maine without
blemishes. Hayward has boycotted varieties of seafood he believes
are being overfished. ``The ecological catastrophe in the Gulf of
Maine has been my biggest heartache,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, these chefs consider themselves lucky. ``Always, chefs
work in the city but their dream is to get out into the country,''
said Kelly. ``Their dream is to be connected to the land, to have a
garden.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
