<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIM-TRIALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC TRIALS POOL BRIMS WITH VETERANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ There's no truth to the rumor that USA Swimming
was going to hold these Olympic trials at the senior citizens
center at the other end of Michigan Street. Not that it wasn't
tempted. There just weren't enough lockers.
</P>
<P>
   What we have here at the Indiana University Natatorium is
Jurassic Pool. Ron Karnaugh is 34. Three years ago, he was already
the oldest man to make a US world team. Angel Martino is 33, with a
3-year-old son. Dara Torres, also 33, is back after seven (that's
right, seven) years out of the water. Jon Olsen is 31, Lea Maurer
29, Jenny Thompson, Amy Van Dyken, and B.J. Bedford all 27.
</P>
<P>
   There are enough old folks here to qualify for a group rate on
the early-bird.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's comforting,'' said Bedford, the unsinkable backstroker
from Etna, N.H., who's here for a fourth try after three misses.
``I've got all my buddies with me. We've all cumulatively cried
enough tears to fill up that pool.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the fourth time in five Olympiads that the trials have
been held in this chlorinated boombox. For some of the contenders _
like Torres, who's trying to become the first swimmer to compete in
four Games _ these next eight days could be a renaissance. For
others _ like Thompson, who didn't make the team in an individual
event last time _ they could be redemption.
</P>
<P>
   But for all but four dozen of the 1,300 qualifiers in 26 events,
this meet will yield little more than aching shoulders, a pat on
the back, and a soggy souvenir T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympic trials is the hardest, most heartbreaking meet for
99 percent of the people out there,'' said Bedford, who came up
short in 1988, 1992, and 1996 but has a strong chance in the 100
backstroke this time. ``The people you're swimming with every day,
your friends, are all trying to knock you off.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the track and field version, the swimming trials are a
one-shot, no-appeal deal. But here, only the top two get tickets to
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can break 10 world records during the year,'' said Torres,
who's favored to win the 50 freestyle and could also make a couple
of relays. ``But if you come to trials and get third, that's it.
It's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Last time, Thompson came with a legitimate shot to make the team
in seven events. But after finishing third in the 100 freestyle,
her best race, she came unglued and made only the relays.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst meet I'd had in a long time, if ever,'' said
Thompson, who got three gold medals in Atlanta as consolation.
``After the 100, I had insomnia all week. It was stress.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, who holds the American records in both the 100 free
and 100 butterfly, still could make the team in half a dozen
events. But she's taking nothing for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``People could come out of nowhere and make it, which happens
every single time,'' said Thompson, who's shooting for her third
team. ``And people who everyone thinks will make it, don't make
it.''
</P>
<P>
   As they say on Wall Street, past performance is no guarantee of
future results. A bunch of medalists from Barcelona (Summer
Sanders, Mel Stewart, Tom Jager, Anita Nall, Lea Loveless) didn't
make the 1996 team. And a bunch who were on the podium in Atlanta
(Van Dyken, Martino, Amanda Beard, Gary Hall Jr., Brad Bridgewater,
Beth Botsford) will have to scramble to qualify here.
</P>
<P>
   The new quadrennium has brought fresh faces. Tom Wilkens is who
Tom Dolan was. Neil Walker is now the sprinter supreme. Lenny
Krayzelburg, who was born in the old Soviet Union, holds the world
record in both backstrokes. Ed Moses, who didn't begin swimming
seriously until he was 16, is now the man to beat in the 100
breaststroke. Megan Quann, who was 12 in 1996, rules the women's
100 breast.
</P>
<P>
   This should be their week, their meet, their team. But there's a
lot of water between should and did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing's for sure,'' said Krayzelburg, ``until you touch the
wall.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
