<HEADER>
A6681 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      08-09 1268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETIREMENT WON'T HURT 53-YEAR-OLD'S LIFESTYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Can I retire in 10 years and live a lifestyle that will allow
me to travel, belong to a nice, but not exclusive, country club,
and, in general, live very well? Will the equivalent of $90,000 in
today's dollars be enough? I realize what I am asking is ambiguous.
</P>
<P>
   C.N., Natick, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Of course you will be able to retire comfortably, and it
shouldn't be ambiguous. If your portfolio growth averages 9.5
percent _ a figure I lowered from my customary 10 percent
projection because of the substantial amount in emergency savings _
you should accumulate $3,019,437 by 2010, presuming ongoing savings
of $32,100 a year.
</P>
<P>
   If inflation averages 3.5 percent, you would need $126,953 to
support a lifestyle equivalent to $90,000 today. You'd need only a
bit less than $2 million in a fixed-income portfolio to supply such
an income stream, presuming the fixed-income accounts produced an
average 6.5 percent yield. That would provide over $1 million to
leave in growth investments, protecting you against future
inflation. And since you plan to beging drawing Social Security at
age 66, it should be a long time before you'd need the money that's
designed to buffer you from long-term inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Will you be comfortable in retirement on the equivalent of
$90,000 in today's money? Look at it this way. Discounting the
amount of your income that's going into savings, you live on
$90,900 a year, so you would be in about the same situation as you
are now _ with a couple of extra elements (which I edited out of
your letter) that would brighten the picture still further. These
are that you expect to save more after financing a child's college
education, and that you plan to do a bit of consulting after you
officially retire. So, as Red Barber used to say, you should be
sitting in the catbird seat.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'd like to roll my two investments into mutual fund accounts
with a better return. I do not plan to withdraw any money before
age 65, at which time I would like to have about $5,000 available
in a cash account for special purchases. All of this money is for
special purchases, since our major savings are in my husband's
401(k) account. I was looking at some of the Janus funds but would
like your input on maximizing return.
</P>
<P>
   L.T., Fort Worth, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A. What you propose is almost precisely the opposite of what
most people would do. Even though you don't anticipate a
predictable sequence of withdrawals, and none at all before three
years, most people just entering retirement are looking for safer
and more conservative investments, not aggressive ones.
</P>
<P>
   You don't specify which of the many TIAA-CREF investment
vehicles you are using, but you should be able to find a solid,
growth-oriented investment there, without rolling over the money at
all. Probably the most aggressive is the TIAA Growth Equity
account, which has built a solid record in about three years.
</P>
<P>
   To take a fairly aggressive course, I would venture no further
than considering the TIAA/CREF Growth and Income account, which is
a little more cautious. The managers consign some assets to
indexing, tracking the Standard and Poor's 500 Index, and actively
manage the remainder. The upshot is a portfolio with both
price-to-earnings and price-to-book ratios that represent about 90
percent of those of the S&AMP;P 500. The managers have done a good job,
and the fund has been modestly outperforming the index in recent
years with what is, at least statistically, a more conservative
porrtfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Fidelity Contrafund has an excellent long-term
record, despite modestly trailing the results of the S&AMP;P 500 Index
in recent years. It is classified as a growth fund but is among the
more conservative in its class, partly as a result of its huge
asset base. This is plenty aggressive enough for the portfolio of a
recent retiree. So I would suggest no change there.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. We just had a child. We currently invest 5 percent of our
earnings in the 401(k) plan, the maximum allowed by the plan. Can
you suggest ways to invest an additional 5 percent of income in
taxable accounts to support retirement and college costs? In
addition to the Index 500 fund, is a mixture of mid-cap, small-cap,
international, and/or technology funds appropriate? I would prefer
Vanguard or Fidelity funds.
</P>
<P>
   B.O., Franklin, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You should be in good shape _ particularly if you adopt a
more aggressive posture toward the money loafing in those money
market accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Since you don't provide an income figure, I can't calculate a
total accumulation that includes your contributions. But you can do
it based on these figures: If you were to move the bulk of the
money market funds to stock investments, you might reasonably
expect average annual growth of 10 percent over the next decade.
With no contributions, the current account would reach $810,141 in
10 years. To that you could add $17,068 for every $1,000 per year
you add during the 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   If you continue to hold nearly half of your savings in the money
markets, a more reasonable expectation would be 8 percent total
portfolio growth, which would take the account to $664,288 after 10
years, to which you could add $15,244 for every $1,000 per year
that you contribute.
</P>
<P>
   I have no problem with your list of prospective investments for
the taxable accounts and would suggest Vanguard's various index
funds over Fidelity's offerings, simply because index funds tend to
be more tax-efficient than actively managed funds. But given the
fact that more than half of your money is already in an Index fund
that tracks the Standard and Poor's 500 Index _ the Barclays
holding in the 401(k) _ I would switch the Index Growth position
for one in Vanguard Health Care fund, a move that would have no
short-term tax implications, since it is an IRA.
</P>
<P>
   I would leave the Index 500 account as it is _ why pay taxes
when you don't have to? _ but would add no more to it, opting
instead for new positions in Vanguard's Mid-Cap, Small-Cap, and
Total International index funds. If you decide later to add a
technology fund, I would look instead to the array of Fidelity
offerings. Picking and choosing among the confusing bevy of
technology stocks is not the sort of thing that lends itself to
Vanguard's disciplines.
</P>
<P>
   As I said at the outset, I would suggest that you move most of
the money market funds into stock accounts, if you are indeed
looking to the long term _ either a college education in 17 or 18
years or your retirement in a decade. I know that may seem
difficult in the current market, and I wouldn't blame you if you
used a dollar-cost-averaging discipline to get this money into the
market. But your investment time frames should allow
more-aggressive investments, and as federal employees you probably
shouldn't have the kind of worries about employment security that
dictate keeping a large financial security blanket in liquid funds.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, however you plan to handle the college savings, I have
two suggestions. First, carefully earmark the money so you know
what you have saved for that purpose and what you have saved for
retirement. Second _ and this does not contradict the first
suggestion _ leave the college savings in your own names, thus
increasing your child's potential eligibility for financial aid.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
