A6684 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-HOTELS-POOR-HNS &LR;      08-09 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOTELS-POOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COURT REVIVES CHALLENGE TO LAW ON HOTEL CONVERSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB EGELKO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A California appeals court has revived a
challenge to San Francisco's hotel conversion ordinance and said
hotel owners shouldn't have to pay the costs of housing the poor.
</P>
<P>
   In a 3-0 ruling Tuesday, the 1st District Court of Appeal
reinstated a lawsuit by owners of the San Remo Hotel that claims
San Francisco acted unconstitutionally when it restricted the
conversion of long-term residential hotel rooms to short-term
tourist use and charged the owners $567,000 for a conversion
permit.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990 ordinance, under constant legal attack since its
passage, requires hotel owners to get a city permit before renting
former residential rooms to tourists. To get a permit, an owner
must agree to replace the lost residential rooms or pay a fee equal
to 80 percent of the rooms' construction costs, plus site
acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   It applies to about 500 hotels with a total of 18,000
residential rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The ordinance replaced a somewhat less stringent 1981 measure
that was also intended to preserve residential hotels as a source
of low-cost housing for the poor. But the court said the ordinance
might violate the constitutional ban on confiscating private
property for public use without just compensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Affordable housing for the indigent may be a worthy goal, but
it is also an expense traditionally and rightly borne by society as
a whole,'' said the opinion by Justice Lawrence Stevens. ``Even
well-intentioned measures may create unconstitutional takings.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputy City Attorney Andrew Schwartz disagreed, saying the
ordinance was no different from any other zoning measure that
restricted land use. He also contended it did not differ
substantially from the 1981 version, which was upheld in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The need for affordable housing is one of the paramount goals
of the government and has been affirmed and reaffirmed by the
voters,'' Schwartz said. ``With the recent dramatic increase in
housing costs, the hotel conversion ordinance is more important
than ever. . . . We feel that it balances the rights of residential
hotel owners against the public's need to preserve the dwindling
supply of affordable housing.''
</P>
<P>
   The court overturned two rulings in the city's favor: Superior
Court Judge Raymond Williamson's dismissal of the hotel owners'
claim that the ordinance is unconstitutional, and Superior Court
Judge William Cahill's dismissal of their challenge to the $567,000
fee they paid in 1996 to continue renting most of their 62 rooms to
tourists.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court stopped short of a definitive ruling on either
issue but said the case must be reconsidered in Superior Court
under legal standards more favorable to the owners than those used
by Williamson and Cahill. Schwartz said no decision had been made
on whether to appeal to the state Supreme Court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 1340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
