<DOCNO> NYT20000809.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6688 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-COSMO-RUBENSTEIN-ART-     08-09 1631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSMO-RUBENSTEIN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 COSMOGIRL!'S QUEEN OF TEEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As a frizzy-haired and pimply Long Island
fifth-grader, Atoosa Rubenstein would sign autographs for her
friends, adding a simple postscript: R.S.
</P>
<P>
   That would be short for Rock Star, as in, dream on _ which she
did, landing a glamorous job and capturing a mass audience in her
own way.
</P>
<P>
   Today, at 28, she's the youngest editor in the Hearst magazine
empire, overseeing CosmoGIRL!, which turned a year old with its
August issue, a milestone that has Rubenstein celebrating. Last
July, when the ``little sister'' to Cosmopolitan magazine was about
to be launched, she told the Globe: ``There's nothing firm planned
for 2000. We have our fingers crossed.''
</P>
<P>
   Cathleen Black, president of Hearst Magazines, had asked
Rubenstein to develop a prototype of the magazine in 1998 and
within 48 hours of receiving it offered her the job as editor.
Rubenstein was then 26.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But her success as a queen of teens might have been hard to
predict just a decade ago, when, as an Iranian immigrant trying to
blend into suburbia, she took a job selling Fudgie the Whale ice
cream cakes at Carvel to keep her mind off the fact that no one had
asked her to the prom. Worse, she sprouted a cold sore for her
senior picture.
</P>
<P>
   It stands to reason that Rubenstein has built a career based on
this theme: Ugly ducklings can become swans.
</P>
<P>
   She became hooked on fashion magazines in an attempt to learn,
among other things, how to clear her skin. After an internship at
the now-defunct Sassy magazine, she moved to Cosmo after graduating
from Barnard with a degree in political science and in 1998 married
Ari Rubenstein, a commodities trader. She has two cats, Thurston
and Lovey, and a baby: CosmoGIRL! Not to mention an 11th-floor
corner office in midtown Manhattan with an ice-blue iMac and the
credentials that really matter: ``I've been a girl all my life and
I'm a good friend.''
</P>
<P>
   How has the magazine fared? Executives say advertising pages
have jumped 30 percent from the premiere issue and about 500,000
copies are being sold each month, some internationally. The
CosmoGIRL! offices are also relocating into the same building as
Cosmo, a block down Broadway _ an acknowledgement of the magazine's
success at tapping into the $98 billion teen market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the most aggressive launches in the history of
Hearst,'' said Donna Kalajian Lagani, publishing director of
Hearst's Cosmopolitan Group. ``God bless the little brat!''
</P>
<P>
   Nina B. Link, president and CEO of the Magazine Publishers of
America, says there's been a rush to capitalize on the demographic.
``We are seeing an influx of teen-oriented titles: CosmoGIRL!,
Entertainment, MH17, Teen People, Girl, etc., and we expect to see
more magazines as teen tastes change,'' Link says.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Rubenstein can still recall how it feels to be a
teenager, outside the in crowd, and she shapes the editorial
content of her magazine with those emotions in mind. You can see
her imprint in the monthly editor's notes where she wraps the table
of contents around her own teenage experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize the importance'' of moments like being snubbed on
prom night. ``And we don't downplay it,'' says Rubenstein. ``If
they don't get good advice, it could be devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Walking through the steel security door into the CosmoGIRL!
office space, a visitor first notices the pervasive, cheery scent
of citrus emanating from the candle burning on Rubenstein's desk.
Smells like teen spirit. It's no surprise, either, that the office
is full of ``youngiepoohs'' (Rubenstein's term) or that only two
men work in the editorial offices and that they, of course, dress
stylishly. Otherwise, the space _ intended only to be temporary _
is bland, with beige walls that could use a little touching up.
Rubenstein's office is spare, too.
</P>
<P>
   But she's all strappy heels, skin-tight gray T-shirt just short
enough that it can't be tucked into her pale blue, snakeskin skirt,
midcalf length, with a slit up the back and girly print underwear
peeking out the waistline near the small of her back. (This last
detail is likely more accident than fashion statement.)
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she always dresses like this, Rubenstein shoots back:
``Dress like what?''
</P>
<P>
   Her sort of zest is rooted, at least in part, in a tragedy far
more devastating than sitting home on prom night. During her junior
year of high school, Rubenstein's father, Mansour Behnegar, died of
pneumonia. He caught the illness from Atoosa, the youngest of his
four children. Hours after she was released from the hospital, he
died in the same facility. He was 69.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't seem real. It felt like he was on holiday,'' she
recalls, gazing out the window. ``I didn't grieve. I was in
shock.'' She breathes deeply and pauses. ``One thing that it's
taught me is to appreciate life.''
</P>
<P>
   The Behnegar family immigrated to New York City when Atoosa was
3, leaving behind a comfortable pension for a new life in a country
that Mansour Behnegar believed rewards achievements.
</P>
<P>
   It was a difficult transition. Rubenstein's father, an Air Force
general and mayor in his native country, found work as a cab
driver. There was also a significant cultural gap. Their household
was a strict one and at a time when her friends were staying out
late, Rubenstein was not even allowed to talk to boys, let alone
date them. Her single act of adolescent rebellion, she says, came
when she sneaked from her room to go to McDonald's and was
grounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was raised by a strong woman, who had very strong values,''
Rubenstein says. ``I never disobeyed my mother except for that one
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Her mother still lives on Long Island with Rubenstein's siser
Elahe, who's 45. Another sister, Anousheh, is a 43-year-old doctor,
and her brother, Nasser, 37, teaches political science at Boston
College.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is that (growing up)was more difficult for her,'' her
brother says. ``I suspect that's probably part of the secret of her
success in the magazine. She actually makes a contact with her
readership, as opposed to being an adult who's merely interested in
high sales.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaning into the crook of a cushy tan sofa in her office,
Rubenstein recalls a supportive family and an isolated adolescence.
Her siblings were well into adulthood when she was a teenager, and
her mother, . . . well, who talks to her mother about boys or sex?
So she turned to magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you need is honesty, someone to level with you. I never
had that,'' not even, Rubenstein adds, from the industry stalwart
Seventeen, which was founded in 1944 and sells more than 2 million
copies a month.
</P>
<P>
   Rubenstein points to her thick hair. The teen magazines, she
says, ``would all say deep condition your hair'' to defrizz. ``It
doesn't work! We'd never say that in our magazine.'' Instead, she
says, you should dry your hair pulled back in a bun.
</P>
<P>
   As for Seventeen, which its spokeswoman describes as ``the
oldest, the biggest, and the best,'' Rubenstein shrugs. It's too
fashion-oriented, she says, bent on showing expensive clothing.
That brings Rubenstein rummaging once again through her closet of
childhood memories. ``I'd see a $400 dress (advertised) and think,
`I'm so poor,' '' she says. ``But I wasn't poor. That was
ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubenstein says CosmoGIRL! is a ``masterblend'' of a teen
magazine, and the first to have a money page. The publication is
also known for including sheets of stickers, like the recent one
featuring Ben Affleck, and for having an editor who personally
responds to voluminous e-mails, many of which arrive after
midnight.
</P>
<P>
   It also deals with sex in an age-appropriate way. This is not
Cosmo with Clearasil ads. In the August issue, for example, a
16-year-old reader says her boyfriend wants to have sex but she
wants to wait until she's 20. ``You should have your talk,'' the
magazine's Dr. Judy advises, ``way before the kissing gets out of
hand.''
</P>
<P>
   The trick, says Rubenstein, is ``treating a 16-year-old girl as
a person, being real and letting them know we, too, are real.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the August anniversary issue of CosmoGIRL!, Rubenstein kicks
off her Editor's Note with one word: ``Hey!'' And she signs it
``Atoosa,'' written in red pen with a hand-scrawled heart before
the A. In between, frank words:
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked about problems I had as a teen and how I got over
them. But there was one problem I didn't kick until this year; I
was terrified (this last word is in hot pink bold letters) of going
anywhere alone. Perfect example? Let's say I was supposed to meet
my friends at a party. I'd be totally frozen (again in hot pink) if
I didn't spot them right away. Inside my head I'd be saying, `Say
hi to someone. Just say hi. SAY HI YOU MORON!' But I was so scared,
I'd rush into the bathroom and wash my hands or study my face until
my friends got there.'' She goes on. ``Why did I feel weird? Let me
count the ways: I was so emotionally connected to music that
sometimes I'd cry...''
</P>
<P>
   Rubenstein, who was tickled recently when she rediscovered a fan
letter she wrote to Menudo, insists she's not a teen-aged girl
trapped in a woman's body. She just has an outstanding memory of
her youth, of how she felt, what she wore, and even that Saturday
morning American Bandstand program when Madonna uttered those
famous words to Dick Clark that she wanted to ``rule the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a place in my mind,'' she says, ``where I go and
remember.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 1343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
