<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-RUIZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDERCUT ON THE UNDERCARD? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ The week barely had begun and there already were big
problems with the John Ruiz-Evander Holyfield card. Fortunately,
they didn't involve Ruiz or Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   The bout between World Boxing Association welterweight champion
James Page and mandatory No. 1 contender Andrew ``Six Heads'' Lewis
is being billed as the semi-main event on Saturday's Showtime card.
But the way it looks, Six Heads will need six pairs of eyes to find
Page.
</P>
<P>
   According to Page's Washington attorney, Kiyo Oden, the champion
was informed of the fight only five days ago and has no intention
of defending the title Saturday night. Oden said the WBA has
dragged its feet on rescheduling the fight since June 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel one week's notice of a world title fight raises safety
and health issues for James,'' Oden said.
</P>
<P>
   But according to boxing sources, this is all about Page's
threatened move to dump manager Carl King, the son of his promoter,
Don King, in favor of James Prince, the former rap impresario who
has signed Floyd Mayweather and is wooing Roy Jones Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Since he began to quarrel over his managerial contract, Page has
not fought; his last ring appearance was July 24, 1999, and he has
gone through four trainers since his troubles with King began.
</P>
<P>
   Page, who is scheduled to earn only $112,500 for this fight, has
not been seen in Las Vegas and is not expected to attend Thursday's
press conference. Don King was in Los Angeles Tuesday publicizing
the Ruiz-Holyfield fight for the vacant WBA title; efforts to reach
him were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Oden fears that the WBA will try to strip Page for failing to
appear Saturday night because the organization and King are
longtime allies. ``James's main concern is the WBA stripping him of
his title,'' Oden said. ``We've had no contact from them since June
27 until I got a voice message from (WBA president) Gilberto
Mendoza on Aug. 3 saying no decision had been made on the fight or
whether there needed to be a new purse bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Later that day, they informed us not only that the fight was
on but that it was scheduled for Aug. 12 in Las Vegas and there was
no warranting a new purse bid. How do you make no decision early in
the day and later in the day have a site and a date for the
fight?''
</P>
<P>
   Page (25-3, 19 KOs) is a fearsome puncher, and so is Lewis
(18-0-1, 17 KOs). Lewis has not fought since Dec. 11, 1999, but has
knocked out 12 of his last 13 opponents, which is an obvious reason
why trying to fight him on a week's notice seems unwise.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact the title he is fighting Ruiz for became vacant
only because of boxing's odd politics, three-time world champion
Holyfield said Tuesday he still believes it will be a
record-breaking performance if he wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't feel it's tainted because I look at what this
game's always been,'' Holyfield said. ``When you don't follow the
rules and regulations, you lose your title. I decided to keep
fighting (after losing to Lennox Lewis) and the guy who was the
best didn't follow the regulations (and defend against Ruiz, his
mandatory challenger, instead opting to make more money fighting
Michael Grant in April). He forfeited his belt. I don't feel
ashamed.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz has been training in Las Vegas at the legendary Johnny
Tocco's gym. Although Tocco died several years ago, the gym has
remained an out-of-town home for some of the greatest fighters of
all-time.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz for months has been asked to justify his No. 1 ranking and
shot at the world title, even though no one seems to bring up that
question to Grant, who was destroyed in less than two rounds by
Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   On that matter, Ruiz is growing weary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have put myself on the line so many times,'' Ruiz said.
``First of all, I wanted to fight Grant (who was then the WBA's No.
2 contender), and what happens next? He decides to fight Lewis, and
that leaves me out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lewis is totally avoiding me. What am I supposed to do? I'm
basicaly going by the rules. I was No. 1 in both the WBA and WBC,
which I earned because I came up the ladder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely feel I have a lot to prove. Even to myself. I
know I'm a great fighter and I intend to prove it. There's always
going to be criticism no matter what happens. There's nothing I can
say that will change people's minds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
