<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COULD THIS SITUATION BECOME UNMANAGEABLE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Jimy Williams is two-thirds of the way through
his fourth season managing the Boston Red Sox. If he makes it to
Opening Day 2001, he will have more continuous service on New
England's hot seat than any man since Joe Cronin (1935-47).
</P>
<P>
   Lately, there has been reason to wonder whether Jimy will last
that long. This has been a trying season for the Sox, and the deep
freeze between the manager and general manager Dan Duquette is
enough to cool the World Trade Center. Most recently, Williams got
little support from the front office when he confronted the team's
out-of-control center fielder.
</P>
<P>
   So what about it, Jimy? Will you be back next year?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a contract for next year,'' he answered. ``Why would
you ask that?''
</P>
<P>
   I told him. It strikes me that he might not need all this grief.
He's made plenty of dough. Life might be simpler as a coach with
the Braves again. He could be fired (like almost all managers) or
he could quit (like so few).
</P>
<P>
   ``That's your opinion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's not an opinion, really. Just a question. As the Sox lurch
toward the finish of this goofy 2000 season, Williams has the look
of a man who could decide that he doesn't want to go through this
again. Then again, maybe it's just my imagination. Maybe managing
the Red Sox under Duquette isn't such a bad thing. Maybe the talk
shows and papers aren't driving him nuts. Maybe he thrives in an
environment where the smallest event takes on enormous importance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Boston,'' he said. ``I like the way the fans come out
and pull for us. People in that city, they want us to be good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good things don't come easy, and I like that. People here,
when we don't win, they point at me. The starters aren't going six
innings and you're not getting the hits you want. Everybody has an
idea, but that's because they want the team to be good.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston is a tough town in which to manage, and this has been a
challenging season (47 players, too many injuries) for any big
league skipper. Williams has been uneasy and downright testy with
some of his postgame nonanswers. But he says he still likes it
here.
</P>
<P>
   How are things with you and Dan?
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan, he's fine,'' said Jimy. ``Our communication has been
fine. Dan gave me an opportunity to manage and I appreciate that.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he involve you in personnel decisions?
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly I'm asked, yes, a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Did you know Jeff Frye was going to be traded?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are his answers and he's sticking to 'em. He's not going
to tell you the real story on Frye, Izzy Alcantara (whom he'd like
to banish to Alcatraz), the games he's been forced to manage
shorthanded, his confrontation with the wacko center fielder, or
his relationship with Duquette.
</P>
<P>
   Jimy managed only one other big league team, the Blue Jays. In
Toronto, he stood up to loco outfielder George Bell but was not
supported by the front office and eventually lost his job after a
12-24 start in his fourth season. It's hard to believe he'd want to
repeat that scenario.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's not that bad. Maybe Jimy and Dan are harmonious and
happy with one another. But it looks to me like they're just being
cool and professional as they work through their differences. When
Williams talks about Duquette, I'm reminded of Bill Parcells
talking about Bob Kraft in the final weeks of the 1996 Super Bowl
season.
</P>
<P>
   Jimy will tell you that there's nothing like managing in Boston.
He said he tries to answer his mail and acknowledges he's gotten a
few lineup suggestions. He said he's never listened to talk radio
and rarely looks at a newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't sleep because I know I'm missing those
articles,'' he said (good zinger there).
</P>
<P>
   He still refers to his players as ``kids.'' Always, he talks
about winning ``tonight's game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like our team,'' he said. ``I love baseball. It's been very
special for me and my family. Baseball owes me nothing. I owe
everything to baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's game is the last one in Anaheim, game No. 110, with 52
to play in the fourth year of the James Francis Williams
administration.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by
e-mail at dshaughnessy(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
