u i BC-TORIES-BLAIR-BOS &LR;      08-09 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORIES-BLAIR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORIES SCOLD BLAIR'S WIFE FOR POLICY STAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In an unusually scathing personal attack, Britain's
Conservative party has accused the wife of Prime Minister Tony
Blair of inappropriately using her position to take a political
stand and branded her a cross between an ambitious Hillary Clinton
and a murder-minded Lady Macbeth.
</P>
<P>
   The attack, described as unprecedented by some commentators,
touched off a vitriolic debate about the proper place of the person
married to Britain's leader, in a nation that gives the spouse of a
prime minister no formal role or title.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate indication of how the broadside was
playing with the British public, but with next year's general
election hovering, the Tories could be playing with fire. On the
very same day, the Independent newspaper published an internal Tory
party report warning Conservative leader William Hague that his
party is not in step with most Britons' views on marriage and
women's issues.
</P>
<P>
   The brouhaha erupted Monday when Blair's wife, using her
professional name, Cherie Booth, wrote an opinion piece for The
Daily Telegraph newspaper lauding the pending incorporation into
British law of the European Convention on Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Many conservatives opposed to surrendering British sovereignty
in the name of European integration say the new law will usurp the
authority of British judges and lead to a plethora of frivolous
lawsuits, especially by criminals using specious human rights
claims to try to quash their convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Booth, a lawyer who specializes in human rights litigation,
praised the new law, suggesting that it ``forms an integral part of
the government's program of constitutional reform, which has the
aim of modernizing Britain to make it a strong and confident
democracy in the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Later on Monday, the Tories unleashed an attack dog in the
person of John Bercow, a parliamentarian who is the party's
spokesman on home affairs. Bercow charged that Booth had broken
``the long-established convention that prime minister's spouses do
not push their own political agendas.'' The Blairs, who were out of
town on an annual vacation trip to Italy, had no immediate
response.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a swipe at the Clinton administration, which is cozy with
Blair's government, Bercow said Booth had a ``bad dose of `Hillary
syndrome' '' and accused her of wanting either to ``direct policy
from behind the throne'' or set herself up to become lord
chancellor, Britain's highest legal authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``She forgets that in Britain we already have a first lady: the
queen,'' Bercow said. ``If the Blairs bothered to look at their
soulmates the Clintons, they would see that American voters are not
impressed by unelected spouses who seek to ram politically correct
prejudices down their throats. People in Britain will not put up
with anyone who thinks they can be an unaccountable cross between
the first lady and Lady Macbeth.''
</P>
<P>
   At 10 Downing St., Blair's aides were trying Tuesday to figure
out how comparing Booth to Mrs. Clinton, who is much admired by the
Blair administration, amounted to an insult. But given that
Shakespeare's Lady Macbeth is so ambitious that she talks her
husband into murdering the king, there is little doubt what the
Conservatives had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Tanya Joseph, a spokeswoman for the prime minister, rejected the
suggestion that Booth had broken an unwritten rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is an experienced, well-respected human rights lawyer, and
occasionally she writes on matters within her area of interest and
expertise,'' Joseph said. ``Besides being married to the prime
minister, she is an independent, working woman.''
</P>
<P>
   At Labor Party headquarters, they were calling the attack on the
prime minister's wife ``despicable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the sort of utterly offensive rubbish that you expect
from the Tories these days,'' said Fraser Kemp, a Labor
parliamentarian.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Party spokesman Peter Craske acknowledged that
Bercow's unusually harsh comments, which some have described as
sexist, had drawn a mixed reaction. Still, he said, Bercow was
voicing the views of the party leadership and his comments were
authorized by the party's central office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point behind what he said is valid,'' Craske said. ``In
this country, prime minister's wives don't get involved in
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how such a rule would apply to a prime minister's husband,
especially since the Tory standard bearer remains former prime
minister Margaret Thatcher, Craske replied: ``Right. Prime
minister's spouses. Whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Craske said Booth should refrain from voicing any opinions on
public policy until her husband leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Tuesday whether Bercow or anyone else in the Tory
leadership had seen the party's internal report on women's issues
before launching the attack on Booth. The Conservative Policy Forum
report, based on surveys of party members, suggested that placing
``too heavy an emphasis on traditional marriage by our party would
be politically unwise.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Many groups believe that the party itself should improve its
image for young working women,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   It struck some as odd that a party that seeks to attract young
working women would attack the nation's most visible working mom.
Just days before giving birth to her fourth child in May, the
45-year-old Booth went to court to challenge the policy of her
husband's government that denies parental leave to some British
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Allyson Abel, a lawyer from North London who balances work with
looking after her 1-year-old daughter, noted that the Tories had no
complaints when Booth legally challenged her husband's government
in court in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't accept that in her role as a lawyer she can't say
anything or take a position,'' Abel said. ``She was a lawyer before
her husband became prime minister, and she'll be one after he
leaves office.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Abel knows many British women disagree. Her mother-in-law
disapproves of her using her maiden name professionally.
</P>
<P>
   A poll last year found that although British women are getting
ahead in business, with their ranks in executive positions growing
and the gap between them and male managers beginning to narrow,
four out of five working women with families still do all or most
of the housework.
</P>
</TEXT>
