u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      08-09 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EATON PUTS HIS NOSE TO THE GRINDSTONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ Understand this: Chad Eaton is a nice man.
He'd be someone you'd like, regardless of whether he was a football
player. He'd be someone you'd want to have a soft drink and a pizza
with. He's got charisma and pizzazz. No wonder every media outlet
in New England wanted him.
</P>
<P>
   And Eaton was more than accommodating.
</P>
<P>
   That's why his current silence is the ultimate sacrifice for the
Patriots nose tackle, a sign of devotion to his full-time job,
football. He no longer engages in media interviews or idle
chitchat. He doesn't rehearse funny lines to throw out for sound
bites. He doesn't even talk that much to his own teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Eaton, 28, didn't have the best of years in 1999, but it wasn't
as bad as some have portrayed it. The coaching staff was concerned
that Eaton was devoting too much time to talk shows. He would
appear on WEEI's ``Dennis and Callahan'' show every Monday, even in
the worst of times when the callers were irate. He also went on
WNRB's Patriots show on Mondays. He'd often do postgame interviews
with flagship station WBCN, or just about anyone else who asked.
Then he'd show up on a late-night Sunday sports show.
</P>
<P>
   It was all Chad, all the time.
</P>
<P>
   But now he is dealing with it differently, staying away from
interviews. Occasionally he will be quoted in Sports Illustrated or
on ESPN.com, but his reasoning is that those are special
circumstances, media people he doesn't deal with every day. It's
not that Eaton has turned his back on the media _ which created his
character to begin with _ but he wants to be taken seriously as a
football player.
</P>
<P>
   It was a realization he came to on his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Chad just realized that it was an issue, something
that was affecting him,'' said linebacker Ted Johnson. ``I don't
know the whole story. Chad . . . loves life. He feeds off
everything. He gets energy off things that happen. He's a fun guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just realized that he needed to take it a little more
seriously. From what I've seen, he's done real well. He's doing his
job out there and not saying much off the field, and that's more
advantageous for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Eaton came out of nowhere, a practice squad guy
discovered by Bill Belichick in Cleveland in 1995, then nurtured by
Pete Carroll to the point where he became a very good player. But
with that came more attention on the field. He often was
double-teamed. This was new to him, and sometimes confusing. In
some games, it seemed he didn't show up, but in just as many he did
a lot of little things that wouldn't show up in statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Eaton was used to feeding off Johnson. Both played in the middle
of the field and were responsible for shutting down the run. But
Johnson missed the first 11 games last season, and that seemed to
affect Eaton adversely.
</P>
<P>
   With Belichick running the Patriots, Eaton is trying to be at
his best again, and if that means having tunnel vision when it
comes to the media and personal appearances, so be it.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriot who has known him the longest, Drew Bledsoe, a
former teammate at Washington State, thinks Eaton is willing to do
whatever it takes to be the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just seen the progress over the years, and it's
amazing,'' said Bledsoe. ``I've seen him mature as a player and as
a person. He's a terrific player who can be very disruptive in the
backfield. I think Chad just needed to get himself going again and
get to the next level. That's what he's doing right now. He's a
winner and he's doing everything he can to get there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I wouldn't have to speak to the media, either,'' said
Bledsoe, half-kiddingly.
</P>
<P>
   When Eaton arrived in New England, he had blue hair and tattoos
and didn't mind explaining them. Now he's had most of his body art
removed, and his hair is cropped short and back to its natural
color. He's a husband and a father, and has endured some personal
tragedy with the death of his mother.
</P>
<P>
   He also is in shape like never before, an indication of his
seriousness. In the first two exhibition games, Eaton was
disruptive on the line and in the backfield. That's what Belichick
challenged him to do. After watching films, the coach basically
asked Eaton what he wanted to be _ a dominating player or a ``JAG''
(just another guy)? It's obvious which path Eaton has chosen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chad can be very good,'' said Johnson. ``Athletically, he's
very gifted. He's a rocket man. He's strong. He's chiseled. You
never see Chad dominated. He might have a bad play here and there,
but he's never overmatched. And now, he's lost weight, he's
stronger, quicker. I'm excited for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Free agent defensive lineman Reggie Grimes from Alabama has had
a ball playing alongside Eaton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very, very intense,'' said Grimes. ``He's taught me a
lot. He'll tell me where I should be and what I should be doing.
He's very knowledgeable about the defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Even center Damien Woody, who has battled Eaton in training camp
and practice the past two years, sees more intensity. Woody gets
quite a workout day in and day out.
</P>
<P>
   In past seasons, Eaton likely would be trash-talking about what
he does to Woody on a daily basis. But that was the old Chad. This
is the new one. He may not be as fun, but every once in a while you
have to reinvent yourself. The Patriots believe that this is a new
and improved Chad Eaton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
