<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6703 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-BOS &LR;      08-09 1861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN EUROPE, RYDER HOPEFULS TEE OFF ON EACH OTHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WISHAW, England _ After the Europeans collapsed last September
at The Country Club, allowing the Americans to claim the greatest
comeback victory in the history of the Ryder Cup, they consoled
themselves on the long flight back across the Atlantic by noting
the differences between them and their hillbilly hosts in
Brookline.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans were golf Philistines. American fans made a
mockery of the etiquette so treasured by golf traditionalists,
mercilessly heckling Europe's Colin Montgomerie, calling the pudgy
Scotsman ``Mrs. Doubtfire.'' They cheered every good shot by an
American and every dubbed shot by a European with a jingoism that
bordered on xenophobia.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, going beyond the beyonds, as Sean O'Casey might
have put it, the American team and their wives danced on the 17th
green after Justin Leonard improbably holed a 45-foot putt,
oblivious to the fact that Spain's Jose Maria Olazabal still had a
chance to halve the hole. His line walked on, his concentration
destroyed, Ollie left his desperation putt well short.
</P>
<P>
   We'd never do that, the Europeans said.
</P>
<P>
   We have too much class for that, the Europeans said.
</P>
<P>
   We're sportsmen, the Europeans said.
</P>
<P>
   We respect the etiquette of the game, the Europeans said.
</P>
<P>
   And they swore vengeance, saying things would be different in
September 2001 here at The Belfry.
</P>
<P>
   Well, so far, things are indeed different. Almost one year after
the debacle at The Country Club, and one year before the Ryder Cup
is staged here, the Europeans are at war _ not with the Americans,
but with each other.
</P>
<P>
   Never has the European team been so fragmented and riven by
personality clashes, hurt feelings, and grievances, real or
imagined.
</P>
<P>
   To paraphrase Peter Gammons's famous description of an
infamously self-centered Red Sox team, the 2001 European Ryder Cup
team could turn out to be 12 guys, 12 cabs.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the European feud has claimed a victim. Mark James, the
European captain at The Country Club, was forced to resign last
week as the 2001 vice-captain after several continental players,
and even England's Nick Faldo, questioned his temperament and
integrity. Sam Torrance, the Scotsman who is the current European
captain, tried to save his friend, James. But the European Ryder
Cup committee wanted to end what had become an embarrassing soap
opera, precipitated by James's tell-all book ``Into the Bear Pit,''
an account of the golf war at The Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   The continentals, especially Olazabal and France's Jean Van de
Velde, who stewed at Brookline when James refused to play him in
the early matches, complain that the British in general and the
English in particular have too much control of the European team.
The continental players resent that the leadership of the 2001 team
is entirely British. Ian Woosnam, a Welshman, survives James as
Torrance's other vice-captain.
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal recently threatened to leave the European tour and
compete exclusively on the American tour. Olazabal claims the
European tour is British-oriented. He said the British players get
preferential treatment, alleging that too many photos of
Montgomerie, Europe's No. 1 player for most of the last decade,
adorn the European tour programs, at the expense of continental
players.
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal's complaints, which are shared by many other
continentals who are more reticent about airing them, have to be
taken seriously, if only because he and his countrymen, Sergio
Garcia and Miguel Angel Jiminez, may make up such a big chunk of
the next European Ryder Cup team _ unless Olazabal decides to
follow through on his threat and bolt for the American tour.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   James's fate was sealed by his book, which is mostly an account
trashing the trash-talking Americans, and a spirited defense of his
own strategy, which many more objective observers have blamed for
the Europeans' collapse on the final day of singles matches at The
Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, James questions the moral integrity of Tom Lehman
and mocks Faldo, who had been a member of the previous 11 Ryder Cup
teams, as a preening has-been. In the most controversial passage,
James claims that when Faldo sent a letter wishing the European
team good luck in Brookline, James rolled the letter up in a ball
and tossed it into a wastebasket in front of the players.
</P>
<P>
   It was a great story, but, it turns out, slightly apocryphal.
While Lee Westwood, England's best golfer, suggested the letter
belonged ``in the bin,'' Van de Velde said the rest of the team did
not witness the incident, as James claims in his book.
</P>
<P>
   Faldo accused James of fabricating the story. Even after James
was forced to resign, Faldo vowed to press on with his campaign to
expose James as a liar. But then European PGA officials warned
Faldo against throwing stones, as he was not without sin himself,
having made some unsupportable accusations against officials and
fellow players over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, a chastened Faldo declared his feud with James
was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has gone on too long,'' said Faldo. ``It's time to bring
the matter to a close. Golf is all bigger than this.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether golf is as big as the egos involved, however, is another
question.
</P>
<P>
   James, who refused to use one of his two captain's picks to put
Faldo on the 1999 team, is one of the few people who could rally
sympathy for Faldo, seen by many of his peers as a self-absorbed
loner. But if Faldo is egotistical, James is considered by some
European players, and more than a few Americans, to be a
condescending jerk.
</P>
<P>
   It was telling that the only vocal support James got after his
dismissal came from fellow Britons: Westwood and Darren Clarke, the
cigar-smoking big hitter from Northern Ireland who beat Tiger Woods
in match play earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke, who shares Woods's coach, Butch Harmon, said James did a
good job at The Country Club, and noted that the European tour's
tournament committee, which represents players, voted unanimously
to back James. Clarke made it clear that he considers Faldo the
real villain in this tawdry affair, though he despises Faldo so
much he would not use his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``A certain person took great offense to the book, even though
he spends most of his time in America, and decided Mark shouldn't
have anything to do with the Ryder Cup,'' said Clarke, voicing the
sense of betrayal many European players feel when their peers leave
the European tour for the US tour, and underscoring why Olazabal's
threat to do so is so sensitive here.
</P>
<P>
   Woosnam diplomatically declined comment while Montgomerie was
conspicuously ambivalent about backing James, though clearly
relieved that James got the boot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our attention must focus on looking forward to The Belfry in
2001,'' said Montgomerie, who was as vocal as James about loutish
American behavior at The Country Club and has had his own running
feud with Faldo for years.
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal, Van de Velde, and other continentals among likely
members of the 2001 team were reported to be pleased by James's
sacking.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Huggert, who was captain of the 1977 Ryder Cup team that
played at Royal Lytham and included both Faldo and James, was also
relieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Mark very much and I don't think that when he wrote the
book he knew the trouble it would cause,'' said Huggert. ``But in
my opinion he was never a good choice as vice-captain after
captaining the team in 1999 when there was all that trouble. To
have Mark inside the ropes at The Belfry in quite an important
position would have caused a lot of friction.''
</P>
<P>
   European sportswriters, even some notoriously jingoistic
Englishmen, were overwhelmingly in favor of James getting the boot,
saying his defensive, tell-all book showed poor judgment at best
and, at worst, was evidence that he had used his position as
captain to enrich himself.
</P>
<P>
   While some Britons stood up for James, many others welcomed his
dismissal. Mark Reed, the affable head teaching pro here at The
Belfry, was so busy giving lessons last week that he didn't know
James had been sacked. When informed by the Globe of James's forced
resignation, Reed said, ``Good. Now we can get back to the game,
which is what it's supposed to be all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed spoke for many golfers, pros and hackers alike, who were
appalled by the Ryder Cup becoming a sideshow for petty personal
disputes and score-settling. The Ryder Cup is taken far more
seriously in Europe _ and especially in Britain and Ireland _ than
it is in the United States. For Europeans who complain about
American domination in sports, politics, and business, winning the
Ryder Cup takes on a dimension far larger than a simple golf
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many European fans believe there is enough time for their team
to put aside the last few months of dissension and be ready when
the Americans descend on The Belfry next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a special place, because it's hosted three of the last
eight Ryder Cups, and three of the last four played in Europe,''
said Colin Johnston, from nearby Telford, as he contemplated what
club to use at the par-3, 190-yard 14th hole, where Faldo's
hole-in-one helped him halve his match with Paul Azinger in 1993,
when the Americans won here. ``I think by the time the matches
begin here next year, everyone will have forgotten about this. I
know I will.''
</P>
<P>
   The championship Brabazon course here gobbles up mis-hits. Water
guards approach shots at seven of the holes, and small brooks lie
in wait in the middle of several fairways. This great track rewards
shrewd course management far more than sheer power. It is the
course and the game, the history of both, and the Ryder Cup that so
many Europeans are hoping will assert itself in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in the middle of the fairway of the 473-yard 18th hole,
near the spot where Christy O'Connor Jr. hit a flawless 2-iron to
beat Fred Couples and help the Europeans secure the Ryder Cup in
1989, Sean Maguire said he hoped the dissension would be
overshadowed by the history of The Belfry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at that,'' said Maguire, an Irishman living in London,
pointing to the plaque embedded in the fairway, commemorating
O'Connor and the 2-iron heard all over Europe. ``This is what it's
about. Not someone selling books. Not someone trying to score
personal points over a rival. This is about golf.''
</P>
<P>
   After the European collapse at The Country Club, James quit as
captain of the Ryder Cup team, saying he wanted to concentrate on
making the 2001 team as a player. Faldo, meanwhile, is rejuvenated,
playing his best golf in years, and hopes to make the team, too.
</P>
<P>
   Mustering a smile after a difficult few months, Torrance last
week said he looked forward to playing Faldo and James together in
the foursomes at The Belfry next year.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Faldo and Mark James, standing next to each other on the
first tee of the Brabazon, with blunt instruments in their hands?
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, that is something to look forward to.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
