<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6705 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-PERKINELMER-ART-BOS &LR;      08-09 1825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERKINELMER-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 RENAMED, PERKINELMER THRIVES AFTER BREAK WITH GOVERNMENT WORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLESLEY, Mass. _ The transition was swift, so fast that the
new company name still is only printed on paper and pasted on the
lobby doors, covering the old logo, etched into the plate glass.
</P>
<P>
   But Gregory L. Summe, the new chief executive of the company
that now calls itself PerkinElmer Inc., seems in a hurry to
obliterate much of the past connected with the old name of EG&AMP;G
Inc. In less than two years, he has radically reshaped a one-time
electronics icon into a contender in a quite different field,
dumping its biggest division.
</P>
<P>
   The turnaround remains a work in progress. But already it has
lifted the company's once slumbering stock to new heights. Since
being named chairman and chief executive in April 1999, Summe, 43,
has tried to raise investor interest by building on existing assets
and products.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, PerkinElmer is betting on a strategy that
positions it as a player in a field many believe could be the
world's next big economic engine, biotechnology and genomic
research.
</P>
<P>
   The gamble could qualify the firm as ``a case study in corporate
transformation,'' says life sciences consultant Marc Hennebert of
Arthur D. Little Inc. in Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   EG&AMP;G, founded in 1947 by Massachusetts Institute of Technology
professor Harold E. Edgerton and two former students, has long
boasted an eclectic product mix, beginning with high-speed flash
lighting for photography, which Edgerton invented.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the company catalog grew to include scanners for
supermarket checkout counters, explosives-detection equipment for
airports, high-vacuum pumps and valves used in machines that make
computer chips, scientific instruments for research, and literally
hundreds more. Bernard O'Keefe _ the longtime chief executive, who
died in 1989 _ once said he couldn't keep track of them all in his
head.
</P>
<P>
   But EG&AMP;G also had a dark side. For much of its life, the bulk of
the company's revenues came from managing major parts of the US
government's nuclear weapons program, beginning with atomic bomb
tests on the South Pacific atolls of Bikini and Eniwetok in 1947
and 1948. Even earlier, O'Keefe was responsible for wiring the
trigger for the atomic bomb dropped on Nagasaki, Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Although EG&AMP;G dropped its nuclear management work, beginning in
1994, the Technical Services division remained the largest
operating unit, even though it returned the slimmest profit. As a
result, stock performance was lackluster for years, and Wall Street
commentator Ron Dorfman put EG&AMP;G on his list of ``do-nothing''
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been languishing in the swamps,'' said John Keane,
founder and chief executive of Keane Inc., a Boston high-tech
consulting firm and an EG&AMP;G director.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1998, EG&AMP;G's board took action, hiring Summe as
president and putting him in line to succeed John M. Kucharski,
then 61, who was making plans to retire as chairman and chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Summe says his task was to find product lines among existing
holdings that could be developed into businesses with the potential
to be marketplace pacesetters.
</P>
<P>
   ``My charter from the board was to make EG&AMP;G a successful
commercial enterprise,'' he said during an interview in his office,
which lacked the usual corner-office decor of framed photos and
certificates.
</P>
<P>
   Summe, who runs and skis to keep fit, still speaks with traces
of his Kentucky boyhood. He holds a master's degree in electrical
engineering, but says he was bitten by the business bug at age 12,
thinking he might take over his father's electrical contracting
business. After college he worked in Texas designing semiconductor
chips, taking night business courses before heading to the
University of Pennsylvania's Wharton School for a master's degree
in business administration.
</P>
<P>
   For seven years, he was a McKinsey &AMP; Co. consultant, followed by
five years moving through the executive ranks at AlliedSignal Corp.
His last job there, before a headhunter's call led him to EG&AMP;G, was
running its automotive products group.
</P>
<P>
   The transition following his arrival was wrenching. Kucharski, a
27-year EG&AMP;G veteran who had been chairman since 1987, summed it up
this way: ``Transitions are difficult. You never know how much so
until you get into one.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of EG&AMP;G executives retired, were reassigned, or left. The
total work force was cut 10 percent, to about 12,000, about 1,000
of them now in Massachusetts. Corporate staff was cut in half, and
the executive suite was trimmed from 15 people to 10, nine of them
new to their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Three of those nine, including chief financial officer Robert
Friel, came from AlliedSignal, as Summe began reorganizing and
regrouping the 31 individual operating units EG&AMP;G had built up over
five decades of technological innovation.
</P>
<P>
   Several units were sold, including Technical Services, which
handled the government work and was EG&AMP;G's cash cow for more than
30 years. As recently as 1992, the unit brought in about 70 percent
of EG&AMP;G's revenues. Even after dropping its nuclear facilities
management work, it still accounted for 59 percent of the company's
$927 million in sales in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But the cost-plus contracts under which Technical Services did
its work delivered thin margins, hurting stock performance. Summe
believed that this reliance had created a complacency that thwarted
commercial product development.
</P>
<P>
   EG&AMP;G's culture ``had really been driven by what was successful
in the government contracting world,'' he said. ``You can't have
the same kind of financial ambitions.''
</P>
<P>
   Keane agreed, describing the company's atmosphere as ``very
genteel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But it was a far cry from the world of cyberspace, high
technology generally, where you are crunching time, always trying
to reduce costs, trying to leap out and stay ahead of your
competitors,'' he said. ``It was not the type of ball game a lot of
the newer directors came to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the first operating units to catch Summe's eye in early
1999 were two in Europe, Berthold GmbH, in Germany, and Wallac Oy,
in Finland, which Kucharski had acquired in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Both made scientific instruments for biotechnology and genomics
research laboratories. Hennebert, at Arthur D. Little, estimates
that spending in this marketplace runs about $5 billion a year and
will grow about 15 percent annually for at least two more years.
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time, Perkin-Elmer Corp. _ an old-line,
Norwalk, Conn., maker of precision scientific instruments _ was
putting its manufacturing operations up for sale, as it moved into
direct genomic research. Renamed PE Biosystems Corp., the company
had taken genomics researcher J. Craig Venter's Celera Corp. under
its wing and joined the race to map the human genome.
</P>
<P>
   Perkin-Elmer's scientific hardware unit was a nice match to
those of Berthold and Wallac, and in March 1999 Summe agreed to buy
these operations for $250 million cash, plus assumed debt.
</P>
<P>
   The Perkin-Elmer name was part of the deal. That July Summe
announced EG&AMP;G would be renamed PerkinElmer.
</P>
<P>
   In August, the company's Technical Services unit was sold for
$250 million to the Carlyle Group, a Washington, D.C., investment
group. The EG&AMP;G name went with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Changing the name was very controversial at the time,'' Summe
said. But keeping it, he said, would endorse the status quo. A new
brand, built on a name scientists knew, ``changed us culturally.''
</P>
<P>
   J. Kent Hansen, a Massachusetts Institute of Technology
professor of nuclear engineering and senior member of the
PerkinElmer board of directors, said: ``Changing the name was a way
to sever our connection with government contracting. One has to
give Greg credit for this.''
</P>
<P>
   Two more moves further solidified the company's position in
genomics. One was an $8 million investment in Genomic Solutions
Inc. of Ann Arbor, Mich., which is also involved in genome mapping
and went public in May.
</P>
<P>
   The other was PerkinElmer's June announcement of a deal to
acquire NEN Life Sciences Inc. in Boston's South End, which makes
and sells radioactive isotopes for medical use and research. The
price: $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   NEN already made nonradioactive luminescent research reagents
for laboratory use, a field in which Wallac also is active. It
already had plans to expand into genomics research, and later this
year will begin selling glass microscope slides carrying samples of
human genomic material for research laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   Summe expects NEN Life Sciences to post $125 million in sales
this year, up from $108 million in 1999, pushing total revenues for
PerkinElmer's life sciences unit to nearly $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   There's activity at other PerkinElmer divisions, too, led by a
unit that has helped set the pace in developing machines to detect
explosives in airport luggage and cargo. Just before changing its
corporate name last fall, EG&AMP;G bought one of its biggest
competitors in the business, Vivid Technologies Inc. of Woburn, for
$62.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Other growth opportunities the company cites are in strobe
lighting for the entertainment industry, fiber-optic devices, and
flat digital display panels made from an EG&AMP;G-invented substance
called amorphous silicon. Panels for reading X-rays without film
are now on the market; the images can be stored in digital files
and transmitted to doctors and hospitals around the world. Summe
also foresees applications in luggage and cargo inspection.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts are bullish about these prospects. The
company ``is more than a turnaround now,'' said Paul Knight of
Thomas Weisel Partners in New York. ``They are morphing from a
conglomerate to a growth stock.''
</P>
<P>
   He expects PerkinElmer shares, which hit a closing high of
$76.25 in March and closed at $65.5625, up 43.75 cents, on Friday,
to reach $95 during the first half of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   James Samuels, a Banc of America Securities analyst, applauds
the focus on life sciences. ``I don't know if Greg scours the
scientific journals or what, but anything that's interesting, that
seems to have any promise, they're doing it.'' Samuels has set a
target share price of $75 by Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Summe says that more acquisitions and divestitures are likely.
``We'd rather be in fewer businesses, but in really strong
competitive positions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Edgerton and his founding partners, Kenneth Germeshausen and
Herbert Grier, are dead, but those who knew them say they'd like
what's happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doc,'' as Edgerton was known, ``thought change was
wonderful,'' Hansen said. ``Everything that opened broader horizons
and brought new ways of seeing things _ Doc would be all for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
