<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000809.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6713 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     08-09 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO TITANS OF INDUSTRY RIDE A WAVE OF GROWTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brand new companies, especially technology companies, get
investors' juices flowing because they promise fast growth. They
double and triple their sales quarter by quarter, albeit from tiny
bases.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is, start-ups don't have a monopoly on explosive
growth. Sometimes big established companies can blow the doors off
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Two recent examples came from a pair of America's corporate
giants, General Electric and Merck.
</P>
<P>
   At GE, the stellar performance was turned in by GE Power
Systems, a division of the company that has been turning out
turbines for the utility industry practically forever. You can't
get much more old economy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the second quarter, Power Systems turned in numbers that
would make any new economy company jealous. Sales rose 60 percent
to $3.74 billion and profits rose 45 percent to $752 million.
Orders rose 80 percent to $5 billion. Just to be clear, that is
billion with a ``b.''
</P>
<P>
   To some extent GE is benefiting from being in the right place at
the right time. The nation's utilities went years without ordering
new generating capacity. Now, short of power _ witness this
summer's near blackouts in California _ they have opened up their
wallets and started buying.
</P>
<P>
   But GE is more than lucky. ``They have picked up market share
and they have come up with new and better products,'' said William
Fiala, an analyst with Edward Jones. According to one report, GE
won 65 percent of the orders for heavy duty gas turbines in the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In typical GE fashion, Power Systems also has figured out how to
boost revenue by selling more services to utility customers.
Analysts say the current boom should last at least a few more years
with orders coming from both American and foreign customers.
</P>
<P>
   Power Systems, now GE's biggest industrial business, has done
well enough to make its boss, Robert Nardelli, one of the three
candidates vying to succeed chief executive Jack Welch.
</P>
<P>
   At Merck, the star is a new drug called Vioxx. Vioxx is one of a
new class of painkillers that reduce inflammation without causing
the stomach problems associated with aspirin. Celebrex, a
competitor drug, works similarly. Vioxx has been approved to treat
symptoms of osteoarthritis, menstrual pain, and acute pain.
</P>
<P>
   Merck introduced Vioxx in May 1999. The drug had sales of $97
million in last year's second quarter. Sales rose to $111 million
in the third quarter, $265 million in the fourth quarter, $370
million in the first quarter of 2000 and $475 million in the most
recent quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The drug has already been approved for use in 70 countries.
``When Merck gets a blockbuster in their system they know what to
do with it,'' said William Sahlman, a professor at the Harvard
Business School.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Vioxx still has plenty of room to grow. According
to Rob Petrie of MFS Investment Management, the drug is still being
rolled out in more countries and is likely to be approved for more
conditions. ``If this is a nine-inning game we are probably only in
the second or third inning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Can you imagine the backflips Wall Street would be doing if a
new company _ a biotechnology company _ came out with a new product
that ramped up this fast?
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of fact, if Vioxx were an independent biotechnology
company its sales would be greater than all but one company in the
industry, Amgen. Genentech, currently the nation's number two
biotech firm, had lower sales than Vioxx in the second quarter yet
still boasts a market value of $44 billion. And Genentech loses
money.
</P>
<P>
   The point here is not to say that General Electric and Merck are
unappreciated or undervalued. ``Both these companies have rich
valuations,'' said Thomas O'Neill, chief investment officer at
FleetBoston Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Rather it is that we need to be careful when we make sweeping
judgments about giants and start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old companies in trouble are those that don't embrace
change or add real value,'' said Sahlman. ``What we need are enough
big companies to thrive to offset the ones that get massacred. In
the meantime little ones will grow and displace the big, bad ones.
That has always been so.''
</P>
<P>
   For investors the lesson is simple: Not everything worth owning
is turned out by three guys in a garage. In fact, sometimes the new
new thing comes in a very old package.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
