<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-SOUTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FLORIDA, A FEAR OF A BACKLASH TEMPERS GLEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By YVONNE ABRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ The seniors at Sunrise Lakes
Condominiums, a massive, sprawling development of dirt-colored
stucco apartment buildings near Fort Lauderdale, are watching
Senator Joseph I. Lieberman very closely indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Some see great cause for celebration in the fact that Vice
President Al Gore chose Lieberman as his running mate, making him
the first-ever Jewish candidate for the vice presidency. But they
know how things are, so they're worried, too. Stop by one of the
pools at the retirement community, where most of the residents are
Jewish, and free with their opinions, and you will find an optimism
that is decidedly guarded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very good,'' said Cathy Bulavram. ``So do I,''
said Jack Bulavram. ``But!''
</P>
<P>
   ``But!'' repeated Jack's 48-year-old son, William.
</P>
<P>
   Those buts are rich with years of history and experience for the
Bulavrams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish him luck, 'cause I like the idea,'' said Jack Bulavram,
``but there are so many anti-Jewish people around.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel a lot stronger against Jews, but they won't talk
about it,'' said William Bulavram.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the swimsuit-clad residents of Sunrise Lakes had watched
the talk shows and read the papers Tuesday morning. They'd heard
the pundits say Lieberman's early stand against President Clinton's
behavior with intern Monica Lewinsky could inoculate Gore against
criticism that links him to Clinton's character flaws. And they
agreed, mostly, with what they heard.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman certainly had their votes. But then again, most of
these retirees would have gone with Gore anyway, they said.
Lieberman simply makes them that much more certain to turn out on
Election Day, and more likely to get more involved in the campaign
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish voters make up 6 percent of Florida's voters, according
to local pollster Jim Kane. Whether the Senator from Connecticut
makes any difference to the rest of the state's voters was the big
question by the pool Tuesday, as it was elsewhere in this crucial
Southern state. The seniors wondered whether Lieberman's religion
would turn off non-Jews and whether he would be a victim of
anti-Semitism. Analysts wondered whether Gore's candidacy could be
helped anywhere in the South by his choice of running mate, but
agreed that if Lieberman could help the vice president's chances in
any southern state, it might be Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The contest in this state is far closer than it is elsewhere in
the South, according to recent polls. Those polls show Gore
trailing Texas Gov. George W. Bush badly in the rest of the South,
but by only single digits here. Florida is far more urban and
diverse than other Southern states, and voters are almost evenly
split between the two major parties. Indeed, many locals will say
the state is hardly southern at all, which makes it more fertile
ground for Gore than other states in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman might not help Gore in Florida as much as the very
popular US Senator Bob Graham, who was also under consideration as
Gore's running mate, might have, but he does change the equation
here, some analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut senator is ``a godsend'' said Susan MacManus, a
political scientist at the University of South Florida, Tampa.
Voters in Florida are 53 percent female, and comprise the oldest
electorate in the country. In 1996, 40 percent of those who voted
were over 60, MacManus said. Those voters carried Clinton to
victory in Florida in 1996, and made his 1992 defeat in the state a
narrow one.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Governor George W. Bush, whose brother Jeb is the popular
governor of Florida, has made inroads among those female and
elderly voters, she said, mostly by trying to tie the vice
president to Clinton's sins. Lieberman may allow Gore a way out of
that pigeonhole in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does bring the morality issue to the forefront,'' MacManus
said. ``He gives undecided, particularly female, voters _ wavering
towards George W. because of the morality issue _ some excuse to go
back to their ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My first reaction is that I feel very comfortable with Joe
Lieberman,'' said Jacques Abitan, a Miami travel wholesaler and
Morroccan immigrant, who is Jewish. ``Yesterday, I definitely
probably would vote for Bush. Today, I'm ready to listen to both of
them. I have to give Gore credit for his choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Abitan said his new open-mindedness was due to Lieberman's
integrity, and had nothing to do with the fact that the senator is
Jewish. ``I think it would be very wrong for Jews to vote for
Lieberman just because he's Jewish,'' Abitan said.
</P>
<P>
   But some local political organizers said Lieberman's faith alone
is shifting people's positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``His selection has energized people both ways,'' says Barbara
Miller, active in in the Fort Lauderdale area. ``Those who are
afraid and those who are attracted. A lot of Jewish people are
afraid to have a Jew spotlighted because there has been the belief
that that has brought some repercussions.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Miller said, her own son, who usually eschews politics,
said he was going to become involved in Gore's campaign after his
selection of Lieberman. Others are less optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Rosalie Phillips, a Sunrise Lakes retiree with a ready supply of
Jewish mother jokes was torn Tuesday. She is Jewish, and was proud
that Lieberman had been chosen, but worried that he wouldn't help
Gore in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a staunch democrat,'' she said. ``But I'm hoping this
won't be a detriment to us. It will make religion a big issue.''
</P>
<P>
   It pained her, but Phillips conceded that she would have
preferred the Vice President choose a sure winner than a Jewish
running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and his campaign have clearly decided Lieberman is both.
</P>
<P>
   And so has Edie Booke, the fast-talking lifeguard at Sunrise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, he's the greatest!'' she yelled when she realized who
everybody was talking about. ``The best thing. And I'm not talking
religion. If you looked at the other five guys Gore looked at,
(Lieberman) was so clean!''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Maltz, a man who gave his age as ``two years younger than
God,'' also downplayed talk of religion in talking of the
Lieberman's religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the American people are way beyond that now,'' he
said. ``You got these fringe people, but the majority of American
people won't care that he's Jewish. They'll go for his integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts said the majority of American people won't care
about Lieberman, period. They say a vice presidential nominee has
little effect on people's decisions in November, particularly after
the initial flurry over their selection dies down.
</P>
<P>
   ``When push comes to shove, the nominee's choice of Vice
President says more about presidential candidate,'' said Kane, the
pollster. ``It's the first real decision voters get to see the
person make. It's not who he picks so much as person he picks is
somebody he respects and trusts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
