<SLUG> BC-IPOS-RETURN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IPO MARKET HOT AGAIN AFTER TECH MELTDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The IPO market has sprung back to record territory, after
slowing to a near halt when technology stocks plunged in April.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, networking, telecom, and Web infrastructure
companies are leading the charge, not e-commerce companies, and
biotech companies are making their biggest showing ever.
</P>
<P>
   So far in August, 33 companies nationwide have sold shares to
the public for the first time, and another 39 are lined up to be
priced in the coming week, according to Thomson Financial
Securities Data. If this pace keeps up, it will easily outrun the
65 IPOs completed in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IPO market is clearly in an upswing,'' said George
Nichols, IPO analyst for Morningstar Inc. in Chicago. ``We're
finally seeing quality names coming out.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the stream of software, Web, and telecommunications
companies heading for the public markets, the summer surprise is
biotech and pharmaceutical IPOs _ likely fueled by the acute
interest in the recent decoding of the human genome. Suddenly,
biotech, which enjoys sporadic interest among venture capitalists
and other investors, is hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biotech is the latest issue to be in vogue,'' said Richard
Peterson, IPO expert at Thomson Financial Securities Data in Newark
</P>
<P>
   According to his research, the nation has seen 35 biotech deals
so far this year, raising a record $3.3 billion. In 1999, 11 IPOs
in the sector raised $2.5 billion, he said. The largest number of
biotech deals completed was 51 in 1996; Peterson predicts a new
record by year-end.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, drug research and life sciences companies that have
gone public since late June, such as Cambridge's Variagenics Inc.,
Wilmington-based Charles River Laboratories, and Billerica-based
Bruker Daltonics Inc., have seen their shares jump close to 100
percent.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question that, across all industries, the most
popular IPOs are seeing huge, first-day pops in their prices,
sometimes into the triple digits. But these aren't the
consumer-oriented Web stocks that stoked the euphoria of the first
quarter. The big winners lately are networking, telecom, and Web
infrastructure companies.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the five biggest-returning IPOs nationally since May are
headquartered in Massachusetts. Leading the pack is Sonus Networks
Inc., a Westford telecom infrastructure player, whose stock has
soared 1,035 percent since May 25.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of StorageNetworks Inc., a Waltham data storage company,
have jumped 385 percent since June 30, while Boston-based
Speechworks International has seen its shares fly 392 percent since
Aug. 1. And Avici Systems Inc., a North Billerica maker of
high-speed data networking equipment, went public July 28 and its
shares have gained 305 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For high-tech entrepreneurs and the venture capitalists who
finance them, the stellar gains follow a brief period of gloom. The
Nasdaq composite index lost one-quarter of its value in a brisk
week in April, and its recovery has been modest and slow. While
investors appear to have regained confidence in technology stocks,
many have come back with higher standards than they had before the
plunge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IPO market functions on a binge-and-purge basis,''
Morningstar's Nichols said. ``I don't think this market can support
quantity _ just quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Small investors often are missing the fast, early gains in the
hot stocks, Thomson's Peterson said. He pointed out that, of 70
IPOs this year that doubled in the first day, more than 50 are now
trading below their first-day closing price.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're the typical, average investor, more likely than not
you've lost money,'' Peterson said. ``It's a very difficult market
to be successful in.''
</P>
<P>
   As many as 100 companies delayed or canceled stock offerings in
April and May, analysts said, and the stronger of those companies
are now coming back for second tries.
</P>
<P>
   Companies expected to complete IPOs this week include Radview
Software Ltd. of Burlington; Intrinsix Corp., a Westborough
semiconductor maker; and Medicines Co., a Cambridge pharmaceutical
company. McData Corp., a Colorado company spun off from Hopkinton
storage giant EMC Corp., is also slated to sell shares to the
public for the first time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
