<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWSUITS AND SENATORS' BILL SEEK BENEFITS FOR PERMATEMPS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes contingent labor text table.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even in good times, there is a lot to be said for a steady job
with paid vacation, sick time, health benefits, a pension, and a
paycheck as regular as a time clock.
</P>
<P>
   These thoughts had settled deep in Moira Casey's mind the day
she threw up her hands two years ago and decided to do more than
just talk about equity.
</P>
<P>
   Casey became the lead plaintiff in a class-action lawsuit
challenging the use of permatemps by the Atlantic Ritchfield Co.
(Arco), now BP Amoco.
</P>
<P>
   Permatemp is a 1990s expression, a byproduct of the new economy.
It refers to people who work the same hours and have the same jobs
as full-time employees but are classified as part-timers, even
though they have been with the company for years. Others are leased
out by contract firms.
</P>
<P>
   Most are ineligible for benefits, such as medical, dental,
retirement, paid vacation, and stock options. That's why some
employers rely on them: Permatemps can help trim the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   In April, a federal judge in Los Angeles dismissed the lawsuit
brought by Casey and a dozen others who contended that Arco had
illegally classified them as temps to avoid paying retirement
benefits. The judge ruled, as Arco had argued, that the workers
were considered leased employees and, as such, had no legal right
to company-paid pensions.
</P>
<P>
   Now, nearly four months after the ruling, US Senators Edward M.
Kennedy, Democrat of Massachusetts, and Robert Torricelli, Democrat
of New Jersey, have proposed a bill that would amend the Employment
Retirement Income Security Act, known as ERISA, to prohibit the
misclassification of full-time workers as leased, temporary,
part-time, contingent, or contract workers.
</P>
<P>
   Called the Employee Benefit Eligibility Fairness Act of 2000,
the bill requires employers to use objective criteria, based on the
actual terms and conditions of employment, to determine whether
contingent workers are eligible for benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recent court cases demonstrate the need to clarify ERISA to
make certain employers do not miscategorize employees as
independent contractors or temporary workers for the purpose of
excluding them from employee benefit plans,'' the senators said in
a joint statement.
</P>
<P>
   Casey's lawsuit was not the first. Two years ago, temps and
independent contractors at Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric in California won
a similar lawsuit when a judge ruled they were common-law
employees.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the US Department of Labor sued Time Warner Inc.,
alleging that the company had denied pensions and health benefits
to some full-time journalists by misclassifying them as temps or
independent contractors.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a lawsuit against Microsoft Corp., which for nearly a
decade has waged a legal battle over the classification of
independent contractors, has been decided in favor of the
plaintiffs. Those workers, many of them technical staff who had
been with the company for years, had sought benefits such as stock
options, which were routinely offered to permanent employees.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the matter likely will gain more public attention,
because the number of contingent employees entering the work force
is increasing, and many are working at the same job longer than a
few weeks or months. The result is the permatemp, a new species of
the part-time or temporary worker whose appearance at the office is
now as regular as that of the veteran full-time employee.
</P>
<P>
   In a June 30 report, the General Accounting Office reported that
up to 30 percent of the US work force, about 39 million Americans,
are contingent workers, a category that also includes short-term
temps and highly paid contractors who negotiate their own hours and
wages.
</P>
<P>
   Not all employers are looking to cut corners. Many use
contingent workers on a short-term basis to accommodate workload
fluctuations, fill in temporary absences, screen applicants for
permanent jobs, and help permanent workers gain more flexibility,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, some employers are relying on permatemps to
help avoid paying benefits, reduce compensation costs, prevent
unionizing, or mask layoffs, the GAO said. These situations have
led to a flurry of lawsuits by contingent workers seeking full
employment or benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Companies have responded by scrambling to adopt protective
measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Management lawyers are now telling their clients that they
should develop waiver agreements that state that the employee, or
the independent contractor, will waive his or her right to any
benefits,'' said David Stobaugh, a Seattle attorney who has
represented several permatemps, including Casey. ``These are
bilateral agreements, and the goal is to absolve the employer from
knowingly and intentionally misclassifying employees.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedy-Torricelli bill, which will likely face tough going
in a mostly Republican Congress, would disqualify such waivers.
</P>
<P>
   The senators contend that really independent contractors do not
need waivers, because their work automatically defines the terms of
their employment. The true independent contractor, they say,
controls how and where he or she works, including whether to do the
actual job or hire a subcontractor. By contrast, the employer
controls the hours, work, and even the ideas of the permanent,
full-time employee.
</P>
<P>
   Before she filed suit, Casey had been a permatemp at an
Alaska-based division of Arco in the Bering Sea for nearly 10
years. The 43-year-old Vancouver woman says she held three
different jobs at the company and each lasted about three years.
</P>
<P>
   The company's lawyer, Paul Ondrasik of Washington, could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, I was making $12 per hour,'' Casey said.
``But the last job I had as an environmental technician paid $20 an
hour. We would get some benfits, but they were not what the Arco
employees got, by a long stretch. I'd be in a job, and then Arco
would change contract companies, and then I would have to start my
benefits over again, and there would be a waiting period of up to
one year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was frustrating to have been there so long and to be
treated so differently from the full-time people,'' she continued.
``We were referred to as subemployees, which meant less than
regular employees, but we did the same work. If there was a
position open within Arco, regular Arco employees could apply, but
we couldn't. When we got laid off, we got nothing, nothing at all.
But when Arco people got laid off, they got (severance) packages.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Casey has a full-time job in British Columbia as an
executive secretary. ``I have to say that I would never do that
type of work again,'' she said of her previous employment. ``But at
43 I really care about benefits. At 20, I didn't care. Now, I am in
a panic. I'm thinking about retirement and the fact that I have
zero, but I'm not going to win the lottery.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Diane E. Lewis is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached
at 617-929-2069, by e-mail at dlewis(at)globe.com, or by mail at
The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
CONTINGENT LABOR &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A June 30 report by the General Accounting Office on contingent
work in the United States found:
</P>
<P>
   _Since 1982 the number of temporary help jobs has grown 577
percent.
</P>
<P>
   _Up to 30 percent of the US work force, or 39 million people,
now hold contingent jobs.
</P>
<P>
   _21 percent are included in employer-sponsored pension or
retirement plans. By contrast, 64 percent of all full-time workers
are part of a company-backed pension.
</P>
<P>
   _Most contingent workers are employed in the service industry.
</P>
<P>
   _Most agency temps, on-call workers, and day laborers would
prefer a permanent, full-time job. One reason: Some 30 percent of
all agency temps earn below $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   _Most independent contractors, self-employed contingents, and
standard part-time workers prefer the flexibility of such work.
These workers, unlike agency temps, are more likely to be employed
in professional services such as nurses, engineers, computer
professionals or accountants.
</P>
</TEXT>
