<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BOMBING-0810-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIA'S PUTIN VOWS TO 'WIPE OUT' TERRORISTS AFTER DEADLY
BOMBING
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russian President Vladimir Putin tried to calm rising
tensions here Wednesday about the possibility of more terrorist
acts in Russia's capital, while authorities searched for those
responsible for the blast that killed at least seven people and
wounded 100 others.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Security Service, Russia's primary intelligence
agency, reaffirmed that it was treating Tuesday's deadly bombing as
a terrorist act and said it did not rule out as suspects the
guerrillas fighting against Russian forces in the breakaway
republic of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Chechen President Aslan Maskhadov and other rebel leaders have
denied that they were responsible for the blast that rocked
downtown Moscow's busiest intersection, Pushkin Square.
</P>
<P>
   Putin vowed in a nationally televised address that the bombers
would be caught and the government would successfully wipe out
``terrorists'' _ a word the Kremlin has used to describe Chechens
throughout the 11-month war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Humankind has not developed any other effective way of
combatting terror, except one. And this is the only remedy, a
response in kind. We should carry through what we are doing in the
North Caucasus and finish off the terrorists in their lair,'' Putin
said, referring to the region where Chechnya is located.
</P>
<P>
   Security officials, under pressure to make a breakthrough after
Putin said he was taking personal responsibility for the case, said
they arrested two men in their 20s, one of whom they described as
an ethnic Chechen. Authorities said the two matched descriptions
given by survivors of the blast of men who were last seen at the
site of the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's attack comes nearly one year after blasts destroyed
three multi-story apartment buildings in Moscow, killing more than
300 people. Those explosions were blamed on Chechens, and led to a
renewed military campaign in the southern province. No one has been
charged in connection with those bombings.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech Wednesday, Putin urged Russians not to seek
retribution against ethnic minorities for the latest attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be wrong to look for any ethnic connection, to look
for Chechen or any other ethnic connection. In general, it is not
really right when we put a label on a whole people because
criminals, above all terrorists, have neither nationality nor
religion,'' said Putin, who has been criticized by international
human rights organizations for the Russian army's treatment of
Chechen civilians in the war.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the mood in Moscow was visibly ugly. Those paying their
condolences at the bomb site Wednesday said they had no doubt about
who was behind the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only good Chechen is a dead Chechen,'' said Alexei
Medvedev, a 24-year-old student. ``They won't get away with this.''
</P>
<P>
   There were conflicting reports Wednesday on the casualty toll.
Interior Minister Vladimir Rushaillo said the death toll was seven,
with 93 people receiving medical treatment. But city authorities
said an eighth person died overnight from wounds received in the
blast. They also put the number of wounded at 103.
</P>
<P>
   Experts said the explosive device, which was probably left near
a theater ticket kiosk in the passageway beneath Pushkin Square _ a
busy intersection equivalent to New York's Times Square. The bomb
was between 1 pound and 3.3 pounds, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite extensive damage, police on Wednesday morning reopened
the tunnels, which link three subway lines and two major streets,
after an initial clean-up operation. The entrances and walkways
were dotted with flowers left by mourners.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in Moscow, police stepped up security after
authorities found a suitcase containing nine pounds of dynamite at
a lost luggage office at the city's Kazansky railway station on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   (Margaret Coker's E-mail address is: megc(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.kolumbus.fi/kavkaz/english/index.html
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
