<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6728 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-BOWDOIN-POSSE-ART-BOS     08-09 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOWDOIN-POSSE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 POOR, MINORITIES IN POSSE BRIDGING THE CAMPUS GAP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICK HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are a gang of 10 _ all hardened youths from Boston _ being
sent onto the campus of elite Bowdoin College to start a
revolution.
</P>
<P>
   In a radical social experiment, Bowdoin has dropped its usual
admissions process and given full scholarships to a tight-knit
group of 10 underprivileged seniors, on the hope that they will
upend the school's atmosphere of advantage. Amid the age-old crew
team and debate team, these freshmen will try to gain a toehold
amid the evergreens.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many kinds of revolutions,'' said Eider Gordillo, a
Colombian immigrant who once dropped out of high school and is now
headed to Bowdoin. ``I'm hoping we'll be able to bring a small
social revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordillo is among the 10 who are the first in the region to join
Posse, a privately funded non-profit that brokers admission and
financial aid from college partners like Bowdoin. In return, these
schools get minority students who show academic promise but who
might not have applied on their own.
</P>
<P>
   But the Posse strategy is a response to a growing recognition of
how alienating the poor and minorities can find exclusive schools
like Bowdoin _ and how far schools may have to go to change that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you want to end up catering to a very small cross
section of the country,'' said Richard Steele, Bowdoin's dean of
admissions, ``you better find ways to bridge differences, and do it
in a hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   Posse began 11 years ago in New York, but Boston is now home to
the first branch office. Posse Boston, which recruits local youths,
receives money from the US Department of Education and a scattering
of private donors and foundations. Bowdoin is paying the tuition,
about $25,000 per student annually.
</P>
<P>
   What awaits Boston's first posse, no one can really say. A
number of teams sent from New York have done well, with about nine
out of 10 students graduating. But others have floundered so badly
that two schools dropped out of Posse.
</P>
<P>
   As Gordillo keeps an eye on his 7-year-old sister, Tita, darting
around the small rooms of the Posse Boston office, he worries aloud
about being overwhelmed, frustrated, terrified. He had never seen a
rural college like Bowdoin before. While he thinks the posse will
add new voices and accents to clubs and classrooms, his firmest
hope is that the team offers safe havens in the dorms and dining
halls for one another, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'll rely on them at Bowdoin because it's a difficult
experience, defining yourself and finding what you can do in
school,'' said Gordillo, a 19-year-old with tightly wound black
hair, wearing a muscle T-shirt. ``We're leaving a lot of people
behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Ambitious, tough-talking, spirited, these 10 are also still very
much teenagers. They have become like sisters and brothers during a
32-week crash course on how to make it in college. An easy
familiarity passes among the six girls, especially, as they diss
over who is the ``queen'' of the posse. (There are no kings,
apparently.)
</P>
<P>
   After each meeting, the group locks hands and swirls around a
lone member, until they have formed a ``cinnamon roll.'' Bound
together, holding close.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a city girl, so I'm kind of scared,'' said Lauren Flinn,
one of two white students in the posse, and a graduate of Boston
Latin Academy. ``People don't expect kids from the city to survive
in college.''
</P>
<P>
   With the stakes high, Posse chooses carefully.
</P>
<P>
   For the ten spots, guidance counselors and community groups
nominated about 210 city youths with leadership and academic
talents, and who came from diverse or disadvantaged backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Posse staff pared the list to 27 for a team of Bowdoin
officials who came to Boston to help make the final cut.
</P>
<P>
   They sized up the finalists in interviews and a series of games.
One icebreaker was a ``human scavenger hunt'': the students and
administrators who played won points by showing off talents _
fluency in two languages, a few dance moves, the delivery of a poem
commited to memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Bowdoin, they saw the students as very real,'' said Shani
Jackson, one of the leaders of Posse Boston.
</P>
<P>
   At Brandeis University, which has taken 30 New York City
students, the posses have started a gospel choir and a ``dialogue
group'' for talking about identity and race. Most importantly, to
some at Brandeis, is that members take risks _ speaking plainly
about identity in class, or breaking racial clusters in the
cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Posse student had a birthday, and other students in the
posse had a party in the dining hall _ and it was the most diverse
table Brandeis had ever seen,'' said Mimi Arnstein, a Posse
coordinator there, with a bit of wonder in her voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``For them to be together publicly, in an intergrated group,
starts to make change,'' Arnstein added.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston group includes black, Hispanic, and white students,
many of them from poor or immigrant families. Next year, Posse
hopes to send another 10 to Bowdoin, as well as 10 to Hamilton
College, in New York, and to Bryn Mawr College, a women's school in
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Bowdoin's Steele could not say if the incoming 10 would have
been admitted under traditional standards. And he worries that
their writing abilities might not measure up to their future
classmates. But the Posse concept is more promising, he said, than
the typical, imperfect admissions strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've found ways to identify potential that we hadn't fully
exploited,'' Steele said. ``Posse has convincingly argued that
students' ability to relate well to peers, and endure through
difficulty, has a lot to do with success in college.''
</P>
<P>
   The Posse approach has drawn national attention for its
potential to narrow the gap between rich and poor in college. About
82 percent of high income seniors go on to college directly from
high school, compared to only 57 percent of lower-income seniors,
according to the US Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   ``This idea of a team is a really interesting approach,'' said
Maureen McLaughlin, deputy assistant secretary of education. ``We
all know the climate and support for a student on campus is really
important.''
</P>
<P>
   But at Rice and Lehigh universities, the Posse teams did not
meet expectations, leading the schools to drop out.
</P>
<P>
   At Rice, a one of the nation's top engineering schools, the
curriculum was overwhelming, and the random dormitory assignments _
used by many colleges _ cut into the esprit de corps. Some felt
isolated on the 300-acre Houston campus, Rice officials said. Only
one of the 18 members graduated in four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were taxed so much by their academics, they were less
able than initially planned to get involved,'' said Julie Browning,
Rice's dean of undergraduate enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   But Posse officials said they have since sharpened both the
selection process and the preparation for college.
</P>
<P>
   During a Posse training session last week, a Brandeis professor,
Jane Hale, led a mock college class to give students a flavor of
the work ahead. She urged them to buy computers and hefty
dictionaries (``You're working with big words now''), and said that
studying 30 hours a week was the average _ and would get them only
average grades. (``If you want As, do more.'')
</P>
<P>
   When it came to classes, the students seemed more worried about
pleasing professors and wearing the right clothes than fomenting
debates about diversity. But each was also confident that they
could make a difference at Bowdoin.
</P>
<P>
   Gordillo, sounding more like a realist than a revolutionary,
laughed, ``We're going to bring some chocolate chips to the
cookie.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
