<HEADER>
A6732 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-09 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALEC GUINNESS'S GENIUS ENLIVENED MANY A MOVIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With a shy smile, he called his most famous role ``my little
annuity.'' Before signing on as the only star in ``Star Wars,''
Alec Guinness got what most actors dream of: a percentage of the
gross.
</P>
<P>
   His ethereal and indestructible Jedi knight, Obi-Wan Kenobi, won
him millions of fans in 1977. A smaller number of moviegoers
already knew _ from Gulley Jimson to George Smiley, from ``Great
Expectations'' to ``Little Dorrit'' _ that Alec Guinness was a
genius.
</P>
<P>
   I once heard him read poetry as his small, even baritone
breathed life into ``Lepanto'' by G. K. Chesterton:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Strong gongs groaning as the guns boom far,
</P>
<P>
   Don John of Austria is going to the war.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No actor enlivened as many cult films _ movies repeated and
remembered, once at repertory art cinemas and now at home. ``Kind
Hearts and Coronets'' and ``Lavender Hill Mob'' are still
hilarious. A drama that oft inhabits my VCR is ``Tunes of Glory,''
filmed in 1960. It is quintessential Alec Guinness because he plays
against type.
</P>
<P>
   Having won an Oscar in 1957 for ``Bridge on the River Kwai'' as
the stiff-necked Colonel Nicholson, he was a natural for the
stiff-necked colonel who takes over a Scottish training battalion
from the acting commander, a raffish cut-up, the specialty of
Guinness's old friend, John Mills.
</P>
<P>
   ``The script was turned down by every major company,'' Mills
recalled in his memoirs. He and Guinness agreed to star and to
switch. ``We would do some `offbeat' casting,'' Mills wrote. ``I
would play the neurotic, nerve-wracked Colonel Barrow, and Alec
would play the hard-drinking tough Scots colonel up from the
ranks.''
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, how could the movie miss? A strong supporting
cast included Dennis Price, Gordon Jackson, Duncan Macrae, Kay
Walsh, and, in her debut, a luminous Susannah York. The screenplay,
by a young British novelist, James Kennaway, was a business manual
on tradition, transition, and decision-making based on ``Macbeth.''
</P>
<P>
   Guinness, in red mustache and crewcut, sparkles. In the
officers' mess on the eve of the new colonel's arrival, his
character, Jock Sinclair, declares: ``Corporal, whiskey for the
gentleman that like it. And for the gentlemen that don't like it,
whiskey!''
</P>
<P>
   As Guinness plans a big funeral, a major, played by Dennis
Price, interrupts. ``Quite an elaborate do, this,'' he says.
``Brigade will never permit it.'' Guinness retorts with an anthem
for obituary writers everywhere: ``To hell with brigade! The way we
bury our colonels is ours and ours alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Movies were not the first, or even second, love of Alec
Guinness. He preferred the theater, with its gossip and
conviviality, and the lonelier art of writing. He cherished an
Oscar nomination for his screenplay based on Joyce Cary's novel
``The Horse's Mouth'' in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   On location in Ceylon for ``River Kwai,'' he and Jack Hawkins
learned that William Holden got no set fee but a piece of the
profits. When George Lucas recruited him for ``Star Wars,''
Guinness remembered.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1999 memoir, ``A Positively Final Appearance,'' Guinness
voiced regrets about his ``little annuity.'' ``I shrivel inside
each time it is mentioned,'' he wrote. ``When it was first shown,
it had a freshness, also a sense of moral good and fun. But it has
led to a worldwide taste for a fantasy world of secondhand,
childish banalities.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Guinness character plans bagpipe funeral marches in the
Scottish highlands, he gets flustered, naming ``The Black Bear''
and ``Scotland the Brave,'' then demanding of Duncan Macrae:
</P>
<P>
   ``Some others, Pipe Major.''
</P>
<P>
   `` `Cock of the North,' sir.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yon's a cheesy tune. You'll no play that!''
</P>
<P>
   Let no cheesy tunes echo at the funeral of the great artist Alec
Guinness. As Jock Sinclair promised his officers, ``We'll have all
the tunes of glory, to remember the more clearly.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Martin F. Nolan's column appears regularly in the Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
