<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RABBI'S BOOK EXTOLS THE HEALING POWER OF THE PSALMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Samuel Chiel speaks of the healing power of psalms, he
speaks from personal experience.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, when he suffered his first mild heart attack, he began
to fear for his future.
</P>
<P>
   He found himself turning for strength to Psalm 30, which
includes the verse ``weeping may linger for the night, but joy
comes in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Chiel survived that heart attack, an eventual bypass operation,
and now he recites that psalm daily. And, at the age of 73, the
Newton, Mass. rabbi has written a new book about the healing power
of psalms, called ``For Thou Art With Me.''
</P>
<P>
   The book, co-authored by Chiel's nephew, health writer Henry
Dreher, is meant as a kind of solace for those in crisis. In the
book, Chiel walks readers through 15 of the 150 psalms, offering
anecdotes and commentary to flesh out their meaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are great religious poets who deal with virtually every
human emotion _ despair, joy, exaltation, sadness, betrayal _
virtually all the human emotions that each one of us experiences,
and they connect those emotions and human aspirations to God,''
Chiel said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The psalms are part of the third section of the Hebrew Bible.
They have traditionally been attributed to King David, but most
scholars believe that although David may have authored some of the
poems, there are also numerous other poets who contributed over
several centuries nearly 3,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The psalms are a basic part of Jewish ritual liturgy, but in
recent centuries they have arguably been even more popular among
Christians, some of whom read them daily or include them in
liturgical prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The psalms are universally loved by Jews and Christians and
others who may not be of these faiths but who love the psalms as
literature,'' Chiel said.
</P>
<P>
   Judaism in the late 19th and early 20th centuries shifted away
from the raw spirituality associated with the psalms, but began to
move back late in the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many Jews, Christians, and people who may not be part of
either faith are looking for some deeper understanding of what the
meaning of life ought to be,'' Chiel said. ``There's much more talk
by rabbis about God now. There's a renewal of interest in God and
spirituality and in finding that meaning in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Chiel is best known for his 27 years as the rabbi of Temple
Emanuel in Newton, the largest conservative congregation in New
England. Retired since 1995, he is now a scholar-in-residence at
Combined Jewish Philanthropies of Greater Boston and an adviser to
the president of Hebrew College.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, Chiel offers numerous examples of how the psalms
have affected his life, those of some of his congregants, and
famous people such as Bill Clinton, Oprah Winfrey and Natan
Sharansky, the Soviet dissident turned Israeli politician.
</P>
<P>
   He says his book, which he calls a ``handbook for the soul,'' is
aimed at individuals in crisis, many of whom, he says, have asked
him for something to read to give them hope or strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``With their lyrical expressions of faith, their powerful
imagery, and their uninhibited evocation of passionated feeling,
the psalms speak to people in every imaginable crisis,'' Chiel
writes.
</P>
<P>
   But he cautions that the psalms should not be seen as a source
of a miraculous cure, but rather of spiritual healing.
</P>
<P>
   ``God does not respond to our prayers the way a first-class
mail-order company faithfully delivers its products,'' he writes.
``Being heard by God, though, cures our spiritual isolation. That
is itself a profound form of healing beyond biological recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   He calls the psalms ``millennial sources of comfort,''
contrasting them with much of the grief literature now available.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many trees have been sacrificed for self-help books that
spin out the same theme with less eloquence and economy?'' he asks.
``There is something uniquely stirring about reciting these
timeless words, knowing that we are connected to generations who
have turned to these same verses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
