<HEADER>
A6736 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-BAT-PROJECT0810-COX     08-09 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAT-PROJECT0810-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Colorado bat program aimed at protecting, promoting the flying
mammals
 &HT;    By Rachel Sauer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. - When San Luis Valley residents wake up
each morning, there are 2 tons fewer bugs outside than there were
the night before.
</P>
<P>
   Tons of bugs disappear each night, especially in summer, not
that the farmers mind. They're glad, and so is everyone else. And
the fact that they have bats to thank for the insect eradication
doesn't seem to bother anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Bats, it turns out, aren't the bloodthirsty villains often
portrayed in books and movies. They're vital to many Colorado
ecosystems and, in the case of the San Luis Valley, vital to the
economy because of crops saved from insects. And bats are being
unintentionally exterminated.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the United States, destruction of bat habitat is
driving them into abandoned mines. In the past 20 years, mines have
been closed to ensure public safety, but with little thought to the
bats possibly living inside.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the North American Bats and Mines Project, a
national initiative to seal abandoned mines with bat-friendly
gates, has been gaining momentum. Since the 1990s, said project
director Sheryl Ducommon, hundreds of mines in the United States
and Canada have been sealed with bat gates that make it easy for
bats to get in and out of the mine, but still prevent people from
entering.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who are closing mines are not intentionally trying
to rid the earth of bats,'' she said. ``They're trying to ensure
the safety of the general public. But as an unfortunate consequence
they've closed mines when bats are hibernating in winter or in
summer when they're in the mines with their babies.''
</P>
<P>
   She said 10 percent to 15 percent of abandoned mines are
critical for bat use and 60 percent to 70 percent show evidence of
bat use. Considering Colorado's 50,000 abandoned mines, that may
mean a lot of bats affected by mine closures.
</P>
<P>
   In the San Luis Valley, a colony of about 250,000 Mexican
free-tailed bats roosts in the old Orient Mine. They're the ones
that eat the 2 tons of bugs each night and help preserve the area's
rich agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   At a bat conservation and mine closure workshop July 19 and 20
in Grand Junction, Kirk Navo of the Colorado Division of Wildlife
said biologists, bat conservationists and mine owners have been
through almost 3,000 of Colorado's mines and found bats or evidence
of bats in many of them.
</P>
<P>
   In western Colorado the most common bats are Townsend's
big-eared bats, little and big brown bats, fringed myotis, pallid
bats, Yuma myotis and long-legged myotis. As many as 14 of
Colorado's 18 bat species rely on abandoned mines for survival.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the bats seen in Colorado are migratory and seasonal
residents, or are tree and boulder roosting. But because of
increased wilderness use and environmental destruction, bats are
being driven into mines. Bat-friendly mine gates ensure that date
bats.
</P>
<P>
   In the western United States, one of the most sensitive species
is the Townsend's big-eared bat, which is dependent on abandoned
mine habitat, Ducommon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gated hundreds and hundreds of mines for Townsend's
big-eared bat,'' she said. ``We'll potentially keep the species
from being threatened or endangered, and if we can keep them off
the federal threatened or endangered species list, there are so
many more management options.''
</P>
<P>
   Navo said the fringed myotis is a concern because they have been
found in several old uranium mines in western Colorado, and uranium
mines are being closed quickly and frequently.
</P>
<P>
   Ducommon said the project also offers public education to help
dispel myths about bats and make people care that they're being
closed in mines. Often when biologists are in an area surveying
mines for bats, they speak at schools and in community meetings to
discuss rabies concerns, bats' economic and environmental impact
and how they're not birds or reptiles, but mammals. The goal,
Ducommon said, is to make the public aware of bats so mine owners
will have biologists survey a mine before sealing it with the wrong
kind of gate or with a mound of dirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very strange creature for some people,'' Ducommon said.
``People don't understand bats all that much sometimes. But once
they find out how fascinating they are, how beneficial to the
economy, they have an interest.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information about the bat conservation and mine
closure, call the North American Bats and Mines Project,
(512)327-9721.
</P>
<P>
   Email: Rachel Sauer can be reached at rsauer(at)gjds.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
