<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAURABUSH-SUITS0810 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dallas designer Faircloth suits Laura Bush to a T
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - People expect a first lady, whether of
Texas or of the United States, to have a certain look _ feminine,
professional and conservative, regardless of her political
leanings.
</P>
<P>
   Should she monkey with that formula even a tad, they'll let her
know.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas designer Michael Faircloth creates the outfits that Laura
Bush wears for public appearances, including the half-dozen suits
she packed for last week's Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   When he stitched a lace panel _ a very fashion-forward detail _
into the hem of one of her campaign-trail skirts, the citizens
quickly cast their votes. ``We got numerous comments that her slip
was showing,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Future lace panels were vetoed, but Faircloth hasn't ruled out
runway influences entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly make gentle nods toward fashion trends, keeping
in mind what works best for her figure,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He finds inspiration in trendy trims, colors and textures, but
``the vast majority of what's in fashion right now, the first lady
would not be wearing.''
</P>
<P>
   This is what Mrs. Bush does wear:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sculpted suits worn without blouses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Bush is very practical. Too many layers gets too
confusing,'' Faircloth says.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, it's easier for Faircloth to achieve a slim, clean-lined
look without throwing a blouse into the mix.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Feminine shapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to design for a feminine figure, and Mrs. Bush
certainly has a nice, feminine figure,'' he says. To emphasize her
gentle curves, Faircloth fits her suits close to her body and keeps
her skirts slim.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't go by specific sizes, but she's close to an 8,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Shorter jackets.
</P>
<P>
   Because she's not wearing a blouse, the jackets stay permanently
buttoned. That means Mrs. Bush can't undo a button when sitting
down, so a shorter jacket makes sitting easier.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Slim skirts, bright, clear colors.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bush has bright blue eyes, so blues and greens are
especially pretty on her. Although she favors neutral tones,
Faircloth says, those don't read as well on television.
</P>
<P>
   All told, it's a uniform that Mrs. Bush, a casual dresser in her
personal life, has grown into over the last several years.
``Through her public appearances, we've adopted this look that's
easy for her to maintain and to look sharp and also is very
functional,'' Faircloth says.
</P>
<P>
   Faircloth, 40, met Mrs. Bush through mutual friends seven years
ago when husband George W. first ran for governor of Texas. When he
isn't designing for her or buzzing around Dallas helping her pick
out accessories, Faircloth creates looks for Big D socialites as
well as a worldwide clientele that drops by the Lily Dodson
boutique where he works as the full-time in-house designer.
</P>
<P>
   Lily Dodson is the only place to buy the Faircloth label, which
sports prices similar to those by his New York counterparts, he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Is Faircloth, a native Texan, ready to relocate to Washington,
D.C.?
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't given that any consideration yet,'' he says.
``There's always airlines.''
</P>
<P>
   Email: stacisturrock(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
