<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MONEYMEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GRIM LOOK AT MONEY'S STRANGLEHOLD ON POLITICIANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT L. TURNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE MONEY MEN 
The Real Story of Fund-raising's Influence on Political Power in
America 
By Jeffrey H. Birnbaum 
Crown, 288 pp., $25.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Democratic Party officials were planning to celebrate the
bicentennial of the party's founding (ostensibly by Thomas
Jefferson, in 1792), they sought to rally all the party faithful.
So they went to the computer files of the Democratic National
Committee, seeking the names and addresses of the thousands of
party regulars, the ward and town committee members, the precinct
workers and poll watchers, who they assumed were the backbone of
the party.
</P>
<P>
   What they found was a list of donors. Period. The money men were
in. The street workers were out. William B. Greider, who recounted
this story eight years ago, concluded, ``In the age of television,
big money and high-tech candidacies, the `regulars' of party
politics have been rendered irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder that voter participation is dismal and getting
worse? Politicians, in catering to their big donors, often show
little regard to taxpayers, consumers, environmental consequences,
or the public interest in general. If voters object, that can be
overcome with a well-targeted _ and well-financed _ ad campaign.
But the voters are not fools. They question why, if their voices
are not going to be heard, they should speak at all.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran journalist Jeffrey H. Birnbaum, currently the Washington
bureau chief for Fortune magazine, is the premier chronicler of
money in American politics. His new book, ``The Money Men,''
describes a blur of political fund-raising that has gone beyond
frenzied competition to become an addiction.
</P>
<P>
   How ridiculous can it get? Birnbaum relates that Republican
elders, responding in 1998 to the plaints of the overly dunned,
established the season pass: for a mere $250,000, givers could buy
plenty of access _ and a guarantee that they wouldn't be solicited
again. ``Unfortunately, money demands being what they are,''
Birnbaum writes, ``the season pass didn't last the whole election
season. The Republican Party broke its promise and went back to
these big givers for more anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Birnbaum's lively account is bipartisan. President Clinton's
frenzied fund-raising in 1996, and the use of White House visits
and other perks as incentives to give, he says, show that ``the
president . . . was without scruples.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the few reforms that are enacted sometimes produce
consequences that are not only unintended, but perverse. Gift
restrictions Congress has voted on itself mean that lobbyists
cannot pick up the tab for lavish meals the way they used to, but
there are no such restrictions on fund-raisers. The result,
Birnbaum points out, has been a proliferation of intimate
fund-raising dinners.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Money Men'' is thin on fresh reporting of venality. The
few examples of legislation being written or altered specifically
to benefit a contributor are mostly old stories attributed to other
reporters. Birnbaum does provide vivid accounts of one subset of
the problem: ``the shakedown,'' in which lawmakers delay action on
legislation until they wring enough contributions out of interested
parties.
</P>
<P>
   Birnbaum speaks strongly against the abuses in the current
system, saying soft money ``and its many allied forms of legal
cheating have rendered the entire effort to control and regulate
campaign fund-raising a farce.'' But the remedies he offers are
weak _ limits on lobbyist contributions during sessions, free air
time for candidates, and restrictions on attack ads.
</P>
<P>
   With a shrug, Birnbaum says more fundamental reforms run up
against the valid free-speech rights of the heavy contributors, and
also against societal realities: ``Inequities in the
campaign-finance system reflect the far larger and far more
intractable inequities in society as a whole and can't be
legislated away.''
</P>
<P>
   This view explains the book's major disappointment. In a
democracy, politics is not supposed to reflect inequalities _ it's
supposed to correct them. The electoral system, with its
one-man-one-vote principle, is the great hope of individuals at all
levels to have an equal voice in their government. When big money
washes that hope away, many voters will stay discouraged until they
see reforms more fundamental than those Birnbaum recommends.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
