<HEADLINE>
CAN THIS PUDDING BE SAVED? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some hilarity but still more uncertainty attends the future of
Harvard's Hasty Pudding troupe, famous for handing out
tongue-in-cheek awards (Mamie Eisenhower _ 1953's Woman of the
Year) and dolling up future presidents (Franklin Roosevelt, John
Kennedy) in dresses. The venerable organization, a theater group
and separate social club controlled by an entity known as the Hasty
Pudding Club-Institute of 1770, is on its uppers. Translation: It's
broke.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Pudding has been going broke since at least 1986,
when the club sold the land under the theater to Harvard for back
taxes and agreed to pay rent to the World's Greatest University.
The Pudding, as the old joke goes, has been getting a little behind
in the rent _ $480,000 behind. The university plans to take over
the building Aug. 31, and what happens next is anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   The worst-case scenario is this: The Holyoke Street building,
home to the Up Stairs at the Pudding restaurant as well as the
cross-dressing joyboys, will become a nothingburger Undergraduate
Activities Center that the Pudding would share with other student
groups. Worse yet, under direct WGU control, the Pudding might be
forced to include _ gasp! _ women in its traditionally all-male
cast. Harvard president Neil Rudenstine has blathered about how the
club needs to become more inclusive, blah blah blah.
</P>
<P>
   How did things get this bad? The alumni board that controls the
Pudding feels that Harvard has never properly supported its
world-renowned gang of idiots. (Said idiots have included Alan Jay
Lerner, Erich Segal, and Jack Lemmon, who played piano under the
stage name Jack Orange because he was on academic probation and
banned from extracurricular activities in 1946.) Since 1986, the
board's attempts to mount a capital campaign on behalf of the
theater have been thwarted by Harvard's voracious development
office, which lays first claim to squeezing wealthy alumni.
</P>
<P>
   Worse still, some Pudding shows have lost money, and the
financial relationship with the much-praised restaurant has been
stormy. Up Stairs used to host board meetings for free, in lieu of
missed rent payments, one man recalls: ``But we would have had to
eat there about five thousand times to recoup what they owed us.''
``We paid a substantial rent,'' is all co-owner Mary-Catherine
Deibel cares to say on this subject.
</P>
<P>
   Associate Dean David Illingworth promises that the Pudding show
will go on. Harvard plans to spend $6-8 million renovating the
building next year, and then will allow the plays to continue
starting in 2002. ``Since it's a drag show, putting women on the
stage doesn't seem to make any sense,'' he says. The Pudding's
high-living private social club, I suspect, will get the gate.
Neither Harvard nor the restaurant wants to comment on the future
of Up Stairs at the Pudding, but staffers have been telling
customers that they will probably have to move in a year or so.
</P>
<P>
   Free Plug
</P>
<P>
   Thornton Wilder's venerable chestnut ``Our Town'' is not
everyone's cup of tea. It is the perennial nightmare high school
theatrical; since it won the Pulitzer Prize in 1938, it has
supposedly become the most-produced play in the country. Over the
past half-century, every significant critic has had his or her say
about Wilder's spare, ultimately tragic account of life in
``Grover's Corners, New Hampshire,'' a pre-World War I Anytown,
U.S.A. Mary McCarthy liked it; George Jean Nathan hated it. Arthur
Miller complained, justifiably, that the play lacks a psychological
dimension.
</P>
<P>
   But it is hard to imagine the play better rendered than in the
real-life Grover's Corners _ Peterborough, N.H. _ in the current
production by the Peterborough Players. Wilder wrote most of ``Our
Town'' at the nearby MacDowell Colony, and when Stage Manager James
Whitmore (yes, the craggy Miracle Gro pitchman) points over to Mt.
Monadnock, or down to Boston, the effect is electric. I wager that
Whitmore is the best Stage Manager since Henry Fonda defined the
role for a generation of theatergoers in 1969. For obvious reasons,
the Players are hyping the presence of Hollywood veterans Whitmore
and Mary Beth Hurt (Mrs. Webb) in the cast, but the entire
25-person ensemble is superb.
</P>
<P>
   Through Aug. 20. For tickets call (603) 924-7585.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Alex Beam's e-mail is beam(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
