<P>
   With photos, NYT1,2.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH (Dateline to kum) _ Bush W. Bush is in southern California,
Washington state and Oregon. He will be joined for part of the trip
by Arizona Sen. John McCain. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   CHENEY (St. Louis) _ Dick Cheney starts first solo run.
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN-SENATE (Washington) _ What the Lieberman selection
means to calculations about the fight for control of the Senate. By
Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   REFORM-PARTY (Long Beach, Calif.) _ Developments at the Reform
Party convention: The wrangling continues. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   REFORM-BUCHANAN (Long Beach) _ Pat Buchanan arrives on the
scene. By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Notes from the hustings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FREEDOM-MEDALS (Washington) _ President Clinton awards the
Presidential Medal of Freedom, the nation's highest civilian honor,
to 15 Americans, including Jesse Jackson, Adm. William Crowe,
Marian Wright Edelman and Simon Wiesenthal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CONJOINED-TWINS (Undated) _ In a surgical tour de force,
performed with minutes to spare, doctors in Boston separated
conjoined twins who shared a heart. Because of highly unusual
circulatory abnormalities, one of the twins was doomed; the
question was, could the other be saved? Through elaborate planning,
including computer modeling, the doctors found a way to save her
and now, at 14 months, she is living with her family in Paterson
and doing well. By Denise Grady. (1600 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-QUAKE (Mexico City) _ An earthquake centered under the
Pacific Ocean shook western and central Mexico. There were no
immediate reports of injuries or damage.
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-TROOPS (Marjayoun, Lebanon) _ A 1,000-member force of
Lebanese security officers moved into the former Israeli-occupied
zone, marking the first time the government has asserted control
over the border areas of southern Lebanon since the 1970s. By John
Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BOMB (Moscow) _ President Vladimir Putin cautioned
Russians against blaming the people of Chechnya for the explosion
on Tuesday that killed seven and harshly criticized Moscow's mayor
for his comments. Police discovered another bomb just before
arresting two men from North Caucasus in the bombing. By Patrick E.
Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-POLITICS (Jakarta) _ President Wahid says he is giving
more day-to-day responsibilities for running the government to Vice
President Megawati Sukaranoputri, who was supposed to have become
president last October before he out-maneuvered her. By Seth
Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-MARRIAGE (Tehran) _ Iran's new reformist parliament
approved its first major bill, giving women more rights by saying
fathers cannot arrange a marriage for a daughter until she is at
least 15. A 21-year-old law allowed fathers to marry off daughters
as young as 9.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TIRE-RECALL (Washington) _ Bridgestone, the world's
second-largest tiremaker, says it will recall 6.55 million tires
for light trucks and sports utility vehicles that are the subject
of a safety investigation into at least 46 deaths. It is fewer than
reports that 20 million tires would be recalled and fewer than the
14 million tires Firestone recalled in the 1970s (which nearly
bankrupted the company. Looking at which tires are covered, how to
get them replaced, what role the government played and how the
companies involved are handling this. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT3,8.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   TIRE-FIRESTONE (Undated) _ Looking at the recall in the context
of what is happening at Firestone and in the tire industry. It all
comes at a weak time for the industry _ high oil prices mean high
rubber and other materials prices, but there's been huge resistance
to price. Looking at the role law firms are playing in setting the
tone of the safety inquiry. By Claudia H. Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   TIRE-FORD (Traverse City, Mich.) _ What it means to Ford Motor.
By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   TIRE-BRIDGESTONE (Tokyo) _ What the recall means to Bridgestone.
What it says about Japanese business culture and how it responds to
crises in the United States. In Tokyo, shares of Bridgestone
tumbled more than 8 percent. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   VERIZON-STRIKE (Undated) _ Developments in strike against
Verizon Communications. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column. By Patrick
McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   JOBS-DISPLACEMENT (Undated) _ The Labor Department's biennial
jobs displacement survey. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   SOFTWARE-MERGER (Undated) _ Internet software companies
Phone.com and Software.com say they will merge in a stock deal
worth $6.8 billion, combining two companies that provide software
that delivers Internet features to wireless devices.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECON (Sao Paulo, Brazil) _ Brazil's economic growth
expanded sharply in the first half of the year, confirming the
accelerating recovery by Latin America's largest economy from the
currency crisis of January 1999. Economists called the latest data
stronger than than they had expected and said the central bank's
recent series of interest rate deductions would likely lead to
higher growth rates. By Jennifer L. Rich.
</P>
<P>
   BARCLAYS-WOOLWICH (London) _ Barclays, Britain's third-largest
bank, says it is in talks to buy Woolwich in a deal valued at $8.3
billion. A deal would more than double the mortgage business for
Barclays, and could set off another wave of consolidation in
British banking. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   WEALTH-ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The Economic Scene column: That the
rich are getting richer and the poor are getting poorer is a
populist truism, Exhibit A in the case against the economy's recent
dynamism. But what if increasing inequality is mostly a myth _ an
artifact of misleading data and changing lifestyles? What if just
about everyone is getting richer? By Virginia Postrel.
</P>
