<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6757 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-09 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LEARN SOMETHING FOR THE FUN OF IT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Stands for LEARNING)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sometimes the best road to career success is a
blind alley. Workers get so used to learning a few particular
skills for one particular career that they deprive themselves of
the joy of learning. It becomes a chore, not an adventure.
</P>
<P>
   One big regret from a lot of young people who go straight
through college and get a master's degree is that they didn't take
a year off somewhere along the way. By the time you reach college,
it can be a lot easier to focus on the end of the educational
treadmill (or on mass quantities of beer, for that matter) than on
the joy of learning.
</P>
<P>
   In his book ``Living, Loving &AMP; Learning'' years ago, Leo
Buscaglia recalled how his father, who called him Felice, used to
always ask a question after their Sunday dinners: ``Felice, what
did you learn today?'' Young Buscaglia knew the question was
coming, of course, so he made it a point to look up something in
the encyclopedia before dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I want to tell you a secret,'' Buscaglia writes. ``Even
now, when Felice goes to bed, maybe he's worked 29 hours that day
and he's exhausted, but when he crawls into the sheets, that
gorgeous moment before you go off, he says to himself, `Felice,
what did you learn today?' And if I can't answer that question, I
have to get up and get the encyclopedia and flip to something and
learn something new.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who love to learn are the ones who succeed, in their
careers and in life. If you have lost that joy and it isn't just a
temporary funk, do whatever you can to get it back.
</P>
<P>
   The best career move I ever made had nothing to do with
journalism. After 10 years or so as a reporter, I was at a plateau.
I still enjoyed newspaper work, but had the itch to explore another
career.
</P>
<P>
   So I tried moonlighting as a financial planner. I went through a
training program and earned licenses to sell things like life
insurance and disability insurance and mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't right for me. I liked the idea of helping people with
their money, but financial planners back then made most of their
money through commissions. And I wasn't much of a salesman.
</P>
<P>
   But I learned a lot about personal finance, especially about
focusing on the long term. That training, along with the
availability of information on the Internet, allowed me to bring in
more money during the 1990s as a financial planner than as a
journalist, even though the only people I did any financial
planning for were my wife and me.
</P>
<P>
   I also remember what my boss told me when I quit the financial
planning job: Every job is a sales job. She was right, of course.
Good workers learn how to sell their bosses on particular projects,
and good bosses know that workers will do a better job if they are
convinced that a project is worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   Soon I sold my newspaper boss on the idea of writing a column
for home computer users. This was in 1989, when computers were far
more frustrating than they are today. Honest.
</P>
<P>
   That got me into writing a regular column, which has become one
of the most rewarding parts of my career. Most of that might not
have happened if I hadn't gotten back into the habit of learning.
</P>
<P>
   I know career gurus preach about building skills _ and you
should _ but that can sound like a huge chore when you're already
feeling overwhelmed by work. Just get started by finding something
you think would be fun, even if it has nothing to do with your
career.
</P>
<P>
   Do you love to travel? Learn more about the history of your
favorite state or country. Even if you feel swamped by work and
life, you might find time for learning by listening to foreign
language tapes while you are commuting.
</P>
<P>
   Read self-help books. Pursue your hobby over the Internet.
Research the details about some unusual factoid you learned from
watching ``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   If you look upon learning as a chore, it's easy for inertia to
set in. But if you get into the habit of learning things you want
to learn, it will be easier to add whatever skills that you do need
to survive.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
