A6775 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-COOKSKITCHEN-TEX     08-09 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOKSKITCHEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTAURATEUR'S NEW MEXICAN RETREAT INCLUDES A 1,200-SQUARE-FOOT
KITCHEN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BEVERLY BUNDY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA FE, N.M. _ The casual visitor would be knocked out by the
vista from the living room _ 50 miles north to Los Alamos, 50 miles
south to Albuquerque _ a panorama of 150 miles of sunset
interrupted by only five blend-into-the-sand adobe structures and
not a single utility wire.
</P>
<P>
   The frescoed walls _ smoother than a debutante's complexion,
with layered shell-thin coats of pigmented plaster _ would also
have their admirers. The six fireplaces, too, would surely elicit
oohs and aahs.
</P>
<P>
   But for a cook, the main event in Mark Miller's New Mexico house
is the 1,200-square-foot kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, owner of the Coyote Cafes in Santa Fe and Las Vegas and
Red Sage in Washington, D.C., knew what he wanted when he designed
his 4,300-square-foot hacienda. He wanted peace, he wanted quiet,
and he wanted a kitchen where he could entertain and work without
the noise, activity and interruptions of his restaurant kitchens.
But he also wanted the functional advantages of professional
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, he designed a kitchen that works when he's
developing recipes and menus for his restaurants, yet also reflects
his love of travel, New Mexico and most things Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   ``In restaurant kitchens, you have to use stainless equipment
because it's the most functional, but I didn't want to see it from
another room; I don't want a demonstration kitchen in my house. The
last thing I want to look at is another kitchen.''
</P>
<P>
   To get form and function, he tucked the freezer into an
anteroom. Only one slick side of the professional Traulsen
refrigerator is visible outside of the kitchen. The Montague stove
_ with built-in fry basket and flat frying surface _ hides in
another corner. An in-stove wok, fired by built-in jet flames, sits
flat on the range. His two-grated custom-built grill (''I can cook
a duck on one side and a fish on the other at the same time'') was
built by a local ironworker, based on a drawing Miller made of an
ancient Spanish model. A pizza oven is carved out of one brick
wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a mistake by having just gas burners in the stove top;
I should have gone with half gas and half conduction heat,'' Miller
says, noting the benefits of the can't-miss settings of the
cool-heat cooking system.
</P>
<P>
   He has one oven, a convection model, and can't see that any home
cook would need more. A very clever idea is his pastry station: A
small-size refrigerator is housed under one of the marble counters.
Because the top of the refrigerator is cut off, the marble is
always cool and ready for pastry work. The small refrigerator
stores butter, nuts, cream _ ingredients that would pick up odors
in the bigger refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Refrigeration is big in Miller's kitchen _ he figures he has
$15,000 to $20,000 in cooling equipment between the refrigerators,
the ice maker, the wine cooler and the freezer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most kitchens don't have enough linear space,'' Miller says.
``Every person working in a kitchen should have a 3-foot-by-18-inch
flat surface to use; ideally, it should be three feet by 24
inches.''
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate people cooking in his kitchen, Miller installed a
19-foot-long, 38-inch-wide island down the center of the room. It's
topped with butcher block, a surface he calls affordable. Inlaid
into one end of the island is a piece of marble _ a ``landing
zone'' for hot items coming off of the stove or out of the oven.
</P>
<P>
   Everything was designed to fit into a modular system holding the
standard full- and half-sheet trays that are de rigueur in
restaurant kitchens. The trays can slide into the freezer, be
transferred and slid into the refrigerator brackets, and taken from
there directly to the oven.
</P>
<P>
   A man of distinct tastes (''I always stay in Hyatts because I
can't stand those fake antiques in the Ritz Carltons''), Miller is
exacting in his own home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anything higher than eye level is wasted. You forget
about it if you don't see it. And I don't like cabinets for the
same reason.''
</P>
<P>
   To store the necessities of cooking and serving, Miller built
two walk-in pantries lined with open shelves. One pantry is filled
with plates and ceramic pieces. It's an eclectic collection,
including such pieces as Villeroy &AMP; Boch Petite Fleur vegetable
bowl and an old tinware fish poacher. The second is filled with
ingredients: One shelf holds dried mushrooms and chiles, another
holds oils and vinegars, a third displays Asian chile pastes and
spices.
</P>
<P>
   He found another solution for wineglasses, storing them in
glass-fronted olive-wood cabinets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be able to see things; you can easily break a $100
Baccarat champagne glass by dragging it out of a cabinet,'' Miller
says.
</P>
<P>
   But his kitchen is not all about function.
</P>
<P>
   The walls are a shade called ``carmelita,'' not quite oxblood,
not quite burgundy. Miller has loved the color since first seeing
it in Spain, where it is often used in monasteries. Another exotic
touch is the pink dome, inlaid with glass discs, that rises from
the ceiling _ an idea taken from Morocco's public baths. Middle
Eastern-inspired designs frame the kitchen's doorways.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the gravity of Miller's purposeful design, he has one
piece of advice for home cooks designing their own kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make the kitchen an area where you'd like to play. If you
don't like the kitchen, cooking will be drudgery.''
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
