<DOCNO> NYT20000809.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6779 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-EXTRAS0810-COX     08-09 1491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXTRAS0810-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Read all about how to land a role as a real-life movie extra
 &HT;    By Chris Hutchins
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - Wanna be in pictures? You're in the
right place. It looks like Palm Beach County has become Hollywood
East.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Palm Beachers watched Sigourney Weaver, Gene Hackman
and Jennifer Love Hewitt film scenes for ``The Breakers,'' an
upcoming big-budget release from MGM Studios. This month, a young,
scrappy crew in Jupiter is filming ``Do You Wanna Know a Secret?,''
an independently produced horror thriller aimed at teens.
</P>
<P>
   But while studios are making movies in our back yard, breaking
into the biz is still tough. One place to start is by being an
``extra.'' You know, those nameless, dialogue-less folks who
provide background and atmosphere for film scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Moviemakers need extras. They believe extras add ``legitimacy''
to a movie. Think about it: How authentic would a film set in New
York City be without crowds crawling along the sidewalks?
</P>
<P>
   When a movie is filmed on location, the extras are usually local
residents. And, in the case of ``Do You Wanna Know a Secret?,''
that's where you come in.
</P>
<P>
   When ``The Breakers'' did some extras casting, it uttered a call
for the rich and sockless. Now, the producers of ``Secret?'' are
looking for folks to help film scenes at a beach and at a rave
club. This is your chance to get dressed in your sexiest duds and
be in the motion picture business.
</P>
<P>
   To help you land the role, we slipped on our shades, spiked up
our hair, grabbed a mocha latte and visited the set in search of
tips. Executive producer Del Tenney's Jupiter home _ where the
majority of the movie is being filmed _ has been overtaken by the
cast and crew. Power cables lie everywhere. The words ``Do You
Wanna Know A SECRET?'' are spray-painted on a bay window.
</P>
<P>
   We chatted with the movie's producers and some of its stars
about being an extra. We met Joey Lawrence, former Blossom TV star,
now a strapping 24-year-old fresh from the set of his last movie,
``Urban Legends: Final Cut'' (it'll be out next month). We had a
few minutes with Jack McGee _ a ruddy-faced character actor
audiences love to hate (he was the surly cops reporter in ``The
Paper,'' and the skeptical Sgt. Jordan in the recent remake of
``The Out-Of-Towners''). We also talked with Tom J. Jones. This is
his first feature-length movie, but he's been in several
commercials (nowadays it's a 1-800-COLLECT ad, starring alongside
Alyssa Milano. ``I'm the guy on the phone,'' Jones says).
</P>
<P>
   Cool. Even cooler: These guys offered inside information on
getting the extras gig ... and keeping it once you're on set.
You'll also hear from producer Kermit Christman, who is going to be
selecting the extras. Christman _ who founded the Palm Beach
Shakespeare Festival 10 years ago _ will tell you what the
filmmakers are looking for.
</P>
<P>
   Ready for some free advice? Then quiet on the set!
</P>
<P>
   Reality check
</P>
<P>
   Before we go any further, let's check some misconceptions at the
door. Being an extra can be hard work. It's not glamorous. You're
not going to get your own trailer. You're not going to have a
six-hour work day. In the case of ``Do You Wanna Know a Secret?,''
you're not even going to get paid. You will, however, score some
free meals, and your name will be tossed into a raffle to win
either $500 or a water scooter.
</P>
<P>
   This is a typical day in the life of an extra: Get to the set,
wait around, take direction. The crew will film a scene a few
times. Then you wait around some more. Take more direction. Film.
Wait. Film. Wait. Film. Wait.
</P>
<P>
   Get the idea? Days in the movie business are long. Everyone _
including extras _ will put in 12 hours, probably more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commitment to do this means you will be there for many
hours,'' Christman explains. ``Motion pictures are not made
swiftly. It's `Hurry up and wait.' ... We need people with patience
for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Long hours and no pay? OK, so it's not a career, but you do get
to be in a movie.
</P>
<P>
   And how do you get in? In the case of Secret, Christman is
looking for people ages 18 to 24 to participate in a ``beach''
scene and a ``rave'' scene. Show up at Palm Beach Community
College's Eissey Theatre in Palm Beach Gardens. Auditions for the
rave scene will be at 5 p.m. today; casting for the beach scene
will be at 5 p.m. on Aug. 14.
</P>
<P>
   OK. Say you fall into that 18-to-24 demographic. Don't think age
is the only thing Christman's looking for. He has his eyes peeled
for upbeat people with a sense of style. The extras in Secret?
should be spunky, a little funky ... and beautiful. When you come
to the audition, be dressed in attire for the scene. Shiny club
clothes would help for the rave scenes. Women couldn't go wrong
with bikinis for the beach scene.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't try too hard, Christman says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is, be yourself. The movie is about
people like you,'' he says. ``So if you're going to great lengths,
you're going to be preparing to not be `you.' Understand? Just be
yourself. How do you dress to go to the beach on a sunny day? How
do you look when you go to a nightclub? ... That's how you should
look when you come do this.''
</P>
<P>
   And come prepared for potential disappointment. Although the
movie's script calls for about 200 to 300 extras, Secret's
producers will have to turn some folks away. Still, it might be
worth a shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just come down and try out,'' says Jason Goldman, assistant to
the producer. ``Almost every (actor) starts at the ground floor.
... Obviously, we're not guaranteeing that you'll be a movie star.
But if you want to pursue that, here's a great first opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the part
</P>
<P>
   OK, suspend your disbelief for a moment: You've scored a role as
an extra in ``Secret?,'' and now you need some ``survival tips.''
We got 'em, straight from the stars.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing you need to understand is that the cast and crew
are there to make a movie. It's a big deal to them _ literally
every minute costs them money. That said, here are some things to
remember, so you don't end up on the cutting room floor:
</P>
<P>
   Do what you're told: ``Like any job, just pay attention and do
what they ask you to do,'' says executive producer Tenney. ``If you
try to be outstanding, you are going to be a problem. This is all a
team effort. It's like any other job out there; it's teamwork, and
you have to do your job when it's time to do your job. It's that
simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't look at the camera: ``Your natural tendency is to gawk
right into the camera,'' says character actor McGee. ``What you
have to do is be conscious that the camera's there, but act as if
it isn't. If you're in a dance scene, there's nothing wrong with
turning away from the camera. Swinging back, turn around.''
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, you're an actor: ``The director just wants
you to be yourself and act natural,'' says young actor Jones _ who
was an extra in the movie ``Waterworld.'' ``Acting is pretending
that you're not pretending. In this case, if you're at a club,
you're at a club. If you're talking to your friends, talk to your
friends. Laugh, dance, do whatever. But that's what they want,
because they want to create the ambiance that this is real.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember the long hours: ``As glamorous as this racket is, it's
a long, tedious day,'' admits McGee. ``When they need you to come
to set, they need you. Don't dilly-dally around. It's not easy to
do. ... You're probably going to make friends while you're there,
you'll get to know people and maybe want to goof around a little
bit. But be serious about it. Be serious, but have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Timing is everything: ``When they say `Cut,' you gotta cut,''
says lead star Lawrence. ``You have to be like soldiers; that's
kind of what it's like. You'll be given directions as a whole body
of people _ and like a choir, you have to sing on cue. You have to
nail your parts. And you have to be that tight about it, because we
don't have time to waste.''
</P>
<P>
   Be on time: Ellen Jacoby, the extras casting director for ``The
Breakers,'' offered this observation: ``Never, ever approach the
stars. Never ask for autographs. Never take pictures. And get there
a few minutes early. If there are 500 extras and you show up 10
minutes late and say, `Oh! The traffic was terrible!', I'll say,
`499 other people got here on time. I'm here on time.' We'll ask
you to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Yikes! In the end, just remember this extras bit is a lot of
work, but a lot of fun, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone loves the movies. We just love it,'' Christman says.
``Why? I think we love the magic of it. We go to the cinema in the
dark and we see this lightshow in front of us, that tells a story.
That really is it. ... And now, here it is, in your own back yard.
Be a part of it. Enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail chrishutchins(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
