<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6782 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-T     08-09 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUCCOTASH GOES GOURMET _ SUFFERIN' IS HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ART CHAPMAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Sylvester the cat uttered his trademark, ``Sufferin'
succotash,'' I always thought he must have eaten in the same school
cafeteria that I did.
</P>
<P>
   Succotash creates a bad image for me. I remember the pale-yellow
corn and the uneasy green lima beans swimming in a watery cream.
Not only was it unappetizing, but it ruined the food resting next
to it.
</P>
<P>
   The succotash juices spilled over the tomato sauce and onto the
meatloaf, causing a sort of sick pink backdrop for the entire meal.
</P>
<P>
   The name itself _ succotash _ has a curious sound to it.
Succotash is promoted as a summer dish, a simple recipe for fresh
summer corn, but its history is more or less linked to
Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional explanation is that succotash comes from the
Narragansett Indian ``misickquatash,'' a term for boiled corn. That
doesn't look or sound like succotash to me, but I guess it's close
enough.
</P>
<P>
   The dish has come to refer to a combination of corn and beans,
and the Pilgrims and Indians are believed to have eaten that very
combination when they established the American Thanksgiving holiday
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   That was the feast held in 1620 for the Indians by the newly
arrived English settlers to celebrate their hopes for peace after
the first harvest in the Plymouth Colony.
</P>
<P>
   Or, maybe it was in 1621, and the party was really thrown by the
Indians.
</P>
<P>
   One account says that the first Thanksgiving celebration is
believed to have taken place in Plymouth, Mass., in 1621. In the
late fall, the Wampanoag Indians traditionally held a harvest
festival to give thanks for the food they had grown; in England,
the Puritans had observed a solemn thanksgiving in November as part
of their religious practice.
</P>
<P>
   In the autumn of 1620, the Pilgrims did land in Massachusetts,
but there wasn't much to celebrate. Many accounts of the time say
several people fell ill or perished that winter. In spring 1621,
two Wompanoag Indians, Squanto and Samoset, found the survivors.
Squanto stayed with the Pilgrims through the summer and taught them
about native foods and how to grow them.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall, the harvest was bountiful, and the Pilgrims had
enough food for the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. William Bradford declared a day of thanksgiving, and Capt.
Miles Standish invited Squanto, Samoset and their leaders to join
the celebration. So many Wampanoags showed up, the food supply was
strained, and the Indians had to bring their own covered dishes.
That could have been when green-bean casserole was invented.
</P>
<P>
   There probably weren't any pies or cakes, because no flour was
available. Some blasphemous people say there wasn't even a turkey.
The best-guess menu is fowl of some kind, deer, and cranberry
sauce. Along with corn soup, white fish, maple-sugar candies,
cornstarch candy, wild plums, watercress, beans, squash and boiled
pumpkin.
</P>
<P>
   And succotash.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder relations became strained.
</P>
<P>
   Today, things have changed. Succotash has busted out of its
traditional role of sloppy cafeteria food, and the list of
ingredients has grown.
</P>
<P>
   Purple onions, cherry tomatoes and cucumbers have added
additional flavors to the old beans and corn. Succotash has even
made its way into high-tone magazines.
</P>
<P>
   This month's ``Gourmet'' offers a spicy version that uses cider
vinegar and jalapenos for extra zing.
</P>
<P>
   It's no longer ``sufferin' succotash.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SUCCOTASH
</P>
<P>
   Yields 8
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound sliced bacon
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   4 ears corn, kernels cut off and cob discarded
</P>
<P>
   1 large fresh jalapeno, seeded and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 (10-ounce) package frozen baby lima beans, thawed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound okra, cut into 1/3-inch slices
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound cherry tomatoes (1 pint), halved
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cider vinegar, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 chopped fresh basil
</P>
<P>
   Cook bacon in a large skillet over moderate heat until crisp.
Drain on paper towels, leaving fat in skillet.
</P>
<P>
   Add onion to skillet and cook over moderate heat, stirring,
until softened. Add garlic and cook, stirring, 1 minute. Stir in
corn, jalapeno, lima beans, okra and tomatoes; cook, stirring,
until vegetables are tender, about 7 minutes. Stir in vinegar,
basil, and salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Serve succotash with bacon crumbled on top.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 159 calories, 4 grams fat, 26
grams carbohydrates, 7 grams protein, 6 milligrams cholesterol, 141
milligrams sodium, 23 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes on food for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Write to him at: Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101. E-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Web Site:
www.startext.net/interact/chapman.htm. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
