A6787 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-FORD-MODEL-E-HNS &LR;      08-09 0381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-MODEL-E-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FORD RENEWS CHALLENGE OVER USE OF `MODEL E' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Its case thrown out by a Detroit judge for
lack of jurisdiction, Ford Motor Co. has refiled a lawsuit against
an Internet startup company called Model E.
</P>
<P>
   The automaker contends that the name Model E would create
consumer confusion about whether Model E's business was associated
with Ford's antique vehicles, most notably the Model T, said Ford
spokeswoman Kathleen Vokes.
</P>
<P>
   The Fremont-based Model E plans to offer customers
built-to-order vehicles sold over the Internet. Clients also will
be able to subscribe to various cars over specified time periods,
an option similar to leasing but the deal would include
registration, maintenance and other services.
</P>
<P>
   The automaker maintains the Internet company has violated a Ford
trademark.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're protecting a trademark,'' Vokes said. ``What was ruled
on was not necessarily the validity of the case. It was the
validity of the jurisdiction.''
</P>
<P>
   The Michigan court's decision, made Monday, was in response to a
motion filed by Model E on Aug. 3 to dismiss Ford's lawsuit, which
had been filed July 28. Ford refiled the case in the U.S. District
Court in Oakland after the Detroit court said it did not have
jurisdiction over the case.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ford never produced a ``Model E'' car, it did sell a
truck under that name. And the company is using the name for its
program to provide computers to all its employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the dismissal of the Ford suit against us in Michigan, we
were hoping to rededicate ourselves and resources to those that
matter most to us _ our customers,'' said George Kim, Model E's
chief business development officer.
</P>
<P>
   Kim said the company has made it clear to Ford it would like to
discuss a resolution. ``Obviously, we do not want to spend our
precious time and resources on this matter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that our use of the Model E name does not violate
any rights of Ford,'' said William Santana Li, Model E's president
and chief executive. ``In fact, Ford has known of our company since
last year and never told us of any concern until just recently.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 1500EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
