<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6815 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-     08-09 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING GOOD NEIGHBORS, PART I 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Constructing a simple fence, in a straight line on relatively
level ground without a gate, is within the skill level of an
intermediate do-it-yourselfer. The hardest part is making an
accurate layout, estimating the needed materials and setting the
posts.
</P>
<P>
   First check with community building officials to see if the
local codes affect your project. Many codes require that the
''good'' side of the fence project away from the house. Codes often
have restrictions on height and how far the fence must be from the
property line, the setback.
</P>
<P>
   Also check with utility companies to find the location of all
underground pipes and cables. Many companies will come to your
property and mark the locations for you. When you dig the post
holes, stay at least 18 inches from these marks. It is also a good
idea to notify your neighbors that you plan to erect a fence. This
simple precaution can ease a lot of tensions before they have a
chance to fester.
</P>
<P>
   When you are ready to plan the fence, put in stakes and string
to mark its position. The line should be at least six inches within
your property line. Be certain you know exactly where your boundary
lines are. If you are not sure, hire a surveyor to mark the lines
before proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   After you have determined the length of the fence, map out the
sections. Each will be supported at the ends with a post. Fence
posts should not be farther apart than eight feet from center to
center. To find the total number of posts needed, divide the total
length of the fence by eight. If you come up with a remainder,
divide again by a slightly smaller number. By adjusting the number
through trial and error, you will eventually come up with a whole
number. To that number, add one (for an end post), and that will be
the number of posts needed. Return to the string line and mark the
location of the posts with stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Each section will be made up of three elements: The posts, the
stringers and the pickets. Make a scale drawing of a section, and
use it as a guide to help estimate the amount of lumber needed for
the entire fence.
</P>
<P>
   You have already determined how many posts are needed, but you
need to figure their length. The posts will be made of 4-by-4
stock. The length will be determined by the height of the post plus
enough extra stock to set the posts in the soil. Minimum setting
depth is 32 inches. Assume that your fence will be 6 feet high. Add
32 inches to that and you will arrive at fence posts about 8 1/2
feet long.
</P>
<P>
   Two stringer boards are required for each section. The stringers
are the horizontal boards that support the pickets. Use
two-by-fours for the stringers. They will be four inches shorter
(to allow for the width of the posts) than the section length.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, you need to calculate the amount of lumber needed for
the pickets. The total number of pickets will be determined by the
dimensions of the fence and by its design. First, decide the width
of the pickets. Next determine how much space you want between
them. You can, if you desire, butt the pickets together so there is
no space. This will create a fence that will give you plenty of
privacy, but it will also block the breezes.
</P>
<P>
   If you decide to space the pickets out, consider the picket
width and space as an individual unit. Divide that number into the
section length. You may have to adjust either the picket width or
spaces to arrive at a whole number. Multiply this figure by the
number of sections to find the total number of pickets.
</P>
<P>
   Next, determine the length of the pickets. This is really a
design choice. There are only two factors to consider. The pickets
should be at least one inch off the ground and they should not be
higher than the posts.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the lumber, you will also need rust-resist nails
made of aluminum or stainless steel, or nails with a galvanized
coating. If you decide to set the fence posts in cement (you can
use ordinary dirt but the posts will not be as sturdy), you will
need about two 80-pound bags per post.
</P>
<P>
   The best place to order this material is from a lumberyard that
sells fencing materials. The dealer can check your estimates and
the yard will have a stock of ready-cut fence parts in a variety of
woods. Pine is the cheapest wood, but requires periodic
maintenance. Cedar and redwood are maintenance-free but more
expensive. Next week, this column will describe the technique for
building the fence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
