<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6829 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-DIVORCE-LAWYER-ART-NY     08-09 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIVORCE-LAWYER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCOURGE OF STARS, RICH SPOUSE'S NIGHTMARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 5 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOYCE WADLER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You ready for the show? Because the set is waiting
for you. The office door of Philip Marlowe, Private Detective, is
on one side; the office of Sam Spade, Criminal Investigator, is on
the other, and in the center, befitting the star, is the name of
Raoul Felder, in gold. Trompe l'oeil, the doors of Marlowe and
Spade, though Europeans have been known to get confused.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a cheap gag _ we are talking office space on the
30th floor on Madison Avenue _ but Felder, matrimonial lawyer to
the stars, is doing well. We could let him discuss the art in his
office, the Groz, the Picasso; or permit him his old trick of
beguiling the adversary into a sense of superiority with a
self-deprecating comment regarding his accomplishments or health.
(Today's: ``You have allergies? My sinuses are killing me.'')
</P>
<P>
   But because this is Felder, gallantly looking out for the rights
of single mothers in the case of the Brazilian lingerie model
Luciana Morad vs. Mick Jagger (``The wrinkly rocker, I called him.
That's a nice phrase.'') by seeking $35,000 a month in child
support, let's cut to the chase.
</P>
<P>
   Felder, you've got a lot of rich, spoiled people for clients _
``Yeah,'' interrupts Felder, agreeably. ``They usually go together,
by the way, those two adjectives. I had very little choice in my
career. A Jewish boy growing up in Brooklyn, it was doctor, lawyer
or, if you weren't so bright, selling shirts.''
</P>
<P>
   But you didn't have to do this kind of law.
</P>
<P>
   Deadpan, which Felder does as well as his pal Jackie Mason:
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah. It was the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Now playing, in one of the longest-running shows in town, our
own matrimonial song and dance man, Raoul Felder. How old are you
getting to be, Felder? ``Sixty-three. That's a lie,'' he says,
trimming three years.
</P>
<P>
   The National Law Journal called him a ``publicity machine
extraordinaire,'' and some say his wife and partner, Myrna Felder,
is the superior legal tactician. But Felder's friend and frequent
adversary, Eleanor Alter, calls him ``terrific at what he does, who
knows how to negotiate.''
</P>
<P>
   And, given his public relations philosophy _ ``I knew and still
know how to use the media'' _ he will rarely show offense.
</P>
<P>
   Felder, you seem very often to get the fiscal have-nots. Mick
Jagger's girlfriend and not Mick. Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``Men, particularly wealthy men, usually have regular lawyers.
The women go with a name they see in the newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   So you don't feel bad that Mick didn't call?
</P>
<P>
   ``No. When you represent men _ I don't like to mention names,
but I represented Brian De Palma and Richard Harris years ago, when
they were big stars _ they come in with a gang of their sycophants,
they're used to ordering people around. They have these guys:
`Yeah, baby. Go, baby. Great idea, baby.' The wife starts out
tabula rasa, she listens to the lawyer. Do you come with a troop of
retainers when you go to any other professional? You go to a
doctor, you don't take a press agent.''
</P>
<P>
   It is possible there is some genuine melancholy here. Growing up
poor in Brooklyn, Felder had an elder brother who had been sent to
the country to escape an epidemic of infantile paralysis and there
contracted polio, an event which could instill in anyone an
appreciation of the dark ironies of life. That brother, the
legendary songwriter Doc Pomus, who died in 1991, wrote the hits
``This Magic Moment'' and ``Save the Last Dance for Me.''
</P>
<P>
   Raoul Felder begins legal life as a federal prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   How does he become a divorce lawyer?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a boring story,'' Felder says. ``Thankfully it's short.''
</P>
<P>
   We'll make it even shorter. Felder represents a pal in a
divorce, and The Daily News writes it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first year I made $50,000,'' he says. ``I'd been making
$11,000 a year in the prosecutor's office. It was a great way to
make money. It's not a religious endeavor.''
</P>
<P>
   Struggling with the allergies. ``I'm passing away. I got to take
a spray up my nose. I'll show you the bottle, I want you to know
it's not crack cocaine.''
</P>
<P>
   A brief adjournment, after which Felder is asked about a framed
front page from a British tabloid, about a consultation with Diana,
Princess of Wales.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't comment,'' Felder honks. ``I get consulted by a lot of
people, make a lot of enemies. One enemy I made for no reason at
all was the poor kid that got killed in the plane crash, John
Kennedy, when the rapist was being tried. Remember his cousin
William Kennedy Smith, he was a rapist, tried in Florida?''
</P>
<P>
   But Smith was acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   Felder continues speaking about the trial, undeterred.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a statement, `This could turn out to be the fall of the
house of Kennedy.' After the rapist was acquitted I get flowers
like you send for a dead person and a note that says, `We're still
standing, baby,' and signed `John.' I didn't quite believe it. I
called one of the columnists and said, `You check it out,' and it
was him, the flowers were charged to Kennedy's account.''
</P>
<P>
   Felder did not need to send that to the papers. He could have
checked it all out himself.
</P>
<P>
   A look innocent of any ulterior motive, which you might believe,
if you had been declared brain dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I call, maybe I could con them out of it if I wanted to
spend the time. If a newspaper calls up they can get it easier.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 1520EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
