<SLUG> BC-WINDOWS-MAINTENANCE0810-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Routine maintenance is a must to keep windows in good shape
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - My house has aluminum siding that's in decent
shape, so I don't have to paint the exterior walls. But that
doesn't mean I escape entirely; owners of brick-, aluminum- and
vinyl-covered houses still need to attend to window frames.
</P>
<P>
   Whether your windows have wood, vinyl or aluminum frames,
routine maintenance will help keep them working well.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional wooden windows, when properly maintained, are
good-looking and functional, and they can be good insulators when
used in pairs to create a dead air space in-between.
</P>
<P>
   Wooden windows, though, are vulnerable to water damage and must
be protected with paint or some other surface sealant. Inspect
windows inside and out at least once a year to check for
deterioration or mechanical problems.
</P>
<P>
   The claylike glazing used to hold glass in the frame should be
supple and moist. Dried, cracked glazing should be removed and
replaced. Deteriorated glazing can allow moisture to enter the
window frame.
</P>
<P>
   Check the paint on frames outside the house. If the paint is
cracked or peeling or if pigment comes off when you rub a finger
over the surface, the window should be repainted.
</P>
<P>
   Wash the surface with a rag or a soft-bristled brush and a
cleaning agent such as TSP (trisodium phosphate), which can be
found in most home-improvement and paint stores. Rinse with clean
water and allow the surface to dry completely.
</P>
<P>
   Scrape off any remaining loose paint and sand the rough edges
with medium-grit sandpaper. If your sanding has exposed any bare
wood, you'll need to prime the surface with an oil-based primer.
</P>
<P>
   Use a good-quality acrylic-latex exterior trim paint to repaint
the frame.
</P>
<P>
   A common problem with inside wooden window frames is that they
are sometimes painted shut. A film of paint between the sash, the
part of the window that goes up and down, and its track locks the
window in place.
</P>
<P>
   To correct that situation, cut through the paint film along the
sash with a utility knife or a paint zipper, a specialty tool found
in paint and hardware stores. Move a block of wood along both edges
of the sash and tap it lightly with a hammer to break the seal.
</P>
<P>
   Remember both the top and bottom sashes should be able to move,
so you should unseal both.
</P>
<P>
   If the windows stick just a little, check the inside of the
track where the sashes move. Sometimes scraping away any stray
paint you find in the track will help. Wrapping sandpaper around a
small block and using it to smooth the inside of the track can be
effective.
</P>
<P>
   If the window is warped, you might have to remove and reposition
the stop, the strip of wood that forms the front border of the
window's track.
</P>
<P>
   To keep the window operating smoothly, occasionally rub a little
candle wax in the track.
</P>
<P>
   Nonwooden windows aren't as vulnerable to water as wooden
windows, but they do accumulate dirt and must be kept clean and
lubricated.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the sashes can be removed by depressing the butmake
them more airtight. The type of weatherstripping varies with the
type of window you have, but remember that felt and pliable rubber
usually last longer than foam rubber, and metal usually lasts
longer than plastic.
</P>
<P>
   While you're working on your windows, assess their security. Are
the latches sturdy and in proper working order? How easy would it
be to force open your sliding windows?
</P>
<P>
   Consider key locks for windows easily accessible from the
ground. You might even want to think about security bars. Remember
that if you install security bars on your windows, you won't be
able to use the windows to escape in a fire or other emergency
unless the security bars can be opened from the inside.
</P>
<P>
   To improve the security of a wooden, double-hung window, add a
simple pin lock. With the window closed and locked, drill a pilot
hole at a slight downward angle through the top of the front sash
into the bottom of the back sash. Slip a metal pin _ a hefty nail
or scr
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
