<HEADLINE>
WHAT GENS X AND WHY WANT IN A PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release August 9, 2000.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's TRENDS-NEXTGEN column. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of TRENDS-NEXTGEN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By JANE RINZLER BUCKINGHAM  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  FALL
<TEXT>
<P>
   As today's politicians discuss the future of America at the
Republican and Democratic presidential conventions, they probably
should wonder what the future of America thinks of them. The good
news is that while Xers and Boomers may have written off the
political process, today's teens are taking a downright
pro-government stance.
</P>
<P>
   My company, Youth Intelligence, recently surveyed 300
trendsetters (young people who we know to be bellwethers for the
rest of the teen population) and 750 nationally representative
14-30 year-olds. We found that only 4 percent considered the state
of politics to be the biggest issue facing their generation. Drugs,
violence and education topped the list.
</P>
<P>
   And according to a CBS study of the class of 2000 due to be
published this year, 91 percent of graduating seniors believe the
government has a positive impact on the country and on their lives
compared with only 80 percent of the class of '97. In the same
study, 41 percent said they can trust the government most of the
time and 52 percent said some of the time.
</P>
<P>
   So what changed? Well, don't expect the Class of 2000 to be out
on the hustings with buttons and banners. Although they are indeed
more optimistic, they are hardly naive. Today's teens have lived
through political scandal and potential impeachment, but they have
also enjoyed a great economy, a welcoming labor market and little
conflict. And how can they fault a president's infidelities when
they may have experienced the same in their own lives?
</P>
<P>
   As one 15-year-old in Austin, Texas explained, ``Hey,
politicians are humans, right? Of course they are screwed up. I
feel sorry for my parents because I think they thought that
politicians were like gods or something. The way I look at it, I
just want a guy who will keep the country in good shape and not get
us blown up.''
</P>
<P>
   This may be why, among the nationally representative 14-30
year-olds we surveyed, Bill Clinton topped a list of public figures
that ``are just really cool.'' (He was beaten only by Michael
Jordan). As one 16-year-old in Detroit said, ``The way I see it, if
that guy can get out of the mess he was in with (Monica), you know
he'll be able to keep us out of any war.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it may well be that this time of economic prosperity has
significantly affected young people's outlook. More than 40 percent
of the 300 trendsetters we surveyed in April think the economy will
improve over the next year, and as long as that stands, they don't
seem too concerned about who occupies the chair in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   But what may also be driving these teens' pro-government
mind-set may be an underlying cry for stability. Today's teens
don't want to rebel against the government. Instead, they want the
government to offer some safety and security in a world that often
seems to be spinning out of control. As one 14-year-old in Los
Angeles explained, ``I guess I want to believe they know what
they're doing. I mean sometimes the world is just nuts and you've
gotta believe that someone's in charge.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be this hope that influences their presidential choices.
In our April survey, respondents were split down the middle over
whether they would prefer Al Gore or George Bush. But no matter who
they chose, the themes were the same:they expected their candidate
would help regain control and make sure nothing truly bad happened.
Our respondents did not seem to be voting on issues so much as hope
and confidence that their guy wouldn't screw up.
</P>
<P>
   Young people seem to want a hero who can help right some of the
wrongs we continue to face. Yet they realize heroes are not
flawless. Teens know that a good politician might make an awful
husband. That's OK, so long as he keeps the country out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is this teen generation may not be looking for
presidential timber only in the traditional places. In the CBS
poll, 65 percent of students surveyed stated that the United States
is ready for a woman president, while in 1999 only 48 percent of
all adults in the United States would have agreed. Although no
question was asked about a non-Caucasian candidate, my guess is the
answers would have been similar.
</P>
<P>
   As you watch this election and as politicians start planning for
2004, remember that by then, many of these teens will be able to
vote.
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
<P>
   HERE TODAY
</P>
<P>
   1980s style
</P>
<P>
   Go-peds
</P>
<P>
   Bowling bags
</P>
<P>
   COMING TOMORROW
</P>
<P>
   1940s style
</P>
<P>
   Collapsible bikes
</P>
<P>
   Doctor bags
</P>
<P>
   Jane Rinzler Buckingham is the president of Youth Intelligence,
a market-research firm specializing in the 7- to 35-year-old
market. Her company publishes the Cassandra Report, a comprehensive
survey focused on identifying emerging trends among Generations X
and Why?
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
