<HEADER>
A6834 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-CIRCUS-FUTURE-1000(2T     08-09 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIRCUS-FUTURE-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH ROOTS IN 19TH CENTURY, CIRCUS IS STILL THE `GREATEST SHOW ON
EARTH'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By WAYNE LEE GAY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Was P.T. Barnum talking about the popularity of the
circus that bears his name when he said, ``There's a sucker born
every minute?'' Or is there another reason _ a rite of passage,
perhaps _ that explains why year after year, in cities across
America, parents and grandparents lead wide-eyed children to
arenas, convention centers and big tops to watch a form of
entertainment that might be considered passe?
</P>
<P>
   The circus, with its roots in the late 19th century, flourishes
even as society _ with all its bells and whistles _ prepares for a
new millennium. Crowds still get goose bumps watching the high-wire
acts, the daring young men and women on the flying trapeze, the
parade of elephants, the animal trainers, and don't forget the
clowns.
</P>
<P>
   It is ironic that the more things change in this world of
high-tech show business, the more the circus stands apart and
retains its unique appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll survive, because of the same reasons it has in the
past,'' says Joe McKennon, a circus historian in a telephone
interview. ``Circus acts don't work anyplace else.''
</P>
<P>
   The most famous circus of all, of course, is the Ringling Bros.
and Barnum &AMP; Bailey show. Its popularity still transcends
generations and its audience is still composed largely of families.
They've come to see the self-proclaimed ``Greatest Show on Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Some tykes may nod off in the arms of their parents or be more
interested in their cotton candy as the night wears on, but
audiences still marvel at acts they've seen over and over before.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen elephants kneel and march in unison; horses dance and
kitty-cats perform wire acts with birds. A confident animal trainer
beams at the crowd while directing tigers by the cage-load; poodles
jump through hoops and over hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   And let's not forget the human element. The exuberant audience
encourages a trapeze artist who misses four attempts to connect
with his fellow artist and falls unceremoniously into a net before
he finally succeeds. Imagine the reception for Troy Aikman if he
threw four interceptions in a game?
</P>
<P>
   But there are subtle signs that the circus is evolving, too. A
female animal trainer belts out a Broadway-style song, accompanied
by the live combo that has replaced the traditional calliope; the
ringmaster mixes a little of yesterday and today _ singing songs
and also introducing acts with oldtime bravado: ``Never before
performed on the planet.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when scores of independent circuses
crisscrossed the country, stopping in small towns as well as big
cities. In small backwater places, the circus had a special appeal,
appearing quite glamorous and adventurous to people who earned a
living in a labor-intensive agrarian society.
</P>
<P>
   ``In its golden age, when the circus came to town, all the
businesses closed, the schools closed,'' says New Jersey-based
social commentator and circus historian Ernest Albrecht.''It was
the one day when you could see that sort of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaudeville has disappeared, replaced by television and the
pop-rock entertainment acts. The exploits of semi-pro teams became
less attractive to fans enticed by the mega-bucks major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   But the circus survived, making its rounds of the country,
finding a niche in the post-industrial, market-driven economy.
There are a number of touring and permanent circuses, although Feld
Entertainment, the owners and presenters of the Ringling Bros. and
Barnum &AMP; Bailey touring show, Disney on Ice and Siegfried and Roy,
dominates the circus industry, with an average revenue flow in the
neighborhood of half a billion dollars annually.
</P>
<P>
   Two equally large units of the Ringling Bros. circus _ each
transported from city to city in a mile-long train _ tour the
country for 45-48 weeks every year, visiting approximately 90
cities.
</P>
<P>
   Although the circus remains economically viable, its survival in
America is strengthened by the unflinching loyalty of the
performers.
</P>
<P>
   The circus has ``always been my life,'' says Catherine
Hanneford, a 31-year-old animal trainer who also sings and acts as
a master of ceremonies at the pre-show, interactive sessions.
Hannefords have been in the circus since the 17th century in
England. Catherine's parents have retired from touring and operate
the non-touring Hanneford Family Circus in Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   Catherine is married to a circus performer _ Hungarian-born
acrobat Aklos Feher. She was discovered by the Feld organization
while performing at the Hanneford circus, and returns to work there
during the few off-weeks enjoyed by the Ringling Bros. show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Circus is a family tradition,'' says Hanneford, who envisions
continuing success for the art form.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not staying in the past,'' she says, pointing out its
relevance in the age of family values. ``The circus is the last
place left to take children for live entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   At one time, a person almost had to be born into a circus family
to work there; nowadays, outsiders enter the profession via
organized training programs. Mark David, who is 39, a lean,
athletic 5 feet 11 inches tall and 145 pounds, grew up in Baraboo,
Wis., one of the traditional winter quarters for the circus. Thus,
he was close to circus families from childhood. David, who is the
son of a gymnast, started studying the art of trapeze when he was 8
and began performing professionally at 13 with a smaller touring
circus. His act _ which features him hanging upside-down by his
heels from a swing _ dates back 60 years.
</P>
<P>
   As with other circus acts, David's is not without the occasional
injury.
</P>
<P>
   And like with any athletic career, injuries, as well as age, can
take a toll and determine a performer's longevity. ``There's always
an element of danger,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   David's worst injury has been a broken finger, but he says a
close friend was killed while performing.
</P>
<P>
   Still, other career options ``never entered my mind,'' he says.
``For sure I couldn't be in an office.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in the early days of the circus, the high-wire acts and
trapeze artists are working with nets. Still, for animal trainers
and daredevils such as J.P. Theron, the element of danger remains
very real. Theron, 44, is billed as ``the human comet.'' He wears a
skin-tight costume that is set on fire before he dives 42 feet into
a large, inflated mattress.
</P>
<P>
   Theron is married to a former aerial artist who is wardrobe
mistress for the circus. They have two children. He has worked at
circus jobs ranging from clown to rigger before a slight weight
gain (he is still a trim 195 pounds on a 6-feet-2-inch frame)
forced him to abandon an aerial act he had developed. Theron also
was born into a circus family and made his debut when he was 4
years old as a last-minute replacement for a short adult who wore a
clown costume.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard the audience roaring in laughter, I was hooked,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   As for the potential for disaster that is built into his act,
Theron smiles and acknowledges that this is part of the appeal of
the circus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants to see an accident,'' he says. ``But nobody wants
to miss one, either.''
</P>
<P>
   But while audiences may accept the chances humans take,
historian Albrecht sees a looming challenge on the horizon for the
circus from the animal rights movement. The circus has come under
frequent attack for keeping animals in captivity and training them
for difficult, unnatural stunts.
</P>
<P>
   The circus industry is taking activists seriously. The Feld
public-relations campaign includes press kits explaining and
vigorously defending the company's treatment and use of animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Circus people will have to decide whether to face that sort of
thing, or, as Cirque du Soleil has done, to tour without animals,''
Albrecht says, referring to the upscale, adult-targeted
Montreal-based touring organization that has been one of the
surprising success stories of the entertainment industry in the
past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition of animal-rights activists, plus the growing
expense and difficulty of transporting animals, may lead more
circuses to tour without animals. But would that eventually signal
the beginning of the end of the circus as generations of Americans
have come to know it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Where else can you see 15 elephants?'' Mark David says.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the circus were to disappear tomorrow, it would leave
its imprint on society. From phrases such as ``three-ring circus''
to describe any complicated, confusing scenario, to the common
recurrence of clowns as a dream symbol, to references in
literature, music and the fine arts, the circus is eternal. Italian
filmmaker Federico Fellini, American composer Charles Ives _ and
even the shy poet Emily Dickinson _ were fascinated by the color,
and sometimes the dark underside of the circus; volumes have been
written on the underlying meaning of the circus and its appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Dickinson summed it up best, in fourteen poetic words:
``Friday I tasted life. It was a vast morsel. A circus passed the
house.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
