800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FROM THE INDEPENDENT OF LONDON: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVED TUESDAY, 8 AUGUST: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DUBYA'S DADDY ADMITS `I WENT TOO FAR' IN THREATENING CLINTON &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRASH-TALK-PRESIDENTS-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former U.S. President George Bush conceded that he
went too far last week in threatening to say just what he thought
of his successor, Bill Clinton, ``as a human being and a person,''
if Clinton persisted with personalized attacks on his son. ``I made
a mistake,'' Bush told Time magazine. The former president's threat
raised eyebrows on two counts. Not only would any attack on Clinton
breach the convention that former presidents do not attack
incumbent presidents; it also sent the message that George W. Bush
was a ``Daddy's boy,'' incapable of fighting his own battles....By
Mary Dejevsky, The Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (475 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VICE PRESIDENCY: NO LONGER JUST A `PITCHER OF WARM SPIT' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VEEP-SWEEPSTAKES-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If you wonder why Dick Cheney and Joseph Lieberman
these days grin as though they have drawn the best tickets in the
great sweepstakes of American political life, the answer is simple.
They have. Forget the jokes about the office they are competing
for, and study the statistics: get elected vice president and
you've got a 50 percent chance of winning the top job one day. And
in an age when the workload of the president _ simultaneously head
of state and head of government of a country whose power is unique
in history _ grows ever larger, the vice presidency matters as
never before....By Rupert Cornwell, The Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (850 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IT'S LIBERAL, IT'S JEWISH _ IT'S TINSELTOWN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIEBERMAN-HOLLYWOOD-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Jewish groups across the country Tuesday hailed
the choice of Senator Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut as Al Gore's
number two as a bold decision, one they hope will sweep away any
remaining misgivings about the place of Jews in the mainstream of
American life. One of the highest concentrations of influential
Jewish Americans is to be found in Hollywood, whose celebrity
firepower can have enormous sway over political races. But Senator
Lieberman raises mixed feelings in the entertainment industry
because of a series of attacks on the moral values of film,
television and video games, and proposed restrictive legislation.
Nonetheless, many political observers believe that liberal
Hollywood has nowhere other than the Gore-Lieberman ticket to
turn....By Andrew Gumbel, The Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (825 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVED MONDAY, 7 AUGUST: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BARNUM AND BAILEY MEETS GEORGE ORWELL: THE GOP CONVENTION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GOP-CIRCUS-ORWELL-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ As the balloons descended into the air at three
minutes before eleven on Thursday night, the music struck up and
the fireworks went off to acclaim George W. Bush, the party's
candidate, it was hard to think of the Republican National
Convention in Philadelphia as anything but the Greatest Show On
Earth. But there was another side of the week, the hidden face of
the Republican machine which designed and steered every second,
every minute, every smile and whoop. A GOP convention is about
political control: it is Barnum and Bailey meets George
Orwell....By Andrew Marshall, The Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (875 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW DIFFERENT HOUSTON 1992 WAS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOUSTON92-PHILLY00-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ How different last week was from the last occasion
when a Bush accepted the presidential nomination of the Republican
Party. Whereas George W. Bush took a double digit lead into
Philadelphia, his father arrived in Houston in 1992 running 17
points behind Bill Clinton in the polls and the mean-spirited,
divisive gathering which followed was never really going to change
things....By Rupert Cornwell, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (400 words) &QL; 
