u e BC-TEAMSTERS-MOVIES-BOS &LR;      08-09 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEAMSTERS-MOVIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAMSTER WOES DETAILED NATIONWIDE BY FILMMAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH RANALLI AND SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Allegations of strong-arm tactics, mob ties, and favoritism in
Boston Teamsters' dealings with the movie industry _ currently
being probed by a federal grand jury _ have been variously
described as disturbing and overblown.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing they apparently are not, according to union
officials, is unique.
</P>
<P>
   An examination of Teamsters locals across the country reveals
widespread problems with those who deal with movie and television
productions, resulting in the suspension and firing of union
officials and even criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, for example, a powerful member of Local 25 has
allegedly intimidated movie officials into renting equipment from a
company he runs on the side. In Honolulu last year, a local
Teamster was convicted of torching trailers belonging to a rival
rental company.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, disgruntled rank-and-file union members say that
lucrative film and TV work goes to a select group of members, many
of whom have criminal records and ties to organized crime. Similar
allegations have dogged local union officials in Florida, Texas,
and Illinois, contributing to their locals being taken over the
international union.
</P>
<P>
   The reason problems are so rampant in the Teamsters' dealings
with the movie industry, specialists say, is that the glamorous and
cushy jobs are often used to curry loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   Those who get the jobs remain loyal in order to keep them;
others, hopeful to one day make it onto the coveted movie lists,
are cowed into silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a closed system that feeds on itself,'' said one
local member of Teamsters For a Democratic Union, the reform
faction of the 1.5 million-member union. ``It becomes a retro-power
center in the local and it is only natural for that to connect with
corruption and organized crime.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 1997 report to Congress, the Independent Review Board, a
government-appointed watchdog group established as part of a civil
settlement between the Teamsters and the Justice Department,
apparently agreed.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Teamsters Local 714 in Chicago, review board
investigation found that nepotism and favoritism were the guiding
criteria for assigning the best work controlled by the local.
</P>
<P>
   Control of that work _ the movie and trade-show business _
contributed to control of the 10,000-member local by members of one
family, the review board report said. In fact, the board found that
there hadn't been a contested election for a union office since at
least 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Other locals have had similar troubles, including Local 390 in
Miami, which was placed into trusteeship by the international in
1996 due to alleged ``nepotism'' in the assigning of jobs on film
and TV shoots. The previous year, the president of Local 79 in
Tampa was suspended for giving jobs to family members and friends.
</P>
<P>
   In Dallas, meanwhile, the IRB recommended putting Local 745 into
trusteeship after finding that the premium work under the local's
control was assigned on the basis of nepotism and favoritism. The
IRB also found that top organized crime figures from the Midwest
had infiltrated the union.
</P>
<P>
   Several members of the Teamster local in Rhode Island with
criminal backgrounds or ties to organized crime have landed jobs as
drivers on major film productions in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   According to sources, at least four such members of Teamster
Local 251 in Providence have been working on the set of ``Osmosis
Jones,'' a movie by the Farrelly brothers being shot in the
Plymouth area.
</P>
<P>
   They include Anthony Parrillo, who was paroled in 1993 after
serving 16 years in the manslaughter death of two men. He was also
a member of the Teamster crew that worked on the Farrelly
production last year, ``Me, Myself and Irene,'' according to
documents.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, other sources say that Ronnie Carter, also a member
of Teamster Local 251 in Providence whose criminal record includes
arrests for assault with a dangerous weapon, drunk driving and
possession of cocaine, has also worked on movie productions filmed
in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who helped establish the Rhode Island chapter of the
Hells Angels, is one of several men with ties to the motorcycle
gang or to organized crime who are caught up in an investigation of
the Teamster Local 251 by Rhode Island authorities. The other two
Teamsters from Local 251 in Providence who have worked on the
``Osmosis Jones'' set are: Danny Allen, a close associate of
Parrillo's who has been under investigation by Rhode Island
authorites for allegedly fencing stolen property, and Jeff
Chakoian, whose late brother had ties to the Patriarca crime
family.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1997 interview with Ch. 12, WPRI-TV in Providence, Stuart
Mundy, president of Local 251, defended the practice of giving the
highly-paid positions of film crew drivers to individuals with
criminal records. Parrillo was assigned based on his work record,
not his criminal record, Mundy said.
</P>
<P>
   Mundy did not return phone calls Tuesday. George Cashman,
president of Local 25 in Boston, also did not return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   However, a source familiar with the ``Osmosis Jones'' production
said that said that the four from the Providence local were among
more than two dozen drivers who had been hired to work on the movie
by Robert Martini, the Teamsters transportation coordinator on the
set. The others were all members of Local 25 in Boston, the source
said.
</P>
<P>
   Martini had been pleased with Parrillo's work on last year's
movie by the Farrelly brothers, which was shot in Rhode Island,
Massachusetts and Vermont, and sought him out again this summer,
the source said. He was unable to explain how the other three
members of Local 251 had gained their jobs on the set.
</P>
<P>
   The source also said that because another major Hollywood
production is being filmed in Boston, ``What's the Worst That Could
Happen?'', there is currently a shortage of qualified Teamsters to
work on movie productions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Stephen Kurkjian of the Globe staff contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
