<HEADER>
A6879 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-N     08-09 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE SHOPPER: THE INS AND OUTS OF THE ONLINE CD MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  (Circuits) 
 By MATTHEW MIRAPAUL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trading in your compact discs can be a humiliating experience.
As you stand at the counter, trying to recover some cash for a
musical experiment gone awry or a summer hit that started to sound
silly in the fall, you often learn that your $16.98 investment is
now worth a couple of bucks _ or nothing at all.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Grundy, president and a founder of Spun.com, a used-CD shop
on the Web, knows the feeling. ``I've walked into stores with a
stack of 10 CDs and they're like, `I'll take these two,''' Grundy
said.
</P>
<P>
   By selling discs on the Internet, he said, online customers can
avoid ``the clerk with a pierced nose who laughs at you and seems
to be saying, `You bought this?'''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not ashamed to admit that my large, eclectic collection
consists mainly of previously owned titles acquired at local shops.
But in recent months, I've started buying most of my used CDs over
the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Used CDs can provide a cost-effective alternative for those who
feel new disc prices are too high but are uncomfortable with the
intangibility and questionable legality of free song downloads
through sites like Napster.
</P>
<P>
   The online selection at sites like Spun.com, SecondSpin.com and
smaller operations like UsedMusicExchange.com tended to be better
than what I found at the neighborhood stores, and because I rarely
rush to pick up a new release, I'm willing to wait until a CD comes
available.
</P>
<P>
   Buying used CDs online is no different from buying new discs:
Search for the CDs you want, toss them in a virtual shopping cart
and pay with your credit card.
</P>
<P>
   Some online stores also sell new CDs and used movies and
computer games. Several sites augment album entries with song lists
and audio clips, but to make sure I am getting the latest reissue
(the one with all the bonus tracks) and a sufficient price break, I
usually open another browser window and crosscheck the entries
against those on sites that sell new CDs. This method is reliable
but not fail-safe.
</P>
<P>
   A disc of Debussy piano music that arrived last week from
Spun.com was a live recording from a performance in Italy instead
of the major-label classic that I expected. The company will pay
for the return.
</P>
<P>
   I conducted an informal check of five used-CD sites by shopping
for six popular but slightly dated releases _ ``Play'' by Moby,
``Supernatural'' by Carlos Santana, ``On How Life Is'' by Macy
Gray, ``Fly'' by the Dixie Chicks, ``Human Clay'' by Creed and
``Appalachian Journey'' by Yo Yo Ma, Edgar Meyer and Mark O'Connor
_ and found the potential savings to be considerable.
</P>
<P>
   Buying the same discs new, at discounted prices, from Amazon.com
would cost $71.94. Including shipping and handling fees, the lowest
total would have been $49.44, from SecondSpin.com for the used CDs.
</P>
<P>
   I have rarely received a defective disc, only two of the 150
I've ordered in two years, and all the used-CD sites guarantee
their merchandise. But availability can be an issue, if not an
outright disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Spun.com was the only site with all six discs in stock, for
$53.94. Most of the sites had half the titles on hand, and
SecondSpin.com had one. But inventories changed daily, and several
sites offered a notification feature that sent an e-mail message
when a desired title arrived.
</P>
<P>
   I also tested the stores with five obscure titles, including
``Too Tired to Sleep'' by Dirk Hamilton and ``Bricolage'' by Amon
Tobin, and five just-released titles, including ``The Marshall
Mathers LP'' by Eminem and ``Anarchy'' by Busta Rhymes. Once again,
Spun.com's shelves were full when the others were empty. Grundy
said used copies of current titles usually sell quickly.
</P>
<P>
   So much for buying CDs, what about selling. Like everyone else,
I have acquired my share of turkeys. And as I discovered last week,
using the Internet to trade discs can be more complicated than
buying them. Determining the value of your castoff discs required
some effort, and it might take several weeks to receive
compensation in cash or virtual credit.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was there any guarantee that your undesirable CDs would be
accepted. When I asked Todd Ramcke, general manager of
UsedMusicExchange.com in Glendale, Calif., via an e-mail message
how much he would pay for a Mahler symphony and another disc of
classical music, he replied, ``Sorry, but both of the CDs you want
to trade us are of no value to us. Try SecondSpin.com.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in cyberspace, my rejects had been cruelly rejected. In a
subsequent phone interview, Ramcke apologetically confessed,
``Classical stuff we just don't sell at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Grundy said most Spun.com customers sell discs at the same time
they buy. The company sends a postage-paid mailer for trade-in
discs along with the order. SwapIt.com ships a postage-paid
container when you register online, or you can print out a mailing
label from its site.
</P>
<P>
   SecondSpin.com and the CD Exchange (www.thecdexchange.com)
require you to pay the freight, although the CD Exchange lets you
cut costs by keeping the jewel-box containers.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to trade-ins, online stores can be just as picky
as real-world shops. The discs are expected to be playable, and the
cover and liner notes must be intact. Recordable CDs are out, as
are designated as being for promotional purposes. (CashForCDs.com
buys promo copies.) SecondSpin.com deducts 50 cents for cracked or
broken cases.
</P>
<P>
   Determining the value of trade-ins takes work. The CD Exchange
lets you type in a list of discs and returns a quote, but most
sites ask you to search for titles and add them to a trade-in cart.
When a title can't be found, you can sometimes use the number on a
disc's universal product code.
</P>
<P>
   I also sought trade-in quotes for a half-dozen discs, a mix of
mainstream and offbeat titles. Despite my best efforts, I had
trouble getting prices for the nonhit CDs _ or they weren't
accepted at all.
</P>
<P>
   Of the sites that would take all six discs, Spun.com and
SwapIt.com offered the best deals: about $30. Except for Spun.com,
which offered an immediate credit, the others asked me to send in
the CDs, whose value would be verified, and then would send a check
or issue a credit, a process that generally takes two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   For comparison, I took the same six discs to the local branch of
Djangos, a national chain store that sells used CDs but does not
accept trade-ins through its Web site (www.djangomusic.com). The
clerk examined the CDs and offered me $13. He was overruled by a
manager who was monitoring the transaction and upped the offer to
$18 in cash or $24 in store credit.
</P>
<P>
   I could do better online, so I turned down the offer. The clerk
looked puzzled, and maybe a little hurt. But I'll still shop there.
I found a musical cast recording of ``Babes in Arms'' for just
$7.95.
</P>
<P>
   What a steal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
