r e BC-TV-BUGS-TEX     08-09 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BUGS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV VIEWERS ARE BUGGED BY `BUGS'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scene from a ``Saturday Night Live'' skit:
</P>
<P>
   Actors Tim Meadows, Cheri Oteri, Will Ferrell and Fort Worth's
own Bill Paxton play newscasters trying to deliver the evening
headlines _ only they can't, because as the newscast progresses,
more and more graphics pop up on the screen, obscuring them.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the skit, the four are clawing at the screen and
desperately jumping around, trying to peer out from behind the
barrage of TV logos, sports scores, weather forecasts and financial
stats that have taken over the screen.
</P>
<P>
   The skit, ``Newsforce,'' aired more than a year ago, in January
1999, but the point is even more valid now: You simply cannot watch
a sports channel, a news broadcast or, in some cases, a movie
without being inundated with ancillary information.
</P>
<P>
   Most TV and cable networks run their logos _ called ``bugs'' _
in one of the four screen corners throughout every show. Top that
with the sports scores or weather advisories that constantly zoom
across the bottom of the screen, which are known as ``tickers.''
</P>
<P>
   Pile onto that a graphic heralding Emmy nominations for the show
you're watching and teasers for which show is coming on next or
what's going to be on the news later.
</P>
<P>
   It was enough to make Robert Carlock pen the ``Saturday Night
Live'' skit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like they're throwing information at you just for the
sake of throwing information at you,'' the SNL writer and producer
says, speaking by phone from New York. ``It's an overload. I'm
watching CNBC right now and I can't tell what's going on, there's
so much stuff on my screen.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlock's got a point: Specialty networks, such as news stations
CNN and Headline News and financial network CNBC, try to cram an
especially enormous amount of information onto your screen, from
sports scores to stock quotes.
</P>
<P>
   But Paul Capelli, vice president of public relations for CNBC,
says that's why people watch such stations _ they want the
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have viewers, we have users,'' Capelli says of the
network's recently upgraded ticker, which delivers up-to-the-second
stock trade information. ``It allows the individual to act on
information that's current, that's live. We're making information
available to individuals, and they can act on it and make money
from it. They love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike McCarley, communications director for the NBC Olympics,
says that on-screen information, such as network bugs, is necessary
in today's hundred-channel TV universe.
</P>
<P>
   ``One, it identifies the station, obviously, and if you're
traveling a lot, you'll know the affiliate,'' he says. ``And it
also helps deter piracy. Someone may be going around selling
videotapes of some movie, then there's our logo at the bottom of
the screen, so you know they taped it.''
</P>
<P>
   The logos, McCarley adds, also help people remember the network.
And the better the logo, the more likely you are to remember it.
NBC's striking Olympics logo is a peacock engulfed by Olympic
rings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The peacock is one of the most recognizable brands in the
U.S.,'' he says. ``And the Olympic rings are one of the most
sought-after brands in the world. You're not going to forget that
logo.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just news shows that are being plagued by
information overload. VH1 and Fox Movie Network run specialty shows
_ Pop Up Videos and Production Notes Presents _ in which music
videos and theatrical movies are cluttered with ``pop-up''
factoids, such as ``This was so-and-so's directorial debut,'' ``The
day of the shoot, Madonna had a cold'' and ``Can you spot the
up-and-comer in this cluster of nobodies?''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Hall, vice president of programming and production for Fox
Movie Channel, defends Production Notes Presents, saying the
station is simply trying to put an interesting, informative spin on
the movies it shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our equivalent to a DVD or director's cut,'' Hall says,
referring to the ``extras'' many DVD movie releases include. ``We
present you with all the information you could ever want about that
particular movie. It gives viewers an insight into the filmmaking
process. But it's just a handful of films we're doing it with, and
we only do it about once a month.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall says all the movies that are shown on Production Notes
Presents are also shown in their original, uncut, uncluttered forms
at other times.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time that he defends Production Notes Presents, Hall
also acknowledges that the bombardment of secondary information is
veering out of control and that some viewers aren't happy about it.
That's why, he says, Fox Movie Channel tries to keep its station
IDs as low-key as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bug is far less obtrusive than standard network bugs
because it's not on during the whole movie,'' he says. ``ABC's or
NBC's are there for the whole film. With our films, we try to
replicate the moviegoing experience as much as we can. We try to be
as unobtrusive as possible. I can't say that about everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
