<DOCNO> NYT20000809.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6885 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SHAKESPEARE-HISTORIES     08-09 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAKESPEARE-HISTORIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT STRATFORD, A MARATHON OF 15TH CENTURY ENGLISH HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STRATFORD-ON-AVON, England _ Facing one of the most demanding
theatrical challenges imaginable, William Houston has stopped
smoking and drinking and eats steak for lunch. His obsession is so
complete that he hardly noticed when a steak was brought to his
table one day recently, letting it sit for half an hour before
taking a bite.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is killing me,'' Houston lamented. ``I'm so dog-tired.
Living like this is driving me crazy. I'm into it every hour of the
day, and then I dream about it at night. Every day I think, `I
can't do this, I'm not up to this, I'm not physically strong
enough, I can't carry it off.' I look in the mirror and see myself
aging.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally noticing the plate in front of him, he sighed, tossed
the mangled napkin onto the table and tried to calm himself. ``All
right, all right, we'll get it,'' he said, seemingly to himself.
``Little stressed out these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston is a crucial figure in an extraordinary marathon that is
unfolding on the stages of the Royal Shakespeare Company here. Over
the next year the company will present, in chronological order,
eight history plays in which Shakespeare depicts the upheaval of
15th-century England. The plays contain some of his finest poetry,
deepest insights and most memorable characters.
</P>
<P>
   Because the plays cover closely related historical events,
seeing them together is an incomparably richer experience than
seeing them individually. It is also a rare one, having been
attempted less than a half-dozen times on the British stage.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the fascination of the current series is that many roles
are carried from one play to the next by the same actors. Houston
appears as the wild Prince Hal in the first part of ``Henry IV,''
drinking, wenching and stealing purses. In the second part he
portrays the prince as he assumes the throne, pledging that he has
``turned away my former self.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston is also rehearsing the title role of ``Henry V,'' the
warrior king who inspires his nation by conquering France and
setting an example of noble leadership. He must play the character
over a period of more than two decades, growing t in years, wisdom
and dignity. To add to the challenge, the first two plays are
performed in period costume while the third, which is to have its
premiere on Aug. 24, has a different director and is done in a
modern post-apocalyptic setting.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, 32, has played just one title role with the Royal
Shakespeare Company, the relatively straightforward male lead in
``Troilus and Cressida.''
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare's eight-play sequence covers a period of 87 years.
The first play, ``Richard II,'' opens in 1398 with the king
adjudicating a dispute between two of his nobles, one of whom,
Henry Bolingbroke, will overthrow him.
</P>
<P>
   The series continues with both parts of ``Henry IV,'' which show
Bolingbroke reigning as a troubled monarch, then dying and leaving
his throne to Hal; ``Henry V,'' in which Hal rules brilliantly; and
the three parts of ``Henry VI,'' depicting England's collapse into
civil war. It ends with ``Richard III,'' whose title character
rises to power by killing his closest friends and relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The last scene of ``Richard III'' depicts the king's death in
battle as he calls in vain for a horse. Bosworth Field, where the
battle was fought in 1485, is 40 miles from Stratford. A plaque
marks the spot where Richard fell.
</P>
<P>
   After the Stratford season ends in October, the first of the
history plays will move to London. The series will continue into
next year. There is no plan for a full-fledged foreign tour,
although the company will perform the last four plays at the
University of Michigan on two successive weekends next March.
</P>
<P>
   To succeed, the first plays of the series need much more than a
gifted actor as Hal. The role of Bolingbroke needs at least an
equal talent, and for that the Royal Shakespeare Company has chosen
one of its veterans, David Troughton. He portrays Bolingbroke first
as an offended knight, then as a scheming politician who deposes a
king, and finally as a dying monarch who fears God will never
forgive him for the ``indirect crook'd ways I met this crown.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``A play's relevance to the modern day, no matter how old the
play is, will come out,'' Troughton said before one recent
performance. ``It was just so brilliant that as we were preparing
this play, a bunch of British football hooligans were arrested in
France. It shows what the plays are telling us, which is that we
are a nation of thugs. We are very good at beating people up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Patriotism and jingoism is what moves this country,'' he said.
``When Bolingbroke dies, he tells his son to `busy giddy minds with
foreign quarrels.'' Troughton sees contemporary parallels like the
war in the Falklands. He likens Bolingbroke to Prime Minister Tony
Blair, ``because he's so desperate to be liked and knows every
trick to use to become liked.''
</P>
<P>
   Troughton and others involved in the project do not see its
importance as limited to Britain. In the lobby of one of the
Stratford theaters they are displaying a notebook full of material
they used to prepare themselves. It includes historical accounts
and a newspaper article portraying Blair as obsessed with his
image, but also articles about slaughter in Africa and photographs
of 20th-century strongmen ranging from Franco to Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The two parts of ``Henry IV'' are classics not just because of
the ways they deal with great historical and political themes, or
even because of their magnificent verse. They are also the works
that brought to life one of the great comic figures in theatrical
history, the bloated Falstaff, ``that trunk of humors, that
bolting-hutch of beastliness, that swollen parcel of dropsies, that
huge bombard of sack, that stuffed cloak-bag of guts, that roasted
Manningtree ox with the pudding in his belly.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the attraction of the plays is that they cover vast
ground, from city to country, battlefield to council chamber, royal
palace to taverns and brothels, and that their characters are not
only contending nobles but also drunkards, braggarts, pickpockets
and whores. Without Falstaff the plays would be all but
unthinkable, and in the current Stratford productions Falstaff is
played by Desmond Barrit, who established a reputation as a great
comic actor with his successes as Malvolio in ``Twelfth Night'' and
Bottom in ``A Midsummer Night's Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The great thing for me and for everyone in these plays is that
you have so much time to develop your character,'' Barrit said as
he sipped tea on a balcony overlooking the Avon River. ``You
needn't show too much at once. Not only do you have a chance to
decide what you want to hold back for the second scene, you can
even hold things back for the second play.''
</P>
<P>
   As with the actors who play Bolingbroke and Prince Hal, Barrit
finds himself merging with his character more fully than many
actors do when they perform in single plays. After some
performances he turns up at a pub down the street from the theater,
and there he seems almost as riveting a figure as Falstaff was in
the taverns of Eastcheap.
</P>
<P>
   The two personalities even merge onstage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prince Charles is the patron of our company, and Henry IV is
his favorite play,'' Barrit said with a Falstaffian glimmer in his
eye. ``He came to one of our first performances, and at the point
where Falstaff says he hopes to become a duke or an earl, I stared
right at him. Later I realized I was doing just what Falstaff did.
I was looking at the future king of England and saying I hoped the
knighthood would be pending.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
