<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6896 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-OLDER-AMERICANS10-COX     08-09 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLDER-AMERICANS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STATISTICAL PORTRAIT SHOWS THE ELDERLY'S LOT IMPROVING
 &HT;    With OLDER-DATA.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Americans are living longer, healthier and
wealthier than ever before, but there are wide disparities based on
age, race and sex, according to a federal report released
Thursday.(cq)
</P>
<P>
   The 128-page report, which compiles data from more than a dozen
federal agencies, is the first in a series that will track 31 key
indicators of the nation's elderly population.
</P>
<P>
   The report paints a graphic picture of a growing, thriving and
increasingly more ethnically diverse population of Americans aged
65 and older. It also pinpoints areas where the elderly have not
fared well.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really are two stories here,'' said Richard Suzman, an
associate director at the National Institute on Aging. ``One is how
much progress there has been in a variety of areas: life
expectancy, health, disability, reduction of poverty, increase in
eduction ... juxtaposed with the fact that not everyone has shared
equally in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   The size and share of the elderly population is growing
dramatically, and the aging of the baby boom generation born
between 1946 and 1964 will accelerate the trend.
</P>
<P>
   There are 10 times more elderly Americans at the turn of the
21st century than there were at the turn of the 20th, and the
number will double again to about 70 million by 2030.
</P>
<P>
   A child born in 1900 had a life expectancy of about 49 years,
while a child born in 1997 had a life expectancy of more than 76
years. In both cases, the figure is higher for females than males.
</P>
<P>
   Americans over 85 are the fast-growing segment of the
population, and are expected to increase from 1.6 percent of the
nation now to about 4.8 percent by 2050.
</P>
<P>
   Financially, the elderly are better off today than ever. Only
10.5 percent live in poverty, compared to 35 percent 40 years ago.
The median net worth of a family headed by an elderly person
increased about 70 percent from 1984 to 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Older Americans are healthier, and can expect to live longer
once they reach age 65 than their predecessors. A 65-year-old today
can expect to live another 18 years. In 1900, a 65-year-old had a
life expectancy of another 12 years. The percentage of older
Americans with disabilities dropped from 24 percent to 21 percent
between 1982 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Socially, most older Americans reported being active in contacts
with friends, family and organizations. But about one-third
reported a sedentary lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the oldest of the elderly pay more for health
care than those near 65. In 1996, the average health care
expenditure _ out-of-pocket and insured _ was $5,864 for those 65
to 69, and $16,465 for those 85 and older.
</P>
<P>
   Today's elderly are far better schooled than those of a half
century ago. In 1950, less than 18 percent of the elderly had
graduated from high school, and less than 4 percent from college.
In 1998, about 67 percent were high school graduates and 15 percent
were college graduates.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, minorities and women have not done as well on most
indicators of well-being as the overall elderly population. As the
elderly population becomes more diverse, these trends will grow in
importance.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, about 84 percent of the elderly are non-Hispanic
white, 8 percent are black, and 6 percent are Hispanic. The
remaining roughly 2 percent are Asian and Pacific Islanders,
American Indians or Alaska natives.
</P>
<P>
   By 2050, whites will make up about 64 percent of the elderly
population, Hispanics 16 percent, blacks 12 percent and Asians and
Pacific Islanders will be 7 percent. The remaining less than 1
percent will be American Indians or Alaska natives.
</P>
<P>
   Women and minorities have not shared the financial success of
older men. In 1998, roughly 7 percent of elderly men lived in
poverty, compared with 13 percent of women. Among white men and
women, 8 percent lived in poverty, compared with 21 percent for
Hispanics and 26 percent for blacks.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest ol
</P>
</TEXT>
