<HEADLINE>
THE WORLD IS A RADIO, AND THERE'S NO `OFF' BUTTON
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROBERT PHILPOT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Along Fifth Street in downtown Fort Worth, rows of restaurants
compete for the lunch and going-out crowds. Let's listen for a
second.
</P>
<P>
   At Reata, we hear old western tunes like ``Red River Valley''
and Marty Robbins' ``El Paso,'' which fit in with the restaurant's
cowboy decor. At the Pour House, a burgers-and-nachos sports bar,
Jewel's plaintive ballad ``You Were Meant for Me'' plays. Lionel
Richie fills the room at Schlotzky's, a quickie sandwich joint.
</P>
<P>
   The Corner Bakery is broadcasting its music outside, where all
but the rhythm track of a smooth-jazz composition gets lost in the
air. Across the street at Chili's, Phil Vassar's country song
``Carlene'' is having better luck being heard out on the street. At
Picchi-Pacchi, a pizza-by-the-slice eatery, soft-oldies station
Memories 96.7 plays. Next door at a Subway sandwich shop, generic
hip-hop competes with the noisy lunchtime crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The world has become a radio, and walking through places like
downtown Fort Worth is like hitting its scan button. It's virtually
impossible to walk into a restaurant, grocery store, clothing
store, hair salon or movie theater these days without hearing some
form of piped-in music. And not everyone's happy about it.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Griffith, a Fort Worth lawyer, is one of the people who'd
like to turn that radio off. ``I'm not alone in that it bothers
me,'' Griffith says. ``Recently at a grocery store, I had to leave
because the music was getting to me. Part of it might be the type
of music that they're playing. It's very distracting, and they may
be losing sales by distracting the customer. You might forget an
item or two that you came in for.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffith certainly isn't alone, but he does seem to be in the
minority. Music has become so much a part of our lives that, unless
it's played too loud, we might not even be aware of it when we're
going about our daily activities. And unlike Griffith, some people
enjoy the incidental music, either because it resurrects old
favorites or because it introduces them to music that they might
not otherwise hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes over well,'' says Eric Tschetter, owner of the Pour
House, which subscribes to a satellite system with several
channels; Tschetter prefers to play Top 40 at night and relatively
older music during the lunch-hour rush. ``I get a lot of comments
on it. A lot of people are very excited to hear songs from the '70s
and '80s because (the songs) remind them of something in their
past.'' Tschetter says that he receives few complaints about the
music, and when he does, it's usually a request to turn the music
down or to change a channel if it's been on a while. And the
employees, he says, have no gripes about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a change for them,'' says Tschetter, who prefers the
'70s stuff himself. ``It's something they don't listen to in their
car or at home.''
</P>
<P>
   The music isn't there to entertain, however; it's there to get
you to buy, or to linger long enough to have dessert. Marketing
researchers believe that it succeeds in that mission more often
than it alienates customers. How it does it is up for debate.
</P>
<P>
   But first, a little history: The granddaddy of all the piped-in
services is Muzak, which was founded by Gen. George Squier in the
early '20s (Squier came up with the name by combining ``music''
with ``Kodak''). Muzak earned its tag as ``elevator music'' _ which
it has long since transcended _ because it was originally used to
calm nervous riders of early elevators. William Benton, who took
over Muzak in 1939, began supplying music to the workplace, saying
that it increased morale and productivity. MORE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   By the '80s, Muzak was using direct-broadcast satellite to
deliver its product, and it entered into an agreement with
Seattle-based Yesco. Muzak provided background music, or
rerecordings of songs, while Yesco delivered ``foreground'' music _
compilations of current hits, offered via satellite or by cassette.
Muzak has about 500 cassette programs and 60 satellite channels.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not your father's Muzak. Don't think of it as some
anonymous orchestra desecrating the Beatles' ``Eleanor Rigby''
while you're getting your teeth cleaned. It's often more hip than
what you hear on the radio, and you might not even be aware that
what you're hearing is Muzak.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do this for some of the most unique and diverse brand names
in the world,'' says Kenny Kahn, vice president of marketing for
Muzak. ``We do this for everyone from J.C. Penney to Sally Beauty
Supply to companies right in your back yard. We do this for Armani
and Donna Karan, we do this for Gap and Old Navy and Banana
Republic, and we do this for Yahoo! and Microsoft on their hold
lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Kahn says that Muzak's products serve more than 100 million
people a day, and are in more than 300,000 stores and restaurants.
Muzak and other incidental-music services are so ubiquitous,
they've inspired a number of marketing studies, and conclusions
seem to be even more numerous and varied than the studies. Most
seem to agree that the music has a profound effect on customers;
they just don't agree on what that effect is.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are pretty bummed out by the shopping experience,''
says Barbara Caplan, a partner in Yankelovich Partners, a
marketing-research and consulting firm based in Norwalk, Conn.
``Music may blur or blunt the anger and frustration that they have
when they can't find what they want or can't find someone to take
their order.''
</P>
<P>
   Or _ according to another market-researcher, James Kellaris, an
assistant professor of marketing at the University of Cincinnati _
it can blur or blunt the realization that they've been in a store a
long time. Kellaris is interested in the influence of music on time
perception, and believes that if customers like what they hear,
their sense of time shrinks and the experience becomes more
pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   ``What fascinates me are the effects of music that are not
immediately obvious to consumers,'' Kellaris says. ``Not only is
there this temporal distortion, but music tends to lower our sales
resistance. Your brain can only process so much information at a
time, and if part of your brain is engaged in processing music,
that diminishes the capacity to resist sales influence.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it can influence consumers in another way _ it can make
them interested in the music itself. Some retailers, including
Starbucks and Pottery Barn, not only program their own music, but
have created a spinoff business by marketing their own compilation
CDs. And although a portion of the buying public wishes that
retailers would tune out and shut up, enough people are attracted
by it that the CD programs have been successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, the response has been overwhelmingly positive,''
says Chris Gimbl, a spokesman for Seattle-based Starbucks. ``We
actually created the in-store program in 1995. We had a ton of
customers asking where they could get the music we were playing. So
we began creating the CDs in response. The first CD was done in
conjunction with (mainstream jazz label) Blue Note Records, and it
was a phenomenal success.''
</P>
<P>
   Gimbl says that what you hear piped in to Starbucks is meant to
be in sync with customers' moods. As a result, Starbucks'
programming can even appeal to foes of background music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you go into a place like Starbucks with something
different in mind, which is to relax over a cup of coffee,'' says
John Giordano, the former music director of the Fort Worth
Symphony. ``The nature of a place like that is that you're much
more aware of what you're hearing than in a place like Foley's, and
the music is part of the experience.''
</P>
<P>
   But like Griffith, Giordano prefers to have some control over
what he hears. And most incidental music annoys him _ even music he
likes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem I have with background music is the nature
of the music that's played is often so insidious and insipid that
it's like a Chinese water torture,'' Giordano says. ``That's
predominantly in shopping centers, department stores, those kinds
of places. But restaurants often play some form of classical music.
On the one hand, I appreciate that they're playing it to provide
some form of ambience, and that they're playing good music. But I
can't stand having classical music in the background because I
start listening to it. My attention becomes drawn to it, and it
distracts me from my thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Giordano says, there's enough noise in this world.
During a phone chat, he ticks off the sounds that he hears: his air
conditioner buzzing, his refrigerator humming, outdoor sounds
creeping in. He doesn't even like using classical music in the
background at home; if he listens, he listens actively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like silence,'' he says. ``I feel silence is very
refreshing. There are so many ambient sounds in our society, there
are few places you can go to find silence.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffith agrees, but what annoys him more is his lack of choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing you can do,'' he says. ``You can't turn it
off. Any time you're put in a situation where you can't stop the
noise, it's aggravating. I guess you could put on earmuffs all the
time to shut it out, but you shouldn't have to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
