<HEADER>
A6900 &Cx1f; tie-z
* u &Cx14;  6 &LR;      08-09 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN(2TAKES7 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
6  )-NYT8  
 (  ATTN9: N.C.)  
 PC10 101: PITFALLS TO AVOID 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CIR-TEACHING-SOFTWARE 11 , CIR-DORMS-COMPUTERS 12 ,
CIR-HIGHSCHOOL-GADGETS 13 ) 
 (Circuits)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Students in the freshman class of 2000 were born at the same
time as the original IBM &UR; 14 &LR;  PC &UR; 10 &LR; . They have never known a world
without microprocessors. They grew up with cable TV and Nintendo,
learned to program the VCR &UR; 15 &LR;  before they could ride a bike,
became virtuosos with call-waiting and three-way conference calling
and took for granted answering machines, microwave ovens, audio
CDs &UR; 16C &LR; , pagers, fax machines and cell phones. They came of age
with the Internet and the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Now they are heading off to college, where they will be immersed
in technology more deeply than at any time of their young lives.
</P>
<P>
   As if to prove that the cosmos has a sense of humor, we, their
technologically befuddled parents, are supposed to choose a
computer for these children of the technology age as they head off
to school. Here are some data points that may help.
</P>
<P>
   Nine out of 10 college students will be connected to the
Internet when school starts in a few weeks, according to Jupiter
Communications, a research firm. By the time this year's freshmen
are seniors, the number will rise to 95 percent, Jupiter says.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers are actually a bit low compared with those at the
University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, where every one of the
estimated 3,500 freshmen will be required to own a laptop &UR; 17 &LR; 
computer this fall.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina is unusual in both the size and ambition of its
computer program for new students, but the reasons behind its
laptop &UR; 17 &LR;  initiative could be instructive for any parent or
student who is thinking about computing strategies for the coming
school year.
</P>
<P>
   As in years past, this column strongly advises that all new
students check first with the admissions office to find out about
the school's computer recommendations. Doing so can save money,
time and frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with North Carolina's decision to require students
to have not just any computer, but specifically a laptop &UR; 17 &LR;  or
notebook computer.
</P>
<P>
   Laptop &UR; 17 &LR;  computers are more expensive, less powerful, less
versatile and easier to damage and lose than desktop computers. So
why did North Carolina decide to require students to go mobile?
</P>
<P>
   ``Desktops &UR; 18 &LR;  are dead, but nobody has taken their pulse
lately,'' said Marian Moore, vice chancellor for information
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Moore said the university decided two years ago to begin the
transition to mobile computing on its campuses. ``We are absolutely
positioned to drive local wireless networks into the classrooms,
the public areas on campus, the dining halls and out into open
areas, because we know every student will have a laptop &UR; 17 &LR; ,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Going to a wireless campus gives faculty and administrators
greater flexibility in using classroom space, costs less than
trying to string wires through old buildings and enables students _
virtually the only people on campus who do not have their own
offices _ to work wherever they are, either inside or while sitting
under a tree.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina is just beginning to develop its wireless network
and does not yet require students to have wireless modems for their
laptops &UR; 19 &LR; . Moving the entire student body to laptops &UR; 19 &LR;  is the
first step in the transition to campuswide &UR; 20 &LR;  wireless networking.
</P>
<P>
   Just as mobile phones are overtaking wired phones, mobile
computers will eventually overtake desktop computers for all but
specialized tasks. But wired networks are not dead yet. They will
always offer higher connection speeds than wireless networks, which
is important for such important college tasks as collaborating on
engineering projects and downloading bootleg MP3 &UR; 21 &LR;  music files.
Until wireless networks are fully deployed on campus, the
laptops &UR; 19 &LR;  can tap into the wired networks through a standard
Ethernet &UR; 22 &LR;  adapter card.
</P>
<P>
   According to Moore, 85 percent of the new students will buy
their laptops &UR; 19 &LR;  through the school. Because it buys so many
computers, North Carolina was able to negotiate substantial
discounts, as much as $800 less than the best prices available on
the Internet. (To minimize profiteering &UR; 23 &LR;  through reselling &UR; 24 &LR; ,
students and faculty can buy only one computer each year.)
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the manufacturer was IBM &UR; 14 &LR; , which makes the
highly regarded and highly priced ThinkPad &UR; 25C &LR;  line of notebooks.
There are less expensive laptops &UR; 19 &LR;  on the market, but North
Carolina decided to go for the best machines available.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get what you pay for,'' Moore said. ``If you're going to
make the purchase, purchase something that will last.''
</P>
<P>
   Because North Carolina has adopted only two models _ the
ThinkPad &UR; 25C &LR;  600X &UR; 26 &LR;  and ThinkPad &UR; 25C &LR;  820M &UR; 27 &LR;  laptops &UR; 19 &LR;  _ as
its standard, it can offer expedited repair, replacement parts and
loaner services right on campus. Students can rarely afford to be
without a computer for a week or more, and the standardization
allows the school to minimize downtime.
</P>
<P>
   To help make sure the computer does not drop out before the
student graduates, the discounted price at North Carolina includes
a four-year service and repair warranty, a one-year insurance
policy against damage or theft, a cable lock for securely tethering
the laptop &UR; 17 &LR;  to desks or other hard-to-move objects and a basic
package of software.
</P>
<P>
   Extended warranties are even more important for laptop &UR; 17 &LR; 
computers than they are for desktop machines. If the laptop &UR; 17 &LR; 
screen is damaged, it can cost almost as much to repair as the cost
of a new machine.
</P>
<P>
   Some homeowner insurance policies will cover the loss or theft
of a child's laptop &UR; 17 &LR;  at college, but many will not. Supplemental
coverage can be added. Or consider, as North Carolina chose to do,
a company like Safeware &UR; 28 &LR;  (www &UR; 29 &LR; .safeware.com), which
specializes in coverage of computers.
</P>
<P>
   Kensington &UR; 30 &LR;  makes my favorite locking security cable for
laptops &UR; 19 &LR;  (about $40). Targus &UR; 31 &LR;  (www &UR; 29 &LR; .targus.com) has a
motion-sensing notebook alarm device called the Defcon &UR; 32 &LR;  1 ($50)
that shrieks louder than Marilyn Manson when somebody tries to
steal a laptop &UR; 17 &LR;  or backpack.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
