<SLUG> BC-MA-DOGFISH-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOGFIGHT BREWING BETWEEN US REGULATORS, BAY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (In 4th graf, corrects name of judge who rejected fishermen's
challenge of the rules.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH DALEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With beady eyes, venomous spines, and a habit of biting
chunks out of living whales, the spiny dogfish was, for decades, a
trash fish _ so hated that fishermen routinely poisoned or
dynamited them.
</P>
<P>
   But like a prom queen picked from a crowd of wallflowers, the
3-foot-long shark has undergone a popularity boost in the last
decade, feeding the seemingly bottomless British appetite for fish
and chips.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in yet another sign of how heavily fished the Atlantic has
become, the lowly dogfish is at the center of one of the country's
nastiest water wars. A US District Court judge in Boston has ruled
that fishermen must severely restrict their catches, setting up a
showdown between the federal government and Massachusetts, the
nation's leading dogfishing state.
</P>
<P>
   Federal managers say the dogfish can't reproduce fast enough to
keep up with all the fishing and imposed limits on dogfishing in
all federal waters. Judge Edward F. Harrington two weeks ago
rejected the fishermen's challenge of the rules, clearing the way
for a crackdown that will hit hard in Massachusetts ports such as
Scituate, where dogfish are the top catch.
</P>
<P>
   But fishermen have vowed to appeal and Massachusetts officials
declared that, despite the court case, they plan on bucking the
limits in state waters, which extend to 3 nautical miles, with a
quota that is 11 times higher. In most cases, states closely follow
federal guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned about overfishing too . . . and we understand
this is a highly controversial issue,'' said David Pierce, acting
assistant director for the state Division of Marine Fisheries.
``But we can rebuild and continuously harvest.''
</P>
<P>
   This month, a Massachusetts delegation will meet with other
Atlantic states to hash out how much dogfish should be harvested in
state waters.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, dogfish lovers complain of a cascading problem.
First, the seemingly endless supply of cod was exhausted. Then
scallops. Fishermen soon developed markets for so-called ``trash
fish,'' such as monkfish and dogfish, that had grown so plentiful
in part because they had been ignored. Now, even these more obscure
beasts are facing collapse. Next, say ocean specialists, could be
the skate _ a delicacy in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many stocks are in bad shape,'' said Anthony Chatwin,
marine scientist at the Conservation Law Foundation, an
environmental advocacy group. According to a federal report issued
last October, New England had at least 16 stocks that were
overfished. ``Fishing stocks have been managed for years without a
vision or a strategic plan,'' said Chatwin.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, there never was any plan for dogfish, which used to
illicit only groans from fishermen. Traveling in packs of
thousands, the brown and slate-gray fish would go after precious
cod and herring _ and virtually anything else: worms, lobster, and
even algae. Their name _ along with aliases skittledog, cod shark,
and thorndog _ comes from that voracious and all-encompasing
appetite.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the infamous fish have been bestowed with a
kinder name in an effort to improve its image: Cape shark.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, fishermen began chasing the dogfish as cod became
scarce. Now, roughly 55 percent of the 49 million pounds of dogfish
catches that land in the United States comes from Massachusetts.
There are three processing plants in the state, and in Plymouth,
spiny dogfish account for 96 percent of all fish landings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very important industry in Massachusetts and
elsewhere,'' said Harvey Mickelson, attorney for the American
Dogfish Association. The group plans to appeal the federal
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stocks are at an all-time high,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fishery experts counter that the number of sexually mature
females has dropped. The gestation period for dogfish is unusually
long _ 22-24 months _ so killing off adult females could cause
serious problems in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Although the fight is far from over, fishermen say they find
themselves in a familiar situation: wondering if there is another
species out there, like the dogfish, that will keep them in
business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
