<HEADER>
A6905 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-ABORTION-0810-     08-09 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ABORTION-0810-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICO'S FOX ON HOT SEAT OVER NEW STATE LAW PUNISHING RAPE
VICTIMS WHO SEEK ABORTIONS
 &HT;    (700&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ After a euphoric July victory based on pluralism
and moderation, some members of Mexican President-elect Vicente
Fox's conservative party have come under attack for hardening their
stance on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in an unanticipated move, members of Fox's National
Action Party, or PAN, in his home state of Guanajuato voted to
amend the state's criminal code to include jail time for women who
seek abortions after being raped.
</P>
<P>
   The action provoked an immediate nationwide outcry by other
political parties, women's groups and political commentators.
</P>
<P>
   One newspaper cartoon showed a brutal caveman dragging a woman
by the hair, with the disembodied voice of a priest saying ``Bless
you, my son,'' as a hand sprinkled holy water over the rapist.
</P>
<P>
   Some top members of Fox's party at the national level were
stunned by their colleagues' decision in Guanajuato, and also
issued statements saying they disagreed with the action. A movement
is afoot by the PAN's opposition to reverse the initiative either
though another vote, or a veto by the current PAN governor, who
appears ambivalent about the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Fox is a devout Catholic, who, like many PAN members, doesn't
believe in abortion, which is illegal in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox has promised repeatedly to build a government of
pluralistic ideology drawing from the left to the right when he
takes office Dec. 1. He overcame accusations of being too
religious, and won the July election here with ample support from
more liberal voters who wanted to end 71 years of one-party rule by
the Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the Guanajuato action, Fox said he has no
intention of encouraging federal or state bans on abortion in the
case of rape. He called the dispute in Guanajuato a local matter.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the PAN's federal congressional representatives and
a future senator also weighed in. ``It seems unnecessary to get
into this polemic right now, and I do not agree with the reform
that was done,'' said Carlos Medina Plascencia, who is also a
former PAN governor of Guanajuato.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents of the new law in Guanajuato said they fear others
in the PAN, which captured more state and federal congressional
seats in the last election, will pursue similar amendments on
abortion. And they say that the party and Fox have suffered damage
in the court of public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess all rapists should now come to Guanajuato. This will
be the only state in Mexico that doesn't protect victims of rape,''
said Marta Lucia Micher, a member of that state's legislature who
belongs to the leftist Democratic Revolutionary Party, the PRD.
</P>
<P>
   Micher and others are vowing to reverse the law, which won by
one vote on Aug. 3. If it stands, the law will be enacted on Oct. 1
and allow for between six months and three years in jail for women
who terminate a pregnancy even if they have been raped.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an added pressure on Fox he probably didn't count
on,'' said political analyst Joel Estudillo of the Mexican
Institute of Political Studies. ``He might be pressured to clarify
his position on this more. The national PAN could also be under
pressure if some sort of initiative on this reaches the federal
congressional level.''
</P>
<P>
   Women's groups that have been trying to liberalize abortion law
in Mexico gathered in Guanajuato to protest the recent amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The mother of a 13-year-old girl Paulina Ramirez, who was raped
and gave birth to a baby this year in a widely publicized case, has
also made an appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez lives in Baja California, a state dominated by the PAN.
Her mother charged that pro-life state authorities there confronted
and effectively blocked her daughter from having an abortion after
the rape.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of Mexico's other main political parties
anajuato, the PRD and the PRI, are mustering forces to try to
reverse the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think women should be punished after being raped,''
said Guanajuato PRI legislator Ruben Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, both sides of the argument introduced rival
proposals for either overturning or modifying the new law.
</P>
<P>
   The state PAN representatives were apparently called to Mexico
City to consult with an angry national leadership on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Armando Gomez, one of the state's PAN legislators, said he and
others in the state PAN based their amendment on the party's
platform, which includes ``the right to life.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the local party ``doesn't want to go back'' on its
position, but is willing to consider a range of opinions during
more debate and consider ways to avoid punishing women.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that PAN members have divergent views on what
the right to life means. The party, he added, has been flooded with
comments from citizens for and against the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've received calls from people who said they were the
product of a rape and are thankful for being born,'' Gomez said,
calling it a ``scientific fact'' that life begins at conception.
</P>
<P>
   ``A woman who has been raped has to accept that this has
happened and can't be reversed,'' he said. ``But there should be
all the help and support possible offered to her so she can get
over her pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Micher, the PRD legislator, said she and other women are
prepared to go on a hunger strike to protest the law if it is not
overturned.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents may also consider filing constitutional challenges in
Mexico's Supreme Court or with the Organization of American States,
which has a commission that reviews and sanctions human rights
abuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the PAN passed this, they told us, 'This is our
doctrine,''' Micher said. ``Come on! I'm Catholic, too. But this is
about the legal rights of women.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss' e-mail address is: susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
