<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-DELASOUL10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trio's best days are behind them
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bow your heads in respect, longtime rap fans. It's finally
happened: The hip-hop world has caught up to De La Soul. Dave,
Posdnuos and Maseo set a new standard on using samples and smart
lyrics way back in 1989 on their debut, ``3 Feet High and Rising.''
It was a remarkable precedent the band built upon with its next
three albums.
</P>
<P>
   Musically, this moves with characteristic ease from the
turntable scratch of the early '80s (``Squat'') to the Latino
infusion of today (``The Art of Getting Jumped''). But lyrically,
De La Soul has started to copy other rap acts. Hmmm. ... Puff Daddy
and Mase are dancing around in shiny suits in the ``Mo Money/Mo
Problems'' video _ oh, about two albums ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now the formerly gentle trio that was deemed rap's hippies are
teaming up with the loud (rapper Busta Rhymes on ``I.C. Y'all'')
and the profane ( rappers Xzibit and Tash &AMP; J-Ro of Tha Liks on
``My Writes''); making for a strange blend. Clearly De La Soul
isn't dead _ as they wryly declared on their 1991 CD. They've just
shown themselves to be less than we thought they were.
</P>
<P>
   ``Art Official Intelligence: Mosaic Thump''
</P>
<P>
   De La Soul. Tommy Boy. 17 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on De La Soul and Tommy Boy Records:
www.spitkicker.com and www.tommyboy.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
