<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESSERTS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bonbons are most definitely good
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Picking deep red cherries from the produce bin is a fleeting
delight of summer and one that's hard to improve upon _ except with
chocolate. If you love chocolate-covered cherries, you'll want to
try the cookie counterpart, a new recipe from the Northwest Cherry
Growers. For more recipes, see www.nwcherries.com.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Cherry Bonbon Cookies
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 48
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: about 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 12-14 minutes per cookie sheet
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup unsweetened cocoa
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup soft butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   1cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1large egg
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2teaspoons vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2teaspoons cherry flavoring, cherry liqueur or amaretto
</P>
<P>
   48sweet fresh cherries, pitted and drained on paper towels
</P>
<P>
   1(6-ounce) package semisweet chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup sweetened condensed milk
</P>
<P>
   Combine flour and cocoa in small bowl and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, beat butter, sugar and baking powder with
electric mixer until blended. Add egg and flavorings and beat until
well-combined. Gradually beat in flour mixture. Shape dough into
1-inch balls; place 1/2 inch apart on ungreased baking sheet. Press
down center of each ball with thumb to create a small hollow; fill
each center with a cherry.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In a small pan over very low heat, combine chocolate chips and
condensed milk; heat until chocolate is melted, stirring
occasionally, about 6 to 7 minutes. Spoon about 1 teaspoon of the
chocolate mixture over each cherry, spreading with the tip of a
knife or your finger to cover the cherry.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 12 to 14 minutes or until set. Remove to wire racks to cool
completely.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 85 calories, 1 gram protein, 4 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 41), 12 grams carbohydrates, 8 milligrams
cholesterol, 53 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   TRY THIS
</P>
<P>
   Cherry pitting. We're not the only ones who admire Acme's simple
plastic pitter (at left in photo) with the cute red cherry on the
side ($4.99). Lechter's at North Point Mall is discontinuing the
fine, Italian-made stainless steel pitter from Pedrini that costs
more than twice as much, in favor of the scissorlike model, made in
China. Even children find it works easily. It's dishwasher safe,
and when cherries are out of season, you can put it to work on
olives.
</P>
<P>
   _ Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
