r d BC-DINNER-SCHOOL10-COX     08-09 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINNER-SCHOOL10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Help us cook up ideas to make homemade family meals happen
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back-to-school time means back to busy schedules for many
families (though I know summer no longer means slow). Many will be
adjusting to new schedules, activities and adventures.
</P>
<P>
   But one old challenge is likely to persist: how to make sure
everyone eats a healthy dinner, preferably together and at home.
We've all heard the statistics. On any given day, as many as half
of us will eat one meal or more in a restaurant and another 20
percent will get takeout or delivery, according to the National
Restaurant Association.
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder, since parents are busy juggling jobs, shuffling
kids from one activity to another and tackling Atlanta traffic.
It's only natural to grab and go rather than chop, bake or saute.
</P>
<P>
   But there are a few problems with heavy reliance on eating out:
It can be expensive and unhealthy. And it can rob the family of
important ``home time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were really eating out a lot and found it was costing us
$50 to $100 a week, on top of our groceries,'' reports my friend
and co-worker Kris Jensen. Kris and his wife, Karen, a
schoolteacher, have three children: Melissa, 17; Mark, 15; and
Andrew, 13.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years back, they struck upon a solution to their
problem. They convinced Melissa to prepare weeknight family meals
in exchange for money. Now, she has a job in a department store and
has passed the spatula to Mark. Since he gets home around 3 most
afternoons, he can get a meal prepared by the time his parents get
home. He gets paid $5 for each evening's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives him responsibility, takes the pressure off Karen and
teaches him how to cook,'' says Kris. ``All of my kids can cook to
some degree. I know when they get to college, they'll be able to
feed themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Mark says he enjoys the extra money, which
supports his golf habit. He sits down once a week with Karen to
compare schedules and plan menus. Mark plays trombone in the
marching and concert bands, so he is booked on some afternoons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make a main dish and some sides, but I don't really do
desserts,'' says Mark. ``My sister doesn't like some of the things
I cook, but my brother pretty much likes everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Mark's greatest hits: chicken cacciatore, crunchy baked
chicken and hamburger stroganoff. And he admits that his growing
culinary portfolio sets him apart from many of his peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes up sometimes at school, and everyone is surprised
that I cook,'' Mark said. ``But my friends like it, and some of
them have asked their parents if they can do it to earn some money,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to hear from other families who've come up with
creative ways to prepare weeknight meals at home. Here's one of
Mark's standby recipes to add to your menu options.
</P>
<P>
   crunchy
</P>
<P>
   baked chicken
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 400 degrees. In a bowl, combine 2 cups
crushed cornflakes, 1 tablespoon sesame seeds, 2 teaspoons paprika
and salt and pepper to taste. Next, brush 4 to 6 boneless, skinless
chicken breasts with skim milk (you'll need about 4 tablespoons).
</P>
<P>
   Coat the chicken with the crumb mixture and place on a nonstick
baking pan. Dot the chicken with margarine and bake for 30-45
minutes or until done.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
