A6912 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-GUINNESS-VIDEO10-COX     08-09 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUINNESS-VIDEO10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tired of politics on TV? Try these movies
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sir Alec Guinness, who died last weekend of liver cancer, was
never one of The Triumvirate. As in, the Olivier-Gielgud-Richardson
triumvirate. And somehow that seems fitting.
</P>
<P>
   Guinness was different _ capable of the big classical roles but
more the consummate character actor. He once said, ``As far as I'm
aware, I have no personality of my own whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   He was drawn to films of all sorts _ quirky oddities as well as
epics like ``Lawrence of Arabia'' or ``Dr. Zhivago.'' Of course,
his most famous role was as the Jedi Knight, Obi-Wan Kenobi in
``Star Wars.'' He reportedly got about 2 percent of the profits
from the film, but hated the role so much he convinced George Lucas
to kill off the character. ``I just couldn't go on speaking those
bloody awful, banal lines,'' he said. ``I'd had enough of the mumbo
jumbo.''
</P>
<P>
   He was, quite simply, magnificent and totally unique. Here are
some video suggestions to celebrate his genius.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Bridge On The River Kwai'' (1957): Before ``Star Wars,''
this was the movie with which Guinness was immediately identified.
He plays the stiff-necked senior British officer in a Japanese POW
camp during World War II. He at first resists the demand made by
the camp's equally unyielding commander (Sessue Hayakawa) that his
men help build the titular bridge. But then in a kind of mad
embrace of a colonial we-do-things-best mentality, he becomes
obsessed with seeing the thing built. The character is both hero
and fool, a courageous fanatic who blinds himself to the fact that
he is collaborating with the enemy. He won an Oscar for the part
and it made him an international star. Yet, ironically, he was
director David Lean's third choice; both Charles Laughton and Noel
Coward turned the role down.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Lavender Hill Mob'' (1951): Guinness plays a meek Bank
of England clerk in charge of delivering gold bullion from the
refinery. This seemingly harmless fussbudget teams up with some
crooked cronies and they arrange to steal the gold in order to mold
it into souvenir miniature Eiffel Towers to export to France. The
movie won an Oscar for its clever script, but much of its success
is due to the spirited comic interplay between Guinness and fellow
thief, Stanley Holloway.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Kind Hearts and Coronets'' (1949): This black farce is a
Guinness tour-de-force. Literally. It's the story of an eccentric
English family and an ambitious young man (Dennis Price) who
decides to murder all eight of the relatives standing between him
and the family title. The twist? Guinness plays all eight of them,
including a suffragette named Lady Agatha. The actor later recalled
that initially he was asked to play only four of the victims, but
was so amused by the script that he sent a telegram saying, ``'I
see no point in playing four parts. How about me playing eight?'''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Great Expectations'' (1946): The film that marked both
Guinness's screen debut (not counting an appearance as an extra in
a forgettable something called ``Evensong'') and the beginning of
his long collaboration with Lean. One of the greatest adaptions of
a Dickens' novel _ of any classic book, for that matter _ it's the
tale of an orphan named Pip (played as an adult by John Mills)
whose life is shaped by a mysterious benefactor. Guinness plays
Herbert Pocket, Pip's ut's very good, but when it's bad. ... Ben
Affleck plays an ex-con who poses as his former cell mate in order
to bed babelicious Charlize Theron and gets caught in a nasty mess
with her psycho brother (Gary Sinise), who wants him to help rob a
casino. With John Frankenheimer as the director, the movie is
always watchable, but sometimes it's just plain ludicrous, as if
there were too many hands messing around in post-production. Grade:
C+
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Here On Earth'' (PG-13) _ A limp and clueless variation on
``Love Story.'' Leelee Sobieski, Chris Klein and Josh Hartnett star
as kids in a love triangle. Trapped in this hermetically sealed
setting, with a script that would run 10 minutes if the cliches
were yanked out of it, they can't win. Grade: D+
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Bedrooms &AMP; Hallways'' (unrated) _ A sunny look at a series
of revolving bedroom doors in modern London, Rose Troche's (``Go
Fish'') comedy widens her focus, from Chicago's lesbian dating
scene to a view of sexuality (gay and straight) that's constantly
in flux. Robert Farrar's cheerfully satiric script concerns an
attractive bunch of young people whose love lives reflect the
title: sex experienced as a constant mix of journey and arrival at
a destination. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _SM
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Grandfather'' (PG) _ It's not a good sign when a movie
starts to bore you even before the actors appear, but that's the
effect of the camera's crawl through a drawing room at the start of
this Spanish film. Fernando Fernan-Gomez plays Count Don Rodrigo,
the penniless patriarch of a noble family visiting an estate that
once belonged to the family. It's now owned by former servants,
whose petty treatment of the old man reflects the film's
class-conscious, conservative politics. In Spanish with subtitles.
Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _SM
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For upcoming video release dates:
www.comingsoon.net/videos.htm
</P>
