<HEADER>
A6913 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-MINIS10-COX     08-09 0202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MINIS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CD mini reviews
 &HT;    By Nick Tate
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  FUSION
</P>
<P>
   ``Outbound''
</P>
<P>
   Bela Fleck and the Flecktones. Sony. 16 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   He plays the banjo, and his music has heartland roots. But
nothing on Bela Fleck's captivating new album remotely resembles
the theme from ``The Beverly Hillbillies'' or ``Deliverance.''
Fleck's radical jazz-rock style is as far from chicken-pluck banjo
as John Coltrane's take on ``My Favorite Things'' was from the
original. In his hands, Aaron Copland's ``Hoedown'' morphs into a
jazz-inspired workout. And with such eclectic originals as the
world-party jam ``Shuba Yatra'' and Eastern-tinged ``A Moment So
Close'' (with Shawn Colvin and Jon Anderson), Beck takes obvious
pleasure in blurring the lines with his electric, acoustic and
sitar banjo. ``Outbound'' departs from the live-in-the-studio
approach of past outings, with strings and horns added for color.
But the studio craft never eclipses the spontaneity that drives the
music.
</P>
<P>
   _Nick Tate
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on the Flecktones: www.flecktones.com
</P>
