<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6917 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-BOTTLED-H2O-COX     08-09 1638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOTTLED-H2O-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hip sippers drive growth of water sales
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For some people, it's as necessary as a cell phone. It's right
at home in the cup holders of sport-utility vehicles. And before
you even get to the wine list in an upscale restaurant, you're
likely to be confronted with the choice of still or sparkling, Fiji
Islands or France.
</P>
<P>
   It's bottled water, the elixir of our times. We're willing to
pay as much as 40 cents a glass for it, even though the free stuff
is still flowing from the faucet.
</P>
<P>
   For some, it's simply a matter of taste. Others are drawn to the
convenience of portable water. Some think it's safer than tap. And
yet others simply want to sip with the hip.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started in the business in 1988, the concept of buying
bottled water was fairly foreign,'' said Kevin McClanahan,
president and chief executive officer of Fountainhead Water Co.,
based in Marietta. ``Now it's gone from rare to all the rage. There
are more than 600 brands, and it's the fastest-growing beverage in
the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, overall sales of bottled water jumped about 13
percent from 1998, topping 4 billion gallons in the United States.
Though sales trail soft drinks and beer, bottled water has seen a
59 percent increase from five years ago, according to various
industry reports.
</P>
<P>
   Supermarket News polled grocery stores and found that most are
giving more shelf space to bottled water, and Restaurant Business
has been tracking double-digit annual increases in restaurant sales
of bottled water for the past several years. Restaurants are
finding that having servers suggest one-liter bottles is an easy
way to increase check totals by $5 and up.
</P>
<P>
   At New York's Rainbow Grill, a one-liter bottle of water can set
you back $12. In Atlanta, the going price is around $5 a liter. At
Seeger's, diners don't have a choice; bottled water is the only
kind offered. But at other restaurants such as BluePointe, Nava,
Floataway Cafe and Bacchanalia, servers make a point of offering
bottled or tap.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a lot of people who are fine with tap, who think
it's silly to pay for water,'' said Matt Lutsey, the maitre d' at
BluePointe, which serves Fiji and San Pellegrino bottled waters.
``But other diners don't want plain, ordinary tap water.''
</P>
<P>
   Health concerns
</P>
<P>
   Lynne Gigliotti, chef of Grappa, said bottled water is very
popular at her restaurant. ``I think people are suspicious of how
tap water is filtered, and they don't like the chlorine.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the incidents of contaminated tap water are very rare.
Both tap and bottled water are regulated and must meet limits for
contaminants set by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration and state
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   A recent state audit of Georgia's public water systems found
that 95 percent had no reported violations of federal standards
during the past four years. (Some groups, such as the Center for
Science in the Public Interest, say the rules aren't tough enough.)
Consumer Reports magazine recently tested 39 bottled waters and
seven municipal sources, and all fell within current limits.
</P>
<P>
   Safety aside, health is a concern for bottled-water drinkers,
said Lisa McCue, spokeswoman for the Grocery Manufacturers of
America. And while most of us are well aware that drinking water is
good for us, ``it has never been so accessible before,'' said
McCue, who believes portability is driving the trend. ``It's in
convenience stores, at the gym, at the grocery. And when it comes
to drinking in the car, there's nothing easier.''
</P>
<P>
   McClanahan agrees. ``Consumers are recognizing that every time
they have a bottle of water, that's 8 to 10 ounces less of
caffeine, sugar and preservatives they get in other beverages,'' he
said. ``And the easiest way to get it is to grab a bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   Fighting for attention
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey of Atlantans conducted by Yankelovich Partners
of New York showed convenience (51 percent) as the strongest reason
Atlantans drink bottled water, followed by taste (46 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Reason enough to pay anywhere from 75 cents to $5 for a product
that otherwise is virtually free. And now more than ever, consumers
have their choice of brands. They range from smaller producers such
as Fountainhead, which bottles spring water from a protected source
in North Carolina, to beverage giant Coca-Cola, which bottles
purified municipal water under the name Dasani. And flavored waters
are making a splash, too. (For an explanation of the types of
bottled water, see the glossary below.)
</P>
<P>
   That means bottlers are doing more than ever to get customers'
attention. Labels with cool mountain scenes are big, even if the
water isn't from a mountain source. Pepsi's Aquafina bottles show
mountain peaks on the label, even though the water is purified tap
water. Fountainhead goes with a light blue, ridged plastic bottle
in a tapered shape, to set it apart from clear, smooth plastic
bottles. Ty Nant water from Wales (sold locally at Star Provisions)
offers a cobalt blue glass bottle that's so popular in Britain that
the International Herald Tribune reports many folks refill them
with tap water just to keep the bottles around. Ty Nant reportedly
has red bottles in the works.
</P>
<P>
   But the effort put into the type of bottle isn't all about
looks. The material a bottle is made from can greatly affect the
taste. Water in clear, strong plastic usually tastes better than
water from plastic gallon jugs similar to milk jugs. Glass is most
neutral but least practical.
</P>
<P>
   Bottled water is trickling into vending markets. Pepsi offers
its Aquafina brand in vending machines across from Turner Field,
among other locations. The ever-growing availability means the
upward trend is likely to continue, McCue said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just something not classy about drinking water out of
the tap anymore,'' she said. ``Bottled water looks better, so
refreshing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Find out how much water your body needs daily and other health
facts on www.ajc.com/epaper
</P>
<P>
   /editions/tuesday/living.html
</P>
<P>
   WATER GLOSSARY
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey of Atlantans showed convenience (51 percent) as
the strongest reason Atlantans drink bottled water,
</P>
<P>
   followed by taste (46 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Not all bottled waters are the same, with the key difference
being the source. Here's a breakdown of the types of bottled water.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Spring water _ Comes from an underground formation and must
flow naturally to the earth's surface. Water is collected at the
spring or through a hole that taps the source. The source must be
stated on the label. Spring water is typically protected from
microorganisms sometimes found in surface water. Carbon dioxide can
be added to make it ``sparkling.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mineral water _ Typically spring water. Can be sparkling or
still, but contains at least 250 parts per million of dissolved
solids such as calcium, magnesium, sodium, potassium, silica and
bicarbonates.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Naturally sparkling water _ Usually comes from a spring and is
naturally carbonated; bubbles lost during treatment or collection
may be replaced with the same amount of carbon dioxide the water
held originally.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Purified drinking water _ Comes from any source, usually tap
water, and has been processed by reverse osmosis, distillation
(boiling) or similar procedures that remove minerals and
contaminants. The process can remove fluoride, too. All bottled
waters lack fluoride, so frequent drinkers may need fluoride
supplements, especially children.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Soda water or seltzer _ Not considered bottled water by the
Food and Drug Administration; regulated instead as a soft drink,
under rules that are less strict. Some products have added sugar,
flavors or salts. (Read the label.) They're usually carbonated tap
water, sometimes with extra filtration.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Consumer Reports, August 2000
</P>
<P>
   Resources for learning more about the taste and safety of
drinking water are abundant.
</P>
<P>
   The August issue of Consumer Reports gives the results of their
taste and safety tests of 39 bottled waters. The October, 1999
issue of Consumer Reports reviewed faucet-mounted and carafe water
filters.
</P>
<P>
   The June issue of the Nutrition Action Health Letter, published
by The Center for Science in the Public Interest, (www.cspinet.org)
takes a look at the safety of drinking water. It also include the
following info on how to find out what's in your tap water:
</P>
<P>
   ``The first place to start is with your local public water
utility. Ask for the most recent ``Consumer Confidence Report.''
This report should tell you where your water comes from, whether
it's surface water (from rivers and lakes), ground water (from
underground rivers, streams, etc.) or some mix. It will also tell
you whether your water exceeds the limits for any of the 80
contaminants that are regulated by the Environmental Protection
Agency. You should also ask for a printout of the levels of all 80
contaminants.
</P>
<P>
   If you get your water from a well, you'll need to get it tested
yourself. Call the EPA Safe Drinking Hotline (1-800-426-4791) for
information on how to obtain a list of certified labs.''
</P>
<P>
   For bottled water, check out the website of the International
Bottled Water Association (www.bottledwater.org). This site offers
some of the nitty gritty about bottling, safety and consumption and
it's member companies are open for unannounced inspections by the
NSF International, a water and food safety monitoring company.
Visit www.nsf.org to see their latest reports.
</P>
<P>
   We also like www.bottledwaterweb.com, which gives excellent
direction for staging your own water taste test, based on the
annual Berkeley Springs taste test.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
