<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Summer salads
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Summer is salad season. When heat and humidity put a crimp on
appetites and you don't want to spend a lot of time in the kitchen,
a main dish salad is a healthful, tasty and creative way to get
dinner on the table.
</P>
<P>
   With supermarkets and roadside stands overflowing with
wonderful, fresh produce, summer is also the time to take a
breather from the iceberg lettuce, tomato and cucumber drenched in
bottled dressing.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you think your pantry pickings are spare, chances are
that if you look behind this and under that, you will find the
makings of a knock-out summer salad.
</P>
<P>
   Do you have rice? Some kind of pasta? A potato or some lentils?
Surely your cupboard will yield cans of beans, corn, diced
tomatoes, salmon or tuna.
</P>
<P>
   Now check your freezer. Is it possible you have a couple of
sausages wrapped up in there or _ joy of joys _ maybe some frozen
shrimp?
</P>
<P>
   Now the fridge. Is there a bell pepper, a zucchini, a carrot or
squash hidden in the vegetable bin? Any packages of cheese lying
around?
</P>
<P>
   If you have any of these ingredients, just add a little
creativity and you are on your way to a tasteful, cool and easy
summer meal.
</P>
<P>
   Check out these sites for loads of summer salad ideas.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lundburg Gourmet Brown Rice at
www.lundberg.com/recipes/ssalad.html has put together a number of
salad recipes using rice and other everyday pantry items and
spices. Cumin, cilantro, black beans, corn, peppers, tomatoes and a
mild salsa combine with rice to make a salad with a Southwestern
flair. Sun-dried tomatoes, olives, olive oil, balsamic vinegar,
parmesan cheese, rosemary, basil and lemon juice inspire a
Mediterranean dish.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Surprising color and taste combinations are the order of the
day in a number recipes at Fun Summer Salads at
www.ivillage.com/food/tools/recipe/articles/0,5370,6596,00.html
</P>
<P>
   Your pantry may yield the makings of the unusual Tropical Tomato
Salad that combines diced tomatoes, pineapple, hearts of palm,
green onions, blue cheese and olives _ a combo that goes especially
well with grilled chicken. Other colorful entries include an
unusual combination of blueberries, cherry tomatoes, olive oil and
balsamic vinegar. What about green beans and julienned beets or
sweet potatoes and canned green chilies?
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Some inventive salad recipes using pantry staples such as
canned fish, salmon, tuna and shrimp with summer fruit and veggies,
plus an inspired Asian vinaigrette, are at Summer Salads at
lubbockonline.com/stories/061400/lif061400025.shtml
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tabasco's Sizzling Summer Salads at
www.tabasco.com/html/tastesummer002release.html include Avocado and
Grapefruit Salad With Poppy Seed Dressing, Mediterranean Chicken
Salad, Warm Shrimp and Ham Salad Over Seasonal Greens, Shrimp Louis
Salad, Spicy Spinach Salad, Tuna Cracked Wheat Salad cauliflower
pieces, blanched 2 minutes in boiling water and drained
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup thinly sliced carrots
</P>
<P>
   1 sweet pepper (red, yellow, green, or purple), cored, seeded
and diced
</P>
<P>
   1 green onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound large cooked shrimp, optional
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped fresh dill leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons balsamic or red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon crushed dried oregano leaves
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   In a large mixing bowl, toss together the cooked pasta, snow
peas, cauliflower, carrots, sweet pepper, green onion, shrimp (if
using) and dill until well combined.
</P>
<P>
   To make the dressing: Combine garlic, vinegar, lemon juice,
sugar, oregano, salt and pepper in a food processor or mixing bowl.
While processing or whisking, add water and oil slowly, mif
``Cookwise'' (Morrow, 1997). ``You know things won't get any hotter
than 212 degrees because water evaporates after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Corriher also points out that we wouldn't have bread without
water, because it links the two proteins in gluten. And for many
recipes, water is preferred over stock or wine because it lets the
flavors of the food shine through.
</P>
<P>
   Bittman, in an essay for Amazon.com, points out that a touch of
water can help balance the oil and vinegar in a basic vinaigrette.
If you make the vinaigrette in a blender, water will help create a
creamy consistency. All this with no added fat.
</P>
<P>
   Below are some scrumptious dishes that just couldn't be without
H2O _ an icy raspberry granita, a roasted corn soup, a simple
poached salmon with a bold chimichurri sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Dive in.
</P>
<P>
   RECIPES DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Peaches in Rosemary-
</P>
<P>
   Red Wine Syrup
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   Sweet but subtle, this is a dessert for grown-ups and a
wonderful way to enjoy seasonal peaches. Set a chunk of
Parmigiano-Reggiano on the table for nibbling along with the
wine-soaked fruit.
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chianti or other dry red wine
</P>
<P>
   1 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 3-inch-long sprig fresh rosemary
</P>
<P>
   8 firm but ripe peaches, pitted and cut
</P>
<P>
   in quarters
</P>
<P>
   Combine wine, water and sugar in a small saucepan and bring to a
boil over medium-high heat. Reduce heat to low and simmer until the
mixture is reduced by half, 8 to 10 minutes. Pour the syrup into a
heatproof bowl or measuring cup. Add the rosemary and steep for 5
minutes. Remove the rosemary, cool the syrup to room temperature,
and then refrigerate until cold, about 1 hour, or up to 3 days.
Divide the sliced peaches among four dessert bowls. Pour the syrup
over the fruit and serve. _ From ``Just Add Water'' by Lauren
Chattman (Morrow, $22)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 178 calories, 1 gram protein, no fat, 45 grams
carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 1 milligram sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Acquacotta
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 45-55 minutes
</P>
<P>
   A very old dish from the peasant cuisine, ``cooked water''
perseveres more for its goodness than out of necessity. It's the
essence of simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds ripe tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   4 onions, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   8 fresh mint or basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   6 slices Tuscan or other rustic bread, whole-wheat
</P>
<P>
   if possible, several days old
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Pepper
</P>
<P>
   Grated Parmigiano-Reggiano cheese
</P>
<P>
   Cut the tomatoes in half and squeeze out the seeds. Roughly chop
the tomatoes and place them in a saucepan over medium heat with
barely enough water to cover; bring just to a boil, lower heat to a
simmer and cook until the tomatoes are broken down and the liquid
has begun to thicken, about 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the onions, mint and a pinch of salt, partially cover the
pot and continue to simmer until the ingredients resemble a sauce
of medium consistency, about 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   If the bread is not quite stale, lay the slices on a baking
sheet and place in a 350-degree oven to dry, but not to toast.
Place a slice in each of six soup plates and drizzle the olive oil
over; season with salt and pepper to taste. Adjust the thickness of
the soup if necessary with small amounts of water and ladle over
the bread. Sprinkle cheese over each portion or pass it at the
table. _ From ``Yesterday's Bread'' by Carole Lalli
(HarperPerennial, $12.95)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 223 calories, 5 grams protein, 13 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 51), 25 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 154 milligrams sodium, 4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Grilled Sweet Corn
</P>
<P>
   Soup
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 10 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 45 minutes-1 hour
</P>
<P>
   Grilling time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 1/2 hours
</P>
<P>
   Chef Kevin Taylor of Restaurant Kevin Taylor in Denver insists
that water is key to this delicious, robust soup. Stock would
overwhelm the flavor of the roasted corn. Next time you fire up the
grill, put on some extra corn.
</P>
<P>
   10 ears sweet corn
</P>
<P>
   1 or 2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   5 strips bacon, diced
</P>
<P>
   1 white onion, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 quarts water
</P>
<P>
   1 large chipotle chile (or canned chiles in adobo sauce)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 tablespoons fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   Prepare a hot grill. Lightly coat the ears of corn with the oil,
place on the grill and cook, turning frequently, until most of the
kernels are dark brown. Remove kernels from the cob, cutting close
to the cob so as to remove as much of the starch in the cob as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   In a large Dutch oven or stockpot over medium-high heat, combine
the bacon and onion and cook, stirring constantly, until the bacon
is browned, 10 to 12 minutes. Add cumin and cook for another 1 to 2
minutes. Add the corn, water and chipotle and bring to a boil.
Reduce heat to maintain a slow boil and cook for 1 hour, stirring
occasionally. Puree the soup in batches on high speed of a blender
or in a food processor, and strain through a medium sieve. Season
with salt and lime juice and serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Per cup: 147 calories, 5 grams protein, 4 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 24), 28 grams carbohydrates, 3 milligrams
cholesterol, 1,149 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   CONDIMENT
</P>
<P>
   Sesame Dressing
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 1 cup
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   For many dressings and sauces like this one, the addition of
water while emulsifying can create a creamy appearance and texture
and help balance the flavors.
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons toasted sesame seeds (available pre-toasted in
Asian markets)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup rice wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced fresh ginger, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   (optional)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dark sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   In the work bowl of a food processor or in a blender, combine
sesame seeds, vinegar, ginger (if using), soy sauce, sugar and
water. In a small bowl, combine the vegetable oil and sesame oil.
With the processor motor running, add the combined oils in a thin
stream until well-blended and slightly emulsified.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 68 calories, trace protein, 7 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 96), 1 gram carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 121
milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Raspberry Granita
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15-20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Freezing time: 3 hours, plus 8-24 hours
</P>
<P>
   Nothing quite satisfies like an icy, fruity finish to a summer
porch dinner. Think snow cone for grown-ups.
</P>
<P>
   2 cups fresh raspberries (or frozen unsweetened raspberries,
thawed)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup plus 2 tablespoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   In a food processor fitted with a metal blade or in a blender,
combine raspberries, water and sugar. Puree until smooth. Pour the
puree through a coarse sieve set over a metal bowl to remove the
seeds. Press firmly on the solids with a rubber spatula to extract
as much liquid as possible; discard the solids.
</P>
<P>
   Place the puree in a shallow nonreactive dish in the freezer.
Whisk every 30 minutes, until semi-firm, about 3 hours. Cover and
freeze without stirring until frozen solid, at least 8 or up to 24
hours.
</P>
<P>
   At least 1 hour before serving, place 4 martini glasses or
wineglasses in the freezer.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, using a fork, scrape the surface of the granita to
form ice crystals. Scoop the crystals into the frozen glasses and
serve immediately. _ From ``Ice Creams &AMP; Sorbets,'' Williams-Sonoma
Kitchen Library (Time-Life Books, 1996)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 152 calories, 1 gram protein, no fat, 39 grams
carbohydrates, no cholesterol, trace sodium, 4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Cold Poached Salmon
</P>
<P>
   With Chimichurri Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings, 1 1/2 cups sauce
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15-20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Sitting time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 1-2 hours
</P>
<P>
   There's hardly an easier way to cook salmon. The technique comes
from Lauren Chattman's ``Just Add Water'' (Morrow, $22). The fish
pairs well with many kinds of sauces and condiments. Try a salsa,
pesto or this chimichurri sauce, from Steven Raichlen's ``Barbecue
Bible! Sauces, Rubs and Marinades'' (Workman, $12.95).
</P>
<P>
   Water to cover the salmon fillets in a frying
</P>
<P>
   or saute pan
</P>
<P>
   4 (6-ounce) salmon fillets
</P>
<P>
   1 large bunch fresh flat-leaf parsley, washed,
</P>
<P>
   stemmed and drained
</P>
<P>
   8 cloves garlic, peeled
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons minced onion
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons distilled white vinegar,
</P>
<P>
   or more to taste
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon coarse salt (kosher or sea)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   1/2 to 1 teaspoon hot pepper flakes, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   In ms cholesterol, 75 milligrams sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Per tablespoon (sauce): 82 calories, trace protein, 9 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 100), trace carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 80 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   WATER SAFETY INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   Resources for learning more about the taste and safety of
drinking water are abundant.
</P>
<P>
   The August issue of Consumer Reports gives the results of its
taste and safety tests of 39 bottled waters. The October 1999 issue
of Consumer Reports reviewed faucet-mounted and carafe water
filters.
</P>
<P>
   The June issue of the Nutrition Action Health Letter, published
by the Center for Science in the Public Interest, www.cspinet.org,
takes a loed by Oconee County and Rome in a tie for second. Jekyll
Island, Ga., earned the lowest score of the nine. Cartersville,
Ga., was the winner in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
