<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6920 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-R-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN     08-09 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PC 101: PITFALLS TO AVOID 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeats for all needing. ATTN: N.C.)  (See also CIR-TEACHING-SOFTWARE, CIR-DORMS-COMPUTERS,
CIR-HIGHSCHOOL-GADGETS) 
 (Circuits)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Students in the freshman class of 2000 were born at the same
time as the original IBM PC. They have never known a world without
microprocessors. They grew up with cable TV and Nintendo, learned
to program the VCR before they could ride a bike, became virtuosos
with call-waiting and three-way conference calling and took for
granted answering machines, microwave ovens, audio CDs, pagers, fax
machines and cell phones. They came of age with the Internet and
the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Now they are heading off to college, where they will be immersed
in technology more deeply than at any time of their young lives.
</P>
<P>
   As if to prove that the cosmos has a sense of humor, we, their
technologically befuddled parents, are supposed to choose a
computer for these children of the technology age as they head off
to school. Here are some data points that may help.
</P>
<P>
   Nine out of 10 college students will be connected to the
Internet when school starts in a few weeks, according to Jupiter
Communications, a research firm. By the time this year's freshmen
are seniors, the number will rise to 95 percent, Jupiter says.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers are actually a bit low compared with those at the
University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, where every one of the
estimated 3,500 freshmen will be required to own a laptop computer
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina is unusual in both the size and ambition of its
computer program for new students, but the reasons behind its
laptop initiative could be instructive for any parent or student
who is thinking about computing strategies for the coming school
year.
</P>
<P>
   As in years past, this column strongly advises that all new
students check first with the admissions office to find out about
the school's computer recommendations. Doing so can save money,
time and frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with North Carolina's decision to require students
to have not just any computer, but specifically a laptop or
notebook computer.
</P>
<P>
   Laptop computers are more expensive, less powerful, less
versatile and easier to damage and lose than desktop computers. So
why did North Carolina decide to require students to go mobile?
</P>
<P>
   ``Desktops are dead, but nobody has taken their pulse lately,''
said Marian Moore, vice chancellor for information technology.
</P>
<P>
   Moore said the university decided two years ago to begin the
transition to mobile computing on its campuses. ``We are absolutely
positioned to drive local wireless networks into the classrooms,
the public areas on campus, the dining halls and out into open
areas, because we know every student will have a laptop,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Going to a wireless campus gives faculty and administrators
greater flexibility in using classroom space, costs less than
trying to string wires through old buildings and enables students _
virtually the only people on campus who do not have their own
offices _ to work wherever they are, either inside or while sitting
under a tree.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina is just beginning to develop its wireless network
and does not yet require students to have wireless modems for their
laptops. Moving the entire student body to laptops is the first
step in the transition to campuswide wireless networking.
</P>
<P>
   Just as mobile phones are overtaking wired phones, mobile
computers will eventually overtake desktop computers for all but
specialized tasks. But wired networks are not dead yet. They will
always offer higher connection speeds than wireless networks, which
is important for such important college tasks as collaborating on
engineering projects and downloading bootleg MP3 music files. Until
wireless networks are fully deployed on campus, the laptops can tap
into the wired networks through a standard Ethernet adapter card.
</P>
<P>
   According to Moore, 85 percent of the new students will buy
their laptops through the school. Because it buys so many
computers, North Carolina was able to negotiate substantial
discounts, as much as $800 less than the best prices available on
the Internet. (To minimize profiteering through reselling, students
and faculty can buy only one computer each year.)
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the manufacturer was IBM, which makes the highly
regarded and highly priced ThinkPad line of notebooks. There are
less expensive laptops on the market, but North Carolina decided to
go for the best machines available.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get what you pay for,'' Moore said. ``If you're going to
make the purchase, purchase something that will last.''
</P>
<P>
   Because North Carolina has adopted only two models _ the
ThinkPad 600X and ThinkPad 820M laptops _ as its standard, it can
offer expedited repair, replacement parts and loaner services right
on campus. Students can rarely afford to be without a computer for
a week or more, and the standardization allows the school to
minimize downtime.
</P>
<P>
   To help make sure the computer does not drop out before the
student graduates, the discounted price at North Carolina includes
a four-year service and repair warranty, a one-year insurance
policy against damage or theft, a cable lock for securely tethering
the laptop to desks or other hard-to-move objects and a basic
package of software.
</P>
<P>
   Extended warranties are even more important for laptop computers
than they are for desktop machines. If the laptop screen is
damaged, it can cost almost as much to repair as the cost of a new
machine.
</P>
<P>
   Some homeowner insurance policies will cover the loss or theft
of a child's laptop at college, but many will not. Supplemental
coverage can be added. Or consider, as North Carolina chose to do,
a company like Safeware (www.safeware.com), which specializes in
coverage of computers.
</P>
<P>
   Kensington makes my favorite locking security cable for laptops
(about $40). Targus (www.targus.com) has a motion-sensing notebook
alarm device called the Defcon 1 ($50) that shrieks louder than
Marilyn Manson when somebody tries to steal a laptop or backpack.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Even with the discounts, the ThinkPad 820M package will cost
$2,200; the 600X package, $2,900. ``You can't expect to require a
kid to come to school with technology like that without some
financial aid commitment,'' Moore said. Depending on their
financial status, some students will get laptops free, while others
will get loans from the school. She said the money the school
spends on financial aid would be offset by the money it saves by
making the transition from wired to wireless buildings on campus.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, all new students get a two-hour computer orientation to
learn how to tap into the school's network, use e-mail and
otherwise master the system.
</P>
<P>
   That's the story in Chapel Hill. Most undergraduate schools stop
short of making computer ownership a requirement, as North Carolina
does, and simply urge students to have their own PC's. Many
colleges make computers accessible in libraries and study centers
for students who cannot afford to buy one.
</P>
<P>
   For those who are shopping for a desktop system, ``this is
actually one of the best times in the last few years to buy a
computer,'' said Stephen Baker, vice president of technology
products research at PC Data in Reston, Va. ``Prices aren't exactly
collapsing, in fact they're pretty flat from last year, but the
consumer is getting a lot more for the same amount of money. We're
seeing bigger hard drives, better and faster processors and
preinstalled CD-RW drives.''
</P>
<P>
   Big hard drives and CD-RW drives are vitally important for
managing large volumes of MP3 music files. (Yes, I know, there is
more to college than downloading Napster files. Dude, whatever.)
When shopping for a computer that will be used far from home, it is
valuable to know which brands have the best reputations for
reliability, service and support. Each year PC Magazine asks
thousands of readers to rate their desktop and laptop computers and
printers on the basis of reliability and service satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   In this year's survey, published in June, the only desktop
computer maker to get an A grade from readers was Dell. The lowest
scores went to Acer, AST, Compaq and Packard Bell. Packard Bell has
always been the class clown in terms of service and reliability,
but Compaq's low score was surprising.
</P>
<P>
   In the notebook computer category the grading was tougher: No
company scored an A. The highest scores, all B's, went to Dell, IBM
and Gateway. Again, Compaq scored a surprising D. In the printer
category, PC Magazine readers gave A grades to Panasonic and
Hewlett-Packard. Epson got a B. Canon got a D for its relatively
weak support, and Tektronix a D for frequency of repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Handheld organizers like the Palms, Handspring Visor, HP Jornada
and Compaq iPaq are not replacements for a desktop or laptop
computer at school, but they can be useful for keeping track of
assignments and taking notes, especially when equipped with a
folding keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   And for extra credit, students, remember to turn off your cell
phones before entering class.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
