<HEADER>
A6922 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-REFORM-SHADOWBOXERS-I     08-09 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-SHADOWBOXERS-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFORM PARTY: HEY, GUYS, YOU'RE SUPPOSED TO FIGHT BUSH, GORE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Commentary Editors: TIMELY for Reform Party Convention, AUG.10)   (This 700-word ``separate-buy'' article on Reform Party infighting,
is from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``p''
political news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ANDREW GUMBEL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was just another day in the life of the Reform
Party. With no agreed candidate to run for president, much less a
running mate or a platform of agreed policy, the party's two
seemingly irreconcilable factions shouted at each other, swung
their fists and, when the police came to break up the fight,
marched off in different directions threatening lawsuits and all
manner of more intimate forms of revenge.
</P>
<P>
   That was Tuesday. Thursday, at least in theory, the party that
once hoped to become the force that would break the
Democrat-Republican duopoly in American politics opens its national
convention in Long Beach, Calif., in an atmosphere of blood-baying
anticipation more commonly associated with prize fights than with
political coronations.
</P>
<P>
   In the blue corner stands Pat Buchanan, erstwhile scourge of the
Republican Party, virulent free-trader, and hero to America's white
supremacists, Jewish conspiracy theorists, anti-abortionists and
prayer-breakfast isolationists.
</P>
<P>
   He has the advantage of national prominence, the crucial support
of the Reform Party's chairman, Gerald Moan, and a majority _
albeit a contested majority _ of the party's national committee.
</P>
<P>
   In the red corner, meanwhile, is the altogether less pugnacious
figure of John Hagelin, a libertarian quantum physicist with a
penchant for transcendental meditation.
</P>
<P>
   He is the hastily presented alternative to Buchanan, ardently
championed by those members of the Reform Party who want nothing to
do with neo-Nazis or Christian fundamentalists and who remain true
to the secular, reformist agenda of their founder, the Texas
billionaire Ross Perot.
</P>
<P>
   To say the two sides have no common ground is an understatement.
Reform Party politics have come to resemble the schisms of the
medieval papacy, all factionalism and anti-popery, with a healthy
dose of brawling thrown in too.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that Buchanan will formally win the nomination, and
the $12.6 million in federal campaign money that goes with it.
</P>
<P>
   But it also appears that the victory will be pyrrhic at best: he
will represent the Reform Party in name only, will be subject to
unceasing attacks from his opponents within the movement, and can
probably expect no more than a blip on voter radar screens come
election day on Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   The Hagelin faction intends to hold its own separate convention
and, possibly, run its own presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of this faction, Reform Party secretary Jim Mangia,
has argued for months that Buchanan has strong-armed his way to the
nomination, sent out party nomination ballots to people ineligible
to vote in them, and betrayed Perot's founding spirit.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is a far cry from Ross Perot's 1992 presidential
campaign, when his platform of deficit reduction and opposition to
unfettered free trade won him 19 percent of the national vote.
</P>
<P>
   Perot has ducked out of Reform Party business almost entirely in
the past couple of years and will not be making an appearance in
Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   His interest waned considerably when the wrestling champion
Jesse Ventura was unexpectedly elected governor of Minnesota on the
Reform Party ticket in 1998. Ventura quickly grabbed the Reform
Party limelight, only to walk out of the party last February
because of irreconcilable differences with the Perot faction.
</P>
<P>
   With the party desperate for a high-profile presidential
candidate, Buchanan was able to beat off challenges from the likes
of Donald Trump, the New York real-estate developer, and impose his
brand of radical firebrand conservatism on a skeptical party base.
</P>
<P>
   For a while he was allied with the Trotskyite Lenora Fulani, a
marriage made in hell if ever there was one, before busting up with
her and going it alone.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan and Mangia have been exchanging incendiary e-mails
throughout. Mangia claims to have received death threats from the
Buchanan camp, including a voice mail message saying ``You
miserable piece of s-t... I'm going to get you in Long Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, none of this is impressing voters, and the Reform
Party is polling little more than one percent nationwide. If
anything, Perot's mantle has passed to Ralph Nader, the
consumer-rights advocate running on the Green Party ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Third-party politics in America remain as elusive as ever. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 700-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 1648EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
