u k BC-COMPUTER-DISPOSAL-NEW     08-09 1868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-DISPOSAL-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFUSION OF OLD COMPUTERS CREATES TOXIC PROBLEM
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Wednesday, AUGUST 9, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADV: With graphic showing growing number of obsolete computers 
 By TREVOR MAXWELL  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The profusion of computers in American life has produced a toxic
problem: a mounting stockpile of outdated equipment containing
millions of pounds of lead and other dangerous substances for which
there are few disposal sites and recycling plans.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two decades, an estimated 175 million computer sets
in the United States have been tucked into warehouses and
residential basements and attics. Contained in those computers are
roughly 650 million pounds of lead, 987,000 pounds of cadmium,
231,000 pounds of mercury and more than 2 billion pounds of
plastics.
</P>
<P>
   ``People spend a lot of money on this technology, and they can't
bear to throw it away when it's obsolete,'' said Bill Bree of
Oregon's Department of Environmental Quality. ``A lot of people
have one or two machines tucked away somewhere. Those are the ones
an organized program should be able to make available for reuse or
recycling.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for those collected by a handful of recovery efforts
nationwide mainly serving large industries, the computers that do
leave storage end up in public and private landfills designed for
trash. There, these components release toxic substances and mix
with liquids that in some cases leach into soils and threaten
ground water.
</P>
<P>
   Solid waste planners estimate that 30 percent to 40 percent of
lead in municipal landfills comes from computers and other
electronic equipment. Lead is widely known to cause central nervous
system disorders and interfere with the neurologic development of
children.
</P>
<P>
   The accumulation of dead and out-of-use computers is dizzying.
The number of PCs in use has jumped nearly 150 percent since 1992,
to 164 million units nationwide, according to the Computer Industry
Almanac. In that same period, however, the expected lifespan of a
PC has been cut in half, from more than four years to about two.
This rush to obsolescence rapidly multiplies the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Obsolete computer systems have nearly doubled in number since
1997. Last year, 24 million computers in the United States were
retired, yet only 3.3 million were recycled, a National Safety
Council report shows. The ``missing'' 20.7 million sets?
</P>
<P>
   Tucked away in storage, mainly. Others go to the landfill or
incinerators -- or are shipped to foreign markets for dumping or
stripping down for the reuse of certain parts, federal officials
and industry specialists say.
</P>
<P>
   Most computer users are unaware of the toxic contents of their
PCs.
</P>
<P>
   A standard display monitor contains from 4 to 8 pounds of lead,
which lines the glass cathode ray tube, or CRT, as a user shield
against radiation. A 1999 University of Florida study classifies
most standard monitors as hazardous waste.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts this year became the first state to ban CRTs from
landfills. Other states and cities, particularly in the East where
landfills are filling rapidly, are considering similar actions.
</P>
<P>
   Minute amounts of mercury, a highly toxic and environmentally
persistent metal, appear in a computer's printed wiring boards,
switches, relays and batteries. Cadmium compounds, metals suspected
as persistent carcinogens, appear in a computer's batteries, wiring
boards and plastic stabilizers. And plastics, the computer's No. 1
ingredient, are pesky: They typically have little value yet require
difficult separation for an expensive recycling process that is
itself toxic.
</P>
<P>
   All of these things mix with a landfill's more traditional
garbage stew, altering the landfill's leachate, or pungent liquid,
that either drains into a collection system or the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The National Safety Council sees a clear, ominous trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still no real infrastructure for collecting and
disseminating equipment,'' says Bud Ward, executive director of the
council's Environmental Health Center. ``The big companies have
asset recovery programs established, but what about the smaller
businesses and households?''
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Quantum Resource Recovery, based in Beaverton, Ore., handles
cast-off electronic materials for Intel, Fujitsu and Tektronics,
among other companies. Quantum is one of the few recyclers in the
United States that will accept individual PCs free of charge.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Mike Wenzinger said the growing company has held computer
collection days, coordinated with local governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Eugene, we took in 23,000 pounds of equipment in four
hours, and that's only on a two-week notification,'' Wenzinger
said. ``The next week we had a bunch of calls asking when we were
going to do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   But such days are rare. If someone wants to properly dispose of
a PC now, it's almost always up to that person to find a private
recycler and pay a fee. That's started to change in at least one
Oregon venue. The Marion County Department of Solid Waste
Management this summer teamed with Computer Drive Connection Inc.,
a Cornelius recycler, and allowed free drop-offs at its
Salem-Keizer Recycling and Transfer site. In just three weeks, a
30-yard container was filled with PC parts.
</P>
<P>
   Similar programs in Seattle and Minneapolis have experienced
overwhelming responses.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   The electronics recycling industry is new and small; it lacks
the capacity and support to handle the growing computer stockpile.
And its priorities are not always the same as those who would
supply it.
</P>
<P>
   To reduce costs, computer manufacturers are using fewer precious
metals and more plastics, making recycling more difficult and
expensive. And the profusion of lead-heavy monitors poses the
biggest and toughest recycling challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The Doe Run Co. of St. Louis, Mo., operates the nation's only
two primary lead smelters handling glass from computer monitors.
Doe Run's environmental specialist, Cliff Asberry, is blunt on the
subject of CRTs:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm assuming if it's not coming to me, or going to
glass-to-glass recyclers or overseas, it's going to landfills. I'm
bringing in a lot of glass, but the smelters can only use so much
of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get calls every week from people looking to get into the
recycling business. But people don't realize the environmental
sides to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency confirms the problem
but is beset by loopholes in regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The waste stream itself has been growing significantly,'' says
Michael Shapiro, an EPA deputy assistant administrator in
Washington, D.C. ``Our feeling is that there is much more that
could be done.''
</P>
<P>
   The EPA now requires large producers of electronic waste -- an
industry discarding 80 computers, for example, after purchasing
more powerful machines -- to meet standards for handling,
distributing or recycling the cast-offs.
</P>
<P>
   But a residential exemption in EPA's rules applies to those
discarding less than 220 pounds of computer monitors monthly. That,
it turns out, applies to most small businesses, exempting them from
recycling requirements.
</P>
<P>
   It also means household users in most states can take their
outmoded machines to the dump or landfill.
</P>
<P>
   Recycling industry representatives say the EPA's rules are
inconsistent, not well understood and often intentionally broken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our experience is that the commercial sector either does not
know or is ignoring any regulations regarding electronics,'' said a
Michigan recycler, Greg Heynen, during a National Recycling
Coalition roundtable discussion. ``I spoke to someone ... who
landfilled a whole trailer of electronics and (monitors). ... Many
just don't want to pay and would rather sneak it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Even responsible businesses struggle to find proper disposal
outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Kirk, information technology manager with United Companies
Financial in Baton Rouge, La., found it impossible to give away 800
Pentium PCs for which the company had once paid top dollar. The
machines sat in storage for six months before Kirk sold some to
employees and the rest went to recycling intermediaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to donate them, but they didn't meet the school
system's criteria, and at that time, most of the liquidators in the
Southeast didn't want any more equipment,'' Kirk said.
</P>
<P>
   Frances O'Brien, an asset analyst with the Gartner Group in
Stamford, Conn., advises companies to plan for electronics
obsolescence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a problem that just snuck up on people,'' O'Brien
said. ``I have clients that have old equipment in warehouses
because they can't find outlets for it. The situation came on fast,
and very few have plans on how to address it.''
</P>
<P>
   Donation has been a popular option for companies and individuals
seeking to unload computer gear. But donation, while sometimes good
in the short term, transfers disposal responsibility to
organizations that do not have adequate resources, some critics
say.
</P>
<P>
   An emerging debate addresses manufacturer responsibility.
Michael Dell of Dell Computers has publicly discussed computer
recovery as a mounting problem, and IBM and Hewlett-Packard are
credited with making strides toward recoverability. But at this
point no one -- manufacturer, local government or federal agency --
wants to be stuck with the entire bill for end-of-life
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Until gathering and recycling systems are in place for the
nation's computer stockpile, landfills -- and the water tables they
sometimes affect -- remain vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   The Silicon Valley Toxics Coalition has tracked the problem at
the heart of the nation's chip-producing center.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is more ground-water pollution in the Silicon Valley
than anywhere else in the country,'' said Ted Smith, the
coalition's executive director. Smith's organization tracks
recycling issues and has pushed for increased manufacturer
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some companies that are clearly trying to do the
right thing,'' Smith said. ``But they are so good at what they do,
so powerful and so prolific, that they never have time to
anticipate the unintended consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   The computer stockpile is growing faster than any solution.
</P>
<P>
   By 2002 in the United States alone, more than 50 million
computers will become obsolete annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is going to be a real temptation to feed them into
landfills,'' said Ward, of the safety council. ``There is no
question that there are a lot of heavy metals that pose a toxicity
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those in industry who tend to minimize the environmental
concerns on toxicity still have to confront the quantity issue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
