<HEADLINE>
U.N. FORCE AND LEBANESE ARMY SWAP INTENDED ROLES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This 625-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London. Middle East correspondent Robert Fisk was
recently named ``Amnesty International Print Journalist of the
Year.'')  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ROBERT FISK  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   RMEICH, SOUTHERN LEBANON _ At last. The Lebanese army moved
through the streets of southern Lebanon's stony villages Wednesday
while U.N. peacekeepers looked down from their new observation
posts on the Lebanese-Israeli frontier.
</P>
<P>
   Given the smartly-dressed Lebanese troopers in their gleaming
Land Rovers, the military police in their dark green armor and the
paramilitary lads in their grey and black camouflage, it was almost
possible to forget that it was all the wrong way around.
</P>
<P>
   For the United Nations was originally supposed to be in the
towns and the Lebanese army _ so far as the U.N.'s brains were
concerned _ on the border with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the United Nations sits on the ``blue line''
shoulder-to-shoulder with the Israelis while the Lebanese soldiers
settle into their new billets to the north.
</P>
<P>
   At least 200 of them _ half from the formerly occupied area in
the south _ had taken over the Lebanese Technical High School at
Bint Jbeil Wednesday, sipping bottled water by the sports ground or
driving their vehicles through the little hill villages of Rmeich
and Ein Ebel.
</P>
<P>
   On U.N. paper, it all looks fine. Secretary General Kofi Annan's
special U.N. envoy, Terje Roede-Larsen, arranged for the 600 U.N.
soldiers to be posted to the frontier in order to prove that Israel
really had withdrawn from all Lebanese territory.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese government had insisted upon this step. But just a
few weeks ago, before Roede-Larsen _ one of the supposedly heroic
architects of the deeply flawed Oslo agreement between Palestinians
and Israelis _ turned up in Beirut, the boot was on the other foot.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations was insisting on a peacekeeping deployment
within the former occupied zone, but with Lebanese troops on the
border. If the Lebanese did not accept this, then the United
Nations planned to pull out of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   As one old U.N. hand in New York put it to me Wednesday over the
phone: ``We were ready to fulfill the mandate _ which is to
`establish peace and security' in the area which the Israelis have
vacated. But we've now allowed the Lebanese _ who should be on the
border _ to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are in the towns where we are meant to be. We are on the
frontier where they are meant to be. Larsen screwed it all up.''
</P>
<P>
   Which appears to be true. The U.N. soldiers on the ``blue line''
_ running along the old Palestine-Lebanon frontier _ are now tasked
to be ``observers''; something they were never supposed to be under
U.N. Security Council Resolution 425 of 1978 which followed
Israel's first invasion of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   It is the Lebanese army's duty to defend the frontier of Lebanon
_ just as it is the Israeli army's job to defend Israel. Now
Roede-Larsen has effectively given that impossible and unmandated
mission _ to ``defend'' both countries _ to about 600 U.N.
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Junior U.N. officers on the ground are not supposed to talk to
journalists, but ``cover-up'' was the least unpleasant of the
epithets one of them Wednesday had to say about the United Nations
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can we do on the border?'' he asked. ``UNIFIL (the United
Nations Interim Force in Lebanon) can't stop infiltrations or
attacks in either direction. We don't have the arms or the mandate.
But now we're going to be blamed for everything that goes wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, the Lebanese are delighted at the new scenario.
Their soldiers sit snugly in the newly-``liberated'' towns of
southern Lebanon while the United Nations take the stick.
</P>
<P>
   In Marjayoun, the Lebanese authorities took back the old army
barracks in the Christian town for the first time in 22 years. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
