</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SADDAM-FESTERS-PESTERS-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DECADE LATER, SADDAM STILL FESTERS, PESTERS WEST  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This 650-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By RUPERT CORNWELL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ A full decade after the Gulf War, the West is still
searching for a way of getting rid of Saddam Hussein and the
chemical, biological and nuclear weapons facilities it believes he
is continuing to develop.
</P>
<P>
   It was 9 p.m. Washington time on the evening of Aug. 1, 1990,
when a startled Dick Cheney _ now Republican vice-presidential
candidate, then defense secretary in the Bush Administration _ was
phoned at home by an aide to be told that Iraqi tank columns had
crossed the Kuwaiti border at dawn and were racing, unopposed,
towards Kuwait City.
</P>
<P>
   The American response was to send an army of half a million men
half way around the world, and seven months later a U.S.-led
coalition liberated Kuwait and routed Saddam's forces, after a
ground campaign lasting barely 100 hours.
</P>
<P>
   But apparently complete victory gradually turned into a
stalemate which persists to this day.
</P>
<P>
   At least three times in the intervening years, allied aircraft
have launched major air attacks, the last Operation Desert Fox in
December 1998. Since when U.S. and British warplanes have carried
out strikes against Iraqi targets roughly every other day.
</P>
<P>
   No-fly zones have been imposed in the north and south of the
country. Stringent United Nations sanctions have been in force
since the invasion and with varying success U.N. arms inspectors
have sought to garner information on Saddam's weapons of mass
destruction programs. But to scant avail.
</P>
<P>
   As the years have passed, the original Gulf coalition has
crumbled, and deep splits have emerged among the five permanent
members of the U.N. Security Council, pitting Britain and the U.S.
against Russia, China and, increasingly often, France.
</P>
<P>
   Though crippled by sanctions, Iraq is starting to edge out of
its international isolation. Several Gulf states _ though not
Kuwait _ have resumed ties, while 80 countries will be represented
at the forthcoming Baghdad trade fair.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday saw the restoration of rail links between Iraq and
its former sworn enemy Syria, for the first time in 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   But if others wobble, amid mounting international unease at the
humanitarian crisis which the blockade has helped bring about, the
U.S. and Britain are adamant that sanctions must stay until Iraq
has stopped trying to build chemical, nuclear and biological
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still evidence of all three of them,'' senior Foreign
Office diplomats said last week. ``We expect Saddam to carry on
seeking to improve bilateral relations with as many countries as
possible, and to sow new discord among the Western allies.''
</P>
<P>
   Saddam's bait is primarily economic, the prospects of rich
contracts for the country's reconstruction to be paid for out of
sharply increased oil revenues.
</P>
<P>
   But the real crunch will come in a few weeks, with the possible
return of the first U.N. arms inspectors since the departure of the
last such mission, UNSCOM, in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In late July Hans Blix, the Swedish diplomat who leads the
latest team, called UNMOVIC, said it would be ready to start work
at the end of August. It remains to be seen whether Iraq will allow
them in.
</P>
<P>
   With fewer Westerners in its ranks, the new body is reckoned
more acceptable to Saddam. Though ``Blix will be firm,'' in the
words of a British official, the mandate of the new team contains
more carrots as well as sticks, notably a more clearly mapped path
towards the lifting of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far Iraq has said it will have no truck with UNMOVIC.
</P>
<P>
   The West now waits to see whether that is mere bluff, or a
reflection of Saddam's belief that the sanctions dam, already
leaking, may soon collapse _ perhaps when a new president enters
the White House next January. &QL; 
