<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6936 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-HATE-USA-TEHRAN-INDEP     08-09 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE-USA-TEHRAN-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEE, GO TO HELL: BITTER IRANIANS BLAME AMERICA FOR WAR DEAD  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This 650-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By JUSTIN HUGGLER  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   TEHRAN _ Hassan Safir was finishing the grave of his son, in the
hot Tehran afternoon. Mohamed Ali Safir died in 1986, at the age of
18. But his father has only just buried him.
</P>
<P>
   They found his body last year: he was one of ``the Lost,'' those
who died in the war with Iraq and whose bodies were not recovered.
They are still finding bodies, even though the war ended twelve
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In the suburbs of every Iranian city, there is a rose garden:
the Garden of Martyrs. Here, you can understand why it is so hard
for Iran to make peace with the United States _ as Washington,
encouraged by the reforms of President Mohamed Khatami, has been
signalling it would like to.
</P>
<P>
   Mohamed Ali Safir is buried in the garden in Tehran. You can see
his photograph there, one among thousands that stretch in every
direction _ pictures of those who died in the war with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The photographs are more poignant than any memorial could be. In
some, the dead are shy before the camera. In others, they stare at
it directly, proud in their new uniforms, smiling before they set
off for death. Often, they are teenagers, sometimes even children.
Occasionally, there is the veiled face of a woman.
</P>
<P>
   The relatives, tending the graves of their dead, remain bitter
towards the United States for its perceived role in the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't start the war,'' says Hassan Safir, over the newly
dug grave of his son, draped with the red banners of martyrdom.
``Iraq invaded us. And who gave them the weapons? America, England,
NATO. They gave the chemical weapons to Iraq,'' he says. ``The
chemical weapons that were used on our children.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's evident who is to blame for the war: America,'' says
Mohsen Kheirabadi, repairing the grave of his brother, Naghi.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 300,000 Iranians died in the war. It was the
defining experience for an entire generation of Iranians _ and
everybody here believes the United States started it, by
encouraging Iraq to invade in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   The war brings out a passion that unites Iran's hard-liners and
reformers. Hossein Shariatrazavi voted for Khatami, but beside the
grave of his brother, Ali Reza, the patriot in him gets the better
of the reformer.
</P>
<P>
   He insists that Iran is united, that reformers and hard-liners
are struggling together for the Islamic Revolution. ``It was the
enemies of Islam who started the war with Iraq,'' he says. ``And
the leader of them is America.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday was the tenth anniversary of Iraq's invasion of
Kuwait, which led to the Gulf War. But the bombardment of Baghdad
by American jets did nothing to change the view of people here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that Iraq is weak they are doing everything they can
against Iraq,'' smiles Safir. ``Countries like America are just
arming the small countries against each other.'' All around Safir
stretch the pictures of the dead, killed in a war Iranians blame
the U.S. for starting.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the old man insists peace with America is possible. ``We're
not against America,'' he insists. ``We're just against their
hostile policies. If there was mutual respect between us, there
would be no problem. But we will not let them destroy Islam.''
</P>
<P>
   Even here, amongst all this wasted youth, Safir is not bitter at
his son's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we could all go the same way,'' he says, gazing at the
photograph of his son. ``We believe the martyrs died for us, for
our country, for Islam. Even now, if the country was in danger, I
have more children. I can give them.''
</P>
<P>
   His son cannot tell if he believes it was worth while dying,
probably in agony, at the age of 18. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 650-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
