<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6938 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-HIPHOP-HATE-2000(2TAK     08-09 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIPHOP-HATE-2000(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS EMINEM FOR REAL OR PLAYING A CHARACTER? DO WE REALLY WANT TO
KNOW?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By DAVE FERMAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eminem is pop music's bad boy du jour, the guy who jokes about
enlisting his daughter's help in killing her mom, the guy who
bashes gays and jokes about how much dope his mother did when he
was a kid. He disses 'N Sync, Britney Spears, Will Smith and
Christina Aguilera, and he makes no apologies.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, there is nobody hotter in music _ Eminem's second
CD, ``The Marshall Mathers LP'' (Mathers is his real name), has
sold more than 5 million copies in two months and has been atop the
national CD charts since its release _ and nobody whose life looks
more out of control. On June 4, police say, he pointed a gun at
Douglas Dali of Insane Clown Posse; the next day, he reportedly
pistol-whipped a man who kissed his wife, Kim, in a parking lot.
Both men are pressing charges.
</P>
<P>
   Eminem is also being sued for $10 million by his mom, Debbie
Mathers-Briggs, for saying on his breakthrough 1999 hit ``My Name
Is'' that she ``does more dope than I do.'' More recently, he's
been sharply criticized by gay organizations for his frequent
gay-bashing on the ``Marshall Mathers'' CD, and has earned the
wrath of many women for songs such as ``Kim,'' a brutal fantasy in
which he kills his wife.
</P>
<P>
   The night the current Up In Smoke Tour played his hometown of
Detroit, Kim attempted suicide by slashing her wrists.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by CDs and tickets sold, however, Eminem has become a
bona-fide hero to disaffected American youth who quite simply don't
want to be told what to do and who want to live vicariously through
the anger smoldering in his songs.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, there's no disputing his talent as a rapper: Everyone
from mentor Dr. Dre to hip-hop bible ``Vibe'' magazine to gospel
superstar Kirk Franklin notes his skills on the microphone.
</P>
<P>
   If you hate him, there's no shortage of reasons. ``Marshall
Mathers'' is a series of obscenity-filled outrages that find Eminem
lashing out against everything and everyone.
</P>
<P>
   His life, in other words, is a vortex of court dates, sold-out
arenas, travel, intense pressure and scrutiny. Everyone wants a
piece of Eminem _ or is it Slim Shady (his evil alter ego) or
Marshall Mathers, the troubled kid who was raised by a single mom
in poor inner-city Detroit, dropped out of school in the ninth
grade and was, until recently, a fry-cook?
</P>
<P>
   He might be any one of the three in a given song, thereby
honoring the timeless legacy of singers assuming personae in their
work, according to Alan Light, editor of ``Spin,'' which had Eminem
on the cover of its August issue. Light calls Eminem's playing of
various characters ``slippery but legitimate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a tradition of rock 'n' roll but it's also part of the
dialogue in hip-hop _ rappers will defend problematic lyrics by
saying the kids understand the difference in `me' and the person
onstage,'' Light says. ``You don't think Clint Eastwood is a bad
guy because he killed people in a movie. Why can't recording
artists and their audiences receive the same respect, that they can
tell the difference between storytelling and a documentary? In `Cop
Killer,' Ice-T used the voice of a character, like a fiction writer
would.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes and no, says David Cross, an associate professor of
psychology at Texas Christian University in Fort Worth. He says
that although many children and teens can distinguish fact from
fiction and characters from real people, those from less-stable
homes may not have that ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ones at risk are the ones whose home life is congruent
with the message in the media,'' Cross said. ``The behaviors they
see modeled in the media are consistent with behaviors modeled in
their environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Eminem's use of characterization can be seen as license to say
anything you want, no matter how volatile, and then hide behind the
character. The message is: ``Hey, lighten up _ that's not the real
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Light is right: U2's Bono, Johnny Cash, Mick Jagger and numerous
country, folk and blues singers _ all have assumed characters in
their songs.
</P>
<P>
   But with Eminem, it gets a bit hazier. Take ``Kim.'' Marshall
Mathers is married to a woman named Kim, and there's no question it
is a volatile relationship; he has ``Kim: Rot in Pieces'' tattooed
on his stomach. But when he fights with her and kills her in the
song, is it Marshall Mathers doing it? Slim Shady? Neither? Will
life imitate art someday?
</P>
<P>
   In this way, too, Eminem is part of a long line of rappers and
rockers who set themselves outside the mainstream to become
weathervanes for their era. From Bob Dylan to the Rolling Stones to
Crosby, Stills, Nash &AMP; Young to the MC5 to any number of punk
rockers to Public Enemy and N.W.A, there have always been
performers that lambasted racism or the government or a war or
violent police, and sometimes advocated anarchy.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to right wrongs and/or protesting those who abuse
authority has become a trademark of rock and rap _ at times its
most useful role in society.
</P>
<P>
   Eminem has earned his outsider/rebel status by making women and
gays his major targets. These two groups have traditionally been
abused by heterosexual men. MORE: &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 1659EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
