<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6940 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-HIPHOP-HATE-2000(2TAK     08-09 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIPHOP-HATE-2000(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS EMINEM FOR REAL OR PLAYING A CHARACTER? DO WE REALLY WANT TO
KNOW?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By DAVE FERMAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
UNDATED: by heterosexual men. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One could make the argument that this is cowardly. Members of
several gay-rights organizations, including the Gay and Lesbian
Alliance Against Defamation, have said as much.
</P>
<P>
   Or is Eminem pouring out a lifetime of rage and frustration in a
cathartic spew that's a source of relief and release for him and
his listeners?
</P>
<P>
   After all, part of what makes Eminem compelling to so many
people is that they can see themselves in him. Young couples in
volatile relationships, young men with slim prospects, teens with
access to firearms _ these are parts of the real world for
thousands of people growing up in America nowadays. For them,
Eminem/Slim/Marshall is lampooning their darkest feelings while
displaying his own foibles and insecurities.
</P>
<P>
   He's the flip side to Britney Spears' living-Barbie-doll looks
and cute, frothy little songs about teen-age crushes and dealing
with boys _ and it's no coincidence that both have sold just about
the same number of CDs in just about the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as Light notes, it's harder to be a rebel these days _ and
easier to be a delinquent quasi-rock star. America is involved in
no major conflicts, the economy is booming, there's a computer in
every house and a new SUV in every garage _ what's a homeboy to do?
Rap about how slow his modem is?
</P>
<P>
   Rock and rap stars are celebrating their wealth and success in
gaudy, sometimes sleazy ways that are reminiscent of the
hedonistic, drug-soaked '60s and '70s: huge pieces of jewelry, furs
(favored by Puff Daddy and Kid Rock), extravagant parties,
champagne, blocklong cars, the best dope, strippers, porn-star
girlfriends. They want you to know they're living large _ even as
they flip the world off.
</P>
<P>
   But beneath the surface are ugly realities that reach into the
lives of people who have never met Eminem and yet take his music
and message seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say he's the cause of abuse cases, but he foments
an atmosphere that says that you can do these things, that this is
how to treat women,'' says a member of the Tarrant County Task
Force on Family Violence, which serves North Texas. The woman spoke
on condition of anonymity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She points to a recent case in which a young woman was trying to
get a protective order against her abusive ex-boyfriend. The
boyfriend often called up and play Eminem's notorious ``97' Bonnie
&AMP; Clyde,'' the song in which the narrator enlists the help of his
young daughter to dispose of the child's mother in a lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would play this song in the background and say, `Listen to
this _ I'll get you,' '' she says. ``It was just like when O.J.
Simpson was on trial. I had women who wanted to break up with men
and the guy would say, `I'm gonna pull an O.J. on you _ you just
wait.' This says to me that Eminem has a lot of influence on a
certain segment of the population _ young people. Many of them
haven't had that many life experiences and are more
impressionable.''
</P>
<P>
   Cross adds that these more vulnerable youths have not seen good
examples of how to deal with other people in their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two salient phenomena we see,'' he says. ``The
Columbine thing, or gang-related behavior. When I hear about a
12-year-old kid becoming an assassin, my bet is that his home life
wasn't good, and he wasn't being monitored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Empathy comes from healthy relationships _ it's a major
preventative. If the child is in an environment where there's not
much empathy, they're more likely to act out on a media message.''
</P>
<P>
   Eminem's first CD sold around 3 million copies _ at day's end,
the new one could do three times that, even if its sales level off
in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, nobody's suggesting he's responsible for the actions
of every person who listens to his music. No recording artist is;
as Tom Petty noted long ago, you can't worry about the dumbest
members of your audience and what your music may lead them to do.
</P>
<P>
   In Eminem's case, though, there seems to be a fine line between
life and art, between fantasy and reality _ and sometimes no line
at all. That's what makes him worrisome to so many people _ and so
popular to millions more. Does he, as a result, deserve to be hated
or pitied? Or both?
</P>
<P>
   You decide. As noted, Marshall Mathers _ whoever he is _ isn't
going to apologize. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
