<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-POPE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     POPE BRINGS PRIDE, POSE TO RAIDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By FRANK BLACKMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAPA, Calif. _ Marquez Pope aspires to more than just being a
member of the 2000 Oakland Raiders. He wants to be one of their
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why am I here?'' Pope asked rhetorically. ``I love to play the
game. I have a passion about the game. In my California journey,
I'm here with the Raiders now. I'm happy. I'm very excited. I feel
and think I can bring a lot to this team. Through performance. And
leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Since this is Pope's first training camp with the Raiders, his
goal to become a team leader might seem somewhat presumptuous.
After all, aren't new guys in the locker room supposed to keep a
low profile, at least for a while?
</P>
<P>
   Pope does not intend to rally his teammates with rousing
speeches. That is not his style. He believes if he goes out and
does his job every day, demonstrates that it can be done with
maximum effort and concentration, then it will inspire the men
around him to do the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's doing it,'' Pope explained. ``It's showing poise.
Being relaxed and comfortable with yourself. And understanding that
there are obstacles that occur, but training yourself to say if I'm
in this situation do I panic or do I calm down? It takes calm. You
have to be very calm and relaxed through life. You don't rush. You
work through things and just make sure it's done right.''
</P>
<P>
   Darrien Gordon has been around Pope long enough already to see
that his new teammate can be a positive influence on the field and
in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just doing what he's already been doing,'' Gordon said. ``Come
in with the professionalism he has, the work ethic, the playmaking
ability. Guys see that. Guys respect that. Him coming in and doing
the kind of things he's done his whole career. That's going to put
him into a leadership role.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Gordon's eighth year, and he figures to have a
leadership role. Eric Allen, beginning his 13th season, definitely
does. Then there are Tim Brown and Steve Wisniewski, the senior
members of the offense.
</P>
<P>
   `It appears as if this job already has been filled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to win a championship,'' Gordon said. ``Think
about the dynasties the 49ers had, the Cowboys had, even the
Broncos. There's any number of guys you can point to for leadership
on those teams. Of course, there's going to be one or two that
everybody points to. Here it's probably Tim Brown and Steve
Wisniewski. But there's so many other guys, so many veterans, like
Eric Allen, who are leaders. You can never have enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Pope doesn't have to be introduced to football fans in the San
Francisco Bay Area. He played four years with the 49ers and also
has suited up for the Chargers and Rams. He spent last season in
Cleveland, was unhappy there and asked to be released. He knew
immediately where he wanted to work next.
</P>
<P>
   Raiders coach Jon ``Gruden and I had talked last year,'' Pope
said. ``I felt this would be the best place. He liked my style of
play and understood the type of person that I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Although a natural safety, circumstance forced Pope to play
corner for much of his career. So he is a versatile athlete. In
this training camp, he has been working exclusively at strong
safety.
</P>
<P>
   When the exhibition season began last weekend in St. Louis, Pope
was playing behind Je'Rod Cherry. But during drills on Tuesday,
Pope played with the first team.
</P>
<P>
   If the competition between Pope and Cherry ultimately is decided
on poise, it's no contest. Pope wears a cap with the word relax on
it. It is his way of reminding people to calm down. Don't worry,
he's got it all under control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very optimistic,'' he said. ``Therefore, I create a
winning and successful mind-set. Have I not been a starter? You
have to work at wanting something. If you want something you have
to work to get it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's relax, but my pulse is still beating very rapidly. I'm a
very eager person. But that's inside. It's hidden. All this energy
in me comes out on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   And that energy, he believes, will help the Raiders become a
champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a time for everybody,'' he said. ``I think it is time
for the Raiders. Me being here, I'm saying I want to be a part of
this building to something. Gruden has been here three years. He
has this image in his mind. And everybody has to see this same
picture. That's the ultimate goal in sports, being a champion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
