 &HT;    Locate hard to find items
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having trouble finding a particular item? We'll try to help you
locate it. But because of the volume of mail, we cannot track down
every request. Readers whose queries are answered in the column
will receive a blue-and-cream canvas Buyer's Edge tote bag. Write
us at Buyer's Edge Find It,The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O.
Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302; e-mail us at buyersedge(at)ajc.com
(please include your name, the city you live in and daytime phone
number); or call 404-582-7642
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am trying to locate ``food pails,'' takeout containers with
little metal handles. Can you tell me where I can buy these items?
</P>
<P>
   _ Peter Yu, Norcross, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: Takeout containers have never looked so chic. We discovered
these handy-dandy items at Cost Plus World Market, 4733-A Ashford
Dunwoody Road (678-731-0014). Each paper pail, which comes in such
colors as red, purple, green and brown, holds 1 pint and is 79
cents. And the Container Store sells plastic Chinese cartons
($1.49-$1.99) that can be used for food, gifts or party favors.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Over a year ago I purchased ``Instant White,'' a spray used
to whiten teeth. It works much better than any whitening toothpaste
I have ever used. The problem? I can no longer find it. Do you know
where I can find this product?
</P>
<P>
   _ Sandra Maloy, Marietta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: This is one request we could really sink our pearly whites
into. You can purchase the Instant White Kit ($18.95) on the
Internet at www.cooltvproducts.com. Or call 1-877-734-4822. Simply
spray Instant White on your teeth and in seconds tiny oxygenating
bubbles work to whiten and brighten your teeth. It's sugar-free,
with a fresh mint taste. According to the advertising, the product
also ``removes stains, reduces plaque, fights bacteria and promotes
healthy gum tissue.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: A friend brought me a fabulous body lotion from Israel made
by Ahava. Does anyone in Atlanta carry this line?
</P>
<P>
   _ Carol Wyatt, Duluth, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: Ahava, Hebrew for love, is a hypoallergenic line of skin-care
products containing Dead Sea minerals _ calcium, potassium and
magnesium _ vital to skin cells. The line, manufactured at a
kibbutz on the banks of the sea, includes cleansers, lotions, bath
salts, soaps and mud masques for hair and body. Price: $9-$60.
Specially priced kits with one or more products are available.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy the products at: Wildwood Flowers &AMP; Gifts, 692 N.
Glynn St., Fayetteville (770-716-0702); King's Drugs, 2345
Peachtree Road N.E. (404-233-2101); Dakota J's, 1030 N. Highland
N.E. (404-870-0690); and Nordstrom, Perimeter Mall (770-394-1141).
Or shop online at www.ahava.com. If you prefer, call 1-800-252-4282
for a catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am trying to find rough or Turkish towels.
</P>
<P>
   _ G.R. Blackley, Conyers, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: No, you don't have to travel to Turkey for Turkish towels,
which are thick terry-cloth cotton towels. Order them through the
Hammacher Schlemmer catalog at 1-800-543-3366. The Web site is
www.hammacher.com. A bath towel, 27 inches by 55 inches, is $29.95.
An oversize bath sheet, 39 by 70 inches, is $49.95. These towels,
according to the catalog, are 47 percent heavier than comparable
bath linens. Their 1/4-inch-thick pile makes them exceptionally
soft, while ``69,000 tightly wound loops offer superior warmth and
absorbency.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I find a Steak Button? It is about 3 inches long,
with a 1-inch dial and a probe about 2 inches long. The probe is
inserted into a steak before cooking and, when the steak is
finished to your specificati
</P>
