<HEADER>
A6944 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w BC-DRUGS-MISTAKES-0810-C     08-09 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGS-MISTAKES-0810-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEDICAL MISTAKES BLAMED FOR NURSING HOME INJURIES
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Medical error accounts for most of the frequent
medication-related injuries in nursing homes, a new study has
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Of 546 cases examined, more than half could have been prevented,
says the report to be published next week in the American Journal
of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The study ``offers an incredible opportunity to impact
meaningfully on the health of a very vulnerable patient
population,'' said Jerry H. Gurwitz, the University of
Massachusetts Medical School professor who led the research team.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the study, which focused on 18 nursing homes in
Massachusetts, found that the more serious incidents tended to be
the most preventable.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all of the mistakes could be traced either to
prescription errors or negligent nursing care, the report says.
</P>
<P>
   In about half of the 276 ``preventable'' cases, physicians
ordered incorrect doses, prescribed drugs with harmful interactions
or chose the wrong medication. In the other cases, injury from
medication was traced to improper monitoring, such as a failure by
the nursing staff to notice or respond to symptoms of drug
toxicity.
</P>
<P>
   Medications most often involved in medical errors were
psychoactive drugs (including antidepressants and sedatives) and
anticoagulants, which are taken to reduce blood clotting.
</P>
<P>
   The research team also found 188 instances of drug reactions
that almost resulted in injuries. About 80 percent of these ``near
misses'' were traced to the blood thinner warfarin.
</P>
<P>
   ``This study points out that it's not just a small list of
so-called 'bad drugs' in the elderly that we need to be concerned
about, it's the whole range of drugs,'' Gurwitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Applied nationwide, the findings indicate that an average-sized
nursing home (106 beds) would have at least 24 adverse drug
incidents a year. That would mean that among the 1.5 million U.S.
nursing home residents, there are at least 350,000
medication-related injuries annually and that the majority of those
cases could be avoided.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier Institute of Medicine study estimated that medication
errors in U.S. hospitals cause 40,000 to 100,000 deaths a year.
</P>
<P>
   The nursing home research, sponsored by the National Institute
on Aging, called for more systematic, computer-assisted ways to
monitor prescription drugs for nursing home residents, who average
six medications each.
</P>
<P>
   However, the report did not call for penalizing nursing homes or
physicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``One approach is to seek out and punish health care providers
who make errors that lead to adverse drug events,'' the report
concludes, ``but that approach ignores the fact that failures in
the design of systems of care often contribute to the occurrence of
medical errors, as well as the injuries that result from some of
those errors.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the report called for ``enhanced surveillance and
reporting'' of drug-related injuries and continued education on the
proper use of drug therapies in the frail elderly population.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 1708EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
