<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SHARK-SUITS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     IF THE SWIMMING SUIT FITS, WEAR IT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GWEN KNAPP  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The dress code came. The dress code went. Then
the guest list grew and grew until the U.S. Olympic Swimming Trials
turned into one of those weddings where the second cousin of the
groom's barber ends up with an engraved invitation.
</P>
<P>
   The theme of these trials, which begin their eight-day run
Wednesday, is excess. More swimmers, more races, more fabric.
</P>
<P>
   It may be appropriate since the Olympic team picked here will go
on to Australia, where the significance of swimming is blown out of
proportion in a manner akin to the ``Tiger Woods, World Savior''
frenzy gripping the sports media in this part of the globe.
</P>
<P>
   But the Olympic trials should be designed for elitism, sorting
out the best swimmers, not excess. U.S. Swimming lowered the
qualifying standards for this year's meet, hoping to let younger
swimmers gain experience. A total of 1,306 people made the times.
Four years ago, only 570 did.
</P>
<P>
   Picture a jammed pool for warmups and preliminary heats that
stack up all afternoon. As Tom Malchow, the world-record holder in
the 200-meter butterfly, says: ``It isn't pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he wasn't talking about difficulty getting into a
crowded pool. He was talking about the complications of getting
into his bathing suit. It is an innovative full-body outfit,
completely different from the microscopic slashes of Lycra that men
have worn in competitive swimming for ages. Malchow finds himself
morphing into an Olympic gymnast, hopping and twisting every which
way, just to pull the suit on. The process takes at least five
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   For the trials, wriggling into the suit took much longer. U.S.
Swimming initially banned the new product, known as the ``shark
suit'' because the fabric allegedly mimics the sleek skin of a
shark. The suit would be permitted in the Olympics, but the
governing body feared that some competitors wouldn't be able to get
one in time for the meet.
</P>
<P>
   A little saber-ratting from the lawyers for a manufacturer
changed that policy. Malchow will wear the suit, which he believes
helps him ride higher in the water. Some other swimmers find it
constricting, and they'll stick to the traditional, skimpy garb.
The only remaining excess in this controversy will surface when the
shark suit hits the open market after the Olympics _ at a price of
$250.
</P>
<P>
   Even the timing of this meet goes to extremes. It is very, very
unfashionably late.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 1711EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
