<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Aug. 10, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Strong thunderstorms will erupt Thursday across parts of the
Tennessee Valley and Middle Atlantic states in the vicinity of a
front on the leading edge of less humid air. In the wake of the
front, humidity levels will recede from Wednesday's sultry levels
across the eastern Great Lakes and much of the Northeast. Humidity
levels will only slowly ebb over parts of the northern Middle
Atlantic Seaboard, where the southern end of the front slows.
</P>
<P>
   Tropical Depression Four will raise the chance of showers and
thunderstorms along Florida's east coast from about Daytona south.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated to widely separated thunderstorms will develop later
Thursday over the mountains of southern Montana and northern
Wyoming as a cool front approaches. Storms will then move toward
the high plains of the western Dakotas.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: TROPICAL INFLATION &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The National Hurricane Center christened Tropical Depression
Four Wednesday morning, a small, modestly swirling group of showers
and thunderstorms 120 miles northeast of Freeport, the Bahamas.
Before satellites, such a diminutive system might have gone
unnoticed unless a ship navigated into it. Even Tropical Storm
Alberto, which early this week was a hurricane over the remote
Atlantic, might have escaped detection before the 1960s. By virtue
of technology, the modern count of tropical systems tends to be
inflated compared with tallies before satellites.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
