<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-POLITICS-360&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBATTLED INDONESIAN PRESIDENT GIVES UP ROLE IN DAY-TO-DAY
ADMINISTRATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Battered by a hostile parliament for his
haphazard managment style, President Abdurrahman Wahid said
Wednesday that he would hand over daily government administration
to Vice President Megawati Sukarnoputri.
</P>
<P>
   His announcement came after a day of raucous attacks on Tuesday
in a legislature where he can count on the support of only a small
minority and where some members have called for his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regarding the criticisms of my style of management, I can
understand them and I will assign the vice president to handle the
daily tasks of management, to draw up the cabinet's working agenda
and to establish the focus and priorities of government,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the speech, read by an aide because the president is
virtually blind, he emphasized that Megawati would report to him
and that the arrangement was within the constitutional framework of
the presidential system.
</P>
<P>
   It was a retreat for Wahid after 10 tumultuous months in office,
but perhaps a tactical one as he fends off threats from almost all
sides, including the much of the tenuous coalition that voted him
into office.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear, in the long run, whether it would calm the
political scene, where uncertainty and disarray have caused the
currency to slide in value and investors to withhold their business
from Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid had said on Monday that he would appoint a deputy to
handle the daily affairs of government while he concentrated more
on external affairs. Prominent parliamentary figures immediately
insisted that Megawati be named.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear how this devolution of his duties would be
implemented and aides said the details of the arrangement remained
to be worked out. Megawati herself, though politically popular, is
not a hands-on manager and the possibility remained that a separate
``first minister'' would be named to report to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose it amounts to facing a new reality and new
expectations and making the best of a complex and difficult
situation,'' said Aristides Katoppo, an editor and political
commentator. ``There may still be compromises within the
compromise.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Greg Barton, an Australian academic who is writing Wahid's
biography and has daily access to him, said: ``We'll have to wait
and see in the next days. I think we've just seen a fairly slick
bit of footwork. He's seized the initiative and turned it around on
his own terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Megawati won a large plurality in June 1999 in
Indonesia's first democratic election, Wahid triumphed in the
parliamentary session in October that formally chose the president.
</P>
<P>
   He had won only a small portion of the popular vote but was the
compromise choice of legislators who opposed Megawati. Now much of
that coalition has turned against him as Indonesian politics
descends into a free-for-all.
</P>
<P>
   Some political commentators said Wednesday that Wahid's
opponents, having failed to manipulate him in office, might be
hoping that Megawati may be a softer target.
</P>
<P>
   The new arrangement, if it does move forward, throws Indonesia's
leadership into new flux, analysts said. The relationship between
the president and vice president has been difficult and their
political constituencies remain at odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably a necessary but insufficient condition for
trying to reach a deal,'' a Western diplomat said of the
announcement. ``What has got to be done is to see whether the offer
is accepted and how it works in practice. The devil is in the
details and the modalities.''
</P>
<P>
   Wahid had already handed certain responsibilities to his vice
president _ including management of separatist and sectarian
violence in Irian Jaya and the Maluku islands _ but she had been
largely passive as those crises worsened, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Though Wahid described their relations on Monday as like a
brother and sister, their dealings in recent weeks have been
severely strained. Megawati failed to attend his birthday party
last week and declined his request to read recent speeches on his
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the issue is whether they can establish a modus vivendi to
really work these things out,'' the diplomat said. ``If she is to
be a kind of de facto prime minister, the question will be whether
she is prepared to exercise power and whether the president and
vice president are prepared to work together in a constructive
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Megawati, the daughter of Indonesia's founding father, Sukarno,
enjoys broad and enthusiastic public support. She has shown little
appetite for political battle or active leadership, but she has put
together a solid team of aides.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid has earned widespread respect for his integrity and
democratic ideals but demonstrated little aptitude for
administration. In addition, he has found himself in charge of weak
and incompetent government institutions that were neutered and
corrupted during the 32-year rule of President Suharto, who was
forced from office in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Often, when Wahid pulls the levers of power, little happens.
</P>
<P>
   But he has shown himself a master of one-upmanship, disarming
his challengers with unexpected moves that Barton, his biographer,
recently compared to the deceptively agile cut and thrust of the
blind swordsman of martial arts films.
</P>
<P>
   After his address Wednesday evening, Barton said, the president
seemed to be in high spirits. ``He turned to me and he said,
chuckling, `So the drunken master wins again.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
