<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISTORY-ONTHETABLE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALLAS EXHIBIT RANGES FROM FINE CHINA TO TV TRAYS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ANDREW MARTON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Memory comes alive at the Dallas Museum of Art's current
exhibition, ``Tabletop to TV Tray: China and Glass in America,
1880-1980.'' In this retrospective setting, the banal plate, bowl
and jug suddenly take on artistic totem status, displaying a
swanlike grace and sparkling color palette.
</P>
<P>
   Through more than 500 objects, ``Tabletop to TV Tray'' spans 100
years of how America surrounded itself with objects from which to
nibble or gorge, imbibe or quaff with abandon. The viewer tours a
range of domestic tableware, including fine crystal, delicately
etched china and highly practical refrigerator containers.
</P>
<P>
   All the recognizable names have been assembled from yesteryear's
pantries. Baccarat and Wedgwood, Lenox and Spode, Waterford and
Steuben are just a few of the labels whose furnishings have been
part of so many generations' sideboards.
</P>
<P>
   This exhibition is also a rearview mirror on a century's worth
of social history. It is a highly democratic undertaking,
displaying elite White House china and glassware side-by-side with
that 1960s staple, the foldable TV tray. The bridal registry (for
the record, the practice started in Marshall Field's grand
department store in the 1930s) is celebrated for its seismic social
contribution.
</P>
<P>
   Although organized in only a lazy chronology (one of the few
miscues), the exhibition traipses back to the latter years of the
1800s, when dining was a heavily starched affair full of Victorian
ceremony and unassailable refinement. Majolica dinnerware featured
almost comically extravagant use of flowers, fruit and game motifs
on everything from beer steins to bulbous casseroles. Wealth was
celebrated in the manufacture of dozens of specialized dishes: an
indented one for oysters, an apothecarylike jar for pickles. Lacy
Limoges porcelain was a period staple, but perhaps nothing marked
the apogee of status better than the ``Grand Prize'' pattern punch
bowl of 1905. The bowl on exhibit is molded with so many facets
that it glitters with the fire of a diamond.
</P>
<P>
   As the 20th century dawned, it heralded the emergence of the
middle class and a lifestyle demanding more practicality and less
precious beauty from its tableware. The 1920s saw the heavier use
of the striated ``Pyramid'' and ``Tea Room'' patterns for glasses
and jugs, in addition to designs featuring colored enamels and
gilding. America would come to consider the unbreakable quality of
Pyrex glass a miracle hybrid of cooking and tableware.
Advertisements from Corning Glass Works from the period called
dining ``an art'' when Pyrex was involved. Meantime, Tiffin Glass
introduced a heavily etched jug, made to hold the novelty of the
day, iced tea.
</P>
<P>
   The 1930s produced a panoply of novelty containers for every
kind of food, from spaghetti sets to egg and corn holders. This
decade was also a launching pad for the eye-catching shapes and
mustard and salmon tints of ``American Modern'' tableware, in
addition to the molded fanning of dishes seen in ``Petalware.''
Acid-etching on glass in the early '30s resulted in whole art-deco
scenes played out on the sides of dining goblets.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, Wedgwood managed to induce the most
conservative of Americans to add English bone china (the
``Josephine'' and ``Wildflower'' lines) to their table settings.
Postwar America was a land inebriated by victory, with a giddiness
seen in china sets rife with speckles, stripes and geometric grids.
Late 1940s shapes are softly rounded with burnished edges, with the
``Jubilee'' set all shades of pale cream and mint.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, martini shakers and backyard barbecues accent the
flashy way to entertain. Charles Murphy's delicately swirling
casserole dishes appear on tables while stemware, mostly cut in a
clean-lined, Swedish style, emerges in every hue from transparent
to rose-petal red. Dansk Designs almost singlehandedly popularizes
stoneware worldwide with its hard, matte finish and understated
form. And Northern Industrial Chemical Company comes up with
plastic designs that mold pursed-lipped edges onto various oval
containers.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, the new and socially domineering medium of television
barges into the dining hour, requiring even more casual forms of
china and the birth of the stackable TV tray table _ the perfect
companion for 1954's newly introduced Swanson TV dinner. The
invention of the automatic dishwasher all but eliminates the
once-robust sales of fine china, and also forces dinnerware to
become more resistant to crude detergents.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1960s, radiant color schemes and trippy patterns spill
all over table settings. The ``Man in Space'' series illustrates
the surreal themes often played out on the plate. Still, hard-core
endurance was a selling point as Corning advertised its ``Centura''
tableware as being as delicate as porcelain but able to pass the
``3,000 meal test.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit all but genuflects before the White House's
unwavering standard of dining refinement. There is an oyster plate,
chosen by Mrs. Rutherford B. Hayes, who also added the special
touch of American animal and flower ornamentation to the forever
classic Limoges design. Some of the infamous Reagan White House
1981 china, in its nouveau regal-blue-and-white pattern, is on
display. There's also an iced-tea glass that was selected for the
White House by Jackie Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   The intersection of the various global art movements, such as
cubism, and day-to-day glass and china appears in the ``Ruba
Rombic'' plate, salad plate, sherbet glass and tumbler. First
bowing during a 1928 glass and china exposition in Pittsburgh, this
set celebrates all the clean-lined cubist angularity. The
between-the-wars Bauhaus movement is shown to best effect in a 1930
tea set, with its bravura display of conical shapes with
disk-shaped attachments. Later, the ``Freeform'' butter dish and
``California Aztec'' patterned plate reflect the disparate
influences of sculptors such as Alexander Calder and Henry Moore.
</P>
<P>
   And no tabletop exhibit would be complete without a bow to the
mass migration of the American middle class toward the wilds of
outdoor dining. ``Tamac'' tableware of the 1940s accessorized much
of this movement with its wavy-gravy shapes and distinctive rainbow
of tints from avocado green to ``frosty fudge'' brown.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, what perhaps brands this exhibition as triumphant is
the wave of nostalgia that it sends washing over any patron. The
mere sight of a Danish modern bit of stemware, or the rough
geometric shapes emblazoned on numerous plates, should be enough to
send anyone scurrying down to the cellar, rummaging for that
discarded accessory of a past repast.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
