<HEADLINE>
GEEK NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Palms Emphasize Price, Power and Color  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just as the stores are stuffed with all the new fashions for
fall, the fresh hot gadgets are beginning to roll out into the
marketplace as well. Earlier this week, Palm Inc. announced its new
product lineup, which includes a low-priced entry-level version of
the Palm organizer, a RAM infusion for the company's wireless model
and two new limited editions of the Palm Vx.
</P>
<P>
   Palm's new low-end organizer, the m100, has new applications and
a simple cable for synchronizing the device to a desktop computer _
all for about $149, which would be the lowest price for a Palm to
date. The new Palm has all the standard applications for things
like addresses and a calendar plus an electronic notepad that lets
people use their own handwriting to jot down phone numbers and
reminders. A new clock application, which displays the time through
a small window in the m100s fliptop case, can be activated with the
press of a button on the front of the unit.
</P>
<P>
   The m100, with two megabytes of RAM, is aimed more at home users
than at business executives or professionals with more demanding
needs for personal digital assistants. Following the lead of Nokia,
which makes available colorful covers for cell phones, Palm is
offering snap-on faceplates in different colors for the m100. Each
plate costs around $20.
</P>
<P>
   The company's Palm VII device, which has attracted a great
number of handheld users seeking instant and integrated wireless
access, is getting just what its critics said it needed: more
memory. The new Palm VIIx, priced at $449, will now be packing
eight megabytes of RAM (up from two megabytes) and twice as many
Web clipping applications as were offered by the original wireless
effort. Users will get 40 of the streamlined-for-the-handheld Web
programs, like CBS MarketWatch.com and Travelocity.com, right out
of the box, and more than 400 applications are available for
downloading from the www.palm.net site.
</P>
<P>
   And it wouldn't be fall without some color, so fans of the
company's popular Palm Vx unit can now choose between a
``millennium blue'' and a goldish ``champagne'' aluminum casing.
The limited-edition devices are available for $399 each at the
company's site.
</P>
<P>
   _ By J.D.BIERSDORFER
</P>
<P>
   Translation Tool Knocks Down Language Barriers for Pen Pals
</P>
<P>
   For years, teachers have been matching their students with pen
pals in foreign countries to encourage them to learn about other
cultures. But language barriers have always been a huge hurdle for
both teachers and students.
</P>
<P>
   Now ePals.com, an education Web site, is using translation
technology to eliminate that problem. Students using the site, at
www.epals.com, compose e-mail messages in their native languages
and then click on a button for automatic translations. So far, the
system lets students switch from English to one of a number of
languages: French, German, Japanese, Italian, Spanish and
Portuguese, or from those languages to English. Several other
combinations, like Spanish to Italian, are also possible. ``This is
the Internet's first e-mail service with language translation
available right within the Web browser,'' said Tim DiScipio,
ePals.com's chief executive and co-founder.
</P>
<P>
   The site provides other tools, too, like a database of high
schools that are interested in pairing (more than 65,000 classrooms
in 182 countries are participating) and filtering software. By the
fall, the service will also include materials from Scholastic.com,
a large educational service that has formed a partnership with
ePals.com to trade content and translation services.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LISA GUERNSEY
</P>
<P>
   A New Home Laser Printer At a Low Inkjet-Printer Price
</P>
<P>
   Computer users seeking a laser printer at those low, low inkjet
prices will find just the thing on the market later this month.
Samsung Electronics is rolling out the ML-4500, a small, versatile
laser printer for the unusually low street price of $199.
</P>
<P>
   The Samsung ML-4500, which prints in black and white, works with
systems running Windows 95 or later. It will also work with Linux
and uses a parallel port to connect to the computer. The ML-4500
can print up to 8 pages per minute and has a resolution of 600 dots
per inch. The printer also features something called ``N-up
printing mode,'' which the company says can be used to print up to
16 minipages of text on one piece of paper, thus creating an index
sheet to help find your way through long documents.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike their slower, less-expensive inkjet brethren, which shoot
small drops of ink onto the paper to create text and images, laser
printers use a printing process similar to that of a photocopier.
Even though laser-printer prices have fallen quite a bit, this
printing method, which is generally faster and produces
higher-quality prints, usually costs more than inkjet printers.
</P>
<P>
   The $199 price, which is about $100 cheaper than for many other
printers in its category, may appeal to buyers for price alone.
Samsung is also touting the ML-4500 for its ``paper-jam-free
technology.'' For anyone who has had to extract bits of the
company's annual report from a printer's innards while on deadline,
the ML-4500 could pay for itself rather quickly.
</P>
<P>
   _ By J.D. BIERSDORFER
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now You Can Your Show From Just About Anywhere
</P>
<P>
   In what the company calls ``the ultimate remote control,''
owners of ReplayTV-based digital video recorders may soon be able
to operate their recorders at home from anywhere in the world
through the Internet. For example, a New Yorker traveling in Texas
would be able to log on to the www.myreplaytv.com Web site, view
hometown program listings, set the recorder to capture a show, view
the amount of recording time left on the disk and make sure that
the show is being recorded. Of course, that's assuming that the
system works as described yesterday. ReplayTV concedes that it has
not been tested outside the laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   The new service, called MyReplayTV, will be available this fall,
when ReplayTV upgrades the system software for its recorders, said
Jim Hollingsworth, a senior vice president for the company, which
is in Mountain View, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the more common videocassette recorders, digital video
recorders capture programs as digital files on a giant hard disk;
users can easily skip through commercials and other tedious parts
of a program. A ReplayTV recorder with 30 hours of capacity costs
about $600, and one with 20 hours costs $400 to $500. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ By PETER H.LEWIS
</P>
