<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-EYEGLASSES-TEC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLASSES THAT LIGHT UP THE DAY MAY ALSO LIGHTEN GLOOMY SPIRITS
</HEADLINE>
 By CATHERINE GREENMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For people who become depressed when the days grow short, a
condition called seasonal affective disorder, one treatment is to
sit in front of bright light for an hour or more each day. But a
common complaint of patients is that they do not have time to do
that regularly.
</P>
<P>
   One solution is to have patients wear light visors, with either
incandescent or white light-emitting diodes (LEDs) under the brims.
That lets the patients move around while they get extra light, but
some doctors question the effectiveness of the visors, saying the
light exposure is inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
   One company, Enlightened Technologies Associates, based in
Fairfax, Va. (www.etai.com), says it has developed special glasses,
called Somnavue, that can deliver light therapy more effectively to
people who need it. Light therapy is also used to help people with
sleep disorders and jet lag, in additional to those with seasonal
affective disorder.
</P>
<P>
   The glasses are attached by a fiber-optic bundle to a
Walkman-size box, worn on the belt or in a pocket, containing
battery-powered LEDs. They produce light that goes through the
fibers to the eyeglasses' frames, at the back of the ears. The
light moves through the frame to six optical fibers that ring the
middle of each lens. Each fiber is linked to its own red, green or
blue LED, and they aim light at the pupil at angles that get light
to the periphery of the retina without interfering with vision, or
being obvious to other people.
</P>
<P>
   Light therapy is thought to be effective for conditions like
seasonal affective disorder or jet lag because light is the most
powerful environmental cue for setting the daily biological
rhythms, called circadian rhythms, that affect things like hormone,
sleep and mood cycles. Light exposure signals an area of the brain
called the suprachiasmatic nucleus, a cluster of cells near the
spot where the optic nerves cross. The brain sends information
about light to the pineal gland, which is at the base of the brain
and produces a hormone called melatonin, which helps regulate
circadian rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of light a person is exposed to determines how much
melatonin is released from the pineal gland and carried through the
bloodstream. The pineal's melatonin production peaks during the
night; light drives melatonin levels down.
</P>
<P>
   A clock and a microprocessor in the Somnavue control box can be
programmed to turn the lens light on and off at specified times of
day, and the light intensity can be regulated.
</P>
<P>
   Enlightened Technologies received a research grant to develop
the glasses from the National Institutes of Health. It has
conducted several studies in the last couple of years with Columbia
University and Northwestern University on Somnavue's effect in
seasonal affective disorder and sleep disorders.
</P>
<P>
   In the winter of 1998-99, early prototypes of the glasses were
used in a study conducted on patients with seasonal affective
disorder at the Sleep Disorders Institute at St. Luke's-Roosevelt
Hospital Center in New York. Dr. Gary K. Zammit, director of the
institute, said the glasses had been tested on 17 people; nine were
exposed to high-intensity light and eight were exposed to lower
intensities.
</P>
<P>
   ``What struck us was that even the low-intensity groups got
better,'' Zammit said. ``It may have been a placebo, or that even
low-intensity light had some biological effect. But by the third
week, there was a statistical improvement in both groups.''
</P>
<P>
   The glasses send light toward the eyes even as the person
wearing them moves, something that bright light boxes or light
visors can not do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The light boxes didn't provide the uniformity of exposure
because people using them could just look away, and the light
visors were only bringing light in from one direction and hitting
the eye at an angle that didn't allow for maximum exposure,''
Zammit said.
</P>
<P>
   Next winter, Zammit said, the Sleep Disorders Institute will
study the effect of the glasses on patients' melatonin levels and
sleep and depression patterns.
</P>
<P>
   At Northwestern University Medical School in Chicago, the
glasses were tested on older patients with sleep problems that made
them wake up too early in the morning, before they had slept
enough.
</P>
<P>
   Each patient wore the glasses for about two hours between 8 p.m.
and 10 p.m. at very high light levels, between 1,400 and 2,000 lux
(brighter than most offices), for several weeks. The study
concluded that the glasses did as good a job at helping people's
sleep patterns as did putting patients in front of light boxes for
their light therapy.
</P>
<P>
   With the glasses on, people could read or walk around, which
they could not do when using a light box.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that light works, but it's so impractical that even
patients who find it effective can't afford to sit for an hour in
front of a light box,'' said Dr. Phyllis C. Zee, a neurology
professor who is director of the sleep disorders program at
Northwestern University Medical School. ``The advantage of these
glasses is that they're more practical, and they're something more
patients will be able to use.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though some of the prototype models did not fit some of the
patients' faces exactly, Zee said, the colored lights emitted by
the lens fibers had a more soothing effect than the direct bright
light of a light box.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were much easier and soothing on the eyes,'' she said,
``because they had this wonderful color spectrum.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman said the glasses were also designed to treat jet lag. A
person traveling from New York to England, for example, could
arrive in England in the morning, avoid bright light for a few
hours, then use the glasses for about three hours in the afternoon
(morning in New York) to reset the biological clock to England's
time, Goldman said.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Charmane Eastman, director of the Biological Rhythms
Research Laboratory at Rush-Presbyterian-St. Luke's Medical Center
in Chicago, said that a single light treatment would be unlikely to
shift someone's biological clock more than two or three hours.
</P>
<P>
   Enlightened Technologies is seeking the Food and Drug
Administration's approval for Somnavue and talking to manufacturers
about producing test models. Goldman said the company had recently
received another grant from the National Institutes of Health to
look at how the glasses might be used to track the slow eye
movements that indicate fatigue. That would let researchers find
out how tired people became while working late shifts in factories,
for example.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fiber can transmit light in both directions, so we could
take the reflection from the eye and analyze that back in the
control box,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 1747EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
