<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOING IT YOUR WAY: SORTING AND COPYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Is there a way to put my Internet Explorer 5.0 Favorites in
the order I want them, instead of in the order I collected them?
</P>
<P>
   A. There are a couple of ways for you to rearrange the Web sites
on your Favorites list to your liking.
</P>
<P>
   You can click on the names of the sites and drag them to where
you want them to go.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a large number of sites bookmarked and would like a
quicker method of arranging them, you can put them into
alphabetical order. To do that, click once on the Favorites menu in
your Explorer menu bar, then right-click on any of the sites on the
list. Select Sort by Name to rearrange the list alphabetically by
site name.
</P>
<P>
   If you use folders within your Favorites list, you will need to
open each folder and right-click to sort by name.
</P>
<P>
   Macintosh users running Internet Explorer 5.0 should click on
the Favorites tab on the left side of the browser window, then on
the Organize button.
</P>
<P>
   Select Open Favorites Window and click on the Name button at the
top of the column to sort them alphabetically.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are MP3 files illegal, or is it trading them that is against
the law?
</P>
<P>
   A. An MP3 audio file itself is not illegal. MP3 is a computer
file format that allows the conversion of music from a compact disc
or other audio source into a small, good-quality computer file.
</P>
<P>
   It is what is done with MP3 files after they are made that has
become controversial, as illustrated by the current legal fight
between Napster and the Recording Industry Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   Napster is one of the Web services that allow people to search
for MP3 files online and download them _ or upload their own MP3
files.
</P>
<P>
   The use of MP3 files falls under U.S. copyright law, and the
recording industry group says that Napster contributes to copyright
infringement. (For anyone interested in the Copyright Law of the
United States itself, a complete version can be downloaded in text
or Portable Document Format at lcweb.loc.gov/copyright/title17.)
</P>
<P>
   Converting songs from a CD to the MP3 format so that you can
play them on your computer or a portable MP3 player is legal as
long as you paid for the original CD.
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, it is just like making a tape from albums in
your music collection for your personal use. As long as you do not
publicly redistribute the music without authorization from the
copyright holder, making a copy for private use is currently fine.
</P>
<P>
   Many songs that surface on the Internet were probably copied
from their original sources and distributed illegally, but there
are many sites where you can legally download and listen to MP3
files.
</P>
<P>
   The recording artists _ most of them not signed with a record
label _ who created the songs on those sites, like the ones found
on MP3.com (www.mp3.com), have given the site permission to
distribute their songs.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I keep getting a ``disk is locked'' message when trying to
copy a file to a floppy. Is it my old Mac or the disk that's bad?
</P>
<P>
   A. The problem is most probably with the floppy disk, but it's
not as bad as it might seem. On the back of the disk, you should
see a small plastic tab in a corner. If that tab is in the ``up''
position, exposing a small hole in the disk, then the disk has been
locked to prevent anyone from overwriting the files on it.
</P>
<P>
   To unlock it, slide the tab to the lower position and reinsert
the floppy into your drive. Windows users who are getting ``cannot
write'' messages while trying to save a file to a floppy should
check the tab on the disk as well.
</P>
<P>
   The lock is similar to the cassette-tape tabs that you can punch
out to keep the tape from being copied over. The machine senses
whether the tab is there and stops you from overwriting a
write-protected disk.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
e-mail to Q&AMP;A(at)nytimes.com or mail to Questions, Circuits, The
New York Times, 229 West 43rd Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959.
This column will answer questions of general interest, but letters
cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
