<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOGA-WORKPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY JOB: YOGURT THIS IS NOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Jack England is a yoga instructor, Club Med Sandpiper, Port St.
Lucie, Fla.; this was written with TANYA MOHN)  
 By JACK ENGLAND   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I teach every day, seven days a week. I'm on stage three or four
nights a week in different shows. I do things that 16-year-old
girls can't do. I didn't start yoga until I was about 50, and I'm
79 now.
</P>
<P>
   Some people are frightened by the word yoga. They think I'm
going to twist their mind or something. We don't do the meditation
here; we do the physical aspects of yoga. Stretching is something
that you can do all your life _ in your 70s, 80s and 90s. There's
no bouncing, no jumping. When you stretch, your veins and arteries
become more elastic, improving your circulation.
</P>
<P>
   I remember I was warming up once in one of the conference rooms
here and I saw some people go by. I brought one leg straight up
over my head and touched the wall behind me, parallel to my ear,
and I heard the child say to her mother: ``Look. That man has only
one leg.''
</P>
<P>
   And that exercise is really so simple. Some of the stuff I do is
even more surprising to people. I've got a board that I made so I
can get up on a headstand in a water ski show that I'm in on Monday
afternoons. As we go past the audience, I'm in a shoulder stand.
Then I come into splits, then lotus up and down. I'm down in a wake
so you don't see my head. The announcer is saying, ``He is now
holding his breath for 7, 8, 9, 10, 11 minutes.'' Of course, I'm
breathing all the time, but you can't see that 'cause you can't see
my head.
</P>
<P>
   During the Korean War, I was shot down and I fractured my back,
so I lost a year out of my life in the hospital. As a result of
physical therapy, I became more conscious of my body, so somebody
took me to a yoga class one day.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't know yoga from yogurt. But I worked on these various
different aspects of flexibility, and it just got easier and
easier. It changed my life.
</P>
<P>
   I retired after 44 years as an electronic engineer with the
Department of Defense and started traveling around the world going
to different health spas and yoga ashrams, getting ideas for
something that I would like to own, and I dropped in at Club Med
Ixtapa, in Mexico. I put on a yoga demonstration, and they asked me
to stay. That was 16 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Most disease is stress-related. It's usually the damn job or the
boss. Learn how to calm yourself down, breathe abdominally like a
baby in a crib. When you suck in that stomach all the time, that's
creating tension and stress.
</P>
<P>
   When men have their first heart attacks and survive, they go off
to a health spa, and for the first times ever they eat the right
food. All of a sudden they get their bodies back to their skinny
high-school weight, and they get one more chance to get it right.
</P>
<P>
   I once said to a woman, ``Keep your husband thin and you will
keep him longer.'' She whispered in my ear, ``I don't want to keep
him any longer.'' The world is filled with widows. Just load your
husband up with eggs and red meat, keep him smoking and you can
finish him off before he reaches 50!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 1748EDT &QL; 
