<DOCNO> NYT20000809.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6976 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0810-COX     08-09 2966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0810-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Show me your roots, I'll show you mine
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore and Joseph Lieberman focused their first day campaigning
together on ``shared values,'' but also confronted the nuanced
differences between them on school vouchers and abortion. ``I'm not
afraid to have a vice president who disagrees with me on some
issues,'' Gore said at an elementary school in his home town of
Carthage, Tenn. ``The policy will be the policy I decide.'' Said
Lieberman: ``The differences are very, very few. We share values;
we share a vision for the future.'' After Tennessee, the newly
minted team was headed to Lieberman's home town of Stamford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST SOLO STOP FOR CHENEY: HOMELESS SHELTER
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney visited a homeless shelter in St. Louis today on his
first solo campaign trip, touting George W. Bush's plan to help
faith-based groups that serve the poor. Cheney began a three-day
swing through Missouri, Ohio, Kentucky and Illinois at the the
Sunshine Mission, a privately funded Christian homeless shelter
with a rehab center for drug addicts and services for needy
families. As part of his ``compassionate conservative'' campaign,
Bush has called for partnerships between the government and
churches, charitable organizations and individuals who provide
services or donate money to fight the nation's social ills.
</P>
<P>
   SCORING ON ABORTION RIGHTS FRONT
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton is winning the battle against Senate rival Rick
Lazio when it comes to convincing New York voters who is the
stronger abortion rights supporter, a statewide poll reported
today. The Quinnipiac University Polling Institute found that 56
percent of voters said the first lady would be a strong supporter
of abortion rights in the Senate, while just 8 percent felt that
way about the Long Island congressman. Forty-five percent of New
York voters said abortion should be ``generally available to those
who want it'' while 13 percent said ``abortion should not be
permitted.'' Another 39 percent said abortion should be available,
but with stricter limits.
</P>
<P>
   REFORM SPLIT BRINGING ANOTHER CONVENTION?
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party forces opposed to ex-Republican Pat Buchanan as the
party's presidential candidate split from the group today and
started organizing their own convention to nominate someone else.
But Buchanan campaign officials said they had the delegates to win
the nomination and would press ahead with the planned convention,
which they said was the only legitimate Reform Party gathering. The
convention is slated to formally start Thursday in Long Beach,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   BUCHANAN'S BATTLE TOO MUCH UPHILL
</P>
<P>
   As Pat Buchanan fights to secure the Reform Party nomination
this week, an even bigger battle lies ahead: winning over the
public. Only 17 percent of Americans say they'd seriously consider
voting for Buchanan, according to an ABCNEWS.com poll _ and that's
more a cap on his support than a base, since just considering a
candidate is a far cry from supporting him. Buchanan's actual
support for president is only 4 percent. In addition, just 17
percent want to see Buchanan nominated in the first place. And even
fewer, 10 percent, classify themselves as Reform Party supporters _
down from a high of 18 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   CIVIL RIGHTS AND LIEBERMAN
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Jackson said he thinks Al Gore's selection of the Jewish
Joseph Lieberman as his running mate will further break down
barriers of religion and race. ``Let the nation rejoice. The tent
is getting bigger and better,'' Jackson said at his Rainbow/PUSH
Coalition headquarters in Nashville. ``Another barrier falls and
another opportunity arises. A political risk, a moral certainty.''
Gore ``rejected a pattern of discrimination'' that has limited the
political opportunities of minorities, Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   UNCIVIL RIGHTS AND LIEBERMAN
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP is considering suspending its Dallas branch president
for his harsh criticism of Joseph Lieberman. Speaking on a radio
talk show, Lee Alcorn, president of the Dallas NAACP, said, ``If we
get a Jew person, then what I'm wondering is, I mean, what is this
movement for, you know? Does it have anything to do with the failed
peace talks?'' Alcorn continued: ``So I think we need to be very
suspicious of any kind of partnerships between the Jews at that
kind of level because we know that their interest primarily has to
do with money and these kind of things.'' Kweisi Mfume, national
NAACP president. condemned the remarks as ``repulsive,
anti-Semitic, anti-NAACP and anti-American.'' He said he probably
would suspend Alcorn's membership and his position with the Dallas
branch.
</P>
<P>
   BARRAGE ON THE INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Lieberman's selection for the Democratic ticket prompted
a barrage of anti-Semitic comments in online chat rooms and
Internet message boards, leading some online services to start
purging offensive postings. Chat rooms on America Online and Yahoo
were peppered with slurs against Jews. At times, as many as half
the comments included offensive remarks. More than 20,000 comments
have been posted to an AOL message board devoted to conversation
about Lieberman, and many included disparaging references to Jews.
AOL began removing offensive postings, and said it was prepared to
suspend or cancel the accounts of those found to have violated the
service's rules against hate speech, vulgar language or harassment.
</P>
<P>
   HIS FAITH _ AND FAITH IN AMERICANS AND HIMSELF
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Lieberman says the American people will vote for him
based on what they think of him as a person and as a candidate, not
on his religion. An Orthodox Jew, Lieberman dismissed the idea that
anti-Semitism could damage Al Gore's chances of winning the White
House. ``I don't kid myself. I'm sure there are some anti-Semites
out there,'' he said on CNN's ``Larry King Live.'' ``But you know .
. . the American people are so tolerant, they're so open; I'm just
convinced that they're going to vote for me or against me, based,
not on my religion, but based on how they judge me as a person and
whether they think I can do this job.''
</P>
<P>
   PRAYERFUL POLITICS: HOW MUCH IS TOO MUCH?
</P>
<P>
   Normally in national politics it is the Republicans, influenced
for years by the religious right, who wear religion on their
sleeves. But Joseph Lieberman's introductory remarks to the nation
as Al Gore's running mate stood out as a very publicly invoked
display of religious faith and stirred some concern. ``If (the)
speech were the speech he gave every day, I would be troubled about
what he's trying to communicate,'' said Barry Lynn of Americans
United for Separation of Church and State. ``Americans are a
religious people, but they get very nervous, properly so, when
candidates appear to have more to say about their faith than they
do about their solutions to the country's problems.''
</P>
<P>
   LONG PROCESS OF INTEGRATION
</P>
<P>
   The arc of Joseph Lieberman's life neatly encapsulates the
remarkable change in circumstance of American Jews over the past
half-century: a rise to prominence, prosperity and acceptance in a
non-Jewish society. When Lieberman was born in 1942, American Jews
still couldn't buy property in many places in the United States. In
Connecticut, Jewish businessmen still couldn't borrow money locally
and had to drive into New York City to find friendly bankers. When
Lieberman arrived at Yale in the early 1960s, the university still
limited the number of Jewish students it accepted.
</P>
<P>
   GOP FIRES BACK IN ENVIRONMENTAL WARS
</P>
<P>
   A new Republican ad criticizes Al Gore for getting thousands of
dollars in royalty payments from a zinc mining operation on Gore
land in Tennessee, alleging the company has been found polluting a
nearby river. The TV spot, accusing Gore of hypocrisy, also claims
that Gore has been distorting George W. Bush's environmental record
in Texas. Republican officials are spending $3.7 million to run
their new spot in 17 states: Arkansas, Florida, Georgia, Iowa,
Illinois, Kentucky, Louisiana, Maine, Maryland, Michigan, Missouri,
New Mexico, Ohio, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Washington and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   MILLIONS TO GET OUT THE VOTE
</P>
<P>
   Republican Party leaders say they'll raise an unprecedented $100
million to mobilize voters for the Novembsaying that he had no way
of knowing how most senators would have acted, Daschle said, ``A
lot of people felt that by giving that speech, they didn't need to
go further than what he articulated on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   PLAYING POLITICS TO MAKE POLITICS WORK
</P>
<P>
   When Sen. John McCain opened his recent Senate drive to force
secretive political groups _ the so-called 527 groups, named after
their tax-code loophole _ to start disclosing their finances, it
sounded familiar to Joseph Lieberman. There was a good reason: It
started out as Lieberman's bill. But Lieberman's aides say he knew
it would attract more attention with McCain, whose presidential
primary campaign was based on that issue. So Lieberman co-sponsored
McCain's measure, McCain gave Lieberman credit for the idea and,
together, they steered the proposal _ the first successful campaign
reform initiative in two decades _ through all the legislative
traps and into law.
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY INAUGURATION OK
</P>
<P>
   Inauguration Day next year falls on a Saturday, the Jewish
Sabbath. But if Joseph Lieberman is elected vice president, he
could still participate in the ceremony, his rabbi said. Lieberman,
an Orthodox Jew, observes the Sabbath by not working, driving or
writing from sundown Friday to sundown Saturday. But he does vote
when the Senate meets in a rare Saturday session, by citing an
exception in Jewish law that allows work when human life or
national security is at stake. Rabbi Mark Dratch of Congregation
Agudath Sholom of Stamford, Conn., said Lieberman's faith would not
keep him from the festivities on Jan. 20.
</P>
<P>
   PALESTINIANS LESS THAN OVERJOYED
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials have been choosing their words
diplomatically when commenting on the choice of the first Jewish
U.S. vice presidential candidate. But the buzz on the Palestinian
street, according to the Boston Glove, was that this would not
favor their side in the Middle East peace process. ``The real
feeling on the street is that here is another example of the
American unfairness and leaning towards Israel because of the
Jewish vote,'' said political analyst Ghassan Khattib, who heads
the Jerusalem Media and Communications Center. ``This is not good
news for the Palestinians.''
</P>
<P>
   NO MILITARY FOR LIEBERMAN
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Lieberman avoided serving in the Vietnam War with two
deferments, one as a student and another for being a father, said
his spokesman, Eric Kleiman. Lieberman graduated from Yale College
in 1964. He attended Yale Law School for the next three years,
graduating in 1967. Al Gore served five months in Vietnam as an
Army journalist. George W. Bush served in the Texas Air National
Guard, but didn't go to Vietnam. Dick Cheney, who later was a
secretary of defense, avoided military service with deferments as a
student and expectant father.
</P>
<P>
   A CONNECTICUT YANKEE IN DIXIE
</P>
<P>
   For all the kind words Joseph Lieberman is getting in Tennessee,
some Southern analysts don't see him helping Al Gore much in the
South. In fact, with the possible exception of Florida, he could
hurt. The selection of Lieberman ``is probably a signal that Gore
isn't going to make a major pitch for the South,'' said Hastings
Wyman of the Southern Political Report newsletter. Gore lags behind
George W. Bush across the South except in his home state of
Tennessee. And even Tennessee is no cakewalk for the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDWATER AND THE JEWISH QUESTION
</P>
<P>
   The selection of Joseph Lieberman, an Orthodox Jew, as Al Gore's
running mate marks the first time a person of his faith has been
part of a major political party's national ticket. But 36 years
ago, when the late Arizona Sen. Barry Goldwater was running for
president, the conservative Republican was confronted with
questions about his religion because, while he was raised an
Episcopalian, his father was Jewish. Michael Goldwater, grandfather
of the presidential candidate, was a Jewish peddler who left
Russian-ruled Poland in 1849. In his 1988 autobiography, Goldwater
wrote that it was only upon entering Washington politics that ``I
was reminded I was a Jew.''
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON CENTER STAGE ON OPENING NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton will speak Monday night at the opening of the
Democratic convention in Los Angeles as he relinquishes the party's
leadership, making the case why Al Gore should be president and
carry on the legacy of the Clinton-Gore administration. This is no
hurry-up speech: Clinton has been testing it, refining it and
rehearsing it for months. It's the valedictory address of his
presidency, boasting of his achievements, and a political
testimonial for his hoped-for successor. And after last week's
Republican convention, it also will be an answer to George W.
Bush's jabs and barbs. Clinton will speak after his wife, Hillary,
and he'll give her Senate campaign a boost.
</P>
<P>
   BROWNE CATCHES BUCHANAN
</P>
<P>
   The Libertarian Party is hailing a national survey by Rasmussen
Research showing that their presidential candidate, Harry Browne,
is now tied with the Reform Party's Pat Buchanan. Each had 1.6
percent in the Rasmussen three-day rolling average of 2,250 voters.
Green Party candidate Ralph Nader garnered 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ADDRESSING PAST MISTAKES
</P>
<P>
   In a step toward atoning for what many Democrats agree was one
of their party's biggest political blunders, the sons of the late
Pennsylvania Gov. Robert Casey have been invited to the convention.
Casey had asked to speak at the 1992 Democratic convention and
deliver a report opposing the party's platform, which called
``reproductive choice'' a ``fundamental right.'' But the nominees _
Bill Clinton and Al Gore _ wanted the convention to send a message
of unity for abortion rights, and Casey was barred from speaking.
This year, Robert P. Casey Jr., facing re-election as
Pennsylvania's auditor general, and Patrick Casey, a candidate for
Congress, will participate in a video tribute to their father.
</P>
<P>
   MITCHELL'S TOP CAREER GOAL: FATHERHOOD
</P>
<P>
   George Mitchell said he took himself out of consideration to be
Al Gore's running mate a month ago because he is having another
child. Mitchell said his wife, Heather, is 4 1/2 months pregnant
with the couple's second child. Their first, Andrew, was born in
October 1997. Mitchell, 66, a former Senate majority leader and
more recently an outside broker trying to bring peace to Northern
Ireland, reportedly was a finalist in Gore's selection process.
</P>
<P>
   YOU GO WHERE THE MONEY IS
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Lieberman lives in Connecticut, but his political money
center is New York City, where investors, insurers and accounting
firms have welcomed his support for issues like limits on lawsuits.
In building a $3.4 million campaign treasury in his Senate
re-election effort against an obscure opponent, Lieberman has
raised nearly one of every five dollars from the financial
industry, which often has been at odds with the Clinton-Gore
administration. Donors from New York City, according to an analysis
by the Center for Responsive Politics, accounted for $421,260 of
Lieberman's contributions, compared with $327,910 from those in
Hartford, the Connecticut capital.
</P>
<P>
   SURVEILLANCE BEING WATCHED, TOO
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for activists planning demonstrations during the
Democratic convention next week are demanding that the Los Angeles
Police Department halt its surveillance of the protesters'
headquarters. They said that unless authorities agree, they will go
to court Thursday to seek an injunction against the department. At
least five times in the past month, authorities have visited the
four-story building near MacArthur Park, and activists fear the
LAPD will emulate police in Philadelphia and Washington, D.C., who
shut down buildings where protesters were storing banners and
puppets.
</P>
<P>
   TEENY-BOPPERS GO FOR BUSH
</P>
<P>
   Teenagers _ even those too young to vote _ readily expressed
their opinions as part of the Horatio Alger Association's annual
gauge of teen attitudes and expectations. ``The State of Our
Nation's Youth,'' a mail-in survey conducted this spring, also
showed that students overall are less worried about crime than a
year ago, and increasingly optimistic about finding jobs and
success as adults. Of the 1,334 students who responded to the
mailed survey, a majority of the 14-to-18-year-olds surveyed
favored George W. Bush. The survey didn't represent the teen
population at large: Just over half of those mailed surveys
returned them.
</P>
<P>
   IF A WOMAN CAN DO IT, WHY NOT A MAN?
</P>
<P>
   A candidate may use his wife's maiden name as his middle name on
the ballot, Minnesota Secretary of State Mary Kiffmeyer has ruled.
And it doesn't matter if it's a Scandinavian name that rings a lot
of bells in Minnesota. Greg Carlson Wersal, who is challenging
state Supreme Court Associate Justice James Gilbert, says he added
Carlson to his name when he married Cheryl Carlson. His birth name
is Gregory Fremont Wersal. ``It's fundamentally unfair to deny men
what females have been doing for years,'' Kiffmeyer said. State law
requires candidates to use their ``true name or the name by which
the candidate is commonly and generally known in the community.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
