<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6977 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-PRACTICALMAN0810-COX     08-09 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICALMAN0810-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Back to school: Pop quiz for mom and pop
 &HT;    A practical back-to-school parental primer
 &HT;    POP'S QUIZ!
 &HT;    Practical school is now in session
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - All right, parents, let's be honest.
Let's pull no punches. Let's tell it like it is.
</P>
<P>
   School's about to start, and it's about dang time!
</P>
<P>
   No more hacking paychecks in half to finance cutesy camps where
wee ones waste weeks weaving coasters out of Popsicle sticks. No
more toiling till sunset while your surly teen snores till noon,
then scarfs $15 worth of cold cuts and falls asleep again. Best of
all, no more bedtime BS. That's right, tykes. Whine all you want.
From now till June, the practical parent will have but one refrain:
</P>
<P>
   ``Get in bed, boy! You've got school in the morning!''
</P>
<P>
   To make sure you get the most out of the new school year _ and
do right by your kids _ the practical man will now enlarge your
minds with his Back to School Lessons for Practical Parents. Take a
seat, folks. School's in session.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson 1 _ Arithmetic: One and one is two. Two and two is four.
When Billy blubbers about taking the bus, kick his bony butt out
the door.
</P>
<P>
   While equations this advanced may melt some minds _ especially
those of softhearted moms _ trust the practical man, they must be
learned. Those who fail to grasp their intricacies will quickly
find themselves in a remedial class, ciphering the following
brainbuster:
</P>
<P>
   Four and two is six. Six and two is eight. Drive Billy to school
today, and you'll be driving him till he graduates.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson 2 _ Reading: Spot is a dog. See Spot run. Sally feeds
Spot in the morning, or Sally's evenings ain't no fun.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, interpreting this dense passage is no job for a
beginning literary critic, but the practical man urges you to read
it over and think it through. What was the author feeling when he
wrote these words? What is the underlying meaning? Is he talking
about some particular child, Sally, and that child's dog, Spot? Or
is he speaking allegorically, aiming at a more universal truth?
</P>
<P>
   Need a hint? Here it is: Do your chores before you roam, or deal
with Dad when you get home.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson 3 _ Spelling: I before E, except after C. A before D, if
you want to watch TV.
</P>
<P>
   Pithy proverbs such as these are powerful learning tools, but
they take parental interaction to reach their potential. If Billy's
teacher is a Whole Language disciple who lets him forget that I and
E are letters, for instance, he should be grateful for the knock on
the noggin he ``recieves'' from his concerned pop. Similarly, if
Sally forgets that A and D are grades, she'll understand when mom
torpedoes the tube and hounds her about homework.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson 4 _ Physics: Newton's laws of motion are slippery devils,
but a good teacher can tame them with concrete examples. Take notes
while the practical man demonstrates.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``An object at rest tends to stay at rest unless acted upon by
an unbalanced force'': Let that teen-ager sprawled on your couch be
the object at rest. The unbalanced force would then be you,
clutching the teen's car keys and bellowing, ``Cut the grass, or
walk to class!'' Trust Newton, motion is inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Acceleration equals force divided by mass'': In practical
parenting terms, this can be restated thus: The rate at which Billy
gets cracking on his book report (acceleration) depends upon the
size of your shoe (force) and the breadth of his backside (mass).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Every action prompts an equal and opposite reaction'': Say
your daughter demands $300 to go to Disney with the high school
band. That would be an action. Say you demand she help you paint
the house on the next three weekends. That would be an equal and
opposite reaction _ for which, coincidentally, you'll pay her
exactly $300.
</P>
<P>
   Pop Quiz: Close your books, class. The practical man will now
test what you've learned.
</P>
<P>
   1. Oh no! Your eighth-grade daughter has a boyfriend. You've
said no dating till she's 15, so now she ties up the phone for
hours every night prattling with her pimply prince. What do you do?
</P>
<P>
   A) Put in a second phone line. Your little girl is becoming a
young woman and she needs her space.
</P>
<P>
   B) Institute the laundry-for-phone-privileges rule: ``She who
flirts folds some shirts.''
</P>
<P>
   C) Snatch the phone out of her hand and bellow: ``Do you feel
lucky? Well, do ya, punk?''
</P>
<P>
   2. Your 10th-grader is taking algebra and needs help with his
homework. You can't remember anything about it. How do you help
him?
</P>
<P>
   A) Hire a tutor. There's no problem money can't solve.
</P>
<P>
   B) Swipe his book and give yourself a crash course. It'll be
good for both of you.
</P>
<P>
   C) Throw up your hands and bellow: ``I just don't see how X and
Y can be numbers!''
</P>
<P>
   3. Your sixth-grader comes home crying. The kids are laughing at
the Air Jordan knockoffs you bought him. He says he needs a $90
pair of sneakers or he'll never be cool. What do you say, practical
pop?
</P>
<P>
   A) OK. The shoes aren't worth $90, but your child's happiness
is.
</P>
<P>
   B) It's up to him, but $90 is a lot of yard work.
</P>
<P>
   C) ``Forget the feet, boy, and check out these hand-to-hand
combat moves I learned in the Marines! ``
</P>
<P>
   4. Good news: Your fourth-grader is all excited because she got
an ``Excellent!!!!'' on her essay. Bad news: When you read her
paper, you notice she's misspelled half the words and apparently
doesn't know a comma from a compost pile. What's a practical parent
to do?
</P>
<P>
   A) Congratulate her and hush. You don't want to damage her
budding self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   B) Congratulate her and take tomorrow afternoon off. Her
teacher's going to explain.
</P>
<P>
   C) Congratulate yourself on this brilliant plan: She's going to
do that thing over and do it right!
</P>
<P>
   Scoring: B), B), B), B). OK, so that was kind of cheap, but if
you think the practical man is going to waste time scrambling
answers around, you've still got a lot to learn.
</P>
<P>
   Send questions and comments to The Practical Man, Accent, The
Palm Beach Post, P.O. Box 24696, West Palm Beach, FL 33416. Or
e-mail PracticalMan(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
