<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-PEACE (Johannesburg) _ A major effort to broker a peace
agreement designed to end years of war in central Africa appears to
collapse, dramatically increasing the danger of a new round of
blood-letting. Burundi looms as the next flashpoint; Congo's
Laurent Kabila appears to be girding for battle against his three
neighbors; and Tutsi tribespeople fear another genocidal offensive
against them. By Kurt Shillinger. 1400 words.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-PINTS (London) _ Another controversy erupts as William
Hague, the 37-year-old head of the Conservative Party who has been
on a roll against the Blair-led Labor government, tells a men's
magazine that, despite his image as a bookish nerd, he used to down
14 pints of beer a day as a teenager _ apparently in a bid to
increase his political appeal to the affluent ``lad'' culture of
hard-drinking yuppies who are seen as up for grabs. By Kevin
Cullen. 1100 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-CAMPAIGN (Carthage, Tenn.) _ Al Gore wants to make one
thing clear: Policy differences with his running mate aside, he
will be the one in charge should the Democratic team make it to the
White House. By Susan Milligan and Jull Zuckman. 1100 words.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-BUSH (Ventura, Calif.) _ Defiantly rejecting conventional
wisdom about his prospects here, George W. Bush goes to California
to stake his claim on unfriendly territory, visiting a mostly
Democratic district less than an hour from the site of the
Democratic Convention next week. By Anne E. Kornblut. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BCBS-DOCTORS (Boston) _ Starting Sept. 1, Blue Cross Blue Shield
_ Massachusetts' largest health insurer _ will change the way it
pays doctors, reducing fees for many surgeons and other specialists
and raising them for many generalists. Some doctors are angry and
forecast problems, including dwindling numbers of specialists and
long waits for patients. By Liz Kowalczyk. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICATION-ERRORS (Undated) _ Study finds injuries caused by
medication errors in nursing homes are surprisingly common, yet
preventable. Blood-thinner and psychoactive drugs were involved in
the largest number of incidents. By Richard Saltus. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ECONOMY-SLOWS (Undated) _ Despite signs of a national economy
that's in a controlled decline, a tight labor market still forces
employers in July to raise pay and find other ways to entice
workes, Fed says. By Anthony Flint. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   EXITSOURCE-SERVICES (Undated) _ Epitomizing how the wireless
Internet market is growing more in specific services rather than
Web-surfing from your phone, eXitsource is offering information
about services available at 20,000 US highway exits. With a few
clicks you can find out every McDonald's, hospital or hotel for the
next 100 miles. By Peter J. Howe. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   INFORMIX-MANAGEMENT (Undated) _ Informix Corp., a database and
e-commerce software company based in Menlo Park, Calif., opens an
office of the president in Massachusetts, with plans to expand its
management presence there. By Ronald Rosenberg. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
