<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV27-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., AUG. 27, 2000. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 c.2000 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: To publish Bernard Gladstone's ``Home Improvement
Questions and Answers'' it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndication Sales. For purchase
information call toll-free 1-888-269-8796.) 
 (The NYTSS sales representative also has information on how to
subscribe to Gladstone's ``Home Improvement Questions and Answers''
weekly column which moves on Wednesdays.) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: I often use aerosol spray cans of paint in my workshop when
doing small jobs.
 &HT;    After each use I turn the can upside down and spray out a little
paint to clear the nozzle, but sometimes even this procedure does
not prevent the nozzle from clogging before the next use.
 &HT;    Any suggestions as to what I can do to clear the nozzle when
this does happen, and what else I can do to prevent this?
 &HT;    A: It's likely that when you invert the can to spray excess
paint out of the nozzle you do not spray long enough to completely
clear out all the paint. You should spray until no more paint comes
out.
 &HT;    To clear a nozzle that is already clogged here is a method that
often works:
 &HT;    Pull the nozzle off the spray can and soak it for several hours
in paint thinner.
 &HT;    Then use a needle or pin to scrape out as much of the softened
paint as you can from the bottom end of the nozzle (where it fits
onto the spray can).
 &HT;    Press this nozzle onto the far end of the snorkel-type thin tube
that comes with most aerosol lubricants. Connect the other end of
this tube to the lubricant nozzle.
 &HT;    Squirt a small blast of the penetrating oil into and through the
paint-can nozzle to clear it completely.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: I have a mahogany dining room table, but the top is not solid
mahogany _ it is a mahogany wood veneer.
 &HT;    The finish on the veneer is quite dull and there are a number of
small pieces missing. There are also several cracks in the surface
and the top has not been waxed for years.
 &HT;    Can I refinish this table top by sanding and varnishing in the
usual manner?
 &HT;    A: Sanding would be problematic because the veneer is likely to
be too thin to take much sanding.
 &HT;    You can try sanding with the finest grain sandpaper but work
carefully to avoid going through the veneer.
 &HT;    The cracks can be filled with a matching wood putty, but the
patches would show and there is still little you can do about the
missing pieces of veneer.
 &HT;    My suggestion would be to forget about refinishing this table
top. Either cover it with a new layer of thin mahogany plywood
(which can then be varnished) or cover it with a plastic laminate
such as Formica.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: I am refinishing some tables and chairs that have round legs
and spokes. Sanding by machine is impossible.
 &HT;    I have also been told not to use steel wool because this often
leaves little particles of steel that will get into the wood and
the finish.
 &HT;    How can I hand-sand and smooth these round legs without using
steel wool and without creating flat spots in the wood?
 &HT;    A: You actually can use steel wool, but you will have to be
careful to get all of the small metal fibers out of the wood after
you are done (these can leave little rust spots in the finish). But
using steel wool will also take longer.
 &HT;    A better method is to cut the sandpaper into strips, then back
each strip with masking tape or duct tape cut to size.
 &HT;    These strips of abrasive paper can then be wrapped halfway
around each leg and ``seesawed'' back and forth from different
directions. The wood or finish can thus be sanded without creating
any flat spots.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Glasses or plates left on the marble top of my coffee table
often leave spots that are almost impossible to remove.
 &HT;    Do you know how I can remove them and what I can apply to this
marble to protect it against such staining?
 &HT;    A: Marble stains easily because it is actually very porous. That
is why most marble tops have a sealer applied after installation.
 &HT;    However, even with a sealer, spills and stains should be mopped
up promptly because removing them later on can often be much more
difficult _ depending on the type of stain and how old it is.
 &HT;    You can try using a marble cleaning kit that you can buy from a
local hardware store or marble dealer. These kits have various
solvents and cleaning agents in them for removing different types
of stains.
 &HT;    Otherwise you may have to bring the marble in to a dealer to
have it professionally polished and refinished.
 &HT;    To protect against future staining, apply a marble sealer that
you can buy from the dealer, and then coat this with a white paste
wax at regular intervals thereafter.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NOTE: Drawing captioned ``CLEARING PAINT NOZZLE'' goes with this
column.
 &HT;    CAPTION: Blasting penetrating lubricant through a clogged
paint-spray nozzle will often clear it out.
 &HT;     
