<P>
   MEXICO-ABORTION _ MEXICO CITY _ Women have erupted into protest
over a new anti-abortion law in Mexican President-elect Vicente
Fox's home state of Guanajuato. Last week, that state's local
congress suddenly passed by one vote a new provision of the
criminal code that makes abortion illegal even in the case of rape.
The vote provoked a crisis in Fox's party, the conservative
National Action, the PAN, which, along with Fox, has portrayed
itself as more middle-of-the-road of late. The PAN's national
leadership was angered by the vote _ some openly denounced it _ and
Fox distanced himself from the action by saying he had no intention
of pursuing such a ban. Opponents say the current PAN governor of
Guanajuato has an option to veto the law, which he might do, or
other legislators will put up a fight to have it struck down.
Abortion is illegal in Mexico, but in all states it can be sought
in the case of rape. Just as Fox is preparing to take office Dec.
1, the PAN has been damaged. (Ferriss, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 4 p.m. (EDT) on the NYT wire.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BOMBING _ MOSCOW _ Russian President Vladimir Putin tried
to calm rising tensions here Wednesday about the possibility of
more terrorist acts in Russia's capital, while authorities made
little headway into finding out who was responsible for Tuesday's
blast that killed seven and wounded close to 100. Authorities
believe it was the work of Chechen rebels fighting for independence
in Russia's breakaway southern republic. Putin told the nation that
Russia would fight back against terrorism with ``a response in
kind,'' and with vigorously continue the war in Chechnya. (Coker,
Cox News Service)
</P>
