<P>
   COXNET FOOD 0805: BRUSCHETTA _ Bruschetta is a healthy,
delicious alternative to convenience food if you are eating on the
run, especially during hot weather, when appetites wane. But it
also adapts easily to just about any type of entertaining.
(Puckett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes a five
1-column color photos of bruschetta with various toppings.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BRUSCHETTA TIPS _ Helpful tips to make your bruschetta as
delicious as it can be. Art includes a 1-column color photo of the
flag of Italy.
</P>
<P>
   RECIPES _ Recipes for Basic Bruschetta, Crostoni, Bruschetta
with White Bean, Tomatoes and Olives, Bruschetta with Tomatoes and
Basil.
</P>
<P>
   OFFICE APPETITES _ At many fast companies, and even some slower
ones, the office kitchen has evolved from a nook with a mini fridge
and a handful of plastic forks to a temple of snacking where every
indulgence is allowed. (Flaherty, N.Y. Times News Service) Art
includes a 2-column color photo illustration of a an office worker
in a well-stocked kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   END OF COXNET PAGE
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-WATER _ When it comes to basic ingredients, it's hard to
get more basic than water. During this drought-stricken;
heat-ridden month of August we take a look at this liquid of life.
Cover: copy block with three teases to inside package. Inside: A
lengthy intro on recipe page to the roles water plays in cooking
and then a package on bottled water that looks at the craze and
offers the results of our taste test. (Walker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH COLOR PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BOTTLED-H2O _ They've become as important accessory to our lives
as cell phones. And before you can even contemplate the wine list,
you have to make a choice between still or bubbles, Fiji or France.
Bottled water is hip and getting hipper. It's the fastest growing
segment of the beverage industry and no matter if the water comes
from a protected spring or is purified tap water, consumers are
drinking it up. (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-WATER-RECIPES _ Recipe page to go with Water story
centerpieced on AJC weekly food section. (Walker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH LAYOUT.
</P>
<P>
   DINNER-SCHOOL _ Back to school time for many means new
activities, new schedules and the same old problem _ how to get
dinner on the table everynight with so many going in so many
different directions. My friend Kris has come up with a solution
for his family of five. He pays his 15-year-old to cook the evening
meal, a win-win for everyone. (Walker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) 16.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERTS _ Just Desserts story about cherries with tested recipe
for chocolate covered cherry cookies and brief on two cherry
pitters. (Langhenry, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 13.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-RECIPESWAP _A weekly recipe exchange column. This week:
Oatmeal Bread. (Langhenry, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-CYBERSPICE _ A weekly column looking at the plethora of
recipes on the Internet. (Parham, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   GUINNESS-VIDEOS _ With the recent death of Alec Guinness,
Eleanor Ringel Gillespie steps through a variety of videos
displaying the strength of the Oscar-winning actor. Plus, she
reveals his true thoughts about ``Star Wars.'' (Ringel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) 19.
</P>
<P>
   EXTRAS _ Extra! Extra! Read all about how to land a movie role
in our guide to Hollywood extras. 'Do You Wanna Know a Secret?'is
filming in Jupiter, Fla., and they're looking for a few hundred
good men and women. (Hutchins, Palm Beach Post) 42.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-HOLYSMOKE _ Video of the week: ``Holy Smoke.'' Grade: B+.
(StMurray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 16
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-NEXT _ Coming soon: ``Erin Brockovich,'' ``The Cider House
Rules,'' ``Ghost Dog: The Way of the Samurai,'' ``Croupier,''
``After Life.'' (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AUDIO-DELASOUL _ A review of the new De La Soul CD ``Art
Official Intelligence: Mosaic Thump.'' Grade B-. (SoMurray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) 5.
</P>
<P>
   AUDIO-MINIS _ Mini reviews of new CDs. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) 12.
</P>
<P>
   HOME AND GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   GARDENING-LIFE _ A gardening column by Lee May. This week: After
my July 27 column about the old oak from next door crushing my
garden with one of its two trunks, many readers wrote with
condolences, reminiscences _ and humor, which so often helps
mitigate pain. (May, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WINDOWS-MAINTENANCE _ My house has aluminum siding that's in
decent shape, so I don't have to paint the exterior walls. But that
doesn't mean I escape entirely; I and other owners of brick-,
aluminum- and vinyl-covered houses still need to attend to window
frames. Whether your windows have wood, vinyl or aluminum frames, a
little routine maintenance will help keep them working well.
(Cummings, Dayton Daily News) 26. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is James Cummings' Nuts &AMP; Bolts column.
</P>
<P>
   WRESTLING-GRAPEVINE _ Our wrestling columnist keeps up with the
latest twists and turns of the soap opera of professional wrestling
_ in the ring and behind the scenes. (Allen, Cox News Service)
MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
