<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANK-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: AN UPSTART INVESTMENT BANK TRIES TO CARVE OUT A
NICHE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   By BERNARD STAMLER  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   They don't sell consumer goods. Although they are financial
institutions, they don't have street-level branches, tellers or ATM
machines. Many people have no idea what they do, and few of them
will ever interact directly with one, even if they do.
</P>
<P>
   So just how do you advertise an investment bank?
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, the answer was simple: with ``tombstones,'' the
somber boxes in the financial press that announce this big deal or
that, complete or in the works. But that was before the Internet
economy and its lucrative initial public offerings changed
everything, inspiring heightened competition among the players in a
once buttoned-down industry. Nowadays, extensive display and
broadcast ad campaigns have become the norm.
</P>
<P>
   The latest to join the fray: Robertson Stephens, the upstart San
Francisco-based investment banking arm of FleetBoston Financial
Corp. In an industry dominated by old-line giants like Goldman,
Sachs &AMP; Co., it is determined to make its mark. Or, at the very
least, to carve out its niche.
</P>
<P>
   The company was founded in 1978, not far from Silicon Valley and
at about the same time that the high-tech industry there began to
blossom (It was acquired by FleetBoston's predecessor, BankBoston
Corp., in 1998). Lately, its revenues have risen sharply, from $360
million in 1998 to $970 million last year to ``nearly a billion''
so far this year, according to Allen Olivo, its chief marketing
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Because Robertson Stephens has specialized for years in bringing
technology companies to market, with clients like the Etrade Group,
the online investment firm, it is, he said, ``the first investment
bank to focus on the new economy.''
</P>
<P>
   But how can that translate into an advantage over bigger, Wall
Street-based johnny-come-latelies? The idea is to build brand, said
Olivo, who has been involved in branding before with companies like
Amazon.com and Apple Computer, where he was senior director for
marketing communications during the ``Think Different'' days of the
late 1990s. Robertson Stephens was in Silicon Valley, literally and
figuratively, before anyone else, he said, and because of that has
``knowledge that gives us a unique perspective in a global growth
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hence an unconventional new campaign devised by Portland,
Ore.-based Wieden and Kennedy that breaks Thursday, in this
newspaper and others. ``Thanks old economy,'' proclaim the
double-page spreads, words floating on an otherwise blank
background. ``We'll take it from here.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad is designed to ``say something, but quietly,'' said the
account director Trish Adams, and to stress the fact that Robertson
Stephens' ``culture is a little different from other investment
banks.'' Future print ads, also featuring one-line statements will
follow, she said, in publications like The Wall Street Journal,
Industry Standard and Fast Company. . And, like Thursday's example,
they will feature one-line statements _ ``headlines,'' Adams called
them _ that will be more like philosophical statements than
hard-sell slogans.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson Stephens' 30-second television spots _ all of them
apparently filmed in double or triple time _ also aim to be
irreverent or even edgy in their message, she said, all without
delving too far into the substance of what, exactly, an investment
bank does.
</P>
<P>
   In one of them, for example, an off-camera, voice-over announcer
muses about America's westward migration and the fact that there is
``still so much more to be done.'' ``It's not time to settle
down,'' he intones as a freighter scoots by the Golden Gate Bridge,
waves lapping nearby and San Francisco's skyline barely visible in
the distance. ``It never is.''
</P>
<P>
   In another spot, the same voice asks if ``you really think that
all the technology in the world can erase economic truths that have
held for hundreds of years.'' And as clouds speed over the tops of
buildings in San Francisco's financial district, shot from a camera
looking up at times at nearly a 90-degree angle, he answers the
question himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``So do we,'' he says. ``Ladies and gentlemen, this time it's
different.''
</P>
<P>
   The commercials will run primarily on Bloomberg television, CNBC
and CNNfn, Adams said, beginning this week and continuing through
at least year's end. And the lack of substance in them and in print
is deliberate, she said; for now, the idea is to say ``who they are
and what they stand for,'' with respect to Robertson Stephens.
Advertising with ``more content will be rotated in later, Adams
said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither she nor Olivo would disclose the size of the Robertson
Stephens effort, although the trade press put the figure at $25
million when Wieden and Kennedy was awarded the account back in
May. And while Olivo hopes that the campaign will result in
increased business for the firm, that will be only one of the
benchmarks by which its success will be gauged, he said. There are
other, more intangible measures as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our target is multi-faceted,'' he said, involving, among other
things, ``recruiting, as we grow in size and geographically,'' as
well as ``getting better known by the public'' and wielding
''greater influence in the general conversation about the
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be the next Goldman, Sachs or Morgan,
Stanley,'' Olivo said. ''We're just trying to become the most
influential investment bank in the new economy.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
