<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7008 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GOP-DEM-STEAL-HNS &LR;      08-09 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-DEM-STEAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GORE AND BUSH JOCKEY TO STEAL EACH OTHER'S THUNDER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     News Analysis  
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's a daring heist in broad daylight without a
glint of guilt _ the Democratic candidates for the White House are
stealing venerable Republican campaign issues just as brazenly as
their GOP rivals are seizing Democratic campaign themes.
</P>
<P>
   In doing, both Democrat Al Gore and Republican George W. Bush
appear to be borrowing a favorite tactic from the master of the
campaign co-opt _ Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and his freshly minted running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman
of Connecticut, used faith-based rhetoric on the campaign trail
again on Wednesday to grab for the heart of Bush's appealing
crusade for ``national renewal'' in the aftermath of Clinton-era
scandals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was here that I learned to cherish faith, family and
community,'' Gore told supporters in his hometown of Carthage,
Tenn. ``It was here that I learned the importance of honor,
responsibility and doing the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, mindful that Americans rank family values and
restoration of national morals ahead of a balanced budget, defense
or abortion, emphasized that he and Gore ``share values'' as well
as a ``vision for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman last came to national attention with a Senate floor
speech in September 1998 condemning Clinton for behavior with
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky that was ``not just
inappropriate; it is immoral.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Gore is fashioning a far wider appeal to all-important swing
voters in the Nov. 7 election by underlining support for a variety
of tried-and-true GOP proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plans include such Republican staples as paying off the
national debt, boosting the number of cops on the beat and adding a
constitutional amendment to ``make sure that victims and not just
criminals have guaranteed rights in our justice system.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore even used his nationally televised announcement of his
selection of the first Jew to serve on a national ticket into a
reminder on Tuesday that he and Lieberman are so pro-defense that
they ``broke with our own party to cast two lonely Democratic
votes'' to support President Bush's request for congressional
authority to go to war to oust Iraqi occupation forces from Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   Only 10 of the Senate's 55 Democrats voted to use military power
to force Iraq out of Kuwait _ giving Bush a 52-47 vote of support
on the first de facto declaration of war since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also is taking a page from the populist crusade waged in
the presidential primaries by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who left
the race after a series of defeats by Bush. As Gore put it in a
television interview on Wednesday: He and Lieberman will mesh
because ``we both have the desire to fight for people and not the
powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of McCain's campaign was limiting big-money
contributions to the political parties.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's bid appears to be paying off, enabling him to stage a
rebound in the polls. Bush's double-digit lead after the GOP
convention dwindled to 2 percentage points in a USA
Today/CNN/Gallup poll released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush has been turning the tables on Gore just as
effectively, embracing issues in a bid to enlist the independent
voters and crossover Democrats who may hold the key to the outcome
in battleground states in the Middle West.
</P>
<P>
   Bush touts diversity, as he did at the GOP convention in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   He advertises plans to overhaul entitlement programs such as
Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   He vows to augment Head Start for poor children to add a
literacy program _ an expansion of a program that his running mate,
Dick Cheney, sought to cut back as a congressman from Wyoming in
the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the two-term governor of Texas, even echoes the
traditional Democratic rhetoric of giving disadvantaged Americas a
leg up on the ladder of upward mobility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are their country too,'' says Bush, insisting that the GOP
is ``not the party of response but the party of reform.''
</P>
<P>
   The art of borrowing from political rivals is noting new. Many
trace the tactic to Dick Morris, the canny New York political
operative who helped Clinton craft a centrist, can-do message for
re-election in 1996 that enabled the president to become the first
elected Democrat since 1936 to win a second term.
</P>
<P>
   Morris successfully persuaded Clinton to retake the so-called
``values agenda'' by voicing support for proposals such as public
school uniforms, a moment of silent prayer in the classroom and
denunciation of gratuitous portrayals of violence on television, in
movies and in music.
</P>
<P>
   Morris once explained his approach as ``a process of taking the
best ideas from each party and combining them into a coherent
policy and program,'' adding in an interview with the New York
Times: ``It is not just splitting the difference but molding a
creative synthesis which rises above the doctrine of either
party.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the heavy borrowing by the two sides, Gore on Bush
differ on abortion rights, Social Security overhaul, prescription
drug benefits for Medicare and environmental regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign scholars say that candidates have raided rivals' ideas
for generations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly didn't start with Dick Morris,'' said Larry
Sabato, a scholar at the University of Virginia and the author of
``Feeding Frenzy: Attack Journalism and American Politics.'' ``The
beliefs of political parties are only skin deep and after a few
losses, they'll very often put on the clothes of the other party in
an effort to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabato recalls Clinton's success in 1992 co-opting GOP campaign
hallmarks including support for the death penalty, greater defense
spending and fiscal discipline to steer the Democratic Party out of
the political wilderness back and back into the White House for the
first time since the 1976 election.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Schick, a campaign scholar at the University of Maryland
who wrote ``American Government: Continuity and Change,'' said Gore
and Bush are trying to grab each other's agendas to offset
shortcomings in their own campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each party is trying to make up for a deficit _ Republicans
are short of new programs and the Democrats suffer a deficit on
values,'' Schick said.
</P>
<P>
   Added to that, Gore and Bush are competing for the same
middle-of-the-road swing voter who responds to pragmatic proposals
to solve problems rather than schemes that excite the party
faithful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans are smack in the center right now,'' Schick said.
``There's just not a market for big change so the candidates are
battling for the same ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Bert Rockman, a presidential scholar at the University of
Pittsburgh who edited ``The Clinton Legacy,'' said Gore and Bush
are courting trouble from their party faithful.
</P>
<P>
   ``The political parties want these candidates to stick to the
party agenda,'' Rockman said. ``But the candidates have to create
some elbow room to make their way to the center. That creates
inevitable tension between the record and the rhetoric.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
