u i BC-MOSCOW-BLAST-BOS &LR;      08-09 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOSCOW-BLAST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECURITY INTENSIFIED IN WAKE OF MOSCOW BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Fear, grief and anger engulfed Moscow Wednesday as
police beefed up security in the aftermath of an explosion that
ripped through a pedestrian walkway in the heart of Russia's
capital, killing seven people and wounding at least 93.
</P>
<P>
   President Vladimir V. Putin tried to reassure his jittery
nation, calling ``hysteria and disorganization the best gift for
terrorists,'' and warning Russians not to rush to blame Chechens
for Tuesday's blast.
</P>
<P>
   Police meanwhile found a bag filled with explosives and
detonators at a Moscow train station, possibly preventing another
explosion, and sparking anxiety that Russia could be on the verge
of a new wave of terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Muscovites turned the site of Tuesday's blast, a walkway under
Moscow's popular Pushkin Square a short walk from the Kremlin, into
a makeshift shrine. Hundreds of people, many in tears, laid
flowers, candles and religious icons. Late Wednesday night, Putin
placed flowers on the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are defenseless,'' said Vladimir Starostin, 70, standing
amid the rubble near the blast site. ``Explosion after explosion.
When will this all end?''
</P>
<P>
   The explosion evoked fearful memories of a series of apartment
bombings that killed over 300 people last September. Putin blamed
Chechen guerrillas for the blasts and sent troops to quell the
separatist republic.
</P>
<P>
   Several politicians, including Moscow Mayor Yury Luzhkov, said
Chechen rebels, or their sympathizers, were also responsible for
Tuesday's bombing.
</P>
<P>
   But Putin, who gained popularity and rose to power largely due
to his tough response to last years explosions, warned against an
ethnic witchhunt aimed at Chechens. Putin said the blast could have
been either a terrorist act or part of a turf war among criminal
gangs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must say that it is wrong to look for an ethnic connection,
a Chechen connection, to this or any other crime,'' Putin said in
televised comments. ``It is very wrong when we brand one nation,
because criminals, terrorists above all, do not have a nation or a
belief.''
</P>
<P>
   The president added, however, that Russia would continue its
11-month-old battle against Chechen separatist rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Chechen rebel leaders, including President Aslan Maskhadov,
denied any connection to the blast.
</P>
<P>
   Law-enforcement officials said seven people had died in the
explosion, correcting earlier reports that said that eight people
had died.
</P>
<P>
   Among the wounded were two US citizens, Natalya Yelin and her
13-year-old son, Ilya, both of whom received burns and scratches
from the explosion. The US Embassy did not release their hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Police fanned out across Moscow to check pedestrian underpasses,
subway stations, basements and attics for explosives. Vehicles
entering and leaving Moscow were searched extensively and police
vigilantly checked the passports of pedestrians on the street and
commuters riding public transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses to the explosion said two men left a bag near a kiosk
before rushing away and driving off in a car just moments before
the blast.
</P>
<P>
   Earlyier, police detained two men, one from Chechnya and one
from neighboring Dagestan, and questioned them about the explosion.
Authorities later said the two were being held for possession of
narcotics but were not directly linked to the bombing. Adding to
the confusion, police released four sketches of suspects, but by
Wednesday night, Russian television was airing only one composite
portrait.
</P>
<P>
   Police meanwhile found a suitcase containing nine pounds of TNT
and seven detonators in a lost luggage office at the Kazan Railway
Station in Moscow. Law enforcement officials said the explosives
were not wired for detonation, but police were investigating a
possible link to Tuesday's blast.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the smoldering rubble under Pushkin Square where the bomb
exploded, hundreds of Muscovites gathered to pay homage to the
dead.
</P>
<P>
   Sergei Kochenko, 12, lost his grandmother in the explosion. He
kneeled and prayed in front of small shrine of flowers, candles and
icons.
</P>
<P>
   A group of young men, who bystanders said were friends and
relatives of some of the deceased, stood off to the side sobbing
and embracing each other. They quietly drank vodka and ate dark
bread, in remembrance of their friends.
</P>
<P>
   When reporters approached them, they became aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a person I am asking you all to back off,'' one of the men
shouted.
</P>
<P>
   Oksana Maurina, 23, who left the underground walkway minutes
before the blast, returned to the site to pay her respects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel terrible,'' she said. ``Why does fate allow one person
to live, while it takes the life of another. This is very
frightening,'' she said. ``I pass through here all the time and I
just can't believe what has happened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
