<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7013 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-MURRAY-COLUMN0813-COX     08-09 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN0813-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    Being taken for a ride
 &HT;    By Ernest Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ Before I made that dash from the air-conditioned
office to the air-conditioned car, I checked my finances. I had 65
cents to my name. I could buy a cold drink to sip on the way home,
or be 65 cents ahead tomorrow. I decided I needed the change more
than the soda.
</P>
<P>
   As I pulled out of the newspaper parking lot, cranked up the AC
and headed to the intersection, I saw her, looking like a
frightened rabbit. I figured her for somewhere in her 30s, although
a hard life had obviously taken its toll. Her dark hair framed a
face that had been too long exposed to the sun and her dark eyes
were pleading. If she wanted a handout, she was going to be out of
luck, I thought.
</P>
<P>
   As she rushed to my car window, I considered speeding away and
avoiding the whole mess, but cross traffic played to her advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Rats, I was caught.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please, sir,'' she begged, ``it's so hot, can you please give
me a ride to the grocery store?'' I could tell she was close to
heat exhaustion. We were in the midst of a record-breaking
103-degree hot spell.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you doing out in this heat,'' I asked, trying to
figure out if she really needed a ride or if she was going to take
me for a ride.
</P>
<P>
   She said she had been downtown for an interview. Judging from
the condition of her clothes, and that she hadn't been close to
soap and water for awhile, I knew she likely wasn't going to be
hired anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Reluctantly, I told her to get in.
</P>
<P>
   The air conditioning was blowing cold and I was hot under the
collar. What kind of patsy am I, I thought as I stepped on the gas.
I don't know this person. She could have a gun for all I know. And
all I have is a lousy 65 cents.
</P>
<P>
   As I raced down the street on the fastest route to the grocery,
I noticed my passenger was concentrating on getting her face as
close to the air vent as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so hot,'' she kept repeating. The best response I could
muster was an icy, ``Well, you had no business being out on the
hottest day of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   As we drove along, her breathing became more relaxed and she
began to hum along with the tune coming from the radio. I didn't
know what to say to her. ``Hot enough for you?'' just seemed to be
the wrong conversation starter. Taking a quick glance at her to
make sure she was recovering from the heat it became clearer why
she was in such dire straits. She had the unmistakable profile of a
woman with child.
</P>
<P>
   It was beginning to make sense now. She most likely had been
downtown to interview for financial assistance for her unborn
child. I pulled up to the entrance to the grocery store and as she
was getting out I said, ``Wait a minute.'' I dug in my pocket and
pulled out the quarter and four dimes. ``Here,'' I said. ``It's all
I've got. Go inside, cool off and buy yourself a cold drink.'' She
took the change without hesitation, thanked me for the ride and
disappeared into the store.
</P>
<P>
   I wish I had had more than 65 cents to give her.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
