u e BC-BLUEGRASS-BOOK-REVIEW     08-09 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUEGRASS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CAN'T YOU HEAR ME CALLIN': GOOD AND BAD IN THE CREATOR OF
BLUEGRASS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Monroe was a mandolin virtuoso, an unforgettable singer, a
visionary bandleader, a brilliant judge of musicians and the
songwriter behind ``Blue Moon of Kentucky.'' He was also a
skinflint, a womanizer and man who could hold a grudge for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Richard D. Smith, a journalist and mandolinist who wrote
``Bluegrass: An Informal Guide,'' chronicles the great musician and
his messy life in ``Can't You Hear Me Callin','' and his reverence
for Monroe's music doesn't keep him from mentioning the
unflattering details.
</P>
<P>
   Smith makes bold claims for Monroe, calling him ``the most
broadly talented and broadly influential figure in American popular
music history.'' Partisans of Duke Ellington, Louis Armstrong,
Robert Johnson, Hank Williams, Bob Dylan, James Brown and others
might well disagree. But Monroe clearly belongs in the American
pantheon.
</P>
<P>
   He single-handedly turned rural string-band music, with a touch
of the blues, into bluegrass: music that brought together high,
lonesome harmony singing with an aggressive beat and breakneck
instrumental virtuosity. His repertory brought together Southern
ballads, gospel songs and dance tunes, professionalizing them and
revving them up to reach an audience that eventually spanned the
world. Monroe's bluegrass _ named after his band, the Blue Grass
Boys _ is a cornerstone of country music and, in turn, of rock.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Can't You Hear Me Callin','' Smith has gone through
small-town records, farm ledgers, interview transcripts, bootleg
recordings and legal documents; he has interviewed not only
Monroe's musicians but also his ex-girlfriends. It is a
meticulously researched and footnoted biography, intent on
straightening out chronologies and pinning down apocryphal stories.
It also looks into Monroe's music, connecting songs to the people
and landscapes that inspired them and explaining, without getting
too technical, Monroe's innovations and his evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe, born in 1911, was the eighth and youngest child of a
farm family in Rosine, Ky. He was born cross-eyed, a defect that
was not surgically corrected until he was a teen-ager; other
children teased him, and he grew up shy. His father was
hard-working and distant, his mother nurtured him, and his brothers
were rowdy. Smith psychologizes, perhaps too neatly, that the
family set the pattern for Monroe's later personality: affectionate
with women, stoic and competitive with men.
</P>
<P>
   Bill's older brothers Charlie and Birch took up the family's
prized instruments, the guitar and fiddle, leaving Bill with the
lowly mandolin. It had been used mostly for backup. But Bill Monroe
turned it into a brilliant solo instrument with fierce runs, blues
bends and sharply syncopated rhythm chords.
</P>
<P>
   He worked with Charlie as a duo on the grueling country circuit
of daytime radio shows and nighttime concerts. In 1936 the Monroe
Brothers began recording for RCA Victor, tearing into the old
mountain songs in performances still cherished by country
aficionados. Two years later they went separate ways; Smith
determinedly debunks old rumors that Charlie made advances on
Bill's wife. On his own Bill Monroe began putting together the
music that would start its own tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe's new music crystallized in 1945, when the Blue Grass
Boys included a singing guitarist named Lester Flatt and took on a
new banjo player, Earl Scruggs. His three-finger picking style
originated in North Carolina, but he took it to a new plateau of
virtuosity, surrounding a melody with a shower of arpeggios. Monroe
had perfected a rhythm that seemed to jump ahead of the beat, and
with Monroe, Scruggs and a fiddler named Chubby Wise, songs became
contests among virtuoso soloists. Bluegrass was part of a postwar
renaissance of American music: brash, gutsy and built for speed.
</P>
<P>
   But it couldn't withstand the commercial onslaught of honky-tonk
country and of rock 'n' roll. Monroe's fortunes declined in the
1950s, only to be revived through an unlikely ally: the folklorist
Ralph Rinzler, who repositioned Monroe in the folk revival.
</P>
<P>
   Bluegrass, which had not long before been a vanguard music, was
greeted by Northern folk fans as a noble tradition. Monroe moved on
to the college and folk festival circuit; his bands began to
include Yankees, some of whom _ the guitarist Ry Cooder (who played
banjo in the Blue Grass Boys), the guitarist and singer Peter Rowan
and the fiddler Richard Greene _ would go on to find a place in
California rock and country-rock.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1970s, there was a growing circuit of bluegrass festivals
where Monroe was venerated. He was a barnstormer, staying on the
road until a stroke felled him in March 1996; he died that
September.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way Monroe left his wife and children for a series of
overlapping affairs; the women, Smith notes in passing, stayed in
touch with Monroe afterward, even those who sued him. Monroe made
misguided investments; he received songwriting credit on his
sidemen's work. He didn't speak to Flatt or Scruggs for more than
20 years after they left his band to become rivals. Smith patiently
sorts out the squabbles, usually taking Monroe's side or pointing
out that he came from an era when things were done differently.
Eventually, however, he grows exasperated with Monroe's obtuseness
in business matters.
</P>
<P>
   For all its information, Smith's biography is unable to
reanimate Monroe's character. And while he had access to the
extensive interviews Rinzler did for a book he never wrote, Smith
uses too little of Monroe's own terse, cantankerous voice. Monroe
remains a bundle of paradoxes: heartfelt and stone-faced, ruthless
and kindly. He was hardly the first great artist who turns out to
have been a user of the people around him.
</P>
<P>
   And Monroe's songs, with their constant tensions amid
poker-faced control, speed-fingered exuberance and abiding pain,
still dole out his story in three-minute revelations.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `CAN'T YOU HEAR ME CALLIN':
</P>
<P>
   The Life of Bill Monroe, Father of Bluegrass'
</P>
<P>
   By Richard D. Smith
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 365 pages. Little, Brown &AMP; Co. $25.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
