A7042 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-DEMS-LA0810-COX     08-09 1349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-LA0810-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LA officials to roll out the red carpet today for Democratic
National Convention
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES - Mayor Richard Riordan and Democratic Party
officials will literally roll out the red carpet today at Staples
Center for the 35,000 delegates, guests and media who will attend
the Democratic National Convention at the gleaming new complex.
</P>
<P>
   Unfurling the rug is ``the symbolic welcoming of the world to
Los Angeles,'' said Ben Austin, spokesman for the Los Angeles host
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations for the convention, the first here since President
Kennedy was nominated in 1960, are high in a city that has
experienced more than its share of problems recently. But the
anxiety level is also rising.
</P>
<P>
   Police are bracing for between 25,000 and 50,000 demonstrators -
far more than were present at the Republican convention in
Philadelphia - to stage marches, block traffic and engage in civil
disobedience. Much of the action will take place across the street
from the convention center's main entrance.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Police Department canceled all days off for the
9,300-member force during the convention, which begins Monday and
ends Aug. 17. Officers are expected to work 12-hour shifts.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI, Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department, California
Highway Patrol and Secret Service are also sending personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions between the police and protest leaders are high and
some fear there is a potential for violent conflicts, similar to
those that caused $2.5 million in damage in Seattle during the
World Trade Organization meeting last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be enormous scrutiny,'' says City Councilman
Michael Feuer. ``The pressure is on. But I am optimistic that we
are going to rise to the occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the protesters say there has been too much
scrutiny. They demanded Tuesday that the LAPD halt its surveillance
of the protesters' headquarters and said that, unless authorities
agree, they will go to court today to seek an injunction against
the department.
</P>
<P>
   Activists fear the LAPD will emulate police in Philadelphia and
Washington, D.C., who shut down buildings where protesters were
storing banners and puppets they planned to use during
demonstrations in those cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who are here are very alarmed at the surveillance
and the threat they will be raided by the LAPD,'' said Dan Tokaji,
an attorney with the American Civil Liberties Union of Southern
California. ``They are very concerned the LAPD will be taking
action to suppress their right to free speech.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't supposed to be this way.
</P>
<P>
   City officials pursued the Democratic Party for the right to
host the convention as way to stage a coming out party for Los
Angeles after a decade of setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   First, there were the riots after the Rodney King verdict in
1992, then there were devastating 1994 earthquakes that caused $20
billion in damage. Also, the recession of the early 1990s lingered
longer in California, and Los Angeles was one of the last major
cities to recover.
</P>
<P>
   City officials believed it was time to rewrite the negative
stereotypes when in April 1999 they won the right to host the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the city's opportunity to showcase Los Angeles to the
world,'' says Councilman Alex Padilla, who chaired the council's ad
hoc convention committee.
</P>
<P>
   Padilla himself puts a face on the diverse, ethnically vibrant
city Los Angeles has become. The son of Mexican immigrants who
attended only four years of school, the 27-year-old Democrat
graduated from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology with a
degree in engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles is now the most ethnically diverse city in the
country, home to the largest concentration of Mexicans outside of
Mexico, the largest population of Koreans outside the Korean
peninsula and citizens from 140 other nations.
</P>
<P>
   The city is in the midst of a mini-high technology boom, with a
high-tech workforce of more than 200,000. In 1999 $1.2 billion in
venture capital flowed to the city.
</P>
<P>
   The $350 million Staples complex, home of the Los Angeles
Lakers, is one of several major new developments downtown. A new
2,300 seat concert hall, designed by Frank Gehry, is being built
for the Los Angeles Philharmonic. The city also recently completed
a new, though costly metro-rail system to help ease the city's
notorious traffic congestion.
</P>
<P>
   Even the city's air quality, long the butt of many jokes, is
something to brag about. Air pollution has been cut by two-thirds
since the 1960 convention, when media were given eye drops along
with their credentials to ease the polluted air's burning side
effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't have hosted this convention eight years ago, even
four years ago,'' says Austin, of the host committee. ``The mere
fact that we were able to have this convention reflects how far we
have come in such a short period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Optional add follows.
</P>
<P>
   But the convention was awarded prior to televised images of
rioting in the streets of Seattle, where demonstrators brought the
WTO trade meeting to a virtual standstill and showed how such
high-profile gatherings could also become a public relations
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The level of trust between the police and the demonstration
leaders is low, according to several officials who have been
attempting to mediate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a climate of fear and dire predictions of
hundreds of anarchists burning our city down,'' says James
Lafferty, director of the city's National Lawyers Guild, blaming
police for escalating the tensions. ``There are good people here in
this city who are trying to calm folks down, but I would be less
than honest if I didn't say I was nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Police say that they expect the majority of demonstrators to be
law-abiding, but believe a small minority will attempt illegal
disruptions. Of special concern is the North American Anarchist
Conference that happens to be scheduled in Los Angeles during the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Police have purchased paint-ball guns to tag law breakers and
have signaled they will use rubber bullets and other ``impact
munitions'' to keep the peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our concern is those groups that have clearly indicated that
they are coming to Los Angeles to shut the city down,'' says Lt.
Horace Frank, the department's spokesman. ``We're not going to let
that happen. We owe it to the people of this city to do everything
we legitimately can to stop it from happening.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the protest leaders say they also don't want
violence. But they plan a variety of marches and street actions,
including civil disobedience that will likely result in arrest, to
communicate their political message of social justice and corporate
greed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The civil disobedience part of this is very important,'' says
Margaret Prescod, a spokeswoman for the coalition of groups
planning a weekong series of marches. ``But we are not violent
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the demonstrators are young and they hope to convey
their messages in colorful street theater and music. At the
protesters' command center a few blocks from downtown, volunteers
have been building giant puppets featuring menacing versions of the
heads of presumptive Democratic presidential nominee Al Gore and
the Republican nominee, Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Erlenbusch, an advocate for the homeless, says he wants to
call attention to the 50,000 to 80,000 people who he estimates are
homeless in Los Angeles on any given night.
</P>
<P>
   Many are veterans of the protests in Seattle and Washington,
D.C., where demonstrators disrupted a World Bank conference earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What most of us are interested in is showing the country and
the world the real Los Angeles, a city where 50 people control as
much wealth as two million, a city where at least one-third of the
children grow up in poverty,'' says Garrick Ruiz, 23. ``Those
people don't have the money to contribute to the Democratic
Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
