u w BC-GUNS-TEXAS10-COX     08-09 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-TEXAS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TEXANS WITH CONCEALED GUN LICENSES MORE PRONE TO GUN ARRESTS
 &HT;    By MIRIAM A. GARCIA
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texans with licenses to carry a concealed handgun
have been arrested for weapons-related crimes at a rate nearly
double that of the state's overall adult population, the Violence
Policy Center reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the gun-control advocacy group's report was described as
distorted and politically motivated by Texas state Rep. Suzanna
Gratia Hupp and the office of Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   From 1996 to 1999, the Washington-based center reported, there
were 873 arrests of licensed gun holders in Texas for
weapon-related offenses.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that 183 of the arrests were for assault and
aggravated assault with a deadly weapon, and 108 for deadly conduct
and discharge of a firearm. It said 486 were for unlawfully
carrying a weapon, and the rest for a variety of charges ranging
from discharge of a firearm to disorderly conduct.
</P>
<P>
   The study relied on statistics compiled by the Texas Department
of Public Safety from January 1996 to last April.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Brock, the center's policy analyst, said that 4 out of
1,000 licensed gun holders were arrested on gun-related charges
over the period of the study, compared to about 2.4 out of 1,000
persons in the general population.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texans were promised that only law-abiding citizens would be
allowed to carry concealed guns, but the arrests of these license
holders show that instead of stopping crimes, they are committing
them,'' Brock said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association ``promised all of us that
concealed handgun owners were the cream of the crop of gun owners,
so we decided to take a look at how this law actually operated,''
said Josh Sugarmann, the center's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The center reported that over all, there were 3,370 arrests of
licensees in the four-year period, but not all of them were
weapon-related. The study did not say how many of the arrests
resulted in convictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose (of the Texas Concealed Handgun Law) is to promote
and sell handguns. This law is not about public safety,'' said Nina
Butts, a lobbyist for Texans against Gun Violence, a group that
promotes stricter gun regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to comment on the study, the National Rifle Association
provided the name of Hupp, a Republican state representative.
</P>
<P>
   Hupp said many of the arrests were due to careless licensed gun
holders bringing the weapons into places where they were not
permitted.
</P>
<P>
   Licensed gun holders ``are more likely to have a weapons-related
offense, but that has nothing to do with violent crimes,'' said
Hupp. ``I'm not worried about running into (concealed handgun
license holders). I am worried about running into rapists and
murderers.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush signed the concealed handgun law in May 1995, during his
first term as governor. To obtain a license, applicants must pay a
$140 application fee and undergo 10 hours of firearms proficiency
training. They cannot have a criminal record, and lose their
license if convicted of a serious crime.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Jones, a spokesperson for Bush, said the center's research
is misleading and implied that it was intended to harm the
governor's presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more than 31 states with concealed handgun laws, yet
the study only chooses to look at Texas,'' said Jones. ``What
people really care about is violent crimes, and other studies show
adult males without concealed carry permits are eight times more
likely to commit a violent crime than permit holders.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Violence Policy Center: www.vpc.org
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign: www.bush2000.com
</P>
<P>
   Miriam A. Garcia's e-mail is miriamg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
