<HEADLINE>
GETTING THE ORIGIN OF `FRICK AND FRACK' DOWN COLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What is the origin of the expression ``Frick and Frack''? _
A.D.E., Everman, Texas &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: Frick and Frack were the show business names of a comedic ice
skating duo who performed for the Ice Follies.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss skaters Werner Groebli (Frick) and Hans Mauche (Frack)
joined Ice Follies in the '30s, wearing Alpine costumes with
lederhosen and performing tricks such as the ``cantilever
spread-eagle.''
</P>
<P>
   Attesting to their popularity, ``Frick and Frack'' has become a
reference for similar people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The phrase has become a fairly common one in North America for
any two people who are closely connected in some way,'' writes
Michael B. Quinion of the Web site World Wide Words at
www.quinion.com/words.
</P>
<P>
   Groebli, 85, lives in Palm Springs, Calif., and was featured on
a 1999 PBS special.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a Chatty Cathy doll from the '60s that still talks.
How can I find someone who might be interested in buying it? _
M.G., Worcester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A: Contact the Chatty Cathy Collectors Club, an 11-year-old
group that mails out a quarterly newsletter. Write to Box 4426,
Seminole, FL 33775-1426, or visit the Web site
www.ttinet.com/chattycathy.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel originally produced Chatty Cathy in 1959 with sayings by
June Foray, the voice of Rocky the Squirrel, Tweety's owner Granny
and other cartoon characters. A 1970 version was produced using the
voice of Maureen McCormick from ``Brady Bunch''.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Mattel began producing some of the original Chatty
Cathy dolls again in collector's editions. They say 11 phrases,
including ``I'm hungry'' and ``I hurt myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I write to Charley Taylor, former wide receiver for
the Washington Redskins? _ B.T.
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Taylor and other past or present players in care of
Washington Redskins, 21300 Redskin Park Drive, Ashburn, VA 20147.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, a first-round draft pick as a running back in 1964,
retired as the league's all-time leader in pass receptions with
649. He also had 9,410 yards receiving, 90 touchdowns and was a
1984 inductee into the NFL Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   After attending Dalworth High School in Grand Prairie, Taylor
was an All-American running back for Arizona State University.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
