<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7052 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-CAD-ARCHITECTURE-     08-09 1520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-CAD-ARCHITECTURE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCHITECTS GROW RELIANT ON THE 40-POUND PENCIL: THE COMPUTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Circuits) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By ERIC TAUB  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The power of ones and zeroes is invading the centuries-old field
of architecture, helping today's designers and artisans create
structures that would otherwise be much more difficult _ or even
impossible _ to build.
</P>
<P>
   The results can be seen in such showcased structures as the
recently opened Experience Music Project in Seattle and the
Guggenheim Museum in Bilbao, Spain, both by Frank Gehry. It is also
apparent in the ambitious design, completed last fall, of the New
York Presbyterian Church in Queens, N.Y., an alteration of an older
building.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we didn't have computers,'' said Greg Lynn, one of the
architects of the church project, ``the interior of this building
would have been much simpler.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of whether computers take a leading role at the start
of a project or later in the process, digital technologies are
transforming the way buildings are designed and constructed.
Computers can speed things up, allowing architects to compete in a
world where everything needs to have been done yesterday. They also
make it possible for architects to sell their designs to clients in
new ways.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Presbyterian Church, in the Sunnyside neighborhood,
features a large, open sanctuary that seats 2,500 and has a ceiling
composed of warped surfaces, computer-designed ribbed forms that
look different from different angles. On the building's exterior, a
staircase is partly enclosed in a tunnel-like structure that
shields arriving churchgoers from a view of the gritty industrial
neighborhood yet gives them a view of the Manhattan skyline as they
leave.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn, an architect in Venice, Calif., who is also a professor at
Zurich University's architectural school, and his colleagues _ Doug
Garafalo in Chicago and Michael McInturf in Cincinnati _ are in the
forefront of a group of architects who are creating complex shapes
that emphasize continuity, rather than borders, between walls and
ceilings. It is a style made feasible by the computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before computers, you'd start designing using shapes of
cubes,'' Lynn said. ``Now I can start with something like a
handkerchief, an object that doesn't have strong inside and outside
boundaries or much closed volume.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn and other proponents of this type of architectural design
are able to do that because they are using software that looks at
shapes not as the product of a collection of straight lines that
are each specified by fixed two-dimensional coordinates, but rather
as the product of three-dimensional curves that can be defined by
mathematical formulas. In this way, even a straight line can be
defined as a curve _ just one that has not yet been inflected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a computer, every point on a structure has to be
calculated with reference to everything else,'' Lynn said. ``But by
using a PC, I can create complex curves that don't have radii or
centers. Since the entire form is tied into itself through a
complex mathematical equation, I can easily push and pull the shape
and have the equation automatically recalculate the new
relationships within that form. If I tried to do that by hand, a
day's work would take a couple of years _ literally.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn has thrown away the architect's tools of wooden models and
hand-drawn diagrams in exchange for a practice based solely on
software. Using 3-D animation programs like Maya, Lynn creates
structures that can be rotated on the screen in three dimensions
and covered with textures and shadows.
</P>
<P>
   The Queens church is a $10 million structure that was built atop
an Art Moderne building, the old Knickerbocker Laundry Factory,
which had 88,000 square feet. When working on the church, Lynn sent
his files via modem to his two partners. Some of those same files
were also sent to materials fabricators who used
computer-controlled machinery to cut needed materials automatically
with high degrees of precision.
</P>
<P>
   While Lynn works to create forms that would not be practical
without computers, others, like Gehry, continue to create in real,
rather than virtual, space. Gehry, based in Santa Monica, Calif.,
does not use computers to create a design, but he uses them to
communicate the design's essentials to those who will ultimately
execute the plan. Without computers, carrying out Gehry's designs
would be extremely difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Gehry's most-celebrated recent structures also include the Walt
Disney Concert Hall in Los Angeles, as well as the museums in
Seattle and Bilbao. All those projects began with wooden models,
which were translated into three-dimensional digitized computer
files only after the architects were satisfied with the designs.
Those digital files then served as a nexus for parts suppliers,
fabricators and contractors around the world, all of whom had
access to one central, tightly controlled online source of
documentation.
</P>
<P>
   One strong advocate of digital design is Terry Beaubois, an
architect who is also director of the Palo Alto, Calif., chapter of
the American Institute of Architects. ``My goal is to be able to
retrieve, view, store, modify and send my architectural files to
collaborators, clients and manufacturers,'' Beaubois said, ``so
that we can all view things in three dimensions on the computer.''
</P>
<P>
   The need to draw designs on paper has slowed architects down.
Not only do building designs generate reams of paper plans, with
multiple copies of blueprints for every participant in the project,
but every product used in a building must be drawn fresh each time.
In a study conducted by Beaubois, he learned that in some cases, an
item as simple as a toilet would be drawn multiple times: by the
manufacturer, for its brochure; by the architects, for their
design; by the subcontractor, for more detailed shop drawings; and
by the facilities manager, to create the post-construction ``as
built'' drawings. And all those drawings are two-dimensional,
making it hard to visualize them accurately.
</P>
<P>
   Computers can minimize such delays. Using computer modeling, and
using the computer to forward files electronically to his client,
Beaubois recently completed plans for a 10,000-square-foot house,
including a guest house and stable, in just five days, instead of
the weeks or months such a project would usually take.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before this technology, you could go to lunch while waiting
for an element in a design to be redrawn,'' Beaubois said. ``Now,
with tools such as Photoshop, I can create and recreate something
in an instantaneous flow. If a client doesn't like something, I can
change it immediately, and no misunderstanding or mistrust is
created. It's like Wolfgang Puck cooking your meal to order in
front of you.''
</P>
<P>
   The renderings produced with a computer can be much easier for
clients to understand. Architects like Mark Miller, co-owner of
Miller, Kelley Architects of San Francisco, are creating highly
detailed, animated ``fly-overs'' of their computer-generated
structures.
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate Miller's concept for a new General Motors design
center in Warren, Mich., the firm created a five-minute animated
film. Viewers feel as though they are sitting in a helicopter as a
daredevil pilot swings up, around and even through the building,
walls and all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our animations are so literal,'' Miller said, ``our clients
think they're almost watching a photograph. And they want their
building to look exactly like the animation.''
</P>
<P>
   This sophisticated short film took 20 linked computers one week
to create. Software that would allow a viewer to choose a path to
travel around a highly detailed neighborhood in real time does not
yet exist.
</P>
<P>
   Some architects look forward to faster computers that will let
them create life-size three-dimensional models that can be
projected on a wall and be viewed from any angle. Even when such a
trick becomes possible, there will be some limitations: No matter
how much one twists and turns a three-dimensional computer model of
a structure, in some ways it is still a two-dimensional experience.
The image is displayed on a flat surface like a computer screen.
The viewer cannot really walk around it, peer into its windows or
run in and out of it to understand the relationship of the building
to its surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   While computers may speed up the design process, they, like any
medium, including the human hand, impose their own artistic
limitations. Depending on the software used, buildings can take on
a particular look.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I see a finished building and say, `Oh, yeah, that
was made using Form Z,''' said Charles Stilworth, an architect in
Studios Architecture. ``If you develop a project using AutoCAD,
which favors extrusions, it'll come out different than if you used
Maya, which can replicate wave actions. If you're smart, you'll
pick a program based on what's in your head.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Gehry prefers to develop his concepts on paper, creating more
and sophisticated physical models as his ideas take shape. Once the
design is set, the physical model is digitized by plotting various
coordinates, using a tool developed for neurosurgeons. The
resulting points are then manipulated on the computer in Catia, a
modeling program originally created for the French aerospace
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The original design for the Disney Concert Hall called for stone
cladding across the exterior. The firm used the computer to
streamline the design, reducing the variation in the stone shapes
and thereby cutting fabrication costs. The plan was to manufacture
the cladding through an automated process to cut costs and to have
computer data sent electronically from Gehry's office to the plant
to control the machinery that would cut the material. The cladding
was eventually changed from stone to metal to meet seismic
requirements. But Jim Glymph, a partner in Gehry's firm, said the
time was near when these kinds of novel designs ``will cost no more
than mass-produced products.''
</P>
<P>
   Glymph is entranced by computers not because they can create
designs, but because they can help bring efficiency to the
now-chaotic control process inherent in construction. The
construction industry, however, is still far from the time when
laborers will walk around every building site with laptops,
checking the latest updates to the buildings' designs.
</P>
<P>
   A typical construction project can generate up to 10,000
documents. ``The paper process is imbedded in this industry,''
Glymph said. ``The generation of permits, legal processes and plans
is all done on paper. In construction, there's always a change that
will wind up generating thousands of documents. On the Disney
Concert Hall, switching from stone to metal cladding alone meant
that we had to make 5,000 new drawings.''
</P>
<P>
   Within a decade, Glymph and others say, the design and
fabrication process will become much more centralized, and the
Internet will become a hub for the business. All documents will be
posted in a central location. Contractors and fabricators will
receive different levels of access to plans _ some will be able to
modify them while others will only be able to read them.
</P>
<P>
   Materials fabricators anywhere will be able to download
specifications and create samples to compete for a construction
contract. As a result, the Internet has the potential to let more
people compete in the construction industry. Previously unknown
artisans, even those working in remote villages, will be able to
vie for contracts if they have Internet access, and that will give
architects more choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, we'll be able to create computerized plans that,
when you click on a certain part of it, will show all of an
object's attributes,'' said Beaubois, of the American Institute of
Architects. ``That way, a contractor will be able to get
information without having to call the architect. High-speed
Internet access will allow this to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, referring to the architectural flowering during the
Renaissance, ``Thanks to computers, this is the most exciting time
in architectural history since 1492.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
