<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7056 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-SMOKEJUMPERS0810-COX     08-09 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOKEJUMPERS0810-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Business smoke jumpers drop into hot financial situations
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - RealEstate.com Inc. was in a fix.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based Internet start-up faced an audit, and most of
its financial history lay in boxes. So company executives called in
``smoke jumper'' Susan Baader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually had boxes of invoices and paid bills and canceled
checks and bank statements. It was about 15 cardboard boxes,''
recalled Baader, a financial consultant. ``I came in. They set me
up in a conference room with a couple of (temporary helpers) and
said, `Here, have at it. ...''
</P>
<P>
   That was in April 1999. By the time auditors from
PricewaterhouseCoopers arrived in May, Baader had unraveled enough
of the company's financial data for them to review.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the company was ``able to build that road map to
solid financial statements,'' said Bob Sutton, then
RealEstate.com's chief financial officer, who brought in Baader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to say I was just the expert in putting out fires,''
said Baader, who has 25 years experience in finance, accounting and
risk management. Baader, 54, now is vice president of finance for
RealEstate.com, which lists real estate for sale online.
</P>
<P>
   Smoke jumpers are tech-age troubleshooters. These fix-it
specialists work quietly and quickly, setting up or repairing the
business end of high-tech start-ups. They're highly skilled, highly
paid and highly sought-after, setting them apart from traditional
consultants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of Web and dot-com companies need to get their products
to market quickly,'' said Pat Turner, associate director in the
contract services division of Matrix Resources, an information
technology staffing firm. ``To do that, you usually need a seasoned
senior-level expert who can come in quickly and size up a problem
and work quickly by either doing it themselves or leading others.
Smoke jumpers jump into time-critical situations. Sometimes it's
the life or death of a business.''
</P>
<P>
   In their rush to get services and products launched, many
high-tech and Internet firms are neglecting the basics of business,
said Michael Nadeau, editorial director of Contract Professional
magazine, a Watertown, Mass.,-based career guide for contractors
and consultants in information technology. Consequently, Nadeau
said, people and projects aren't being managed well and many of the
systems for running a company _ payroll, inventory, accounting,
billing _ aren't in place. ``Traditionally IT workers have been
badly managed,'' Nadeau said.
</P>
<P>
   Smoke jumpers are often called in after ``the existing team has
quit because of unrealistic expectations or working impossibly long
hours,'' Nadeau said.
</P>
<P>
   The term is borrowed from U.S. Forest Service terminology for
firefighters who parachute in to suppress fires. It began to be
heard regularly late last year, when many firms were looking for
solutions to anticipated Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   Smoke jumpers usually stay with a company three to six months.
</P>
<P>
   Many are helping companies tie together payroll, inventory,
accounting and other business systems in what's known as enterprise
resource planning. ``There's not a lot of experience out there in
(ERP) so those projects can get off track,'' Nadeau said.
</P>
<P>
   Initial public offerings provide smoke jumpers with other fires
to put out. Many numbers-crunching jumpers work with startups to
determine when going public is a good idea. They're also being
sought to help start-ups' get venture capital, said Turner.
</P>
<P>
   Jumpers can make up to $200 an hour _ roughly twice what their
peers make doing the same job for one company, Nadeau said.
</P>
<P>
   While they make more money, they also assume more risks. When
smoke jumpers fail, it can mean financial losses for their clients
and strained or severed business relationships for the jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   But Joe Dudar, a smoke jumper for Matrix and a software
architect, likes the challenges of solving other people's problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of advantage to going from one problem to
another because you begin to see things from a different
perspective versus looking at it from one angle,'' said Dudar, 35,
who does a lot of work with dot-coms. ``You very often come up with
solutions that you wouldn't usually be able to get from working on
just one business problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``What may be a rejected approach at one company may have
newfound value for another company. That happens often and that's
another value of the smoke jumper,'' said Dudar. ``There are no
real clear-cut rules.''
</P>
<P>
   At RealEstate.com ``we needed somebody who could come in, who,
without disrupting me or others in the business, could get this
thing figured out,'' said Sutton, the company's former CFO. ``It
not only takes someone who's competent in accounting but who has
good common sense skills and broad financial business knowledge and
who's not afraid to make decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
