<HEADER>
A7058 &Cx1f; tie-z
u v BC-CIR-BACK-TO-SCHOOL-AD     08-09 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-BACK-TO-SCHOOL-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For editors planning back-to-school sections or seeking
individual back-to-school articles, we commend to your attention
these six from the Circuits section of Thursday's New York Times.
All are for immediate release and all have moved on the wire.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-HIGHSCHOOL-GADGETS (Undated) _ Rohnert Park, Calif., 60
miles north of San Francisco, is mostly white and middle class, but
it is no Lake Wobegon. At the local high school, most of the
students are academically average. SAT scores hover around 1025,
and the dropout rate is 1.7 percent. Some of the sports teams
shine, while others struggle. The homecoming dance in the fall and
the prom in the spring are the year's two social high points. And
like their counterparts around the country, the 2,000 students at
the school, Rancho Cotate, are no strangers to electronic devices.
That makes it as good a place as any to see what kind of gadgets
the thoroughly modern high school student is using these days. When
the Ranch, as the school is called, reopens this fall, students
will arrive with electronic paraphernalia aplenty, their backpacks
heavy with cell phones, pagers, CD players and custom-burned CDs,
as well as graphing calculators and the occasional Palm organizer
and laptop computer. By Katie Hafner.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT4.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-WEB-RESEARCH (Undated) _ For students who grew up with the
Web, the idea of roaming library stacks to do research is as quaint
as the thought of writing with a quill pen. Even though libraries
are organized and easily navigated, students prefer diving into the
chaotic whirl of the Web to find information. One problem with this
strategy is that many students are not well versed in advanced
searching techniques so a simple search for, say, information about
the planet Saturn can yield tens of thousands of hits. Yet students
persevere with this hit-or-miss approach, saying that they are
simply more comfortable sifting through hyperlinks than they are
flipping through a card catalog. And they admit that using the Web
requires less exertion. But while the keyword approach to searching
makes perfect sense to teenagers, it troubles many educators, who
fear that point-and-click research can lead to lazy study habits
and ineffective searches. By Lori Leibovich.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ Students in the freshman class
of 2000 were born at the same time as the original IBM PC. They
grew up with cable TV and Nintendo, learned to program the VCR
before they could ride a bike, became virtuosos with call-waiting
and three-way conference calling and took for granted answering
machines, microwave ovens, audio CDs, pagers, fax machines and cell
phones. Now they are heading off to college, where they will be
immersed in technology more deeply than at any time of their young
lives. As if to prove that the cosmos has a sense of humor, we,
their technologically befuddled parents, are supposed to choose a
computer for these children of the technology age as they head off
to school. Here are some data points that may help. By Peter H.
Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-DORMS-COMPUTERS (Undated) _ During back-to-school season 25
years ago, any list of essential items for dormitory rooms usually
featured one piece of equipment at the top: the stereo. Ten years
later, the stereo still ruled, but another appliance was also
considered essential: the answering machine. How 20th century,
college students today might say. The computer, they declare, is
the only item that could possibly deserve to be first on any list
of dorm necessities. In fact, the computer not only displaces other
technology in importance but also replaces the need for some other
appliances. By Lisa Guernsey.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-TEACHING-SOFTWARE (Undated) _ The red phone on your desk
rings sharply in the middle of the night. The voice you hear is
that of the White House chief of staff, alerting you to a crisis in
the Eastern European country of Krasnovia. You're needed at the
White House, pronto. ``We'll send a limo,'' he says, and hangs up.
After an emergency meeting with the president, you're given a
classified intelligence report and access to the country's foremost
diplomats, policy analysts and military leaders. You are to submit
a report in time for a presidential address that evening. The
president is waiting to act on your recommendation. Welcome to high
school, circa 2010. The scene is from an interactive software
course, Crisis in Krasnovia, that its creator, Roger Schank,
believes will revolutionize how children are taught. ``Software is
going to replace classes as we know them,'' said Schank, director
of the Institute for Learning Sciences at Northwestern University.
By Joshua Green.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-READING-SCREENS (Undated) _ Some skeptics may believe
something only when they see it in writing, but is the writing more
believable when it is seen on paper rather than on a computer
screen? Apparently it is, based on a recent study at Ohio State
University. The study, which looked at differences in comprehension
of something read on a printed page and the same thing on a
computer screen, found that students who read paper versions found
articles more interesting and persuasive than did the students who
read them on computers. By Catherine Greenman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 or (212) 556-1927: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The day supervisor is Gary McCardell.
</P>
<P>
   The evening supervisor is Pat Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   The late-night supervisor is Sam Weiss.
</P>
