<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7060 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-JEWS-SOUTH-NYT &LR;      08-09 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEWS-SOUTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY SOUTHERNERS SAY LIEBERMAN'S RELIGION IS A NONISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Max Heller had been mayor of Greenville, S.C., for
seven years when he decided to run for Congress in 1978 and
discovered the limits of religious tolerance in the South of the
post-civil rights era.
</P>
<P>
   One of his opponents said Heller should not be elected because
he was Jewish and did not ``believe Jesus Christ has come yet.''
Another opponent, Carroll Campbell, who later became governor,
conducted a poll with the assistance of the consultant Lee Atwater
that reminded voters that Heller was a ``Jewish immigrant.''
</P>
<P>
   Heller lost that race, and never ran for office again. But
today, as he contemplated with pleasure the selection of Sen.
Joseph Lieberman as the first Jewish member of a national political
ticket, he said he believed his adoptive region had moved far
beyond its earlier distrust of non-Christian candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The South has grown up,'' said Heller, 81, who was born in
Vienna. ``So much of the old anti-Semitism is gone now, with all
the new people who've moved in. If the candidate is someone like
Joe Lieberman who is faithful to his religion, I don't think he
would have any problem in the South anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   With his selection of Lieberman, Vice President Al Gore was
probably not expecting to convert any Southern states to his
column, with the possible exception of Florida, which is 4.3
percent Jewish. But both Jewish and non-Jewish leaders in the South
agreed that the presence of an Orthodox Jew on the ticket was no
longer a liability in the nation's most religiously conservative
region.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Guin, the majority leader of the Alabama House of
Representatives, said he had spent the last two days going to
coffee shops and restaurants in the Birmingham area to gauge
reaction to the announcement, and had not even heard a murmur of
discontent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get the sense that his religion is going to make any
difference in the race,'' said Guin, a Democrat from Carbon Hill,
who is a leader of his Methodist church. ``In fact, his being
devout in his faith may even be a benefit in the South. This is a
place where people take religion very seriously, and they like to
see others take it seriously, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Although his opponents in his last race drew attention to his
religion, Heller said he believed that being an observant Jew was
an important reason he was repeatedly re-elected as mayor of
Greenville _ the home of Bob Jones University and of one of the
highest proportions of conservative Christians in the country _
back in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Friedman, executive director of the Birmingham Jewish
Federation, agreed, saying it was precisely Lieberman's Orthodoxy
that would make him respected among the South's churchgoing
population of Baptists and evangelical Christians.
</P>
<P>
   ``People respect people of faith,'' he said. ``They value
someone who has developed an authentic relationship of meaning with
his God.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Alabama, like most of the Southern states, is still
expected to vote heavily for Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, and Guin
wasn't predicting any change. At the moment, Gore is thought to be
a contender only in Florida, Tennessee and possibly Georgia. But
Guin said Gore might actually improve his chances in Alabama by
bringing Lieberman there a few times and campaigning hard.
</P>
<P>
   There have been examples in recent years of Jewish political
candidates in the South whose opponents have made an issue of their
religion. In 1996, John Mitnick, a Republican, tried to unseat U.S.
Rep. Cynthia McKinney in Atlanta, and was accused by McKinney's
father of being ``a racist Jew.'' A campaign flier said Mitnick was
a member of several Jewish groups. Billy McKinney later resigned
from his daughter's campaign and apologized for his comments.
(Mitnick lost a race for the state Senate on Tuesday.)
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Lee Alcorn, the president of the Dallas chapter of
the NAACP, questioned Lieberman's selection in a manner that
angered many listeners. ``I think we need to be very suspicious of
any kind of partnerships between the Jews at that kind of level
because we know that their interest primarily has to do with money
and these kind of things,'' he said on a radio show. The national
president of the NAACP, Kweisi Mfume, condemned the remarks as
repulsive and anti-Semitic and formally suspended Alcorn from his
post.
</P>
<P>
   There are undoubtedly silent sentiments of anti-Semitism that
persist in the small rural towns, inner cities and gated suburbs of
the South, but public expression of such views remain rare. In
recent years, there have been repeated examples of Jewish
officeholders elected by Southern districts with only a handful of
Jewish voters. Ben Erdreich, a Democrat, represented the Birmingham
area in Congress for five terms in the 1980s and early '90s; Martin
Frost, a Democrat, has represented a Dallas-area congressional
district since 1978; Virginia is likely to have two Jewish
congressmen in November.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama's governor, Don Siegelman, is Catholic, but his wife and
children are Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The South has grown more tolerant as it has grown more
prosperous,'' said Hastings Wyman, editor of the Southern Political
Report, a newsletter published every two weeks in Washington. ``The
education systems are better, the universities are better funded,
and people are less defensive than they used to be. And we've got
all these Yankees here, now that we've got air conditioning.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, according to the National Jewish Population Survey,
about 21 percent of the country's core Jewish population lived in
the South, a number that has probably grown in the last decade. But
the region actually has a much lower percentage of anti-Semitic
incidents, according to the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith,
which reported recently that only 12 percent of such incidents in
1999 occurred in the 12 states of the Southeast region. The
majority of the incidents, 58 percent, occurred in the Northeast,
the group said, with 21 percent in the West and 8 percent in the
Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The South actually has a better track record than other parts
of the country,'' said Jay Kaiman, the Southeast regional director
of the league, based in Atlanta. ``We've got fringe groups here, of
course, and you never really know what kind of talk goes on in
country clubs or in the backrooms of workplaces. But I think when
it comes to voting, being Jewish is a nonissue.''
</P>
<P>
   Which doesn't mean there won't be some suspicion of Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   ``His biggest problem here won't be that he's Jewish,'' said
Kaiman. ``It's that he's a Northerner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
