<HEADLINE>
BARCLAYS NEGOTIATING TO BUY BRITISH MORTGAGE LENDER 
</HEADLINE>
  By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Britain's third-largest bank, Barclays PLC, said on
Wednesday that it was negotiating to acquire Woolwich PLC, a
leading British mortgage lender, for about 5.5 billion pounds or
$8.3 billion. A deal could be reached by the end of the week,
executives close to the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   If the companies reach an agreement, it would strengthen
Barclays' home mortgage business in Britain as well as accelerate
its Internet banking strategy; Woolwich has been praised for its
comprehensive Internet facilities, which would be integrated into
the Barclays system.
</P>
<P>
   Barclays, which only a few years ago was one of Britain's most
troubled banks, has been on a tear in the past year under its chief
executive, Mathew Barrett, who took over about 10 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett has cut costs, closed 172 branches and has made several
small acquisitions. The bank has also raised it profile in Britain
with a $22 million advertising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Barclays said that if the bank makes a bid, it would value each
share of Woolwich at 362 pence, a 34 percent premium over Woolwichs
closing share price on Tuesday. The bank said the offer would be in
cash and stock; 0.1175 shares of Barclays for each Woolwich share
plus 164 pence in cash per share.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Woolwich jumped 27 percent, or 72 pence, to 341 pence
or about $5.12. Shares of Barclays dropped 49 pence, or 2.9
percent, to 1,615 pence or about $24.22.
</P>
<P>
   Barclays is making its play for Woolwich at a time when the
mortgage lender's share price has been battered. Woolwich's shares
reached a low on July 31 of 245 pence. The shares had rebounded a
bit since then on speculation that the company could become a
takeover target.
</P>
<P>
   A Barclays-Woowich deal could set off another rash of
consolidation in the British banking industry. While more megadeals
like The Royal Bank of Scotland's recent acquisition of National
Westminster Bank are not expected because of regulatory concerns,
analysts said Britain's other mortgage lenders will become
attractive takeovers targets.
</P>
<P>
   The most watched mortgage lenders include Abbey National,
Alliance &AMP; Leicester and Northern Rock. Almost across the board,
shares of British mortgage lenders have been in falling, making the
group even more attractive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
