u f BC-JOBS-DISPLACEMENT-NYT     08-09 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOBS-DISPLACEMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAYOFF RATE FALLS IN NEW GOVERNMENT REPORT
</HEADLINE>
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the U.S. economy enjoying its longest economic expansion on
record, the number of permanent layoffs declined over the last
three years, the government reported on Thursday. The rate may now
match the lowest in the 20-year history of the survey.
</P>
<P>
   The new data also shows that women are now laid off virtually as
often as men, closing a wide gap that had existed for most of the
last 20 years. At the same time, the layoff rate for blacks rose.
And the gap between the layoff rate for blacks compared with whites
widened significantly over the last three years. The layoff rate
for Hispanics, however, dropped sharply, falling below that of
blacks. The differential between whites and Hispanics also
narrowed.
</P>
<P>
   During the three years that ended with 1999, 3.3 million workers
on the job for three years or more were laid off while 4.3 million
workers on the job for less then three years lost their jobs, the
Bureau of Labor Statistics reported in its biennial job
displacement survey. This compares with total layoffs of 8 million,
3.6 million of them on the job for three years or more, from 1995
to 1997. And that is down from a total of 8.4 million in the period
from 1993 through 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The decline is more drastic when looked at as a percentage of
laid off workers compared with the total number of employed
workers. According to the bureau, that declined to 6.1 percent in
the last three years, from 6.6 percent in 1995 through 1997 and 8
percent in 1993 through 1995. And this 6.1 percent may be near or
even match the low for the survey, which goes back to 1979.
</P>
<P>
   The first bureau survey was released in 1984. But because the
way the survey was conducted was changed from five-year periods to
three-year periods in the report released in 1994, it is difficult
to make historical comparisons. Steve Hipple, the economist at the
bureau who oversees the job displacement data, said that the rate
of job layoffs was probably understated in the earlier data.
</P>
<P>
   If this is the case, the 6.1 percent layoff rate from the last
three years may actually be equal to the 5.5 percent rate reported
for 1987 through 1989, the low in the bureau's data.
</P>
<P>
   But the decline in the layoff rate in the last three year was
far less than in the preceding three years, when the rate for all
workers 20 years and older fell 17.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not surprising that in a strong job market that job loss
declined,'' said Henry Farber, an economist at Princeton University
who studies job displacement data. He said that even with a strong
economy, there would be layoffs as some industries shrink while
others grow.
</P>
<P>
   The lowest layoff rate, 5.7 percent, was for workers 45 to 54.
Of all the displaced workers, nearly three-quarters had new jobs by
the time the survey was taken in February. Nearly three-fifths of
those laid off from wage and salary jobs found new jobs that paid
the same or more.
</P>
<P>
   While the layoff rate for blacks did increase to 7.3 percent, it
is still significantly below the level earlier in the 1990s, when
it was as high as 9.4 percent between 1991 and 1995. The increase
in the difference between the layoff rate for blacks and whites
ends six years of narrowing. In the three-year period from 1991
through 1993, the gap was 1.4 percentage points. It narrowed to 0.5
percentage point in the next three-year period and was 0.6
percentage point in 1995 though 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Hipple could not say why the gap had widened again. He said that
the existence of a gap was consistent with the fact that the
unemployment rate for whites is lower than that for blacks. But he
said it was hard to tell whether this year's widening of the gap
was a one-time event or not.
</P>
<P>
   Farber, who has worked with the bureau's jobs data for years,
could not comment in detail on the change in the layoff rates for
blacks because he had not yet received the backup data on which
Thursday's release was based. But he said ``the black number is an
interesting number and something to point out.''
</P>
<P>
   The layoff rate of Hispanics fell to 7 percent over the last
three years from 8.8 percent. That is the lowest it has been since
the the 1990-1991 recession. The gap between the white and Hispanic
layoff rate narrowed to 1 percentage point from 2.3 percentage
points in the 1995-97 period.
</P>
<P>
   The gap between the layoff rate for women and men has been
narrowing over the last 20 years, with the biggest changes coming
in times of strong job growth. In 1991-93, the gap was 7.4 percent
for women and 8.8 percent for men. That narrowed to 7.6 percent for
women and 8.4 percent for men in 1993-95, to 6.5 percent for women
and 6.7 percent for men in 1995-97 and to 6.1 percent for women and
6 percent for men in the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women's jobs are concentrated in service industries and the
risk of job losses in services industries has grown over time,''
Hipple said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
