<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TRIXIE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITS PARTS ARE BIGGER THAN SOME OF ITS HOLES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROBERT PHILPOT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Director Alan Rudolph doesn't make foreign-language films, but
his movies always seem to come from a strange place: Rudolphland,
where everyone has an idiosyncrasy and outlandish coincidences
become commonplace. When everything falls into alignment, as with
1984's ``Choose Me'' and parts of 1997's ``Afterglow,'' it can be a
wonderful place, but more often it's a frustrating locale to visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trixie,'' which Rudolph calls a ``screwball noir,'' contains
some small joys if you're in the right mood, but it's probably very
frustrating if you're not. It features a typical mix of Rudolphian
eccentrics: Wannabe detective Trixie (Emily Watson) who speaks in
an unending stream of malapropisms, redundancies and mixed
metaphors; a second-rate celebrity impersonator (Nathan Lane) with
a drinking problem and a past; a scroungy Lothario (Dermot
Mulroney) who gets Trixie mixed up with gangsters and blackmailers;
and a sleazy senator (Nick Nolte) who becomes the subject of
Trixie's first, um, case. It has to do with the death of a failed
lounge singer (Lesley Ann Warren).
</P>
<P>
   The movie takes way too long to meander into its convoluted
plot, and it's disconcerting to see Watson _ trying on a broad
Chicaaaaago accent _ turn down her natural intelligence; she
appears stiff and uncomfortable playing someone as daffily serious
as Trixie. But Rudolph's screenplay celebrates wordplay in a way
that too few movies do these days; you have to love the English
language to mangle it as amusingly as Rudolph does with the words
that he puts in Trixie's mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph cheekily makes the other characters speak in cliches and
platitudes, and Trixie's desecration of the language acts as a
clever counterpoint to their banalities. Rudolph's direction can be
irritatingly loose, and the emphasis on words makes the movie a
little too script-bound. It's drastically uneven, but as Trixie
might say, its parts are bigger than some of its holes.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
