   With photos, NYT3,8,21, and a graphic.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-WHALES (Tokyo) _ To understand why Japan expanded its
whale-hunting activities last month, despite international
opposition, come to dinner at Taruichi, a restaurant in the trendy
Shinjuku district. On a recent evening, not a seat or sake glass
was empty as dozens of jovial patrons, ranging from business
executives to domestic workers, feasted on platters of the house
specialties: fried whale, raw whale, whale bacon, whale heart,
whale testicle, whale kidney, and even whale ice cream, made from
the cetacean's fat. Whale, after all, is part of their national
culture and identity and they strongly defend it. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
