<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-PINTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRINKING CLAIMS BY OPPOSTIION LEADER HAS BRITAIN ASTIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ William Hague, a lad?
</P>
<P>
   Baring his soul to a men's magazine, the sober and serious
leader of the British opposition party confessed this week that in
his teenage years he drank a lot of beer, as many as 14 pints a
day.
</P>
<P>
   But if it was a bid to boost his electoral appeal with so-called
``lads,'' the beer-swilling yuppies who make up a sizable
constituency in Britain, it flopped. His claim has been met mostly
with skepticism and derision.
</P>
<P>
   ``That lying little toad,'' said Terry Glossop, assistant
manager of the Angel, one of the pubs in Hague's hometown in
Yorkshire, where he claims he used to knock back pints while on his
summer job delivering soft drinks and beer for his father's
distributing business. ``No one can remember Hague coming in for as
much as a half a lager.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Glossop said, Hague was known for his taste for soda
pop, earning him the nickname ``Billy the Fizz.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sun tabloid treated Hague's claims with characteristic
restraint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy Liar!'' Wednesday's headline blared.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of blare, you never hear Hague's nemesis, the
circumspect prime minister Tony Blair, boasting of his drinking
exploits. According to fans and critics alike, Blair is not only
sober, he is downright boring.
</P>
<P>
   But Hague is widely considered even more boring, which is why
most political pundits believe Hague sat down with the British
edition of GQ magazine and admitted to serial pint downing in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   GQ in Britain is different from its sister publication in the
United States. Here it is one of a genre aimed at the ``laddism''
subculture of middle-class British men who revel in drinking,
yelling rude things at women, and generally acting like boors.
</P>
<P>
   This, apparently, is the constitutency that Hague's confessional
was aimed at. But according to many political observers, his
admission to a youthful indiscretion backfired horribly _ not
because it reveals a character flaw, but because no one believes he
really drank all those pints.
</P>
<P>
   At Conservative Party headquarters Wednesday, a cheerful press
officer declined to answer questions, saying only, ``The article
stands for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   It says something about Britain, a nation where binge drinking
is a major problem, that more people were asking whether the man
who wants to be the next prime minister was exaggerating his
drinking prowess than whether he, like many other Britons, had a
drinking problem in his youth.
</P>
<P>
   At offices of Alcohol Concern, the national agency that combats
alcohol abuse, Lisa Leonard sounded depressed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have hoped that someone in a position like Mr. Hague
would have urged people to engage in responsible drinking,'' said
Leonard, the communications director. ``It's very sad that because
of our drinking culture, being able to drink excessive amounts of
beer is seen as a positive quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard said that in terms of total consumption, Britons rank in
the middle of the pack among Europeans, but British teenagers drink
more than their European peers. She said Britain has the highest
incidence in Europe of alcohol-related violence, much of it traced
to binge drinking. The government, she noted, recommends that
people drink no more than two pints a day, so if Hague was telling
the truth, he routinely drank seven times that.
</P>
<P>
   The bald, slight Hague, who looks older than his 39 years, has
always been something of a nebbish. His detractors suggest he is
kind of goofy.
</P>
<P>
   But, like many supposed nerds, Hague is smart. He burst onto the
national scene as a 16-year-old in 1977, when he wowed a
Conservative Party conference with a rousing speech that showcased
his oratorical skills _ not to mention an Osmond brothers haircut
that showed off a head of hair that, alas, melted away like the
Conservative majority in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   In his interview with GQ, Hague seemed to want to distance
himself from his sober image, saying he downed pints like a
stevedore while delivering crates of soft drinks and beers to pubs
all over South Yorkshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who thinks I used to spend my holidays reading
political tracts should have come with me for a week,'' he boasted.
``We used to have a pint at every stop . . . and we used to have
about 10 stops a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``You worked so hard you didn't feel you'd drunk 10 pints by
four o'clock, you used to sweat so much. But then you had to lift
all the empties off the lorry. It's probably horrifying but we used
to do that, then go home for tea, and then go out in the evening to
the pub.''
</P>
<P>
   Hague, a judo expert who is in superb physical condition,
stressed he no longer drinks anywhere near as much.
</P>
<P>
   The whole experience, he went on ``was a great education,
actually. Knowing what Labor voters feel like as well as
Conservatives. I think I learned more going round the clubs of
Barnsley than I learned at Oxford about the human race in
general.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which is probably true, but few people seem to believe
him, at least the part about sinking 14 pints in a day.
</P>
<P>
   John Perry, editor of Loaded, the granddaddy of the ``lad''
magazines, was skeptical of Hague's claims, calling it as an
attempt to woo younger voters. Perry said the strategy was ``a
slippery slope, like wearing a baseball cap.'' Unless Hague goes
out, drinks 14 pints, then walks onto the floor of the House of
Commons, he said, the ``lads'' won't believe it anyway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 1916EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
