<SLUG> BC-FREEDOM-MEDALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON HONORS 15 WITH PRESIDENTIAL MEDALS OF FREEDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Presidents get to hand out plenty of perks _ from
ambassadorships and State Dinner invitations to, on the low end of
the scale, specially made boxes of M&AMP;Ms bearing the presidential
seal.
</P>
<P>
   With just five months left in his term, and his opportunities
for give-backs dwindling, President Clinton on Wednesday singled
out 15 people for Presidential Medals of Freedom, the country's
highest civilian honor. Some of the awards seemed to represent
belated presidential thank-yous. Some clearly had a political
twist. At least one was a consolation prize.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the awards, Clinton said he had huddled with his
Senate candidate wife in recent weeks to review the possibilities,
upstanding people from all walks of life nominated by aides and
outsiders alike.
</P>
<P>
   The honorees crowded the stage in the East Room. John Kenneth
Galbraith, the Harvard economist, sat next to Monsignor George G.
Higgins, a labor activist, and the Rev. Jesse Jackson, who is
Clinton's envoy to Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many things that I and the president are going to
miss about living and being part of the White House's life but
nothing more than this ceremony,'' said Hillary Rodham Clinton
during the elaborate ceremony featuring a Marine band, smartly
dressed military aides and the attendance of much of the Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Although the selection process itself is cloaked in mystery,
Mrs. Clinton perhaps had a role in advocating the names of Marian
Wright Edelman, her first boss at the Children's Defense Fund; the
Rev. Gardner C. Taylor, a prominent preacher from Brooklyn who has
backed her campaign; and Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, the man she
hopes to succeed in the Senate representing New York.
</P>
<P>
   The award was a consolation prize for Wesley K. Clark, who was
supreme allied commander of NATO during the air campaign over
Kosovo but lost out in his goal of becoming chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff. Now an investment banker, he wore a dark suit
instead of a uniform but still stood ramrod straight.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, over the course of his presidency, has doled out 83 of
the gold medallions decorated with red, white and blue _ half a
dozen during his first year, only a pair in 1997, 17 during the
mid-point of his second term. There are no limits to the number of
medals that can be issued, and although White House spokesman Joe
Lockhart said this was the final medal ceremony of the year, he
added, ``The president always reserves the right to do something on
a more ad hoc basis near the end of the administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has always reached out to Republicans in handing out the
awards, a practice he continued this year. Former Sen. Bob Dole won
the honor the year after he lost to Clinton in the 1996
presidential race. Former President Gerald Ford joined former
President Jimmy Carter and his wife, Rosalynn, in the East Room
Ceremony in 1999. This year, John Chafee, the late Rhode Island
senator, won the award posthumously.
</P>
<P>
   Other honorees this year included Holocaust survivor Simon
Wiesenthal, who listened to the ceremony by telephone while
recovering from a fall; Cruz Reynoso, a former judge from
California who is vice chairman of the U.S. Commission on Civil
Rights; former Sen. George McGovern, who was the 1972 Democratic
presidential nominee; James Edward Burke, chairman of the
Partnership for a Drug-Free America; William Crowe, former chairman
of the Joint Chiefs of Staff; Mildred Jeffrey, a labor activist;
and Mathilde Krim, founder of the AIDS Medical Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the highest honor of my life,'' said McGovern. ``I
treasure it even more than running for the presidency of the United
States. If I had won, that would have been the greatest honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, of course, he would have been the one handing out medals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
