<SLUG> BC-CDREVIEW-DELASOUL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MOSAIC THUMP' IS INTELLIGENT BUT FLAWED
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Out of ideas or hoping to cash in on past fame, a lot of
groundbreaking bands often wind up retreading the ground they
broke. Long Island hip-hop trio De La Soul is one of the few
groups, rap or otherwise, that don't look to their past to bank on
a secure future. No doubt, the trio's days of opening doors, as
well as minds, seem to be gone. But the guys _ Kelvin Mercer, David
Joliceur and Vince Mason _ are still making relevant, intelligent
music, as they've done on ``Art Official Intelligence: Mosaic
Thump,'' their first effort in four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Art'' is different from the threesome's previous efforts; it's
almost the flipside to its 11-year-old masterful debut, ``3 Feet
High and Rising,'' which pushed rap's envelope in an entirely
different direction with its mingling of hip-hop, reggae and jazz,
and its low-key humor and peace-and-love lyrics, which directly
defied the then-burgeoning gangsta-rap scene.
</P>
<P>
   This is hardly low-key. Most of ``Art,'' supposedly the first in
a three-disc series to be released in a year's time, has a
house-party vibe, sort of a first for De La. As with any good
party, there's a ton of guests, from Busta Rhymes to Chaka Khan to
members of the Beastie Boys. The Beasties' Mike D and Ad Rock's
turn on the rambunctious ``Squat!'' is one of the best things here.
</P>
<P>
   But De La hasn't lost its intellectual edge. Songs like ``My
Writes, Declaration'' and ``View'' may be upbeat, but the yrics
still address compelling issues, namely the corroding state of
hip-hop.
</P>
<P>
   What keeps this from ranking up there with De La's first effort:
too much filler, too much production. There are 17 tracks here, and
about five of them _ including the overly syrupy ``With Me'' and
the Quincy Jones-sampled ``Foolin' '' _ should have been axed.
</P>
<P>
   The production is a little too polished, too. A raw, organic
sound flows through their early records. That sound has been
replaced by studio slickness _ the same slickness found on most
other hip-hop discs. Hope production is as close as these guys come
to being like everyone else. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   De La Soul &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Art Official Intelligence: Mosaic Thump'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Boy Records &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a 1-5 scale &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
