<HEADER>
A7077 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-HELEN-THOMAS-HNS &LR;      08-09 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELEN-THOMAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DEBATES WILL PLAY A CRUCIAL ROLE IN THIS ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HELEN THOMAS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Just as George W. Bush got a big bounce in the
polls from the Republican National Convention, so will Vice
President Al Gore from the Democratic convention next week.
</P>
<P>
   But a bigger test for both will come when they kick off their
October debates. That's when the voters will really start paying
attention to the men who would be president.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor has not been enthusiastic about the match-ups
with his Democratic counterpart, but a Bush spokesman, Ray Selleck,
says, ``There will be debates.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush relies heavily on what he calls his ``good advisers'' to
articulate his policies. But you can bet he will be well coached
when the first debate rolls around.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, on the other hand, is licking his chops over the prospect
of going into the arena with Bush. With 16 years of experience as a
congressman and senator from Tennessee and eight years as vice
president, Gore knows the domestic and international issues that
will come up.
</P>
<P>
   He is remembered for trouncing Ross Perot, the feisty Reform
Party candidate, in a joint TV appearance in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Simple as it sounds, I recommend that both candidates go to the
grocery store before the debates and get the lowdown on grassroots
prices. In the past, candidates have marred their campaigns by
tripping up on the cost of everyday goods, giving voters the
impression that they are out of touch with the common people.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of the current candidates is known for high eloquence or
inspiring rhetoric in the manner of Abraham Lincoln and Stephen A.
Douglas in their historic debates of 1858.
</P>
<P>
   But in the recent past it's often the little things that count _
the gaffe that hurt and the repetitive one-liner that disarmed the
more earnest foe. So there are pitfalls even when the debaters have
been coached for weeks and are primed for the kill.
</P>
<P>
   There have been many memorable moments in modern debates. In
1988 comedians joked for months about Lloyd Bentsen's rapier
response to Dan Quayle, who linked himself to President John F.
Kennedy in the vice presidential debate: ``Senator, I served with
Jack Kennedy. I knew Jack Kennedy. Jack Kennedy was a friend of
mine. Senator, you're no Jack Kennedy.''
</P>
<P>
   In a debate in 1984 with Walter Mondale, President Reagan
startled millions of viewers as he rambled on about ``riding down
the California highway.'' He appeared to have lost his train of
thought and had a hard time getting back on track.
</P>
<P>
   He later recounted in his post-presidency autobigraphy that he
had ``crammed so hard on facts and figures, I flattened out.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that he had ``spent too many hours pouring over
briefing books and at skull sessions and mock debates preparing for
the encounter, and on the night of the debate I think I was just
over-trained.''
</P>
<P>
   When that debate was over, his wife Nancy was furious with his
aides for over-prepping him. Afterward, there was no question who
was in charge of scheduling the candidate. She was.
</P>
<P>
   I'll never forget the debate between President Gerald Ford and
Democratic challenger Jimmy Carter in October, 1976 when Ford said
there was ``no Soviet domination of Eastern Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a collective gasp in the audience, and the questioner,
New York Times correspondent Max Frankel, tried to get Ford off the
hook by asking if he meant that Russians did not have a ``sphere of
influence` in Europe. But Ford did not take the lifeline and
reiterated there was no Soviet domination of Poland, Yugoslavia and
Romania.
</P>
<P>
   That became THE story. It took Ford five days to acknowledge his
mistake. But the faux pas hurt him and he lost the election.
</P>
<P>
   When Reagan was challenging President Jimmy Carter in 1980, he
later recalled of their late October debate that it ``went well for
me and may have turned on only four little words.''
</P>
<P>
   Those words, which Reagan said just ``popped out of my mouth,''
were ``there he goes again'' after Carter accused him of opposing
Medicare benefits for Social Security recipients. Reagan repeated
the taunt several times in response to Carter attacks on his ultra
conservative positions. And the tactic worked. As Reagan said,
``The audience loved it ''
</P>
<P>
   He thought he scored even bigger when at the end of the debate,
he turned to the TV audience and suggested that people ask
themselves, ``Are you better off now than you were four years
ago?''
</P>
<P>
   That's one line George W. Bush can't steal. He might not like
the answer in this era of peace and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   But if Gore has the proud resume, Bush can present the winning
personality. And following Reagan's example, he could use a teasing
quip and throw the more intense Gore off balance.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, Bush's handlers are already laying the groundwork
for low expectations. When he's asked about what kind of
performance Bush will give in the debates against Gore, Bush's
chief campaign strategist, Karl Rove, paints Gore as a veteran of
political jousts and a master of the issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to survive,'' Rove says, trying to keep a
straight face.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans hope Gore will overplay his hand and come across as
a know-it-all, generating sympathy for Bush. The Texas governor,
who had debates with several other presidential aspirants in the
GOP primaries, takes after his feisty mother, Barbara Bush, and may
have some gibes of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Mannerisms are also important. In a 1992 debate, President
George Bush did not help himself in a three-way debate with Bill
Clinton and Ross Perot by looking at his watch and apparently
wondering when the ordeal would end.
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, the elder Bush did not help his Brahmin
image in 1984 when he bragged to a group of hardhats the day after
his vice presidential debate with Democrat Geraldine Ferraro. He
said he had ``kicked a little last night.''
</P>
<P>
   Both of the current candidates could have a problem if Patrick
Buchanan of the Reform Party and Ralph Nader of the Green Party
join one of the debates. If that occurs, fasten your seat belts.
Neither Buchanan nor Nader is a shrinking violet, and the whole
thing could turn into a four-ring circus.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Helen Thomas can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address helent(at)hearstdc.com
</P>
</TEXT>
