<DOCNO> NYT20000809.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7083 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TV-DYLAN-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      08-09 0454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DYLAN-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MEANINGLESS LOOK AT AN ICON
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below. `Tonight' refers to Sunday, Aug. 13, 2000) 
Our rating: 2 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For anyone who'd actually be interested in watching, ``Bob
Dylan: American Troubador'' could be retitled, ``Everything You
Already Knew About Bob Dylan and Didn't Have to Ask.'' It's a fan's
high-school term paper with such audio-visual aids as archival
footage of '50s Minneapolis, a New York blizzard and race riots,
combined with a line or two from a handful of Dylan classics.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons for the program's stunning lack of insight
into Dylan is the paltry band of witnesses it rounds up _
gnarly-toothed geezers who knew Dylan back in the day, a couple of
session guys, folks who apparently never even met the guy but have
listened to his albums (hey, you and I could probably be in this
film). Only The Band's Levon Helm, who appears here, could be said
to have spent any meaningful time with him, and his observations
are none too acute.
</P>
<P>
   There's a particularly strong '60s bent to the material, where
the inspirations for even semi-obscure songs are discussed at
length, while entire albums of the '70s, '80s and '90s aren't even
mentioned. (Potentially interesting subjects, such as the
underground controversy surrounding Dylan's authorship of ``Blowin'
in the Wind,'' perhaps his most famous song, are of course
ignored.) Dylan's previously well-documented '60s rate an hour of
the documentary, while the '80s and '90s scarcely rate 15 minutes,
when those are the decades that hold the most questions _ such as
how the heck did he tumble so far, anyway? And how did he muster
enough oomph to put together one last great album, 1997's ``Time
Out of Mind?''
</P>
<P>
   Dylan never comes off as particularly friendly _ or, in archival
interviews, even as vaguely articulate _ but his misanthropy is
hardly challenged or explored beyond a sweeping nod to the
``pressures of fame.'' Interviewees mainly spend their time trying
to convince us of his greatness, which seems fairly unnecessary
given his still-substantial place in pop music history.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well, the producers do un-earth one hilariously jaw-dropping
piece of footage _ a kitschy, Vegas-style tribute to Dylan from the
'60s. And the snippets of music here should be enough to inspire
fans to dust off their Dylan CDs and give them another play. Which
can be done without, and more entertainingly than, sitting through
this perfunctory exercise in hagiography. &QL; 
______ &QL; 
The Show ``Bob Dylan: American Troubador'' &QL; 
What: ``Biography'' on the folk-rocker. &QL; 
Where: A&AMP;E. &QL; 
When: 8 tonight. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 1921EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000809.0278 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7084 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-OPPORTUNISTS-REVIEW-L     08-09 0411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPPORTUNISTS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPORTUNITY NEVER KNOCKS HERE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily New 
``The Opportunists'' is a modest, slice-of-life film that tries,
seemingly against its will, to turn into a caper yarn, with a
standard-issue reformed crook dragged, also against his will, back
for one last heist.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Christopher Walken does a fair approximation of an average guy _
well, there is a scene or two in which a line reading recalls the
nut cases he's built his career essaying _ playing Victor Kelly, a
former safecracker with a heart of gold. Now, he's a
none-too-talented auto mechanic with a mountain of debt and a
bar-owning girlfriend (former pop novelty Cyndi Lauper, who's OK
except she always needs to do something with her hands) who wants
to lend him money and keep him on the straight and narrow.
</P>
<P>
   Well, of course it's not that easy. In drifts Michael Lawler
(Peter McDonald), an Irish scam artist who claims familial roots
while at the same time hitting on Vic's daughter (Vera Farmiga,
oozing casual charm). He convinces Vic to organize a no-brainer
boost of a vault, which, of course, doesn't go as planned.
</P>
<P>
   Connell, however, is too fond of his characters to truly dump on
them, which in truth makes for some pretty listless drama.
Likewise, he pads the movie with a lot of protracted establishing
shots and scenes of characters just walking, walking. And for all
the footage he uses in an airport, you'd think something would
actually transpire there, but no _ it just looks like he couldn't
believe his good luck to shoot in an airport on such a tight
budget. And Kurt Hoffman's music may be the most blandly obscure
score in years _ the music evokes nothing emotionally in the scenes
over which it plays, it just takes up space on the sound track.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing about ``The Opportunists'' that's poorly
rendered, it's just that, try as Walken and Connell may _ and
perhaps they try too off- handedly _ they can't generate much
empathy for Vic's plight. It makes low-key movies seem
over-caffeinated. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
-The film: ``The Opportunists'' (R; language). &QL; 
-The stars: Christopher Walken, Peter McDonald, Cyndi Lauper, Vera
Farmiga, Donal Logue. &QL; 
-Behind the scenes: Written and directed by Myles Connell.
Producers John Lyons, Tim Perell. Released by First Look Pictures. &QL; 
-Running time: One hour, 29 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 1921EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000809.0279 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7087 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AMD-CHIP-NYT     08-09 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMD-CHIP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVANCED MICRO RELEASING DETAILS OF NEW CHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  By LAWRENCE M. FISHER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Advanced Micro Devices Inc. plans to release
design details of its new 64-bit processor on Thursday, a chip that
is intended to compete with the Intel Corp.'s forthcoming Itanium.
Advanced Micro said it expected the chip to help it gain sales in
the workstation and server market.
</P>
<P>
   With the public distribution of an overview by Advanced Micro's
programmers, software developers can now begin modifying existing
applications or creating programs to run on the chip, which the
company expects to ship next year.
</P>
<P>
   Software applications that are expected to benefit from the
increased power of 64-bit computing include large databases;
digital content creation, computer-aided design; security and
encryption; Internet content delivery; simulations; weather
prediction and oil exploration.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that is crucial to the company's strategy, the chip is
an extension of the so-called x86 architecture that is used in
Intel's Pentium family and in Advanced Micro's own Athlon; unlike
the Itanium, it is not an entirely new design. Advanced Micro says
this means that existing 32-bit applications will run on the chip
without modification and that writing 64-bit versions of those
applications will be a more straightforward process than it is on
the Intel product.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a very different approach from our main competitor, who
is essentially defining an entirely new architecture that is not
compatible with existing programs,'' said Martin Booth, Advanced
Micro's product marketing manager for computer products. ``Our
approach makes the job a lot simpler. You get 64-bit performance
while remaining compatible with the existing 32-bit installed
base.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Sullivan, an Intel spokesman, said the Itanium chip
would be compatible, even though it was not an extension of the x86
design.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the Itanium processor is designed from the ground up for
advanced 64-bit server and workstation environments, 32-bit
software runs on the processor in silicon with no emulation
required,'' Sullivan said. Intel published the details of the
Itanium on May 26, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said that there was some merit to Advanced Micro's
assertions of higher performance on existing applications, if no
way to prove them at this time, and that the company's strategy
made sense in light of Intel's market dominance. Although Advanced
Micro has made considerable gains in market share in the low and
middle end of the desktop PC market, it has only a tiny share in
workstations and servers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a segment of the market that will find their
proposition appealing,'' said Drew Peck, an analyst with SG Cowen.
``On the other hand, AMD doesn't have much experience marketing to
the high end of the market,'' Peck said, noting that those
customers willing to use a non-Intel processor can already turn to
Sparc, made by Sun Microsystems Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``My view is this market will be highly fragmented, so the total
opportunity is not huge,'' Peck said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Leibson, editor in chief of the Microprocessor Report,
said that Advanced Micro was taking a practical approach, albeit
one more likely to gain sales in the PC market than in servers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This backward compatibility stuff really only makes sense in
the desktop market, and I don't think it will affect price that
much,'' Leibson said. ``I think what they're doing is very
intelligently spotting an opportunity within Intel's strategy that
they can exploit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 1922EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000809.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7088 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-AIMEE-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      08-09 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIMEE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOVE IS WHERE YOU FIND IT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 1/2 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suggest the idea of a movie about Nazis and lesbians in
war-sundered Berlin, and you might first conjure up images of some
tastelessly campy item from the no-budget Troma catalog, or a lurid
wallow in self-loathing from Rainer Werner Fassbinder.
</P>
<P>
   Well, forget it _ ``Aimee &AMP; Jaguar'' is a stunningly layered and
humane film, based upon a true story, that deftly balances its twin
examinations, of the politics of both hatred and forbidden love, in
a surprisingly accessible fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Impeccably and vividly shot by Tony Imi with lots of saturated
colors, ``Aimee &AMP; Jaguar'' depicts the unlikely love affair between
a Jew and an anti-Semite who didn't know her lover's true identity,
between a woman who played both sides against the other as part of
her fierce, live-for- the-minute philosophy and one who was the
dully unfaithful wife of a German soldier and bored mother of four.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, outside their bedroom, outside the concert halls and
newspaper offices and tony dance clubs where they lived their
lives, bombs dropped obliviously, reducing their landscape to
rubble. The Nazis, inevitably, would do the same to their psychic
landscapes.
</P>
<P>
   Felice (Maria Schrader), who called herself ``Jaguar'' around
``Aimee,'' was a woman of many disguises. She worked at a Nazi-run
newspaper but more sincerely for the resistance; she first became
interested in ``Aimee'' when a friend who worked as her nanny told
her she had once claimed she could tell a Jew by their smell
(ostensibly, she wanted to see if it was true). Lilly (Juliane
Kohler), or ``Aimee,'' was a self-satisfied but scarcely
self-examining woman whose propensity for not considering the
consequences of her actions was adapted by her impetuous love; the
befogged decisions of both led to disastrous consequences.
</P>
<P>
   What could account for these two getting together, for these two
who ordinarily would not have met to have immersed themselves in
one another so deeply? Certainly, the nihilistic romance of being
spoiled yet implicitly doomed in accursed Berlin contributed to the
passion with which the two tore into one another, and yet the film
digs tantalizingly deeper, seeking out something more. Director Max
Farberbock, who co-wrote the screenplay with Rona Munro, adapting
Erica Fischer's book, builds the events leading to their first
ill-fated clinch and their first halting, tremulous flight of
passion deliberately, mesmerizingly, inexorably.
</P>
<P>
   Farberbock crams a lot of story and sociology and psychology
into his film's two hours and change and gives the film an
uncommonly strong sense of time and place on what couldn't have
been a particularly impressive budget. Given how timid much German
cinema that lands Stateside is regarding the Holocaust, this
hard-edged, boldly scurrilous and scandalous look back at the
world's darkest hour represents something like blue sky for fellow
fatherland filmmakers, paving the way, one hopes, to further
adventurous examinations of their country's greatest shame.
</P>
<P>
   Schrader and Kohler, who shared the Best Actress Award at the
Berlin Film Festival (certainly, no one would want to pick one over
the other), are marvels, giving fearlessly assertive performances
and appearing alternately ridiculously glamorous and shockingly
bedraggled by their country's policies. ``Aimee &AMP; Jaguar'' is
easily one of the year's best films _ not that it's traveling with
a particularly fast pack at this point _ and certainly one of its
most original and visually flamboyant. It's smart, it evokes a
world both alien and exotic and, ultimately, it's genuinely
affecting. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
-The film: ``Aimee &AMP; Jaguar'' (not rated; nudity, sexuality, adult
themes, violence). &QL; 
-The stars: Maria Schrader, Julia Kohler, Johanna Wokalek, Heike
Makatsch. &QL; 
-Behind the scenes: Directed by Max Farberbock. Written by Max
Farberbock and Rona Munro, based on Erica Fischer's book. Produced
by Gunter Rohrbach and Hanno Huth. Released by Zeitgeist Films. &QL; 
-Running time: 2 hours, 5 minutes. &QL; 
-Playing: Laemmle's Town Center 5 in Encino, Laemmle's Colorado in
Pasadena, Laemmle's Music Hall 3 in Beverly Hills. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 1922EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000809.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7090 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-AIMEE-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      08-09 0721
