<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7093 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DNA-MOTORS-ART-NYT     08-09 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNA-MOTORS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHERS BUILD MOLECULAR-SIZE MOTORS OUT OF DNA 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Portending a possible role for DNA beyond biology,
researchers at Bell Laboratories and Oxford University have
fashioned molecular-sized motors out of the chemical that stores
the genetic code.
</P>
<P>
   The DNA motors resemble tweezers that are so small they could
potentially pick up a single atom, with 13 trillion of the motors
fitting into a drop of water. The molecular tweezers are opened and
closed by other DNA that serves as ``fuel.''
</P>
<P>
   The development is part of an effort, still in its infancy, to
harness DNA as a structural and electronic material that might one
day be used to make ultra-tiny computers or mechanical devices,
like a robot that could cruise through the bloodstream to repair an
injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as we know DNA is not used this way in the body,'' said
Bernard Yurke, a physicist at Bell Labs who led the work, described
in Thursday's issue of Nature. ``We're using DNA in very
non-biological way, as a structural material and as a fuel in some
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   DNA could be attractive for such molecular construction because
a strand of DNA will stick only to another strand with a
corresponding sequence of bases, the chemical units that form the
genetic code. So DNA strands in solution could automatically
assemble themselves into a structure. ``Think of it as a smart
glue,'' Yurke said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the DNA tweezers might one day be used to pick up
particular ions for molecular construction or to provide motion to
a tiny machine. But Bell Labs, which is in Murray Hill, N.J., and
is part of Lucent Technologies, is more interested in computing.
For that the tweezers are not of direct interest but do demonstrate
the idea of self-assembly. In the future it might be possible to
attach electronic components to DNA and have the DNA strands link
to form a computer with far more speed and information storage
capacity than exists today, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nadrian C. Seeman, a professor of chemistry at New York
University, has used DNA to make three-dimensional ``stick
figures'' like cubes and also a mechanical switch that flips
between two positions when a chemical is added to solution. Nanogen
Inc., a biotechnology company in San Diego, received a patent this
year for a method of using DNA connected to fluorescent dyes to
make an optical memory that could potentially hold far more
information in a given space than a compact disk.
</P>
<P>
   But experts say it will be 10 years and possibly much longer
before practical devices could be made out of DNA. And some experts
said other chemicals might prove more useful than DNA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be cute little laboratory experiments,'' James
M. Tour, professor of chemistry and a molecular electronics
researcher at Rice University, said of work using DNA. ``I'm not
sure how viable it's going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem, Tour said, is that DNA works best in solution, not
solid form. DNA also does not conduct electricity well, limiting
its direct use in electronic devices.
</P>
<P>
   DNA is nature's method of storing huge amounts of information in
a tiny space. The space between each letter in the genetic code is
0.34 nanometer, or billionth of a meter. Existing electronics
technology makes features about 100 nanometers in size, more than
100 times as large.
</P>
<P>
   For several years scientists have been experimenting with using
DNA directly for computation. A problem to be solved can be encoded
in a sequence of bases. The DNA is then put into a test tube and
the DNA strands match up in a way that produces a strand encoding
the solution.
</P>
<P>
   But some experts say such chemical computers will be slower and
more cumbersome than electronic ones. So Yurke and others are
looking at using DNA more as a scaffolding to build electronic
computers.
</P>
<P>
   DNA is a double helix, a twisted ladder with each rung made of
two of the four bases in the genetic code. The base represented by
the letter A always pairs with T, and C with G, so when the ladder
is split down the middle, each half will bind only with another
half that has the complementary sequence of bases.
</P>
<P>
   To molecular tweezers are made by putting three specific strands
of DNA into a test tube. The strands stick together to form two
stiff double-stranded arms connected by a short single strand that
acts as a hinge. A single strand dangles off the end of each arm.
</P>
<P>
   To close the tweezers, a single strand of DNA that is
complementary to both dangling ends is put into solution. This
``fuel'' DNA binds to those ends and pulls them together, almost
like tying a shoe. To open the hinge, a strand complementary to the
fuel strand is put into the solution. It eventually out-competes
the tweezers' arms to bind to the fuel DNA. This double-stranded
``waste'' product floats away, like the exhaust from an engine.
</P>
<P>
   Others taking part in the work were Andrew J. Turberfield, a
physicist at Oxford; Allen P. Mills Jr. and Friedrich C. Simmel of
Bell Labs; and Jennifer Neumann, a graduate student at Rutgers
University.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 1924EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
