<HEADER>
A7098 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-YALE-1960-COFFIN     08-09 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-YALE-1960-COFFIN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIGHT COLLEGE YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Thursday, Aug. 10, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By WILLIAM SLOANE COFFIN    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   STRAFFORD, Vt. _ College life in the 1950s was once described as
the bland leading the bland. Certainly on every campus there were
professors with disquieting thoughts and more than a handful of
students who worried about the world's future as much as their own.
But most students in the '50s considered their education more for
gain than for growth.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the '60s. At Yale, where I served as chaplain and
where three of this year's presidential and vice presidential
candidates were students (Joseph Lieberman arrived in 1960, George
W. Bush in 1964, and Dick Cheney was there briefly early in the
decade), a strong social consciousness was emerging. The 1955 bus
boycott by blacks in Montgomery, Ala., had put that city on the
moral map, and in 1960 I invited the movement's leader, Martin
Luther King Jr., to speak in the Yale chapel.
</P>
<P>
   The church was packed. King emphasized social, not personal,
morality. Quoting Paul Tillich, he declared, ``Since the law cannot
be wholly internalized in the conscience of imperfect human beings,
conscience must be externalized into law.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of students were still hanging around my house when I
returned from taking King to the railroad station. Said one, ``That
man makes us blacks proud to be black,'' to which a Southern white
quickly added, ``and us whites proud to be human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the '60s Yale students and a few faculty and chaplains
helped integrate buses, motels, lunch counters, parks, pools and
housing in New Haven. In the summer of '64, many students joined
voter registration drives in Alabama and Mississippi. Urging them
on was the editor of The Yale Daily News, Joe Lieberman, who in
October 1963 was himself a civil rights worker in Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   I thought highly and was very fond of Joe. For him Judaism
represented a world view undergirding progressive thought and
action. It was a view widely shared by many religious groups at
Yale. His being a Jew and editor of The News was less a
breakthrough than a validation of the fact that anti-Semitism was
receding.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1960s, the Peace Corps attracted many Yale
students. Students began seeking careers reflecting John Ruskin's
thought that the primary reward for human toil is not what you get
for it but what you become by it. The college became far more
diverse: many more Jews, African-Americans and foreign students
were admitted, and finally in 1969 Yale became co-ed.
</P>
<P>
   Fraternities lost popularity as many students agreed with E.B.
White that ``the opposite of fraternities is fraternity.''
Teach-ins and demonstrations opposing the Vietnam War were jammed _
addressed by John Hersey and Arthur Miller, among others. On Oct.
16, 1967, draft cards were turned in around the country in protest
and then handed over to the Justice Department in Washington. The
largest number from any one college came from Yale.
</P>
<P>
   I am sorry to say that during these years I knew only Lieberman,
neither Bush nor Cheney. It is also important to note that in all
these activities only a minority played active roles. But a
prophetic minority always has more to say than any majority,
``moral'' or ``silent.''
</P>
<P>
   I am sure Bush is right in criticizing the self-righteousness of
many of us in the anti-war movement at Yale. It is hard to fight
national self-righteousness without personal self-righteousness.
But it is also sad not to share in the action and passion of your
time. Often called a decade of student unrest, the '60s would be
better termed a time of ethical unrest, a time that I hope will
soon come again to disrupt our present complacency.
</P>
<P>
   (William Sloane Coffin was the university chaplain at Yale from
1958 to 1976.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
