<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7107 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-MEXICO0810-COX     08-09 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-MEXICO0810-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke may face probe in Mexico
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola is about to face another regulatory problem
in Mexico _ one of its most important markets.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's antitrust agency has reportedly found indications of
monopolistic practices by the Atlanta-based beverage giant. The
country's Federal Competition Commission will notify the company by
Friday, according to El Financiero/Infolatina.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola would then have to respond to the preliminary probe. A
more detailed investigation could follow.
</P>
<P>
   Coke spokesman Ben Deutsch said he could not comment because the
company has not seen details of the competition commission's
complaint.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the competition commission decides to proceed with an
investigation of the way Coca-Cola goes to market, it will look
into its sales practices, promotions, rebates and discounts to the
retail trade,'' said Andrew Conway, an analyst with Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   Conway said Pepsico and other competitors have complained about
Coke's selling practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coke's actions contradict their words,'' said Pepsi spokesman
Larry Jabbonsky. ``Saying they'll play by the house rules and
actually playing by them are two very different things. Talk is
cheap. Unlawful, monopolistic activity is not. It stifles
competition and restricts retailer and consumer choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Conway said Pepsico and other competitors ``may attempt to keep
Coke focused on regulators, rather than building brands. But under
(Chairman) Doug Daft's new strategy, Coca-Cola will work diligently
with regulators to try to come to a workable solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Coke has faced similar concerns in the past, and they have
hindered acquisitions in Europe, Australia and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   On July 26, Coke announced it was abandoning attempts to buy
Cadbury Schweppes' beverages in Mexico and Canada after failing to
overcome regulatory concerns. But on Aug. 1, Jabbonsky said, Coke
appealed a Mexican court's decision about the Cadbury deal to the
country's supreme court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Again, Coke's actions don't line up with their words,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsch, the Coke spokesman, said Jabbonsky was ``grossly
mistaken in his attempt to mislead the public. This appeal has
absolutely nothing to do with the acquisition of the Cadbury
Schweppes brands now or in the future. We decided not to pursue the
acquisition out of respect for competition concerns by the
regulatory authorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Deutsch said, the company is appealing certain
``procedural conclusions'' by the regulatory authorities that could
affect its operations in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Among Coke's major markets, Mexico has the highest per-capita
consumption, surpassing the United States for only the second time
last year, Conway said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Coke controls about 65 percent of the Mexican carbonated
soft drink market and about 23 percent of the market for all
nonalcoholic beverages.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
