<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEPRACOR-RULING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROZAC RULING HITS SHARES OF SEPRACOR, ELI LILLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shares of Sepracor Inc. and pharmaceutical giant Eli Lilly &AMP; Co.
plummeted Wednesday after a federal appeals court overturned a
lower court ruling in a decision that paves the way for generic
versions of Prozac to be in drugstores within a year.
</P>
<P>
   Sepracor has licensed to Lilly a variation of Prozac that is
believed to have fewer side effects. The Marlborough, Mass. company
saw its stock drop 23.375 to $104.50. Trading in Lilly shares were
halted after dropping 33.4375 points to $75.125.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge to Lilly's patent on Prozac, a controversial but
hugely popular antidepressant, was brought by generic drug
manufacturer Barr Laboratories Inc., which saw its stock nearly
double on the victory, rising 31.3125 to $77.75.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, which is potentially good news for consumers,
delivers a significant blow to Lilly. Prozac had 1999 sales of $2.6
billion, accounting for a quarter of its sales last year.
</P>
<P>
   Lilly officials said they would appeal the decision, but some
legal analysts said it is extremely rare for the US Supreme Court
to hear a patent case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, to the extent that Barr prevails, generic Prozac will
be on the market sooner than previously thought,'' said David P.
Southwell, executive vice president and chief financial officer of
Sepracor.
</P>
<P>
   Lilly officials said the soonest generics could be on the market
would be August 2001, but Barr officials said generic Prozac could
be out by February.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the ruling, Lilly believed it had patent protection on
Prozac until 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Sepracor's R-fluoxetine is currently in the latter stages of
phase two trials conducted by Lilly, and the soonest it could be
marketed is in 2002, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Southwell said the ruling does not affect Sepracor ``because the
product we licensed to Eli Lilly has a greater material efficacy
and fewer side effects against Prozac and other antidepressants. .
. . Clearly, we think we have a better drug.''
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts said a generic on the market before
R-fluoxetine will make it more difficult for the new drug to gain
market share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers might be swayed to generics, especially if generics
are out ahead of time and consumers have the chance to get
comfortable with them before the Sepracor drug is approved,''
analyst Robert Parente with Leerink Swann &AMP; Co. told Bloomberg
News.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, we are disappointed with the appellate court's ruling
and I have instructed our attorneys to appeal the decision,'' said
Sidney Taurel, Lilly chairman, president, and chief executive in a
statement. ``Going forward, we have developed a detailed plan of
action through which Lilly will continue to deliver innovative
products and earnings growth performance, even if we experience the
loss of this patent.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles E. Golden, Lilly's chief financial officer, said the
company expects to see earnings decline in the second half of 2001
and the first half of 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings per share growth had been 18 percent between 1998 and
1999, and the company expects only single-digit earnings-per-share
growth in 2001 and 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, continued strong underlying growth of our current
newer products, coupled with the expected launches of a number of
new products and indications in 2001 and 2002, will lead to a
return to earnings growth in the second half of 2002,'' Golden said
in a statement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
