<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-BUSH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH, MCCAIN BEGIN BATTLE FOR CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VENTURA, Calif. _ Defiantly rejecting conventional wisdom about
his prospects here, George W. Bush came to California Wednesday to
stake his claim on unfriendly territory, visiting a mostly
Democratic district less than an hour from the site of the
Democratic Convention next week.
</P>
<P>
   But the visit, designed to ``send a message'' to Vice President
Al Gore, was more an attention getting gesture than a real attempt
to raid Gore's base. If there is a real struggle for California _
and political analysts think there may be for the first time since
1988 _ it begins Thursday when Senator John S. McCain joins the
Bush caravan for the first time since their bitter California
primary fight.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans hope McCain, who once lured hundreds of thousands of
voters from other political parties in California, will help
transform what has for more than a decade been a losing battle for
the GOP. Republicans were defeated here the last two presidential
cycles. Both US senators are liberal Democrats. The highest ranking
Republican official is the Secretary of State.
</P>
<P>
   Bush aides insist the Texas governor could win here in his own
right, appealing to Hispanic voters as he has in his own state and
presenting the moderate face that emerged from the Republican
convention last week. But with 54 electoral votes at stake, and
with fond memories of a winning streak that lasted from 1960 to
1988, Republicans are placing unusual emphasis on McCain to appeal
to centrist Democrats and Independents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think Senator McCain will help Governor Bush reach out to
independents and swing voters,'' Bush communications director Karen
Hughes said. ``We are obviously saying that we think California is
a state we can win, and we don't want the Democrats to have free
reign with publicity for their convention.''
</P>
<P>
   Another possible incentive for the trip: Bush plans to raise up
to $400,000 at a fundraiser at the Stockton home of Alex Spanos,
owner of the San Diego Chargers footall team. He is attending
another fundraiser in Seattle Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Only five months have passed since McCain and Bush waged fierce
warfare during the California primary, which pitted all four
Republican and Democratic candidates against each other on the same
ballot. During an especially contentious stage, McCain was the
target of a negative advertising campaign in San Francisco that
attacked his environmental record and was paid for by a prominent
Texas Bush supporter.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, California helped seal McCain's fate. The Arizona
senator had hoped to win the so-called ``beauty contest'' to give
his campaign a symbolic boost, but he ended up in third place,
pulling in just 23 percent of the vote. Bush won the vast majority
of Republicans, with 60 percent, and a week later McCain dropped
out of the race. At the time, Bush heralded his victory as proof of
the power of the party faithful, who had chosen him to ``lead the
Republican Party'' to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the Democrats preparing to use California as a
launching pad to retaining the White House, Bush officials are
reinterpreting those California primary results _ and reshaping
their image to present a candidate who is directly allied with
McCain. Instead of noting that Gore came in first place in
California, winning 34 percent of the total vote, Bush aides point
out this: That together, Bush and McCain drew 3.9 million
Californians to the polls, while Gore and Bradley attracted only
3.3 million. And McCain alone drew 40 percent of the Independent
vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The combination of George Bush and Senator McCain is a
powerful combination,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush aides also point to polls that suggest Gore may hold a weak
lead in California, perhaps as little as three or four percentage
points. But the greatest indicator of their confidence is simply
that the campaign has chosen to spend time here. Instead of
continuing to plow through genuine swing states as he did last
week, Bush is devoting almost an entire week to the West Coast,
traveling to Stockton and Sacramento Thursday and on to Seattle
Friday. In total, he has spent 25 days here since the campaign
began, and Wednesday marked his seventh trip since the March 7
primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, we should be getting our brains beaten in
California,'' senior Bush strategist Karl Rove said. ``Gore should
be way ahead. But if you take every poll, and look at private and
public polls over the last month and average it out, we're down by
three points.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush reflected that confidence even in one of the most
Democratic sections of Ventura County, appearing before thousands
at a train station rally in Oxnard before boarding a north-bound
train along the coast. Ignoring a vocal handful of Gore supporters
in the crowd, Bush promised to repeal the estate tax, a pillar of
his stump speech. And he insisted he would not cede California as
some previous Republican candidates had.
</P>
<P>
   ``My intentions are to come here a lot, not only because it's a
pretty place but we plan to come here a lot because we intend to
carry California,'' Bush told the crowd. ``We're not writing off
any place, particularly this important state. . . . Come November,
mark my words. When the nation's watching, California will be in
the Bush-Cheney column.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 1931EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
