<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INFORMIX-MANAGEMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA FIRM OPENS MANAGEMENT OFFICE IN BAY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Informix Corp., a 20-year-old database and e-commerce software
company based in Menlo Park, Calif., has opened an office of the
president in Westborough, Mass. with plans to expand its management
presence there, according to Peter Gyenes, the company's new
president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The troubled software company has seen its stock plummet from
$35 a share four years ago to $21.25 in April to less than $5 a
share. Wednesday Informix shares closed at $4.6875, up 6.25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Named to the top post July 14, Gyenes was instrumental in
Informix's acquisition of Ardent Software Inc. in March for $1.1
billion, its largest purchase. He was chairman and chief executive
of Westborough-based Ardent.
</P>
<P>
   After the sale, Gyenes, 54, became an Informix board member. He
succeeds Jean-Yves Dexmier, who joined Informix in 1998 but served
as chief executive for just one year. He left after Informix
reported lower-than-expected sales and earnings in two quarters,
due, in part, to difficulties selling against rivals such as Oracle
Corp., and fewer sales of its Internet-retailing software.
</P>
<P>
   Gyenes said that while Menlo Park will remain the corporate
headquarters, he plans to expand the company's East Coast presence
in Westborough. Informix also has sales and service operations in
Burlington. Together they employ about 300 of the 4,400 employees
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Gyenes, who has a permanent office of the president in both
Menlo Park and Westborough, said he might ``possibly bring some
West Coast people here. We have functions that we can do in
Westborough in the corporate marketing area and we have other
members of the management team here.
</P>
<P>
   ``But frankly,'' he said, ``I have been CEO for about three
weeks and I am more concerned that Informix execute on its
corporate strategy in terms of reaching customers, showing that we
can meet their requirements. We have to perform better.''
</P>
<P>
   Informix's financial problems _ some of which date back to an
accounting scandal in 1997 _ have led to an exodus of some top
executives this year from Menlo Park, according to published
reports. The company has also had trouble with its purchase of
Ardent, which has taken longer than expected to integrate and has
not provided the revenue boost and earnings Gyenes expected.
</P>
<P>
   Last month Informix said its revenues for the second quarter
were $240.5 million, compared with $250.6 million in the same
quarter last year. Net income was $4.9 million, or 2 cents a share,
compared with net income of $22 million, or 8 cents, in the second
quarter of 1999, and excludes a $112 million one-time charge. The
quarterly results include Ardent Software's financial results.
</P>
<P>
   Informix, a distant number two competitor of Oracle Corp.,
bought Ardent to gain software tools such as DataStage, a data
extraction and transformation tool aimed at the e-commerce market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was one of the Ardent managers who was not planning to
continue in the operation, but here I am,'' said Gyenes, who
previously was president and chief executive of VMARK Software
Inc., Ardent's predecessor company.
</P>
<P>
   His ascension to the top of Informix was widely welcomed, as
some company employees and Wall Street analysts believe Gyenes can
turn the company around.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 1932EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
