u i BC-BOSNIA-CORRUPTION-NYT     08-09 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-CORRUPTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARREST SPOTLIGHTS CORRUPTION IN BOSNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ The arrest of a prominent Bosnian
banker and former government minister is being watched by foreign
officials here as a test of the government's resolve to fight
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, Alija Delimustafic, an owner of BH Banka, which
collapsed two years ago owing foreign embassies and international
organizations $15 million, was arrested on Friday night and charged
with fraud and abusing his position.
</P>
<P>
   But the case ``is not just about money going missing,'' a
foreign official here said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very, very high-profile fraud case,'' the official
said. ``It's an important test case, and we want to see it
succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Local news media have hinted that the affair goes to the core of
the Bosnian leadership in Sarajevo, some of whose members were
Delimustafic's close colleagues in the war from 1992 to 1995. The
government has been silent on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign officials here say corruption has reached such levels
that the powerful vested interests of the governing parties are the
major obstruction to democracy and development in Bosnia, as a
recent report by the General Accounting Office said.
</P>
<P>
   Delimustafic, 46, was arrested at the offices of his company,
Cenex, which ran the collapsed bank and still controls a trading
company, supermarket chain and an insurance company. The
well-connected businessman was interior minister in the early '90s.
In the war, he was foreign trade minister of a collapsed country
that had almost no trade and only the most tenuous links to the
outside world.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mirsad Bajraktarevic, head of the 120-member
financial police unit that is investigating corruption in Bosnia,
BH Banka collapsed with debts of $15 million. Some $900,000 of that
total belonged to the U.S. Agency for International Development and
represented operating funds and loan payments of its assistance
programs to Bosnia, according to the General Accounting Office
report. The Swiss Embassy has also acknowledged losing a
significant sum.
</P>
<P>
   None of the foreign creditors has retrieved money since the bank
crashed, and they have pushed the government hard to investigate
the case. Cenex has continued trading, and creditors have set their
sights on its assets, particularly a shopping center on the
southern edge of Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
   The center was probably built with some of the missing money,
Bajraktarevic said in an interview. ``And the bank made credits
beyond its means,'' he said, adding that the credits were not
insured.
</P>
<P>
   Bajraktarevic's task has been to track the dealings of the bank
over the last 10 years. He transferred the case to the prosecutor's
office last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very complex,'' he said. ``Twenty people were involved
in setting up the bank, and a lot of transfers were made out of the
country, and Bosnia has not signed any international conventions.''
</P>
<P>
   PricewaterhouseCoopers has been brought in to audit the bank, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another bank, the SAB Bank, collapsed with debts of $14 million,
also heavily at the expense of international organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The representative for the World Bank here, Elaine Patterson,
noted that banks in transitional economies are fragile and crashes
are to be expected before regulations are in place. But the World
Bank, itself a victim of fraud in Bosnia, has pressed hard for a
full investigation and pursuit of the banks' assets to pay back
creditors.
</P>
<P>
   Bajraktarevic echoed her insistence. ``We realized that if the
international community loses money in these banks,'' he said, ``it
will make it very difficult for Bosnia and Herzegovina to join the
European Union, and no investment will flow in, and there will be
no jobs, and we will remain totally isolated.''
</P>
<P>
   Local news media have hinted that Delimustafic is part of a
larger network of corruption that runs to the top levels of power.
A leading independent newspaper, Dvevni Avaz, suggested that the
government might have used him as a sacrificial lamb to placate
impatient foreign officials.
</P>
<P>
   Delimustafic was arrested days after the dismissals of two
powerful figures, the head of the Federation Tax Administration,
Ramiz Dzaferovic, and Agriculture Minister Ahmed Smajic. Both were
dismissed for corruption by the high representative, Wolfgang
Petritsch, who, although he has no power over the police, can
remove officials whom are deemed to be obstructing the rebuilding.
Petritsch has dealt similarly with more than 24 senior officials in
recent months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
