<DOCNO> NYT20000809.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7125 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MEDICATION-ERRORS-BOS     08-09 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICATION-ERRORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT DETAILS WIDESPREAD NURSING HOME MEDICATION ERRORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than 150,000 US nursing home patients suffer adverse drug
reactions each year _ from dizziness to dangerous falls to
potentially fatal liver damage _ because the staff makes
preventable errors in prescribing and monitoring medications, says
a groundbreaking new study.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from the University of Massachusetts School of
Medicine and Brigham and Women's Hospital, both in Boston, found
546 medication-related injuries at 18 Massachusetts nursing homes
over a year's time, including one death and 31 injuries that were
life threatening.
</P>
<P>
   If the results are extrapolated nationally, there are an
estimated 350,000 adverse drug events yearly in nursing homes and
20,000 of them are fatal or life-threatening, according to Dr.
Jerry Gurwitz, a gerontologist at UMass, one of the researchers in
the study. About half of those events could have been prevented, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has always been a `forgotten' population,'' said Gurwitz,
who directs the Meyers Primary Care Institute, an initiative of
Fallon Health Care System and UMass medical school.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Plumb, senior vice president of the Massachusetts Extended
Care Federation, which represents nursing homes, said the report
was not entirely surprising.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking care of far more seriously ill patients than in
the past, with frail patients on more and more medications,'' he
said. ``Secondly, we're in the middle of the worst staffing crisis
we've had'' since MediCare was established in the 1960s. One in 10
nursing positions is unfilled, and there is a high turnover rate of
less-skilled staff.
</P>
<P>
   The study, the first to focus on medical errors in long-term
care facilities, found one death during the one-year study, a
patient that died from liver damage. However, other patients were
oversedated, had severe allergic reactions, developed bleeding that
sometimes requiring transfusions, fell, broke bones, got
infections, suffered weight loss or experienced other ill effects,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the errors, the researchers noted 188 ``near misses,''
errors that could have resulted in adverse effects but didn't.
</P>
<P>
   The 546 medication errors picked up in the study translate to
about two errors per month, or 24 every year, in a 100-bed nursing
home, the researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And these figures are probably conservative'' because they
only included adverse effects that were noted in patients' charts,
said Dr. Gurwitz. The study report is being published in the August
issue of the American Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Nursing home patients may be more vulnerable to drug reactions,
Gurwitz said, because doctors don't spend a lot of time there and
do a lot of ``telephone medicine'' where patient records aren't
always at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Medications taken by nursing home residents are prescribed by
physicians who either have patients living in the facility or who
work directly for the extended care home. In contrast to hospitals,
which have in-house pharmacies, drugs for nursing homes are
typically supplied by large, warehouse-like distributors where
pharmacists may not have full information about the patients who
will be taking the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   When the patient starts taking the drug, it's the nurses'
responsibility to watch for any adverse side effects.
</P>
<P>
   If the staff knows the patients well, it's easier to ``notice
the cues, which may be subtle, that a resident may be having and
adverse reaction,'' said Marva Serotkin, CEO of The Boston Home in
Dorchester, Mass., which specializes in the care of patients with
multiple sclerosis.
</P>
<P>
   But with the high staff turnover rate in today's environment of
stingy reimbursements for nursing home care, and with frequent use
of temporary employees, patients' unusual reactions are more likely
to be overlooked, said Serotkin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed that one of the greatest needs is better ways of
keeping track of patient data,'' said Dr. David Bates, a Brigham
and Women's researcher and co-author of the study along with Dr.
Jerry Avorn, also at the Brigham, and others.
</P>
<P>
   Frequently involved in adverse events was warfarin, a
blood-thinning drug that many older people take to avoid clots. The
drug has a narrow range of effectiveness and too much or too little
can be injurious. Gurwitz said some of the incidents occurred when
doctors prescribed drugs that exaggerated warfarin's effects,
leading to bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   Gurwitz said that half of the events were judged as preventible:
that is, they could have been averted in the current system of
health care. The analysis also showed that the more serious adverse
events were also the most preventible.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999 the National Institute of Medicine estimated that as
many as 100,000 patients die every year in hospitals because of
medical errors of all kinds. Gurvitz said he and his colleagues
wanted to extend such studies to nursing home patients, who are a
population of 1.6 million nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, about 54,000 people are currently patients in
580 nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   Comparing the nursing home findings to those in acute-care
hospitals, Bates of Brigham and Women's said, ``many more of the
problems in the nursing homes related to a problem with with
monitoring'' drug treatment. ``And many more of them were
preventable,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The Serotkin of The Boston Home said quality improvement
programs that are common in hospitals are becoming more prevalent
in nursing homes. In one such measure, now required by federal law,
pharmacist-consultants visit nursing homes to audit drug records
and to train the staff in the safe use of medications, Serotkin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Growing concern over medication errors in the past several
errors have led many hospitals to install computerized systems that
automatically check dosages, drug interactions and research
protocols to prevent mistkaken drug prescription. Most nursing
homes, however, can't afford the costly equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Some do have, them however, and Gurwitz said he and his
co-authors are preparing for a study of two such nursing homes, one
in Toronto and one in Connecticut, to see how effective they are in
reducing medication errors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
