A7126 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-AFFAIR-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      08-09 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFFAIR-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN `AFFAIR` TO FORGET
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The French import ``An Affair of Love'' is more a parlor trick
than a film _ a pretty intriguing one, but a parlor trick all the
same. It documents the rise and fall, so to speak, of an apparently
kinky sexual relationship without revealing the participants' names
or occupations or much of their personalities _ and it also coyly
declines to specify what their particular fantasy life entailed.
</P>
<P>
   Nathalie Baye and Sergi Lopez play the couple _ he responds to
her personals ad, they meet in a Paris bistro, make some awkward
small talk and high-tail it for a nearby hotel room, leaving the
camera tantalizingly on the other side of the door. Emerging from
the room, their faces are blank, their good-bye busses desultory.
This pattern continues for a time; since sex preceded their melding
of minds, conversation flows more freely than it otherwise might,
and the only time we're allowed beyond the door is for a session of
what they call ``normal'' lovemaking.
</P>
<P>
   The constraints they've placed upon themselves begin,
inevitably, to strain their elliptical relationship. Their
``Rashomon''-like memories of the affair contradict one another.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``After Life,'' an affecting, winsome Japanese film
released last year, ``An Affair of Love'' depends a lot on your own
imagination and emotional contribution to the film, placing
yourself in the characters' positions and conjuring up images of
what happens behind that door and in their everyday lives. (``After
Life,'' however, was not about remotely sex, but people selecting
the one memory from their lives that they wanted to retain in
death.)
</P>
<P>
   The sexual McGuffin, however, becomes fairly irrelevant, as
director Frederic Fonteyne and writer Philippe Blasband seek to
strip a relationship to its bare bones _ sex and conversation _ to
divine what causes them to crumble. In fact, though, mundane,
day-to-day stuff contributes to love's decline just as much, just
as it also enriches affections, as well. Ultimately, Fonteyne and
Blasband deduce that lovers' needless misinterpretations of one
another's feelings can result in tragic breakups; if you need a
movie to tell you that, more's the pity.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Baye and Lopez serve as generically attractive tabulas
rasa for viewers to project upon, and still manage to give studied,
nuanced performances that hint at the lives they're not allowed to
discuss. Melancholy drapes over the proceedings as the film
suggests that in addition to the door separating the camera from
our athletic couple, there's also a palpable barrier separating our
lovers from the strangers in our own brains. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
-The film: ``An Affair of Love'' (R; nudity, language). &QL; 
-The stars: Nathalie Baye, Sergi Lopez. &QL; 
-Behind the scenes: Directed by Frederic Fonteyne. Written by
Philippe Blasband. Produced by Patrick Quinet/Artemis Productions.
Released by Fine Line Features. In French with subtitles. &QL; 
-Running time: One hour, 17 minutes. &QL; 
-Playing: Laemmle's Music Hall in Beverly Hills. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
