<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7129 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-09 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: SMILES ALL AROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB HERBERT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a clever strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Newt Gingrich is gone. And the others _ the Strom Thurmonds, the
Trent Lotts, the Tom DeLays, the Dick Armeys _ are all wearing
camouflage outfits and hiding in the tall grass. They will stay
there at least until November.
</P>
<P>
   What we see on television is the perfect front man, George W., a
happy-go-lucky guy who hasn't a harsh word to say about anyone, and
the avuncular Dick Cheney. They are meant to epitomize mainstream
America, and to deflect (via images that could have been crafted by
Norman Rockwell) any suggestion that the GOP is extreme.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes Al Gore with his brand new running buddy, Joe
Lieberman. At the moment they are sprinting away from Bill Clinton.
No sex, please, we're religious. But their real mission is to
convince voters that they are closer to the so-called mainstream
than Bush and Cheney, and that the reality of the GOP is something
other than moderate, tolerant, inclusive and kind.
</P>
<P>
   This is not easy without the delightfully unabashed
mean-spiritedness we've come to associate with the GOP ( Gingrich
once told a group of young Republicans, ``I think one of the great
problems we have in the Republican Party is that we don't encourage
you to be nasty.'' Tom DeLay has characterized the Environmental
Protection Agency as the ``Gestapo of the government.'')
</P>
<P>
   George W. may need a cheat sheet when it comes to naming world
leaders, but he was smart enough to recognize the need to put a
friendlier face on his party.
</P>
<P>
   But is a friendly face enough?
</P>
<P>
   The biggest decision Bush and Gore have had to make so far was
picking a running mate, and a comparison of their choices is
instructive.
</P>
<P>
   By today's standards, Joe Lieberman is pretty moderate. He
supports the Clinton administration's budget and trade policies,
favors a cut in the capital gains tax, is pro-choice on abortion,
feels strongly about protecting the environment, voted for the
Clinton administration's welfare reform legislation, is willing to
experiment with school vouchers, and has taken a harsh stand
against what he views as excessive sex and violence in the
entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney is another story. His avuncular persona is one
thing. But his political views are something else. The Republican
Party can't find a smile wide enough to conceal those aspects of
his congressional voting record that were way outside the American
mainstream. At times he was more extreme than the guys now hiding
in the high grass.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988 Dick Armey and Tom DeLay were part of the overwhelming
majority to vote for the AIDS Federal Policy Act, which was the
first major bill to provide funds for AIDS testing and counseling.
Dick Cheney was one of only 13 House members to vote against it.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984 and 1987 he voted against funding the Older Americans
Act, which offered nutrition and other services to the elderly. He
voted repeatedly against funding for Head Start. (Now that the
national spotlight is on him, he says he will support Head Start.)
He voted against subsidizing school lunches for poor children. He
voted against aid to college students. He voted against fair
housing legislation. He was one of only eight members of the House
to vote against the Clean Water Act in 1987, and was one of only 21
to vote against the Safe Water Drinking Act in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   He is far outside the mainstream on abortion. He has
consistently opposed abortion even in cases of rape and incest, and
even when the life of the mother is at stake. That, to most
Americans, is extreme.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the legislation to ban plastic guns, which
could not be detected by airport security. Even the National Rifle
Association supported that measure. But not Cheney. He was one of
only four members of the house to vote against the ban. You will
not find many Americans of any political persuasion who would
support that position.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney is way out there.
</P>
<P>
   But he's got a nice, quiet, steady way about him. He doesn't
look like an extremist.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Lieberman believe their views are in sync with the real
American mainstream. But they will have a tough time trying to
unmask this year's happy-face Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
