<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7130 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-REFUGEE-SHIP-ART-NYT &LR;      08-09 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEE-SHIP-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARCHING FOR A SUNKEN SHIP TO HONOR 778 JEWS KILLED IN TURKISH
WATERS   IN 1942 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: England, Ore.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT25, NYT26 and NYT27 is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By DOUGLAS FRANTZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ Greg Buxton is searching for sunken treasure
of an elusive nature _ not gold or artifacts, but memories of 778
lives lost and largely forgotten in the depths of the Black Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning on Thursday, he and a crew of volunteers will scour
the seabed north of here with sonar for the Struma, a steamer sunk
by a Russian submarine in 1942. The victims were mainly Romanian
and Russian Jews fleeing the Holocaust. Among them were Buxton's
paternal grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   The search and an attempt to organize a memorial ceremony next
month have resurrected a wartime tragedy. They are provoking
discomfort in Turkey _ the authorities recently indicated that they
might not allow divers to approach the ship if it is found _ and
renewing old questions about the response of other countries to the
Nazi genocide.
</P>
<P>
   The Struma death toll was small compared with the totals in the
millions in Europe. But Radu Ioanid, a scholar at the U.S.
Holocaust Memorial Museum in Washington, said the sinking
symbolized the indifference of many countries to the plight of the
Jews during the war.
</P>
<P>
   The Struma's journey was desperate from the start. Fleeing
massacres and labor camps, nearly 800 people paid $1,000 each for
passage on the ship from Romania's Black Sea coast to Palestine.
The passengers were jammed onto the 150-foot vessel, with makeshift
bunks stacked 10 high and only one freshwater outlet.
</P>
<P>
   Before the ship left Constanza, Romania, on Dec. 11, 1941, the
Romanian police took almost everything of worth, down to the copper
pots in the galley. The engine failed a few miles out of port, and
the captain of a passing tug repaired it in exchange for the
wedding rings of the passengers, their only remaining valuables.
</P>
<P>
   The Struma limped along for three days, but its engine failed
again, and Turkish tugs towed it into Istanbul. Fearing that
passengers might try to remain in the country, the police kept them
on board while the Turkish and British authorities decided their
fate. Istanbul's Jews donated food, but conditions grew squalid as
talks dragged on.
</P>
<P>
   Britain, which controlled Palestine, was generally unwilling to
let in large numbers of refugees, and this case proved no
exception. British officials refused to allow the passengers to
continue without visas. Three people with expired visas were
permitted to proceed overland, and a family of four left the ship
through the intervention of Vehbi Koc, an influential Turkish
Muslim businessman, who intervened at the request of an associate.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an emotional debate in Parliament in London, the British
would not budge. Turkey was struggling to remain neutral in the war
and feed its population and did not want to provide sanctuary for
more people.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy days after its arrival, on the evening Feb. 23, 1942,
the Turkish police took over the Struma and towed it up the
Bosporus to the Black Sea. It was set adrift without a working
engine. At dawn the next day, a Russian submarine sank it with a
single torpedo. There has never been an explanation of why a
Russian submarine would have attacked the Struma, a nonmilitary
steamer out of a neutral port.
</P>
<P>
   David Stoliar was 19, fleeing Romania with his girlfriend and
her family when the ship was torpedoed. Now 77 and living in Bend,
Ore., he remembers each detail of that morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was one of the lucky ones who was blown up into the air, and
I fell into the sea,'' Stoliar said in a telephone interview
Wednesday. ``When I came to the surface, there was nothing except a
tremendous amount of debris and many, many people swimming in the
water. It was very, very cold, and slowly we had a hard time moving
our feet and our hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoliar recalled fighting to stay afloat as the number of
swimmers dwindled. As night fell, he was clinging to a piece of
deck with a Bulgarian crewman. He saw no one else.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning Turks from a lighthouse plucked the two men
from the water. The crewman was dead and, it turned out, so was
everyone else _ 103 children, 269 women and 406 men.
</P>
<P>
   Buxton, a computer programmer in Birmingham, England, heard the
tale of the Struma from his father, Michael, now 83 _ who, a young
Romanian at the time of the sinking, had enlisted in the British
Army. Two years ago he decided to locate the ship, film it and
conduct a memorial service to honor the grandparents he had never
met. He sold his house to finance the effort and received some
money from the Washington Holocaust museum.
</P>
<P>
   The first step is finding the wreckage, which is believed to be
in about 250 feet of water 7 to 10 miles offshore. A museum and
foundation affiliated with the Koc family, one of Turkey's
wealthiest, is providing a research ship, and the museum director,
Selcuk Kolay, will supervise the search.
</P>
<P>
   But the actual diving may not take place. Buxton said he had
earlier received permission from the Turkish authorities for
experienced divers to survey and film the Struma after it was
located. But recently the authorities have reversed themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish officials declined to discuss the matter. It is unclear
whether the objection is a result of a bureaucratic snag, or
whether, as a Western diplomat theorized, the government is
uncomfortable about publicizing the wartime incident.
</P>
<P>
   As the tour boats and tankers plowed the Bosporus outside his
hotel, Buxton tried to be philosophical. Whether the ship is found
and the dive goes forward, he said, the memorial service on Sept. 3
will serve as a proper farewell to the 778 victims.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of some passengers are expected to attend, and
Stoliar, the lone survivor, said he would like to come to offer his
own goodbyes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
