<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CHEERLEADER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRYING TOO HARD FOR APPROVAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When ``But I'm a Cheerleader'' screened at Q Cinema, Fort
Worth's Gay &AMP; Lesbian Film Festival, it drew a sellout crowd and
enthusiastic response. It's baffling, then, to see the bludgeoning
the movie has taken from some critics. Yeah, the film's hardly
perfect, but it's far from worthless.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it would be interesting to see someone put a little more
teeth into a satire about ``curing'' homosexuality. ``Cheerleader''
is just too nice about it. Director Jamie Babbit seems to want to
avoid the mean-spiritedness of the homophobia that her movie sends
up, but more than that, she wants the movie to be liked. She
shouldn't have to try so hard; after all, it's already preaching to
the converted.
</P>
<P>
   Natasha Lyonne plays Megan, who doesn't give much thought to
sexual orientation one way or the other; after all, she's a
cheerleader, and she has a boyfriend, so she must be straight,
right? But Babbit and screenwriter Brian Wayne Peterson give things
away too fast: Not only does Megan have slo-mo daydreams about her
cheering-squad mates, she also has pictures of scantily clad women
decorating her locker, and she's a vegetarian who listens to _
gasp! _ Melissa Etheridge.
</P>
<P>
   If the movie had been more ambiguous about Megan, it might have
had more resonance. As it is, it's a sporadically funny tale about
gay rehabilitation as Megan's parents and friends shanghai her to a
camp that ``fixes'' gay teens. Predictably, Megan falls for one of
her campmates, the cynically earthy Graham (Clea DuVall), and the
movie begins to feel like an overtly lesbian ``Girl, Interrupted.''
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, the most amusing moments use the same sort of
stereotype-mocking humor that dominated the decidedly more
mainstream ``In &AMP; Out.'' All involve RuPaul Charles working (out of
drag) as a counselor trying to instruct the males in the rituals of
manhood: i.e., auto mechanics, football and chopping wood. It's a
sign that the movie's eager to please, and it offers enough laughs
to be pleasing. But it should have been eager to rage. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
