<SLUG> BC-DR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 AURA-DUEL10-COX &HT;    Like many parents, Atlantans are caught in the middle as advice
mavens Laura Schlessinger and John Rosemond spar over child care
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For millions of stressed-out parents, radio host Dr. Laura and
family psychologist John Rosemond are the twin titans of tough
love.
</P>
<P>
   Looming over the media landscape, both have emerged as stars of
radio, TV, the Internet and newspaper columns. Between them, they
have authored more than a dozen how-to books for confused mommies
and daddies.
</P>
<P>
   They are proudly conservative and deeply religious. Their
careers have been built on nagging (Laura Schlessinger) and nudging
(Rosemond) their followers toward a child-rearing promised land: a
disciplined, spiritually fulfilled family.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, however, there's been trouble in paradise.
</P>
<P>
   They've never met, but Rosemond and Schlessinger have spent
recent weeks sparring publicly on an issue that 9-to-5 parents have
been agonizing over for decades: putting kids in day care.
</P>
<P>
   And as the sparks fly, Rosemond vs. Schlessinger has done more
than just prompt thought about day care. The tiff also exposes the
pitfalls of taking celebrity advicemongers too seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Child rearing, says Laurie Bengochea of Alpharetta, Ga., who has
four children ages 8 to 20, ``is like being in a war.''
Schlessinger and Rosemond, she says, ``are like two generals
telling you to read the manual. But when you're in battle, you
can't sort it all out that easily.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosemond, who has a family practice in North Carolina, has
recommended day care when both parents work, regardless of their
reasons for working.
</P>
<P>
   The feud apparently started in May on CNN's ``Larry King Live,''
when Dr. Laura criticized working parents who put their children in
day care. When asked by King if couples should avoid having
children if they plan on putting them in day care, Dr. Laura
answered: ``Yes. If you're not going to make them your first
priority, get a parakeet.''
</P>
<P>
   When reporters later solicited Rosemond's opinion of Dr. Laura's
remarks, he wrote a July column, accusing her of
``self-righteousness'' and ``unbending dogmatism.'' (Rosemond's
weekly column appears in the AJC; Schlessinger's radio show is
carried locally on WGST, 640 AM.)
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Laura in turn slammed Rosemond in a radio show. Her office
would not return calls seeking a tape or transcript.
</P>
<P>
   Rosemond, who is to appear in Atlanta tonight as part of a
public-television fund-raising drive, fired another salvo in a
telephone interview. He questioned Dr. Laura's credentials,
pointing out that Schlessinger's eponymous doctorate is in
physiology, not psychology. (Rosemond has a master's in psychology
and a license to practice in the state of North Carolina.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't stand to listen to her for more than five minutes,
she's such a know-it-all,'' Rosemond said. ``We both call ourselves
conservatives, but we're not on the same team. I would love to
debate her on the air. But it would have to be arranged by Don
King, not Larry King.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Laura, who is based in Los Angeles, declined an interview
request, but her position on day care is well-known. She has often
referred to working mothers with children in day care as
``selfish'' and sternly warned them about the dangers of
``parenthood by proxy'' _ which is also the title of her latest
book.
</P>
<P>
   In it, Dr. Laura warns that a generation of children raised in
day care has contributed to juvenile delinquency, high divorce
rates and a growing acceptance of antisocial behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her opinions on child care show that we don't have the same
family values,'' Rosemond said. ``I believe the marriage should
come first. She believes the child should come first. I think the
center of attention should be the adults, not children.''
</P>
<P>
   Bengochea of Alpharetta is stay-at-home mom who sides with Dr.
Laura. Her husband works full-time outside the home, and she has
never considered putting her children in day care to pursue a
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your career is more important than your children, then you
are very selfish,'' Bengochea said. ``If you don't have to be a
working mom, why should you be?
</P>
<P>
   ``The only problem I have with Dr. Laura is that she's not very
graceful when she gives advice. She can be brutal, and that makes
it more difficult for some parents who may be feeling guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Laura's take-no-prisoners style and strident position on day
care may inspire guilt in her callers, but it has made her much
more famous than Rosemond, who is best known for his hard-line
approach to issues such as potty training and child discipline.
Schlessinger boasts a daily audience of 2 million listeners who
tune in for her topical tongue lashings on radio.
</P>
<P>
   Make that 2 million minus Ellen Fix, 44, of Dunwoody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to listen to her on the radio, but she stressed me out
so much that I stopped,'' said Fix, an advertising copy writer who
has a 7-year-old daughter and a 9-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   ``My kids were in day care from 3 months until they went to
school, and they're in the gifted program getting straight A's,''
Fix said. ``If you listen to her, you'll spend every waking minute
with them wiping their butts until they're 18. Now that's what
makes them juvenile delinquents.''
</P>
<P>
   The day care decision was not so easy for Larry and Donnah
Wilson of Acworth. Long before Schlessinger and Rosemond became
celebrity kibitzers, the couple agonized over child care issues
when Donnah decided to earn a college degree. The only experts they
trusted were each other, Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't an easy call for us, and I think from my wife's
perspective her natural urge was to stay home with the kids,'' said
Larry Wilson, 51, a pediatric nurse practitioner.
</P>
<P>
   But his wife's decision to advance her education has paid off,
Wilson says. She not only earned a degree in occupational therapy,
but also a degree of respect and admiration from her children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was the right decision because she really enjoys
her work, and my kids saw this woman who went back to school in her
30s and became very successful,'' he said. ``It's funny, though,
that my wife and I don't listen to Dr. Laura, but our kids do.''
</P>
<P>
   Doree Lynn, a practicing psychologist in Washington and author
of the upcoming book ``Getting Sane Without Going Crazy'' (Xlibris,
$25), has been keeping tabs on the tiff between Dr. Laura and
Rosemond.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn says she believes that divergent opinions on difficult
issues such as day care are more helpful than harmful for parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people hear these so-called experts disagree, maybe they'll
say, `Wait a minute, there is no one right answer,''' Lynn said.
``The only real danger here is if we take complete strangers and
empower them to lead our lives for us in 20-second sound bites.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa DeGrace, 37, of Tucker, says she isn't swayed much by
celebrity therapists when it comes to raising her 10-year-old
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people listen to them mostly for shock value or
entertainment, but I form my own opinions,'' DeGrace says. ``My
daughter was in day care since she was 3 months old. I've always
had to work and I never felt guilty. I'm very glad aon WGTV
</P>
<P>
   John Rosemond will be in the Atlanta studios of Georgia Public
Television from 8 to 9:30 tonight to take part in WGTV's August
membership campaign and introduce his public television special,
``Assuming the Power of Parenthood With John Rosemond.'' He will
take questions from callers if time permits.
</P>
<P>
   Lyle V. Harris writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
