<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEST-FIRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH QUESTIONS ARISE FROM WORST FIRE SEASON IN 50 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  By ROSS E. MILLOY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMILTON, Mont. _ After a steep hike to the top of a hill
overlooking Dixon Creek near here, Bobby Kitchens pointed to a
mound of rubble surrounded by blackened trees, smoking stumps, and
everywhere, a 2-inch layer of gray soot.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was one beautiful home, someone's dream home, with one
beautiful view,'' he said, sweeping an arm across the Stygian
panorama left behind by forest fires that swept through this area
on Sunday. A thick fog of smoke still lingered in the air, and,
stretching into the misty horizon, all that could be seen on the
rolling hills below were blackened tree stalks, many still smoking.
</P>
<P>
   The house that Kitchens, a Forest Service information officer,
was pointing out had been reduced to ashen remnants of someone's
lost mountain lifestyle: twisted tin; stones from a toppled
chimney; a half-melted refrigerator; some charred mattress springs;
and a scorched television set overturned when the table it was
resting upon burned away.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people did a lot of things right in protecting their
house. They just didn't do enough,'' said Kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of what officials are calling the nation's worst
fire season in more than 50 years _ with 70 major fires consuming
over a million acres of forests in a dozen Western states _ Forest
Service officials are having to answer a lot of questions about the
unprecedented dimension of this summer's crop of forest fires, said
Kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people say, `Why don't you just put out those fires?'
Frankly, it's just not that simple,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the sheer magnitude of this year's fires, trends
in population migration and the Forest Services own policies
exacerbate the difficulty of combating them, according to Kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   One problem, he said, is what the Forest Service refers to as
``human interface.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got too many people moving into heavily wooded areas
like this. There's no way we can save a home like this, positioned
at the top of hill, surrounded by all these trees. It's just not
going to happen,'' he said. ``When humans interface with the
natural environment in a remote setting, you're going to have
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been fighting fires for 37 years, and I see a definite
trend. It used to be we'd never see a house or structure when we
were on a fire, but these days, it's rare that you have a fire
where you are not trying to save buildings and people,' said
Kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   The official policy of the Forest Service, he said, is to
protect people and structures first, then to worry about putting
out the fire. ``Saving houses and buildings diverts resources away
from containing the fires, so you ultimately get bigger fires with
more destruction,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And no place is that problem more apparent than here in the
Bitterroot River Valley of Montana.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of property damage, the valley may be the most
vulnerable part of the state to forest fires. Ravalli County, where
Hamilton rests, is the fastest-growing county in Montana, having
grown 40 percent in the last eight years. There are 35,000 people
living in the dry Ponderosa pine forests in the valley bottom.
</P>
<P>
   And that is where the fires burn the hottest, said Bill Armold,
a planner for Ravalli County.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have come here because it's the last best place,''
Armold said. ``It's an unspoiled picturesque mountain valley with
views, a river and wilderness.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those people is Lisa Wissenbach, who was canning tomatoes
on Sunday when a city official told her it was time to evacuate the
home she and her husband had built in the community of Pinesdale
near here.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, she was still staying at a junior high school in
Hamilton with her five children, waiting to hear if her home would
survive the fires moving near Pinesdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never occurred to me that this might happen. We even let
the fire insurance lapse when my husband was changing jobs, and
now, with the fires on, the company won't reinstate us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth and Bob Sporer had read a lot of magazines about the
Bitterroot Valley and fallen in love with the area before they had
even seen it, said Sporer, a retired heavy equipment operator from
El Cajon, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a place to get out of the rat race,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday the Sporers were forced to evacuate their dream home
when the fires turned their way. They have not been back since.
They have heard their home is still standing, though two nearby
homes and most of the trees have burned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our neighbors got in and said everything in their home is
black with ash and dirt from the fire. And I just got new bedroom
furniture,'' Sporer said. ``But at least the house is still
standing.''
</P>
<P>
   Sporer shook his head emphatically when asked whether the
charred landscape would force him from his mountain refuge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't discourage me that much. I'll have to cut down some
burned trees. But things will grow back. It'll green up, if we ever
get any rain,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another part of the growing fire problem is a contradiction that
has not been addressed, according to Forest Service officials.
</P>
<P>
   Western ecosystems have adapted to periodic, low intensity fires
that clean out accumulated debris and thin the number of trees. But
for decades the policy has been to suppress all fires, and people
have built their home amid a dangerous accumulation of fuels.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think the more trees you have, the healthier the
forest, but actually, it's just the opposite,'' said Jerry
Williams, director of Fire and Aviation Management for the Northern
Region of the U.S. Forest Service in Missoula, Mont.
</P>
<P>
   ``A healthy forest has 60 to 70 trees per acre. Instead, we have
600 to 700 trees per acre here and it's the driest period ever
recorded in some places. These places are very vulnerable to high
intensity fire,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As fire officials here noted that single-digit humidity, high
temperatures, and an extended drought had conspired to create
almost textbook conditions for more fires, they warned local
residents Wednesday to brace themselves for an incoming lightning
storm that was recording 300 strikes per hour just west of here
Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot guarantee that we can protect every structure,''
said Jack Sept, chief of external affairs at the National
Interagency Fire Center. ``That's the cold truth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
