<SLUG> BC-REFORM0810-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reform Party rivals battling for high stakes
 &HT;    By Saeed Ahmed
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For political junkies tired of tightly choreographed
conventions and eager for a little mudslinging, the Reform Party
gathering this week promises to be must-see TV.
</P>
<P>
   The four-day nominating convention that begins in Long Beach,
Calif., today pits one-time GOP fixture Pat Buchanan against
loyalists of party founder Ross Perot who want the conservative
commentator disqualified.
</P>
<P>
   They say Buchanan padded voter rolls in the party's national
mail-in primary and refused to turn over a list of those who
received ballots from him.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high: the fractured party's future, the
presidential nomination and $12.5 million in federal matching
funds.
</P>
<P>
   The hostility between the two camps came to a boil Tuesday, when
Buchanan called a pre-convention national meeting and overturned
his disqualification using the majority of delegates he has
garnered touring the country and creating new chapters.
</P>
<P>
   The showdown degenerated into a shouting, shoving match, with
Perot loyalists storming out and promising to run a rival
convention in the same convention center and nominate their own
candidate. They also are considering a lawsuit to block Buchanan
from gaining access to the federal matching funds that Perot earned
in the 1996 election by winning 9 percent of the popular vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not over until we defeat the Brownshirts and despicable
tactics of the Buchanan campaign,'' said national secretary Jim
Mangia, who led the walkout.
</P>
<P>
   The bizarre turn of events could mean a hostile face-off between
the two Reform Party factions on the opening day of the convention
today.
</P>
<P>
   So combustible is the atmosphere that organizers have beefed up
security, with state and local police outside the convention halls,
installed metal detectors at the entrances and stationed a dozen
bouncers inside to handle any rowdy outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are prepared for every eventuality in terms of physical
threats, because there will be people there who will try to disrupt
the proceedings,'' said Gerald Moan, the interim party chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Buchanan, who claims that ``it is pretty much the end
of the Reform Party'' if he is denied the nomination, is so sure of
getting the party nod that he has alerted reporters to the time and
place of his victory party.
</P>
<P>
   But lost in all the brouhaha is the man standing between
Buchanan and the $12.6 million: John Hagelin. A nuclear physicist
from Iowa and a third-time nominee of the Natural Law Party,
Hagelin agreed to run on the Reform ticket at the behest of Perot
supporters who needed someone to block the socially-conservative
Buchanan after their leader declined entreaties to oblige.
</P>
<P>
   ``For over a year, I have been campaigning to forge a powerful
coalition of America's leading third parties, and the Reform Party
in the past has been such a powerful voice for reform in America
(that) it was a perfect fit,'' Hagelin said.
</P>
<P>
   Like his opponent, the secular and socially liberal Hagelin
believes that in the end the nomination will belong to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the courts talk to the lawyers, the lawyers will tell them
that the faction that holds up legally with the proper
credentialing procedures is ours, and the other is just a Buchanan
pageant,'' Hagelin said.
</P>
<P>
   The party's convention lasts until Sunday. Perot loyalist Mangia
promises more turmoil, and Buchanan backer Moan agrees: ``You ain't
seen nothing yet.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
