<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL STRONG SECOND QUARTER SPURS RECOVERY 
</HEADLINE>
  By JENNIFER L. RICH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ Brazil's economy grew 3.92 percent in the
second quarter compared with the same period a year earlier, the
government said on Wednesday in a report that suggested the
country's recovery from its devastating currency crisis in early
1999 was accelerating.
</P>
<P>
   The report by the National Statistics Institute was stronger
than many forecasters had expected. It led some to project that
growth rates for the second half of the year and in 2001 would also
be stronger than forecast as the country benefits from a series of
interest rate reductions made by the central bank this spring to
stimulate borrowing and spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows that we are having a really solid recovery,'' said
Gustavo Loyola, a consultant at Tendencias Consultoria and a former
president of the central bank. ``Investor and consumer confidence
is growing. Barring any imported crises, we can expect even better
growth for next year.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first six months of the year, Brazil's gross domestic
product grew 3.84 percent compared with the period in 1999, when a
devaluation of the currency, the real, in January sent shock waves
throughout the economy and reduced that year's growth to little
more than 1 percent. Analysts say that the six-month results now
make the government's growth target of 4 percent this year
achievable. For next year, economists expect growth of around 4.5
percent to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Agricultural production was a major contributor to
second-quarter growth as crops of coffee, soybeans and other
staples grew by 10.75 percent, more than expected. Brazil's
industrial production growth rate of 4.34 percent in the quarter
was also considered a strong sign of steady expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Agricultural production is a volatile figure that can vary
greatly from year to year,'' said Andre Carvalho, chief economist
at the Federation of Industry of the State of Sao Paulo.
``Industrial growth usually builds on itself every quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Carvalho said companies were taking advantage of cuts in
interest rates to finance expansion, which will add to growth
figures over the next year. At the same time, the central bank's
recent reduction of compulsory reserve requirements has allowed
banks to offer more credit to industry and consumers.
</P>
<P>
   So far, consumers have been shy about spending more
aggressively, but cheaper credit and a gradual fall in the
unemployment rate are expected to entice shoppers in the second
half of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The strong growth figures come at a propitious time for
President Fernando Henrique Cardoso, whose administration has
recently been accused of being involved in the embezzlement of more
than $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a continuing Senate investigation, Cardoso's approval
rating increased to 19 percent in July from 13 percent the month
before, according to the pollsters Vox Populi.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
