r s BC-FBC-UGATAILBACKS0810-     08-09 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGATAILBACKS0810-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Healed from injuries, new Georgia running backs starting to feel
at home
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS - New Georgia running back Musa Smith was hoping his
college career would start with a bang. What happened in June
wasn't exactly what he had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, from West Perry High in Elliottsburg, Pa., suffered
severe burns when a firecracker exploded in his right hand. He
spent two days in the hospital and was forced to pull out of a high
school all-star game.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 6 feet 1, 210 pounds, was worried that the hand wouldn't
heal before the start of Georgia's preseason camp. But a family
vacation to Ocean City, Md., last month ended his doubts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The saltwater really helped the wounds recover,'' said Smith,
who has scarred fingers. ``It was really a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia coach Jim Donnan is hoping Smith and fellow freshman
Albert Hollis are a fountain of youth for the Bulldogs' backfield
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Smith rushed for 2,041 yards and 32 touchdowns as a senior,
averaging more than nine yards per carry. He chose Georgia over
several schools after making a nationwide tour last summer with two
of his high-school coaches.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1999, Smith and his coaches visited Florida, Georgia and
North Carolina. The following week, they traveled to Wisconsin,
Michigan State, Notre Dame and Purdue. After another trip to
Virginia Tech, West Virginia and Penn State, Smith decided he
wanted to attend Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really liked Penn State, but they were recruiting me as a
defensive back,'' Smith said. ``I wanted to carry the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollis, from Christian Brothers High in Sacramento, Calif.,
committed to UCLA in May 1999. When Hollis started to waiver on his
commitment to the Bruins, a high-school track coach told him he
should consider Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me that I should look at Georgia because of Herschel
Walker and the great tradition of running backs they have here,''
Hollis said. ``Herschel Walker also ran track here, which is
something I really want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   After a trip to Georgia's Internet web site, Hollis contacted
one of the Bulldogs' track coaches. Another telephone call to
Georgia recruiting coordinator Rodney Garner resulted in Hollis
making an official visit to Athens. He later picked the Bulldogs
over UCLA, Southern Cal, Texas, Notre Dame and Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really the running back tradition here and my
relationship with Coach Garner that attracted me to Georgia,''
Hollis said. ``I just felt more comfortable at Georgia, even though
it's so far from home. This is like my home away from home.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollis, 5 feet 11, 199 pounds, injured his left hamstring June 3
in the 100-meter finals of the California high school track
championships. Favored in the 100 meters and 200 meters, he wasn't
able to finish either.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hamstring is fine,'' Hollis said. ``They're starting to
unleash me a little more. I'm getting more reps than last week.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollis rushed for 2,053 yards and 31 touchdowns in his final
prep season.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs open Sept. 2 against Georgia Southern.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
