<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7145 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH10-COX     08-09 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OXNARD, Calif. _ Gov. George W. Bush praised his Democratic
rival's vice-presidential pick Wednesday as he prepared for a
whistle-stop tour through California.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told reporters that U.S. Sen. Joseph Lieberman of
Connecticut, ``was a good pick by Vice President Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe Lieberman is a man who is praised by people from both
sides of the aisle,'' Bush said. That's a good sign. I don't know
him personally, but I do appreciate his strong positions on ethics
that he has taken ... I think he's a man of integrity ... ``
</P>
<P>
   Bush today begins his second whistle-stop tour in as many weeks.
This one will take him through some of the agricultural communities
dotting California's coast and Central Valley _ areas the GOP has
mostly lost in the last two presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   Bush traveled several Mid-Western states last week, where his
vice presidential running mate, Dick Cheney, is campaigning this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, on his 7th campaign trip into California since March 7,
campaigned with wife, Laura, Wednesday. Former Republican primary
foe Arizona U.S. Sen. McCain joins him in Salinas today. They will
stop in Lodi and Stockton before a fund-raising event at the home
of San Diego Chargers owner Alex Spanos. The event is expected to
raise up to $400,000 for the California Republican Party. Before
Gore tapped Lieberman as his running mate, Bush had sought to tar
the vice president with President Clinton's scandals. Asked if that
tactic will work now that Lieberman is by Gore's side, Bush urged
voters to remember that the race is between him and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Vice President Gore wants to say, 'I'm different from
President Clinton', let him explain how. I'm saying I am ... I'm
saying we'll set a new tone.''
</P>
<P>
   At a rally in the coastal town of Oxnard, Bush sounded the
themes he will use to drum support among conservative Democrats and
swing voters along his route. Clinton won Ventura County, home to
Oxnard, in 1992 and 1996. An estimated 30 percent of the voters
here are considered, swing voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It worries me that we're forcing our farmers off the land in
America because of bad tax policy,'' Bush told the crowd. ``It
worries me that when a person dies in a family it forces the small
business people, or the people who toil the land, to have to sell
in order to pay the death taxes. I think in these times of plenty
... we ought to get rid of the death tax in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Repbublicans so far have been unsuccessful in their efforts to
repeal the federal estate tax, which they have dubbed the death
tax. Bush supports phasing out the tax, a theme he frequently
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush greeted his first crowd in this heavily Latino state
speaking Spanish, telling them, ``With your support I'm going to
win. With your support I'm going to be the next president of the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush then traveled to San Luis Obispo and Santa Barbara
counties. Clinton won Santa Barabara County in the last two
elections but lost San Luis Obispo four years ago to former U.S.
Sen. Robert J. Dole, 47 percent to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is trying to reach conservative Democrats and independents
he needs to win. About 30 percent of the voters in each of the
three counties are swing voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going through areas that we did not do well in in 1992
or 1996, but they are areas that have a lot of swing voters and we
think Governor Bush has an opportunity to do well in this year,''
campaign spokeswoman Karen Hughes told reporters aboard Bush's
plane Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Polls are tight, California leans heavily Democratic and Bush
faces a tough fight here. Despite the odds, he said he isn't
conceding.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, they said, 'Well, Republicans play like we're
going to run and then write it off,'' Bush said. ``I'm not writing
off this state.''
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jena Heath at jenah(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
