<HEADER>
A7146 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ECONOMY-SLOWS-BOS &LR;      08-09 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-SLOWS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMY SLOWING FOR `SOFT LANDING' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANTHONY FLINT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hard-charging US economy slowed in the late spring and early
summer, the Federal Reserve reported Wednesday, suggesting a ``soft
landing'' for the 10-year expansion indeed could replace the
traditional boom-and-bust dynamic.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from the Fed's 12 regional banks indicate a downshifting
in consumer spending, manufacturing and construction in every area
of the country except St. Louis, and that energy costs have peaked.
Accordingly, the central bank almost certainly will refrain from
raising interest rates for the seventh time later this month.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow was off 71 points and the Nasdaq closed just barely in
positive territory Wednesday. Many investors already largely had
factored in the Fed staying on the sidelines through the fall,
because it would be too close to the election.
</P>
<P>
   Labor markets remained extremely tight, but in a trend that
impressed economists, increased productivity held inflation at bay.
A government report Tuesday said American productivity rose at the
fastest pace in 17 years while labor costs declined.
</P>
<P>
   Companies continued to invest in new technology to increase
efficiency, keeping a lid on wage increases and effectively
ensuring the economy did not overheat even in these later stages of
its expansion.
</P>
<P>
   The trend _ technology-driven productivity gains heading off
inflation, helping to bring about a soft landing _ was seen as the
economist's equivalent of ``The Perfect Storm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is pretty impressive stuff. You just don't see this, so
late in a cycle,'' said Fred Breimyer, chief economist for State
Street Corp. ``The question remains: How much of this is an
entirely new experience that transforms all the old assumptions, or
is it just a different kind of cycle? But the stamp of approval is
on this economy, no question about it.''
</P>
<P>
   FleetBoston economist Wayne Ayers agreed that ``The basic laws
of supply and demand have not been repealed.''
</P>
<P>
   If the productivity gains aren't permanent, inflationary
pressures could come right back into the picture, he said. ``But so
far, so good. And it really hasn't happened before.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically, wages and productivity conspire to derail an economic
expansion. In the early stages of an expansion, right after a
recession, employers are slow to hire until they are convinced the
recovery is for real. As a result, per-worker output is high. In
the later stages of an expansion, employers are reluctant to fire
anyone, and indeed often have trouble finding workers. That puts
upward pressure on wages and per-worker output falls off.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, employers using new technology were able to do
more with the workers they had, doing an end-run around the usual
rules.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Latta, principal US economist at Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI
said the nifty trick was made possible by ``an economy that has
operated more freely than it has in the past, with a lot of
competition and lot of deregulation. Unions don't have the clout
and the wage-setting role they used to have. And we have this
phenomenon in technology and communications, really changing the
way we do so many things. A lot of opportunity that remains to be
exploited.''
</P>
<P>
   Latta cited another factor allowing employers to do more with
less, in terms of the labor force: ``Businesses learned how to dumb
down the jobs. There was all this talk about needing a college
education for the new economy. But with all this technology,
instead we've just been able to dumb the jobs down.''
</P>
<P>
   If the storyline from the Fed's Beige Book (as the district
reports are known) is that technology helped productivity slow down
expansion, that would be a confirmation of Fed chairman Alan
Greenspan's view of a new kind of economy at work, many economists
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other so-called ``hawks'' at the Fed have been skeptical that
such a three-cushion shot was possible, but now ``they're all
singing from the same hymm book,'' said Ayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much a completely new world, but the safe speed
limit for the economy has just been increased. It used to be, if
the economy grew faster than 3 percent, inflation was going to be a
problem. Now, the speed limit is more like 3.5 to 4 percent. Five
percent-plus, of course, is not a safe speed limit,'' Ayers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more like a standoff than a real resolution,'' said State
Street's Breimyr. ``The labor markets are too tight to be sustained
indefinitely. This is not where you want to be. But those pressures
are being negated by substantial gains in productivity, and that's
enough to keep them on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``So they'll take a pass, for good reasons. That does not mean
they have resolved everything. We'll have to see how far this
goes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Beige Book findings will be used when the Fed's policymaking
Federal Open Market Committee next meets Aug. 22 to set US interest
rates. The Fed has raised interest rates six times since June 1999
to try to cool down the booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's report noted that the economy was still growing
overall, but that consumer spending, manufacturing and construction
``were slightly softer than in the last report. Easing demand
appears to be restraining prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Inflation was not kept entirely at bay. Some companies turned to
big signing bonuses to attract workers. Even fast-food chains
offered regular pay raises and profit-sharing.
</P>
<P>
   But consumers were insulated from input price increases because
of competitive pressures, the report said. Retailers in New York
and Chicago resorted to promotions and discounting.
</P>
<P>
   The report also noted that venture capital funding was less
forthcoming, and slightly more scrutiny was starting to accompany
loans. Demand for credit was still robust, though home-building and
buying slowed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
