<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7150 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BLACKS-LIEBERMAN-HNS &LR;      08-09 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKS-LIEBERMAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BLACK-JEWISH TENSIONS UNLIKELY TO IMPACT DEMOCRATIC TICKET 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ African-American leaders on Wednesday denounced a
Dallas NAACP official who criticized Sen. Joseph Lieberman because
of his religion.
</P>
<P>
   But in the wake of the flap, political experts said occasional
tensions between African Americans and Jews are not likely to
depress the election turnout among blacks who traditionally vote
Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas NAACP President Lee Alcorn, appearing on a local radio
show Monday, said of Vice President Al Gore's selection of
Lieberman, an Orthodox Jew, as his running mate: ``I'm concerned
about, you know, any kind of Jewish candidate, you know, and I'm
concerned about the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sick of the Democratic Party taking the African-American
vote for granted. If we get a Jew person, then what I'm wondering
is, I mean, what is this movement for?''
</P>
<P>
   Alcorn added that, ``I think we need to be very suspicious of
any kind of partnerships between Jews at that kind of level because
we know that their interest has to do with, you know, money and
these kinds of things.''
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP's national president, Kweisi Mfume, suspended Alcorn,
telling him in a letter Wednesday: ``I find your comments in this
matter to be repulsive. They are, in my opinion, anti-Semitic and
anti-NAACP.''
</P>
<P>
   Mfume, a former House member from Maryland, said Alcorn would be
suspended until a full investigation and hearings on his statements
have been completed.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the Rev. Jesse Jackson, who in 1984 referred to New York
City as ``Hymietown,'' was quick to distance himself from Alcorn
and anti-Semitism. He told reporters after a White House ceremony
in which he received the Presidential Medal of Freedom, that
Alcorn's statements are ``absolutely not'' representative of how
African Americans look upon Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must not assume a tree leaf is a tree,'' Jackson said,
adding that he doesn't know Alcorn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to hear more expressions of darkness, but we'll
also hear some more expressions of light,'' he said. Referring to
Alcorn, he said, ``Some people are not enlightened.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said he applauded the NAACP decision to suspend Alcorn
and declared that black elected officials ``are all enthusiastic''
about Lieberman for vice president, and that blacks will
``overwhelmingly'' support the Gore-Lieberman ticket.
</P>
<P>
   From its high-water mark in the 1960s when Jews played a
prominent role in helping Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. and other
black leaders build the civil rights movement, the relationship
between blacks and Jews has been testy at times in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Nation of Islam Minister Louis Farrakhan has referred to Judaism
as a ``gutter religion'' And Jackson's reference to ``Hymietown''
16 years ago was widely interpreted as representative of a growing
anti-Semitic view among American blacks.
</P>
<P>
   But political experts said they do not envision any significant
defection of African Americans from Democratic ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be some negative reaction to Lieberman, but I think
it will fade over time,'' said Allan Lichtman, a historian at
American University who studies civil rights issues. ``In the end,
the very strong bridge between African Americans and the Democratic
Party will remain sturdy.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday night on CNN's ``Larry King Live,''
Lieberman said he was unconcerned about anti-Semitism in the
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people are so tolerant,'' he said. ``I'm
convinced that they're going to vote for me or against me, based
not on my religion but based on how they judge me as a person and
whether they think I can do this job.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, 82 percent of African American voters cast ballots for
the Clinton-Gore ticket. In 1996, 84 percent did. African Americans
also strongly supported Clinton during his impeachment proceedings
in the wake of the Monica Lewinsky sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   With a population of 35 million, blacks are 13 percent of the
U.S. population and 15 percent of the electorate.
</P>
<P>
   For Democrats, the black vote is crucial in southern states that
have leaned increasingly to Republicans in the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last two years Democrats beat Republicans in
gubernatorial elections in South Carolina and Mississippi and kept
the governor's mansion in Democratic hands in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blacks were critical to those victories,'' said Earl Black, a
political scientist at Rice University who studies minority voting
patterns. ``The underlying structure in southern states is that
Democrats don't need the majority of whites to win where they have
significant black voter turnout.''
</P>
<P>
   David Lublin, a political scientist at American University here,
asked if the Lieberman selection might diminish that turnout,
replied, ``Obviously a black vice presidential nominee would have
upped it, but it's hard to see how a Jewish nominee would depress
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lublin, who is Jewish, added, ``Most Jews tend to view
themselves as different from other whites, but most African
Americans view Jews as part of the great expanse of whites in this
countries. So I doubt that the nomination of Lieberman will do
anything to undercut black Democratic support.''
</P>
<P>
   At last week's Republican National Convention, GOP nominee
George W. Bush emphasized inclusiveness and diversity, inviting
retired Army Gen. Colin Powell and foreign policy expert
Condoleezza Rice to address delegates in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   But it does not appear that Bush's effort to reach out to
minorities has won him much black support. A USA Today/CNN/Gallup
poll immediately after the convention found that while Bush
expanded his lead over Gore to 17 points _ 54 percent to 37 percent
_ Gore led Bush among black voters by 58 points _ 71 percent to 13
percent.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of blacks said the Democratic Party best represents
their values.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Bush campaign spokesman Ari Fleischer issued a
statement condemning Alcorn. ``When it comes to fighting
anti-Semitism, Governor Bush and (former Defense) Secretary (Dick)
Cheney stand shoulder to shoulder with all Americans in condemning
such foolish utterances,'' Fleischer said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jewish voters represent 2.2 percent of the population and 3
percent of the electorate. In the last two presidential elections,
78 percent of Jewish voters cast their ballots for the Clinton-Gore
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Jews are an important bloc in places such as New York, where
they are 10 percent of the electorate.
</P>
<P>
   While Jewish leaders express dismay over instances of black
anti-Semitism, polls suggest Jewish voters do not view African
Americans as being particularly anti-Semitic.
</P>
<P>
   In a poll last year of 1,000 Jewish voters conducted by the New
York-based American Jewish Committee, respondents were asked to
rank groups in terms of anti-Semitism. Twenty-three percent
identified the religious right as the most anti-Semitic. Next came
the Muslims, with 21 percent of Jewish voters identifying them as
the most anti-Semitic. Seven percent named African Americans as the
most anti-Semitic.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Freedman and Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or
at the e-mail addresses of dan(at)hearstdc.com and
judy(at)hearstdc.com, respectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
