NYT-08-09-00 2012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000809.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7151 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-TIRE-RECALL-ART-NYT &LR;      08-09 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIRE-RECALL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRESTONE SAYS IT WILL RECALL 6.5 MILLION TIRES 
</HEADLINE>
  (With related stories: TIRE-FIRESTONE, TIRE-BRIDGESTONE AND
TIRE-FORD) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT3,8,21 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The company that makes Firestone tires said on
Thursday that the treads on millions of tires it has produced since
1991 seem unusually prone to fly off, sometimes with catastrophic
results.
</P>
<P>
   Facing 50 lawsuits, 46 deaths, 80 injuries and a federal
investigation, the company said it would replace free the 6.5
million tires still on the road.
</P>
<P>
   But the company, Bridgestone/Firestone, said that some vehicle
owners might have to wait a year to get the new tires, even though
the company will buy competitors' tires to meet the demands that
the recall will create. In fact, some consumers seeking
replacements today were turned away by dealers, the supply already
exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   About two-thirds of the tires in question came new on sport
utility vehicles and pickup trucks made by Ford over the past
decade. The recall will begin in Southern states, the company said,
because the failures seem related to hot weather. But they added
that they did not know why the tires seemed particularly vulnerable
to the failures.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials said the tires that they had been able to
examine showed signs of underinflation, or overloading, exterior
damage from road debris, improper repair or other abuse or flaw,
but acknowledged that all tires produced by all manufacturers are
subject to those conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The recalled tires are ATX, ATX II and Wilderness AT tires for
15-inch wheels, with a size designation that is P235/75R15. All
such ATX and ATX II tires are being recalled, but only those
Wilderness AT tires that also have a Transportation Department
10-digit designation starting with the letters VD are being
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   For reasons that the company could not explain, all the
Wilderness tires made at its plant in Decatur, Ill. _ the ones
designated VD _ seem prone to failure, along with ATX and ATX II
tires made in several plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not identified any manufacturing or design defect,''
Gary B. Crigger, executive vice president of the company, said at a
news conference in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pulling this size now, rather than try to figure out
what the answer is,'' Crigger said. The company has not had time to
``do the forensics'' on tires in accidents, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Experts agreed, however, on the likely mechanism for the
failure: heat, generated by tire sidewalls that flex excessively
because there is too little air in the tire, or too much weight on
the vehicle. The problem is probably aggravated by hot pavement and
air temperatures, according to company officials and others.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford Motor Co. said on Wednesday that it first became aware
of the problem a year ago, with ``anecdotal reports'' from Saudi
Arabia, where drivers let air out of the tires to drive on the
desert, then returned to paved roads and drove at high speeds
without reinflating the tires.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgestone/Firestone, which is the American unit of the
Bridgestone Corp. of Japan, acted in the United States on Wednesday
after extensive discussions with the National Highway Traffic
Safety Administration and Ford, which took about two-thirds of the
tires in question for installation on sport utility vehicles and
pickups. The deputy head of the safety administration, Rosalyn G.
Millman, said in a statement that she was pleased that Firestone
``has taken a positive step toward resolving this safety issue.''
But a spokesman for the agency, Rae Tyson, said that its
investigation had begun only in May and that the agency did not
know enough now to order a recall.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson said the agency had begun its inquiry primarily because of
an increasing number of complaints from consumers to its hot line
and that in recent days, as news reports had cited the problem, the
number of complaints had risen sharply.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went from 21 deaths to 46 just last week,'' he said. ``I
don't think anyone would want us to jump to any conclusions based
on an investigation that just began.'' A key question for
investigators looking into cases in which vehicles rolled over and
had damaged tires is whether the tires were the cause, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But some critics said the government response had been slow.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Claybrook, a former administrator of the National Highway
Traffic Safety Administration and now director of Public Citizen, a
consumer rights group, said that ``the first lawsuits they settled
were back in 1992, and they've known about this for years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They settled them with gag orders,'' Claybrook said. ``This
has been a big cover-up for years.'' And the safety agency has had
weak leadership and been preoccupied with other issues, she said,
including faulty rear door latches on minivans and sidesaddle gas
tanks on pickups.
</P>
<P>
   Crigger, of Firestone, said that the company was faced with 50
lawsuits. Asked on Wednesday if non-disclosure clauses in the
settlement agreements were intended to cover up the problem,
Crigger said, ``I don't know about the status'' of such clauses.
</P>
<P>
   In some of the suits, one question at issue is whether the
suspension, which Ford designed, is partly responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Claybrook said that the problem echoed the problem with
Firestone 500 tires, which surfaced in 1978, when she was the
administrator. That case was a severe financial blow to Firestone
and was one reason it was acquired by Bridgestone in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Of the tires in Wednesday's announcement, about two-thirds came
new on Ford Explorer sport utility vehicles, and Ranger and F-150
pickup trucks, Mercury Mountaineer SUVs, as well as Mazda Navajo
and B-series pickups. All were produced between 1991 and 2000. But
millions of other tires were sold as replacements. GM and Subaru,
two other manufacturers that use Firestone for original equipment
tires, said they had not had any reports of problems.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, in fact, may be related in part to the vehicle,
although statistics were sketchy.
</P>
<P>
   Tire failure in an Explorer may be a bigger problem than in
other vehicles, said David A. Champion, the director of auto
testing for Consumer Reports magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``SUV's are more prone to roll over than other classes of
vehicles because of the high center of gravity,'' Champion said.
Thus a tire failure that causes an accident in an SUV ``can be more
dramatic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford stood by its longtime supplier on Wednesday _ Henry Ford
and Harvey Firestone were friends and business associates nearly a
century ago _ but the company gave slightly different advice to
owners of Explorers that have the tires.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said to keep the tires inflated to 26-30 pounds per square
inch, and Firestone said 30. And while Ford has had what it called
``anecdotal reports'' of a problem for a year, a Ford executive
complained on Wednesday that it had taken until late last month to
get Firestone to turn over data on its warranty experience with the
tires provided on new Fords. (Manufacturers use warranty complaints
to track defects, but the warranties on tires are customarily
separate from cars.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
