<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7154 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-BCBS-DOCTORS-BOS &LR;      08-09 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BCBS-DOCTORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC-BS TO LEVEL PHYSICIAN FEE PLAYING FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LIZ KOWALCZYK  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Massachusetts _ the
state's largest health insurer _ will adopt new physician fees next
month that reduce payments to many surgeons and specialists and put
more money into the pockets of general practitioners.
</P>
<P>
   Many Massachusetts doctors, already unhappy about shrinking fees
and rising expenses, see the move as the latest blow to their
incomes and predict the action will make it be harder to attract
top doctors to the state and could increase patient waits for
certain services.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sitting here right now with my accountant trying to do a
budget,'' said Dr. Francis VanHouten, a radiologist who has
practiced 27 years. ``We're looking at a 5 to 10 percent decrease
in reimbursement for our group. It's difficult to imagine how we
can continue to provide these services.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross officials say the new fees reflect a national trend
toward paying doctors more equitably. For years Medicare, the
federal health insurance program for the elderly, has believed that
reimbursement rates for specialists are too high, and that general
practioners fees are too low.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always going to be debates about whether this is
fair,'' said Dr. William Winkenwerder, executive vice president of
health care services for Blue Cross. ``But because this payment
method has been supported by a large number of physicians, we do
think it's equitable and the best approach anyone has come up with
so far.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the fee plan, set to take effect September 1, radiologists
will face a particularly hefty cut. Blue Cross will lower the fee
it pays doctors to read screening mammographies _ routine
mammographies given to healthy women _ by 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Radiologists said the insurer will lower the fee for screening
mammographies to within a few cents of Medicare, which pays about
$21.50 per x-ray.
</P>
<P>
   While it is unclear whether lower fees for doctors will impact
patients, VanHouten said some colleagues have told him say they'll
stop providing the service, which may increase waits for routine
mammographies. VanHouten said he would continue to provide the
screenings.
</P>
<P>
   Yael Miller, director of health systems for the Massachusetts
Medical Society, which represents the state's physicians, said
anesthesiologists, radiologists and neurosurgeons will be hardest
hit under the new pay scale. Pediatricians, internists and family
practitioners will see their fees rise.
</P>
<P>
   How hard a doctor is hit by the new Blue Cross fees depends not
only on her specialty but on whether she practices in a hospital or
a private office, the mix of services she provides and how many of
her patients are covered by the insurer.
</P>
<P>
   For example, obstetricians said their fee for seeing a woman
through pregnancy and delivering her baby are being reduced 5
percent, or by about $100.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Thomas Raskauskas, an obstetrician, said the new Blue Cross
fees are significantly lower than those of most other insurers he
works for. ``Not a good scenario for you or us,'' he recently wrote
a Blue Cross executive.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross's fee scale is based on a national model adopted by
Medicare, which began changing how it pays doctors in 1992 and
restructured fees again in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Under Medicare, the changes mean that heart surgeons, for
example, will see their fees fall 12 percent over four years, while
dermatologists will be handed a 20 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   Private insurers often follow Medicare's lead, although they are
not required to do so. Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Massachusetts
began to implement the Medicare model last year, but the fees
scheduled to take effect next month are the most significant
changes yet.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts specialists say that the specific way Blue Cross
plans to implement the next step of the fee program will make the
impact here worse than under Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare assigns each of the 8,000 services performed by doctors
a ``relative value unit'' depending on the time and intensity of
the service. The relative value is then multiplied by a dollar
amount called a ``conversion factor,'' which is supposed to
increase each year for inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts specialists said they don't disagree with
assigning each service a relative value. But they said that the
``conversion factor'' Blue Cross is using is too low, and puts its
fees only slightly above Medicare's.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to recruit high quality physicians and
reimburse them competitively,'' VanHouten said. ``They can make
significantly more in Florida and Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross executives said it's true that many specialists will
see their fees reduced, but that on average the physicians in the
Blue Cross network will receive fee increases. Those increases are
4.1 percent for the company's managed care plans, or HMOs, and 6.8
percent for traditional fee-for-service.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross, which insures nearly 2 million Massachusetts
residents, accounts for between 10 and 25 percent of the income of
the 14,000 doctors in the network.
</P>
<P>
   VanHouten, a former president of the Massachusetts Medical
Society, said he called Blue Cross executives three weeks ago.
``Our only leverage is morale persuasion,'' he said. ``They're in
control at this point. All we can hope is that they're reasonable
men.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardiologists and radiologists said they do not want
``unseemly'' fighting with primary care doctors over scarce health
care dollars but think Blue Cross should raise the fees for all
doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure primary care is going up,'' said Dr. John Patti, a
radiologist. ``But they're going up from levels that are so low to
begin with. As a specialist, I would support them being raised an
appropriate level.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said that doctors are well aware that the public believes
they're overpaid to begin with. But, she said, that's a myth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The everyday practicing physician is more hassled and working
longer hours and has less social time and less family time than
ever before,'' she said. ``Patients are surprised with the waits
they have. Physicians try as hard as they can to conceal the
problems from patients, but I believe it's starting to bubble up.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, physicians earned on average $164,000 in 1997, down
from $166,000 the prior year, according to the most recent figures
from the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross executives said they are merely trying to be
competitive, and not pay doctors less _ or more _ than other
insurers in the market, including Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard some feedback from physicians,'' Winkenwerder
said. ``People are kind of scurrying about to see if their
particular interests or concerns are being addressed. But the
changes we've made have generally been well received.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
