<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISON-RATES-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRISON POPULATION GREW AT LOWEST RATE SINCE 1979, JUSTICE
DEPARTMENT REPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Calif., La., Minn., Pa.)   By FOX BUTTERFIELD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After an eight-year drop in crime, the population of the
nation's state and federal prisons grew last year at the lowest
rate since 1979, 3.4 percent, the Justice Department reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The main reasons the prison population has increased even as
crime has declined, the report said, are that the number of inmates
returned to prison for parole violations increased, the length of
the average sentence rose, and drug crimes, which are not included
in the overall crime rate computed by the FBI, did not drop.
</P>
<P>
   There was a 54 percent growth in the number of inmates returned
to prison after being released on parole during the 1990s, as
parole agents became tougher about revoking parole for technical
violations like failing a drug test. By contrast, there was only a
7 percent increase in the number of criminals sent to prison for
new convictions.
</P>
<P>
   The average length of time served in prison was 28 months in
1998, up from 20 months in 1990, according to the report, the
result of tougher sentencing laws.
</P>
<P>
   The report also found that the total number of Americans in all
jails and prisons crossed the 2 million mark for the first time,
reaching, 2,026,596 at the end of 1999, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The report also found that Texas, which has been on a
record-setting prison expansion under Gov. George W. Bush, the
Republican presidential candidate, passed California as the state
with the most prison inmates, though Texas has a much smaller
population, 20 million people compared with 32 million in
California. At the end of 1999, Texas had 163,190 inmates and
California, 163,067. California had long had the biggest prison
system in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Texas had the second highest rate of incarceration per capita,
762 per 100,000, trailing Louisiana, with 776 per 100,000. That
gave Texas an incarceration rate six times higher than Minnesota,
the lowest state, with 125 inmates per 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the report said that 9.4 percent of black men ages
25 to 29 were in state and federal prisons in 1999, almost 10 times
the rate for white men in their late twenties, which was 1.0
percent. Among Hispanic males in their late twenties, 3.1 percent
were in prison.
</P>
<P>
   While the report highlighted the racial disparities in prison,
it contradicted a frequent claim of advocates of prison and drug
sentencing reform, who say most prisoners are locked up for drug
arrests. In fact, the Justice Department found, people who had been
convicted of violent crimes accounted for 51 percent of the
increase in state prison populations between 1990 and 1998. Drug
offenses accounted for 19 percent of the increase, property crimes
accounted for 15 percent, and various other crimes accounted for 15
percent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Altogether, in 1998, there were 545,200 state prison inmates
serving time for violent offenses _ including murder, robbery,
assault and rape _ compared to 242,900 for property crimes _
including burglary, auto theft and fraud _ and 236,800 for drug
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Where prisoners sentenced for drug crimes do predominate, the
report said, is in the federal prison system. Of the 108,925
federal inmates in 1998, 30,470 were sentenced for drug crimes,
compared with 9,557 for violent crimes and 7,935 for property
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred Blumstein, a criminologist at Carnegie Mellon University,
said a major finding of the study, written by Allen J. Beck of the
Bureau of Justice Statistics, was that the continued growth of the
prison population was driven by the huge increase in the number of
parolees being returned to prison.
</P>
<P>
   The report says most of those returning parolees have committed
new crimes.
</P>
<P>
   But Blumstein said the parole system had gotten tougher and more
parolees were being returned for violations like failing a monthly
urine test for drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The 3.4 percent increase in inmates in state and federal prisons
in 1999 _ to 1.37 million _ was well below the average annual
growth rate during the 1990s, of 6.5 percent, the new report said.
The growth rate hit a high of 8.7 percent in 1994, well after the
crime wave of the late 1980s and early 1990s began to decline in
1991, falling gradually for the rest of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   One major issue that the new study did not address is whether
there is any relationship between growth in the incarceration rate
and the drop in crime. Advocates of tougher prosecution and
sentencing say the huge growth in imprisonment, with the
incarceration rate quadrupling since 1980, has been largely
responsible for the decrease in crime.
</P>
<P>
   But Blumstein said crime rates were also going up sharply in the
late 1980s when prison population was increasing as well. Some
other factors that must also be considered, he said, were the
improved economy in the 1990s, better police tactics and the waning
of the crack cocaine epidemic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
