<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7162 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     08-09 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEC INSIDE INFORMATION RULE BRINGS STRONG REACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's an idea that doesn't sound very controversial: make sure
all investors have a chance to learn about significant developments
inside public companies at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   But it causing an uproar. Proposed rules that would mandate just
that have generated about 6,000 public comments to the US
Securities and Exchange Commission, which is scheduled to vote on
the matter Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   There is no formal SEC count of such things, but officials say
it is close to a record, if not an actual high water mark in terms
of public reaction to a commission proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of those messages were written by people like
Peter Schaeffer of Amagansett, N.Y., uring the SEC to level the
playing field for individual investors. ``It is nonsensical for
Wall Street analysts to have exclusive access to information,'' he
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared as of Wednesday the commission was leaning his way
on the proposal, which has been pushed hard by chairman Arthur
Levitt as the way to cleanse a ``stain on the market.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``stain'' is more commonly known as ``selective
disclosure,'' communication by public companies to a group of
analysts, big institutional investors or others who get more
insight earlier than everyone else on business developments.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't happen all the time, but often enough to become a
cloud over a stock market that serves more individual investors
than ever before. Sound reasonable?
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast. There is a powerful group of institutions and
organizations who have lined up in opposition to parts or all of
the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Their message: nice idea, but it would actually have a chilling
effect on the flow of information from public companies to public
markets. Unsure when they were stepping over a line, executives
would instead take the easy way out and just clam up.
</P>
<P>
   There is an element of truth to many of their comments and
evidence suggests they have moved the SEC's staff to revise the
actual proposal around the edges, probably for the better.
</P>
<P>
   But it's hard to miss the fact that all the barking has come
from organizations that benefit from the clubby elements of capital
markets. They include investment bankers, brokerage industry
leaders, big institutional investors, corporate investor relations
executives and even the business press. Every one of them has money
on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's natural for those who have advantages to want to keep
them,'' said Harvey Goldschmid, a former SEC general counsel who is
the architect of the commission's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the proposal is fair and will create a much better world
for investors and avoid areas of selective disclosure perversity,''
said Goldschmid, who now teaches at Columbia University. ``By that
I mean the selective providing of information that has been used to
mitigate criticism by analysts and temper their ability to fairly
evaluate managements and companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives from 15 big investment banking firms and brokerages
signed a comment letter from the Securities Industry Association
urging the commission to ditch the rule proposal and instead employ
Washington's preferred method of killing unwelcome populist ideas:
appoint a ``blue ribbon panel'' to talk it to death.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of Boston's Adams Harkness &AMP; Hill, a full-service
brokerage and investment banking firm, wrote separately that hte
SEC would be playing into the dangers an Internet brokerage boom
that has made it easier for individuals to lose their shirts.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC proposal ``may blunt one edge enjoyed by professional
investors but, possessed with more time and more resources, the
pros will develop others,'' wrote John Adams. ``The only result
will be to encourage individuals to continue to play a game in
which the odds are stacked against them.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Investor Relations Institute published the results
of a poll on Monday suggesting that most corporate executives would
cut back on communications with all investors if the SEC proposal
was adopted.
</P>
<P>
   Janus Capital Corp., the mutual fund company that has chalked up
huge investment gains and new money from happy mutual fund
customers thanks to its high-tech stock picking, complained the
proposal could ``stem an important and wholly appropriate flow of
information.''
</P>
<P>
   Locally, Fidelity Investments wrote the SEC to beef that its
money market analysts might not be able to do their duty to insure
the creditworthiness of investments if information dries up.
</P>
<P>
   Even Dow Jones, owner of the Wall Street Journal and other
publications, objected to the proposal because it would make
routine interviews impossible and the media was in the business of
broadly dissmenating news to the public in the first place.
(Competitor Bloomberg News drolly suggested Dow Jones was simply
trying to protect the Journal's pipeline of merger news leaks).
</P>
<P>
   It seems Dow Jones made headway. Corporate coversations with the
business press appear to have been written out of the proposed
rule. Ditto talk with suppliers, contractors and securities-rating
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   What's left is the communication between senior managers and
stock analysts and insitutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably true that companies will be anxious about
distinguishing between comments that trigger public disclosure
requirements and otherwise harmless corporate talk.
</P>
<P>
   But those kinds of problems have a way of working themselves out
in real-world application over time. The inconvenice is a small
price to pay for a stronger sense of transparency in a stock market
that can use it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
