r e BC-FILM-BLESSTHECHILD-TE     08-09 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BLESSTHECHILD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MESSAGE GETS LOST IN THE MESS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By TODD CAMP 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Bless the Child'' wants so badly to be ``The Sixth Sense'' for
the ``Touched By an Angel'' crowd. But for all its big-name talent,
computer-generated special effects and less-than-subtle ``Go,
God!'' mantra, ``Child'' is just another unremarkable entry in the
rapidly expanding Satan's-gonna-getcha subgenre of American horror.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar-winner Kim Basinger is nurse Maggie O'Conner, a single
working girl turned unexpected mom when her junkie sister Jenna
(Angela Bettis) abandons her newborn infant one snowy Christmas
Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors say the child is autistic, but Aunt Maggie's certain
there's something far more special about little Cody (apart from
the fact that she can spin objects with her mind and resurrect dead
animals, of course, but no one ever notices those things). When a
cleaned-up Jenna returns a few years later to reclaim the child
with her creepy self-help magnate boyfriend Eric Stark (Rufus
Sewell), it's clear that there are dark plans afoot for Cody.
</P>
<P>
   When Mom and Stark abduct the girl, Maggie turns to FBI agent
John Travis (Jimmy Smits) _ a former wannabe priest no less _ who
connects her case to a series of grisly, ritualistic child murders.
Turns out Cody's powers are just what Stark and his minions have
been searching for, and it's up to Maggie and Travis to find the
girl before an Easter eve showdown of good vs. evil.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the heavy-handed mumbo jumbo (all of which was done better
on Fox's defunct series ``Millennium),'' plenty of
computer-generated rats and gargoyles are thrown in for good
measure, which is a good thing considering how flat and unrealistic
the performances are.
</P>
<P>
   Basinger is far too glamorous to pull off the role of heroine,
and Smits is given practically nothing to do. And as for 7-year-old
Holliston Coleman, well, let's just say she's no Haley Joel Osment.
There are also a few glorified cameos: Christina Ricci spits out a
lot of narrative nonsense as a former member of Stark's army of
lost youth, and Ian Holm is the wizened old reverend on hand for
the odd Biblical consult.
</P>
<P>
   What's odd is that, for all the film's ham-handed religious
boosterism (all it's missing is Mel Brooks enthusiastically
shouting ``Send in the nuns!'') ``Bless the Child'' is exceedingly
violent. And this is the queasiest kind of movie violence _ the
killing of children.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Bible's a pretty violent book and all, but all the
angelic visions and biblical allegories aren't going to make the
horrific elements any more palatable for a mass audience. Of
course, maybe the film is going after heathens who flock to see
more irreverent entries such as ``End of Days, Stigmata'' or even
the upcoming rerelease of ``The Exorcist.'' Too bad the message
gets lost in the mess.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bless the Child'' is rated R for graphic violence, scary
business and adult subject matter. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM: ``Bless the Child'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SCORE: 2 1/2 on a 1-5 scale &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR: Chuck Russell &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STARS: Kim Basinger, Jimmy Smits &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LENGTH: 110 min. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RATED: R &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 2028EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
