<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7179 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ALTAMONT-FILM-$ADV13-     08-09 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALTAMONT-FILM-$ADV13-2takes-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALTAMONT:   AN END, AND   A BEGINNING
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, August 13)  
 By GERALD MARZORATI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   What gets called the '60s had any
number of endings, most of them elusive or much debated. But for
those who understood the decade (or era, or moment) as more a
cultural than a political phenomenon _ a last, late Romantic
pastoral _ the end came quite precisely and inarguably: Friday
night, Dec. 6, 1969, at the Altamont Speedway not far from San
Francisco, as the Rolling Stones, distracted and distraught, worked
their way through ``Under My Thumb.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hell's Angels had been hired to provide security at the
free, outdoor Altamont festival, which drew 300,000 people and was
to feature not only the Stones but also the Grateful Dead (whose
manager had recommended the Angels' services), Santana, the
Jefferson Airplane and Crosby, Stills, Nash and Young. The Angels,
many of them new recruits to the club with something to prove,
spent much of the afternoon clearing the area in front of the stage
with the help of weighted pool cues. Then, a few songs into the
Stones' closing set, several of the Angels developed a particular
interest in an 18-year-old black man 10 or 15 yards from the stage.
Meredith Hunter was attacked by one of the Angels, and when he
pulled a gun and ran, was chased down, stabbed and beaten to death
by a pack of them. None of the Stones could see this, but they knew
something was happening _ it was there in the confusion of their
playing, and in the fear they conveyed to one another in those
quick glances with which longtime band mates say all that needs to
be said.
</P>
<P>
   This moment is understood in such terrible detail largely
because of ``Gimme Shelter,'' the extraordinary cinema verite
account by Albert and David Maysles and Charlotte Zwerin of the
Stones' 1969 American tour that ended in the Altamont darkness. The
documentary, which takes its name from a Stones song, was something
of a hit for months after it opened in September 1970 _ a run that
solidified Altamont in the counterculture imagination as the Last
Big Bummer.
</P>
<P>
   The film also inspired reams of a very '60s kind of commentary.
There were analyses of the lyrics of Stones songs like ``Sympathy
for the Devil,'' raising the possibility that the band's own music
had somehow conjured the Altamont debacle. And there were anguished
tracts that pondered the fate of the nation's youth and the
collapse of Woodstock Nation. The critic Albert Goldman, writing in
The New York Times, suggested that the movie documented how the
``most unruly generation in American history is demanding _ and
receiving _ punishment by big father figures.'' For Goldman and
others, the Stones' '69 tour was not about rock music, really. It
was about the big stuff _ the darkness of the social unconscious,
of modern civilization itself _ for which the music was just a
soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   I doubt that the 30th-anniversary rerelease of ``Gimme Shelter''
(it opened on Friday) will engender that sort of Last Days
exegesis. It remains a remarkable film nevertheless, and one of its
many remarkable aspects is its very un-60's-like measure: it
unfolds the story of Altamont vividly, but not to the exclusion of
other stories. One of these _ and the one that, 30 years on,
matters more to cultural history than Altamont _ is that of a band
bringing to pop music the spectacle and glamour and startling sonic
intensity that had always been rock's promise. On what could be
called the prototype for the arena-rock tour, the Stones were not
only securing their place as the premiere band of that time but
pointing where rock, for better and for worse, would go in the
1970s and beyond. The Stones weren't the end of anything but a
beginning, ambitious and sensational.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gimme Shelter's'' first extended scene takes place, oddly and
effectively, after Altamont, with Mick Jagger, Keith Richards and
Charlie Watts ruminating about the concert in the Maysles' editing
room. It's a setting that is returned to time and again as the film
cuts from concert performances to backstage scenes, and
occasionally fast-forwards to the negotiations that at the 11th
hour allowed the big free concert to go on. The editing room trope
creates self-consciousness and distance, durable guards against
sensationalism. But more than that, it permits the Stones _
studying film of the tour on editing monitors _ to be introduced as
many could not or would not imagine them back then: as serious
young musicians baffled by how their story had somehow, in a
knife-flash, come down to this.
</P>
<P>
   The group had not been to America since the summer of 1966, when
a fan was still likely to be a sobbing girl chaperoned by her dad.
The Stones had been through a lot since then: drug charges,
squabbles and, musically, a disappointing psychedelic period that
culminated in a portentous mess of an album, ``Their Satanic
Majesties Request.'' By the end of 1967, Brian Jones was drifting
deeper into drugs and booze, and there were rumors of a Stones
split-up.
</P>
<P>
   In the first months of 1968, Jagger and Richards, who together
wrote the band's songs, set about to rid their music of all
flower-power traces and to recapture the Stones' essence: fast,
hard, rocking blues, metallic and elemental. But the hit singles
like ``Jumpin' Jack Flash'' and the rock songs on their album
``Beggar's Banquet'' _ it had acoustic tunes, too, which sound a
lot like today's alt-country _ represented more than a simple
return to roots. The rock was now more epic and anthemic, the
lyrics more imagistic (and lubricious), the playing more
sophisticated and the sound more grittily viscid than any that pop
music had yet produced. It begged to be played loud and live, and
it's what the Stones brought with them to America in October 1969.
</P>
<P>
   With them, too, was a young blues guitar player named Mick
Taylor; he was taking the place of Jones, who had been forced out
of the group in June 1968 and, a month later, was found dead in his
swimming pool. Along for the tour's last weeks was the documentary
crew _ actually a couple of different crews, hastily assembled when
the Stones decided, more than halfway into the tour, that a film
might be a cool idea. (The band maintained a veto over the film's
content, a power they chose, in the end, not to exercise, though
reportedly not without some anguish.) ``Gimme Shelter's'' anxious,
quickened feel no doubt owes something to the last-minute nature of
the project, but it is in keeping with the Maysles' aesthetic,
which was to grab truth where it lay in agile, relatively
unobtrusive snatches, and so limn the reality hidden in plain
sight.
</P>
<P>
   The ``truth'' about the Stones turns out to be what
fundamentally un-countercultural lives they were leading. There was
more hard liquor around than hard drugs, and their taste in women
ran not to hippie chicks but to Marilyn Monroe ( Richards shows off
a T-shirt with her bosomy image) and Tina Turner (who, with husband
Ike, opened for them on the tour). Mainly, though, there was work:
the shuttles to the airport in packed sedans and to concerts in
dangerously packed helicopters; the meetings with the press and the
concert organizers; the album cover to shoot and the album to mix.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the most inspired work the Stones do in ``Gimme
Shelter'' is on stage. Concert footage was shot not only at the
Altamont festival but during several shows at Madison Square Garden
two weeks earlier, and it's these scenes, in the force and very
essence of what they capture, that put Altamont in perspective _
that, in effect, put the lie to Altamont's stated purpose. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE)  &QL; 
 &QL; 
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the film, Jagger is seen pontificating to the
press about how the festival would create ``a sort of microcosmic
society'' from which everyone, you know, might learn to live
together and love together. But the Stones had no genuine interest
in furthering the Woodstock Nation, whatever that was. On stage,
their desire was to commune with the ghosts of the Mississippi
Delta and with one another. At the Garden, commune they did.
</P>
<P>
   Dramatically lighted, suffused with a pop glamour only the
Beatles rivaled (and they were no longer touring) and benefiting
from a state-of-the-art sound system that captures their dirty
rocking blues with astonishing vibrance and clarity, the Stones
play furiously, the guitars clawing at one another, the bass and
drums thundering.Each of the band members is lost in the music,
particularly Jagger, who, prancing and shimmying and singing
ecstatically, somehow embodies the mesmerizing sound. The audience
connects, but not as compatriots. They're enraptured spectators.
(The film shows this, too.) They're experiencing what gets called
art.
</P>
<P>
   I was there, down with the cameras, when the Stones came on past
midnight at the last Garden show. I was 16, and I had spent much of
the evening wending my way from the cheap seats toward the stage. I
got about as close to the Stones as Meredith Hunter did, and later
I would think about that a lot, but not because I ever thought it
could have been me. Meredith Hunter's death was not about the
Stones, or the '60s. He perished in the miasma of booze and drugs
and testosterone that still poisons soccer matches and late-night
bars along with rock festivals, here and around the world. That
wasn't the mood of the Garden that night.
</P>
<P>
   The only danger that night was the danger created by certain
types of music _ the sound of dread experience, seeking you out. It
couldn't bring about a ``microcosmic society,'' that music, but it
could overpower you, make you feel things, show you a nasty good
time and give you something to marvel at.
</P>
<P>
   The Stones, through the mid-'70s, would perfect this kind of
spectacular rock show by professional rock stars, and countless
others would embroider upon what they more or less invented in the
fall of '69: Led Zeppelin, U2 and Pearl Jam, and, it should not go
unmentioned, Aerosmith, Guns 'n' Roses and Limp Bizkit. No band,
though, ever played it better than the one captured 30 years ago,
and forever, in ``Gimme Shelter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 2055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
