<HEADER>
A7196 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     08-09 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS COWBOYS' MIGHTY '90S GANG FADES AWAY, SO DOES TEAM'S CHARACTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Troy Aikman stared off into the practice
field yonder, saying nothing for a second, but displaying a
hard-edged look.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will find another cornerback, but what we won't find is
another Kevin Smith,'' he finally uttered, sounding dejected.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' ``Brotherhood of the Mighty '90s'' lost yet another
charter member yesterday. It has been a bad year for this sort of
thing. Michael, Moose and now ``Pup,'' forced into retirement by
the same body that not so long ago helped bring a Super Bowl
dynasty to Valley Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   The official announcement on Smith will come this week. But the
first goodbyes were yesterday, after a training camp of
disappointment for Kevin.
</P>
<P>
   For the past month, his health status had appeared worse than
ever, which prompted Smith to leave camp on Tuesday. The end had
come. Retirement is so much better than his being simply released,
which football-wise was a possibility. But respect-wise, that
couldn't and shouldn't have happened.
</P>
<P>
   And the respect factor for Smith is what Aikman was talking
about.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a team wins like we won over an extended period of time,
there is so much more involved than just the talent level or the
system or whatever,'' Aikman said. ``More than anything else, Kevin
was a great team player who was a great teammate, who stands as an
example of what being a true professional is all about. Kevin is
nothing but class. We won, because as a team, we had leaders like
Kevin Smith.''
</P>
<P>
   That grand ol' gang is breaking up, rapidly. The Cowboys of the
early '90s have their place in NFL history as one of the best
collections of talent ever assembled. But it's the foundation
pieces of that era who are now saying good-bye, and the impact is
being felt in different areas. Such as in team leadership all the
way down to salary cap implications.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, as would be expected, had done much to postpone this
farewell, trying desperately to overcome one injury after another.
Most of his ongoing ailments stem from compensating for the
blown-out Achilles' tendon to open the '95 season.
</P>
<P>
   That disaster would change Pup's career forever. He was never
the same. He lost that proverbial ``step.'' Criticism flowed for
his performance, particularly the past few years, but Kevin never
met a sportswriter he wouldn't look right in the eye after every
game, good day or bad day.
</P>
<P>
   He might no longer have been the best cornerback in town, but
Smith was the only true ``stand-up'' cornerback the Cowboys have
had of late.
</P>
<P>
   The best memories of Kevin Smith go back to '92, when the feisty
rookie from Aggieland broke into the starting lineup and stayed
there all the way through the first Super Bowl victory. Fearless
and gifted, Smith was at his best in '93, even verbally gigging
receiver Jerry Rice in a pregame exchange and flare-up before the
famous ``Put It in Three-Inch Headlines'' championship contest with
the 49ers at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   As former teammate and now secondary coach Bill Bates said
yesterday: ``Kevin truly gave his heart, his soul and his body to
the Dallas Cowboys. The only thing I ask is that now, at this
particular difficult time that comes for all of us in the game,
Kevin be given the ultimate respect by the organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Done.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jones will bring Smith onto the coaching staff as an
assistant to Bates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want everything about Kevin Smith to rub off on those young
corners,'' Jones said yesterday. ``I can't think of a better
teacher or guy to serve as an example of what a player in the NFL
is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Of interest, however, is that while Smith was not being counted
on as a starter this season, both Jones and Dave Campo said
yesterday they don't plan on finding a veteran corner to replace
Smith. That goes against some precamp theories that if the Cowboys
could somehow ``persuade'' Smith to retire, they would become very
active in the cornerback market.
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary, however, the game plan apparently stays the
course that Campo and defensive coordinator Mike Zimmer have
privately preached all along. A rookie will be starting opposite
newcomer Ryan McNeil, not necessarily at the beginning of the
season, but at least at some point in 2000. Despite early fan and
media criticism, the Cowboys remain firm in claiming they will find
a starter from one of the three rookie corners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me on that one; I've been doing this 30 years,'' Campo
said, lightly chiding the media during his news conference
yesterday. OK, Dave. We believe you. Sorta. Maybe. Are you sure,
coach?
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, that mighty '90s brotherhood lost another good one
yesterday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
