<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ICE-CREAM-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS DISHES UP ICE CREAM FOR DOGS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW THOMPSON   The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ Kimberly Cohen has an ambitious business
venture. ``I want to be the Ben and Jerry's of doggy ice cream,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, who moved to Gainesville from New York this past year, is
the founder of Pink Belly Ice Pups, which offers four flavors of
ice cream for dogs. With a $10,000 loan from her family, Cohen
expanded on an idea born on a warm afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to spoil my dog,'' she said, referring to Lucy, her
6-pound Yorkshire terrier, ``and I just thought `ice cream.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But like chocolate, ice cream can be harmful to dogs because of
sugar, salt and other preservatives. So, Cohen mixed some nondairy
yogurt with chicken, and had her first batch of
``Cocka-Poodle-do,'' the best-selling flavor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monkey Madness'' has peanut butter and bananas; ``Chubby
Puppy'' is filled with peanut butter, and ``Where's the Beef'' has
meat and honey. All of Cohen's flavors use some combination of
nondairy yogurt with beef, chicken, honey, bananas or peanut
butter. A 3-ounce cup of any flavor sells for $1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trust me, if you were a dog, you would eat it,'' she said
before adding, ``but it's really bland for humans. Lucy loved it,
and now she is my official delivery dog and vice president of puppy
relations.''
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Sujdak, a veterinarian at Gainesville Animal Hospital,
said the ice cream is OK for dogs, as long as it is given in
moderation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can cause diarrhea if you give the dog too much, but too
much of anything can do that,'' Sujdak said. He added that greasy,
fatty foods and dairy products are not healthy for dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Like many small-business owners, Cohen, who is a full-time
computer analyst at Shands Hospital at the University of Florida,
designed a Web site _ www.pinkbelly.com _ to promote her creation.
More than 75 percent of her sales are generated over the Internet,
and she ships the frozen goodies over dry ice across the country.
</P>
<P>
   So far, she has made about $2,000. ``Someone told me you
couldn't launch a product for under $20,000, but here I am,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen has plans to expand into a market she says is ``more and
more about empty-nesters, people whose pets have become spoiled
children.''
</P>
<P>
   In September, Pink Belly Cafe will open inside the Holistic Pet
Foods store in Gainesville. The cafe will feature ``canine cakes''
and ``mutt muffins.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Skelly, the store's owner, said most of her customers
think the ice cream is a novel idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of her customers think it's wonderful,'' Skelly said. ``A
lot of treats for dogs are just piggy- or animal-based treats, but
this is great. You would not believe the extent people go to in
spoiling their pets, because, even with me, my dog is like my
kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen's passion for her Ice Pups stretches beyond making it big.
</P>
<P>
   A portion of her profits is donated to animal welfare
organizations in Florida. She also helps put together ``happy
meals'' for newly spayed or neutered pets.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what others thought about ice cream for dogs, she
said her husband, a resident in dental school at UF, is her biggest
critic.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thinks I'm a nut,'' she said, flashing a wide smile, ``but
I know he'd retire early to scoop doggy ice cream.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Gainesville Sun in Gainesville, Fla., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
