u i BC-LEBANON-TROOPS-1STLD-     08-09 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-TROOPS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEBANESE FORCES REPLACE ISRAELI TROOPS IN SOUTHERN LEBANON 
</HEADLINE>
   (CORRECTS city to Marjayoun in dateline, throughout story to
conform to AP style. CORRECTS spelling of town's name to Bint
Jubail in 5th graf after optional trim, ADDS photo note)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT29 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARJAYOUN, Lebanon _ Lebanese government forces rolled into
southern Lebanon before dawn Wednesday for the first time in 22
years.
</P>
<P>
   The long-awaited deployment came two months and two weeks after
Israel withdrew from its costly occupation, but military and
government officials immediately made clear that they had no
intention of deploying Lebanese troops along the border with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the mixed force of 500 soldiers and 500 special police
will act as an internal security force, keeping order among a
population divided between Christians and Shiite Muslims and
preventing old scores from being settled between the Shiite
Hezbollah guerrillas and people who fought for Israel's proxy
militia.
</P>
<P>
   To emphasize the point, the task force is commanded not by the
army, but by Col. Nazih Abu Nader of the Internal Security Forces,
who reports directly to the interior minister, Michel Murr.
</P>
<P>
   Murr and other Lebanese officials have said repeatedly that the
border is the responsibility of U.N. peacekeepers and that Lebanon
does not want to serve as Israel's border guard.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, the government is said to be worried that the close
proximity of the border posts, sometimes only a few yards apart,
might lead to incidents or that Lebanon might be held responsible
if Palestinian or Islamic guerrillas struck into Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a defensive force,'' Gen. Elias Farhat, the army
spokesman, said. ``The task is maintaining law and order.''
</P>
<P>
   The deployment of the Lebanese contingent was dependent on the
U.N. peacekeepers taking up border positions last weekend and has
been the subject of weeks of haggling between Lebanon, the United
Nations and Israel, beginning with exactly where the border was.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after a telephone call from Damascus, which calls the
shots in Lebanon, President Emile Lahoud gave the go-ahead on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah, the de facto force on the ground for more than two
months, has pledged not to interfere with the government
authorities. Its forces, with a core of about 500 fighters have
reverted to civilian clothes and are not carrying weapons in
public, although they are planning to keep them hidden away.
</P>
<P>
   But a drive along some of the remote back roads near the border
found Hezbollah fighters in casual clothes with binoculars and
walkie-talkies still manning checkpoints and observation posts.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Indeed, at Border Post 14, near the village of Rumaysh, where a
U.N. detail from Nepal was originally posted, the only force
visible on the Lebanese side consisted of five young Hezbollah
guerrillas lounging in an old guard post.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, a tall, bearded young man in a baseball hat and
track suit, showed the way up a road to what had been a major
crossing point into Israel, now a tangled wreck of corrugated metal
and old beams. Just ahead of where the pale blue U.N. flag still
flew near an abandoned pile of sandbags, an Israeli backhoe was
busily digging for a new border fence.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Hezbollah men and U.N. officials said the Nepalese had
left at the request of the Lebanese government, which did not want
U.N. forces at the old crossing points. There was no further
explanation of the reasoning behind the order.
</P>
<P>
   The deployment, when it finally came, was made up of mostly
gray-clad Internal Security police and military police, who spent
the day in their new barracks.
</P>
<P>
   The main body is to be based at an old army barracks here in
Marjayoun,, a mostly Christian town, that had been the headquarters
of the South Lebanese Army, Israel's proxy militia. About a third
were sent to Bint Jubail, a predominantly Shiite town farther
south, where one main street is marked by a sculpture of a hand
grenade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main impact of the deployment is psychological,'' said a
senior U.N. official. ``It's a really badly needed reassurance for
these people who have been alone too long.''
</P>
<P>
   Qulayah, the Christian village next to Marjayoun, was almost
deserted Wednesday. It had furnished many of the officers and
troops for the SLA and, consequently, many of the 6,000 refugees
who scrambled across the border when Israel abruptly pulled out on
May 24.
</P>
<P>
   But in fact, Hezbollah has acted in a remarkably restrained and
disciplined manner, and there has been little in the way of
reprisals. The Christian areas, in particular, where bloodletting
could have revived the passions of the 15-year civil war, have been
left alone.
</P>
<P>
   In the main square of Marjayoun, framed by picturesque stone
buildings and the distinctive cross atop a Greek Orthodox Church,
people waited for the army, barracked just down the road to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   ``How are they deployed? We haven't seen anything yet,'' said
George Mandalek, 67, who immediately mentioned his children in
Detroit and Oklahoma City. ``Well, I welcome the army anyway. We
went through a lot of troubled times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody expected it to be like this,'' he said of the quiet
that has prevailed here since late May. ``That's why those who went
left. They were afraid. The liberation was very calm. To be honest,
nobody expected it.''
</P>
<P>
   Adid Maalouf, 80 and a fit-looking retired soldier, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has never been a more genteel atmosphere,'' he said.
``We went through times when everything was turned upside down. But
now everything is calm.
</P>
<P>
   But Jean Mandalek, George's twin brother, took a dimmer view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody goes back to the root of the problem,'' he said. ``The
Palestinians came here, they massacred and burned. Then the
Israelis came and did the same. Since May, what has the government
done?
</P>
<P>
   ``The people here, how can they live, what will they do?'' he
asked. ``Nothing has happened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
