<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7208 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-REFORM-PARTY-ART-NYT     08-09 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-PARTY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON CONVENTION EVE, A PARTY TORN ASUNDER
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Includes story budgeted earlier as REFORM-BUCHANAN) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT 28 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY and B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Pat Buchanan arrived here Wednesday full of
optimism and bravado, predicting that he would claim the Reform
Party presidential nomination, despite a bitter split that could
leave the party nominating not one, but two, candidates for
president.
</P>
<P>
   Forces allied for and against Buchanan tried several times
Wednesday to resolve their differences but the split remained so
profound that a settlement by the opening gavel on Thursday was
highly unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are on our way,'' Buchanan said on his arrival to a
cheering crowd of 100 supporters at his hotel. ``We will give you
the fight of our lives. This convention belongs to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's rival for the nomination, John Hagelin, made no
public appearances here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the two sides met briefly in the morning, then again
in the afternoon, to consider the possibility of a settlement. But
talks broke off without a resolution. Officials on both sides said
they did not expect a breakthrough before the convention opened.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves each side to plot its own course over the next
several days and beyond _ all with an eye toward the $12.6 million
in federal campaign funds to which the party nominee is entitled.
</P>
<P>
   The party effectively split during a meeting of national
committee members on Tuesday, when opponents of Buchanan, about a
quarter of the 120 attending, stormed out of the room, charging
that his supporters had stolen control of the party. Those who
remained branded the protesters as sore losers, even as those who
left set up a national committee and an executive committee of
their own.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday, the absence of any conciliation made it clear that
both sides were digging in, wholly resistant to any opposing
arguments.
</P>
<P>
   In dueling news conferences, each side used different criteria
to make its case for legitimacy, and in the surest sign yet that
the party was operating along parallel tracks, the anti-Buchanan
group registered its delegates at a table in the Long Beach
Convention Center lobby, after which the pro-Buchanan forces
registered theirs.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, if there was any point of agreement, it was
this: A continuing split would almost guarantee that the ultimate
arbiters would be the Federal Election Commission, and in all
likelihood, a federal court.
</P>
<P>
   With the 596 convention delegates arriving Wednesday, the
question was not so much which candidate, Buchanan or Hagelin,
would receive the campaign money as much as which ruling group was
legitimately in control of the party and, by extension, the
convention, which ends on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   By sheer numbers, the Buchanan side seemed to hold an advantage.
Gerry Moan, the party chairman whose stewardship of the national
committee meeting precipitated the walkout, said that his control
of $2.5 million in federal money to stage the convention made him
and his followers _ almost all of them Buchanan supporters _ the
rightful claimants to authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can say anything they wish,'' Moan said of his opponents.
``But I am the chairman.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Bay Buchanan, the candidate's sister and chief
strategist, said that by her count, Buchanan had control of 410
delegates, more than enough to defeat Hagelin, should it come to
that. In the Reform Party, a candidate can ask that the primary
vote, a monthlong process that concludes this week, be set aside in
favor of a delegate vote.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-Buchanan forces contended that they represented a
majority of the party's original 11-member executive committee and
had proof that, as part of the primary balloting process, Buchanan
violated party rules by sending ballots to ineligible voters.
</P>
<P>
   Accusing Moan and the Buchanan campaign of ``brown-shirt
tactics'' that included physical assaults on party members on
Tuesday, Jim Mangia, the party secretary, said that as far as his
side was concerned, Buchanan was disqualified from the primary.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Mangia said, Moan's side had acknowledged the
authority of the executive committee that Mangia is now running, by
voting on Tuesday to void any actions that committee takes.
</P>
<P>
   Moan dismissed that contention, saying, ``Their executive
committee is irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Russ Verney, the party's founding chairman who is now aligned
with the forces opposed to Buchanan, predicted that the warring
factions would not find accommodation, making it all but certain
the party would make dual requests to the election commission for
the campaign money.
</P>
<P>
   That, Verney said, could work to his side's advantage if the
election commission chooses to investigate charges that Buchanan's
campaign submitted illegal names.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point,'' Verney said, referring to the six commission
members, ``they are going to have to go back and look at the many
activities that have gone on.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan and his sister spoke as if the federal money was
already on the way to them. Speaking to reporters, Bay Buchanan
said she expected that her campaign would receive the money within
three weeks, an inevitability the other side has not accepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideally, I would have hoped these people would have heard the
fat lady sing 30 days ago,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said that the Buchanan campaign had plans to use almost all
the federal money on a media campaign, mostly radio, starting after
Labor Day and aiming at specific states, which she declined to
identify.
</P>
<P>
   By that strategy, she said, Buchanan's popularity would begin to
rise from as little as 1 percent in some recent polls to double
digits, an ascent that would almost surely affect the fortunes of
the Republican ticket of Gov. George W. Bush and Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   That effort, she added, would be immeasurably aided if a court
rules that Buchanan, and perhaps the other leading third-party
candidate, Ralph Nader of the Green Party, should be allowed to
participate in the presidential debates this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The debates are critical,'' Bay Buchanan said. ``I'm hoping
that we can just start clicking, get into the debates and win this
election, even.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
