</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOFTWARE-MERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS SHOW APPROVAL OF MERGER BY PHONE.COM AND SOFTWARE.COM 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The dot-com mania has not died.
</P>
<P>
   Phone.com and Software.com, two relatively small, money-losing
software companies, announced they were merging Wednesday, and
investors responded by adding $2.6 billion to their combined market
values.
</P>
<P>
   The ``.com'' suffix in both companies' names, moreover, is
somewhat misleading, as neither does business through its Web site.
Software.com sells software that Internet service providers, like
AT&AMP;T Worldnet, use to operate their electronic mail systems.
Phone.com has developed a tiny browser program that allows wireless
telephones to view specially formatted Internet sites. The browser
is free, but Phone.com makes money selling software used by
purveyors of sites meant for the wireless phones.
</P>
<P>
   The companies have no overlapping products, and the main thing
they have in common is that they both sell their products primarily
to telephone companies. In the future, however, the companies were
primed to become more direct competitors. They were both developing
products allowing telephone companies to offer unified messaging
services, in which voice messages, faxes, electronic mail and so on
are all collected into a single place and then distributed to the
device of the user's choice, be it a computer, a telephone or a
wireless gadget.
</P>
<P>
   This opportunity appeared to be compelling enough to Donald J.
Listwin, a Software.com board member who was, until Tuesday, also
an executive vice president of Cisco Systems, that he proposed that
he run the combined company last week amid the final negotiations
between Phone.com and Software.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``I approached folks and said you may need help pulling off a
complex merger and how do you feel about my joining the team,''
Listwin said yesterday. He knew the new firm's customers because at
Cisco he managed the business of selling Internet network hardware
to telephone companies and service providers.
</P>
<P>
   Listwin will become president and chief executive. Alain
Rossman, the chief executive of Phone.com, will become chairman and
executive vice president. John L. MacFarlane, the chief executive
of Software.com, will be an executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   MacFarlane's consolation prize for giving up the chief executive
spot is that his shares are now worth $710 million. Rossman's
shares are worth a mere $336 million.
</P>
<P>
   The new company has not been named, but will either be
Software.com or Phone.com. The combined company will be
headquartered in Redwood City, the Silicon Valley home of
Phone.com; Software.com has been based in Santa Barbara. None of
the combined company's 1,500 employees will be laid off.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies have ridden a roller coaster in the stock market,
but unlike most purveyors of Web sites and online stores, they
still enjoyed the sort of stock market values unheard of in the
pre-Internet era.
</P>
<P>
   Phone.com's shares have ranged between $27.50 and $208 in the
last year, and were $78 on Tuesday, before the deal was announced,
giving it a value of $6.1 billion. Software.com's shares ranged
between $22 and $155, closing Monday at $107.75 giving it a value
of $5.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   At best, investors were betting on the companies rapid growth,
rather than their current financial performance. In the most recent
quarter, Phone.com lost $166 million on sales of $28.7 million.
Software.com lost $11 million on sales of $29.5 million. Listwin
said he hopes the company can achieve $1 billion in annual sales in
two years.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lack of overlapping operations, investors appeared
to view the merger as accelerating that growth. Software.com's
shares increased $34.6875, to $142.4375. Phone.com's shares jumped
$13.625, to $91.1225.
</P>
<P>
   ``This stock is not trading on fundamentals,'' said Mark
Fernandes, an analyst with Merrill Lynch. ``There is a great deal
of enthusiasm about the synergies coming from this deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The merger agreement provided that shareholders of each company
would own half of the combined entity, meaning that Phone.com is
paying a premium to Software.com shareholders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
