u a BC-FBI-MOB-BOS &LR;      08-09 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBI-MOB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-FBI AGENT'S POSSIBLE ROLE IN FOUR SLAYINGS PROBED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A federal investigation of FBI wrongdoing is focusing
on whether retired FBI agent John J. Connolly Jr. provoked the
slayings of four government informants by alerting gangsters James
``Whitey'' Bulger and Stephen Flemmi that the informants were
cooperating against them, according to sources familiar with the
probe.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury that indicted Connolly and his longtime
informants, Bulger and Flemmi on federal racketeering charges in
December is considering additional charges against the three men
and others, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a team of federal agents have been questioning many
retired agents from the FBI's Boston office about the slayings of
Richard Castucci, Louis Litif, Brian Halloran, and John McIntyre,
each of whom had given the FBI information about Bulger and Flemmi
or fellow members of the Winter Hill gang, based in nearby
Somerville, in the weeks before their deaths, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Castucci, 47, a nightclub owner, was found shot in the head and
wrapped in a sleeping bag in the trunk of his Cadillac behind the
Northgate Shopping Center in Revere, just outside Boston, on Dec.
30, 1976.
</P>
<P>
   The case remained unsolved until last year, when confessed
hitman-turned-government witness John Martorano, formerly of the
Winter Hill gang, admitted Castucci was among 20 people he killed _
and fingered Bulger and Flemmi in the slaying as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe has learned that Castucci had been an FBI informant
for about a year before he was slain and had told the FBI that
Joseph McDonald _ a Winter Hill gang enforcer _ was hiding out near
Greenwich Village in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, McDonald was on the FBI's 10 Most Wanted list for
fleeing after his arrest for the 1971 heist of a rare stamp
collection. McDonald vanished after a key witness in the case was
murdered.
</P>
<P>
   Castucci's tip failed to lead agents to McDonald. But two weeks
after the Boston FBI office filed a detailed internal report on his
cooperation in the fugitive case, Castucci was slain, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Tracy A. Miner, who represents Connolly, said her
client had nothing to do with the murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Connolly never told Bulger or Flemmi about any
informant,'' Miner said. ``Castucci was not John Connolly's
informant and he had no knowledge that Castucci was an informant.''
</P>
<P>
   Former FBI Supervisor John Morris, who admitted he pocketed
$7,000 in bribes from Bulger and Flemmi and told them about
investigations, was assigned to the stamp theft case. Morris, who
has immunity in exchange for his testimony against Bulger and his
crew, has also been questioned recently about the slayings of the
informants, according to sources.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly, a star agent who retired in 1990, is charged with
tipping Bulger and Flemmi to investigations. Bulger and Flemmi are
the subjects of two federal racketeering indictments: one returned
in January 1995 and another filed last year that accuses them of
controlling bookmaking, drug dealing and loan-sharking operations
around the city under Connolly's protection.
</P>
<P>
   Bulger has been a fugitive since 1995 and Flemmi, known in mob
circles as ``the rifleman,'' remains jailed while awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
   After Martorano fingered Bulger and Flemmi in Castucci's
slaying, Castucci's children vowed to file a multimillion dollar
wrongful death suit against the government.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney John McBride, who represents the Castuccis, said the
family was unaware that Castucci was an FBI informant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assuming that to be accurate,'' McBride said, ``then that
further enhances the likelihood of success that the Castucci family
would have in their suit against the government for its egregious
misconduct.''
</P>
<P>
   McBride described Castucci, owner of the Ebb Tide Lounge, as a
bookmaker and gambler who was ambushed on an errand to collect some
winnings.
</P>
<P>
   Litif _ whose death is also the focus of the current grand jury
probe _ had been an informant for Connolly for about 15 years
before he was slain.
</P>
<P>
   The 45-year-old bookmaker-turned-drug dealer was out on bail for
the murder of another bookie when his body was found April 13,
1980. Litif had been shot in the head, wrapped in plastic and
stuffed in the trunk of his car in the South End.
</P>
<P>
   Halloran, a third informant whose murder is now under intense
investigation, implicated Bulger and Flemmi in the slaying of Litif
and others, including a Tulsa millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   Halloran claimed he dropped Litif off at Triple O's bar in South
Boston, waited outside during the execution, then helped Bulger and
one of his associates get rid of the body. The FBI deemed Halloran
unreliable and refused to cut a deal with him. He was subsequently
gunned down, along with a friend, on May 11, 1982 as he left a bar
on Boston's waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   McIntyre, 32, the fourth slain informant, vanished in November
1984, six weeks after the FBI learned that he had implicated Bulger
and Flemmi in an ill-fated plot to ship guns to the Irish
Republican Army.
</P>
<P>
   McIntyre's fate remained unknown until January, when Kevin Weeks
_ a top Bulger deputy _ led investigators to a makeshift grave in
the city's Dorchester section containing the bodies of McIntyre and
two other victims.
</P>
<P>
   When pleading guilty to racketeering charges last month after
striking a deal with prosecutors, Weeks acknowledged that Bulger
and Flemmi killed McIntyre and Halloran after learning they were
informants. He also said he was the ``lookout'' when Halloran was
ambushed and that he helped bury McIntyre's body.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 2121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000809.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7216 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TIRE-FIRESTONE-2TAKES     08-09 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIRE-FIRESTONE-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIES OF FORCE RECALL SPUR FIRESTONE TO ACT 
</HEADLINE>
  (With TIRE-RECALL) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Bridgestone/Firestone announced a recall on Wednesday of
some 6.5 million Firestone tires, it was the company's first
admission that the tires could pose a danger. But it was also a
first step toward damage control.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years is a long time, but memories of how a
government-mandated recall in the 1970s nearly bankrupted Firestone
Tire &AMP; Rubber _ the company's name before Japan's Bridgestone Corp.
bought it in 1988 _ clearly resonate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The oral history around here is that we were a lot too slow to
cooperate back then,'' said Christine Karbowiak, a Firestone
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the company is recalling the tires without being
forced _ though it withstood a week of withering news articles
before acting. It has established a hot line for worried drivers,
and it is offering to replace _ with virtually no questions asked _
the affected tires, regardless of how long they have been on the
road.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, Firestone is trying to define the
problem as narrowly as possible, so that its brand is not tarnished
as a whole. Though the recall includes all 15-inch Radial ATX and
Radial ATX II tires, the focus is on Wilderness AT tires made at a
plant in Decatur, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are isolating this so that, in the consumer's mind, this
isn't a problem with Firestone tires, but a problem with 15-inch
Wilderness tires made in a particular plant in Decatur,'' said
Stephen Girsky, a tire industry analyst with Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter. ``If they can keep this controlled and isolated, it won't
have a significant long-term impact on their sales.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, plaintiffs' lawyers who have filed lawsuits blaming the
tires for serious injuries say Firestone has been stonewalling. In
settling several lawsuits over the last year, the company has
insisted that the lawyers and their clients not talk about the
cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask them for documents, they say sure, as long as you sign
the usual protective order,'' said Henry Wallace, a lawyer
representing an injured client in Florida. ``Well, I won't sign,
and other lawyers shouldn't either. My research shows there are at
least 31 cases that are astoundingly similar to mine, and I should
have access to their information.''
</P>
<P>
   Karbowiak, the Firestone spokeswoman, said it was common in
business litigation to keep settlement agreements private.
</P>
<P>
   The company also finds itself in less than total agreement with
its customer of 100 years, the Ford Motor Co., millions of whose
Explorer sport utility vehicles are equipped with the Firestone
tires involved in the recall.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference on Wednesday, Firestone and Ford offered
contradictory advice about the optimum pressure for the tires.
Firestone recommended 30 pounds per square inch; Ford suggested
anywhere between 26 and 30 would be fine.
</P>
<P>
   The difference reflected the contrasting interests of automakers
and tire makers. Automakers advise customers to keep tires fairly
soft because this makes the ride less bouncy. That is particularly
true for sport utility vehicles, which have stiff truck suspensions
but are increasingly purchased by people more accustomed to the
ride of a car.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But soft tires, with more of their surface area in contact with
the road, suffer more wear, so tiremakers favor keeping their
products inflated at higher pressure. ``Underinflated tires
deteriorate more rapidly than tires that are properly maintained
and are at an increased risk of tread separation, blowout or other
failure,'' Firestone said.
</P>
<P>
   The conflicting advice prefigures what are likely to be two
crucial chapters in the episode: first, the government's
determination of why the tires are failing, and then the
apportionment of blame and financial responsibility. More
immediately, it spurred expressions of frustration from plaintiffs'
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``So now what is the consumer supposed to do?'' asked Tab
Turner, a lawyer in Little Rock who has 10 lawsuits filed against
both companies.
</P>
<P>
   What had been a quiet issue for Firestone and Ford began to turn
into a storm in February, when someone who had been injured in an
accident involving a Ford Explorer with Firestone tires contacted
KHOU, a Houston tlevision station. The station ran a segment on
possible problems with the tires. Slowly, other stations picked up
on the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until that piece ran in Houston, we'd had maybe 30 or 40
complaints in 10 years,'' said Liz Neblett, a spokeswoman for the
National Highway Traffic Safety Administration. By the time the
agency opened its investigation on May 2, it had 90 complaints of
injuries related to ATX or Wilderness tires on Ford Explorers; as
of Wednesday morning, there were 270.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, whenever a story runs, there's another bump in the
complaints,'' Neblett said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The flood of lawsuits seems unlikely to abate. The American
Trial Lawyers Association has organized a litigation group around
the Firestone tires, in which lawyers representing can compare
notes, and perhaps consolidate suits.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Those lawyers are sure to resist the company's efforts to define
the problem narrowly. Both Firestone and Ford said on Wednesday
that evidence pointed to tires made at the Decatur plant as the
focus of further investigation. But Turner and other lawyers took
issue with Firestone's plan to replace Wilderness tires made in
Decatur with similar tires from other plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a 35-year-old quadriplegic client on a ventilator,
who got that way when a 1997 Ford Explorer rolled over after a rear
tire separation,'' Turner said. ``That tire was made in Wilson,
N.C., one of the plants that is supposed to provide those safe
replacement tires.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the case against the tires may not be cut and dried.
The same tires have been used on sport utility vehicles made by
General Motors, Toyota and other manufacturers without a
particularly high incidence of failure. Likewise, from 1995 through
1997, many Ford Explorers used Goodyear tires without undue
problems with tread separations, said Chuck Sinclair, a Goodyear
spokesman. Moreover, Ford Explorers running on Firestone tires in
cold-weather states do not seem to fail more often than other
tires.
</P>
<P>
   Experts assessing the information available so far suspect that
it is the combination of a burning sun, Ford Explorers, Firestone
tires and drivers' failure to properly inflate them that can prove
lethal.
</P>
<P>
   When a tire is underinflated, there is more flexing in the
sidewall, which generates more heat. If the vehicle is carrying
lots of people, lots of luggage or an otherwise heavy load, the
friction gets worse. Add hot weather and a hot road, and tire
temperature can get critical. A good tire can generally endure
temperatures as high as 210 degrees without an accident. But at 220
degrees, it can start to disintegrate.
</P>
<P>
   When that happens, even the best drivers often lose control of
their vehicles. In such circumstances, the Explorer, with its high
center of gravity, is more likely to roll over.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``These vehicles are used by a lot of different people, in lots
of driving conditions, and a lot of the ways they use it can lead
to tire failure,'' said Marvin Bozarth, executive director of the
International Tire and Rubber Association. ``I can probably walk
out and spot five Explorers in half an hour that are running on
underinflated tires. And if they are full of 200-pound people with
all their luggage, the tires will heat up tremendously.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Whoever is ultimately held accountable, the companies with the
most to gain are Firestone's competitors. Firestone may not have
the capacity to manufacture as many free replacement tires as it
needs for the recall; the company said Wednesday it would buy
competitor's products if necessary.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   So far, tire companies are not using Firestone's woes as an
opportunity to claim market share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Firestone may be bearing the lion's share of the burden, but
something like this is bad for the entire industry,'' said
Goodyear's Sinclair. Indeed, Karbowiak, the Firestone spokeswoman,
said she got a note from her counterpart at one competitive
company, offering sympathy and asking how she could help.
</P>
<P>
   Still, other companies certainly will not turn sales away.
Sinclair noted that Goodyear has been ``looking into our inventory
and our manufacturing capabilities, to make sure we can meet
customer demand.'' Indeed, analysts expect that Firestone's
competitors have much to gain and little to lose by keeping
low-profiles right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tire recalls happen all the time, and they know what goes
around comes around, that if they go after Firestone brutally on
this one, Firestone will go after them on the next,'' Gwirsky of
Morgan Stanley said. ``And they'll probably gain share by default,
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors clearly think so. On July 31, just before stories in
USA Today called national attention to the problems, Bridgestone
shares traded in Tokyo for 2515 yen; Wednesday, they closed at
2075, a drop of 17 percent. By contrast, Goodyear's shares have
gone up 18 percent in the same period, closing on Wednesday at $23
9/16.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that Goodyear's stock is moving on the new potential
for market share gains,'' said Ephraim Levy, a tire industry
analyst with S&AMP;P Equity Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
