<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE0810-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Democrats downplay differences
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. _ Vice President Al Gore and his new running
mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman (D-Conn.), took their campaign on the
road Wednesday, beginning the tricky task of fashioning a unified
ticket out of political positions that have not always been in
sync.
</P>
<P>
   In campaign stops in Gore's hometown, Carthage, Tenn., and
Lieberman's boyhood home, Stamford, Conn., the Democrats papered
over the political differences they have had over the years and
portrayed themselves as ideological soul mates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand this relationship,'' Lieberman told Gore
supporters in Carthage, near where the vice president launched his
congressional career in 1974. ``Believe me, when President Gore
decides, Vice President Lieberman will support him
wholeheartedly.'' Gore, a Southern Baptist whose father was a
Tennessee senator, showed Lieberman and his family around the farm
he still owns. Later, Lieberman, an Orthodox Jew whose father owned
a liquor store, took the Gores to a rally in Stamford.
</P>
<P>
   At a town hall meeting in Carthage, Lieberman told longtime Gore
supporters that Carthage, a rural Southern town of 2,400, reminded
him of Stamford, a wealthy bedroom community near New York City,
because people ``care about each other.''
</P>
<P>
   In answer to a pointed question from a member of the National
Education Association, the politically vocal teacher's union, about
his support for public school vouchers, a position opposed by Gore
and the powerful education lobby, Lieberman signalled his
willingness to follow Gore's lead: ``If you want to get me off this
idea, the best thing to do is elect the Gore-Lieberman ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier on NBC's ``Today'' show, Lieberman defended his position
that parental consent for minors seeking abortions should be
required in some instances.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is adamantly opposed to that. Dan Gerstein, a Lieberman
aide, said the senator supported parental consent only if it
allowed for certain exceptions, such as the health of the woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bottom line, he's pro-choice,'' Gerstein said.
</P>
<P>
   On CNN's ``Larry King Live'' the night before, Lieberman
downplayed comments he has made about potential advantages of
privatizing some portions of the Social Security system. Gore has
been sharply critical of privatizing Social Security and has
accused George W. Bush of jeopardizing the program by proposing
that workers be allowed to invest in private accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's comment on CNN prompted criticism from the Bush
campaign Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that Senator Lieberman hasn't changed his position on
Social Security to clear the way for Al Gore to attack George Bush
for a position Senator Lieberman supports,'' said Dan Bartlett, a
Bush spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman accused the Bush campaign of exaggerating the
differences between him and Gore. ``The other side has been trying
to point out differences between Al and me,'' Lieberman said in
Carthage. ``The differences are very, very few. We share values, we
share a vision for the country, and our voting records are almost
exactly the same, but there are some things on which we disagree.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also sought to portray their political differences as a
selling point. ``I'm not afraid to have a vice president who
disagrees with me on some issues,'' Gore told his hometown crowd.
``I think it is a strength and not a weakness, an asset and not a
liability to be able to have a different point of view represented
in the room when decisions are being made.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
