<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7226 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-LANDSCAPE-ARCHITECT-A     08-09 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANDSCAPE-ARCHITECT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUMAN NATURE AS OBSERVED BY DAVID SEELER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT31-35 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ANNE RAVER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAGAPONACK, N.Y. _ David Seeler is a practical man. When the
landscape architect needed 25,000 tons of fill to build a ha-ha, or
hidden fence, down the road from his house here, he decided to give
his wife a pond for her 55th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an expression around here,'' he said, watching the
bulldozers mold the S-shaped quarter-acre pond taking shape behind
the house. ``Moderation is for monks.''
</P>
<P>
   A ha-ha is a little landscape trick from 18th-century England: a
sunken fence or ditch used to keep the cows at a picturesque
distance from the manor house. The cows appeared to be grazing on
the greensward, but a wide ditch kept them from trampling the lawn
and mooing at the guests.
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward to the Hamptons, where for 30 years Seeler has run
the Bayberry Nursery, a garden center in Amagansett, and shaped the
land for its summer stars: Paul Simon, Ralph Lauren, Edward Albee,
Helmut Lang, Alfonso Ossorio, and others less famous but even
better at making money. Though Seeler's own homes (one here, one in
Amagansett and one planned for a sand dune in Montauk) reflect a
natural restraint and sensitivity to the land, his clients may want
the scrub oak forest turned into a stroll garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been out here so long, I've seen a lot of my gardens
ripped out by new owners,'' said Seeler, who is 58. ``Or many
times, the gardens are consumed by the house, which is four times
the size of the old one. That's a heartbreak.''
</P>
<P>
   He tells of an elderly couple who were talked into a $1.4
million expansion of a house ``to protect their investment.'' They
told him, ``The architect talked us into it.'' He keeps asking
clients who think they want a fabulous landscape, who's going to
mow, weed, spray, do the pool? ``They buy a summer retreat and then
they're never alone.'' They want it all anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much money around, people don't know what to do
with it,'' he said. ``The amount of business I did my entire first
year in 1970, I do now the first four days in April.''
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty of 18th-century park-building going on in the
flat fields and scrub oak woods around here _ even for something as
simple as a pool fence, that modern-day requirement to prevent
being sued for accidental drowning. (A maddening regulation,
really, when a whole ocean glints a few fields away, crashing
fenceless at the feet of little children. But you can't sue the
ocean.)
</P>
<P>
   When his neighbor on Sagaponack Road needed a pool fence, Seeler
built a berm, a kind of ha-ha in reverse. He brought in enough fill
_ from his just-dug pond _ to raise an earthwork around the house
and pool. Then he buttressed it with a stone wall. Voila, wandering
children, like cows, are kept out.
</P>
<P>
   ``And now you can look straight out, forever,'' Seeler said,
standing on his artificial plateau and sweeping his arm toward the
wildflower meadow his wife, Ngaere (pronounced NYE-ree) Macray,
planted a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   She's the one who got a pond in return. It backs on the Sagg
Swamp Nature Preserve, so nearby nesting herons can wade in the
shallow waters, which deepen to seven feet in the center. Macray
bought the property 20 years ago, with her first husband, Arnold
Zohn, when it was still 40 acres of potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted a house that felt like an 18th-century farm,'' she
said. ``Something that was added onto, like the old farmhouses
were, as people's needs grew. If you forgot something _ for the
horse, the dog, the parakeet _ you just added it on.''
</P>
<P>
   Eugene L. Futterman, the architect who had the rare ability to
suspend his ego and draw someone else's dream, built the house
before his death in 1987; Seeler laid out the gardens.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave me the elevations and the spaces,'' said Macray, who
grew up in England, in gardens with ``bones,'' or architectural
elements that flow. Here the bones show in garden rooms at
pleasingly different levels, including one made of clipped beech
and empty except for a bench.
</P>
<P>
   They planted a giant oval of beech trees, started by Macray from
sprouted beechnuts sent through the mail by her English mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the trees grow up, their branches will meet to form a
cathedral,'' Macray said, standing inside the grassy nave, where
her beloved dogs and cats are buried and where she and Seeler want
their ashes scattered.
</P>
<P>
   Come summer, they rent out their winter house and move into
cooler, calmer quarters behind Bayberry Nursery. Seeler grew up in
Huntington, with summers on West Gilgo Beach, and never got the
sand out of his shoes. So after earning a master's degree in
landscape architecture from the University of Georgia, and working
for six years, he came out to Amagansett, bought the nursery in
1971, and two years later, eight acres of land for $59,000.
</P>
<P>
   The land had been stripped of its topsoil, so he rebuilt the
soil with tons of compost. That barren wasteland is now the
Disney-like show grounds for wealthy clients, who can look at
baby-elephant garden ornaments ($2,700) and 10-ton, $36,000 beech
trees, or rest themselves on an Adirondack chair (only $140) by the
quarter-acre pond Seeler built for clients who need to sit down
while they add up their landscape costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people use this like a public park,'' Seeler said,
flopping into a chair to eat his lunch. ``I've always wanted a
garden center that was more garden than center.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be stretching it a bit, but there are some beautiful
specimens here, like the 8-foot, 75-year-old Hinoki cypress that
has grown only two feet in 25 years. ``I'm going to will that to
Longwood Gardens when I die,'' Seeler said of the showplace created
by Pierre S. du Pont in southeastern Pennsylvania. And you can get
lots of ideas, like growing grapevines, with real grapes up a
whimsical dovecote made by the artist Michael Ince.
</P>
<P>
   This is also where Seeler rejuvenates venerable old plants his
clients tell him to haul off to the dump: like Caroline Kennedy
Schlossberg's boxwoods, or a 45-year-old, espaliered apple tree.
Then he sells them to just the right person.
</P>
<P>
   Tucked behind the nursery is the Seeler-Macray summer home.
Seeler replaced the flat roof of the one-story house with a tall,
swooping Thai-like roof, with a four-foot overhang that allows them
to keep the windows open in the rain (to hear it, smell it, feel a
breeze). It also shades the house in summer.
</P>
<P>
   Glass doors to the bedroom and open living room offer views on
one side of a simple courtyard and pool, and on the other of a
secluded meadow, punctuated a few large native cedars.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many rooms do you need?'' Seeler said, showing how the
two-sided fireplace serves both the great room and the bedroom. In
the morning, he rolls out of bed into his Zen-like courtyard for a
swim.
</P>
<P>
   Seeler tries to bring this light touch to the gardens he designs
for his clients. ``I try to find out what their dream is,'' he
said. ``It can be a pond. A super garden. The play area they never
had as a child.'' Then again, ``some people have no dream,'' he
said. ``They just want it decorated.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There is a manicured, parklike quality to many of the gardens,
perhaps because the plants are set in place all at once, rather
than evolving through the years. Sometimes, the best Seeler can do
is to save people from themselves.
</P>
<P>
   His favorite jobs have been for clients who are sensitive to the
land, or the spirit of an old house like Pudding Hall, the
turn-of-the-century dinosaur on the corner of Main Street and Woods
Lane in East Hampton. The monster of gables and shingles used to
command a view of the town pond, from an estate twice its present
size, full of towering beeches and cryptomeria.
</P>
<P>
   Built in 1886 for the founder of the Maidstone Club in East
Hampton, the house was a wreck when the new owners bought it two
years ago. There was blue vinyl over the leaky roof and trees were
sorely neglected.
</P>
<P>
   As the house was restored, Seeler developed a Victorian
landscape to go with it. Taking his cues from the great old
surviving trees, he practiced the ``less is more'' principle. He
left a sprawling old juniper lounging over the front lawn, and
planted a hedge on the other side with Caroline Kennedy's
born-again boxwoods (they had spent six years at Bayberry
recuperating).
</P>
<P>
   He planted a hedge of holly and a little grove of cryptomeria to
match the old ones on Woods Lane, and edged the northern dark side
of the house with white Annabelle hydrangeas. A perennial garden
spills over with blue Nikko and white Peegee hydrangeas, Anthony
Waterer spireas and burning bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``All period old East Hampton plants,'' Seeler said. ``At these
old houses, you only find things that flowered during `the
season.'''
</P>
<P>
   He left a few old cedars, covered with ivy and porcelain vine,
to avoid looking too manicured.
</P>
<P>
   Some clients, like the real estage agent Tina Fredericks, have
spent a lifetime honing a dream. Her house, on Georgica Pond in
East Hampton, rises like a lighthouse out of the briar patch. She
bought the land 25 years ago, when she realized she was selling
property to everyone but herself. She made paths through the wild
bayberry and shadblow to a little bench facing the pond. ``I wanted
to built a Japanese teahouse, but the town doesn't allow an
accessory structure without a house,'' she said. So finally,
working with a young designer, Kenton van Boer, she built two
towers, all cedar shingles and glass, that rise like trees, out of
a sloping foundation of stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideally, if you could drop a house down from a helicopter, you
wouldn't have to wreck the natural landscape,'' Seeler said. But
this house wasn't dropped. So he has had to use a little theater,
such as attaching dead bittersweet vines, as thick as a wrist,
along the new rock walls as a natural trellis for wisteria. He
yanked a mature climbing hydrangea off a Bayberry wall and used
that and that recycled, espaliered apple tree to give the new walls
an old look. He planted native witch hazel, viburnums and native
azaleas to draw nature back up to the house.
</P>
<P>
   On another part of Georgica Pond he demolished much of the
natural woods to put in a pool, complete with a carved rosewood
Indian pavilion, for a Wall Street broker and his wife. Then his
crew spent three years turning five acres of scrub oak into a
woodland park, full of exotic plants, grassy paths and a quiet
pond.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had been mulling over what to do with their house,''
Seeler said, nodding toward the simple wood summer house, built in
1900. ``So I suggested they start with the pool and the gardens and
sort of work backward.'' They got the gardening bug, he said, and
``realized they didn't need a great room and all those things
people think they need.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the couple has moved to England and put the property up for
sale. ``For $10.2 million,'' Seeler said. ``That shocks me.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's my dream. That the new owner wants a scrub oak woods full
of bayberry, cedar and blueberry. That Seeler haul all those blue
hydrangeas, and the Indian pavilion back to Bayberry Nursery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
