<HEADLINE>
FORD TO OFFER NEW SYSTEMS ON SPORT VEHICLES
</HEADLINE>
  (With TIRE-RECALL) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRAVERSE CITY, Mich. _ The Ford Motor Co. announced on Wednesday
that it would offer computerized stability systems on its sport
utility vehicles and pickups by the 2005 model year, to improve the
handling of the tall vehicles and reduce the frequency of
rollovers.
</P>
<P>
   But the systems will be optional on many of the models, meaning
that customers who want them will have to pay extra. Ford currently
charges $725 for the option on its $33,000 Lincoln LS sports sedan.
</P>
<P>
   The expensive suspension systems, which automatically apply the
brakes slightly to one or more wheels to prevent them from
slipping, are currently available only on a few luxury models, like
the Lincoln LS sedan and the Mercedes ML320 sport utility vehicle.
But safety experts have been calling for automakers to make them
more available.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Inglis, Ford's vice president for North American
automotive operations, said the move was independent of the recall
by Bridgestone/Firestone Inc. of 6.5 million tires, many of them on
Ford Explorer sport utilities. Inglis announced the plan at the
auto industry's annual summer meeting, organized by the University
of Michigan and held in northwestern Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors responded by saying that the Cadillac Escalade
full-sized sport utility vehicle would be equipped with the
stability system as standard equipment starting this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Stability systems allow even fairly tall, heavy vehicles to be
driven with agility around obstacles that can cause crashes, like
debris in the road, other vehicles, animals or pedestrians.
Continental A.G., a big German manufacturer of tires and brakes,
recently hosted a demonstration of the technology in the suburbs of
Detroit. When reporters drove the Mercedes sport utility through a
slalom course of cones designed to simulate a swerve around an
obstacle in the road, the sport utility tipped up on two wheels
when going a little more than 30 miles an hour with the stability
system disengaged. But when the system was engaged, all four wheels
stayed on the ground.
</P>
</TEXT>
