<SLUG> BC-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE CLARIFIES RELATIONSHIP WITH VP CHOICE 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARTHAGE, Tenn. _ Democratic presidential contender Al Gore made
it clear Wednesday that while he welcomed running mate Joe
Lieberman's differing opinions on a number of issues, Gore's
position would prevail in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Gore clarified his relationship with his new vice-presidential
pick as the two appeared in the vice president's home town of
Carthage.
</P>
<P>
   With Lieberman and his family by his side, Gore listened to
friends and constituents talk about the boy or young man they knew
who eventually grew up to be a representative, senator, vice
president and now Democratic presidential contender.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the crowd praised Gore for his constituent service over
the years. But one woman, who identified herself as a member of a
teachers' union, raised the touchy issue of Lieberman's support of
private school vouchers, one of several areas of dispute between
the two men.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, a Connecticut senator, defended his support for a
pilot program, arguing he wanted to help students in poor public
urban schools with no hope of reform. But both he and the
presidential candidate made it clear that Gore's position would
prevail in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Although they might disagree privately, Lieberman said,
``Believe me when President Gore decides, vice president Lieberman
will support him wholeheartedly.``
</P>
<P>
   Wrapping his arm around his running mate Gore quickly chimed in,
``I am not afraid to have a vice president who disagrees with me on
some things.'' But he added, ``Our administration will be opposed
to private school vouchers.``
</P>
<P>
   Later Gore also addressed the issue of abortion, where there is
a shade of differences between the two men.
</P>
<P>
   While both men support abortion rights, Lieberman has also
backed parental consent for minors to get abortions. Gore told
reporters on Air Force 2 that he was willing to look at proposals
for parental notification for minors seeking an abortion _ a less
restrictive provision.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore quickly added that he had not seen notification
proposals that would still protect women's rights to chose to have
an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not going to support anything that becomes an attack on a
woman's right to chose,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Lieberman played down any differences over abortion.
``Our views are not all that different,'' Gore said. Lieberman
concurred, ``Our positions are quite comparable there.``
</P>
<P>
   While campaigning in California, Republican presidential
candidate and Texas Gov. George W. Bush offered faint praise of
Gore's choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good pick,'' Bush said, adding that Lieberman has won
bipartisan support during his career and is ``a man of integrity. I
appreciate his views on Social Security,'' which some analysts have
described as more like Bush's than Gore's.
</P>
<P>
   Bush disputed suggestions that by picking a harsh critic of
President Clinton's conduct in the Monica Lewinsky affair, Gore had
inoculated himself against claims that he would carry Clinton's
moral legacy into the next administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people are going to decide who best can bring a
new tone to Washington. If Vice President Gore says `I'm different
from President Clinton,' let him explain how. I'm saying I am,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Embarking on his ninth California visit this year, Bush and
Texas First Lady Laura Bush boarded a special train that delivered
them to spirited train-station rallies in Oxnard and San Luis
Obispo. His running mate, Dick Cheney, was campaigning in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   While in Carthage, Gore listened to friends and constituents
talk about the boy or young man they knew who eventually grew up to
be a representative, senator, vice president and now Democratic
presidential contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every important thing in my life started in Carthage,'' Gore
said, addressing a crowd in the local school gymnasium.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the crowd praised Gore for his constituent service over
the years.
</P>
<P>
   Others offered fond stories about how Gore helped them.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Thompson, editor of the Winchester Herald Chronicle,
recalled how as a 14 year old in 1989 he delivered a note from his
mother to Gore at one of his town hall meetings asking the then
senator to help his grandmother get her Social Security checks.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson produced a letter that had been written by Gore
informing the family that the retirement checks, including back
unpaid benefits would soon be arriving.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got that letter I knew why we were Democrats,'' he
said. Another woman told Gore, ``I'm so proud of you. Don't let the
bad publicity that surrounds you get you down.``
</P>
<P>
   The day began with a visit by the two families to the Gore
family farm and across the street to the house where Gore's mother
Pauline now lives.
</P>
<P>
   It ended with a visit by the candidates to the home of
Lieberman's mother, Marcia, in Stamford, Conn., where the new vice
presidential candidate grew up before heading to Yale University.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, a former attorney general and two term senator from
Connecticut, was greeted enthusiastically at an evening rally at
the Stamford Italian Center.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke proudly of his roots in the town where his father owned
a liquor store. He joked that his late father was having a
conversation with his late uncle in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   ``My uncle Ben is saying ''Do you believe this _ all the way
from Hawthorne Street,`` referring to the street where Lieberman
grew up.
</P>
<P>
   The day was devoted to stressing the theme that while both men
on the Democratic ticket have spent many years in Washington they
are still rooted in mainstream America.
</P>
<P>
   However, some Tennessee critics have questioned Gore's ties to
the state. While both of his parents were born in Tennessee, Gore
was born in Washington D.C. and went to an exclusive private school
in the nation's capital while his father served as senator.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore spent every summer working on the family farm in
Carthage, a small town in the rolling hills about an hour east of
Nashville. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
