u l BC-CHILDS-ROOM-NYT &LR;      08-09 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDS-ROOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMPLE ROOM FOR PLAY, AND EVERYTHING IN ITS PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELAINE LOUIE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A child's room is a stage where children squawk like
parrots, transform themselves into Hansel and Gretel or paint,
fresh from their imaginations, a picture of a red tree on a cobalt
blue ground. The more visible the toys, the easier it is for a
child to play.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Mark and Nancy Zvonkovic asked Robin Elmslie Osler, a
Manhattan architect, to turn two maids' rooms into a bedroom-study
for their daughter Andie, then 2. Their request was basic: a bed,
built-in desk, and lots of shelves and drawers, Osler said.
</P>
<P>
   Andie most likes the lidded opening behind the headboard, which
is 14 inches deep and 24 inches wide. She transformed the space
into a theater for one. ``She would draw scenery on a piece of
paper,'' Osler said, ``hang it on top of the lid of the opening,
and do puppet shows in front.''
</P>
<P>
   Improv space is also what Liz Stern, the mother of two girls, 2
and 3, wanted when she recently asked Marco Pasanella, a Manhattan
designer, to create a playroom in their Upper West Side apartment.
She asked for what she called stations for children's play,
reminiscent of a kindergarten class, with plastic bins full of toys
on shelves, but more delightful. ``Children can see where the toys
are, take them out of the bin, and clean up after themselves,''
said Stern, who has taught kindergarten and nursery school and is
now a full-time mother and the wife of Emanuel Stern, president of
Hartz Mountain Industries, which owns the TriBeCa Grand and SoHo
Grand hotels in Manhattan. What is visible will be played with;
what is invisible will not.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be an art station with table and chairs and all the
supplies at their own level,'' Stern said. ``There will be a
computer station and a television station. There will be a cozy,
nooky kind of area and a dress-up area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want a lot of color, because the color comes out of
their own artwork. If you design a room that is too
representational or too colorful, it becomes stifling to the
imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   The room will have pale yellow or green walls and a wood floor
warmed by a cotton rug _ but it won't be empty. Pasanella will make
the 12-by-17-foot room as conducive to daydreaming as to building a
toy kingdom ruled by co-princesses. The intention is that the room
will be functional, not fanciful. ``It's condescending to make
everything look like Romper Room, meaning that everything is a
caricature, and colors are exaggerated,'' Pasanella said.
</P>
<P>
   The playroom, which will be built this fall, will provide
instant gratification. The children will be able to draw, paint and
display their art all in one space. A 4-foot-wide roll of kraft
paper will hang permanently on the wall. Not only will the children
be able to paint on the paper upright, but their mother imagines a
day when they will also paint with their feet. ``They can put it on
the floor, stick their feet in paint and walk on the paper,'' Stern
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pasanella has designed two display areas for artwork. Two large
linen-covered Homasote boards will be mounted on the wall, on
either side of the roll of paper. The bottom third of the wall is
markerboard, or porcelain on steel, so washable markers can be
wiped clean and magnets can affix art and photographs.
</P>
<P>
   The design calls for a row of pegs mounted just above the
markerboard, so the children can hang up their dresses, hats and
scarves after playing dress-up. Stern nurtures the faint hope that
if there are lots of bins and hooks and cubbies, the girls will
clean up after themselves. ``We'll see,'' Pasanella said.
</P>
<P>
   For daydreaming, moon-gazing or cuddling, the design specifies
low window seats with open storage underneath. Along with curtains,
Pasanella has called for a pull-down canvas shade, which the
children will be encouraged to paint.
</P>
<P>
   Since children like to be on the floor, the television will be
placed in the fireplace, set on andirons that have been rubberized
for safety. The mirror above the fireplace tilts down, so the
children can look up and see themselves. The fourth wall will
contain shallow shelves to hold the books, games, stuffed animals,
paints, crayons and puzzles that make up a child's world.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture? Very little. A table with bins, and a bed on casters
for sleepovers. Mostly there will be floor space. Plenty of room
for a child's imagination.
</P>
<P>
   To make a playroom enticing, Marco Pasanella, a Manhattan
interior designer, provided, among other things, lots of art
supplies and display areas. He also paid attention to safety,
coating a set of andirons with rubber before turning them into a
television stand in an unused fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   Boards for Drawing and Display: The bottom third of one wall is
unframed porcelain-over-steel markerboard. Pasanella pointed out
that the panels must be professionally installed because the edges
are razor sharp and must be covered. (Melamine, a synthetic resin,
can also be used, framed or unframed, though it may discolor over
time.) A 4-by-8-foot panel of markerboard is $471; the same size in
melamine is $104. Both from Demco, (800) 356-1200.
</P>
<P>
   Homasote bulletin boards made of recycled wastepaper are
available at many lumberyards. A 4-by-8-foot version is about $20.
Homasote can be covered in Belgian linen (about $23 for a yard 54
inches wide), from Pearl Paint, (800) 221-6845.
</P>
<P>
   Rubberizing: Prices vary, but it costs about $100 to dip a pair
of andirons. Patterson Rubber, (973) 595-6661.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft paper rolls: A 900-foot roll (4 feet wide) is about $50 at
Wolf Paper &AMP; Twine, (212) 675-4870 .
</P>
<P>
   Designer/architects: Marco Pasanella, (212) 989-5373; Robin
Elmslie Osler, (212) 989-0652.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
