<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDISON-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDUCATIONAL COMPANY SAYS TEST SCORES ROSE AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Performance on standardized tests by students attending Edison
Schools, the country's largest for-profit manager of public
schools, improved at a faster rate last year than in the previous
four years, even as the company enrolled more poor and minority
students.
</P>
<P>
   The gains mirror a national trend of rising test scores, but
Edison's results provide the company with a rebuttal to critics who
have asserted that profit-seeking school managers like Edison might
be able to increase test scores initially but would be unable to
sustain those trends.
</P>
<P>
   In a report to be released Thursday, Edison says that in the
1999-2000 academic year, the percentage of students in 40
Edison-run schools in 14 states meeting those states' achievement
standards rose to 36 percent, from 29 percent. In the previous four
years, Edison students had achieved average annual gains of six
percentage points on state tests, most of which measure performance
against an absolute state standard.
</P>
<P>
   On national tests, which generally measure students' relative
performance against a norm, Edison students performed at the 39th
percentile, up from the 34th percentile in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   While Edison's statistics provide a reliable picture of
performance of those schools, it is difficult to compare those
results to national achievement standards because the scores are
drawn from many different tests in schools in dozens of states.
Some of those tests track students from one year to the next, while
others measure the performance of students in a given grade each
year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the steady improvements have come as Edison has enrolled
growing numbers of minority and poor students, the result of a
national trend of school districts seeking private management for
their worst-performing schools. Last year, African-Americans
accounted for 55 percent of Edison's 37,500 students, up from 46
percent the previous year, while white students dropped to 18
percent of the total from 27 percent the year before.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, 65 percent of Edison's students qualified last year
for free or reduced-price lunches, a generally recognized poverty
indicator, up from 57 percent the previous year. Nationally, about
33 percent of students qualify for the programs.
</P>
<P>
   Edison's performance claims are likely to be closely scrutinized
in New York City, where Schools Chancellor Harold O. Levy has
announced a plan to turn some of the city's worst-performing
schools over to private managers start in the fall of 2001. Edison
intends to offer a proposal to manage several of the schools, said
Christopher Whittle, Edison's founder and chief executive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
