<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JANUS-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE: NO. 2 AT JANUS LEAVING MUTUAL FUND COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When executives of the phenomenally successful Janus
family of mutual funds started feuding publicly with the management
of their parent company last year, some investors feared the
dispute would drive out top talent.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Jim Craig, the No. 2 executive at Janus, said he
would leave but insisted that his resignation was unrelated to the
feud.
</P>
<P>
   Craig, who played a crucial role in building the Janus Capital
Corp. from a small money-management operation in Denver into the
fifth-biggest mutual fund company in the country, said he had
resigned to manage money for a charitable foundation that his wife
would run. Since he turned over the reins of the flagship Janus
Fund at the end of 1999, Craig, 44, had been overseeing the
company's funds as chief investment officer.
</P>
<P>
   He and other Janus officials repeatedly said on Wednesday that
his leaving should not affect management of the $308 billion in
Janus' 23 mutual funds and its institutional and private accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very confident there will be nary a ripple in the
operations at Janus,'' Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors apparently were less certain as shares of Stilwell
Financial Inc. $3.50, to $44.50. That was the biggest one-day drop
since Stilwell was formed a month ago when Kansas City Southern
Industries, the railroad company in Kansas City, Mo., spun off
Janus with three other subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Bailey, the founder and chief executive of Janus, and
other Janus managers had pressed the railroad to spin off Janus
separately. But the railroad executives rejected that idea in a
bitter battle that, at one point, led them to spell out in
financial documents how they thought they could fire Bailey. For
the most part, Craig stayed out of the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has nothing at all to do with Stilwell,'' he said in an
interview. ``That's kind of a sideshow.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, who sold most of Janus to Kansas City Southern in 1984,
remains entrenched at Janus, and a company spokeswoman said he had
no plans to leave. Craig, who was Bailey's designated successor as
chief executive, said he did not expect the company to name anybody
to take his place.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would sell his stock in Janus, which is not publicly
traded, back to the company. He declined to say how much he owned,
but one analyst estimated his stake at about 1 percent. Stilwell
owns 80 percent of Janus, Bailey owns about 12 percent and other
Janus employees own the rest.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Stilwell said the parent company had the
``utmost confidence in Tom Bailey'' and the rest of the Janus
management team. ``We believe Janus has appropriate management in
place to continue to produce returns for the shareholders of the
Janus family of funds,'' the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Guy Moszkowski, an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney, said he did
not take Craig's resignation as a sign of continuing management
turmoil at Stilwell. He continues to recommend that investors buy
the stock, whose price he said has been depressed by concerns about
Janus' concentration on aggressive growth stocks and the
``animosity and tension between Janus and the parent company.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a huge event,'' Moszkowski said. ``If Jim Craig were
departing to start his own money management shop and potentially
taking a lot of the talent and a lot of the assets with him, you'd
have a real cause for worry.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jon Zeschin, a former fund company executive who is a
consultant in Denver, said there was no way to separate Craig's
decision from the hostility created by the infighting over the
spinoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to believe that there certainly are some issues
there,'' Zeschin said. ``It seems rather abrupt.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeschin said he would have expected the managers of Janus and
Stilwell to plan a more gradual transition that would not come as
such a surprise to shareholders. The suddenness of the departure,
coming when the performance of Janus funds has cooled considerably,
inevitably will lead people to wonder, ``Is Jim Craig getting out
now because things aren't going so well?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Until the Nasdaq stock market plummeted in April, Janus funds
had been shocking the industry with their performance. Investors
took notice and flooded the company with cash, prompting the
closing of several Janus funds to new investors. To satisfy all the
demand, Janus created funds, including its first ``value'' fund,
which invests in companies its managers think are underpriced.
</P>
<P>
   The Janus Fund, which Craig managed for 13 years through the end
of 1999, has swollen to $48 billion. It had an average annual gain
of 19 percent while he ran it, but so far this year it has posted a
slim loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``The regulation of the flow of the money into the firm is the
biggest issue,'' Craig said. He said neither he nor anyone else at
Janus had second thoughts about the company's philosophy of loading
up on stocks of the companies they think will dominate the
fastest-growing industries.
</P>
<P>
   That approach made Janus one of the biggest owners of the
Finnish cellular phone maker Nokia, as well as Cisco Systems and
Sun Microsystems. Those stocks were major holdings of several of
its funds, making it difficult for investors to own more than one
Janus fund with having a heavy exposure to a handful of companies.
</P>
<P>
   Craig said he planned to use a similar investing style in
managing money for the Craig Family Foundation, though he probably
will buy stocks of companies that are too small for a giant Janus
Fund to bother with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a stock jockey and never really aspired to be the
M.B.A./C.E.O. type,'' he said. ``Essentially, I'm trading working
at Janus for going to work for my wife. I'll make the money and she
will hopefully deploy it in a way that has some impact in helping
the disadvantaged in our local community.''
</P>
</TEXT>
