u p BC-REFORMPARTY8/10-HNS &LR;      08-09 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCHANAN, PEROT SUPPORTERS SQUARE OFF AGAIN 
 

</HEADLINE>
 PARTY 8/10-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Dismissing his Reform Party opponents as
outnumbered, conservative commentator Pat Buchanan arrived here
Wednesday to claim the party's presidential nomination and
characterized the factional dispute as ``real politics in
America.''
</P>
<P>
   For a second day, Buchanan supporters squared off against
activists loyal to party founder Ross Perot, each claiming to be
the legitimate Reform Party and rightful heirs to $12.6 million in
federal money for the party's fall presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you'll see, just by ourselves, taking a look at the
energy and fire and the numbers here, this nomination belongs to
us,'' Buchanan said outside his hotel, where he was greeted by
about 200 sign-waving and chanting supporters of his third-party
bid.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about allegations that his allies ``used
storm-trooper tactics'' to wrest control of the party, Buchanan
laughed. ``That's another term for winning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, two separate conventions were taking shape, each with
its own delegates. The parallel conventions might end up nominating
different candidates, which would leave the Federal Elections
Commission or the courts to decide who can claim the Reform Party
mantle and the federal campaign money.
</P>
<P>
   One convention was controlled by Buchanan's supporters, who
secured $2.5 million in federal money to put on the three-day
gathering of party faithful. The other group was led by several
former Perot lieutenants who recruited John Hagelin, a physicist
and professor at Maharishi University, to run against Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the two factions _ Gerry Moan on Buchanan's side and
Jim Mangia on Hagelin's side _ met at breakfast, then negotiated by
telephone. By evening, they had agreed only that ``we are wrestling
for control of the party,'' Mangia said.
</P>
<P>
   When Moan and his associates arrived at the Long Beach
Convention Center at mid-morning to begin certifying delegates'
credentials, Mangia and a group of anybody-but-Buchanan supporters
had already occupied the facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't be outsmarted again,'' Moan said, vowing to sleep
inside the building to thwart squatters opposed to Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   When Moan tried to announce that his group was moving to another
room nearby, Hagelin supporters began chanting: ``Democracy!
Democracy!''
</P>
<P>
   Mangia then tried to speak and Buchanan supporters shouted: ``Go
Pat, Go! Go Pat, Go!'' Then chanted: ``We won! We won!''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Truax, a Dallas resident who founded the Reform Party in
Texas, grew red-faced and began shouting, jabbing his finger in the
face of one Buchanan supporter. ``You won nothing,'' he screamed.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Long Beach police with riot gear stood ready but did not
intervene.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the dispute later, Buchanan said, ``This is tame.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These little tiffs, these disputes will be behind us by
Sunday,'' said Buchanan, whose standing in the public opinion polls
hovers somewhere between 1 percent and 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Those opposed to Buchanan, a conservative television commentator
and former Nixon speechwriter who quit the Republican Party last
fall, say they will never stop fighting him.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's campaign claimed to control more than two-thirds of
the delegates at the convention, enough to reject a national Reform
Party primary being conducted by mail-in ballot. The voting, which
was restricted to party members, began July 5 and was to have ended
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Verney and Mangia, the Reform Party secretary, have claimed for
months that Buchanan has strong-armed his way to the nomination and
sent out party nomination ballots to ineligible voters. Buchanan's
strident brand of social conservatism, they say, betrays Perot's
founding spirit.
</P>
<P>
   After his 19-percent finish in the 1992 presidential election,
Perot _ a Dallas billionaire _ spent tens of millions of his own
money to organize the Reform Party as an alternative to the
Republican and Democratic parties that was fiscally conservative
but silent on many divisive social issues. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
