<SLUG> BC-FBC-LSU-PREVIEW0810-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Saban instilling Tigers get down to business
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. _ The interview over, Nick Saban was walking a
visitor toward the office door when he paused and turned. ``Did I
smile enough?'' Saban asked with just the slightest hint of a
smile. ``I don't know where that got started.''
</P>
<P>
   It started right here when Saban was introduced Nov. 30 as LSU's
fourth head football coach in 11 years. He'd abruptly left a 9-2
Michigan State team bound for the Citrus Bowl for a five-year, $6
million deal and the considerable task of resurrecting a program
that had floundered under Mike Archer, Curley Hallman and Gerry
DiNardo, bottoming out last fall at 3-8. Unlike Mike, Curley and
Gerry, Saban's come across so far as a no nyuk-nyuk, no-nonsense
kind of guy.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's how he's been perceived, and portrayed, by some
of the Louisiana media. They've found Saban to be all business,
affording them less access to LSU's coach and players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always harder the first time around,'' said Saban, a head
coach for one year at Toledo and five in East Lansing. ``What head
shots (photos of players and coaches) mean to me means something
different to him (LSU sports information director Michael Bonnette,
who was sitting beside Saban).''
</P>
<P>
   But then, Saban's a football coach, with an ample
NFL-and-collegiate resume. A coach with his own schedule, agenda
and way of doing things. Besides, does it matter whether Saban
wears a perpetual smiley face here? It's not a question of how much
he grins, but wins.
</P>
<P>
   And Saban expects to win. He sees no reason why LSU shouldn't be
at least a perennial Top 25 team, an SEC championship contender and
a player on the national title scene. Unlike in East Lansing,
there's no Michigan down the road in Ann Arbor here. While Michigan
State was always No. 2 to Michigan, LSU football reigns supreme in
this state.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you look at the dynamics of which college teams have a
chance to be successful,'' Saban said, ''most colleges have enough
(talented high school) players in a four-, five-hour radius.''
</P>
<P>
   Saban realized the ''tremendous potential'' at LSU when he left
East Lansing with four years left on his contract. So did the folks
who hired him at $1.2 million a year, and who've just completed an
11,600-seat expansion at storied Tiger Stadium, which includes 70
''Tiger Den'' skyboxes. That will increase capacity to 91,600,
making it the fourth-largest on-campus facility in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ''This place should be one of the most difficult places to play,
with the passion and enthusiasm we have here,'' said Saban. ''We
need to make it that way. It used to be.
</P>
<P>
   After LSU went 10-2 in 1996 and 9-3 in '97, the Tigers stumbled
to 4-7, then last year's 3-8 disaster (1-7 in the SEC). DiNardo was
fired with a game left. It was LSU's eighth losing season in the
last 11.
</P>
<P>
   While being courted for the job, Saban asked ``three or four
times, 'Why aren't you more successful?' I never really got the
answer to that question.
</P>
<P>
   Saban brought here his attacking 4-3 defensive style that worked
so well in East Lansing to LSU. He has a new, imaginative offensive
coordinator in Jimbo Fisher, good offensive talent but little depth
on either line. He inherits most of a group that suffered three
agonizing, last-minute road losses last season: One-pointers at
Georgia and Mississippi State and a 23-17 defeat at Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterback job is open between two QBs who shared it last
season: Josh Booty and Rohan Davey, who missed spring practice
after knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ''Because Rohan wasn't (practicing) in the spring, it's almost
like you're making a decision with a hand over one eye,'' Saban
said. ''It might be more than one guy. They have different styles.
If that's not a problem for your team, it can be a problem for the
other team.''
</P>
<P>
   And wouldn't that be something for Saban to smile about?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
