<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLENTY OF ROOM AT UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As recruiting season swings into full force after
the conclusion of the July evaluation period, the UCLA men's
basketball coaches are letting everyone know this: good seats are
still available.
</P>
<P>
   With at least six players _ including Dan Gadzuric, Jason Kapono
and Earl Watson _ likely gone after next season, incoming freshmen
needn't worry about parking themselves at the end of the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Fey, a 6-foot-11 center from Olympia, Wash., Monday
became the first to sign. Who's next?
</P>
<P>
   ``Starting at UCLA as a freshman looks lovely to a player,''
said Aaron Miles, a point guard from Portland's Jefferson High.
</P>
<P>
   Miles, who is 6-foot, 165 pounds, is widely considered the best
point guard in the West and would give the Bruins their first
pass-first point guard since Cameron Dollar.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins are after several of the best players in Southern
California: Lakewood Mayfair guard Josh Childress, Santa Ana Mater
Dei guard Cedric Bozeman and center Jamal Sampson, and Redondo
guard Dijon Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Bruins lose six players, they can only sign five
freshman. A new NCAA rule goes into effect this year prohibiting
schools from signing more than five players in one year or more
than eight in two years.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, the Bruins are going head-to-head with Kansas
over Miles, Bozeman and Childress. That may add to the significance
of the season-opener between the teams _ Nov. 9 at Madison Square
Garden, the second day of the November signing period.
</P>
<P>
   Childress, Bozeman and Sampson have been longtime friends and
teammates on the Southern California All-Stars. However, Childress
concedes it's unlikely all three will attend the same school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice,'' said Childress. ``But it's not a deciding
factor. As it looks now, I don't know if we'll all be going
(somewhere) together.''
</P>
<P>
   Others the Bruins are recruiting include Chuck Hayes, a 6-6
power forward from Modesto; Matt Carroll, a 6-8 inside-outside
forward from suburban Denver; Andre Patterson, a 6-7 forward who
moved to Los Angeles from Fort Wayne, Ind., last spring; and 6-8
power forward Dennis Latimore from Halstead, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Whom the Bruins sign may be determined by academics. Miles and
Childress each said they have a 3.5 GPA and have scored 1,020 and
1,110, respectively, on the SAT. But Fey does not yet have a
qualifying score on the ACT, and Thompson and Sampson have yet to
qualify for the SAT.
</P>
<P>
   SWING VOTE: The decision last week by Pacific-10 athletic
directors to try to resume the postseason basketball tournament
came when UCLA athletic director Pete Dalis reversed his vote,
giving the pro-tournament group the necessary eight votes it will
need.
</P>
<P>
   Past attempts to revive the tournament, which was discontinued
10 years ago after low attendance, had failed because of opposition
by Stanford, Arizona and UCLA _ the conference's three best
programs who would have the least to gain.
</P>
<P>
   Past proposals always have been for a 10-team tournament, which
would be played over four days. This version will have eight teams
and be played at the Staples Center over three days _ the same
amount of time as a conference trip.
</P>
<P>
   If the tournament were over four days and required a fifth day
for travel, ``they'd lose a whole week,'' Dalis said. ``Then, if
we're in the (NCAA) Tournament, they're gone the following week.
It's very impactful.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, the role of Fox Sports _ which would televise the event _
was crucial. In 1990, each Pac-10 school received $90,000. Now,
each school would earn at least three times that. In UCLA's case,
it would be enough to offset the approximately $150,000 the Bruins
will lose from playing one less nonconference game.
</P>
<P>
   The athletic directors' vote last week was merely a
recommendation to forward the proposal to the Pac-10 Council, which
will vote Oct. 3. If a simple majority favors it, the proposal will
be forwarded to school presidents for an Oct. 23 vote. Eight votes
are needed.
</P>
<P>
   If the proposal is approved, the tournament would start in
2002. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
