r f BC-VC-SFCHRON &LR;      08-09 1314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 WEB INFRASTRUCTURE FIRMS LANDING VENTURE CAPITAL  &HT;     By PETER SINTON  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Like horse-racing fans, venture-capital
investors are placing the biggest bets on entrepreneurs with known
names and proven track records.
</P>
<P>
   One of the top winners in the past quarter was Loudcloud Inc., a
company started in September by Netscape co-founder Marc Andreessen
and three other high-level ``Netscapees.'' The Sunnyvale, Calif.,
provider of Internet infrastructure services raised $120 million in
the second quarter after raising $68 million in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Venture capitalists invest in two things,'' said Ben Horowitz,
Loudcloud chief executive officer and former manager of AOL/
Netscape's e-commerce division, ``the quality of the team and the
size of the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   In Loudcloud's case, the opportunity is huge. The company
handles technology that helps new Internet firms get up and running
quickly, eliminating the need for companies to set up and maintain
their own servers and databases.
</P>
<P>
   Horowitz compares it to the early days of electricity when most
factory owners had their own generators. Eventually safer, more
reliable and expandable generation systems were developed by
independent companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're creating software power grids that companies can use to
run their online businesses,'' said Horowitz.
</P>
<P>
   Loudcloud expects to grow from 275 to a total of 500 employees
by the end of the year. Horowitz figures the most recent $120
million infusion will last ``deep into 2001'' before a likely IPO.
</P>
<P>
   Loudcloud isn't alone in landing big bucks. Despite the downturn
in many high-tech stocks since March, &LR;   &LR; venture capitalists
continue to invest aggressively in innovative startups that are
building a bigger, better infrastructure for the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Local companies were the biggest winners in the past quarter. VC
investment in Northern California companies more than doubled to
$8.8 billion in the second quarter from the like period last year,
according to the National Venture Capital Association in Arlington,
Va.
</P>
<P>
   Although this amount was a shade less than the record $8.9
billion invested in the fourth quarter of last year, it was $146
million more than what was invested in local firms in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, more Northern California companies raised money in the
April-to-June quarter than in the first three months of the year _
495 compared with 482.
</P>
<P>
   ``Venture capitalists are long-term investors, whose investment
strategies are not driven by short-term market fluctuations,'' said
NVCA research director John Taylor. ``What has changed is the shift
of interest from e-tailing and dot-coms that sell dog food over the
Internet to companies that are building infrastructure and
expanding bandwidth to move the new economy to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of VC10 (107876 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;   &UR;  &LR; Companies based in San Francisco were the biggest winners. VCs
invested in 114 startups headquartered in the city compared with 51
in San Jose, 40 in Sunnyvale, 38 in Santa Clara, 35 in Mountain
View and 28 in Redwood City.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, 1,695 companies received $24.5 billion in the second
quarter, compared with the 1,627 companies that received $24.8
billion in the previous quarter, according the NVCA.
</P>
<P>
   Although the numbers from VentureOne Corp, a San Francisco firm
that also tracks VC investments, are lower because of different
tracking methods, they paint a similar picture.
</P>
<P>
   In the past quarter, 1,054 U.S. companies received $17.2 billion
in venture financing, according to VentureOne, compared with 1,084
companies and $18.2 billion in the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In Northern California, VentureOne reports that 351 companies
raised $6.1 billion in the past quarter, compared with 361
companies that raised a record $6.6 billion in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   One reason VCs continue to invest heavily in innovative startups
is that they are loaded with cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is venture capital firms raised a record $46.1
billion for themselves last year, compared to $27.7 billion in
1998,'' said NVCA's Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   The pace of venture-capital fund raising from pension fund,
college endowment and other institutional investors has continued
this year. The NVCA's numbers don't include billions of dollars
invested in startups by the growing legions of wealthy individuals
and entrepreneurs, also called angel investors. But they do include
corporate investment funds, which have been mushrooming.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Intel Corp., Cisco Systems and scores of other companies
invested $7.4 billion in private companies in the first half of
this year, according to NVCA. That compares with $9.5 billion
during all of last year and just $1.5 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The latest numbers show Northern California lengthening its lead
as the epicenter of venture-capital investing. In the most recent
quarter, local companies received 36 percent of the total $24.6
billion tracked by NVCA. That contrasts with 33 percent of total
investments in the second quarter of last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast, which includes Boston and New York, was a distant
second in the past quarter with 377 companies receiving $5.2
billion.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of VC10 (107876 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  According to Venture One, about 86 percent of VC money, both
nationally and locally, flowed to Internet-related companies in the
past quarter. ``Rotation of capital, which began in January,
continues to move from e-tailers and content companies to
infrastructure and communications companies,'' said VentureOne
Research Director Sasha Talebi.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, 36 of the 39 companies that raised $50 million or more
in the second quarter are tied to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Brience Corp., a contraction of ``broadband experience,`` was
the biggest winner. The San Francisco company raised $200 million
to develop software that delivers wireless Web services through
cell phones, personal digital assistants, TV set-top boxes and
other devices. The company was founded by two KPMG Consulting
heavyweights, Rod McGeary, former co-CEO of the consulting firm,
and chief e-business strategist Keyur Patel.
</P>
<P>
   Comstellar Technologies, a venture-capital incubator for
communications infrastructure startups in Los Altos, raised $135
million. Company President Raj Singh founded StratusOne and
Fiberlane, the company that spawned Cerent and Siara, which were
acquired for a combined $11 billion last year. CEO Sanjiv Ahuja was
the former president of Telcordia Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some other incubators for fledgling companies, Comstellar
intends to hold onto stakes in companies it nurtures from
early-stage startup to IPO and beyond. Investors in Comstellar
include Accel Partners and New Enterprise Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Many major VC recipients in the Bay Area such as Metro-Optix,
Zaffire, Luminous Networks, LuxN and BrightLink Networks are using
optical networking technologies to overhaul the Internet
infrastructure and provide faster speed and greater capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago, demand for data bandwidth was doubling every 10
months,'' said Arun Bellary, CEO of Metro-Optix, a Santa Clara
company that received $63 million. ``Now, demand is doubling every
six months.''
</P>
<P>
   Some companies that recently landed large amounts of venture
capital are lining up to sell their shares to the public.
</P>
<P>
   For example, only a few months after raising $94 million from
VCs, Equinix of Redwood City plans to raise $200 million or more in
an IPO. The company builds high-security bunkers to handle Internet
traffic for companies and Internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   One of the winners could be Marc Andreessen, who on top of
starting Loudcloud joined Cisco Systems, Microsoft, AOL and others
as an early backer of Equinix.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; E-mail Peter Sinton at psinton(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 3 of VC10 (107876 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
