<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7254 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BOX-RUIZ0810-COX     08-09 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-RUIZ0810-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ruiz quietly plotting his chances against Holyfield
 &HT;    By Mike Tierney
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Some 1,609 days _ or about half of an eternity in
sports _ have passed since John Ruiz stepped out of his corner and
into a crushing hook to the temple from David Tua.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about your temple of doom. Nineteen seconds into the bout _
or an instant in boxing _ a prone Ruiz heard the last of the
referee's 10-count. That means he was on the canvas one tick longer
than he was upright.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've probably heard this question about 3,000 times,'' an
inquisitor began to Ruiz, who heard it a half-dozen times alone
Wednesday, ``but what happened against Tua?''
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz bit his tongue and answered politely, befitting his
accurate, although impossibly boring, nickname ``Quiet Man.'' If
not for former first baseman Bill ``Between the Legs'' Buckner,
Ruiz would be the longest-suffering athlete from greater Boston
over one faux pas.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, Ruiz evokes the horrid memory himself daily. ``It burns
in the back of my mind,'' he said. ``I got up, and I realized what
I wanted to do with my life. It got me thinking. (Without it), I
never would have changed.''
</P>
<P>
   During the ride home, Ruiz implored manager Norman Stone to set
up gym time for him the next day and to line up some nasty
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz has not failed since. Quiet Man has levitated quietly to
No. 1 contender in two heavyweight rankings. If he can eviscerate
Evander Holyfield on Saturday, his head gets fitted for a WBA crown
_ and his ears are not subjected to the Tua Question anymore.
</P>
<P>
   If Holyfield is No. 2, why is Ruiz a considerable underdog?
</P>
<P>
   Since the quickie with Tua, who likely gets a swing at WBC/IBF
champion Lennox Lewis in November, Ruiz can count only one conquest
out of those seven against a currently ranked foe. He demolished
Jerry Ballard in 1998 on a Holyfield undercard at the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz maintains that the division's luminaries have been hiding.
Lewis' refusal to fight cost him the WBA belt and left the title
unoccupied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lennox and his team should be ashamed of themselves. I was
more than ready to fight him,'' said Ruiz, who was addressed by
Lewis with a less-flattering nickname _ ``John Louise.''
</P>
<P>
   As champion, Ruiz, 28, would bring more than a new face to the
distinction. No Latino has ever ruled any alphabet group as a
heavyweight. (He is Puerto Rican.) A loner with few friends, he
became absorbed in nearly all of the traditional schoolboy sports,
even cross-country. He has been blissfully married since 17. He
spends so much time with his son, 10, and daughter, 7, that they
are scarely aware of his chosen profession. They have never
attended his bouts and witnessed just one on film.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz's devotion stems from the lingering pain over his alcoholic
father remaining in Puerto Rico when his mother moved their four
children back to Chelsea, Mass, John's birthplace. Beinvenido Ruiz
died of a heart attack three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the sad part of my life,'' the son said. ``He never got
to meet my kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what his father did for a living, Ruiz said, ``His
full-time job was his drinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz is so private that Stone, his longtime father figure, was
unaware of dad's demons until this year. It would have been a
logical conversation piece; Stone is a recovering alcoholic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mature?'' he said, noting Ruiz's priorities. ``This guy is way
ahead of his time.''
</P>
<P>
   If carousing and womanizing is no recipe for a champion, so be
it. Ruiz cannot imagine himself a middle-age fighter, such as the
37-year-old Holyfield, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do want to get out of the game a bit earlier,'' he said,
``when I can provide for my family.''
</P>
<P>
   And when is that?
</P>
<P>
   ``When I become undisputed heavyweight champ.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
