<SLUG> BC-MEDIABYTES-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUEST FOR JOURNALISTIC INTEGRITY THWARTED BY NASTY
E-MAIL  SQUABBLE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAN FOST  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It should have been a match made in heaven, but
instead it devolved into a nasty argument, with executives swapping
angry e-mails, chock full of name calling and threats.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the issue lies a question of journalistic
integrity: Line56, a slick new magazine covering B2B _ companies
providing business-to-business e-commerce services _ will
apparently pay a price for writing a negative article about
VerticalNet, one of the hottest companies in that arena.
</P>
<P>
   VerticalNet had an ad on the inside back cover of the premiere
issue of Line56 and was going to be a sponsor of two of the
magazine's conferences. But the magazine made VerticalNet the
subject of its first cover story, and when that article came out,
one thing was clear: Advertisers and sponsors don't get special
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The article questioned VerticalNet's entire business model and
ability to survive.
</P>
<P>
   And then things got ugly.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail to Mike Jefferies, the chairman and chief executive
of Line56, Donna Terp, VerticalNet's director of public relations,
wrote that ``based upon the article ... VerticalNet has decided
that sponsorship of your events is not warranted.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferies responded, saying ``The fact that your company is a
magazine advertiser (and a conference sponsor) with us does not
guarantee positive editorial.'' He said he respected VerticalNet's
decision to ``take your toys back and blow a great marketing and
visibility opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Terp wrote back that ``Line56 comes across as a cheap tabloid.''
Jefferies countered that ``If I was your CEO I'd ... be sending you
back to PR school.''
</P>
<P>
   VerticalNet's chief executive officer at the time was Mark
Walsh. (He has since stepped aside to become chairman when the firm
hired Joe Galli from Amazon.com as chief.)
</P>
<P>
   Walsh e-mailed Jefferies that his missives to Terp were
``impolite and disrespectful,'' and then _ in ``the SMALL WORLD
department'' (Walsh's caps) _ ``a large potential investor of yours
called and e-mailed me a week or two ago asking me for feedback on
what I thought of you and your magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferies, using some choice language, laughed off Walsh's
threat and countered with his own threat that he could potentially
jeopardize some of VerticalNet's funding. How do I know all of
this? Line56's public relations firm sent me the entire e-mail
string. Jefferies professed surprise at this; his PR representative
said she and company officials agreed to send it to select members
of the press after a story appeared on the Web at Inside.com.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of MEDIA10 (68536 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  In any event, Jefferies said the whole thing demonstrates
Line56's commitment to editorial integrity. (Line56 has a number of
alumni of Upside magazine, including Editor Adrian Mello; while the
business is based in Southern California, the editorial side is
based in San Francisco.)
</P>
<P>
   VerticalNet pulled its ads and sponsorships, but Walsh will
still get to speak at Line56 conferences coming up in London and
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll buy him a beer in New York, and hopefully we'll kiss and
make up,'' Jefferies said.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Walsh said he wasn't trying to cross the sacred
Chinese wall that separates a publication's business and editorial
sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy who wrote the article doesn't believe in VerticalNet,
so I don't see why we should sponsor a conference put on by that
magazine,'' Walsh said. ``Why would I write a check for $75,000 if
they don't believe in the company?''
</P>
<P>
   THE NEW TUBE: Anthony Moor has left KRON-TV for the world of the
Internet. The veteran technology reporter will be a national
correspondent for On24, a San Francisco purveyor of Webcast
financial news.
</P>
<P>
   So far, mostly print journalists have jumped to the Web. Now
that video is rising in demand, however, Moor sees himself in the
early days of a new trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all going to be going there soon,'' Moor said. ``Print
started that five years ago. Broadcast is going to start it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Moor said he'll be free of many of the shackles of local
broadcast news. His stories can run at the length they need to be,
not cut to fit a segment on a news hour. He can report on original
stories, rather than fill TV's demand to ``re-report what other
people have already reported.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Broadcast news is moving away from news gathering and into
news production,'' Moor said. ``My day was spent with logistics:
How can I find the pictures to cover this story that was in the
newspaper this morning?''
</P>
<P>
   Now he can focus on reporting, rather than trying to find good
video or pretty pictures. ``We don't do `b-roll' here,'' he said,
using television station vernacular for the background pictures
that appear on the screen while the reporter talks. ``Frankly, you
don't need it. People want to see and hear the newsmakers.''
</P>
<P>
   Moor was one of the most outspoken critics of KRON's new owner,
Young Broadcasting. Under Young, KRON will lose its affiliation
with the NBC television network, and Moor had said he wanted out of
his contract so he wouldn't have to work with an unaffiliated
station.
</P>
<P>
   But he's not talking about that now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish KRON the best,'' Moor said. ``My leaving had everything
to do with KRON and me recognizing that my interests were diverging
from traditional broadcast television. ... We reached an amicable
agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of MEDIA10 (68536 ) &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ROCK STAR: What was Jim Daly, editor in chief of Business 2.0
magazine, doing up on stage at the legendary Fillmore last week?
</P>
<P>
   Guitar in hand, Daly was jamming, as his magazine celebrated its
second anniversary with a big private party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God he can edit better than he can play,'' said one
staffer, who insisted _ understandably _ on anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   TAKE THAT: Speaking of Business 2.0, the magazine takes a
not-too-subtle jab at eCompany Now in its latest issue.
</P>
<P>
   You know eCompany: It's the magazine that Time Inc. launched to
compete with the likes of Business 2.0. Its premiere issue featured
a cover saying, ``Now the Web gets interesting,'' with a picture of
15 Internet entrepreneurs standing fully clothed in a swimming
pool.
</P>
<P>
   ECompany rankled Business 2.0 with its second and third issues,
with one bearing a cover story on General Motors' effort to
integrate the Internet into its business, and another featuring a
cover on ``What Works Now: 11 Companies That Get the Web.''
Business 2.0 had run those same stories on its cover _ in September
1998 and April 1999.
</P>
<P>
   So it's perfectly understandable that Business 2.0 headlined an
August 22 story about Octopus.com, ``Now the Browser Gets
Interesting.'' It illustrated it with a mocking picture of Octopus
executives, standing in a small plastic kiddie pool, pants rolled
up to display dark socks.
</P>
<P>
   If history is any guide, look for an eCompany story on
Octopus.com one of these months.
</P>
<P>
   QUICK DRAW MCGRAW: Terry McGraw may be the scion of an old
publishing company with lots of old-world profits, but that doesn't
mean he's not a 21st century guy.
</P>
<P>
   The CEO of McGraw-Hill Cos. _ which owns Standard and Poor's,
Business Week, and a large educational and professional book
publishing operation _ is enthusiastically taking the firm onto the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   McGraw-Hill, founded by Terry's great-grandfather in 1888, is
just the sort of company one might think fears the Internet as a
force that could cannibalize its core products.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I do think there will be some cannibalization,'' McGraw
conceded in an interview in the Bankers' Club atop the Bank of
America building in San Francisco last month. ``But if you don't
(get online), you will probably erode longer term the brand value
of your better-established product. In many ways, you don't have a
choice.''
</P>
<P>
   McGraw believes that the brand will ultimately prove dominant
online. ``In the info glut ... people are looking for reliability
and credibility,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McGraw's great-grandfather was a schoolteacher who seized on the
changes of the late 19th century by acquiring ``a small magazine
focused on electricity,'' McGraw said. ``He wanted to talk to the
business community about this new technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ironic,'' he said. ``The last 24 to 36 months have done
more to change people's thoughts, to energize, drive, excite people
in a new way. It's a similar period.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 3 of MEDIA10 (68536 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
