<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-DONATE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON FUND-RAISERS ON EVE OF CONVENTION RAISE FEAR OF UNDERMINING
GORE 
</HEADLINE>
  By DON VAN NATTA Jr. and JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore has for months been planning
the Democratic National Convention as a coming-out party for his
presidential campaign and a long-awaited opportunity to step out of
President Clinton's imposing shadow.
</P>
<P>
   But Bill and Hillary Clinton each intend to spend twice as much
time in Los Angeles as the vice president, basking in the spotlight
and raising millions of dollars for their own political projects.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the Democratic convention week, the Clintons will
have raised far more money than the vice president _ $4 million
anticipated for the first lady's New York Senate bid at a
star-studded concert Saturday night and at least $10 million for
Clinton's presidential library at a brunch that Barbra Streisand
will hold Sunday at her compound in Malibu. Each of 50 couples at
the brunch has committed at least $100,000, and some more than $1
million, to the president's library in Little Rock, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Streisand will also lend her cachet to Gore's campaign,
headlining a concert at the Shrine Auditorium next Thursday that is
expected to raise at least $2.5 million for the Democratic National
Committee. Streisand will sing three songs.
</P>
<P>
   Some Gore aides and senior Democratic fund-raisers are angry
about the Clinton-heavy convention schedule, saying they are
concerned the Clinton events will siphon off Hollywood money that
would be better spent assisting the Gore-Lieberman ticket.
</P>
<P>
   The stacked social calendar has also rankled some wealthy
Southern California Democrats, who say they have been bombarded by
invitations to fund-raisers and appeals for money. Finally, the
political ailment known as ``donor fatigue'' may have hit
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Gore's convention, but there are two tributes to
Clinton,'' said a Democratic strategist who insisted on anonymity.
``It's embarrassing for the Gores to have this huge event for the
president that will raise money for Hillary. This convention is not
about her.''
</P>
<P>
   How can it be that three people who work in the same complex and
whose careers have been intimately entwined for the past eight
years seem unable to coordinate what should be one of the most
important events of the Clinton era?
</P>
<P>
   Part of the answer may be that not only is there little
coordination between the Gore presidential campaign and Mrs.
Clinton's Senate campaign, but there is also competition between
Gore and Mrs. Clinton for money and attention, most dramatically at
the coming Democratic convention.
</P>
<P>
   And for his part, the president is trying to balance the needs
of both candidates, while burnishing his legacy and raising tens of
millions of dollars for his presidential library.
</P>
<P>
   The highly visible events spotlighting President Clinton and his
wife in Los Angeles are not only troubling to the Gore forces
because they drain money. They also put the Clintons at center
stage just as the vice president and his ticket-mate are trying to
occupy that territory and distance themselves from Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one adviser to Mrs. Clinton said Wednesday that it might
not have been a good idea for the first lady to use the Democratic
convention as a venue to raise money for her Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Several Gore allies said Wednesday that they were not worried
about the money, but they acknowledged that the symbolism would be
unmistakable: On the eve of Gore's national moment, all of
Hollywood will turn out to honor the president, not once but twice.
</P>
<P>
   Convention organizers had already faced a delicate balancing act
in deciding a role for the Clintons. It was partly addressed when
the president and first lady agreed to address the delegates at the
Staples Center on Monday, the convention's opening night.
Afterward, the president will be saluted by the Democratic party's
top donors at Paramount Studios; the Clintons will then leave Los
Angeles on Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   But the competition over fund-raising demonstrates that the
competition between the two camps is not fully resolved.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The headline event is Saturday night at a private Los Angeles
estate. More than 1,400 people will attend a salute to the
president, with the proceeds going to Mrs. Clinton's Senate
campaign. Among the performers will be Paul Anka, Michael Bolton,
Toni Braxton, Cher, Melissa Etheridge, Patti LaBelle, Brian
McKnight, Diana Ross, Mark McGrath of Sugar Ray, Stevie Wonder and
Luther Vondross. And there will be tributes on stage by Ted Danson,
Michael Douglas, Whoopi Goldberg, Goldie Hawn, Angelica Huston,
Jack Lemmon, Shirley MacLaine, Dylan McDermott, Rosa Parks, Gregory
Peck, Jimmy Smits, Mary Steenburgen, John Travolta and Red Buttons.
</P>
<P>
   The host of the Saturday night concert is Stan Lee, the comic
book publishing icon and creator of Spider-Man.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Tonken, a consultant for Stan Lee Media who recruited the
talent for Saturday's concert, played down the talk in Los Angeles
that it would overshadow Gore's own concert on Thursday night. But
he also acknowledged that Mrs. Clinton was sensitive about the
event.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Clinton's campaign office pushed very hard for me to help
get as much talent as possible for the vice president's event,''
Tonken said. ``She has been very sensitive and almost pushy for me
to help the vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Gore's event on Thursday night at the 6,000-seat Shrine
Auditorium features a concert by Streisand, as well as appearances
by Whoopi Goldberg, Baby Face, Boyz II Men and Gladys Knight.
Tickets range from $150 to $20,000. A few $1,000 tickets are still
unsold.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Saturday night tribute to the president also caused some
concern among members of the host committee, who scheduled the
media party for the same night.
</P>
<P>
   Garry South, a top political adviser to Gov. Gray Davis of
California, acknowledged that there had been competing demands for
entertainers to draw donors to Democratic fund-raisers. ``Some
competition for talent is inevitable,'' he said. ``There's been
some jostling here about the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   South said that aides to Mrs. Clinton called him several weeks
ago to propose a major soft-money fund-raiser on Saturday night
with top entertainment figures. He said he did not advise against
it _ in fact, Davis is a co-sponsor of the event _ but warned the
Clinton campaign that she would be competing with numerous other
fund-raising events during convention week.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a practical standpoint, I told them they'd have to do it
in a way that doesn't distract from other activities, including the
salute to President Clinton on Monday and the concert for Gore and
the DNC Thursday night,'' South said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get this in California all the time,'' South said. ``There
are a zillion people coming out here all year long in ongoing and
nonstop fund-raising activities.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``All three events will come off smashingly and
everybody will be happy as a clam and everybody will make a lot of
clams.''
</P>
<P>
   A supporter of the Clintons complained that the Saturday night
concert benefiting Mrs. Clinton's Senate campaign had ``spun out of
control,'' saying the organizers ``don't care about Hillary and the
president _ they are promoting themselves, and politically, this
just hurts Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   But a senior Gore adviser played down concerns about Mrs.
Clinton's fund-raiser, saying: ``We welcome the event for Hillary.
If any of our fund-raisers think we are being hurt by her events,
they are just wrong. The phones are ringing off the hook. We are
doing great.'' The adviser, who refused to be identified,
acknowledged that there had been ``grumbling'' among fund-raisers,
but added that fund-raisers often complained about the hard task of
raising money.
</P>
<P>
   And Howard Wolfson, Mrs. Clinton's spokesman, also said his
candidate was not draining resources from Gore. ``Thanks to the
very strong economy created under the Clinton-Gore administration,
there is more than enough to go around,'' Wolfson said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One generous Democratic contributor in the entertainment
business turned down an invitation to the Sunday brunch at
Streisand's home. He described the event to an aide as ``a heavy
ticket'' requiring a donation of $100,000 to $1 million in a year
when demand for political money was already intense.
</P>
<P>
   He told the aide he might consider contributing to the library
project next year or later, but felt he had done more than enough
for the party this year.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Los Angeles on Tuesday morning, the president will
travel to Michigan for an appearance with the vice president at a
symbolic passing of the torch. Gore will then depart for Los
Angeles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
