<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR WEDNESDAY, AUG. 9 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-MERRICK (moved on Wednesday, April 26) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An obituary of David Merrick sent by the New York Times News
Service on Wednesday, April 26, and three later articles, including
one on July 19 about a memorial tribute at the St. James Theater,
misstated the date of his death. It was April 25, not April 26. The
David Merrick Arts Foundation reported the error in a fax to The
Times on Friday.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BC-GORE-LIEBERMAN-NYT (moved on Tuesday, August 8)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, August 8,
about Vice President Al Gore's introduction of Senator Joseph I.
Lieberman in Nashville as the first Jewish candidate on a major
national party ticket referred incorrectly to Mr. Gore's comparison
to John F. Kennedy. Kennedy was the first Catholic elected
president; the first one nominated was Gov. Alfred E. Smith of New
York, the Democratic candidate in 1928.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BC-FRIENDS-MEDIA-NYT (moved on Saturday, August 5) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, August
5, about complaints by friends of Al Gore that he is portrayed
unfairly in news accounts gave an incorrect attribution in some
copies for song lyrics that he paraphrased when told about his
friends' defense. The words he used, ``I don't have to speak,
'cause she defends me,'' were based on lyrics by The Band, from
``Up on Cripple Creek,'' not by Three Dog Night.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BC-NY-POLICE-SAFIR-NYT (moved on Monday, August 7) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, August 7,
about Howard Safir's intention to resign as New York police
commissioner referred incorrectly to his studies at Brooklyn Law
School. He attended but did not graduate.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BC-GERMANY-WINE-NYT (moved on Tuesday, August 8) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, August 8,
about a new emphasis on dry wines in Germany for shipment to the
United States misspelled the name of an importer. He is Terry
Theise, not Thiese.  &QL;
</P>
