<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Phone Strike Drags On as Contract Talks Continue
</P>
<P>
   As Verizon Communications prepares to enter its fifth day of
bargaining with its striking unions, the question arises: Has
Verizon gotten more with this strike than it bargained for?
</P>
<P>
   As the walkout by 86,000 workers of Verizon, the nation's
largest telecommunications employer, has developed into one of the
most unruly strikes in years, doubts are growing over the company's
preparation for the contract talks and its handling of the strike.
</P>
<P>
   `Dot-Com' Merger Excites Investors
</P>
<P>
   Phone.com and Software.com, two relatively small, money-losing
software companies, announced they were merging, and investors
responded by adding $2.6 billion to their combined market values.
The ``.com'' suffix in both companies' names is somewhat
misleading, as neither does business through its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   DNA Used to Make Tiny Motors
</P>
<P>
   A team of researchers at Bell Laboratories and Oxford University
has fashioned molecular-sized motors out of the chemical that
stores the genetic code, portending a possible role for DNA beyond
biology. The development is part of an effort, still in its
infancy, to harness DNA as a structural and electronic material
that might one day be used to make ultra-tiny computers or
mechanical devices, like a robot that could cruise through the
bloodstream to repair an injury.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Broker Accused of Murder Plot
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Winkler, a former top executive for a small brokerage
company in New Jersey who is awaiting trial on charges that he
bilked investors of $100 million, was accused of hiring a fellow
prisoner to kill the judge who has kept him behind bars since
April.
</P>
<P>
   ABC to Reprimand Correspondent
</P>
<P>
   ABC News executives said they would reprimand John Stossel, the
news correspondent, for a report challenging the assumed benefits
of organic food that was based in part on evidence that did not
exist. The producer of the segment, David W. Fitzpatrick, is to be
suspended without pay for one month.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Micro Readies New Chip
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Micro Devices plans to release details of its new
64-bit processor, a chip that is intended to compete head-on with
Intel's forthcoming Itanium. Advanced Micro said it expected the
new chip to help it gain sales in the workstation and server
market.
</P>
<P>
   Barclays in Talks to Buy Lender
</P>
<P>
   Britain's third-largest bank, Barclays, said it was negotiating
to acquire Woolwich, a leading British mortgage lender, for about
5.5 billion pounds, or $8.3 billion. Barclays, which only a few
years ago was one of Britain's most troubled banks, has been on a
tear over the last year under its chief executive, Matthew Barrett,
who took the bank's top job about 10 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Carmakers to Add Stability Systems
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor said it would offer computerized stability systems as
an option on all of its sport utility vehicles and pickups by the
2005 model year to reduce the frequency of rollovers. General
Motors responded by saying that the Cadillac Escalade full-sized
sport utility vehicle will be equipped with the stability system as
standard equipment this autumn.
</P>
<P>
   Report Suggests Brazilian Recovery
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's economy grew 3.92 percent in the second quarter
compared with the period a year earlier, the government said in a
report, signaling that the recovery from a currency crisis in early
1999 was accelerating.
</P>
<P>
   Tracking Who Is Getting Richer
</P>
<P>
   The rich are getting richer, and the poor are getting poorer,
right? It will be a familiar refrain this election year. But what
if increasing inequality is mostly a myth _ an artifact of
misleading data and changing lifestyles? What if just about
everyone is getting richer?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
