<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMTRAK-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIDERSHIP INCREASES AS AMTRAK RAISES ITS HOPES
</HEADLINE>
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Amtrak's ridership in July hit a 10-year high and
the total number of passengers for the year is poised to set a
record, railroad officials said on Wednesday, crediting extensive
investments to improve reliability and service.
</P>
<P>
   But the road toward profitability is still rocky. While ticket
sales are strong, the gains in ticket revenues so far this year
make up only about half of the money lost because of delays in
introducing the high-speed Acela service, now about a year behind
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The railroad now hopes to begin phasing in the 150-mile-per-hour
Acela trains on the Washington-Boston route this fall, but has run
into technical difficulties. It is seeking millions of dollars in
damages from the manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the growth in ticket sales, revenues for the year will
be $60 million to $70 million less than anticipated, because of the
loss of $156 million in revenues from the Acela Express, the
company estimated. And some spending has been avoided, like
payments on the new trains.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak will lose money again this year, but will meet the
congressional deadline of weaning itself from operating subsidies
by the fiscal year ending Sept. 30, 2002, officials said. It
expects to need capital subsidies indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   George Warrington, Amtrak's president, said ridership was up
because service was better and because ``the marketplace is feeling
increasingly frustrated with the alternatives,'' namely jammed
highways and delayed airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   The railroad introduced a ``satisfaction guarantee'' four weeks
ago, and credits that with helping raise patronage. Ticket sales in
July were $107.2 million, 11.6 percent ahead of the same month last
year, breaking the previous record, set in June, of $102.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   People who submit claims under the guarantee get a free trip.
Some travelers say that when they initially complained about
extensive delays or other poor service, they were first offered
gift certificates that fell short of the ticket price. The railroad
says, however, that it has a ``no questions asked'' policy if a
passenger asks for the satisfaction guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak ridership statistics go back to 1975. Ridership peaked in
1990, but declined, as the number of trains and the quality of
service declined, in the 1990s, even as travel surged overall.
</P>
<P>
   Ridership rose very sharply on several long-distance trains,
including the Cascades, which runs between Vancouver, British
Columbia, and Eugene, Ore., and the Texas Eagle, which operates
between Chicago and San Antonio. The number of weekly trips was
increased on both, but ridership grew even faster.
</P>
<P>
   The reason, said William Schulz, a spokesman, is that adding
trains had created ``greater connectivity and reach,'' with more
customers riding the trains as the network grew. Railroad officials
said earlier this year that their old strategy, trimming service to
cut costs to balance the books, had resulted in too much pruning,
and a system that was withering away.
</P>
<P>
   The Acela Regional service, which has sharply cut travel times
between New York and Boston, but not by as much as the Acela
Express is supposed to, has seen a 39 percent increase in ridership
over the trains it replaced, the railroad said.
</P>
<P>
   Five high-speed Acela trains are being tested on the Northeast
corridor, and passengers going through Philadelphia can often see
them parked on sidings. But they have had a variety of mechanical
problems, including missing and broken bolts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the railroad said its basic operations are vastly
improved from the mid-90s. In those days, Warrington said, ``the
organization was on the edge of its seat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was in a very difficult position from a cash and budget
point of view,'' he said. ``The approach that was taken, which in
retrospect, was short-sighted, was to nickel-and-dime, to ratchet
back service levels, and, at a practical level, service quality.''
</P>
<P>
   The effect was ``to begin to dismantle the national system,'' he
said. ``Service degenerated, quality dropped several notches, and
loyalty erodes.''
</P>
<P>
   The railroad was founded in 1972 by the federal government,
which combined the passenger assets of several freight railroads.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
