<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7274 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-MRSCLINTON-SPEND-530&AMP;     08-09 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-SPEND-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL DEMOCRATS SEND SOFT MONEY TO NEW YORK TO AID MRS.
CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The national Democratic leadership, clearly concerned
that Hillary Rodham Clinton is facing a tough Senate race in New
York, has mounted an unusually early effort to promote her
candidacy. It has already channeled nearly $3 million into the
state _ much of it from large, unregulated contributions _ and is
girding to spend far more.
</P>
<P>
   No other Senate candidate in the country has received anywhere
near as much financial assistance from either major political
party, according to campaign finance records. The national
Republican leadership has not yet spent money on behalf of
Clinton's opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio, though it undoubtedly will do
so.
</P>
<P>
   This infusion of money into New York by the Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee over the last 18 months reflects how
rules intended to curb the role of big donations in such races have
become increasingly ineffective. Often in league with Clinton at
events in New York and around the country, the committee has raised
millions of dollars in largely unregulated contributions, known as
soft money, some of which has found its way to New York.
</P>
<P>
   The committee sent $1.2 million in June to the New York State
Democratic Committee, much of it soft money, to spend on Clinton's
behalf. The state party in turn bought more than $700,000 in
television advertising attacking Lazio on his stance on a patients'
bill of rights and prescription drug coverage for Medicare
recipients.
</P>
<P>
   The state party spent an additional $43,500 to conduct focus
groups on voters' views of Clinton, hiring a firm in Washington
state, Strategic Frameworking, that has also done extensive work
for clients in the consumer products industry, including the
National Confectioners Association and Kraft Singles processed
cheese slices.
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton is aggressively raising more of this money.
President Clinton is to join her at a fund-raiser in Manhattan on
Thursday night at the home of John Catsimatidis, the Red Apple
supermarket magnate who has been a major supporter of the Clintons.
The president, who in the twilight of his tenure continues to be a
formidable fund-raising draw, has routinely appeared at such events
for his wife.
</P>
<P>
   By relying on soft money to pay for advertising, Clinton can
conserve donations taken in by her official campaign committee. As
of June 30, the campaign committee had spent $11.7 million and had
$6.9 million in the bank. Lazio's campaign committee had spent $2.8
million and had $6.2 million on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Soft money is collected by party committees in unlimited amounts
from any donor, and technically can be spent only on so-called
party-building expenditures, like voter drives, not on candidates'
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, soft-money spending has become virtually
indistinguishable from spending by campaigns. The parties have
carved a wide loophole in the regulations, using soft money to buy
advertisements that promote or criticize candidates without
explicitly mentioning their campaigns. (Such advertisements often
end with announcers urging viewers to call the candidates.) Critics
of the rules cite this change as evidence that sizable donations
are corrupting the system.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Official campaign committees, like Clinton's, can spend money on
advertisements that explicitly seek votes. These committees can
collect a maximum of $2,000 per donor _ so-called hard money _ and
corporations and unions are barred from giving.
</P>
<P>
   Not so with soft-money committees. In June, for example, Perry
Corp., an investment fund, donated $27,000 to a soft-money
committee spearheaded by Clinton, while the American Federation of
State, County and Municipal Employees gave $25,000. Several
individuals also donated more than $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raising arms of the two parties in Congress
traditionally spend millions of dollars in tight races, but they
typically wait until the weeks before the election. Jim Jordan,
political director for the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee
in Washington, said the committee's early spending did not indicate
that it was worried about Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can certainly interpret this as a sign of faith in and
devotion to our candidate in New York, the importance of the race
to the Senate and nationally, and our determination to win it,''
Jordan said. ``This committee spends its money, we hope, as
rationally as possible, and we support winners, not losers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee is led by Sen.
Robert G. Torricelli of New Jersey, who decides in consultation
with other senators and aides how to distribute its money. An
important factor is which candidates helped to gather it, and Mrs.
Clinton has played a prominent role in the committee's
fund-raising. The president does not wield any formal control over
the committee, though he remains an influential figure in
Democratic politics.
</P>
<P>
   The Lazio campaign contended that the spending showed that
Democrats in Washington believed that they must prop up Hillary
Rodham Clinton. It said she was hypocritical for seeking a ban on
soft money even as she collected such donations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Clinton is obviously having trouble raising real hard
money from real New Yorkers,'' said Dan McLagan, a spokesman for
Lazio's campaign. ``Fortunately for her, the left-wing Hollywood
fat cats and big-money special-interests groups are apparently
tripping over each other to help buy the Senate seat for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has not established a committee to raise soft money but
has not ruled out doing so. And whether or not it is aided by
Lazio, the National Republican Senatorial Committee is expected to
spend millions in both soft and hard money in New York in the weeks
before the election.
</P>
<P>
   Both Lazio and Clinton have pledged to abide by a ban on soft
money if the opposition does so first. Yet the two camps have
continued to bicker over the terms of such a ban.
</P>
<P>
   While the national Republican leadership has not yet assisted
Lazio, other groups have. The Republican Leadership Council, an
independent centrist group based in Washington, has spent $500,000
on advertisements promoting Lazio, including one that tries to link
him to Senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan, the Democrat who is
retiring. The council plans to spend another $500,000 by Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   The state's Conservative Party has spent $60,000 on soft-money
advertisements for Lazio. Lazio also controls a political action
committee, governed by relatively lax New York laws, that has spent
$110,000 this year. On the other side, the New York affiliate of
the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League is
paying $50,000 for commercials attacking Lazio's position on
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's aides, apparently mindful that she stirs strong
emotions among conservatives around the country, say they believe
that Lazio's campaign will reap millions in contributions from
donors outside New York, and expect that outside conservative
groups will spend heavily in the state before the election.
</P>
<P>
   The Conservative Leadership Political Action Committee recently
announced that it had formed the Emergency Committee to Stop
Hillary Rodham Clinton, saying in a fund-raising letter that it was
trying to collect $9 million in the next 60 days to pay for
advertisements and mailings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 2210EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
