<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7294 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-NAACP-LIEBERMAN-TEX     08-09 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-LIEBERMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALLAS NAACP LEADER SUSPENDED, RESIGNS AFTER REMARKS ABOUT
LIEBERMAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TAWNELL D. HOBBS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The NAACP suspended Dallas branch president Lee Alcorn
on Wednesday over anti-Jewish remarks he made about Democratic vice
presidential choice Joseph Lieberman, but the outspoken Alcorn said
he has resigned and created a new civil rights group.
</P>
<P>
   Kweisi Mfume, national president and chief executive of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, ordered
the suspension. He said remarks Alcorn made Monday on radio station
KHVN/970 AM about Lieberman, who is Jewish, were ``repulsive,''
``anti-Semitic'' and ``anti-NAACP.''
</P>
<P>
   Alcorn, 53, said during the broadcast that he was ``concerned
about, you know, any kind of Jewish candidate'' and he is ``sick of
the Democratic Party taking the African-American vote for
granted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need to be very suspicious of any kind of
partnerships between the Jews at that kind of level, because we
know that their interest primarily has to do with money and these
kinds of things,'' Alcorn said during the broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   Alcorn's remarks drew criticism from near and far, ranging from
Jewish groups to NAACP members and to politicians such as Rep.
Eddie Bernice Johnson, D-Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Alcorn, who had been president of the Dallas NAACP since 1994,
said at a news conference that he had not been informed of the
suspension and instead resigned the post. He also announced the
creation of the Coalition for the Advancement of Civil Rights, an
organization created by him for people who are dissatisfied with
the NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   Alcorn said that in his remarks on the broadcast, he was
referring to Lieberman raising millions of dollars in New York. He
said he misspoke by making reference to Jews and should have made
sure his comments were directed at Lieberman, whose views he
opposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I misspoke, and I am sorry for that,'' Alcorn said. ``That was
not the best choice of words. I'm sorry if those words offended
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident is the latest of controversies surrounding Alcorn's
tenure as Dallas NAACP president. He has been suspended in the past
for picketing Mayor Ron Kirk's home, conducting an improper
election and most recently, creating a business venture that used
the NAACP name. Alcorn, who lives in Grand Prairie, founded the
Grand Prairie NAACP chapter and was its president before he ran for
president in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Alcorn said he was planning to resign from the NAACP anyway. He
cited his dissatisfaction with his many suspensions from the NAACP,
which he says are baseless, and said the NAACP has lost focus of
its mission.
</P>
<P>
   Alcorn said he has watched the NAACP sell out for years to big
corporations that contribute money to the organization. Most
recently, Alcorn said, the NAACP received $7 million for a voter
empowerment program. He said he does not know who contributed the
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no longer a focus on civil rights,'' Alcorn said.
``The focus is to raise money. I cannot work with an organization
whose center concern is money.''
</P>
<P>
   Also at the news conference, Alcorn said, ``Whether anyone wants
to admit it, the relationship between African-Americans and
American Jews has been tenuous at best for many years.''
</P>
<P>
   The national NAACP office said in a statement that Alcorn's
views are not shared in the NAACP community. Lieberman, of
Connecticut, received an ``A'' for his voting record on civil
rights issues, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are proud of our long-standing relationship with the Jewish
community, and I personally will not tolerate statements that run
counter to the history and beliefs of the NAACP in that regard,''
Mfume said. ``Joe Lieberman is a man of deep integrity who I've had
the opportunity to serve with as a member of Congress. He is a
friend and a fighter for all that is good and decent in our
society.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bledsoe, president of the Texas State Conference of the
NAACP, said, ``We feel the selection of Senator Lieberman was a
momentous occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said in a statement that she was disappointed with the
``insensitivity'' displayed by Alcorn.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a life NAACP member, I was extremely disappointed to hear
the shortsighted comments offered by Mr. Alcorn,'' Johnson said.
``We have fought too hard in this country to tolerate any kind of
insensitive rhetoric. Mr. Alcorn did not speak for the vast
majority of NAACP members nor the vast majority of
African-Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Jewish Congress, based in New York, congratulated
Mfume for his ``spontaneous and vigorous response'' to the
``blatantly anti-Semitic remarks'' of Alcorn, according to a news
release from the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take more than one bigot like Alcorn to shake the
sense of fellowship of American Jews with the NAACP and black
America,'' American Jewish Congress President Jack Rosen and
Executive Director Phil Baum said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Anti-Defamation League praised Mfume for his ``swift and
unconditional'' condemnation of Alcorn.
</P>
<P>
   And the Rev. Jesse Jackson, speaking at the White House shortly
after receiving the Presidential Medal of Freedom, said: ``I
support Lieberman being on that ticket strongly. When we live in
our faith, we live under the law. He is a firewall of exemplary
behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Alcorn's remarks indicate a coming backlash of
anti-Semitism, Jackson said: ``We're going to have more expressions
of darkness, but we're also going to have more expressions of
light. The forces of light will dispel those forces of darkness. We
will prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Fields, the first vice president of the Dallas branch,
will assume presidential duties. The national NAACP board will
appoint a panel to review the allegations against Alcorn, who may
request a full hearing. A final decision on Alcorn's suspension
might be made at the board's October meeting, NAACP officials said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the remarks, Alcorn's appointment to the Grand
Prairie Parks Board is also being questioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed in the statements he allegedly made,''
Grand Prairie Mayor Charles England said. ``I plan to talk to Lee,
and if he did say that, it creates a real credibility problem for
him serving on any board or city commission.''
</P>
<P>
   England said he has questioned Alcorn's leadership in the
African-American community since Alcorn became president of the
Dallas NAACP branch.
</P>
<P>
   ``My observation has been that every time the black community
takes a step forward, the comments he's made puts them two steps
back,'' England said. ``What he's after is noble, but the methods
he uses don't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Alcorn said he doesn't plan to resign his parks board seat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
This report contains material from The Associated Press. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
