<SLUG> BC-DEMS-NRA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NRA TO CONDEMN DEMOCRATS DURING CONVENTION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., W.Va., Ky., Tenn., Pa., Mo. and Ark.) By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The National Rifle Association said Wednesday that
it planned to run newspaper and television advertisements during
the Democratic National Convention next week attacking the party
for wanting ``to destroy the Second Amendment,'' in what the
association's leaders called an effort to divide the Democrats'
conservative and liberal wings over gun control.
</P>
<P>
   In the television spot, which is expected to begin running on
cable television news shows this weekend, the actor Charlton
Heston, who is also president of the rifle association, looks into
the camera and calls the Clinton administration ``the most anti-gun
White House in history.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From anti-gun mayors and marchers to gun-hating celebrities
and politicians, they're almost all Democrats,'' Heston says.
``Tell me: Why are so few Democrats willing to defend
constitutional freedom?''
</P>
<P>
   The NRA has made no secret of its antipathy toward Clinton and
Vice President Al Gore, vowing to throw its resources into
defeating Gore this fall. The group, which has pledged to spend
more than $15 million helping state and federal candidates this
year, has yet to endorse Gore's Republican rival, Gov. George W.
Bush. But its leaders have made clear that they think Bush's record
on gun issues in Texas is to their liking.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite the group's close ties to the Republican Party, it
has never before taken such a broad swipe at the Democratic Party,
rifle association leaders said Wednesday. Indeed, the group
maintains good relations with about 50 Democratic members of
Congress, and is spending nearly $50,000 on a reception at the
convention honoring the Democrats' conservative Blue Dog Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   But Wayne LaPierre, the NRA executive vice president, said
Wednesday that the association would be using its advertising to
hammer home the assertion that the national Democratic Party had
lost touch with its more rural, conservative wing.
</P>
<P>
   And LaPierre asserted that Gore's support for strong gun laws
would hurt him in several swing states that have many hunters and
gun owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, you're seeing a major wedge issue
splitting the national party with its base in places like Michigan,
West Virginia, Kentucky, Tennessee, Pennsylvania, Missouri and
Arkansas,'' LaPierre said. ``My guess is that their polls show they
are getting skewered in all those states.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he declined to give details on the cost of the
advertisements, LaPierre said the group was spending nearly $1
million for the television commercials, which will also run on
network morning shows, and advertisements in USA Today and The Los
Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Hattaway, a spokesman for the Gore campaign, said, ``The
ad is misleading because we support Second Amendment rights and
want to protect those rights for law-abiding gun owners and
sportsmen, while promoting common-sense policies to keep guns away
from kids and criminals.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 2238EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
