A7300 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      08-09 0295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   POLL SHOWS BUSH GAINING IN CALIFORNIA
</P>
<P>
   All year, California polls have shown Al Gore holding a
comfortable 10-point lead in a must-win state for the Democrats.
But a new survey, finished as the Republican National Convention
was ending last week, shows Gov. George W. Bush of Texas running
almost even with Gore here for the first time. The poll, by the
Public Policy Institute of California, found Gore winning 40
percent of likely voters to 37 percent for Bush, and 8 percent for
the Green Party candidate, Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
   The poll of 998 likely voters was conducted July 28 to Aug. 4,
and has a margin of sampling error of 4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS GUN FINDINGS
</P>
<P>
   The Violence Policy Center, a nonprofit group promoting gun
control, released a report Wednesday showing that 3,370 people with
licenses to carry concealed handguns in Texas had been arrested for
crimes since the state's law authorizing concealed weapons took
effect in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Center officials said the report refuted the National Rifle
Association's contentions that only law-abiding people want the
permits and that the law has reduced crime. Linda Edwards, a
spokeswoman for Gov. George W. Bush, who signed the law, said other
studies had shown that people without the permits were more likely
to commit crimes than people with permits. Edwards called the study
``partisan'' for singling out Texas. Center officials said they
picked Texas because it had compiled better statistics.
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH _ Salinas and Lodi, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   DICK CHENEY _ Pickerington, Ohio; Lawrenceburg, Ky.; Holland,
Mich.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE, JOSEPH I. LIEBERMAN _ Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
