<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7303 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      08-09 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   C.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EGYPT: DEFENDING PEACE EFFORTS
</P>
<P>
   In the first high-level response to Clinton administration
critics, Osama el-Baz, an aide to President Hosni Mubarak, gave a
spirited defense of the Egyptian role in advancing Arab-Israeli
peace. ``It is utter nonsense to think we are urging the
Palestinian negotiators to harden their positions,'' he said. ``We
have every interest to encourage a closing of the gap between the
parties.''
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: PARTY MAY BE BANNED
</P>
<P>
   The government held talks with leaders of the country's 16
states over a possible ban on the rightist National Democratic
Party, which is viewed by some politicians as a force with links to
anti-immigrant and anti-Semitic attacks. The party is too small to
be represented in Parliament. A party may be banned by the
Constitutional Court if it is deemed to be a danger to democracy,
but no such ban has been approved since the 1950s, when the
Communist Party was outlawed in West Germany.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: UNDIPLOMATIC COMMENTS
</P>
<P>
   Germany's ambassador-designate to Israel, Rudolf Dressler, faced
virulent protest after saying in a newspaper interview that he
favored the establishment of an ``international administration''
for Jerusalem. Dressler, a longtime member of the governing Social
Democratic party, is to take up his post on Sept. 1. In a
statement, he pledged not to express the views voiced in the
interview once he becomes ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: MANEUVERING FOR DISMISSALS
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit's office scheduled a meeting of
government ministers for Thursday to discuss options after
President Ahmet Necdet Sezer vetoed a decree that would have
allowed the dismissal of thousands of civil servants suspected of
involvement in separatist or Islamic fundamentalist activities. The
Ecevit government tried to make the change through a decree,
avoiding likely defeat in Parliament. But Sezer, the presiding
judge of Turkey's Constitutional Court until he was elected
president in May, said the proposed change required parliamentary
approval.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: CONSERVATIVES DEFECT
</P>
<P>
   The rightist Canadian Alliance won a major breakthrough in
Quebec, the nation's second-most populous province, with the
defection of half of the executive leadership of the Quebec
Conservative Party as well as the party presidents for 25
districts. The switch culminated a two-week stay in Quebec by
Stockwell Day, leader of the alliance, which is trying to expand
its base.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: BANNED FROM POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   The military government has issued a decree that bars anyone
from holding office in a political party who has been convicted of
a criminal offense involving moral turpitude or who has been found
guilty of violating the anti-terrorism act. The decree would seem
to prohibit former Prime Ministers Nawaz Sharif and Benazir Bhutto
from any leadership role in politics.
</P>
<P>
   IVORY COAST: GENERAL SEEKS PRESIDENCY
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Robert Guei, who seized power in a coup last year, declared
his interest in running as a candidate in the presidential election
scheduled for September. The general said he would seek the
nomination of the Democratic Party of Ivory Coast, which had held
power since independence four decades ago until the former
president, Henri Konan Bedie, was overthrown in December.
</P>
<P>
   SUDAN: U.N. COMPOUND BOMBED
</P>
<P>
   The day after the United Nations suspended aid flights in Sudan,
a government plane again bombed a United Nations compound in the
rebel-held south. On Monday, 18 bombs were dropped near the
compound at Mapel in the state of Bahl-el-Ghazal; on Wednesday
another nine bombs were dropped. No one was hurt in either
incident. But U.N. officials said the Sudanese government had
pledged late last month not to attack official aid flights.
</P>
</TEXT>
