SURPLUS DEALERS PROFIT FROM COMING CONVENTION &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE HIESTAND AND LISA VAN PROYEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sales of gas masks and other survivalist
paraphernalia have skyrocketed at Los Angeles surplus stores in
recent days as protesters, media and adventure seekers gear up for
possible unrest at next week's Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign that authorities are girding for conflict, police
officers likewise are lining up at surplus stores to buy battle
dress uniforms and other safety gear, store owners said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people think this will trigger another L.A. riot type
of thing,'' said Peter Kalaydjian, whose Recon-1 in Tarzana has
sold more than 100 gas masks so far this month, compared to about
12 in a typical month.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who say, `We're going to go down there and
face anything that's coming our way.' They want to do their
protests and they don't want to be interrupted.''
</P>
<P>
   Kalaydjian said he has refused to sell gas masks to several
people who appeared to him as ``obvious troublemakers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People are probably overreacting,'' said Los Angeles Police
Lt. Horace Frank. ``It's not that we don't have concerns -- people
saw what happened in Seattle -- but I feel very confident in the
plan we have in place to provide security for this event.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some individual officers with LAPD and other departments
aren't taking any chances, even if it means spending their own
money.
</P>
<P>
   One North Hollywood Division officer said he went shopping last
weekend to buy equipment the LAPD does not provide: soccer pads to
protect his shins, football gloves for his hands and knuckles, and
goggles to wear under his face shield.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are things I need to protect the vital parts of my body,
just in case I do get knocked to the ground, so these fools don't
take a souvenir home of a Los Angeles Police officer,'' said the
officer, who did not want to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   He's also concerned about protesters throwing acid, oil-based
paint and fecal matter on him -- all of which he said was seen
during the World Trade Organization riots in Seattle in December.
</P>
<P>
   The fear of unrest is good for business at surplus stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Police are buying the uniforms. Gas masks are going big time
to the protesters and a lot of media,'' said Dave Leva, a salesman
at Supply Sergeant in Burbank. ``They say they're going to be out
there and if things are going to get rough they want to be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Leva estimated his supply of the popular Israeli army gas masks,
which retail for $20 to $25, will be sold out before the convention
begins Monday.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 of the gas masks are on back order at Recon-1, forcing
Kalaydjian to order another 400 masks just four days before the
convention is set to start at the downtown Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Surplus stores across the San Fernando Valley report they are
doing brisk business selling black or blue battle dress uniforms to
police officers.
</P>
<P>
   The BDUs feature extra pockets and pouches and are more
comfortable and easier to wash than the standard wool uniforms that
need dry cleaning, say officers concerned that protesters may throw
bottles filled with liquids or other materials.
</P>
<P>
   But last week, Police Chief Bernard C. Parks told commanding
officers that officers working the DNC cannot wear BDUs unless they
are with the elite Metro or narcotics divisions and, even then,
only with permission from commanders, said Capt. Mark Perez of the
North Hollywood Division.
</P>
<P>
   That has left some officers fuming, especially those who bought
the BDUs as a precaution.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the standard uniforms, if people throw stuff on them,
they'll wreck the uniforms. And we're going to be soaking wet out
there (in wool) on the hot August days,'' the officer said.
</P>
<P>
   But Frank said an officer's dress must be uniform with other
officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chief does not want two to three types of uniforms out
there,'' Frank said.
</P>
