<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GUN-LAW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK GOVERNOR SIGNS STRICTEST GUN LAW IN NATION 
</HEADLINE>
  By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA 
   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GARDEN CITY, N.Y. _ At a place best known as a scene of random,
irrational violence, Gov. George Pataki of New York on Wednesday
signed into law the strictest gun controls in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki presided over an emotional ceremony at the train station
in this Long Island community, a few yards from where a gunman,
Colin Ferguson, fatally shot six people aboard a Long Island Rail
Road train almost seven years ago. Ferguson was convicted in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of gun control advocates, state legislators and people
who have lost spouses or children to gun violence cheered as Pataki
signed a bill that many of them said they never expected to see
enacted.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said of the law: ``We hope this serves as a national
model. We hope other states follow.''
</P>
<P>
   When the year began, all indications were that Albany's
years-long stalemate over gun control would remain intact.
Downstate lawmakers in both parties were nearly unanimous in
favoring tougher restrictions, but they were consistently blocked
by upstate Republicans in the state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But Pataki, a Republican, seized on the public sentiment created
by a series of school shootings, proposed a package of controls and
helped pressure the upstate senators into allowing the measure to
come to a vote.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association has criticized elements of law as
infringing on the rights of gun owners, while the firearms industry
has dismissed it as meaningless posturing that will have no real
effect on violence.
</P>
<P>
   The law encompasses several measures, most of which have been
tried in a few other states, though no other state has as broad a
combination of restrictions. Most of the measures go into effect
Nov. 1:
</P>
<P>
   _ All new handguns will be required to be test-fired before they
are sold, so that the telltale markings they leave on bullets and
shell casings can be entered into a state computer database. New
York is the second state to enact such a ``ballistic
fingerprinting'' provision, a few days after Maryland. It goes into
effect on March 1.
</P>
<P>
   _ Assault weapons and large-capacity ammunition clips will be
banned, mirroring the ban put into federal law in 1994. Local law
enforcement officials have long complained that they needed a state
law that would apply in state courts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Background checks will be mandated for handgun buyers at gun
shows. The federal background check requirement applies only to
federally licensed gun dealers, but most sales at gun shows are
made by private citizens. The provision goes into effect
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   _ All new guns sold will be required to have trigger locks.
</P>
<P>
   _ The legal age for getting a handgun permit and buying a
handgun will rise to 21 from 18.
</P>
<P>
   _ A new crime of criminal purchase of a weapon will be created
for instances when someone buys a gun illegally or buys one for
someone else who cannot legally buy one.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gun owners will be required to report lost or stolen guns to
the police.
</P>
<P>
   _ A state police study of the sources of illegal guns in New
York state will be mandated. Most of the guns are first bought in
other states.
</P>
<P>
   _ The state police will be instructed to study ``smart gun''
technology that would allow a gun to be fired only by its legal
owner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 2245EDT &QL; 
