r e BC-TV-BABY-SFCHRON &LR;      08-09 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BABY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS HOPING THAT A STAR IS BORN 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We know CBS wants to get younger, but this is extreme.
</P>
<P>
   The network has commissioned a pilot from its corporate cousin,
Viacom Productions, based on the TV commercial character ``Baby
Bob.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby Bob'' is the talking pitchbaby in spots for
freeinternet.com, an Internet service provider based in suburban
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The baby's voice in the commercial campaign, which began in
February, belongs to actor Ken Campbell. He might be remembered,
but probably won't, for his role in the early 1990s Fox sitcom
``Herman's Head.''
</P>
<P>
   The baby's real name is Hunter. It's quite a performance because
``he'' is actually a she. The moving lips are special effects.
</P>
<P>
   CBS figures a baby with an adult sensibility and a gruff voice
might be an amusing central character in a prime-time sitcom. Hugh
Wilson, who created ``WKRP in Cincinnati'' and ``Frank's Place,''
has signed on to develop the prospective series.
</P>
<P>
   Viacom spokeswoman Wendy Luckenbill said no one seems to be sure
whether this is the first time a commercia character was so close
to crossing over into stardom on a prime-time network series.
</P>
<P>
   Not Mr. Whipple, of two generations of Charmin commercials. Or
Clara (``Where's the beef?'') Peller of Wendy's burger fame. Not
the lonely Maytag repairman played by Jesse White and later by
Gordon Jump.
</P>
<P>
   David Leisure's persona as Joe Isuzu was transferred largely
intact to his role in ``Empty Nest,'' but the character wasn't
identical.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Varney's Ernest P. Worrell character made the conversion
from loudmouthed pitchman for dairy products, pizza and car
dealerships to theatrical films, but not to a TV series.
</P>
<P>
   It has worked the other way around, with a character from a TV
show pitching products in commercials. One famous case in point:
Ernestine, Lily Tomlin's snorting telephone operator from
``Laugh-In.'' Another: Max Headroom (Matt Frewer), pushing
Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   If the commercials-to-series route has been taken before, I'll
soon hear about it from a reader with a sharper memory than mine.
I'll let you know.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Baby Bob'' pilot is due to be filmed in November. The
show, if there is one, could reach the air in midseason.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
-0- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   So ABC News has apologized for a February 4 ``20/20'' story in
which its star scold, John Stossel, reported that laboratory tests
showed regular supermarket food was as free of pesticides as
organically grown food.
</P>
<P>
   Under heat from an environmental watchdog group, ABC admitted
this week that no such pesticide tests had been conducted for
``20/20.''
</P>
<P>
   Stossel had compounded the error when the report was repeated on
the July 7 edition of ``20/20,'' with Stossel insisting that ``in
our tests, we found (no pesticide residue) on either organic or
regular produce.''
</P>
<P>
   This was months after the Washington-based Environmental Working
Group complained to ABC that claims of tests had been faked in the
original report.
</P>
<P>
   The curious invention of lab tests _ ABC says it's investigating
how it happened _ could prove fatal to Stossel's career as a
contrarian debunker on ``20/20'' and on his series of ABC specials.
</P>
<P>
   It's Stossel's bad luck that the ABC apology coincided with an
article by Jane Mayer in the August 14 edition of the New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   Mayer takes David Westin, the nonjournalist president of ABC
News, to task for a series of journalistic lapses, including
allowing actor Leonardo DiCaprio to interview President Clinton for
ABC News in March.
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Working Group, which also has offices in
Oakland, wanted Westin to fire Stossel.
</P>
<P>
   Westin stopped short of that Wednesday. According to an
Associated Press report, ABC reprimanded Stossel and suspended his
producer, David Fitzpatrick, for 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
