<HEADLINE>
FOR VAN ROOST, A TOUGH WAY TO GO (OUT) 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN BEACH, Calif. _ Two shots landing over the line sent
Dominique Van Roost over the edge Wednesday in the second round of
the estyle.com Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Van Roost stormed off the court at Manhattan Country Club after
dropping two crucial, controversial points in the third set of her
match against eighth-seeded Sandrine Testud of France.
</P>
<P>
   Van Roost, of Belgium, battled back from a first-set defeat and
needed only to hold serve in order to send the match to a third-set
tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   Down 30-15, Van Roost hit a forehand to the baseline that was
called in by the linesperson, but she was overruled by chair umpire
Leanne White. Van Roost then double-faulted on match point, when
White again interjected and ruled the ball long. Testud won, 6-2,
3-6, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough for the umpire to overrule the last two points of
the match,'' said Testud, who agreed with both calls. ``I can
understand why she was upset.''
</P>
<P>
   FEUDING FRENCH: Testud didn't shy away from the controversy
regarding countrywoman Nathalie Tauziat, who is attempting to earn
a spot on France's Olympic team by appealing to the International
Tennis Federation.
</P>
<P>
   Tauziat offended many players on the circuit with comments in a
book she authored about life as a professional tennis player and
believes that her frankness in the book cost her a spot in the
Olympics. In the book, Tauziat accused Testud of faking injuries to
avoid playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she deserves not to be on the team,'' Testud said.
``She said bad things about different players, and now I think she
deserves what is happening to her.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE TO COME: Conchita Martinez got a preview of her
quarterfinal match against Serena Williams when she defeated
Alexandra Stevenson on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Williams and Stevenson routinely bomb serves faster than 100
mph. Such firepower can make life difficult for a player such as
Martinez, who relies on smart, tactical play rather than raw power
to be successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you face a hard server, you always have to be ready,''
said Martinez, the tournament's No.4 seed. ``It's hard to get into
a rhythm against players like them.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
