<SLUG> BC-EDIT-REFORM-BUCHANAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE BUCHANAN COUP ATTEMPT 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Aug. 10:
</P>
<P>
   Eight years after the establishment of the Reform Party by Ross
Perot, the party's machinery has apparently been seized _ or
disabled _ by Patrick Buchanan, longtime prophet of the Republican
right. As a presidential candidate, Buchanan has little to offer
the American public except the politics of resentment. But if he
gets the Reform Party's presidential nomination this week, his
tirades against free trade, affirmative action and abortion may
draw votes away from Gov. George W. Bush, unless they help Bush by
making him seem more moderate. In any case, it is enough to make
one nostalgic for Perot, the eccentric Texas billionaire who
founded the party.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Perot's comical behavior, the Reform Party has drawn
support from a wide range of well-intentioned Americans who wanted
to elevate the tone of politics. For them it is especially
unfortunate that Buchanan's takeover attempts have been less about
issues than about getting his hands on the more than $12 million in
federal funds due the party because of Perot's past showings on the
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday the party opens its convention in Long Beach,
Calif., where Buchanan says he expects to be nominated after
working hard all year to take over the party organization state by
state. Anti-Buchanan members are charging fraud, and contend that
if they cannot stop his selection at the convention they will break
off and form a separate Reform Party with its own nominee. A court
battle over who gets the $12 million is considered likely.
</P>
<P>
   The high-water mark of Perot's candidacy occurred in the spring
of 1992, when it seemed plausible that he could actually beat
President George Bush and the Democratic challenger, Gov. Bill
Clinton of Arkansas. But Perot's odd tactical reversals _ dropping
out of the race suddenly and, just as suddenly, jumping back in _
and his paranoid-sounding charges of conspiracies against him and
his family did him in. Nevertheless, he brought a certain
truth-telling to the 1992 campaign, warning of the dangers of
federal deficits, the power of special interests and what he said
was declining American competitiveness abroad. In his 1996 race he
was far less credible as a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The only policy that Buchanan has picked up from the old Perot
campaign is opposition to trade agreements. His moralizing and
demands for anti-abortion laws run counter to the libertarian
streak of many Reform Party members, including Gov. Jesse Ventura
of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   When Buchanan walked out of the Republican Party last fall, Gov.
Bush lamented his loss to the GOP. In fact, the party was fortunate
to be rid of his nasty brand of nativism and his divisive rants
about cultural war and the ``Israeli lobby.'' In these generally
prosperous economic times, it is fair enough for Buchanan to try to
call attention to the problems of those not benefiting from the
boom. But it is doubtful that his flame-throwing attacks on his
ever-changing list of foreign and domestic enemies will elevate the
race this year. The Reform Party would do better to nominate a
candidate appealing to idealism rather than the paranoid fringe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
