<SLUG> BC-NY-JUDGE-THREAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY MAN IS CHARGED WITH PLOTTING TO KILL JUDGE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Fla.) By DEAN E. MURPHY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A New Jersey man awaiting trial on charges that he
was involved in a scheme that bilked investors of $100 million was
indicted yesterday on charges that he conspired to murder the
Manhattan judge who has kept him behind bars since April.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Stuart Winkler, 47, of Morganville, N.J., was charged
with hiring a fellow prisoner to kill Justice Leslie Crocker Snyder
of state Supreme Court in Manhattan. The judge has been handling a
vast securities fraud case involving A.S. Goldmen, a Florida-based
firm now out of business, since Winkler, who was its chief
financial officer, and 32 others associated with the firm were
indicted last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Winkler wanted the judge dead in the hope of
having his case assigned to a more lenient jurist. Winkler was
apparently angry that Snyder had increased his bail to $1 million
in cash after he took a vacation in the Cayman Islands with his
family over the Christmas holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, when he was indicted in the securities fraud case,
Winkler had been required to post a $1 million bond, which he
secured with a 10 percent cash payment to a bail agent.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is some dispute whether the Christmas trip
violated Winkler's bail agreement, prosecutors complained to the
judge, and the bail agent withdrew the $1 million bond. Snyder then
insisted on a full cash payment, which Winkler was unable to raise.
He was sent to the Manhattan Detention Complex on April 11.
</P>
<P>
   According to a transcript of taped conversations in the jail,
Winkler tried to hire another prisoner to kill the judge, telling
him: ``Do it. It's a done deal. Don't worry about it. Just don't
get caught.'' The other inmate was cooperating with the authorities
and secretly taped Winkler.
</P>
<P>
   Excerpts from the transcript were read in court Wednesday by
Daniel McGillycuddy, an assistant district attorney, during
Winkler's arraignment. In a brief appearance before Justice Arlene
D. Goldberg, Winkler, looking tired and subdued, pleaded not guilty
to charges of conspiracy and criminal solicitation.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors described the tapes, made during June and July, as
``rock solid'' evidence against Winkler, who they said believed
until a few days ago that his plan was moving forward. Winkler now
faces up to 32 years in jail on the new charges. The prosecutors
declined to release any information about the wired inmate, who was
about to be released at the time of his contacts with Winkler. But
Jack Litman, Winkler's lawyer, described the man as ``an inmate
trying to work his way out of something'' by suggesting the murder
plan.
</P>
<P>
   The defense lawyer suggested that there were other excerpts from
the tapes that pointed to Winkler's innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder, who has heard some of the city's toughest drug and gang
cases, including the so-called Wild Cowboys cases in the mid-1990s,
was never in danger, the authorities said, but her already heavy
security detail is nonetheless under review. The indictment says
that Winkler provided the other inmate with details about courtroom
security and the judge's summer vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are working very closely with the Police Department to
ensure Judge Snyder's safety,'' said Daniel J. Castleman, the chief
of investigations for the district attorney's office. ``There have
been a number of cases over the past years where we had information
that she had been threatened.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge would not speak to a reporter, but David Bookstaver, a
spokesman for the Office of Court Administration, said the
indictment reflected ``the ugly side'' of law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, this is not something that is new to Judge
Snyder, and it will certainly not deter her from doing her job in
the future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bookstaver said it was likely that Snyder would not hear the
stock-fraud case against Winkler, because the district attorney's
office was expected to request that it be separated from the rest
of the Goldmen case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
