<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOTEL-DISCRIM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHIONABLE HOTEL SETTLES WITH 9 BELLHOPS IN BIAS CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  By BARBARA WHITAKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Nine bellhops _ all but one of them members of
minorities _ who were fired from the trendy Mondrian hotel on the
Sunset Strip in 1996 and replaced by whites will be paid $120,000
each under a settlement announced Wednesday by the Equal Employment
Opportunity Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The commission had filed suit under the Civil Rights Act of
1964, charging that the Mondrian's owner, Ian Schrager Hotels Inc.,
engaged in discriminatory recruitment practices against Hispanic,
black and Asian job applicants.
</P>
<P>
   Schrager, chairman and chief executive of the company, is
perhaps best known as a co-owner of Studio 54 in New York. He also
owns a number of fashionable hotels, including Morgans, Royalton
and Paramount in New York, Sanderson and St. Martins Lane in
London, and Delano in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than relying on typical hiring methods, the Schrager
company is known for using a casting approach to filling hotel
staff jobs, including the placement of advertisements in trade
publications like Variety. The complaint brought by the employment
opportunity commission noted that the advertisements sought out
applicants who were ``high-energy, upbeat, handsome/pretty with
cool-looking individual style.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The message,'' Peter Laura, a senior commission attorney in
Los Angeles, said of the settlement, ``is if you're going to create
this hip, cool staff and image, it should include minorities. Hip
and cool is not just white.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura said the commission's investigation into the case had led
among other things to a memo in which Schrager wrote that the
busboys at the Mondrian were ``too ethnic.''
</P>
<P>
   Schrager said through spokesmen Wednesday that he had no comment
beyond a statement issued by the hotel's general manager, David
Weidlich.
</P>
<P>
   In that statement, Weidlich portrayed the firings as an
unintentional consequence of a bustle that had followed Schrager's
purchase of the long-bankrupt hotel in 1995 and a subsequent
nine-month renovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel badly that these former employees were lost in the
chaos of the reopening,'' the statement said, ``and that their
discharge may not have been handled as sensitively as it could have
been.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed for details, the company had no further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Of the nine men dismissed, three were Filipino, two were Latino,
two were Cambodian, one was African-American and one was white.
They had all worked at the hotel for minimum wage plus tips, eight
of them for at least seven years. The $120,000 that each receives
will be paid over three years.
</P>
<P>
   One of the nine, Ben Ison, a Filipino who had worked at the
hotel for seven years, said that while he was pleased with the
financial arrangement, the real goal had been to call attention to
unfair hiring practices at the Mondrian, in hopes of protecting
other workers. He said he thought this goal had been achieved.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Another fired bellhop, Rich Brand, an aspiring actor, said he
had been blindsided by the dismissal, having worked through the
hotel's renovation, when tips were down along with occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were told to stay because things would be getting better,''
he said. Then, just a few weeks before Christmas, came the firings.
</P>
<P>
   Brand said he hoped the settlement would send a message to
employers. ``Someone like Ian Schrager is pretty well known,'' he
said. ``Hopefully, people will pay attention to what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Mulligan, a commission lawyer who worked the case, said
all the men were good employees who had done nothing wrong. The
root of the problem, she said, was that the hiring was done by
managers who were all white and had total discretion.
</P>
<P>
   Ida L. Castro, the commission's chairwoman, said, ``This
settlement should remind employers in California and nationwide
that employees and applicants must be judged strictly by their
ability to do the job, rather than on nonjob-related criteria such
as their race or national origin _ as in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Weidlich, the Mondrian's general manager, noted in his statement
that the manager who ran the hotel at the time of the firings was
no longer there, and cited steps taken to ensure that ``this type
of thing cannot happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Those steps include adding a human resources director to oversee
hiring and firing and help the hotel comply with fair employment
programs. Laura, of the EEOC, said the settlement required the
hotel to report regularly to the commission on those practices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
