</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-HOMETOWN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN'S HOMETOWN SHOWS PRIDE
</HEADLINE>
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. _ The committee planning the 40th reunion in
mid-November of the Stamford High School class of 1960 did not get
much done at its meeting on Tuesday night. Its members were far too
distracted by the thought that their classmate, Sen. Joseph I.
Lieberman, might become the next vice president of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still need to have quite a few more meetings, because all
we were talking about was Joe last night,'' said Vita Lionetti, who
introduced Lieberman at a Democratic campaign rally here on
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   This once-quaint small city is now a bustling corporate mecca,
but Joe Lieberman is still wearing the same smile he did at
graduation in 1960, friends say. And, as he returned on Wednesday,
riding triumphantly in Vice President Al Gore's motorcade, all of
Stamford seemed to swell with pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a momentous occasion,'' exulted Mayor Dannel P. Malloy, a
Democrat. ``It's an exciting time for Stamford.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of the opening speeches at Wednesday's rally, Malloy
proclaimed, ``There are 111,000 people in Stamford and there's
111,000 stories about Joe Lieberman, what a great guy he is.''
</P>
<P>
   That Lieberman is the first Jewish American to run on a national
ticket for a major party will forever be a historical footnote. And
the footnote to that, Stamford residents noted proudly, will be
that he was born here, on Feb. 24, 1942.
</P>
<P>
   The banner headline in Wednesday morning's issue of The
Advocate, the local newspaper, was simply: ``He's Coming Home.''
And although Wednesday's rally was by invitation only, people with
tickets started lining up at 3 p.m., four hours before Lieberman
and Gore were expected to arrive at the Italian Center, a
recreation complex and catering hall.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign had hoped to hold Wednesday's rally at
Stamford High School, where Lieberman began his political career by
running for president of his ninth-grade class. But the building on
Strawberry Hill Avenue was not available because of summertime
construction and renovation projects.
</P>
<P>
   Lionetti recalled in an interview that she had been elected prom
queen and that her husband, Alexander, had lost the contest for
prom king by one vote to _ who else? _ Joe Lieberman. ``He was a
winner from then on,'' she said. ``Not one thing has changed,
except his success.''
</P>
<P>
   Stamford ``will always be home to him,'' she said. ``This is
where his roots are and no matter where Joe is, no matter where he
goes, he has a following. We are so proud. We are really so, so
proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the afternoon, people stopped to stare at a crowd of
photographers and television cameramen gathered across Strawberry
Hill Court from the home of Lieberman's mother, Marcia. The
candidates visited there briefly before joining the 1,000 exuberant
supporters at the rally, which included many of Connecticut's
elected Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd there roared gleefully when Gore introduced Lieberman
as a ``son of Stamford'' and ``the next vice president of the
United States.'' To chants of ``Joe, Joe, Joe,'' Lieberman, who now
lives in New Haven, took the lectern and became teary-eyed in
describing his emotions. ``It, of course, has always been good to
come home,'' he said. ``But never have I felt more grateful and
more proud.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled standing in the same ballroom at the Italian Center
for testimonial dinners and for previous high school reunions. And,
he added, ``What a thrill to come home on Air Force Two to Stamford
with my mom.'' He thanked Stamford for his public school education
and said that it was mishaps on the town's Little League fields as
a child that led him to a career in politics.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic candidates flew north to Stamford after visiting
Gore's hometown, Carthage, Tenn., earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Lenora Cavaliero, another member of Lieberman's high school
class, said she was flabbergasted that history was being made so
close to home. ``Just that somebody from your own town, as it was
then, could build up and do something like this,'' she said. ``I
guess it goes to prove that when you are that determined and have
faith and believe in yourself, it really can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, in his speech, made very much the same point,
describing his father, who worked in a bakery and later owned a
liquor store in Stamford, and his grandmother, who was an immigrant
from Central Europe, both of whom he said reveled in America's
basic freedoms. ``Anybody should be able to succeed here,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
