<SLUG> BC-BUSH-TOUR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH CAMPAIGNS BY TRAIN   INTO CENTRAL CALIFORNIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KRYSTN SHRIEVE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OXNARD, Calif. _ When her boss failed to show up for work
Wednesday, migrant farm worker Maria Luisa Lopez canceled her plans
to pick corn and headed to the Oxnard train station to cheer for
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez joined an estimated 6,000 people from Ventura County and
the San Fernando Valley who donned red, white and blue garb to send
the Republican presidential nominee off on his whistle-stop tour of
Central California.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's being supportive of the Mexican people,'' said Lopez, 39,
as she stood on the outskirts of the crowd, holding a sign for
Bush. ``We're hoping he will support the Latino community and help
diminish prejudice, and we hope he'll recognize the way the
Mexicans in the fields have contributed to the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Oxnard resident Betty Moore broke out a red, white and blue
sequined vest for the occasion. A jeweled GOP pin and buttons
reading ``Bush Posse 1992'' and ``George Bush 88'' decorated her
straw hat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had to come and be part of the festivities,'' the
former president of the Oxnard Republican Women Federated said as
she handed out Bush-Cheney stickers. ``This is the first time any
presidential candidate has ever been to Oxnard. I think Bush just
wants people to know that he represents everyone everywhere -- even
those of us in little towns.''
</P>
<P>
   The day was filled with the sounds of mariachi bands and
children singing patriotic songs. Members of the Oxnard Boys &AMP;
Girls Club sold popcorn, soda and hot dogs, residents scribbled
last-minute slogans on poster board and college interns manned
voter registration booths.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will never forget this,'' said 18-year-old Jennifer
Eastlake, who is interning for Assemblyman Tony Strickland,
R-Camarillo. ``It's great to see all the patriotism and hear
everyone in the background cheering for democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Republicans were in the majority, Democrats made sure
their voices were heard. While Republicans chanted, ``We want
Bush!'' Democrats countered with ``Viva Gore!''
</P>
<P>
   Diana Martinez, a Santa Paula native who works as a counselor at
an elementary school in Sacramento, held a sign that said ``Crees
que estamos estupidos? (Do you believe we're stupid?) Prop. 187: We
will not forget!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pro-child, pro-family, pro-worker and that's why I'm
against Bush,'' Martinez said. ``Republicans are just worried about
making the rich richer and the working class poorer, and I don't
think Bush will be any different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like my sign says, we're not stupid,'' Martinez said. ``We
know what the voting record is and that speaks for itself. As far
as I'm concerned, he can come back here when the voting record
changes.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd erupted in cheers when Bush's train pulled into the
station. White doves took flight as the train came to a halt, and
people swarmed the tracks to catch a glimpse of the Texas governor
as he addressed the group from the back of the train.
</P>
<P>
   ``My intentions are not just to come here a lot because
California's a pretty place,'' Bush told the crowd. ``We intend to
come here a lot because we intend to carry California in November.
This state is the biggest, most powerful state in the Union, and
come November -- you mark my words -- California will be in the
Bush-Cheney column.''
</P>
<P>
   Oxnard resident Elizabeth Castleman was covered with streamers
when she emerged from the throng.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was so inspiring,'' Castleman marveled. ``My hair is
still standing up on end because I'm so excited. I don't even think
of him as a candidate anymore -- but as the next president.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
