<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7461 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-ART-1STLD-WRITET     08-09 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A JOINT TRIP WITH A VOW TO TRAVEL NO LOW ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 12th graf to change reference from Representative Gore to
Senator Gore) (ART ADV: Photos _ NYT1,2 _ are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. _ Vice President Al Gore and his new Democratic
running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman, introduced each other to the
folks back home on Wednesday in a pair of appearances that sought
to ground two men with disparate stories in the common embrace of
family and community.
</P>
<P>
   The day began in Carthage, Tenn., the picturesque town on the
Cumberland plateau that served as one of Gore's two boyhood homes,
the other being Washington, D.C. Gore and his wife, Tipper, gave
Lieberman and his family a tour of the house they have owned in
Carthage since 1973 and then dropped by the farm where he spent his
childhood summers and where his 87-year-old mother, Pauline, still
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as campaign cameras recorded the scene for possible use in
television advertisements, longtime friends and constituents sang
Gore's praises during a scripted gathering in an elementary school
gymnasium. On Wednesday afternoon, the Gores and Liebermans flew
here to Stamford, where Lieberman returned the favor by joining the
Gores at a raucous rally with local supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a thrill to come home to Stamform on Air Force II,''
Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   In Carthage, Gore vowed that he and Lieberman would not level
personal attacks against Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican
nominee, and his running mate, Dick Cheney. ``I will not say a
single unkind word about Gov. Bush or Dick Cheney,'' Gore said,
affecting his twangiest drawl.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how Gore will define ``unkind word'' remains to be seen,
and his pledge was greeted with skepticism by Bush's aides. They
noted that Gore has used loaded terms like ``reckless,'' ``risky,''
``irresponsible,'' ``smug'' and ``arrogant'' to describe Bush's
policies. And indeed, only seconds before making his pledge, Gore
referred to the Republican ticket as ``the old guard.''
</P>
<P>
   In a conversation with reporters aboard Air Force II en route to
Connecticut, Gore said he had ``never made a personal attack
against Governor Bush.'' He then said he had once ``slipped'' when,
in May, he called Bush's Social Security proposals arrogant.
</P>
<P>
   Gore made a similar pledge in the primaries, saying he would not
make any negative personal attacks against his Democratic opponent,
former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey. However, Gore proved quite
skillful at casting Bradley in derogatory terms without calling him
names, although he did call him a ``quitter'' for leaving the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for Bush, said that ``if the vice
president meant what he said, it would be a breakthrough
encouraging development.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, 52, was born in Washington, where his father served in the
House and Senate, and he attended all but a portion of one year of
his schooling there. But he spent his summers on his parents' farm
in Carthage and he has returned there to kick off his campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The event in Carthage on Wednesday was so prepackaged that,
hours beforehand, Gore aides handed out biographies of the
townspeople who Gore called on to speak. Many told stories of
medical problems _ a child with cancer, a kidney transplant _ and
paid tribute to Gore for riding to the rescue with helpful
legislation during his 16 years in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   One man, Mark Thompson, of Cleveland, Tenn., told of riding his
bicycle as a boy to deliver a letter to then Senator Gore seeking
help in securing Social Security benefits for his grandmother. And
as Thompson credited Gore for fixing the problem, he incorporated
the campaign's theme of the week _ ``going the distance for
America's working families.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Vice President, in 1989 you went the distance for my
family,'' he said. ``And I know in November when you're elected
president of the United States you're going to go the distance for
families all across this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore responded, ``We need to get you to come on the campaign
trail,'' as if that were not exactly where Thompson was on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The only comment that was off script on Wednesday came from
Laura Lester, a 55-year-old retired teacher who asked Lieberman
about his support for school vouchers. Lieberman supports pilot
programs that would provide federal funds to the parents of poor
children to pay for tuition at private schools, one of several
areas where he disagrees with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Lieberman used the question to blunt Bush campaign
attacks about their differences on various issues, as they have in
several interviews in the last 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' Lieberman said, ``the folks on the other side are
trying to point out the differences between Al and me and, believe
me, the differences are very, very few.'' Lieberman said the two
candidates did have some differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one,'' he said of vouchers. ``And I think it's a mark
of the strength of leadership of this man that he didn't choose
somebody who agreed with him on every single issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said he would occasionally offer dissenting advice to
Gore but would ``support him wholeheartedly'' once a decision was
made. Then Gore jumped in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not afraid to have a vice president who disagrees with me
on some issues,'' he said. ``I think that's fine. Our
administration will be opposed to private school vouchers. I'm
against them. I think they drain money away from public schools.
But I'll tell you this.'' I think it is a strength and not a
weakness, an asset and not a liability to be able to have a
different point of view represented in the room at the time that
decisions are being made.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gore and Lieberman addressed another issue where they differ,
parental consent and notification for minors seeking abortions, in
a morning television interview.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, who supports abortion rights, said on NBC's Today
that he would support legislation giving parents the right to be
notified about or to consent to a minor child's abortion, but only
if it contained provisions allowing the child to seek permission
from a judge ``when it can't be worked out in the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who also supports abortion rights, has always opposed
parental consent legislation, aides said, but he said on Air Force
II that he had expressed ``a willingness to look at proposals''
that do not impinge on a woman's right to choose. Gore aides later
said Gore was only talking about parental notification, not
parental consent, and that he had never seen a notification bill
with adequate protections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 2316EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
