u s BC-BBA-YANKS-OAKLAND-NYT     08-09 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-OAKLAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETTITTE CARRIES ON WITHOUT STOTTLEMYRE
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The faces they present for the outside world are
similar. Andy Pettitte offers a smile and a greeting delivered in a
soothing Louisiana drawl, and if you read his lips on the mound at
the worst of times, the words are G-rated.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Stottlemyre, the Yankees pitching coach, is the sort of
person who could get stuck on an elevator and immediately laugh
about it; he is unfailingly optimistic. David Cone has known
Stottlemyre for more than a decade and can remember seeing his
anger only one time, on the night the Mets were eliminated in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The inner beings hidden by Pettitte and Stottlemyre are similar,
as well _ both are seething competitors _ and for all that they
share, Pettitte might be the Yankees pitcher most affected by the
absence of Stottlemyre, who left the team Monday to be treated for
bone marrow cancer. With ample run support, Pettitte dominated
Oakland, 12-1, improving his record to 13-6.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland's Kevin Appier was terrible, walking six and hitting a
batter in 32/3 innings, allowing seven hits and 10 runs, and the
Yankees feasted, even after Appier was knocked out.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez blasted a grand slam and drove in five runs, Scott
Brosius laced a three-run double, Jorge Posada crushed his 21st
homer, and Bernie Williams banged his 26th home run _ the 18th home
run hit into the black section in center field in the remodeled
Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Williams has 88 runs scored, 102 runs batted in and 64
extra-base hits with 53 games to play. The Yankees have scored 163
runs in 26 games since the All-Star Game break, an average of 6.3
game, or about a run a game more than they averaged before the
break.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre was not at Yankee Stadium Wednesday night to witness
the wipeout, to see Pettitte maintain his concentration throughout
a long game played on a muggy evening. Pettitte threw in the
bullpen Sunday, and it was apparently at that time that Stottlemyre
told Pettitte of his plans _ the pitching coach is being
hospitalized this week, in preparation for a stem cell transplant,
and will miss the Yankees' road trip.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte's pitching is built on habits. He likes his workout
routine to be consistent; he hates to have an extra day of rest
between starts; he likes to work with the same catcher; he keeps
the bill of his cap low, an attempt to block out anything that
exists besides the hitter and his catcher.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre has been his pitching coach since the outset of the
1996 season, working closely with the left-hander. Joe Torre, the
Yankees' manager, mentioned Wednesday how it is he, Torre, that
gets all the credit for staving off the possible trade of Pettitte
in July of 1999. In fact, Torre said, he took his cue from
Stottlemyre and his reading of Pettitte's problems last summer, and
his faith that Pettitte would rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre possesses a special insight into Pettitte's psyche,
perhaps because of their similar demeanors _ ``Fire and
brimstone,'' Torre called them. There have been games when Pettitte
has stomped back to the dugout after a bad inning, hurled his glove
and cap against the bench and retreated to the clubhouse angrily.
Stottlemyre would turn and give Torre a broad and knowing smile
then follow Pettitte, to calm the left-hander.
</P>
<P>
   But Pettitte proceeded without Stottlemyre Wednesday night.
Presumably, the pitching coach watched the game; presumably, he was
exceptionally pleased.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
