<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-AIRCRASH-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(WITH NJ-AIRCRASH) 
THE SKY RAINS HORROR ON A NEIGHBORHOOD
</HEADLINE>
  By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURLINGTON TOWNSHIP, N.J. _ One instant it was a normal weekday
morning in the suburbs and the next it was a surreal nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Three bodies fell from one of the planes that had collided in
midair, and landed in an athletic field where the children of the
Steeplechase subdivision play soccer and football and families
gather annually for an end-of-the-summer block party.
</P>
<P>
   Another body crashed through the roof of a garage on Spur Court
a few hundred feet east of the field. An engine plummeted into
Jackie Framo's yard, about 40 feet from her front doorstep, while
she was dressing. At first, when she looked out of her window, she
thought an underground gas main had exploded because she saw smoke
pouring up from ``this mangled piece of metal.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bucci, a 34-year-old furniture wholesaler, heard a loud
noise, apparently the collision, as he sat at his home computer,
punching furniture sales orders to a factory in Iowa. He hurried
outside and said he saw a plane spinning in circles and burning as
it passed over a corner of his house about 30 feet above the roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``It scared the heck out of me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bucci started running up Steeplechase Boulevard, the main street
through the development, but was stopped, he said, by an explosion,
a huge ball of fire and flames jumping from the curbside openings
of storm sewers.
</P>
<P>
   The plane had slammed into the side of a garage at 1 Philly
Court and burst into flames, incinerating two cars in the garage
and dooming the remaining five of the plane's original nine
passengers _ all civilian employees of the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   The fire destroyed the brick Georgian home at 1 Philly Court,
with two flower urns flanking the front door. It also scorched a
wall of an adjacent house. All the occupants and their pets fled
safely.
</P>
<P>
   Bucci said that when the plane exploded, he was rushing toward
the house in hopes of helping someone. But the flames blocked him.
</P>
<P>
   The twin-engine plane skimmed the rooftops in Steeplechase. The
other plane, a two-seater, with a pilot instructor and an aviation
student aboard, limped along the development's northern edge and
fell into a field of soybeans, killing both aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Miles, 30, wanted to help some of the victims but realized
minutes after seeing them that her intentions were futile.
</P>
<P>
   She was taking a shower when she heard a rumbling that she
mistook for thunder. Minutes later, she went downstairs, heard a
televised news report about the crash and then looked out her
kitchen window onto the development's athletic field and saw what
she thought was a body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran out to help,'' she recalled. ``But I got about
three-quarters of the way up to the body and realized there was
nothing I could do.'' Realizing the person was dead, she returned
to her kitchen and called 911.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Sausman, 12, said the first instinct of his mother, Kathy,
was to rush to the burning house. Sean said they watched from their
driveway as the plane spun toward 1 Philly Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the plane going down, trailing smoke,'' the boy said.
``My mom's a nurse and she wanted to go down to see what she could
do to help. But all of a sudden all these police cars and
ambulances went flying by our house.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, all the residents escaped unhurt. After visiting the
crash site in late morning, Gov. Christine Todd Whitman of New
Jersey termed the absence of injuries on the ground a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   Steeplechase has about 700 homes, all built in the last five
years on a 37-acre plot once filled by soybeans. It is about 10
miles northeast of Philadelphia and is one of hundreds of big
subdivisions that have filled the woods and fields throughout New
Jersey in the last 20 years. The development has a horse racing
motif. One section is called Belmont, another Churchill Downs and
another the Paddock.
</P>
<P>
   As dusk fell, children and parents pushing babies in strollers
went to the police lines near the complex's ball field to glimpse
the ruins of 1 Philly Court about 300 yards away.
</P>
<P>
   The state police let three reporters view the crash site where
the five bodies were found. They reported to the rest of the media
that neighbors were sitting in their yards, sipping cool drinks,
and declining to talk about the day's events.
</P>
<P>
   Their yards were cluttered with debris from the plane, all
sitting in the middle of bright orange circles of spray paint that
investigators had applied.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
