<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KASHMIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: DANGEROUS KASHMIR 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Aug. 10:
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is right to be concerned about the
military confrontation between India and Pakistan over Kashmir, a
conflict that U.S. intelligence agencies now judge to be one of the
world's most perilous. The dispute over who will control India's
only Muslim-majority state has already provoked two wars. That was
before New Delhi and Islamabad acquired nuclear bombs and
medium-range missiles. Now any resumption of full-scale conflict
carries the risk of starting a nuclear war between the two nations.
</P>
<P>
   The world survived four decades of nuclear confrontation between
the United States and the Soviet Union because Washington and
Moscow established rules of behavior and crisis management. The two
superpowers waged proxy battles in the third world, but rarely
challenged each other's most vital interests or survival. By
contrast, India and Pakistan dispute a common land border not very
distant from either Islamabad or New Delhi. Many Pakistanis, raised
in a country founded on the principle of religious separatism,
believe the Muslims of Kashmir must be liberated from Indian rule.
India feels that retaining Kashmir is essential to its survival as
a diverse, multicultural nation.
</P>
<P>
   America cannot calm this dangerous conflict overnight. But it
must nudge both sides toward dialogue. President Clinton took some
useful steps on his South Asia trip earlier this year. He warned
Pakistan, which has often enjoyed U.S. support in the past, that it
should not assume Washington will come to its rescue if it provokes
a new conflict with India. In India, Clinton stressed U.S.
friendship and desire for better relations, but also urged New
Delhi to seek political dialogue with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   India must also start talks with militant Muslim groups in
Kashmir. A promising initiative with one such group, Hizbul
Mujahedeen, broke down on Tuesday, leading the militants to end a
brief cease-fire. One problem was Hizbul Mujahedeen's insistence
that Pakistan be represented at the talks, something India refuses
to accept. Washington should press both sides to come back to the
table without preconditions. Every reasonable effort must be made
to avoid a new Kashmir war.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
