<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    PICTURE THIS: YOU LOSE EVERYTHING(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By E.J. MONTINI(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - Tracy Matzen has nothing left but the clothes on his
back and a story to tell about confusion, government bureaucracy
and bad luck. But he doesn't want me to tell it.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those things are important,'' he says. ``But if there's
one thing I've learned from all this it's that they're not the most
important things. I'd rather talk about the things we lost that
really matter, that have value.''
</P>
<P>
   Matzen says he didn't understand what those things were until he
lost everything, which happened 10 days ago in northwest Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Like many couples, Matzen and his wife thought it would be nice
to have a brand new home, a place in which they and their three
children would be the very first occupants. Matzen works for a
local communications company. He has a good job and has lived in
town for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was going along just fine,'' Matzen says. ``My wife
and I even joked about things going (beginitalic)too(enditalic)
good. Well, we were right.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the part Matzen doesn't want to dwell on. After their
old house sold, problems developed in the house they were building.
They involved water meters and misinformation and confusion.
Ultimately, it meant the Matzen family would have to find temporary
housing until their new place was finished.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime around 2 a.m. July 31, Matzen and his family pulled
into the Hawthorn Suites near Thunderbird and Interstate 17. He was
driving his 1992 four-door white GMC Jimmy, behind which he towed a
U-Haul trailer. The plan was to put their possessions in storage,
but that would happen early the next day. Matzen went to bed about
3 a.m. By 6 the next morning, the truck and trailer were gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first you're just stunned,'' Matzen says. He looked all
around the parking lot, as if he could have misplaced two large
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you realize what happened, and all that you lost.''
Clothes. Possessions (including Matzen's 25th anniversary Fender
Stratocaster guitar.) Everything. Neither the Jimmy nor the trailer
has turned up yet. Still, Matzen doesn't want charity. He figures
the insurance company will handle the losses, except for the
family's most precious items: their pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inside the video recorder that was stolen is a tape,'' Matzen
says. ``It begins three months ago, just after our daughter (Casey)
was born. I'd give anything to have that tape back.'' Also gone is
a baby book Cori Matzen was keeping on Casey. And pictures of
8-year-old D.J. and 7-year-old Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely, I tell Matzen, that the thieves who case motels
looking for families to rob spend much time reading the papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know,'' he says. ``But you always have hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Matzen never imagined losing everything. And if he had, he
wouldn't have imagined his greatest loss would be pictures. Now, he
knows.
</P>
<P>
   Our recollections fade, whether we like it or not. Our pictures,
which once only reinforced the past, in time
(beginitalic)become(enditalic) our memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should realize how precious they are,'' Matzen says.
``They're the real riches in your life.''
</P>
<P>
   A newspaper article won't get back what the Matzens lost.
They'll have to take new pictures and begin a new baby book. And
they'll need new things to paste into it.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, this.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Montini at ed.montini(a)arizonarepublic.com or (602)
444-8978
</P>
</TEXT>
