<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEST LEADERS RETAIN KEY EMPLOYEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   People join companies. They leave managers.
</P>
<P>
   Every so often a buzzword or phrase jumps to the top of the
business-speak charts. The above is the current buzz. Hot on its
heels is, ``It's the managers, stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   The strong economy's No. 1 employment problem _ attracting and
keeping good workers _ has put supervisors on notice: They're going
to be held accountable for employee retention in their departments.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are managers who are naturally great retention
managers,'' said Sharon Jordan-Evans, co-author of Love 'Em or Lose
'Em: Getting Good People to Stay. ``But they account for maybe only
10 percent. The majority of managers don't fall in that category.''
</P>
<P>
   What does a good retention manager do?
</P>
<P>
   According to Training magazine, the good ones meet with their
workers at least monthly _ not just in a once-a-year appraisal _ to
address problems, recognize strong performance and ask the workers
what they need to make their jobs more fulfilling.
</P>
<P>
   And, once they find out what the good worker wants and needs,
the good retention manager finds job assignments and opportunities
that are likely to encourage them to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Cerner Corp., for example, has become extremely serious about
holding managers accountable for keeping the stars and solid
performers on their staffs. Stan Sword, Cerner's chief people
officer, said turnover was costing the North Kansas City company
$35 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We set a goal to improve retention, and we've placed greater
responsibility among our managers than they'd ever thought
possible,'' Sword said.
</P>
<P>
   Employees leave jobs for many reasons _ bigger challenges,
promotions, fewer work hours, better pay, less travel _ but ``most
of the time (employees) are leaving because of relationships. They
just won't say their manager was a jerk,'' Sword said.
</P>
<P>
   Cerner draws retention tips from Love 'Em or Lose 'Em. In
seminars and written handouts, the company teaches its managers
about their retention responsibilities. Departmental turnover
numbers are monitored monthly and, if the number is too high, the
manager is called in for a ``What's wrong?'' meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Retention experts emphasize that some turnover is healthy.
Generally, nobody mourns the loss of dead wood, the bottom 10
percent to 20 percent of performers. But, for the top 20 percent to
25 percent of employees in particular, woe to the boss who loses
too many or fails to provide rewarding career paths for them.
</P>
<P>
   Cerner even has created a ``career navigation center'' where,
Sword said, employees can ``confidentially get a better position if
their current manager has been stifling them.''
</P>
<P>
   Employee retention is a one-on-one activity, Jordan-Evans
advises. One-on-one, every manager should ask his or her key
employees, ``What will it take to keep you here?''
</P>
<P>
   Managers in many organizations don't ask because they're afraid
of what they'll hear, or they're afraid they have no power (or
budget) to implement the request. Companies serious about retention
are helping their managers figure out how to do it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 2347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000809.0427 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7482 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-SAFIR-NYT &LR;      08-09 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SAFIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NEW YORK'S POLICE COMMISSIONER 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Aug. 10:
</P>
<P>
   The resignation of Police Commissioner Howard Safir, New York
City's 39th police chief, provides the opportunity to praise him
for his dramatic success over the last four years in cutting crime
rates to their lowest levels since the 1960s. It also offers a
chance for Mayor Rudolph Giuliani to choose the right successor to
conclude his own term as mayor. Giuliani should pick someone who
can not only keep crime rates low but also deal more expertly with
the frictions between police and minorities that Safir leaves
behind. It must be someone who can reassure all New Yorkers that
keeping down crime does not involve a tradeoff in civil liberties.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning of his tour of duty, it was clear that Safir
had agreed to leave the boasting rights about safer streets to
Giuliani. The previous commissioner, William Bratton, had reaped
much of the early credit for the drop in crime, never a wise move
for a Giuliani underling. Bratton instituted computer tracking of
crimes to deploy police where they were needed, and began a
``quality of life'' crackdown on lesser violations. Safir continued
or expanded these ventures, but he also launched efforts of his
own, including better training, special units to battle gangs and
drugs and expanded use of DNA analysis to track criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Still, on Safir's watch several high-profile incidents left
minority New Yorkers alarmed about how often they are viewed as
suspects and concerned that the price of lower crime rates was
police harassment of immigrants, blacks and Hispanics. The police
torture of the Haitian immigrant Abner Louima in 1997 and the more
recent shootings of two unarmed black men, Amadou Diallo and
Patrick Dorismond, raised questions about training, reporting of
violations and the expansion of independent street crime units
during Safir's term of office. The commissioner cited statistics
showing an overall decline in police shootings, civilian complaints
and brutality lawsuits during his term. But he seemed to miss the
point that the city's minority communities were in a state of
chronic fear about careless or hostile police tactics.
</P>
<P>
   With the departure of the mayor's loyal commissioner, Giuliani
needs to choose a replacement who can take command of the nation's
largest police department quickly. The new commissioner must
oversee difficult negotiations with police unions and deal with the
demands of federal and state investigators criticizing the
department after the Louima and Diallo cases. And he or she must
command respect not only from New York's 40,000-member police force
but also from a diverse citizenry that wants to feel safe both from
crime and from the fear of excessive police tactics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
