A7484 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      08-09 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEST LEADERS RETAIN KEY EMPLOYEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   People join companies. They leave managers.
</P>
<P>
   Every so often a buzzword or phrase jumps to the top of the
business-speak charts. The above is the current buzz. Hot on its
heels is, ``It's the managers, stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   The strong economy's No. 1 employment problem _ attracting and
keeping good workers _ has put supervisors on notice: They're going
to be held accountable for employee retention in their departments.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are managers who are naturally great retention
managers,'' said Sharon Jordan-Evans, co-author of Love 'Em or Lose
'Em: Getting Good People to Stay. ``But they account for maybe only
10 percent. The majority of managers don't fall in that category.''
</P>
<P>
   What does a good retention manager do?
</P>
<P>
   According to Training magazine, the good ones meet with their
workers at least monthly _ not just in a once-a-year appraisal _ to
address problems, recognize strong performance and ask the workers
what they need to make their jobs more fulfilling.
</P>
<P>
   And, once they find out what the good worker wants and needs,
the good retention manager finds job assignments and opportunities
that are likely to encourage them to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Cerner Corp., for example, has become extremely serious about
holding managers accountable for keeping the stars and solid
performers on their staffs. Stan Sword, Cerner's chief people
officer, said turnover was costing the North Kansas City company
$35 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We set a goal to improve retention, and we've placed greater
responsibility among our managers than they'd ever thought
possible,'' Sword said.
</P>
<P>
   Employees leave jobs for many reasons _ bigger challenges,
promotions, fewer work hours, better pay, less travel _ but ``most
of the time (employees) are leaving because of relationships. They
just won't say their manager was a jerk,'' Sword said.
</P>
<P>
   Cerner draws retention tips from Love 'Em or Lose 'Em. In
seminars and written handouts, the company teaches its managers
about their retention responsibilities. Departmental turnover
numbers are monitored monthly and, if the number is too high, the
manager is called in for a ``What's wrong?'' meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Retention experts emphasize that some turnover is healthy.
Generally, nobody mourns the loss of dead wood, the bottom 10
percent to 20 percent of performers. But, for the top 20 percent to
25 percent of employees in particular, woe to the boss who loses
too many or fails to provide rewarding career paths for them.
</P>
<P>
   Cerner even has created a ``career navigation center'' where,
Sword said, employees can ``confidentially get a better position if
their current manager has been stifling them.''
</P>
<P>
   Employee retention is a one-on-one activity, Jordan-Evans
advises. One-on-one, every manager should ask his or her key
employees, ``What will it take to keep you here?''
</P>
<P>
   Managers in many organizations don't ask because they're afraid
of what they'll hear, or they're afraid they have no power (or
budget) to implement the request. Companies serious about retention
are helping their managers figure out how to do it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 2348EDT &QL; 
