<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ASIAN-AMERICANS-AIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ASIAN-AMERICANS AND AIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Aug. 10:
</P>
<P>
   Recent studies show that Asian-Americans, especially new
immigrants, are largely uneducated about AIDS. More than any other
ethnic group, Asian-Americans do not get diagnosed with AIDS until
the disease is already in its later stages. This reflects a dearth
of Asian-language educational materials. Conservative cultural
beliefs also hamper open discussions about AIDS. Stepping up AIDS
education efforts would help increase understanding. But the most
influence lies with community leaders, who can encourage public
dialogue on AIDS and acceptance of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   So far, community groups have been leading AIDS education
efforts. These organizations have received state and federal
funding, but they need more assistance. Organizations have to
provide educational materials in languages ranging from Punjabi to
Mandarin. But more important, they must focus on cultural
differences. A Japanese group may react very differently to AIDS
education than a Korean one would.
</P>
<P>
   Even improvements in AIDS education will not be enough if the
community's silence on the disease persists. Unfortunately, many
influential religious leaders have refused to allow AIDS education
into their places of worship. It is encouraging that the
Chinese-American Planning Council has begun an AIDS education
program for prostitutes in New York City's Chinatown. Public health
agencies must also do more. But leaders and organizations, which
can reach their communities through a common language and culture,
will have the most effect.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
