<HEADER>
A7487 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-OLY-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     08-09 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMPSON-TORRES: THE RIVALRY THAT ISN'T (REALLY)
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Dara Torres and Jenny Thompson exchanged
first-place finishes and American records Wednesday in the
100-meter butterfly, but not one meaningful glance.
</P>
<P>
   This news flash went along press row at the Indiana University
Natatorium during the opening day of the U.S. Olympic Trials with
all the seriousness of an Eric Sevareid report.
</P>
<P>
   Torres and Thompson, teammates at Stanford, have a relationship
as complicated as Bill and Hillary's. They haven't trained together
since December, a break that coincided with Torres' torrid rise
from retiree to record holder.
</P>
<P>
   Torres trimmed 0.3 seconds off Thompson's American record in the
morning heats with a 57.58 clocking, and Thompson prevailed in the
evening's semifinals with a 57.59, setting the stage for a final
today that promises to be everything Maurice and Michael's 200
meters at last month's U.S. Track and Field Trials was not.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Torres and Thompson's tit-for-tat times, the
interplay between the two sprinters took center stage.
</P>
<P>
   A few reporters, smelling bad blood in the water, have circled
the swimmers and sunk their teeth into the rival angle. Thompson
and Torres have tried to wiggle free, with little success. It has
bordered on the absurd, watching journalists who are so competitive
they won't share quotes turn around and ask why Thompson and Torres
aren't splitting a lane in the pool.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Thompson and Torres have egos, but those aren't what
have clashed. Thompson didn't banish Torres from the group. It was
more of a personality scrap.
</P>
<P>
   We gleaned from more than one member of the team that the
Stanford women, who are tighter than their bodysuits, collectively
voted Torres off their watery oasis because her high-maintenance
personality was upsetting their delicate ego-logical balance.
</P>
<P>
   They decided if Torres wanted the coaching staff to herself, the
least they could do was accommodate her. That's why Torres has been
training on her own for the past eight months under Richard Quick's
supervision. Torres, 33, worked as a model and a broadcaster during
her time away from the sport so she's obviously comfortable with
the personal attention.
</P>
<P>
   Not that there's anything wrong with that.
</P>
<P>
   The sports world is a sanctum for the self-absorbed. And if you
think about it, only someone with a highly evolved hubris would
commit to a comeback after seven years off.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a healthy self-image to attempt the seemingly
unimaginable. Torres is what she is and that goes a long way toward
explaining why she's on the verge of becoming the first American
swimmer, male or female, to participate in four Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   A first or second-place finish in the 100 butterfly final today
and Torres is on her way to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   A first or second-place finish would place Thompson on her third
Olympic team and afford her the opportunity to become the most
decorated U.S. female Olympian.
</P>
<P>
   She is U.S. Swimming's heirloom, having graced the national team
for the past 14 years _ more than half her life. The 27-year-old's
longevity in the sport rivals Darrell Green's in football or Carl
Lewis's in track and field. Her Olympic gold medal collection
(five, all in relays) has been equaled in this country only by
speedskater Bonnie Blair. And yet Thompson's public profile never
has quite caught up to her stature.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't make sense, but it's easily explained: Thompson
doesn't court the spotlight. If it comes, she'll happily take a
bow. But she doesn't need a milk mustache or a magazine cover or a
deferential press to complete her.
</P>
<P>
   One of her friends on the Stanford team said, ``I think Jenny
would like to have more of the attention. She's a wonderful person
and deserves it, absolutely. But she's not going to change who she
is to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's personality indulges thoughtfulness and loyalty and
fun but has no use for preening and posturing. She immersed herself
in swimming not so others would someday feel good about her but
because it made her feel good about herself.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens today and the rest of the meet, Thompson
already has her next challenge in sight; next August she will
enroll at the Columbia University Medical School to fulfill her
childhood dream of becoming a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what kind, she replied drolly, ``A good one, I hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Some wounds are hard to heal. Thompson's closest friends
occasionally wish she had grown a thicker coat of conceit so life's
arrows would bounce harmlessly off her.
</P>
<P>
   At a meet in Irvine in June, Thompson was walking with the
slumped posture of a question mark. Dutch sprinter Inge de Bruijn
was in the midst of a world-record spree _ she has broken eight
world records since May, including Thompson's 100 fly mark _ that
appeared to be shooting holes in Thompson's confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the month, Thompson came down with an intestinal virus
and had to pull out of a meet in Santa Clara. In her absence,
Torres set an American record in the 50 free, one of their four
head-to-head races.
</P>
<P>
   Missing that meet, in her own backyard, ``was devastating to
me,'' Thompson said. ``I had questions, like `Where am I in my
season?' I don't think it was that big a deal in hindsight, but it
seemed like it at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Who knew L.A. was just what Thompson needed? She came to the
Janet Evans Invitational at USC in mid-July swimming in self-doubts
and left as the all-time fastest U.S. performer in the women's 100
freestyle. Her American-record clocking of 54.27 was a 0.21-second
improvement over her 1992 Trials effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``The L.A. meet was really great for me,'' Thompson said, ``just
(in terms of) how I was feeling about my swimming.''
</P>
<P>
   That's all that should matter. How Thompson and Torres feel
about each other is really beside the point. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Karen Crouse's column appears in the Daily News four days a week.
She can be reached at (818) 713-3619. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 2350EDT &QL; 
