<HEADER>
A7488 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-PORK-BATTLE-KAN &LR;      08-09 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORK-BATTLE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE OVER PORK PROMOTION MONEY INTENSIFIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The heat of election season has been turned up, with Republicans
questioning the moral fiber of Democratic leaders and Democrats
calling the new Republican claims of inclusiveness a sham. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But there is no more bitter campaign being waged than an obscure
contest playing out primarily in the Midwest. Already there have
been charges of election fraud, and investigations have been
launched. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The mud being slung in this fight comes off the boots of the
country's pig farmers. Its outcome will determine the future of
about $50 million they ante each year into the industry's promotion
war chest. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Call this pork, the other campaign. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beginning this month, hog farmers can request absentee ballots
for a September vote on whether the 14-year-old national pork
checkoff program should be eliminated. The program requires hog
producers to kick 45 cents of every $100 in value of the hogs they
sell into a fund that pays for research and promotions, such as the
``Pork, the Other White Meat'' campaign. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But a group of independent hog farmers says that mega-hog farms,
some owned by companies that also do meat packing, unfairly benefit
from the checkoff. Mega-farms are putting small producers out of
business, the independents say. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I be paying to cut my own throat?'' said Gary
Comstock, whose family raises about 6,000 pigs a year on a farm in
Vernon County, Mo., about 100 miles south of Kansas City. ``I think
the corporate farms are getting all the licks _ everything is going
their way. I don't think there is anybody in our corner.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fighting to keep the program is the National Pork Producers
Council and its state organizations, to which most of the millions
are funneled. Those groups believe the hog farmers who forced the
referendum are sorely mistaken if they believe they will fare
better against industrial agriculture without the checkoff
program. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The large producers don't need the checkoff. They can spend
the money they would save on their own products better,'' said Karl
Johnson, who with his brother raises about 25,000 hogs a year on a
farm near Mankato, Minn. He is co-chairman of the national
council's Vote Yes Task Force. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said programs funded by checkoff dollars have given him
help with hog genetics and environmental issues that he couldn't
afford to pay for. That assistance has kept Johnson and his brother
in business, Johnson said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The referendum effort was started by grass-roots farm
organizations such as the Campaign for Family Farms in Columbia,
Mo., about two years ago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, a glut of hogs and a shortage of meat packing plants
resulted in hog prices dropping as low as 8 cents a pound, the
lowest at least since the 1930s. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many hog farmers blamed the glut on corporate hog farms, some of
which raise or contract for millions of hogs a year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The financial slaughter of 1998 was a watershed moment, said
Rhonda Perry, a hog farmer from Howard County near Columbia, who is
helping organize the referendum. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Particularly galling has been the defense of corporate farms and
meat packers by the producers council at a time when smaller
farmers have challenged how much of the market they control, Perry
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Pork Producers Association, for example, opposed a
state law pushed by small operators that required meat packers to
daily post prices they were paying for hogs. The association later
backed a less stringent federal law that superseded the state
legislation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The dollars have been used to create political cover for some
of the corporations we think are not playing fair,'' Perry said.
``The NPPC goes before Congress on these issues as if it represents
all hog farmers.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Owners of the big hog operations have been relatively quiet in
this fight. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Farmland Industries Inc. of Kansas City, one of the country's
largest pork processors, also contracts with members to raise some
hogs. It has not taken a public stand, but is urging eligible
members to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Perry scoffs at the idea that anyone besides some public
relations firms and the national producers council has benefited
much from the millions raised in checkoff dollars. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Between the 1987 and 1997 farm census, the number of farms
raising hogs dropped from 243,398 to 109,754, a 55 percent
decrease, while the number of large farms has grown. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Annual per capita consumption of pork has grown slightly, from
49 pounds in 1986 to 52.6 pounds by 1998, according to statistics
from the U.S. Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   The election has been hard-fought on both sides. Some members of
the national producers council contend the petition drive by the
Campaign for Family Farms didn't meet the letter of the law. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In late July, the Campaign for Family Farms accused the Missouri
Pork Producers Association and other state associations of trying
to rig the vote when its telemarketers called and the organizations
offered to get absentee ballots for farmers who supported their
position. The anti-checkoff group said election rules require each
eligible voter to request a ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri association initially denied the allegations, then
sent out a press release saying election rules didn't prevent the
group from helping farmers get ballots. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The implication that the ballot request would violate the intent
of the rules but the agency failed to write them to specifically
prohibit that from happening, Kathleen Merrigan, administrator of
the USDA's Agricultural Marketing Service, said in a statement. The
marketing service is overseeing the election. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the statement said, the practice will not be
prohibited. All the ballots must be signed and the nameswill be
public, the statement said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, the farmer from Minnesota, is sorry to see hog
producers fighting so bitterly among themselves. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology has changed agriculture, like it has changed every
business. While we don't have to like what is going on today, it is
happening,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Perry said she knows it won't ever be like it was 30 years ago.
But she and other small operators aren't going to pretend that what
is good for corporate farms is good for them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The tent is not big enough for packers, corporate hog farms
and independent farmers,'' Perry said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 2358EDT &QL; 
