<SLUG> BC-SUV-RECALL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD RECALLS SOME SMALL SUVS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co. has recalled more than 1,900 of the new small
sport-utility vehicles built at its Claycomo plant, citing a defect
in the steering column.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,300 Ford Escapes and 625 Mazda Tributes were identified
as having a defective nut that could cause the steering wheel to
separate from the steering column, said Rich Voytowich, a Ford
spokesman at its Dearborn, Mich., headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was first reported in the Aug. 7 issue of Automotive
News.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicles were repaired with replacement parts at the
dealerships, Ford officials said. Ford started shipping the new
product to dealers in late July, and only about a dozen customers
around the country owned the small SUVs with the defect, according
to the company.
</P>
<P>
   Ford began assembling the SUVs with the replacement nuts at the
Claycomo plant last week.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing of Escapes and Tributes began in June, and the
Claycomo factory still is trying to increase the line speed on the
new vehicle's production. According to statistics tracked by
Automotive News, 1,259 SUVs were built at Claycomo last week.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's production goal is to build about 220,000 Escapes and
30,000 Tributes at Claycomo for the 2001 model year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-00 2359EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000809.0433 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-09 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7490 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-GIULIANI-NYT &LR;      08-09 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI ACKNOWLEDGES HE KNEW ABOUT HIS FATHER'S CRIMINAL ACTIVITY
</HEADLINE>
  By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani acknowledged for the first
time on Wednesday night, in a television interview, that he knew
about the criminal activity that his father engaged in before he
was born, which was revealed in a book published last month. The
mayor said his father's mistakes influenced him to go into law
enforcment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of it I knew, some of it I suspected,'' Giuliani said of
the accounts in the book, ``Rudy! An Investigative Biography of
Rudolph Giuliani,'' by Wayne Barrett, a reporter for The Village
Voice.
</P>
<P>
   The book describes Harold Giuliani's prison stint for armed
robbery of a milkman and contends that the elder Giuliani was an
enforcer for his brother-in-law's loan sharking operation. ``Some
of it,'' the mayor said, ``did come as a shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Wednesday, Giuliani, a former U.S. attorney, had refused
to answer recent questions about his father, other than to defend
him as scrupulously honest and the ``finest man'' he had ever
known.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday night, in an interview on ``New York Close-up''
on NY1 with Sam Roberts, the program's host and deputy editor of
the Week in Review section of The New York Times, the mayor opened
up a little.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani refused, however, to say just what he knew and when he
knew it. ``Some of it I knew, some of it I suspected, some of it I
absolutely didn't know, and when I write my book, I'll explain
which is which,'' he said with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   According to Barrett's book, in 1934, Harold Giuliani, with an
accomplice, pulled a gun on a milkman in a building on East 96th
Street in Manhattan, robbed him of $128.82 and served a year and a
half at Sing Sing, under a fake name that he gave to the police.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Giuliani, who said he has not read the book, said that his
father was ``compulsive about being honest,'' perhaps to compensate
for his past deeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would tell me, `Never take anybody else's money, make sure
you always pay for things, make sure that you don't make a mistake
when you fill out a form, make sure it's accurate,''' the mayor
said. ``I've driven myself crazy over this all my life. And when
any mistake has been made it really bothers me, and I realize more
than I did as I was growing up why my father was doing that. I
mean, he wanted to make sure that I didn't make the same mistakes
that he believed he had made.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if his father's criminal past had influenced him to
go into law enforcement, Giuliani replied, `I'm sure it did.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrett's book also said that several of the mayor's cousins
were involved in organized crime, and the mayor said that his
parents' decision to move to Long Island was in part an attempt to
get him away from an unsavory element.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the decision that my father and mother made,
essentially was to take me out of Brooklyn, where they thought I
could get into trouble,'' he said, ``and keep me away from some of
the things that I guess my father was worried about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
